<SLUG> BC-MOORE-OVERRIDE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRAT TO VOTE TO OVERRIDE VETO OF MARRIAGE TAX PENALTY BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY AND STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. Rep. Dennis Moore, a Kansas Democrat, said
Thursday he would vote to override President Clinton's veto of a
bill to reduce higher taxes people often pay when they get married.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, in a tough re-election fight, has been an outspoken
supporter of the Marriage Tax Penalty Relief Act, which Congress
passed in July and Clinton vetoed on Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eliminating the marriage penalty not only provides much-needed
tax relief, but it also makes the tax system more fair,'' Moore
said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
   Moore is running against Republican Phill Kline to hold his seat
in the House in a district that had elected Republicans for 40
years until Moore won in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Kline said Thursday that he also would vote to override the
president's veto. In addition, he said Moore on three other
occasions voted against ending the marriage penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis continues to dance the Potomac two-step in an effort to
deceive the voters of Kansas,'' Kline said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   But Moore shot back that he voted three times to eliminate the
tax. Two of his dissenting votes, an aide said, were because the
tax cut was part of a $792 billion package that Moore disliked
because it would have eaten up too much of the budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is I voted for marriage penalty tax
elimination three times, and I guess I'm having trouble
understanding why Phill Kline is complaining about that,'' Moore
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the average annual tax savings under the bill would be
$500 per couple and that it would affect 42 million Americans and
nearly 67,000 people from his 3rd Congressional District.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the bill ``poorly targeted, costly and
regressive'' and one that could cost more than $280 billion over 10
years. He said it would undermine efforts to revamp Social Security
and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   But many Democrats such as Moore and Reps. Pat Danner and Ike
Skelton of Missouri voted for it. Spokesmen for Danner and Skelton
said Thursday they were uncertain if the lawmakers would vote to
override the veto.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Karen McCarthy, a Democrat from Missouri, voted against the
bill. She was unavailable for comment on how she would vote on the
override.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
