<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-LA-BEST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUGAR'S ON TOP OF L.A.'S BOXING CLASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shane Mosley, Fernando Vargas and Oscar De La Hoya
_ with unusual God-given ability, fighting spirit, charisma and
success _ have made Los Angeles the first city of boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, the three rank among the 10 greatest fighters in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   However, who's the best of the bunch, the Ace Angeleno, the King
of Los Angeles?
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News asked three well-known and respected trainers _
Teddy Atlas, Joe Goossen and Emanuel Steward _ to answer that
question and provide their reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict? Mosley is the man, although it was no knockout
punch. He received two votes (Atlas and Goossen), Vargas one
(Steward) and De La Hoya none.
</P>
<P>
   This is the consensus:
</P>
<P>
   Mosley (35-0, with 32 knockouts) was a very successful
lightweight champion and moved up to welterweight to take De La
Hoya's title. He's proven himself over an eight-year career.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas (19-0, 17 KOs) _ who defends his IBF junior middleweight
title against Ross Thompson on Saturday in Las Vegas _ also is
unbeaten but at 22 doesn't have the track record.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya (32-2, 26 KOs) has the most impressive list of
victories and is the best marketed of the three but has lost his
last two big fights, to Felix Trinidad and Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the thoughts of the trainers. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ATLAS
</P>
<P>
   To Atlas, it comes down to this: Mosley, of Pomona, held the
lightweight title for two years _ a solid eight defenses _ and then
jumped over junior welterweight to welterweight and beat one of the
top fighters in the world, De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   He's as complete as any fighter in the world and he has proved
it in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``He defended the lightweight title well,'' said Atlas, who also
is a television analyst on ESPN2. ``There was nobody great (in the
division) but he beat everybody. He showed he had the ability to be
consistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, to move up to another weight class and maintain those
skills and win another title against a fighter like De La Hoya says
a lot. He's ahead of Fernando in that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlas was the most critical of Vargas of the three trainers.
</P>
<P>
   He likes what he sees so far _ a well-schooled, tough fighter
with unusual maturity in the ring and a victory over super-tough
Ike Quartey in April _ but he believes Vargas is still evolving.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a victory over Trinidad (whom Vargas is tentatively
scheduled to fight Dec. 2) would speed up the evolution process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vargas has shown some versatility,'' Atlas said. ``He's
strong, he can box, he has good hand speed. And technically he's
improving. He used to be a guy who stood straight up, he caught
solid shots. He seems to be more aware of that now. I think he's
finding himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``... He hasn't accomplished that much yet. He'll have his
opportunities, though. A mega-fight against Trinidad would be very
big. I think it's a fight he can win. If he does, I think he's
right with Shane.''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as a year ago, De La Hoya was considered by many to
be the best pound-for-pound fighter in the world.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's difficult for Atlas and the other trainers to look
past the two defeats even though neither was one-sided. Most
observers believe De La Hoya beat Trinidad in September and he was
in the Mosley fight until the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason I'm not putting him second (ahead of Vargas)
are the two losses,'' Atlas said. ``You have to respect Vargas'
undefeated record, especially since he fought a substantial guy in
Quartey. He's a fighter on the upswing. De La Hoya is not a fighter
on the upswing.
</P>
<P>
   ``... With all (De La Hoya) has (read: money, fame) it might be
tough for him at this point to change a few things he might have to
change unless it's a personal priority of his, unless he wants to
prove something to himself.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
GOOSSEN
</P>
<P>
   Mosley's victory over De La Hoya, combined with Vargas' youth,
made Goossen's decision easy.
</P>
<P>
   Goossen, who runs a gym in Van Nuys, echoed the common
assessment of Mosley: ``He's got it all. He's great defensively,
great offensively. He'll outbang you, he'll outbox you. He was
outstanding at 135 pounds (lightweight), he still has power at 147
pounds (welterweight).''
</P>
<P>
   And he's a big fan of Vargas, who he believes might be the
``toughest'' fighter in the world and one of the most gifted in
terms of boxing skills. He's Goossen's kind of fighter: fearless.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, he's the prototypical fighter. I'd like to cut along
the dotted line and get about 10 of those guys,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That said, he pointed out that De La Hoya is only a handful of
punches away from the top spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can chalk up his losses to a few minor adjustments he
didn't make,'' Goossen said. ``What separated him from victory
against Trinidad? A few dozen punches (late in the fight). Against
Mosley, he was fairly effective but didn't change his style when
the momentum shifted toward Mosley. He should've gone back to what
got him there, he should've boxed him (instead of stalking Mosley,
as he did throughout the fight).
</P>
<P>
   ``If he does these things, he's 2-0 instead of 0-2 and
everything is different. Is he an underachiever? I wouldn't say
that. I (ital)would(endital) say more could've been squeezed out of
him, enough to win those two fights.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
STEWARD
</P>
<P>
   Steward, who has trained De La Hoya among many world champions,
didn't hesitate when he was asked to name the top L.A. fighter:
Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   He said repeatedly that Vargas has a relative lack of experience
but gushed over the Oxnard fighter as if we were witnessing the
rise of one of the greatest fighters (ital)ever(endital).
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Vargas when his head is right,'' said Steward,
referring to the fighter's out-of-the-ring legal problems. ``I just
think he's a very balanced fighter and he's very, very patient for
such a young fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always in position to execute, to take advantage of his
opponent's mistakes. That's also very unusual for a young fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he loooooooves to fight. If he can control his outside
activities, if he doesn't self-destruct, I feel he's on his way to
becoming a great fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Where can Vargas improve?
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't, really _ except in experience,'' Steward said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Steward likes Mosley. He likes his speed and his
skills but emphasized a less-tangible reason for his success: His
love of boxing. Mosley will beat you up and smile while he does it.
</P>
<P>
   However, Steward did find what some might say is a relative
flaw: Mosley's relative lack of punching power at 147 pounds, at
which he's fought only three times. He landed several extremely
hard punches to the jaw of De La Hoya but was unable to put him
down.
</P>
<P>
   That could change with time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a big puncher yet,'' Steward said, ``but he has
enough qualities to make up for that.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya?
</P>
<P>
   ``Lately, I don't like what I've seen,'' Steward said. ``... He
was such a beautiful fighter. He could punch on his toes, had
upper-body movement. He was like a perfect machine. Now, he's more
flat-footed, one dimensional. Maybe these losses will stimulate him
again, I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at his best, though, I'd have trouble rating him higher
than Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   It's a debate that could rage on for years. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
