<SLUG> BC-TOURISM-FOOTBALL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS TO PROMOTE STATE TOURISM THROUGH SPONSORED ATHLETIC EVENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN A. DVORAK  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ When Kansas Lt. Gov. Gary Sherrer
participates in the coin toss for the Kansas State-Iowa football
game Saturday, it won't be just because he's rooting for the
Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   It's because Kansas state government sponsored the game, part of
a $100,000 project _ paid for with public funds _ to market Kansas
as a good place to visit and do business.
</P>
<P>
   Ads promoting Kansas tourism will appear on the telecast of the
game, at Arrowhead Stadium in Kansas City and in the game program
for the Eddie Robinson Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Kansas plans to bring in out-of-state consultants who help
companies choose new locations for plants and offices, show them
what the state can offer and then take them to the game.
</P>
<P>
   The state will pick up the travel and expense tab for the
consultants, who often take a central role in helping companies
decide where to move.
</P>
<P>
   Sherrer, the economic development czar for Kansas, said state
government hasn't undertaken this kind of venture before.
</P>
<P>
   But the state competes with 49 other states and needs to
aggressively tell its story, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how we're going to promote Kansas if we don't
invest some money.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Sherrer said he can understand why some might
question the use of public funds for a football game.
</P>
<P>
   Such spending, however, isn't unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Eddie Robinson Classic was played in Indiana. The
Indiana Commerce Department sponsored the game, a way of touting
Indiana as a desirable spot for businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the start of a larger marketing campaign,'' said Kevin
Waltman, department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   State officials consider the money well-spent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't receive much criticism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, money for the project won't come from tax revenue,
like income tax or sales tax funds. It will come from the proceeds
of the Kansas Lottery, which are used for many economic development
activities.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsoring the game cost $84,000, state officials said. Expenses
for the consultants will run an estimated $20,000, they said.
Fifteen consultants are expected from out of state, along with
seven from the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   The consultants will tour the Sprint campus in Johnson County,
Kan., and the Kansas Speedway in Wyandotte County.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to know we can do big things in this state,''
Sherrer said.
</P>
<P>
   Sherrer and the Commerce and Housing Department he runs have
faced questions in the Legislature about economic development.
Paying to sponsor the nationally televised football game on Fox
Sports Net may prompt more.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this stuff is beyond me,'' said State Sen. Ed Pugh, a
Republican from Wamego. ``I don't understand it. It doesn't make
sense to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Pugh said state law should be changed so proceeds from the
lottery would be channeled directly to public schools.
</P>
<P>
   According to calculations from the Commerce and Housing
Department, the state will receive considerable value for its
$84,000 game sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas has been mentioned in 1,569 pregame radio and television
ads, exposure that would have cost $300,000 if the state paid for
each spot, the department said.
</P>
<P>
   The economic effect of increased visits to the state could be
millions of dollars, the department said.
</P>
<P>
   As the main sponsor of the game, Kansas paid the most of any
sponsor, said David Gardiner, senior vice president and general
manager of Dorna Sports Promotions, which is staging the contest.
The other sponsors, he said, range from a grocery store chain to a
radio station.
</P>
<P>
   Money from the sponsorships, along with other revenue from the
game, will go to the two participating schools to cover game
expenses, and to charitable causes at the Eddie Robinson
Foundation, named after the legendary college football coach.
</P>
<P>
   With Kansas State growing into a college football power,
sponsoring one of their games is smart, said State Rep. David
Adkins, a Leawood Republican who is the outgoing chairman of the
House Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense has been, when it comes to marketing the state,
Kansas has been far behind our neighboring states,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the state hasn't done nearly as much tourist
advertising as Missouri. Kansas spends about $900,000 a year, while
Missouri spends about $2 million on television advertising alone.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Driskill, director of the Missouri Economic Development
Department, said his state buys television ads in several states to
entice tourists, and periodically meets and entertains consultants
dealing in corporation relocations.
</P>
<P>
   He cannot recall his agency ever sponsoring a football game.
Until this week, he wasn't aware of the Kansas project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the fact,'' said Driskill, ``that they're coming to
Missouri to advertise Kansas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
