A1754 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     08-25 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME, TIZNOW HEALING OLD WOUNDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL MAR, Calif. _ Jay Robbins isn't beating himself up over the
mistake. He doesn't even seem to regard it as a mistake. Still, it
must gnaw at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Less as time passes,'' said the trainer of Pacific Classic
contender Tiznow.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 9, 1995, Robbins entered a 2-year-old son of Cee's Tizzy
and Cee's Song in a $32,000 claiming race for maidens, and watched
the horse run a close second in an encouraging debut. Then Robbins
watched with surprise as the horse was led away to someone else's
barn, having been claimed by Dan Hendricks.
</P>
<P>
   The horse was Budroyale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't know how he got claimed,'' Robbins said this
week. ``That was Cee's Tizzy's first crop (of offspring), so it was
hard to judge how good a sire he was going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine Robbins' surprise when Budroyale went on to earn more
than $2 million in four-plus years of so-called overachievement
that included second-place finishes in the Breeders' Cup Classic,
Hollywood Gold Cup and Santa Anita Handicap for the father-and-son
training team of Ted and Ted H. West.
</P>
<P>
   Budroyale's rags-to-riches story has been told so many times,
it's understandable if Robbins doesn't care to hear any more about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the first time, and it's not the last time, someone
loses (a good) one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Robbins, though, the story may yet have a happy ending.
Saturday at Del Mar, the 54-year-old trainer will saddle 3-year-old
Tiznow, the 5-1 fourth choice on the morning line for the $1
million Pacific Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Tiznow is Budroyale's full brother _ a son of Cee's Tizzy and
Cee's Song, bred and co-owned by Cecilia Straub-Rubens, same as his
elder kin.
</P>
<P>
   Tiznow is no Budroyale clone. Though both are listed as bay,
Robbins said, ``He's a different (darker) color, and he's much
bigger than Budroyale.''
</P>
<P>
   A full sister, 2-year-old Tizsweet, resides in the next stall in
Robbins' Del Mar barn. Tizsweet is gray.
</P>
<P>
   Tiznow, to be ridden for the first time Saturday by Chris
McCarron, could turn out to be a racing rarity, a full sibling who
lives up to the family expectations.
</P>
<P>
   As the lone 3-year-old and least accomplished of the seven
horses entered in the 10th Pacific Classic, Tiznow might be
overlooked by handicappers focusing on 9-5 favorite General
Challenge (the defending champion), 5-2 second choice Skimming
(eight-length winner of the recent San Diego Handicap), and 7-2
third choice Ecton Park (the 1999 Louisiana Super Derby winner
shipping in from Saratoga).
</P>
<P>
   But hidden in Tiznow's record (5 starts, 2 wins, 2 seconds,
earnings of $225,550, all against horses of his age) is the
potential for an upset.
</P>
<P>
   First, consider that as a rule of thumb, 3-year-old
thoroughbreds are still maturing physically and mentally, so what
you see in the Daily Racing Form is not necessarily what you get.
</P>
<P>
   Next, remember the success of 3-year-olds in the Pacific
Classic. Four have run in the race, which is for 3-year-olds and
up. Two have won it _ Best Pal in 1991 and General Challenge in
1999 _ and another, Dramatic Gold, finished third in 1994. None of
them were favored.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, look at how Tiznow has improved since finishing sixth
in his debut in a Santa Anita sprint _ not a claiming race, as if
you had to ask _ in April. After breaking his maiden by 8{ lengths
at Hollywood Park in May, he edged Dixie Union to win the Affirmed
Handicap at 10-1 in July.
</P>
<P>
   Later in July, he ran second to Captain Steve in the Swaps
Stakes. He and jockey Victor Espinoza got boxed in on the turn for
home, trouble that might have cost Tiznow the 2{-length margin of
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Tiznow's trouble on Swaps day was self-inflicted. The
nervous colt sweated away precious energy in the saddling paddock.
But Robbins blames that on the fact he was training his horses at
Santa Anita and vanning them to Hollywood Park for their races.
Tiznow didn't have a chance to get familiar with the Hollywood Park
paddock.
</P>
<P>
   Because Robbins is training his horses at Del Mar this summer,
he has been able to school Tiznow in the paddock here. Robbins
doesn't expect another display of nerves.
</P>
<P>
   Tiznow will carry 117 pounds, seven less than the older horses,
according to the Pacific Classic's weight-for-age format.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going a mile and a quarter, I think seven pounds is pretty
meaningful,'' Robbins said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that isn't why he entered Tiznow in Del Mar's
biggest race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just thought he's training really well down here,'' Robbins
said. ``It remains to be seen whether he can run with these older
horses. I think he can.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, then Tiznow can achieve something Saturday that Budroyale
never did. For all his success and popularity, and for all the
aggravation he caused his original trainer, Budroyale never won a
Grade I race or a million-dollar race.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCENE: Ecton Park arrived at Del Mar on Thursday and had
a two-mile gallop to get used to the track. All of the Pacific
Classic horses are now on the grounds. In post-position order, they
are: River Keen (Espinoza riding), General Challenge (Corey
Nakatani), Euchre (David Flores), Tiznow, Skimming (Garrett Gomez),
Ecton Park (Kent Desormeaux) and Forty One Carats (Eddie
Delahoussaye).
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Classic will be run as the eighth race at about 4:15
p.m. PDT on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The 12:30 p.m. PDT first post is 90 minutes earlier than usual.
Gates open at 9 a.m. PDT.
</P>
<P>
   Race coverage will start at 3:30 p.m. PDT on Fox Sports Net. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kevin Modesti is a Daily News columnist. His horse racing column
appears on Friday. He can be reached at (818) 713-3616. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
