<HEADLINE>
L.A. SCHOOLS BOSS LISTS SEVEN IMPROVEMENT AREAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kicking off the first year of the newly
reorganized Los Angeles Unified School District, Superintendent Roy
Romer unveiled a seven-point plan to improve schools.
</P>
<P>
   At a back-to-school pep rally, Romer spoke on Thursday to 1,800
principals, assistant principals and administrators at a hotel in
downtown Los Angeles. It was his first public address to district
staff since assuming office July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Romer's management plan calls for standards-based guidelines, an
assessment of those standards, more classroom materials, better
quality teaching, parental involvement, and more space and time for
teachers to help students learn.
</P>
<P>
   The former governor of Colorado laced his talk with folksy
analogies, declaring that teachers can improve their skills by
learning the lesson of corn farmers who help each other grow the
best corn.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I became governor of Colorado, it was as sick
economically as it could get,'' he said. ``We turned that place
around. We had a state, at the end of 12 years, that was about the
top of the heap. It wasn't just the governor who did it. It was a
team of very talented people who did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Romer said teachers and principals need to work together to
improve education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all rowing oars on the boat,'' he said. ``And let me
tell you, LAUSD has a lot of people who want to torpedo the boat.
So everybody in the teaching corps and in the management corps
ought to proceed to say we've got to improve our performance or
we're out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   To help accommodate an expected surge of 80,000 students by
2006, the district plans to break ground on nine new schools during
the next 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Space is crucial,'' said Romer, who this week helped break
ground on the San Fernando Valley's first new elementary school in
29 years. ``We're going to build 65,000 spaces in the next five or
six years, but we're going to have a growth of enrollment of 80,000
students.''
</P>
<P>
   He also encouraged principals to use their authority to make
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a moral responsibility, if nothing else, to say, I've
got to manage to get the maximum impact on those kids having an
opportunity to learn,'' he said. ``This institution is not here for
the benefit of us adults.''
</P>
<P>
   During a question-and-answer period afterward, Fernangeles
Elementary School Assistant Principal Charles Addcox asked what
Romer thought about a shortage of computers for students still
receiving bilingual education.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Valley principal said students in Intensive Academic
Support classes, which provide remedial education, are receiving
computers and software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our same IAS classes that have (Prop. 227) waiver-learners do
not get those computers and software.''
</P>
<P>
   Romer said he wasn't familiar with the issue but would
investigate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
