<SLUG> BC-SURVIVOR-TALK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. RESIDENTS SOUND OFF ON `SURVIVOR' OUTCOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Survivor'' winner Richard Hatch may be a
low-down scheming ``snake,'' but much of the talk around town
Thursday focused on trucker Susan Hawk's tirade during the TV
series' cliffhanging climax.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was vile and horrific,'' comedian Robert Lee, 43, said
outside a Woodland Hills coffee shop. ``She should be a truck
driver so she can be confined in a small space with no one else
around.''
</P>
<P>
   A day after the wildly popular ``Survivor'' show concluded, the
chatter at water coolers, coffee shops and just about everywhere
else was focused on the castaways.
</P>
<P>
   People were dissecting the strategy of million-dollar winner
Richard and the power plays and double-crosses of the other
contestants _ among them Susan.
</P>
<P>
   Between breathless recounts of the highlights, Lee, Pierce
College freshman Stacey Lopez and others agreed that the CBS hit
series struck a chord with Americans by reflecting some
contemporary moral attitudes, especially winning at all costs.
</P>
<P>
   Richard made no pretensions about playing the game as ruthlessly
as possible, forming an alliance with other cast members to
eliminate rival contestants with precision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Character at this point doesn't matter in America _ it only
matters if you get the job done and Rich did,'' Lee said, as his
friend Todd Shaffer cringed.
</P>
<P>
   The naked ambition exhibited on the show left him embarrassed,
Shaffer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brought out the worst in people,'' said the 38-year-old
sales representative from Torrance. ``It was like a bad accident.
You just keep driving and hope everyone is OK but rubberneck to see
what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened was a nail-biting thriller in which an estimated
51 million viewers saw Richard beat rival Kelly Wiglesworth by a
single tie-breaking vote in a ``tribal council'' of their peers.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the people who ignored the weekly series or watched
little or none of the final episode knew Richard had a bad
reputation that was expected to cost him the contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won?!!'' said Chris Ramsey, 42, of Pasadena, who favored
retired Navy SEAL Rudy Boesch, many people's odds-on favorite to
win. ``Secretly I figured (Richard) would win just because the
world seems to be backwards these days. His values accurately
characterized our society _ ingenuousness.''
</P>
<P>
   Ludivine Poirier, a French native living in Woodland Hills,
could barely contain her contempt for Susan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was really happy this mean woman was out of the
picture _ we hated her,'' Poirier, 25, said outside the coffee shop
along Ventura Boulevard. ``When I came here it was the first thing
everyone wanted to know: Did you watch `Survivor' last night?''
</P>
<P>
   Poirier found Richard, a 39-year-old corporate trainer from
Rhode Island, to be funny, sweet and nice.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said she found inspiration in Susan's blistering attack on
Kelly, whom she called a two-faced rat who, if dying, would best be
left to the vultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire that she had the guts to tell Kelly off straight
out,'' Lopez said. ``Everyone knew Richard was evil.''
</P>
<P>
   David Arias, 21, an after-school worker from Canoga Park, rooted
for Rudy: ``I guess he was the least objectionable.''
</P>
<P>
   For all its popularity, the show had its share of detractors.
</P>
<P>
   Psychotherapist Andrea Sussman of Sherman Oaks knocked reality
television as creatively void and a trivializing of real life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's people out there who probably know who each of the
survivors are by name but it's scary they don't know who's running
for president or is in the Senate,'' said Sussman, 44, sipping an
iced coffee outside a neighborhood coffee shop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 0018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1760 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT &LR;      08-25 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DETERMINED TO PLAY FOOTBALL, AND FINALLY ABLE TO PROVE It  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Replacements  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keanu Reeves, Gene Hackman, Brooke Langton, Jack Warden, Ace
Yonamine, Orlando Jones &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Howard Deutch &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13
</P>
<P>
   105 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The movie's tag line gets the point across like a tackle
rumbling along with a recovered fumble: ``Pros on strike. Regular
guys get to play!'' After that, everybody might as well go home
because absolutely nothing happens that one hasn't seen before in a
sports movie.
</P>
<P>
   With his $5 million-a-year players walking the picket line, Ed
O'Neill ( Warden), the natty, boozy owner of the Washington
Sentinels, enlists Jimmy McGinty (Hackman), that great old coach
from the '80s, to put together a team of scabs to carry on the
season. McGinty rounds up a crowd of characters he has known (don't
we all): the mad-dog linebacker, the swift receiver who couldn't
catch a balloon, the inevitable convict on loan from prison, the
400-pound lineman down from 600 pounds. (He's a sumo wrestler.) ``I
love to see a fat guy score!'' McGinty exclaims. He's come to the
right place.
</P>
<P>
   For a quarterback he hires a sad sack named Shane Falco
(Reeves). While at Ohio State, Falco was so badly whipped by
Florida State (who wasn't?) that he has quit the sport in shame and
now scrapes barnacles off yacht bottoms. The point McGinty wants to
get across to him and all his misfits is that they aren't
necessarily losers. For this one moment they can be all they ever
dreamed of. So crank up those self-images, get out there and
persevere.
</P>
<P>
   Nasty strikers turn over Falco's pick-up truck, but he drops his
wimp routine, swallows his self-loathing and starts to throw
touchdown passes. What's more, he's a selfless leader, which
impresses Annabelle (Langton), who heads a very hot crew of
cheerleaders recruited from a strip joint. But to reach the
playoffs, the fill-in Sentinels will have to defeat the genuine
Dallas team, the league champions, who have just crossed the picket
line. That's absurd, of course, but do you doubt that redemption is
at hand?
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE _ Football bumps and bruises are augmented by a
whistling-good barroom brawl.
</P>
<P>
   SEX _ The networks would censor the cheerleading routines.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY _ Everything. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTE _ There is heavy consumption of alcohol. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 10 _ Too violent, too profane. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10 AND UP _ In its own obvious way, the film has some
things to say about believing in oneself. That can't be all bad,
and older children will enjoy the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Hollow Man  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Bacon, Elisabeth Shue, Josh Brolin, Kim Dickens, William
Devane, Greg Grunberg, Joey Slotnick &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Paul Verhoeven &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R
</P>
<P>
   114 minutes
</P>
<P>
   ``You should be working,'' reads a message taped to the spot in
the ceiling where Sebastan Caine (Bacon) occasionally gazes when
he's at his computer. The hard-driving Caine heads one of the more
sensitive research projects around Washington. He and his team
inject animals with blue fluid and make them invisible. But they
can't make them visible again _ that is, until Caine cracks the
reversion problem and reconstitutes a gorilla named Isabel.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's a sensitive. There's no stating how badly the
Pentagon wants this stuff. Without telling the military, Caine
decides to take the project to level three _ humans, specifically
himself. This alarms his assistants: Caine's ex-lover Linda (Shue),
Matt (Brolin) and Sarah (Dickens), the project veterinarian, who
already has a problem with Caine over his vivisectionist's attitude
toward the animals, visible and invisible, caged at the lab.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Caine injects himself and disappears. Unlike
Isabel, however, he can't be brought back. At first he is vastly
annoyed, but soon he begins to enjoy popping around the lab scaring
the daylights out of his team members, who can't detect him unless
they wear infrared glasses or he's in contact with liquid, which
outlines his form. Later there's nothing to do but escape from the
lab and have some fun on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this brings out darker elements in Caine, who
immediately rapes a neighbor he's previously only admired through
the venetian blinds. Then, while invisibly spying on Linda, he
discovers she is having an affair with Matt, which sends him back
to the lab for a gory run of terror. The glasses would help.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE _ Graphic and extreme, with people skewered, ripped and
snapped. The same goes for animals (add munched).
</P>
<P>
   SEX _ Caine strips down completely (rear view) before his
injection, and there is partial nudity at other times.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY _ As pronounced as the violence.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTE _ Not that children should find their way into this
film, but if they do, many will be upset at the treatment of their
animal friends. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 14 _ Obviously a bad bet on all counts.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14-17 _ High-tech blood baths will always attract.
</P>
<P>
   Autumn in New York  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winona Ryder, Richard Gere, Anthony LaPaglia, Elaine Stritch,
Sherry Stringfield &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Joan Chen &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13
</P>
<P>
   105 minutes
</P>
<P>
   There she sits, all dewy and ripe and positively gurgling at the
notion of taking up with the nicely notorious millionaire
restaurateur 26 years her senior. This being fairly routine for the
graying, tousled 48-year-old Will (Gere), it is with a kind of
weary, amused resignation that he's drawn into an affair with
22-year-old Charlotte (Ryder). It's OK for now, he tells her, but
she should understand that they have no future.
</P>
<P>
   At the time he doesn't understand the ramifications of that
remark. Will is old enough for Charlotte's mother, and in fact he
was involved with her mother before her death. As for Charlotte,
she is ill with a tumor and a heart problem that has her collapsing
around town at dramatic moments. She hasn't long, he learns, a year
at most.
</P>
<P>
   Will being Will, he has a rooftop fling with an old girlfriend.
To him, that is as consequential as walking the dog, but it rankles
Charlotte. He encounters another attractive young woman
(Stringfield), only this time it's his daughter, whom he's never
met. Mulling that one over and deciding he can't do without
Charlotte, he begs her to let him love her.
</P>
<P>
   After reuniting very cute, she glows and acts adorably feisty
while he stays devoted and trots around looking for a surgeon to
operate on her when the time comes. Then, around Christmas, the
crisis strikes.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE _ None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX _ Will and Charlotte make love, but gauzily and mostly from
the shoulders up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY _ Little of consequence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 11 _ A sleep-inducer, and inappropriate anyway. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11 AND UP _ A narrow stratum of teen-agers might be drawn,
but others would make no connection. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 0025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1762 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-EXPOS-LAD     08-25 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-EXPOS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK DOES IT ALL IN DODGERS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chan Ho Park stood at home plate and watched. Just
like the big guys.
</P>
<P>
   To the Dodgers, no one is bigger right now than Park, whose
first major-league home run provided the confetti in Thursday
afternoon's 7-0 victory over the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Park's pitching _ seven more scoreless innings to add
to a string that has reached 15 _ that gave the Dodgers their third
consecutive victory and a hope for a tailwind leading into their
upcoming road trip and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt great for his home run, but it is the way he has taken
charge that could really mean a lot the rest of the way,'' pitching
coach Claude Osteen said. ``Our starters are coming together and
Chan Ho is a big part. You need that down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with a doubleheader today against the struggling
Chicago Cubs at Wrigley Field, the Dodgers are facing a string of
mutts in these dog days of August. They are out to prove they are
not one of them, even if they still trail idle San Francisco by 7{
games with 36 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Including Montreal, which played the last three games of the
series without superstar Vladimir Guerrero (strained left
shoulder), the Dodgers face the Cubs, Milwaukee Brewers,
Philadelphia Phillies and Pittsburgh Pirates during a 17-day
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Thursday, those teams were a combined 71 games under
.500.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a big series for us to get going,'' said outfielder
Shawn Green, who homered and appears to be breaking out of a
two-month slump. ``Obviously, we're still a ways back, but we're
looking to give ourselves a chance, to get really hot and sneak in
there somehow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone is playing more relaxed than we were a couple
of weeks ago. when we were only 2{ games back. But now we're just
going out there and playing and better things are happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially to Park (13-8). After giving up a first-inning home
run to the Mets' Derek Bell last Sunday, he has allowed just nine
hits his last 15 innings. He has struck out 17 during that stretch
and issued just two walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am having fun,'' Park said. ``As long as I work hard, days
like this will come.''
</P>
<P>
   His victory came one day after Kevin Brown took a perfect game
into the seventh inning and defeated Montreal 4-1. Today's Game 1
starter Darren Dreifort has won six consecutive decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is finally the starting pitching that we have been
lacking,'' manager Davey Johnson said. ``We need to build some
consistency and momentum. You do that with your starters.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is well aware his team fell apart the last time they won
three straight. It came earlier this month after the Dodgers drew
within 2{ games of the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Then they dropped the next three to Milwaukee and Chicago and
six of seven overall.
</P>
<P>
   Until Wednesday, Brown hadn't won for almost a month. The fourth
and fifth starters are winless since June 6, when Eric Gagne beat
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had the pitching we're getting now,'' said Johnson,
who pulled Park on Thursday after seven innings and 109 pitches.
``Chan Ho was perfect today, ask any hitter. He was totally in
control. It was a big and outstanding day for him. He was so
focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Dodgers put away Montreal with four runs in the
fourth. They strung together four consecutive hits, including
Green's 23rd homer. Third baseman Adrian Beltre had an RBI single,
one of his three hits.
</P>
<P>
   Even Park drove in his second run with a base hit to right.
</P>
<P>
   But it was his home run the inning before off Expos starter
Javier Vazquez (8-6) that brought to life the crowd that was much
smaller than the announced 28,896. Park crushed Vazquez's first
pitch 427 feet into the bleachers in right-center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun, my first home run, Park said. ``I was feeling good
even before the game. I was focused from the start and just trusted
my grip. I just threw my curve and changeup the whole day. I didn't
think about it. I just threw with confidence.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
