u f BC-TIRE-RECALL-NYT &LR;      08-25 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-RECALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD ATTACKS THE LAWYERS PURSUING SUITS OVER TIRES
</HEADLINE>
  By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ Officials of the Ford Motor Co. lashed out
Thursday at plaintiffs' lawyers suing the automaker and
Bridgestone/Firestone Inc., accusing them of endangering public
safety by calling for a broader recall of tires and of distributing
Ford documents out of context to journalists.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday afternoon at Ford's headquarters
here, executives again rejected lawyers' calls for a wider recall
of 15-inch Firestone tires and for a new recall of 16-inch
Firestone tires. Only the tires already recalled pose an unusual
risk of failure, said Tom Baughman, Ford's engineering director for
North American light trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials said that dealerships were being mobbed by
customers insisting on replacements for tires not covered by the
recall, draining the supply of new tires and forcing people with
hazardous tires to continue driving on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A broader recall is wrong,'' said Helen Petrauskas, Ford's
vice president for safety and environmental engineering. ``It's
wrong because many good tires will be delivered and used to replace
good tires _ and people who have tires which should be replaced
will have to stand in line and wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Hoar, a consultant for plaintiffs' lawyers who is
coordinating much of the litigation against Ford and Firestone,
said that the two companies should prove that the tires not
recalled are safe by releasing all of their raw data on the
production and failure rates of many sizes of tires. ``It's Ford's
and Firestone's responsibility to restore public faith in them and
in this process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators reiterated Thursday that they had made no
decision on whether the recall undertaken by Ford and Firestone was
broad enough and would continue to investigate many Firestone
tires. Congressional committees are also beginning to look into the
tire problem.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said it would put extensive information on tire failures on
its Web site, www.ford.com, by Friday morning. The data, including
a series of charts, shows that the failure rates for the tires
being recalled, particularly tires made in Decatur, Ill., are up to
hundreds of times those for other Firestone tires. Last week, Ford
put the data on its media site, which is available only to
reporters with passwords.
</P>
<P>
   Hoar said that Ford should make its files available to the
public rather than calculating failure rates and other information
in ways that might serve the automaker's interest.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Vines, a Ford spokesman, said that Ford and Firestone had
replaced 13.3 percent of the 6.5 million recalled tires in the last
two weeks. That is an unusually fast pace in an industry that
normally takes as long as two years for a recall and often only
persuades 50 percent to 60 percent of customers to bring in their
vehicles for work. But the pace of the recall has failed to satisfy
angry Explorer owners at Ford and Firestone dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Petrauskas also accused plaintiffs' lawyers of distributing
documents out of context to journalists with little familiarity
with the engineering process through which automobiles are
designed. The documents involve potential safety problems that Ford
engineers identified in designing the Explorer. Petrauskas said
that engineers at any automaker analyze vehicle designs for
possible safety problems and then fix them before putting vehicles
into production, and she said that Ford did this with the Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really struck that somehow it's being held against us''
that Ford engineers tried to identify potential safety problems in
early prototypes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Petrauskas' comments were indicative of a common worry at Ford
that plaintiffs' lawyers will dribble out documents for months
whenever the recall fades from public attention. The lawyers ``have
a lot of documents,'' fretted a senior Ford executive in an
interview last weekend. Hoar said that Ford had been more selective
than plaintiffs' lawyers in releasing information by refusing to
make raw data available and by labeling some of its boxes of
filings with regulators as proprietary information that cannot be
included in the public docket.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
