<HEADER>
A1777 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-COPS-SUIT-2Takes-LADN     08-25 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPS-SUIT-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAPD ABUSED WHISTLE-BLOWERS, LAWSUIT CLAIMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETH BARRETT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ LAPD Chief Bernard C. Parks and top commanding
officers routinely punished lower-ranking officers who reported
wrongdoing by supervisors, according to a class-action lawsuit
filed in Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   The 43 plaintiffs claim in the suit filed Thursday they blew the
whistle on captains suspected of stealing computers, of falsifying
overtime records in the Devonshire and West Valley divisions, and
of ordering crime-scene response times falsely enhanced, among
other infractions.
</P>
<P>
   For breaking that ``code of silence,'' the officers and civilian
workers said they were targeted by the department as troublemakers
and either disciplined unfairly or drummed out of the department
entirely. About one-third of the plaintiffs are Valley officers or
civilian workers.
</P>
<P>
   The class, which has yet to be certified, is anticipated to grow
to up to 500 officers seeking as much as $100 million in a jury
trial, as well as an injunction to prevent retaliations against
whistle-blowers in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police officers report misconduct and then they are retaliated
against for the pettiest things,'' attorney Bradley C. Gage said
during a press conference at his Woodland Hills office. ``It comes
from the top.''
</P>
<P>
   LAPD spokesman Cmdr. David Kalish said the department doesn't
comment on pending litigation. But he defended the disciplinary
system and argued that morale has not suffered among officers who
support Parks' efforts to get rid of cops who engage in unethical
or illegal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The discipline system of the LAPD is absolutely fair and
equitable for everyone involved,'' Kalish said. ``There is no doubt
the chief holds his employees accountable, but it's always done in
a fair and consistent manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Gage said he did not have specific evidence or documents linking
Parks to the alleged retaliations, but that it was the chief's
disciplinary policies that contributed to the ``pattern and
practice'' of retributions contributing to a climate of fear and
silence in which scandals like Rampart flourish.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the police officers are more afraid of the administration
than they are of the bad guys out there, then they have to be
careful, they can't say anything,'' Gage said. ``It's this code of
silence that's created out of fear that can lead to corruption
within a department.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the captains and other high-ranking officers accused of
misconduct were named in the lawsuit, and it could not be
determined late Thursday whether those identified had been
investigated by the department.
</P>
<P>
   The litigation culminates several years of complaints by members
of the Los Angeles Police Department's rank and file and their
union that Parks has been an arbitrary and draconian disciplinarian
responsible for the department's troubles in recruiting and
retaining cops. Parks has made discipline central to his vision of
reform.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit is a more aggressive and direct thrust at Parks than
anything the Los Angeles Police Protective League, representing
officers, has ventured.
</P>
<P>
   League President Ted Hunt said nonetheless the LAPD's
disciplinary system widely is viewed as dysfunctional, with the
punishment viewed as often in excess of the infraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not working; it's illogical and irrational,'' Hunt said,
adding that nearly every day, an officer contacts him out of
frustration with the department and its rules.
</P>
<P>
   West Valley Division Officer Johneen Jones is a case in point,
Gage said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who appeared with about a half-dozen other plaintiffs at
the press briefing, had complained about a ``No Fat Cops'' poster
displayed in West Valley Division. Jones and several other
employees found the placard offensive.
</P>
<P>
   The poster, however, was deemed to have ``significant historical
value,'' and Capt. Lee Carter allowed it to remain. It was put up
again by Capt. Julie Nelson when she was transferred to another
station, according to the lawsuit. Carter and Nelson could not be
reached for comment late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is now before a disciplinary Board of Rights, where the
charge against her is refusing to obey a direct order given by a
detective, according to LAPD records. Gage said the charge of
insubordination is in connection with photographing the poster and
refusing to leave when ordered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's outrageous what happened to her,'' Gage said.
``She was the victim of a captain who overreacted, and of a chief
who is very punitive.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Devonshire and West Valley divisions, officers who
reported a captain's falsification of overtime all were forced out
of the department or are currently in disciplinary proceedings, the
lawsuit states. The captain has left the department, Gage said. It
could not be determined whether he had been disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Other officers objected when they were ordered to punch their
police-car computers prematurely so it would appear they were
arriving at crime scenes more quickly. The lawsuit said they, too,
were forced out of the department after bogus claims were filed
against them.
</P>
<P>
   Kalish, the LAPD's spokesman, said the department's rationale
for terminating officers is always set forth in Board of Rights
transcripts, but that some retire or resign before their cases can
be heard. Several of the officers who are plaintiffs in the lawsuit
fall into that category.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-count complaint includes allegations of discrimination,
harassment, retaliation for filing claims of discrimination and
conspiracy to retaliate against police officers for reporting
criminal and other serious misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   The retaliations the plaintiffs claim occurred had the added
effect of so frightening other officers that they soon learned to
``keep their mouth shut,'' making them less likely to report
corruption, notably in the Rampart Division, where several officers
are suspected of framing and physically harming suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once police officers keep quiet, officers, supervisors and
managers are then able to engage in criminal conduct, harming all
citizens of the city of Los Angeles,'' the lawsuit claims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 0050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1779 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GOOGLE--GROWING-SFCHR     08-25 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOOGLE--GROWING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOGLE SENSES THAT IT'S TIME TO GROW UP  &HT;     BY VERNE KOPYTOFF
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; Google Inc.'s brief history, from its inception in 1998 by two
Stanford University students to becoming one of the Internet's
leading search engines, is posted on a wall at the firm's Mountain
View headquarters.
<P>
   The posting shows the company's popularity growth to nearly 40
million queries a day, in typical Google fashion: The history is
written in green, purple and red crayons, with exclamation points
punctuating the biggest successes.
</P>
<P>
   So goes business at Google, a company trying to emerge from
adolescence into maturity. It has quickly become a major force in
the Internet industry, underscored by its agreement in June to
provide its search engine to Yahoo Inc., the giant Santa Clara Web
portal.
</P>
<P>
   But like many Internet companies these days, Google is grappling
with very adult issues such as revenue and profit. Long reluctant
about commercialization, the company is just now focusing on some
business basics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to build the ultimate search engine,'' said Larry
Page, Google's chief executive and co-founder. ``We think that we
can make search engines better every month, and I don't see that
ending anytime soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Google's popularity is based on providing particularly relevant
results to user queries. The company usually ranks near the top in
studies of search-engine quality.
</P>
<P>
   Like many others, Google's search engine relies on software that
retrieves Web pages based on word placement and headlines. But it
also includes a proprietary technology called Page-Rank that
retrieves Web pages based on the number and quality of other Web
pages that point to it.
</P>
<P>
   Another lure is Google's simplistic design that is unusual for
all the blank white space. The sparseness helps it download faster
than most search engines, so much so that the company gloats by
displaying for users the time it takes to respond to every query.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, it harks back to the original image of search
engines,'' said Wit Andrews, an Internet industry analyst with the
Gartner Group, a market research company in Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Sullivan, founder of Search Engine Watch, an online
newsletter that follows the search engine industry, said many
people praise Google for its search performance. But he added that
other companies may provide better searches for certain queries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because people are talking about Google doesn't mean that
the other search engines are bad,'' Sullivan said. ``Google may not
be good on a particular query. If you wanted to find multimedia or
audio-visual files, Google wouldn't be helpful at all.'' Google
faces strong competition from the likes of AltaVista Co., the Palo
Alto Web portal, and Inktomi Corp., the Foster City firm that
licenses search technology to Web sites such as Lycos and America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies dwarf Google in size and experience. But they
nevertheless feel threatened.
</P>
<P>
   For example, AltaVista released a bare-bones search engine in
May called Raging Search, partly in reaction to Google. Troy Toman,
general manager of search at Inktomi, said that competition with
Google has pushed his company to be more aggressive but adds that
no firm ``is going to conquer the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, Google replaced Inktomi as Yahoo's search engine, one
of the top prizes in the search-engine industry. Phu Hoang, the
vice president who oversees search at Yahoo, said his firm switched
services because of Google's ability to deliver useful responses
and handle millions of queries a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Google has really built a name for themselves out in the
Internet community,'' he said. ``Our users have been asking us to
work with them.''
</P>
<P>
   How much of a financial success the Yahoo contract is for Google
is unclear, though. Google gave Yahoo an undisclosed number of
stock options as part of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Google, named after googol, the term for 1 followed by 100
zeros, was created by Page and Sergey Brin, now the company's
president, while they were doctoral students in computer science at
Stanford. They operated the Web site out of their dorm room for a
few months, quickly realizing that their idea had potential.
</P>
<P>
   Brin and Page, now both 27, tried to shop Google to the big
search engines of the day like Excite and Infoseek. But those firms
were preoccupied at the time with becoming Web portals by adding
message boards and news, prompting Google's founders to go it
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Google's offices reflect its college dormitory origin with Lava
lamps, a disco ball, hockey sticks and a model roller coaster. But
on a recent afternoon, the headquarters was more like a library
with most of its 120 employees in their cubicles, staring at
computers.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Google has expanded rapidly. The company
announced the biggest search index with 560 million Web pages, it
added 10 languages to its search engine for the international
market and signed several agreements with wireless firms.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign of its maturing process, Google last week
launched its first concerted effort to solicit advertising. Prior
to the announcement, Google's strategy consisted mostly of letting
companies discover for themselves that they could advertise on its
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Brin, Google's co-founder, says the company is not
obsessed with maximizing profits. His strategy is to provide a
better search engine to lure loyal users and reap profits later.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we wanted to sell ad banners, we could call DoubleClick and
be profitable today,'' said Brin, referring to the dominant online
advertising placement company. ``But we can be more successful in
the long run if we grow our user base. I've been happy with our
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of Google searches is increasing by an average of
nearly 20 percent a month, according to the company. Google is
particularly popular among computer-savvy males, though the company
says its demographics are slowly shifting to more mainstream users.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Google was ranked fifth among search engines and
navigation Web sites in terms of unique visitors, according to
Media Metrix, the online research firm. However, that ranking
represents only traffic at the Google.com Web site and not the
search services it provides to Yahoo, Netscape and other partners.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, most of Google's searches come via the companies that
license its technology. Google's own Web site handles 14 million
searches a day, while its partners account for another 26 million,
according to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Because Google is private, it is immune from the criticism
leveled at other Internet firms these days about declining stock
prices. Brin said his company has no immediate plans to go public,
but doesn't rule it out for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews, the Internet industry analyst, said it is unclear what
direction Google will travel in the coming years. While Google has
carved out a niche in providing searches, he said, that is a
relatively limited business.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does Google want to be when they grow up?'' Andrews
asked. ``I don't know the answer to that question. Maybe they'll
look like a competitor to a Yahoo. Maybe they'll do intranet and
local search capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Google's executives say they will not do is transform
their company into a Web portal. While the firm may add
capabilities such as online image and music searches, according to
its co-founders, it will stay away from calenders, news and chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Search is a very core function,'' Brin said. ``It deserves 100
percent focus.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Verne Kopytoff at verne(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
