<SLUG> BC-TECH-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE
</P>
<P>
   FTC SUES ADULT WEB SITES OVER BILLING
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission and the New York attorney general
have sued the owners and operators of a network of adult-oriented
Web sites, including www.playgirl.com and www.highsociety.com,
asserting they illegally billed thousands of people for services
that were advertised as free, and for charging many others who
never visited the Web sites at all. The suit, filed in U.S.
District Court in Manhattan, contends that Crescent Publishing
Group of New York, along with 64 affiliated corporations, routinely
charge people who provided credit card information ostensibly to
verify they were over 18 before they could view the adult sites.
Telephone calls to Crescent Publishing, and its owner, Bruce Chew,
and principal, David Bernstein, were not returned Thursday &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW MP3.COM HEARING SET
</P>
<P>
   Hearings are set for Monday in the copyright infringement trial
of Seagram's Universal Music Group against MP3.com, following a
ruling on Wednesday by a federal judge that could limit the damages
owed by the Internet music start-up. U.S. District Judge Jed S.
Rakoff ruled that damages would be assessed for copyright
violations of each compact disc, not for every individual song that
was infringed by Mp3.com, as the recording industry had wanted.
Universal and four other major record labels sued MP3.com in
January, saying it had made illegal digital copies of songs
available on its site. In April, Rakoff ruled against MP3.com,
saying it had infringed record company copyrights. MP3.com has
settled with four of the record companies.
</P>
<P>
   DEALS
</P>
<P>
   ETRADE BUYING A FINANCIAL START-UP
</P>
<P>
   ETrade Group, the online brokerage firm in Menlo Park, Calif.,
is scooping up another Internet startup. This time it is
PrivateAccounts.com, a Minneapolis-based venture that planned to
connect individual investors with well-known money managers. ETrade
did not disclose what it was paying for PrivateAccounts.com, which
has not even opened for business. Later this year, ETrade plans to
start charging fees to customers with $100,000 or more that they
want managed for them, said Liat Rorer, an ETrade vice-president.
Rorer declined to say who the managers would be or what the cost
would be. ETrade also just bought the Electronic Investing Corp., a
San Francisco-based start-up that had planned to offer online
trading of baskets of stocks. Through these acquisitions, the
brokerage firm hopes to broaden its product line and become less
dependent on commissions from stock trades. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   24/7 MEDIA BUYS WEBSITE RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   24/7 Media in New York, a global interactive media and
technology services company, said Thursday that it had acquired
Website Results in Los Angeles, an Internet marketing technologies
company. The purchase was a stock transaction valued at $95
million. Website Results, with 36 employees and revenue estimated
at $6 million for the first half of this year from clients like
eBay and ETrade, becomes an autonomous division of 24/7 Media.
Douglas C. Wagner, 34, continues as president at Website Results.
</P>
<P>
   HARDWARE
</P>
<P>
   INTEL LOOKING INTO NEW AREA
</P>
<P>
   Intel is forming an industry working group to foster standards
and protocols for so-called peer-to-peer computing, particularly in
business environments. Popularized by music distribution services
like Napster and Gnutella, peer-to-peer computing is a set of
technologies that enable the direct exchange of services or data
between computers. ``Peer-to-peer computing could be as important
to the Internet's future as the Web browser was to its past,'' said
Patrick Gelsinger, vice president and chief technology officer of
the Intel Architecture Group. By using the collective processing
power of the thousands of PCs at Intel in a peer-to-peer network,
the company was able to mothball its mainframe computers, saving
$500 million, he said.
</P>
