<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1782 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NETWORTH--COLUMN-SFCH     08-25 1511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABLETRON SPIN-OFFS AN ATTEMPT TO CREATE NETWORKING'S `FAB FOUR' 
 &HT;     BY KATHLEEN PENDER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;         c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Are four money-losing companies worth more than one?
<P>
   In the case of Cabletron Systems Inc., Wall Street seems to
think so.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the biggest multiple births since the Baby Bells,
Cabletron, an also-ran in the computer networking business, is
spinning off four divisions as separate companies.
</P>
<P>
   During the next year or so, it will sell 20 percent or less of
each unit in four initial public offerings and distribute the
remaining shares to Cabletron stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   Four IPOs amount to a full-employment act for investment banks,
and their analysts have been churning out ``sum of the parts''
analyses that estimate the combined value of the four companies at
$45 to $60-plus per share. Cabletron currently trades at around
$36.
</P>
<P>
   The hype is getting noisier now that the sexiest quadruplet,
Santa Clara's Riverstone Networks, is closing in on an IPO.
Cabletron stock jumped about $10 this month as Riverstone
executives made a pre-quiet-period promotional push.
</P>
<P>
   Riverstone is expected to file an IPO prospectus in September
and start trading in October or November. Sources say Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter will manage the offering, with help from
Salomon Smith Barney, Lehman Bros. and Chase H&AMP;Q.
</P>
<P>
   Given that most of Wall Street is in on the deal, or vying for
one of the others, investors might want to take these
sum-of-the-parts valuations with a grain of salt.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Pyykkonen of CIBC World Markets, one of the few analysts
without a buy recommendation on Cabletron, says, ``These target
prices are not outlandish, but they presume some success in the
company's sales that's not necessarily there today.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, most of the valuations assume Cabletron's offspring will
grow faster in the future than they have in the past.
</P>
<P>
   None is expected to grow faster than Riverstone, which sells
switches and routers to Internet service providers for metropolitan
area networks. Its routers let customers ``shape'' traffic, or
allocate more bandwidth to customers who are willing to pay more.
</P>
<P>
   Riverstone competes with hot ``Internet infrastructure''
companies such as Redback Networks, Foundry Networks and Extreme
Networks. Their stocks now sport sky-high valuations, and
Riverstone would like to cash in before investors go searching for
the next big thing.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley analyst Christopher Stix opines that Riverstone,
by itself, could be worth almost as much as all of Cabletron today.
</P>
<P>
   But Pyykkonen is skeptical. ``It all hinges on Riverstone's
sales execution,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Riverstone Chief Executive Officer Romulus Pereira admits that
in the past, sales and marketing was Cabletron's Achilles' heel.
</P>
<P>
   The company always had good technology and a flamboyant former
CEO who drove around in a tank and once arm-wrestled comedian Joe
Piscopo at a trade show.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Cabletron of Rochester, N.H., was actually
bigger than Cisco Systems. But as information technology became a
commodity, San Jose's Cisco recognized the importance of building a
brand name, and Cabletron didn't, Pereira says.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Andrew, an analyst with A.G. Edwards, is even harsher on
the old Cabletron.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a `hype and disappoint' management team,'' he
says. ``They were slow to come to markets, slow to make
acquisitions, and had a `not invented here' mentality. They screwed
up everything possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Cabletron did one thing right, though. In 1998, it bought Yago
Systems of Fremont.
</P>
<P>
   Yago had a next-generation high-speed switch ``that essentially
saved the company and now accounts for 25 percent of total sales,''
Andrew says.
</P>
<P>
   Yago had something else Cabletron desperately needed _
management. Yago's co-founders _ Piyush Patel and Pereira _
eventually became Cabletron's chief executive and chief operating
officers, respectively. Although the new team began delivering
consistent results, Cabletron never was able to regain respect on
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the breakup.
</P>
<P>
   The company decided that if it split into four parts _ each with
a new name, new management, new stock options and a sharper focus _
it would increase shareholder value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street rewards pure plays,'' Pereira explains.
</P>
<P>
   After Cabletron announced the restructuring plan in early
February, its stock shot up from the high-20s to the high-30s.
</P>
<P>
   In late February, the company disclosed that Silver Lake
Partners _ a Silicon Valley investment firm with deep pockets and
fat Rolodexes _ was investing in the firm, and the stock shot up to
$52 by late March.
</P>
<P>
   But on March 29, when the company announced results for the
fiscal year ended in February, it became clear that losses from the
restructuring would be bigger and longer lasting than expected, and
the stock tumbled all the way back down to $18.64.
</P>
<P>
   After languishing in the 20s, it started moving up again when
Riverstone moved closer to an IPO.
</P>
<P>
   Breakups like this have worked well for companies operating in
unrelated markets. But to the untrained eye, Cabletron's four units
don't seem all that disparate.
</P>
<P>
   Enterasys, the biggest but slowest-growing division, will sell
networking hardware _ routers and switches _ to enterprise
customers, which means big businesses, for their internal networks.
</P>
<P>
   Riverstone will sell switches and routers to ``service
providers,'' such as Internet service providers, application
service providers and Web-hosting companies, for regional networks.
</P>
<P>
   Aprisma will sell network-management software to enterprises and
service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Global Network Technology Services will be a network-consulting
company, capitalizing on the hot outsourcing trend.
</P>
<P>
   All four of the divisions lost money in the latest quarter and
will continue to do so for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to run four different companies, you have to
have four different everything. In the short run, you're going to
have higher expenses,'' says Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, however, analysts say the companies will grow
faster because they can get capital by selling stock to the public,
instead of squabbling with one another for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Riverstone can grow so much faster than the other ones _ 25 to
30 percent a year. That would suck up a lot of resources that
Enterasys thinks they ought to get,'' says Bert Hochfeld, an
analyst with Josephthal &AMP; Co. On its own, Riverstone can get the
same kind of capital its competitors are getting.
</P>
<P>
   He says some of the units will be able to snag new customers by
shaking off real or perceived conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you'd ever be able to sell the Aprisma software
in high volume as long as it continues to be part of Cabletron,''
Hochfeld says. ``It was designed as a network management platform
for Cabletron. So long as it belongs to Cabletron, there will
always be the belief that it's optimized for Cabletron equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, GNTS will be able to expand its consulting clientele
when it's no longer seen as beholden to Cabletron.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there's no proof that separating Cabletron's
hardware business by customer base will be a boon. Pyykkonen points
out that Cisco, Foundry and Extreme all sell equipment to
corporations and service providers _ and are doing just fine, thank
you.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Davidson of Silver Lake admits that ``synergies could be
lost, but there could also be tremendous opportunities. We're
making a bet that the total available market that can be served by
independent companies is bigger, and they'll be more successful
serving those markets as independent companies. Part of it is just
re-energizing the management team and employee base.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver Lake has agreed to invest $90 million in the parent
company and $110 million or more in each of the four spin-offs. But
Davidson doesn't expect to get rich overnight. ``I'm long-term
greedy, not short-term greedy,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from its operating units, Cabletron has investments in 25
or 30 technology companies and plans to make more with its sizable
cash horde. When the breakup is complete, the parent company may
use these investments to form an incubator company similar to CMGI
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   So how much is this whole thing worth?
</P>
<P>
   Hochfeld until recently had a ``hold'' on the stock, but now
says it's worth ``north of $60.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Hare, an analyst with Spin-Off Advisors, a hedge fund,
says the pieces add up to $55 per share. But after subtracting a 15
percent discount for ``execution risk,'' he comes up with a value
of $46 or $47.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew says Cabletron could hit $55 to $60 within 12 months.
But, he cautions, ``a lot could happen: The market could crash,
they could implode. This is a very difficult story to understand,
and they have to get over that hurdle.'' If things go wrong, he
says, the stock could sink back to the 20s.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail kathleen pender at kpender(AT)sfgate.com
</P>
