r f BC-INTEL--PEER-SFCHRON &LR;      08-25 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL--PEER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL MAKING PITCH FOR `PEER-TO-PEER' COMPUTING 
 &HT;     BY HENRY NORR
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN JOSE _ To the average corporate computing manager, the very
mention of the Napster file-sharing site conjures visions of
rampant copyright violation and networks brought to their knees.
<P>
   But Intel says that's only part of the story. Thursday, the
giant chipmaker set out to persuade the high-tech industry and its
business customers to see the positive potential of Napster-style
sharing.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon is called ``peer-to-peer computing,'' which Intel
defines as technologies that enable the direct exchange of data or
services _ including processing power and storage capacity _
between computers over both local-area networks and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peer-to-peer computing could be as important to the Internet's
future as the Web browser was to its past,'' declared Pat
Gelsinger, vice president and chief technology officer of the Intel
Architecture Group _ the company's core division _ in a keynote
speech on the third day of the Intel Developer Forum in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   With respect to the legal controversy surrounding Napster, Intel
is ``neutral,'' Gelsinger said. ``We're creating the technological
framework. It will have good and bad uses, as all technologies
do.''
</P>
<P>
   The good side, he said, is the underlying notion that desktop
PCs as well as network servers can offer information and resources
to other users over far-flung networks. To promote that idea, and
to foster standards and protocols for it, Intel has formed an
industry working group (www.peer-to- &QL; 
peerwg.org).
</P>
<P>
   IBM and Hewlett-Packard have already joined, along with some 16
other companies, mostly little-known startups. Gelsinger also said
Intel's venture-capital fund would play an aggressive role in
promoting the new paradigm.
</P>
<P>
   Citing data from Intel's own experience, the Intel executive
said the peer-to-peer approach could save business customers
billions. Until a decade ago, he said, the Santa Clara company
``bought mainframes like candy,'' particularly to run simulations
of new chip designs.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1990, it developed software called NetBatch, which scans
the company's 10,000 engineering workstations, then dispatches such
tasks to idle machines.
</P>
<P>
   The effect, he said, has been to raise utilization rates on
expensive workstations from 30 percent to 70 percent. As a result,
Intel hasn't had to buy a new mainframe since 1992, and across 10
years, it has saved an estimated $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   Another example involves software Intel is testing for
distributing computer-based training files to its employees.
Instead of each employee downloading the large, media-rich files
over expensive and often congested wide-area networks, only one
worker at each site has to; that worker's machine then serves up
the file to other users at the same site over the LAN, where
bandwidth is plentiful and inexpensive.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers, however, aren't convinced that peer-to-peer
computing will have wide appeal in the business world. ``It's no
accident that Napster is a consumer phenomenon,'' said Jeffrey
Tarter, editor and publisher of Softletter, a software-industry
newsletter in Watertown, Mass. ``The biggest impact of these
technologies is in the consumer world.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel's problem, he said, is that ``processor speed no longer
matters for most tasks,'' but manipulating digital audio and
especially video still taxes the capabilities of today's PCs. By
facilitating distribution of such multimedia files, peer-to-peer
computing could help increase demand for expensive cutting-edge
chips on both end-user computers and network servers.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at hnorr(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
