<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1785 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-EMBRYO-ETHICS-SFCHRON     08-25 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBRYO-ETHICS-SFCHRON(1ST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VATICAN ASSAILS NEW GUIDELINES ON HUMAN EMBRYO RESEARCH
</HEADLINE>
 LEDE)  
 (Eds: Changes Time Element Throughout, From Wednesday To
Thursday)     &HT;     By DON LATTIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ethical debate over the research potential and human rights of
frozen embryos intensified Thursday as the Vatican condemned new
U.S. guidelines on embryonic research, calling them ``gravely
immoral.''
</P>
<P>
   It took Rome only one day to respond to President Clinton's
prediction that new rules from the National Institutes of Health
will encourage medical breakthroughs with ``potentially staggering
benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue are the uses and abuses of stem cells taken from human
embryos that were created in fertility clinics, but never implanted
in the womb of a mother or surrogate mother.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how many thousands _ or millions _ of these tiny
embryos are sitting in suspended animation on laboratory shelves
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   New research may soon enable these ``pluripotent'' stem cells to
be used in the manufacture of muscle cells, skin cells and nerve
cells. These self-replicating cells could lead to breakthrough
treatments for a variety of deadly and debilitating diseases.
</P>
<P>
   What's lost in this high-tech harvest is the embryo itself,
which could have been used to produce another human life.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Thursday, the Vatican's Pontifical Academy
for Life said the medical benefits do not warrant embryonic
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good end does not make good an action that in itself is
bad,'' the Vatican said.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II is expected to address the stem cell
controversy himself next week when he speaks at a scientific
conference in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the pope suffers from Parkinson's disease, one of
the degenerative, age-related ailments that stem cell therapies
could be used to treat.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the opposition to this promising line of research comes
from religious leaders and politicians who oppose abortion because
of their belief that life begins at conception. The Catholic Church
opposes in- &LR; vitro fertilization, but says that embryos deserve
protection, in both the womb and the petri dish.
</P>
<P>
   The new guidelines announced Thursday permit federally financed
researchers to work on stem cells extracted from surplus embryos at
private laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in history, our federal government will
promote research in which developing human beings are destroyed,''
said Richard Doerflinger, Associate Director of the Pro-Life
Secretariat at the National Conference of Catholic Bishops.
</P>
<P>
   Some argue that these surplus embryos would have been destroyed
anyway, so why not use them for beneficial purposes. &LR; ?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's like saying we should take the organs from prisoners on
death row because they're going to die anyway,'' Doerflinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Other ethicists disagree with the hard-line position of the
Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Peters, a professor at Pacific Lutheran Theological Seminary
in Berkeley, warned against oversimplifying the ethical questions
around embryonic research, or viewing it through the ``pro-life''
and ``pro-choice'' arguments in the abortion debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value of this research outweighs the arguments against
it,'' said Peters, who has studied stem cell research for the
Center for Theology and the Natural Sciences in Berkeley. ``We'd be
sacrificing an enormous difference in human health to protect
fertilized ova that won't become babies anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters and Doerflinger also disagree as to whether researchers
could get similar results by using stem cells taken from adults,
rather than using embryos.
</P>
<P>
   Peters said adult cells ``deteriorate rapidly and are too small
to work with.''
</P>
<P>
   But Doerflinger cited a recent study showing that researchers
could ``produce a virtually limitless supply of new nerve cells for
transplants from patients' own bone marrow stem cells.''
</P>
<P>
   Other ethicists note that the enormous potential of stem cell
research opens a Pandora's Box of larger questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lurking behind the scenes is a not-so-subtle quest for
immortality,'' said C. Ben Mitchell, a bioethics consultant for the
Southern Baptist Convention, the nation's largest Protestant
church.
</P>
<P>
   ``A cottage industry is developing to ward off not just
age-related diseases, but aging itself.''
</P>
<P>
   More liberal denominations with a pro-choice position on
abortion, such as the United Methodist Church, still have concerns
about embryonic research.
</P>
<P>
   That church has called for ``a ban on medical and research
procedures which intentionally generate `waste embryos' which will
knowingly be destroyed when the medical procedure or the research
is completed.''
</P>
<P>
   Other churches have embraced both genetic engineering and
in- &LR; vitro fertilization.
</P>
<P>
   Resolutions adopted by the United Church of Christ support ``the
rights of families to make decisions regarding their use of
reproductive technologies,'' and conclude that ``genetic
engineering opens new ways for people of compassion to help those
in need.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
