<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1787 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-INSURANCE-COMMISSIONE     08-25 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-COMMISSIONER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LEGISLATURE CONFIRMS INSURANCE NOMINEE  &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Retired Justice Harry Low was confirmed as the
state's new Insurance Commissioner Thursday, receiving unanimous
approval from both houses of the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Low replaces disgraced former commissioner Chuck Quackenbush,
who resigned under a cloud of suspicion and faced possible
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most importantly, he will restore public confidence in the
public's confidence in the Insurance Department,'' said Senate
President Pro Tem John Burton, D-San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Moving with rare speed, the Senate approved Low, a San Francisco
native, in a 34-to-0 vote that took less than 60 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. John R. Lewis of Orange called Low ``a
fair-minded official. Mr. Low is certainly well qualified.''
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Robert Hertzberg, D-Sherman Oaks, said Low is
exactly what the department needs to restore its credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can once again be assured that the department will lawfully
and carefully carry out the laws that protect consumers under Harry
Low,'' Hertzberg said. The Assembly confirmed Low on a 71-to-0
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis appointed Low, 69, to replace Quackenbush at the
end of July. Low has said that he will assume the office in
mid-September. Law school professor Clark Kelso will continue to
run the department in the interim.
</P>
<P>
   Low, a former state appeals court justice, will serve out the
remaining two years of Quackenbush's term. A Democrat, he has not
ruled out running for the office at that time.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, members of an Assembly committee questioned Low about
his ability to be not just an impartial judge, but an advocate for
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that my role as insurance commissioner will be to
fairly and impartially administer the laws as the Legislature
enacted,`' replied Low, who will become the highest-ranking Asian
American in state government. ``However, the laws are also directed
toward the protection of consumers, and I intend to enforce the
laws. However, as commissioner you must be fair to everyone, and
that includes businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Assemblywoman Shiela Kuehl, D-Santa Monica, said she was at
first worried that Low would be too neutral, and not enough of an
advocate.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've concluded that he will be just right,'' she said
Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 0055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
