u a BC-OBIT-CARSEY-NYT &LR;      08-25 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CARSEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JULIAN N. CARSEY, WHO CREATED 3 IDENTITIES, IS DEAD AT 65
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Fla., Texas)  By ERIC PACE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Julian Nance Carsey, a Maryland college president who twice
vanished and created a new life for himself, died on Sunday at his
home in Jacksonville, Fla. He was 65.
</P>
<P>
   Carsey, known as Jay, had a liver ailment, said his companion,
Corinne Silverton.
</P>
<P>
   Carsey first disappeared in 1982, when he left his job, his wife
and his home in Maryland. After making a new life in El Paso and
remarrying, he disappeared from that life in 1992. He moved to
Jacksonville and took up another existence.
</P>
<P>
   In talking about his disappearance in 1982, Carsey said: ``It
wasn't that I was leaving something. I always felt I was going to
something, but I didn't know what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Coleman, the author of a book about Carsey, ``Exit the
Rainmaker'' (1989, InPrint.com), said what motivated Carsey ``was
just a hope that what he was going to would be better for him than
what he was leaving behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``A favorite expression of his,'' Coleman said, ``was that he
always loved `to seek and search.'''
</P>
<P>
   Carsey had been the president of Charles County Community
College in Maryland for 17 years when he disappeared from the
173-acre campus on a sunny morning in May 1982, only days before he
was scheduled to preside over a graduation ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   His energetic fund raising had enabled the institution to expand
greatly from a program of evening courses offered at a local high
school. But federal education money was evaporating, and he foresaw
difficult times ahead for the college. His marriage had also come
to seem hollow to him.
</P>
<P>
   But in a parting note discovered by his wife, Nancy, he said:
``I am a physical and psychological disaster, I have no will to
improve and I don't want to drag you down with me.''
</P>
<P>
   He took refuge in El Paso, where he was not known, divorced
Nancy and married a second wife, Dawn, and taught subjects
including mathematics for some years at Air Force bases in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   He taught and did administrative work at El Paso Community
College from 1988 until he disappeared again, just before Christmas
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman recalled that shortly before that disappearance he
received a letter from Carsey.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his own way he was trying to tell me that his life was
becoming too much for him again,'' Coleman said. ``So he took
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Carsey's wife said at the time, `` `I'd better go to the airport
to see if the car's there,''' Coleman said, ``and it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Carsey went to Jacksonville, made it his home, and taught at
some colleges in Florida in the 1990s. He lived quietly, often
watching football games.
</P>
<P>
   Julian Nance Carsey was born in Ballinger, Texas, and grew up
there and elsewhere in Texas. He received two bachelor's degrees,
in chemical engineering and in business administration, from Texas
A&AMP;M University, and served as an officer in the Army. In later
years he earned a doctorate in public administration from George
Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   He became separated from his wife, the former Nancy Stevens
Brumfield, who he had married in 1968, at the time of his first
disappearance, in 1982, and they were divorced in 1985. His
marriage later that year to Dawn Peacock Garcia ended in divorce
after his second disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his companion, Silverton, he is survived by a
sister, Susan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1793 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-FRESHMEN-HISTORY-SFCH     08-25 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRESHMEN-HISTORY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 `MINDSET' OF COLLEGE FRESHMEN RUSTY ON HISTORICAL DETAIL  &HT;     By TANYA SCHEVITZ 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   History isn't what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   For college freshmen descending on campuses across the nation
this month, the Kennedy tragedy is a plane crash, not an
assassination. The Osmonds are talk show hosts, not a
brother-sister singing and dancing duo. And Jane Fonda is just a
workout queen, not a Vietnam War icon.
</P>
<P>
   Beloit College in Wisconsin has just released its third annual
``Mindset of First-Year Students'' list to help professors
understand where their freshmen are coming from.
</P>
<P>
   The list of 50 items will get a laugh out of most anyone 30 or
older (Born in 1970? Yes, you are  &UR; old  &LR; to these kids of the '80s)
and provides a startling reminder of the gap between generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hanoi Jane? What is that?'' asked UC Berkeley freshman Joe
Mellin, 28, reading that No. 45 on the list said freshmen of today
never thought of Jane Fonda as Hanoi Jane or connected her with any
revolution other than the ``Fitness Revolution'' videotape they may
have found in the attic. ``Isn't she the workout lady?'' Mellin
asked, clearly puzzled.
</P>
<P>
   The students in the class of 2004 were born mostly in 1982, the
year the Equal Rights Amendment was defeated, Phil Gramm became a
Republican and C-SPAN began 24-hour broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   The freshmen of today feel a greater threat from sex and being
in school with armed classmates than from nuclear attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like a thing of the past,'' said UC Berkeley freshman
Zaneta Wolanska, 18, of a potential nuclear war. ``We have never
really been close to it.''
</P>
<P>
   A George Bush has been on every national ticket, except one,
since 18-year-olds were born. ``MASH'' and ``The Muppet Show'' have
always been in reruns. ``Coming out'' parties celebrate more than
debutantes.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't everlasting pink meat in a can that springs to mind
when they hear the word Spam. For them it is junk e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   And a weekend without cash has never been an issue for this
group since ATM's have been around their entire lives.
</P>
<P>
   There has always been a national holiday honoring Martin Luther
King Jr., television signals have always been available by direct
broadcast satellite. And their experience has led them to believe
that wars are events that begin and end quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the list is compiled in an unscientific way _ coming
from parent contributors and others around the Beloit campus, and
references culled from almanacs and editions of the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   But students themselves find the list fairly accurate, though
they do take umbrage at some of the items.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good portion of them are true, but there are a few that
underestimate our intelligence, like on Russia and communism,''
said UC Berkeley freshman Bryon Winget, 18, who is studying nuclear
engineering.
</P>
<P>
   According to Number 22 on the list, ``They have never referred
to Russia and China as `the Reds.''' They learned those terms in
school, students huffed.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly they knew Madonna sang ``Like a Virgin,'' not just
``American Pie,'' as the list claimed in number 43.
</P>
<P>
   And Winget was clearly offended by Number 47: ``They have never
used a bottle of ``White Out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've written on my book covers with White Out,'' he corrected.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the assertions came from the personal experiences of Ron
Nief, director of public affairs for Beloit College, and one of the
authors of the study _ with Humanities professor Tom McBride and
Richard Miller, director of Institutional Research.
</P>
<P>
   Number 7 _ A ``45'' is a gun, not a record with a large hole in
the center _ came from a chat Nief had with a group of students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said that I still have a closet full of 45s. I got shocked
looks. They said, `You have a closet full of guns?' I said, `No!
They are records!''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the list is whimsical, but that it has a serious
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really done to remind people that things change and
references change. You may have to explain things differently than
you have,'' Nief said.
</P>
<P>
   UC Berkeley Chancellor Robert M. Berdahl agreed that the
differences show up in the classroom. When he taught a course last
year on the history of the UC Berkeley campus, including
information on the loyalty oath, the free speech movement and the
anti-war protests, he found that students didn't always understand
the references.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their perceptions of the world are really quite different. Our
understanding has to be brought into alignment with their reality
every year,'' he said. ``It is a fascinating list of things that
demonstrates how young these freshmen really are in their
consciousness of the world and things we take for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   ...Like that shag carpeting disappeared long ago, never to
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shag carpeting is coming back. I'd like to have it in my
place. It is so nice,'' Mellin said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's scary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
