<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-RAMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS FINISH 0-5 IN PRESEASON AS OFFENSE STRUGGLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ It could be a result of the laser eye surgery he
had last year, but Troy Aikman saw the silver lining in a 24-17
exhibition loss to the St. Louis Rams on Thursday night at Texas
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that if we could get in and out of this game without
getting anybody hurt, it would end the preseason on a very positive
note,'' said Aikman, adding that the regular-season opener against
Philadelphia on Sept. 3 will mark the first time that new offensive
coordinator Jack Reilly will have a chance to map out a game plan
against an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be good to do that at full strength, personnel-wise,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman and the Cowboys' first-team offense _ including Erik
Williams and David LaFleur, each in his first preseason game _
managed only three points in two series against the defending Super
Bowl champion Rams.
</P>
<P>
   As the Cowboys finished with their second 0-5 preseason record
in three years, Aikman and the starters turned the ball over for
the first time in 15 preseason possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman completed double-digit passes of 14, 22 and 22 yards to
three receivers (LaFleur, Chris Warren and Rocket Ismail) on the
opening drive and moved the Cowboys into the red zone. But from the
Rams' 19, Aikman badly underthrew Joey Galloway at the goal line,
and safety Dexter McCleon turned and made the easy interception for
a touchback.
</P>
<P>
   The next time Aikman and the first-team offense got the ball,
they squandered excellent field position _ without making a first
down _ and had to settle for a 44-yard field goal by rookie Tim
Seder.
</P>
<P>
   Seder's seventh field goal of the preseason (in nine tries) gave
the Cowboys a shortlived 3-0 lead just 7 minutes, 6 seconds into
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   This game produced two recurring themes: 1) The Cowboys lost for
the 14th time in 15 preseason games since 1998; and 2) auditions by
the Cowboys' young cornerbacks continued their downward trend.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Kareem Larrimore, expected to be the Cowboys' starting
left cornerback when the regular season opens nine days from now at
Texas Stadium, was called for a pass-interference penalty that was
declined because the play went for 50 yards despite the infraction.
</P>
<P>
   Larrimore stood and argued the first-quarter call as Rams' Pro
Bowl receiver Isaac Bruce made the catch on his back and turned it
into a 25-yard gain. Then, as Bruce was being tackled by linebacker
Barron Wortham, he flipped the ball to Ricky Proehl, who ran
another 25 yards to the Dallas 15.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis settled for a 24-yard Jeff Wilkins field goal after
linebacker Joe Bowden stopped the Rams' Robert Holcombe on
third-and-two.
</P>
<P>
   Tied at 3-3, the Cowboys used the next drive to see what rookie
running back Michael Wiley could do with the football _ five rushes
in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio State fifth-rounder carried for 8, 7, 4 and 4 yards,
then fumbled when stripped by Rams safety Keith Lyle, who returned
it 42 yards for a touchdown. The Rams led 10-3 with 30 seconds left
in the first quarter and never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams took a 17-3 lead early in the second quarter when Trent
Green hit Az-Zahir Hakim on a 15-yard post for a touchdown. Cowboys
free-agent first-year cornerback Stephen Fisher was in tow.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Cowboys second-year cornerback Duane Hawthorne was beaten
by Chris Thomas on a 48-yard touchdown pass from Green. The score
came with 3:19 left in the half, which proved to be a long one for
the Dallas defense.
</P>
<P>
   Between those two St. Louis touchdown drives, the Cowboys
finally put the ball in the end zone, led by Arkansas rookie Clint
Stoerner at quarterback. Wane McGarity, who led all Cowboys
receivers with 10 preseason catches a year ago, turned his fifth
reception of this preseason into an 8-yard touchdown with 7:21 left
in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   McGarity later caught a 26-yard pass from Stoerner that set up a
7-yard touchdown run by Wiley with 12:13 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Two turnovers hurt the Cowboys early. Too many penalties hurt
the Cowboys late. Free-agent quarterback Charlie Puleri tried to
give the handful of stragglers in the seats a comeback effort, but
a Dallas penalty wiped out that effort as well.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the Cowboys were happy to say goodbye to
preseason.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
