<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WHO WANTS TO MARRY THIS SURVIVOR?  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Right now it's just a gleam in my matchmaking
eye.
</P>
<P>
   But I have connections, I really think I can make it happen:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Richard Hatch, I'd like you to meet Darva Conger.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Most annoying nude couple since John and Yoko.
</P>
<P>
   Sure there would be complications, there always are, but love
will overcome. Richard is gay, I understand, but Darva doesn't
sleep with her husbands anyway.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a ``Survivor'' expert because I watched 15 minutes of the
final show. I would have watched previous episodes, but I was deep
into Joyce's ``Ulysses.''
</P>
<P>
   I LIKE the new ``reality'' shows. ``Survivor,'' though, needed
one more touch. When it got down to the final two, they should have
packed up the cameras, and  &LR; cast and crew and sailed away, leaving
behind only naked guy and rat-chick, whatever her name was.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, one of them would have washed ashore at Malibu on
a raft made of woven rat bones, and that would have been great
reality TV.
</P>
<P>
   TV ruined TV's suspenseful ending. Peggy Rourke-Nichols was
watching QVC before ``Survivor,'' and they were selling
``Survivor'' T-shirts with a picture of all the contestants, each
face X'd out except Richard, who was circled. All the breaking
news, right there on QVC.
</P>
<P>
   And just before the show's climax (says reader Elein) there was
a station break, and a teaser for the nightly news, and the
anchorwoman told everyone to stay tuned for an interview with the
man who won a million dollars on ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVING BITS of ``Survivor'':
</P>
<P>
   Cuffs Corbett has studied the motley crew for weeks and says,
``That's the reason I'd never go on a cruise.''
</P>
<P>
   And Old Homeboy brings home the local angle, that Mayor Willie
Brown has created San Francisco's very own island survivor: Wendy
Linka of Treasure Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``HELP WANTED: 34-year-old Mongolian divorcee, must be Lutheran
or atheist.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the sign in the window of Top Dog on Durant in Berkeley,
noted by Tanya Schevitz. Must be a story behind this, right?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the owner has some issues regarding free speech and
PC-run-amok in employment laws. Thus the lampoonish sign. The owner
isn't actually hiring.
</P>
<P>
   Four days ago a woman walked up to the hot- &LR; dog stand and said
she was looking for a job, and that she is a 34-year-old Mongolian
divorcee.
</P>
<P>
   However, the woman admitted to the owner, she is neither
Lutheran nor atheist.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, lady, it's Berkeley. They can train you.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER SIGN of the times:
</P>
<P>
   Dave Toschi was driving through the Richmond on Sunday evening,
saw a young man standing on the traffic island holding a
hand-lettered sign: ``Russian River, need ride, prefer driver with
a BMW conv.''
</P>
<P>
   RALPH NADER, my hero, is sinking in the polls as the dread
specter of President Shrub scares Nader voters to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Many Nader fans sadly realize they can't waste that symbolic
vote on Ralph. But it's going to be hard to give up the
holier-than-thou feeling of walking out of the voting booth having
voted for an honest dude.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Ralph won't be president, but how about creating for him
a new Cabinet post: Secretary of the Road, protecting American from
driving rip-offs?
</P>
<P>
   Like: Ford admits it fixed Explorer rollover tendencies by
underinflating the tires. ... Firestone assembly-line workers say
they were told to pop bubbles with an awl. ... Mitsubishi is busted
for a coverup of customer complaints. ... And Tiger Woods is caught
selling a Nike golf ball that only he has; it's not the same Nike
ball the public drives.
</P>
<P>
   The motto of Nader's new watchdog post: ``Liar, liar, car on
fire.''
</P>
<P>
   CELL STUFF: Down in Silicon Valley, Steve Beck has been
attending cell phone technology conferences, and reports:
</P>
<P>
   ``At the Intel Developers Forum, a slide appeared just before a
wireless panel session: `Please place your cell phones on silent or
stun.'
</P>
<P>
   ``During breaks in the conference sessions, folks used to gather
outside to chat. Now they are all calling someone somewhere on
their cell phones. One pierced and stabbed wirelesser got his cell
phone antenna caught in his earrings.''
</P>
<P>
   KNEE-JERK liberal Rev. Robert Cromey checks into California
Pacific Medical Center Friday for his second knee replacement, and
you have to wonder if all that knee-jerking is just too hard on the
joints. Repetitive stress and all that.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev is also a self-proclaimed bleeding-heart liberal, and
you know the surgeons must hate to work on a guy with jerky knees
and a bleeding heart.
</P>
<P>
   OH, SWEET mysteries of life: From the Grass Valley-Nevada City
Union's Police Blotter (thanks, C. Leach):
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman living on Wolf Hollow Road reported that upon
developing a roll of film, she discovered obscene pictures of
someone in her closet.''
</P>
<P>
   MAILBAG: ``Please give us some more of your keen observations
about interesting places and people. ... I do not enjoy your
`cutesy' columns because I don't think you are `cutesy.' You just
seem to miss.'' (J.M.H. Shane)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but with columnists like me around, the pinata of life
lasts a lot longer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
