<SLUG> BC-NJ-WRONG-RUNWAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANE NEARLY LANDS ON CLOSED RUNWAY, BUT AIR TRAFFIC CONTROLLER
INTERCEDES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  By SHAILA K. DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Continental Airlines plane nearly landed on a closed runway at
Newark Airport before dawn Thursday, but an air traffic controller
noticed the impending mistake and ordered the plane up before it
could land.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, on a red-eye flight from San Francisco, was cleared
to land on one of two parallel runways at 6:15 a.m., a slow time
for the normally busy airport, said James Peters, a spokesman for
the Federal Aviation Administration. But the pilot aligned the jet,
a Boeing 757, with the left-hand runway instead of the right-hand
one.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the plane reached the runway's threshold, the air
traffic controller handling the flight noticed, Peters said, and
ordered the pilot to ``go around.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilot ``powered up, circled the field, came back and landed
on the first runway,'' Peters said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that such ``go-arounds'' or ``missed approaches'' _ when
a pilot cannot execute a planned landing _ happened several times a
day at busy airports like Newark. Sometimes they are requested by
pilots, other times by controllers, but they rarely occur because a
plane is heading for the wrong runway, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the controller and the pilot followed go-around procedures
correctly, said Peters, adding that no one was hurt and that the
flight was not delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Peters said the flight standards district office at Teterboro
Airport would investigate the incident by obtaining tapes of
ground-to-air communications and radar data showing the flight's
path.
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred as an airport duty manager, Dan Harvey,
was inspecting the runway, which had been closed for routine
electrical maintenance, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey was monitoring air traffic on his car radio and heard the
controller's instructions, then saw the plane emerge from the
morning fog, said Steve Coleman, an airport duty manager.
</P>
<P>
   Peters, the Federal Aviation spokesman, said it was too early to
speculate on what caused the mistake. An automated information
service for pilots was announcing that 22-Left was closed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A union official defended the air traffic controller, a 13-year
veteran. Daniel D'Agostino, president of the Newark division of the
National Air Traffic Controllers Association, told The Associated
Press that tapes of air-to-ground communication showed that the
pilot had misunderstood the controller's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Stengel, a spokeswoman for Continental Airlines, said
the company did not know what instructions the pilot had received
nor how quickly he had responded to the go-around order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
