<HEADLINE>
VARGAS, THOMPSON FIGHT BEFORE FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Evidently, Fernando Vargas and Ross Thompson are eager to fight
one another Saturday in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   They opened the final news conference to promote the bout with
an exchange of punches that left Vargas and promoter Gary Shaw with
bloody mouths.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson shouted at Vargas as he stepped up to the dais and
walked past the IBF junior middleweight champ from Oxnard. Vargas
stood up and Thompson landed a right that caused blood to trickle
from Vargas' mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas then knocked Thompson from the dais with a left hook.
Thompson jumped back onto the dais and threw a punch that hit Shaw
in the jaw as he was attempting to break up the fight before
security guards restored order.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw was more confident than ever that his fighter, Vargas,
would win.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to worry about this guy. He can't even drop
(ital)me(endital),'' the 50-ish Shaw reportedly told Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, a 30-1 underdog, will be disciplined, according to
Nevada officials.
</P>
<P>
   TAKE THAT: Oscar De La Hoya has said repeatedly that he won't
fight Vargas because he objects to some of Vargas' comments. Now
Vargas, gaining rapidly on his East L.A. rival in terms of
marketability, is saying the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to fight him,'' he said. ``For what? He has two
losses in a row. There's no incentive there for me. Mosley
definitely beat him. He doesn't do anything for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need a fighter with a name. ... He's history to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
