<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDGEFUND-CHARGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEDGE FUND FOUNDER CHARGED WITH DEFRAUDING ITS INVESTORS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Austria)  By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Michael W. Berger, a hedge fund manager, was charged
Thursday with defrauding 300 people who invested about $575 million
in his fund.
</P>
<P>
   Berger was charged with securities fraud and fraud under the
Investment Advisers Act. He pleaded not guilty and was released on
bail of $75,000 cash and a $100,000 bond secured by his home in the
Hamptons.
</P>
<P>
   Berger, an Austrian citizen, was also required to surrender his
passport. His attorney, Sara Mogulescu, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Berger, 28, was the manager of the Manhattan Investment Fund
Ltd., which bet that Internet and high technology stocks would
decline at a time that they rose.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors from the U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan
said that Berger reported annual fund earnings as high as 27.4
percent in 1997, when his company lost about $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors charge that Berger hid the losses from investors and
from auditors by creating fake financial records and passing them
off as the fund's actual returns. When auditors from the accounting
firm Deloitte &AMP; Touche asked for additional records to confirm
Berger's reports for 1999, prosecutors said, Berger fired them.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year the Securities and Exchange Commission sued
Berger and his management company for overstating the fund's
holdings and using misleading account statements to raise more than
$350 million from investors since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC froze the assets of the fund and the court appointed a
receiver to review the figures. Peter H. Bresnan, the SEC's
assistant chief litigation counsel, said when the fund was frozen
about $35 million remained. Some investors had removed about $140
million, leaving overall losses of about $400 million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bresnan said that for the most part the fund did not attract
small investors. ``These were institutions and high-net-worth
individuals predominantly from outside the United States,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to prosecutors, investors had to contribute at least
$250,000 to participate in the fund.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
