<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1803 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-NADER-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRO     08-25 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NADER-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GREEN PARTY CANDIDATE RATTLES SILICON VALLEY  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Green Party presidential candidate Ralph Nader
trained his sights on issues dear to the heart of Silicon Valley
Thursday, saying he would do away with all corporate-donated
computers in public schools and tax every stock transaction.
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging 90-minute interview with The Chronicle, Nader
also repeated his vow to replace Federal Reserve chairman Alan
Greenspan _ whom he called ``a convenient icon for Wall Street ...
who does very little for the economy'' _ with a central banker who
would aggressively represent the interests of workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Party candidate and consumer advocate made the
comments on his way to a campaign stop in Sacramento and was
especially critical of high tech equipment donated to schools.
</P>
<P>
   He described such gifts as the ``addictive commercial
exploitation'' of children in American schools.
</P>
<P>
   Nader has been met with enthusiastic, overflow crowds on his
California campaign swing this week _ 3,000 turned out for his
appearance in Santa Cruz on Wednesday _ even as a new California
Field Poll suggested his impact on the presidential race may be
waning.
</P>
<P>
   Nader discounted the poll _ which showed his support at just 4
percent, down by nearly half from June _ as ``totally inexplicable.
Unless there are some real angry Democrats who say, `Yeah, our
lives have been saved by safer cars and cleaner food and better
drinking water _ but we don't like him because he's upsetting our
little apple cart.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Nader said his campaign, which he expects will spend about $5
million, plans to air a series of radio spots as well as a
30-minute nationwide television message.
</P>
<P>
   The 66-year-old author and lawyer vowed to continue to challenge
both Democrat Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush to address core
Green Party issues ranging from trade and the environment to a
living wage and child poverty. But he also appeared to acknowledge
the political reality of what even supporters describe as a
quixotic presidential effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Win or lose in November, there's going to be a Green magnet,
or a Green hammer, in the form of a significant Green Party,'' he
said. ``And it will save the two major parties. (We're telling
them) you can have the magnet, and let us pull you into the realm
of decency and responsiveness to the needs of the American people _
or you can have the hammer, which means the Green Party will just
get more and more votes. ... That's going to happen. Regardless.''
</P>
<P>
   With polls showing that Californians, by a 2-to-1 ratio, want
both Nader and Reform Party candidate Pat Buchanan to be included
in upcoming presidential debates, Nader challenged Gore and Bush to
share the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing, the cynical manipulators behind these two party
candidates,'' he said. ``They really think they can lie, cheat and
flummox the public and get away with it. Because they don't think
the press is going to hold them accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader, who has a loyal following among progressives in the Bay
Area, was particularly animated Thursday on a number of issues
affecting Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Nader said he ``absolutely'' supports the removal of all
corporate-sponsored aid to public schools _ including all donated
computers _ a policy that could profoundly affect thousands of
local schools that receive donations from area high-tech firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public schools are the public responsibility. You cannot
mix public functions with commercial functions. All these so-called
donations come with a price, a restraint,'' he said. That price, he
added, might range from an obligation directive &LR;   &LR; to show
commercial television to restraints on ``making corporations look
like the bad guys when you teach environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader called it a ``systemic default'' dating back to
Proposition 13 that so many schools rely on corporate donations.
But ``this is a rich state,'' he said, and ``you have to have a
fundamental reassessment of what kinds of resources are going to be
made available for public need.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader said schools would benefit from his tax policies that
would shift burdens to polluters, ``addictive industries ... and
for the first time, the sacrosanct of all industries, the stock
transactions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't even a tiny little transaction tax on trillions of
dollars of stock transactions every week,'' Nader said. ``In some
states, you buy food and you pay a sales tax ... but you don't pay
a sales tax when you buy 50,000 options or 200,000 shares,'' he
said. ``And that is a huge revenue source that would help pay for
universal health care and education.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader argued his policy would not severly impact the millions of
small traders who have entered the stock market in recent years via
online trading firms. ``It's a matter of pennies per share, a
fraction of 1 percent,'' he said, adding that ``the top 5 percent
of the richest people in this country own 77 percent or the
stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   And in a statement that will surely raise eyebrows among Silicon
Valley's fast-paced financial crowd, Nader confirmed he would fire
Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman who has been credited with
policies that have helped sustain the nation's booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alan Greenspan is the emissary from Wall Street. I mean, do
you want your central bank controlled by bankers? On that basis,
just have the banks develop their own policy,'' he said. ``Why
should there be a government agency?''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, he said, is ``a convenient icon for Wall Street. He
does very little for the economy, but they have to have some
pretext to juggle the stock market on.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked who he would appoint in Greenspan's place, Nader
responded: ```A person who looks at the Federal Reserve as an
instrument to expand employment and living wages and consumer
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader said he would also challenge what he characterized as
unrelenting attacks by corporations and broadcasters on American
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our children are too precious of a resource to be turned over
to a bunch of violent, addictive, pornographically oriented
corporations whose CEOS get invited to diplomatic dinners at the
White House,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want children just to be onlookers, couch potatoes,
getting overweight, out of shape, watching programs that show
violence as a solution to life's problems, that pump them full of
junk food, sugar and fat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A President Nader, he said, would work to ensure that ``every
community would have a children's cultural center, funded by the
government, (which is) one less B-2 bomber or joint strike force.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader also promised to get tough on broadcasters and the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our country allows depraved programming to go unrebutted on
the same media. ... We have to have cable channels that are devoted
to serious subjects: not just entertainment, home shopping and
sports reruns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He called for conditioning licenses for television stations on
the assignments of other cable services. ``Labor would get a
channel. Citizen groups would get a channel. Teacher, education,
students would get a channel. Consumer issues would get a
channel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Our position) is, the commonwealth assets owned by the people
should be controlled by the people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Nader was reminded that _ despite his hopes that Americans
will demand higher-quality TV content _ more than 50 million of
them watched the finale of ``Survivor'' this week, an avalanche
compared to the small numbers who tune in to nightly news or
political shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``People live frantic, beleaguered, tired lives getting back and
forth from work, and they want a little comic relief,'' he said.
``There's sugar, and there's nutrition. And we're not getting
enough nutrition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
