<HEADER>
A1806 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-USC-PENNST-LADN     08-25 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-PENNST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COULD IT BE UNHAPPY VALLEY?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The offensive line is in shambles, the once-vaunted defense is
rebuilt and the quarterback is facing criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, it's business as usual for the Penn State
football team.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations remain high in Happy Valley as the 22nd-ranked
Nittany Lions are again viewed as major players in the
ultra-competitive Big Ten Conference, as well as on the national
scene.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus is that somehow, coach Joe Paterno will pull the
Nittany Lions through their various on- and off-field conflicts and
make them winners again. Won't he?
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not optimistic and I am not pessimistic,'' Paterno said.
``I am just trying to be a realist about it. We have a good, young
squad that is really going to have to stay lucky and healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, good fortune has eluded the Nittany Lions, who
open the season against USC on Sunday with nine new starters on
defense. Perhaps more important are the major issues on the
offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Penn State's success on offense is built around the
power-running game. The Nittany Lions have the running backs _ Eric
McCoo and Larry Johnson _ to build a successful rushing attack, but
the offensive line has crumbled significantly.
</P>
<P>
   Two starters, John Blick and Eric Cole, graduated from last
year's team. The Nittany Lions also lost two potential starters
this fall when guard Jordan Caruso suffered a fainting spell in
practice earlier this month and center Joe Iorio was diagnosed with
mononucleosis.
</P>
<P>
   All-America candidate Kareem McKenzie returns at strong-side
tackle, but otherwise, the Nittany Lions have some holes to fill.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Frank Spano, who started six games last year before being
replaced by Iorio, will start at center. And junior Joe Hartings,
who missed all of last season with a back injury, will replace
Caruso at one guard position.
</P>
<P>
   At the other guard, junior Josh Mitchell will make his first
start on Sunday against the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some people who, if they stay healthy and we keep an
offensive line together most of the season, will be pretty good,''
Paterno said. ``Whether we can be as good as some of the great
lines we have had through the years, when we have had high draft
picks from tackle to tackle, that would be debatable.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news for Penn State is that quarterback Rashard Casey
doesn't require much protection. Casey, one of the nation's most
mobile quarterbacks, has the ability to move the pocket and make
plays happen, even if the line suffers a breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that Casey's ability to focus on football has
been compromised by his arrest in May on charges of assaulting an
off-duty police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Paterno has stood behind his quarterback and denied that the
charges have been a distraction, but questions of morality continue
to follow Paterno and his decision to keep Casey in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't expect me to do something just because something is
alleged,'' Paterno said. ``I don't think there is anything for me
to be perplexed about. If some people out there are perplexed, I am
probably perplexed about their perplexing.''
</P>
<P>
   Less perplexing is what the Nittany Lions will try to do on
offense. McCoo and Johnson make for a strong one-two rushing punch,
if the line holds up.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Drummond returns to lead an unheralded group of receivers
that also includes Sam Crenshaw, Bryant Johnson and Rod Perry, a
junior flanker who transferred from USC following the 1998 season
and ended up at Penn State after first transferring to Cal State
Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   The defense is much less settled, now that three stalwarts from
last year _ LaVar Arrington, Courtney Brown and Brandon Short _ are
in NFL training camps and defensive coordinator Jerry Sandusky
retired after 34 years as an assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   The charge of rebuilding the defensive unit falls to Tom
Bradley, who spent the past 22 years working with the Nittany
Lions' secondary, linebackers and special teams.
</P>
<P>
   All-America candidate Justin Kurpeikis and senior Jimmy Kennedy
return to anchor the line, and Bob Jones shifts from tackle to end
to replace Brown, but there isn't much depth after that.
</P>
<P>
   That might not hurt Penn State against USC, which doesn't have a
particularly large or quick offensive line. But it could be
disastrous against Big Ten opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The linebackers and secondary are completely new, which makes
the Nittany Lions' defense a wild-card against the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   Even Paterno doesn't know how an almost-entirely new unit will
react in a high-profile, nationally televised game against a
higher-ranked opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Paterno has spent much of the preseason downplaying his team's
chances this year, and at one point said he regretted agreeing to
play USC, even though he later retracted the statement. Still,
Paterno acknowledges that a loss could be devastating to his young
and fragile team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be a great experience for our young players,
win lose or draw,'' Paterno said. ``The disadvantages are that you
could take a good licking. We may get a good licking. I would hope
that regardless of that we are young enough that we would have some
resilience and learn from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had known how good Southern Cal was going to be, I
probably would not play it. We are in it and are going to try to
make the best of it. We are going to try to make it a positive
experience, win or lose.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
