<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1807 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      08-25 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIN OVER VIN: THAT'S THE TASK FACING SONICS BRASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Now that feelings are hurt all the way around, it's
time for apologies, served with milk and cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Unsolicited advice for the Sonics: Make Vin Baker's milk no-fat
and his cookies sugar-free.
</P>
<P>
   Or if the reader prefers food similes from the breakfast table:
Get the omelet pan ready, because many eggs are dripping from a lot
of faces.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I'm done torturing the subject of the Vin Baker-for-Patrick
Ewing trade. It is a little foolish to torture something after it's
dead.
</P>
<P>
   But there is room for a little conversation about the Sonics'
future.
</P>
<P>
   As in: Now what?
</P>
<P>
   The buzz that was created about acquiring the gimp from Gotham
has not only vanished, there is now damage to repair.
</P>
<P>
   Baker and about half the Sonics roster, and perhaps many of
their hipster bartenders in Belltown, were all set to be swapped
around the country in the largest, most surprising NBA development
since the peek into Marv Albert's lingerie drawer.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to a leak in New York and cold feet in Detroit, no
trade was made, leaving the Sonics with a roster full of scowls.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a merry group in the first place, particularly when
they learned the TV remote-control throw was not an Olympic event.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is acute in the case of Baker, the only NBA player
known to mist up whenever he gets within 100 feet of a Hallmark
card shop.
</P>
<P>
   Sonics president Wally Walker, who helped hatch what would have
been the biggest trade in league history, knows he has a $10
million player who needs his nose blown and his head patted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say I'm not worried at all (about Baker),'' Walker
said Thursday, emerging from the bunker. ``At the same time, I'm
convinced things will work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Vin, the organization likes Vin. He'll feel rejected
for awhile, and then I think he'll bounce back.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, liking Baker has never been an issue. He's among the
nicest galoots in the NBA. Which is part of the problem. Most folks
around the Sonics would be thrilled if he said something like,
``Wait 'til I get my hands around Wally's scrawny neck. He'll wish
he had Ewing next to him.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's not Baker. And in this case, he shouldn't be hacked
off, even though his agents claim Baker is upset.
</P>
<P>
   According to all credible parties, the Knicks called the Sonics
a couple of weeks ago, informing them they were one of eight teams
to whom Ewing would accept a trade (he has the lone no-trade clause
among NBA contracts). Walker insists he was not shopping Baker, and
no evidence has emerged suggesting otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Walker alerted Baker on Thursday, and gave permission, should he
assent, for the Knicks to meet with him to talk it over. He did,
and they did.
</P>
<P>
   The four-team, 13-player swap was all set Sunday, just after a
couple of New York papers first published word of the
Ewing-to-Seattle segment. But by Monday, the full story inevitably
leaked. The Pistons, already burned by the loss of Grant Hill in
free agency, belatedly realized they were getting a box of rocks
and called it off.
</P>
<P>
   After various defibrillators were applied unsuccessfully this
week, the patient died Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But neither the deal's birth nor death can be called a Sonics
screw-up.
</P>
<P>
   Baker wasn't betrayed or misled. The Sonics were open to a good
offer after Baker's two sub-par years and signing a big, long,
guaranteed contract, even though few teams had the salary
flexibility to deal with Seattle. When one came along, the Sonics
would have been foolish not to engage, particularly when it
included one of the game's pre-eminent big men and brought
salary-cap relief.
</P>
<P>
   Having said that, the high-risk maneuver failed. The Sonics are
left with a disheartened Baker and several dismayed reserves, all
of whom have eyebrows in permanent arch whenever the coach or
president opens his mouth, if they weren't so disposed already.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the business of trades is a fundamental part of pro
sports. Sure, athletes are well compensated to accept the hassle.
And it's not as if the failed deal cost any one of them much more
than a few phone calls to an attorney to make sure no warrants were
outstanding in the potential new city.
</P>
<P>
   But in the battle with logic, emotion always wins. Half the
roster feels dumped. No one knows how that will manifest itself,
but for a team as tumultuous as the Sonics were last year, starting
the season irked puts them about two months ahead of their record
pace a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Training camp is still more than two months away, but given the
breadth and depth of the team crater, there's no time like the
present to start shoveling.
</P>
<P>
   Sending coach Paul Westphal to the Maui training camp of the
U.S. Olympic team, where Baker and Gary Payton are, ahem, working
out, might be a good start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't talked about it, but it's a possibility,'' Walker
said. ``Certainly, we believe in more communication than less.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the Sonics will be relying on the principals to be
stoically professional.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a bigger shocker than the trade.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
