   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INDIANS-POLITICS (Lummi Indian Reservation, Wa.) _ Mention the
name Slade Gorton in this far corner of Indian Country and some
people will talk about Slade Gorton the senior senator from
Washington who helped to secure $15 million this year to replace a
decrepit tribal school. But most people will think of Slade Gorton
the Indian fighter, the better-known and much-feared figure, a
72-year-old Republican who has spent much of his public life
battling the Lummis and other tribes on everything from fishing
rights to the power of governing their own affairs. In all the
years that Gorton has feuded with American Indians, he has never
suffered a strong political backlash from the tribes. But this
year, flush with money from casino gambling operations, Indians
across the country say they are going to make him pay. By Timothy
Egan. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos, NYT10 and NYT11 and a map are being sent to
NYT photo and graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIFE-ORIGINS (Undated) _ A maverick theory about the origin
of life has received striking support from an experiment that
mimicked the violent interactions of deep seated rock and common
gases during the Hadean epoch, the days when the Earth had just
formed as a planet. By Nicholas Wade. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA-PARKS (Anchorage) _ Former President Jimmy Carter said
his eleventh-hour decision in 1980 to protect millions of acres of
land in Alaska, doubling the national park acreage, was his
proudest achievement. Alaskans burned him in effigy. But Alaska has
changed and tourism is booming. With Carter here to celebrate the
20th anniversary of the Alaska Lands Act, the locals are welcoming
him warmly. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-EDUCATION-GAP (Washington) _ Test results show that the gap
in educational achievement between whites and blacks has remained
steady in the 1990s after narrowing in the 1970s and 1980s. The gap
has even widened for those with the most education. By Kate
Zernike.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-AD (Washington) _ Gov. George W. Bush says that he
intervened to halt the Republican Party from broadcasting a
commercial that harshly attacked Al Gore, a move that exposed
tensions even among Bush's own advisers over how and when to take
on the vice president. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-PERCEPTION (Undated) _ A Political Memo: What a difference
a week makes. Al Gore's crowds are big and enthusiastic, he's
acting with confidence, the polls are up and his opponents seems a
bit defensive. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-TELECOMN-LI (Hong Kong) _ Li Ka-shing, the tycoon known
here as Superman, earned his nickname among investors by amassing
more wealth and influence than any other local businessman here
ever had. His flagship conglomerate, Hutchison Whampoa, reinforced
that reputation on Thursday when it reported earnings of $4 billion
in the first half of 2000. Most of Hutchison's profit, however,
came from a special one-time gain after the sale of its European
mobile phone operations. And the company's encore, an ambitious
plan to offer next-generation cellular services throughout Europe,
is in doubt. Last week, Hutchison unexpectedly gave up a coveted
license to offer advanced mobile services in Germany, saying it was
too costly. Thursday, even as Li and his lieutenants basked in the
glow of rich earnings, they had to explain why the German setback
had not scrambled their plans. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-TELECOM (London) _ On what happens to the smaller
companies in European telecommunications, like Royal KPN of the
Netherlands and Sonera of Finland, now that the big wireless
auctions are over. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NINTENDO (Undated) _ Nintendo has become the last of
Japan's big game-machine makers to enter the competitive market for
next-generation consoles, saying that it will introduce its
Gamecube next year along with as a successor to the wildly
successful Game Boy.
</P>
<P>
   DECIMAL-NORRIS-COLUMN (New York) _ On Monday, the New York Stock
Exchange and the American Stock Exchange will begin trading a total
of 13 stocks in dollars and cents, rather than using fractions.
Sometime next year, all stocks will be traded that way. That
change, in itself, is unimportant. Whether a price is quoted as a
quarter or as 25 cents is irrelevant. What is important is that
arbitrary limits on price competition are vanishing. In 1997, the
smallest change in price on the Big Board was cut in half, to
one-sixteenth of a dollar, or 6.25 cents. Now it will go to a
penny. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   Eds., fyi, there is no Marketplace column on days with a Norris
column.
</P>
<P>
   LAUNDRY-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Campaign season is usually a time
for airing dirty laundry. That is the case at Unilever's laboratory
in Edgewater, N.J., where filthy socks fetch $3 a pair and soiled
shirts are bought for $15 each _ all in service of a coming
marketing campaign to introduce a revamped old product. Unilever is
locked in a race with Procter &AMP; Gamble to reacquaint American
consumers with the laundry tablet, a product they have not seen
since the late 1970s. The repackaging effort is part of a strategy
to shed its more obscure, ancillary products and pour resources
into marketing Wisk detergent and other core brands. By Greg
Winter.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-BUYERS-CLUBS (Undated) _ After decades of ceding control
over their care to cost-conscious health plans, consumers appear
ready to reclaim at least some of the decision-making authority
that they had in the years before managed care. Now, a number of
new companies are setting up shop, often on the Internet, to offer
people with little or no health care discount medical services,
cheaper prescription drugs and reduced rates on everything from
dental care and chiropractics to eye care and acupuncture. The new
companies, many of which operate like buyers' clubs like Costco,
are intended to let consumers and their doctors decide which
medical services they need. By Milt Freudenheim. 1,800 words.
</P>
