<HEADLINE>
PLANE SPINS AROUND AFTER TOUCHDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Continental Express turboprop landing at Newark International
Airport spun around several times on the runway when its brakes
locked shortly after touchdown Thursday night, the Federal Aviation
Administration said.
</P>
<P>
   There were no injuries to the 22 passengers and crew members on
the plane, a Brazilian Embraer 145 arriving from Savannah, Ga., as
flight 4282, said Jim Peters, an FAA spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But four tires on the plane blew out from the stress, Peters
said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, which landed at 9:47 p.m., came to a stop 4,000 feet
from where it touched down, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The runway the plane landed on, 4R, was shut down for nearly two
hours, until 11:30 p.m., after the mishap, Peters said.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the brake malfunction was not known.
</P>
</TEXT>
