<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC ARRIVES FOR KICKOFF CLASSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ USC arrived for the Kickoff Classic late
Thursday night full of confidence, something the oddsmakers seem to
be lacking.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans are 3{-point underdogs to Penn State despite being
ranked higher in both top-25 polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about that,'' USC linebacker Zeke Moreno said.
``I'm glad we're the underdogs. We have to go out and show what the
Pac-10 is capable of. It's just another obstacle we'll have to
overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for USC's underdog status could be that this is a
glorified home game for the Nittany Lions. While the Trojans spent
more than six hours flying Thursday, Penn State was not scheduled
to leave its campus until this afternoon, and then the Nittany
Lions intended to travel by bus.
</P>
<P>
   The difference illustrates a concern for USC coach Paul Hackett.
Just how many of the fans in attendance will be rooting for Penn
State?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's a home game for them in terms of playing
in Giants Stadium,'' Hackett said, before adding, ``They sold
68,000 tickets to Penn State and 5,000 to us. So it will clearly be
a neutral site.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett was joking, but that is about what the fan split was in
1996, when the teams also met in the Kickoff Classic. Penn State
won that game 24-7.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett claims he isn't too worried about the disparity in
attendance because of the configuration of Giants Stadium, where
fans are not nearly as close as they would be in Beaver Stadium,
site of Penn State home games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not right on top of you, like in Happy Valley, so that
should help us out,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   KNIGHT NO-NO: According to sources, linebacker Darryl Knight was
kicked off the field by an assistant coach for not paying attention
during a walk-through practice at UC Irvine. Knight left the field
and has not returned. Hackett said he has left the door open in
case Knight changes his mind.
</P>
<P>
   NO LONGER THE WEAK LINK: Kori Dickerson will try to show Sunday
that strongside linebacker is no longer a source for consternation
for the defense. Last year, teams found ways to exploit the
position by throwing to the tailback or tight end, which is the
responsibility of the strongside linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   But Dickerson, who switched from defensive end last spring, has
already made a difference, with an eye-catching interception in
practice and nice pass-coverage skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the thing that hurt last year,'' Dickerson said. ``I
want to prove I belong. I don't think it will be a big thing
playing in my first game. I'm actually real excited because I want
to see how I can contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett labeled Dickerson one of the most improved players in
training camp, and Dickerson feels more comfortable at linebacker
than he did during spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got all the bugs out. Spring was a learning process, I was
learning the technique,'' Dickerson said. ``But since we got to
camp, playing with Zeke has helped. He sets the standard here, and
makes sure we know we're in the right position on the field and
doing the things we need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   TOURIST TIME: USC will travel to Ellis Island and visit the
Statue of Liberty as part of its sightseeing activities. The
Trojans will practice at the New York Giants' indoor practice
``bubble'' today because Giants Stadium will host an exhibition
game between the Giants and the Baltimore Ravens tonight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
