<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFENSIVE LINE IS GROWING UP, AND OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA's offensive line is so much bigger and
stronger this season, you'd think they'd added a pound of muscle
for every sack they allowed last season.
</P>
<P>
   OK, they're not (ital)that!(endital) much bigger, but the
much-maligned offensive line has returned stronger, more
experienced and more together (physically and mentally) than a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is good news for the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to allowing 35 sacks, the offensive line was a big
reason the Bruins rushed for only 1191 yards and 2.9 per carry _
their lowest totals since 1964.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys have a lot of pride,'' said line coach Mark Weber.
``They know they didn't do as good a job last year as they needed
to. But they did what's been asked. They've worked hard and
committed themselves. As they get out and play, they'll have
success.''
</P>
<P>
   All five starters _ LT Bryce Bohlander, LG Oscar Cabrera, C Troy
Danoff, RG Brian Polak, RT Mike Saffer _ started last year, as did
backup guard Blake Worley.
</P>
<P>
   Noticeably bigger are the three sophomores _ Bohlander, who
gained 18 pounds; Saffer, who added 21; and Worley, who is up 25.
The only one who has slimmed down is Polak, who at 318 is ``in the
best shape he's been in,'' according to Weber.
</P>
<P>
   Polak has been moved to guard, his natural position, which has
allowed the more-athletic Bohlander and Saffer to play the tackles,
where they'll see pass-rushing ends like Cal's Andre Carter and
Alabama's Kenny King.
</P>
<P>
   Danoff has recovered from offseason knee surgery and is playing
like a veteran in his second year as a starter. Cabrera, who
suffered a high ankle sprain on the first day of fall camp and was
expected to miss the first two games, returned to practice Thursday
and is slated to start against Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Weber says this unit, which has only two seniors _ Cabrera and
Polak _ reminds him of the 1997 unit, another young group with two
senior guards, Chad Overhauser and Chad Sauter. And Weber isn't
afraid to let them know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always hear the coaches talking about Jonathan Ogden, Kris
Farris, Chad Overhauser and Andy Meyers,'' Bohlander said. ``Coach
Weber will always joke, `Shawn Stuart wouldn't have missed that
block or Meyers wouldn't have done that.' We weren't complete as a
unit last year. That really motivates us to prepare for this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   DEPTH CHART: The Bruins released a depth chart Thursday, but the
only thing that would qualify as a surprise is that Ryan Nece, who
has been bothered by a sore left shoulder, and Marcus Reese are
listed as co-starters at weakside linebacker. The decision is based
on Nece missing practices and Reese's performance, coach Bob Toledo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tight ends Gabe Crecion, Bryan Fletcher and Mike Seidman are
listed as tri-starters.
</P>
<P>
   KOCHER DOUBTFUL: Defensive tackle Ken Kocher, who sprained his
ankle Tuesday, is listed as doubtful for Alabama. He was on
crutches Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   OPPONENT INJURIES: Alabama defensive end Kindal Moorhead, an
All-America candidate, suffered what appeared to be an Achilles'
tendon injury in a scrimmage Thursday and could miss next week's
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look good,'' Alabama coach Mike DuBose told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Michigan quarterback Drew Henson underwent surgery
Thursday after fracturing his foot in practice and is expected to
miss 3 to 6 weeks, leaving his status for the UCLA game Sept. 16 in
doubt. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
