u k BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-SURVIVO     08-25 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-SURVIVOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: SOUNDING THE GONG IN THE SOUTH CHINA SEA
</HEADLINE>
  By VERLYN KLINKENBORG  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first premise of game-playing is that nobody rebels against
the game itself. That premise worked almost to a fault in
``Survivor,'' the desert-island game show _ let's discard forever
the phrase ``reality-based'' _ that ended Wednesday night. If
survival had really been at stake, the first thing the 16
contestants would have done last March, when the show was taped in
the South China Sea, was take hostage the CBS camera crew and the
host, Jeff Probst, and demand $16 million for their release. It
would have made better drama and edgier viewing, something like a
remake of ``Papillon'' by the producers of ``The Blair Witch
Project.''
</P>
<P>
   But everybody obeyed the rules. The contestants banged the gong
as they entered the tribal council area. They competed in inane
contests and childish rites. They kept their mouths shut, under the
threat of stiff penalties, when they were voted off the island.
Nobody groaned, except perhaps inwardly, when Jeff Probst said,
``You created a new civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he had a point. This indeed is how new civilizations are
created. Strangers bearing complicated contracts show up in places
they deem to be uninhabited and lay down the rules. Then they name
an SUV after the civilization they displaced. The supreme test in
the final episode of ``Survivor'' was whether Probst could say the
words ``Pontiac Aztek'' without breaking the mood.
</P>
<P>
   But the mood went unbroken, at least until the ``Survivor
Reunion,'' which immediately followed the final episode and whose
host was a particularly chirpy Bryant Gumbel, who looked as though
he had just been voted off the island of Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   Created by footage that comes straight from the genre of nature
documentaries and awash in New Age sound emitted by some
New-Age-sound sausage machine, the mood of the final episode of
``Survivor'' was in fact unbreakable. Words that once had meaning
were simply eviscerated, words like ``tribe,'' for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Television is truly the hyperbolic machine, the medium in which
``the ultimate human experiment,'' as ``Survivor'' was billed, was
really to see whether CBS could get 50 million Americans to watch a
show for which the network could charge a fortune for commercials.
The experiment was a success.
</P>
<P>
   There they were, though, the people we had tuned in to see,
their personae sharper than ever _ Rudy, looking more and more like
a disgruntled iguana; Kelly, almost indecipherably impassive at
times; Rich, coiled fetally on the final day; and Sue, who has
given truck drivers everywhere a bad name and whose motto was ``I
never regret what I say,'' when clearly she should have. At the
last it was Kelly and Rich, the one making a plea for personhood,
the other for gamesmanship. You all know who won.
</P>
<P>
   The worst of it is that we are stuck now in
``Survivor''-survivor hell. Commercials beckon the contestants. So
does Playboy. For a time the cameras will follow Rich and Sue and
Rudy and Kelly _ and Gervase and Jenna and Colleen, too _
everywhere they go. Having played by the rules for so long, the
contestants will find it hard to buck them now. And then the real
game of survivor will begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 0153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0045 </DOCNO>
