<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUNNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE FULLBACK IS A FULL BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JILL PAINTER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Usually no one is concerned about a football
player who weighs 270 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Unless he's the fullback.
</P>
<P>
   Cal State Northridge sophomore Crayton Milton played at 240
pounds last year and entered training camp at 260. Now he's 270.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I need to get (the weight) down,'' Milton said. ``Just
think if I'm around 240. I'd be 10 times better. When I came in, I
think (the coaches) may have been concerned. But when I got out
there, they saw I was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Milton, who's 6 feet, isn't preoccupied with losing weight.
While coaches would like to see him shed a few pounds, Milton feels
he's just as effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing at this weight,'' Milton said. ``I'm just as fast
or faster. I'm real confident in my abilities. I started nine games
last year and I did well in spring and `Hell Week'''.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN coaches don't know who will start at tailback, but Milton
has the starting fullback position secured.
</P>
<P>
   Milton said he took both sessions of summer school and worked,
which is why he wasn't running as much as he said he should have.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in a little heavy and we're trying to get him to to
lose some weight,'' said Daniel Escalera, CSUN's running backs
coach. ``He probably could lose a little more. But when he goes to
block he's tough to deal with. He's a big guy. Even when he was
lighter he was pretty aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors have several quality running backs who employ
different running styles. Milton is big and tough to bring down.
But he'll be used in more than just short-yardage situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good pass catcher,'' Escalera said. ``You can put him
out on a pattern. He's not a guy you don't throw to because he
can't catch. He can do damage downfield. He's a component of our
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   INJURY REPORT: Quarterback Marcus Brady was held out of some
drills in Thursday morning's practice because of a twinge and
soreness in the biceps muscle of his right throwing arm, according
to CSUN coach Jeff Kearin.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these injuries are nothing more than us being
conservative,'' Kearin said.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Jason Stone's shoulder popped out and popped back
in on its own during Wednesday's scrimmage, so he was held out of
Thursday's practice. ... Running back Terrelus Wright was hit in
the thigh with a helmet Wednesday and sat out Thursday. He's
expected to return to practice today _ the last day of two-a-days.
... Johnny Acosta, Jason Nicastro and Aschon Madjid, who've all
been nursing minor injuries, started limited practicing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   HICKS STILL NOT PRACTICING: Running back Matt Hicks _ who
transferred from Air Force _ still hasn't been admitted to CSUN and
therefore can't practice. ... Tight end Cory DiSanti hasn't been
admitted to CSUN either. DiSanti _ a transfer from Mt. San Antonio
College _ is waiting for transcripts.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICING POOLSIDE: Kearin decided to cancel Thursday
afternoon's practice in favor of a team swim at the University
Student Union pool. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 0200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
