<HEADER>
A1852 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-CARS-CUSTOM-MADE-ECON     08-25 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-CUSTOM-MADE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELL ON WHEELS: DETROIT ROLLS OUT BUILD-TO-ORDER (BTO) AUTOS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Detroit)  (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 725-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   DETROIT _ Now that they were wired to the Internet, Carol and
Bill Tragar thought it would be easy to order their dream car.
After all, more than two-thirds of all American new-car buyers are
turning to the Web at some point in the process.
</P>
<P>
   For the Tragars, that meant surfing one of the many car sites
where consumers can ``spec out'' a vehicle equipped exactly the way
they want, then find a dealer near their home.
</P>
<P>
   That was the easy part. But they only had to visit one dealer to
discover the Internet's big lie. It may be easy to specify the car
you want. Getting the vehicle is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Tragars were told they would have to wait up to three months
to have what they desired. So, like nearly 90 percent of American
buyers and 80 percent of Europeans, they settled for something
standard on the forecourt.
</P>
<P>
   Things are about to change, though, as car makers prepare to
launch a concept known as either Order-to-Delivery or
Build-to-Order (BTO).
</P>
<P>
   Harold Kutner, head of purchasing for General Motors, calls it
``the most dramatic change I've ever seen in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but all it means is that a motorist will be able to
order a car customized at the factory without having to grow old
waiting to have it delivered.
</P>
<P>
   BTO is based on a system pioneered by Dell Computer: go online
or call a freephone number, and your tailored product will be
assembled and shipped within days.
</P>
<P>
   A car is a far more complex product than a computer, but many
manufacturers believe they can cut the order-to-delivery time to
less than two weeks. The Internet will play a critical role in
making BTO work.
</P>
<P>
   In the system that GM is building, a customer picks his
preferred package and, within seconds, the transaction reaches a
central database that checks to make sure the order matches an
approved design. The car is then scheduled for assembly, based on
the earliest date that parts can be shipped.
</P>
<P>
   Car makers have all sorts of reasons to be interested in BTO.
Giving a customer precisely what he wants is a sure way to
strengthen his loyalty. And studies show that buyers are likely to
load on more expensive options when they custom-order.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, says GM's Kutner, ``I'd consider myself a failure if
I don't take 50 percent out of (overall) inventory in this
process.''
</P>
<P>
   With at least $20 billion in parts on hand at any one time to
support assembly systems, the savings on carrying costs alone could
add up to several hundred million dollars each year.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota is also experimenting with a BTO system at its plant in
Ontario, Canada, which builds Camry Solara coupes and convertibles.
Ford, meanwhile, has launched a BTO program that allows buyers in
Canada's capital city of Ottawa to custom-order any of four models.
</P>
<P>
   But car firms are reluctant to make too many promises. Ford's
Brian Kelley expects that it will take a series of halfway measures
before BTO becomes the normal way of doing business in the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The first step he dubs ``build-to-demand,'' where companies like
his try to guess ahead what buyers will request and build
``predictive'' models, so that dealers will have a more desirable
mix of cars on hand.
</P>
<P>
   GM's Cadillac division is trying that approach already. A
network of regional vehicle depots stock the most popular paint and
gadget configurations, allowing dealers to reduce their
inventories; customers can get all but the most unusual packages
within a matter of days.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy is effective, but it means that Cadillac must carry
the costly burden of stocking those depots _ so GM is trying to set
up an across-the-board BTO system in America by as early as 2003.
It even plans to place cameras along its assembly lines, so that
buyers will be able to watch their vehicles being built.
</P>
<P>
   Will the car makers match the nimbleness of the Dell system?
Probably not, but there are plenty of reasons why they need to try.
</P>
<P>
   And if they succeed, customers like the Tragars will at last be
able to get what they want _ without having to choose between
second-best and an interminable wait. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
