<P>
   &UR; BETTER SALARIES FOR BETTER TEACHERS? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TEACHER-PAY-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The annual Phi Delta Kappa/Gallup poll of attitudes
towards public education released this week found that a majority
of Americans feel it is important to put ``a qualified, competent
teacher in every classroom.'' Bob Chase, president of the National
Education Association (NEA), the main teachers' union, wasted no
time in pointing out that this will require raising teachers'
salaries so that more qualified candidates will enter the
profession and stay there. Al Gore has won cheers from Democrats
for suggesting a pay hike for teachers. Would it really help? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (550 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CANADA ACCUSES U.S. OF CIGARETTE SMUGGLING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOBACCO-SMUGGLING-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Your product, despite loyal customers, is not
selling, and your protests against heavy taxes go ignored. Sales
are suffering. If only some of the tax burden could be shaken off.
What to do? Why, team up with your foreign partners to smuggle, of
course. And, according to the Canadian government, this is exactly
what several North American tobacco companies did a decade ago. A
lawsuit currently winding its way through the courts in the United
States is a tale of conspiracy and intrigue as compelling as any
John Grisham novel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Tobacco-Industry States) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (675 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CHANGING FACE OF EUROPE'S SEX-SLAVE TRADE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SEX-TRAFFIC-EU-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRAGUE _ Highly organized, ruthless gangs of sex traffickers are
luring and smuggling young women, mostly from Eastern and Central
Europe, into prostitution throughout the continent. There are some
20,000 women in 600 or so brothels in the Czech Republic alone,
most of them foreigners smuggled into the country's thriving sex
industry. While the illicit and violent nature of the trade makes
accurate monitoring impossible, a clear pattern has emerged since
the collapse of communism. Simplistically, there is a two-step
movement of women from east to west. First, of Russians,
Ukrainians, Moldovans and Belarussians into Central Europe; second,
of these women and Central Europeans into western cities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (950 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DELL ON WHEELS: DETROIT ROLLS OUT BUILD-TO-ORDER (BTO) AUTOS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CARS-CUSTOM-MADE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Want to customize your dream car? Soon you will be
able to, thanks to a revolutionary concept known as either
Order-to-Delivery or Build-to-Order (BTO). GM's Harold Kutner calls
it ``the most dramatic change I've ever seen in the industry.'' BTO
is based on a system pioneered by Dell Computer: go online or call
a freephone number, and your tailored product will be assembled and
shipped within days. Gentlemen, start your engines... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: DETROIT) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (725 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GREATERGOOD.COM: A WEB SITE FOR DO-GOODERS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHARITY-ONLINE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Though Internet firms have found many a strange
bedfellow, who would have guessed that a dalliance with
philanthropy would prove fertile? Any self-respecting charity sends
newsletters and solicits donations over the Web, yet it is a clever
capitalist who can make money out of online giving. Now a cottage
industry offering services to not-for-profit types is trying. Enter
GreaterGood.com, a two-year-old Seattle firm that, essentially,
acts as matchmaker, bringing together consumers, charities and
retailers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GRATITUDE AND GRATUITY: DOES TIPPING WORK? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOES-TIPPING-WORK?-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Everybody loathes it, but everybody does it. A recent
poll showed that 40 percent of Americans, the world's most lavish
tippers, hate the practice. In America alone, tipping is now a $16
billion-a-year industry. Tips, which are voluntary, above and
beyond a service's contracted cost, and delivered afterwards,
should not exist. So why do they? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (525 words) &QL;
</P>
