<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREW-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-CREW-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    IN `THE CREW,' WIZENED GUYS STEAL THE SHOW(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The guys in (beginitalic)The Crew (enditalic)still have it.
</P>
<P>
   They just can't remember where they put it.
</P>
<P>
   That's part of the fun of this raucous comedy about four old
mobsters who move to Miami Beach and dream up one last caper to
save their retirement home.
</P>
<P>
   The film features a star-studded cast, including Richard
Dreyfuss, Burt Reynolds, Dan Hedaya and Jennifer Tilly. Unlike its
kissing cousin, (beginitalic)Space Cowboys(enditalic), about four
senior citizens who join NASA, (beginitalic)The Crew
(enditalic)offers crisp dialogue and a clever script that keeps the
story moving.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their star power, none of the actors walks through this
picture. They're all working so hard they achieve a chemistry that
makes you believe they've been friends for years.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfuss does a fabulous job narrating the story, and Reynolds
is wonderfully understated as the violent ``Bats,'' who loses his
job at Burger King in hilarious fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Hedaya turns in his finest performance to date as thick-headed
``Brick,'' whose job at a mortuary ultimately comes in handy. The
gang is rounded out by ``Mouth'' (Seymour Cassel), who talks only
at the most inopportune times.
</P>
<P>
   After a snappy opening that introduces us to the gang in their
youth, we fast-forward to the present, where they're living in a
retirement home being circled by yuppie vultures who crave their
ocean views.
</P>
<P>
   As the noose tightens, the boys dream up a plan: They spirit a
body from the mortuary and leave him in the lobby, making it look
like a gang hit. The plan backfires when it turns out that the
``victim'' was the father of a local drug dealer (Miguel Sandoval).
</P>
<P>
   Sandoval gives a great comedic performance as the overserious
dealer, Raul Ventana, who mistakenly thinks he's being victimized
by competing drug lords. Sandoval gets laughs just about every time
he's onscreen. Lainie Kazan does a nice turn as a woman who is
kidnapped by the boys, as does Tilly, playing a stripper without
the requisite heart of gold.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)The Crew (enditalic)includes several sidesplitting
sequences that are as original as they are funny. At one point, the
gang employs a mouse to start a fire, with the camera following the
little guy through all the nooks and crannies. That scene had the
audience roaring throughout.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a really inventive sequence involving Ventana and
some unfortunate members of his gang, who are dangling upside down
by ropes. Somehow, Sandoval is able to keep a straight face, which
makes it even funnier.
</P>
<P>
   On top of this, there's also a sweet back story involving
Dreyfuss' character trying to locate his long-lost daughter, who
disappeared when he was serving a prison term.
</P>
<P>
   The plot line gives the story just enough weight to make it
touching.
</P>
<P>
   The only mystery here is why Touchstone chose to open one of the
year's funniest films in late August. No matter, though.
(beginitalic)The Crew (enditalic)should have legs well into the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the guys still have it.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Muller at bill.muller(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
