<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 08:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1877 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-BRINGITON-REVIEW &LR;      08-25 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRINGITON-REVIEW </SLUG>
  
 BC-BRINGITON-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    `BRING IT ON' COULD MAKE YOU SAY `TAKE IT AWAY!'(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (beginitalic)Bring It On (enditalic)poses the musical question:
Who put the ``duh'' in dumb?
</P>
<P>
   Well, now we know.
</P>
<P>
   This is what happens when you take two dozen cheerleading
routines and patch them together with rejected dialogue from
(beginitalic)Beverly Hills 90210(enditalic). You get
(beginitalic)Clueless(enditalic) without the charm or trace of a
plot.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's not much room for story between cheerleading
tryouts, cheerleading practice, cheerleading contests and
cheerleading summits, which include winning lines such as, ``This
is not a democracy. It's a cheerocracy.''
</P>
<P>
   This movie isn't even cute, mostly because of its parade of
unlikable characters: snippy, foul-mouthed rich girls who seem to
live in their cheerleading uniforms. They're so unpleasant, we
really don't care if they win the big competition.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is clearly aimed at teenage girls; the studio trucked
in a busload of them for the screening in Phoenix. If only they had
drowned out more of the inane dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that the cheerleading theme may bring teens into the
theater, but they might as well watch the real thing on ESPN2.
Except for the predictably corny finale, the pep squad sequences
are pretty unremarkable.
</P>
<P>
   This film is also filled with lewd references and sexual
innuendo that seem out of place in an otherwise lightweight story.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)Bring It On (enditalic)stars Kirsten Dunst as
Torrance, captain of a champion cheerleading squad at a ritzy San
Diego high school. In a crisis of pom-pom proportions, Torrance has
to find a new routine for the nationals after learning her team's
material was stolen from an inner-city squad, the East Compton
Clovers.
</P>
<P>
   The film plays up the race angle, but the Clovers get the short
shrift as caricatures that walk on set, deliver put-downs and then
disappear. Even so, Gabrielle Union stands out as the Clovers'
strong-willed captain.
</P>
<P>
   As Torrance struggles to find a new routine, she meets some
characters lifted from other movies, including Cliff (Jesse
Bradford), a guitar-playing, retro outsider, and his sister, Missy
(Eliza Dushku), a sophisticated tough girl who rolls her eyes a
lot.
</P>
<P>
   Torrance is also equipped with the standard-issue cheating
boyfriend, irritating little brother and nearly invisible but
well-meaning parents.
</P>
<P>
   Dunst gives a totally flat performance, almost as if she's
insulted to be making a cheerleading movie. She has none of the
sparkle that Alicia Silverstone brought to
(beginitalic)Clueless(enditalic). And this film could have used a
little sparkle. Or something.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a fairly well-done opening sequence, the funniest
scenes roll during the credits, when the actors and actresses
freelance to (beginitalic)Mickey,(enditalic) the Toni Basil tune
from the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   As they dance around, you can tell they're relieved that the
movie is over.
</P>
<P>
   Just like the audience.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Muller at bill.muller(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
