<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 10:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1889 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      08-25 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING A SLOW PACE IN A FAST WORLD 

</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've been zooming down the information highway so fast and for
so long we almost forgot there are people still poking along the
back roads, preferring the scenic route.
</P>
<P>
   They are so far offline they don't even have e-mail. They'd be
insulted to be called a user and they don't care about capturing
eyeballs.
</P>
<P>
   When they want to chat, they pick up the phone. To keep up with
what's happening they read (oh, bless them) the printed newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   They like referring to themselves as Luddites, in a self-mocking
and yet prideful way.
</P>
<P>
   Luddites are named for Ned Ludd, who in the early 18th century
worried that machinery was not a good thing for the working man and
inspired his British brothers, who named themselves after Ludd, to
go around breaking up manufacturing equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Flora Lee is a Luddite, although her resistance is merely
personal. Computers, she's long said, are fine for other people,
especially the high school students she teaches and her son, who is
an Internet Web page designer.
</P>
<P>
   Flora Lee still writes letters, for goodness sake, and when she
tells of shopping for the perfect creamy paper with hand-painted
edges and then finding stamps to match and maybe even buying
sealing wax, she sounds as dreamy as someone setting off to buy
their first Palm Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walk into a stationery store, I'm in a cloud,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   But now Flora Lee has tip-toed into the World Wide Web, not to
be snagged, merely to visit.
</P>
<P>
   She went over to the other side for several reasons. First of
all, as a teacher, she believes, ``My role is to present as many
choices and possibilities to students as I can.'' And for them, she
says the Internet is essential. ``If you're a young person and
you're not fluent in this language, it's a detriment.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the school put a computer in her room and she couldn't
ignore it. Also, as a former hipster, she felt some self-imposed
pressure to become more techno-savvy. For the first time in her
boomer life she felt ``on the disadvantaged side of the generation
gap.''
</P>
<P>
   So this summer, she reported almost in an embarrassed way, she
took a junior college course in basic computer use. She would have
preferred to use her time learning Italian, although she makes the
analogy between it and Net-speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is the new language. If everyone suddenly started
speaking Italian and you wanted to know what they were talking
about, you'd need to learn Italian.''
</P>
<P>
   So she's learned a little and maybe enough for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   She appreciates the organizational style. Her teacher compared
the storage of information to 3-D file boxes ``and those Russian
dolls with the smaller dolls nesting inside the bigger ones.''
</P>
<P>
   And she marvels, she said, at the ``brilliant minds'' behind the
Internet's creation, although she says as a Luddite, ``I don't
really like machines. I believe that our chemical and mechanical
advances up to World War II were sufficient enough to run the
planet.''
</P>
<P>
   Until last week she went without cable TV, but then decided she
wanted to watch Joe Lieberman up close.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at a machine is not her style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dig in the earth,'' she says, although she might be won over
if they came up with a voice-activated PC, ``like a Dick
Tracy-style wristwatch.''
</P>
<P>
   I think many of us have our Luddite moments, or maybe just those
who get Dick Tracy references. I like to darkly joke that future
generations will be born with ergonomically correct bottoms, little
beady eyes, round shoulders and ambidextrous claws.
</P>
<P>
   I also love hearing that one of Flora Lee's former students
became a programmer, made a bunch of money, got bored, and is now
teaching kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
