<HEADER>
A1976 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-FINANCIAL-INFO-O     08-25 1565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-FINANCIAL-INFO-ONLINE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MOST ONLINE INVESTORS, INFORMATION BEATS SPEED  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 &HT;    (ART ADV: One B&AMP;W graphic is available electronically by calling
William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 &HT;    
 By JAN. M. ROSEN  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Despite those banner advertisements on Web sites for, say, $7
stock trades, the Internet's greatest gift to investors is not
online trading but the wealth of information it offers people who
are researching a company or a mutual fund before investing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has empowered people,'' said Robert N. Gordon,
the president of the Twenty-First Securities Corp., an investment
management firm in Manhattan that specializes in risk-reduction
strategies. ``Investors used to be hostage to their brokers; if
they wanted stock quotes, they had to call their brokers, and only
the brokers had access to research reports. The Internet has broken
down the information wall. Now investors can eliminate the
middleman.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Kochis, the president of Kochis Fitz, a San Francisco
money-management firm, called online investing ``fast, reliable and
convenient, a great thing.'' But referring to the popular image of
the get-rich-quick day trader, he warned that online investing
``can be abused by the user.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial professionals have long warned against trading
impulsively on supposedly hot tips, saying many people cannot
resist buying shares of what will surely be the next Microsoft the
minute they hear about it from the guy in the office down the hall.
And with Internet chat rooms creating even more hype, people with
poor impulse control can lose money even faster.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, first-class information is also available; it
can be used profitably whether one is trading online or through a
traditional broker, is an active investor or just rethinks
strategies at tax time. All the leading brokerage firms, both
full-service and discount, have secure, accessible Web sites, as do
service organizations such as Morningstar and Bloomberg.
</P>
<P>
   Tracey E. Curvey, the executive vice president of online
brokerage for Fidelity Personal Investments, compares this more
thoughtful approach to the Internet to patients' use of the Web to
research health problems before visiting a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors are also moving from research to trading. Assets
in online brokerage accounts grew 23.5 percent in the first quarter
of this year, to more than $1 trillion, US Bancorp Piper Jaffray
reported last month. And online trading volume rose 69 percent over
the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kochis cautioned, ``stock picking is not for the casual,
lay investor,'' although a handful of his clients who have spent
substantial time and effort on research have been successful in
fairly aggressive online trading. Many more prefer to have the firm
manage their investments.
</P>
<P>
   Neither approach is right or wrong, Kochis added, but is a
matter of personality and individual choice. Some people are
entrepreneurial, while others like to delegate.
</P>
<P>
   With the information available on the Internet, people who feel
insecure about making investments can learn the basics of investing
and personal finance before they trade. Online trading is the easy
part _ with a few mouse clicks, you can buy or sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do it on your own time,'' Curvey pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   But prudent investors do not trade until they have researched a
security's fundamentals and considered how it fits into their
financial plan and their tolerance of risk. One approach is to put
the money you're investing into a money-market account. You can use
the resources on your brokerage firm's Web site to learn about the
market, then set up a dummy portfolio, research stocks or mutual
funds and simulate trades.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you feel comfortable, go ahead and make a transaction,''
Curvey said.
</P>
<P>
   Many consumers are smarter about their future than their
predecessors 20 years ago, having gained experience with their
401(k) plans. Many young people, too, have grown up using
computers, so online research and trading seems natural. The leap
to online trading is undoubtedly easier for self-directed customers
of a discount broker, such as Fidelity, than for those working with
traditional brokers. In return for the higher commissions, the
full-service firms offer clients guidance as well as execute
transactions, but even these brokers are pressured to offer online
trading and resources.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch, for example, offers a lot of information at
www.mlol.ml.com. There are financial calculators, asset allocation
models, courses on financial planning and understanding risk,
mutual fund and stock scanners and detailed reports from the firm's
analysts, as well as access to news and one's own account
performance.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to trading, Merrill Lynch clients can deal with a
financial consultant, as they have traditionally; choose a managed
account; trade online through Merrill Lynch Direct at $29.95 a
transaction; or use some of each by linking accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Joel S. Isaacson, a certified public accountant and certified
financial planner who is the president of his own firm in
Manhattan, said that online trading could be ``good for
do-it-yourselfers, provided they do the research, buy good stuff
and hold it'' rather than trading in and out. Even so, he added,
``most people are better off using some advice or buying index
funds.''
</P>
<P>
   People who open an account where cheap trades are advertised may
lose more through poor executions than they gain on low
commissions, Isaacson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're just executing a trade, you can sometimes negotiate
low commissions with a full-service broker,'' he said, especially
when a block of stock is involved.
</P>
<P>
   For people who do want to invest online, the quality of
information on a broker's site can be more important than the
charge for each transaction. But it is good in any case to remember
that the Internet does not offer investors a superhighway around
the market's ups and downs. People who speed ahead may well crash.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL SIDEBAR: DANGER SIGNS FOR TRADERS
</P>
<P>
   Investing online does not condemn an investor to becoming a
crazed day trader any more than enjoying a glass of wine at dinner
leads inexorably to alcoholism. Still, for certain people, online
investing, like taking a drink, can lead to trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had a bad day at work or with your family, go to the
gym, not the computer,'' said Linda Barbanel, a Manhattan
psychotherapist and the author of ``Sex, Money &AMP; Power.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people who think that they have stumbled or have not been
appreciated in one area try to prove themselves in another, she
explained. In the last couple of years, that other area has often
been the stock market, where people take unwarranted risks in the
quest to make a killing and impress their spouse, boss or friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many alcoholics who give up alcohol take up other compulsions
_ shopping, spending and now online trading,'' Barbanel said.
``Gamblers and day traders tend to be compulsive. They can't tear
themselves away when trading, because when they are doing it, they
do not have to think about their frustration, anger and
depression.''
</P>
<P>
   For people who follow prudent financial practices and research
their investments carefully, online trading can be remunerative,
Barbanel added, but compulsive traders often skip that part of the
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think of it as a game, but it is a treacherous one,'' she
said, citing these warning signs:
</P>
<P>
   _ If you feel it is important to make trades every day.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you see online trading as a way to get rich quick, even
quitting a job to devote more time it.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you are borrowing money, running up credit-card debt or
taking a second mortgage on your house to trade, you are in serious
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   People who do well at online trading tend to be entrepreneurial,
Barbanel said, adding: ``They want to be captain of their own ship.
They like to make their own decisions. They are risk-takers to
begin with.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wish to be powerful, respected and in control,'' she
noted, even when it would be smarter to get help.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
