<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Defense Secretary William Cohen has brought a
welcome moment of sanity to a presidential campaign shouting match
about miliary spending and readiness that was threatening to get
wildly out of hand. With luck, Cohen's comments will discipline the
debate. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.)
MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Jack's in San Francisco; I'm down here, at
the appendage of the United States. We talk often, about
earthquakes and hurricanes. I always tell him that living in an
earthquake-prone area is more comfortable than being in a
hurricane-prone one because earthquakes don't visibly creep up on
you, day-by-day, mile-by-mile. With an earthquake, it's BOOM!, and
that's it (except for the aftershocks.) (Kleinberg, Cox News
Service.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ Spectrum governs the wireless world.
Come September, the feds plan to put up for bid some of the
sweetest spectrum around. Such a choice parcel of wireless real
estate is just what's needed to build out third-generation mobile
systems that enable cell phones to surf the Internet at high
speeds. But there's a hitch. In most large markets, these
wavelengths are already in use. In regulatory jargon, the FCC sale
is ``on the encumbered basis.'' (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox
News Service in the Washington bureau.) 18
</P>
