<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dragons don't like to undress
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ As a reporter, it's the ones that get away that
haunt you.
</P>
<P>
   You don't gloat _ not for long, anyway _ over the big interviews
you bag. It's the ones that elude you that stay with you.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it is with Heater and me.
</P>
<P>
   All summer long, I pursued my prey. Heater is, of course, the
Dragons' mascot, that towering green dragon whose identity has been
more closely guarded than the last Survivor.
</P>
<P>
   I even talked, briefly, with the Elusive One, the Greta Garbo of
the firebreathing set. The ``real'' Heater _ or the one who most
frequently dons the costume _ initially agreed to talk to me, so
long as I didn't reveal the mascot's true identity.
</P>
<P>
   It was a big concession, but one I'd be willing to make for
Dayton's newest superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Look around the stadium, and the eight-inch Heater stuffed
animals are as plentiful as popcorn. Retail manager Christie Wise
estimates that the Dragons Den gift shop has sold 1,750 of the
dolls. ``We're not able to keep it in stock,'' Wise said. ``Kids
love Heater.''
</P>
<P>
   She didn't need to tell me. For my daughter, Heater is not only
the Dragons mascot; he is the Dragons, or at least the primary
reason to come out to the game. I can't tell you how many
accommodating pairs of knees I've sidled past after yet another
Heater sighting.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how many times she wraps herself around Heater's
knees, human Velcro, the dragon never loses patience. ``When it
comes to Heater, you can't get too many hugs,'' Veronica explained,
after the sixth such outing at a recent game.
</P>
<P>
   All summer long, Dragon spokesman Brad Eaton and I played phone
tag. Somehow, the interview never got set up, but I was confident
it would happen before summer's end.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last week, Eaton called with the bad news: There would be
no Heater interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not even if I promised not to reveal his identity?'' I
pleaded.
</P>
<P>
   No dice. ``Everybody knows there is a real person inside the
costume,'' Eaton explained, ``but we want to hold on to that sense
of mystery. When Heater runs into that tunnel leading from the
dugout, nobody sees him but the players.''
</P>
<P>
   Heater has his own dressing room under the stands, right across
from the umps', and the mascot is under strict orders not to remove
the costume until safely in the dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids have all too much reality in their lives. It's important
for them to have that bit of fantasy,'' director of entertainment
Todd Hollst noted. ``It's like Mickey Mouse. For the kids, it's not
a guy dressed in a Mickey Mouse costume, it's Mickey Mouse
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Heater's ``character'' has evolved as the season has worn on,
Hollst said, thanks to the improvisation of the person inside the
costume: ``Initially he was a Barney character who was big and
friendly and hugged babies. As the season went on, he became more
outgoing and developed a bit of an attitude, taking a dive on the
field, or snagging cotton candy from the vendors and giving it to
the crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all very well and good, but I still want my exclusive. I
want ``interview with well-known local dragon'' on my resume. And I
have tough questions that need answering:
</P>
<P>
   How does it feel to walk around in the summer heat in a 40-pound
costume? To be the idol of thousands?
</P>
<P>
   Do you ever feel like telling all those kids to blow their noses
and go home?
</P>
<P>
   And can magic still be magic if you know its face and name?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
