r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN0826-C     08-25 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scheme to hit jackpot on insect repellent not quite foolproof
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ While looking through my home files for a friend's
birth date, a yellowed newspaper clipping fell on the floor. The
headline said ``Insect juice kills pests.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knight News Service article reminded me of two things:
</P>
<P>
   One, my filing system sucks stump water.
</P>
<P>
   Two, how excited I was when I first read this article about 25
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The words in the article written by Rich Kent caused my heart to
race and a light bulb to go on over my head. ``I'm going to be rich
and famous,'' I remember thinking.
</P>
<P>
   The article was datelined Palmetto, Fla. It began, ``Are your
plants bugged? Liquefy some of the creatures with a blender, spray
the stuff on your harried greenery and presto!''
</P>
<P>
   Kent learned about the miracle of blended bug juice from an
article in Organic Gardening and Framing Magazine. The magazine
article told about Mike Sipe, a 37-year-old fish farmer and
pesticide opponent, who came up with a cheap, environmentally
friendly way to combat unwanted insects.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine article asked for reader responses about Sipe's
non-polluting bug-juice method of controlling bugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``After reading the article,'' a Fort Scott, Kan., motel
operator wrote the magazine, ``I rounded up some of the beetles
(that infested his kitchen) and mashed them thoroughly with water.
I dabbed the bug juice on the walls and counter where the bugs were
worst.
</P>
<P>
   NOTHING BUT DEAD BUGS
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-four hours later I checked the counters and found
nothing but dead bugs.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine included a number of other testimonials to the
effectiveness of Sipe's bug juice discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Sipe said he got the idea from the work done by a former U.S.
Department of Agriculture entomologist who used a similar control
method that employed diseased insects.
</P>
<P>
   Sipe tried the method with healthy bugs. It worked.
</P>
<P>
   He figured insects carry pathogens that are released with the
bugs are crushed. Either that, or crushing the bugs releases
distress pheromones that drive off other insects. If not that,
crushing the bugs may release an odor that attracts natural
predators. He didn't know why, it just worked.
</P>
<P>
   About this time, Texas was being invaded by fire ants, a
particularly vicious foreign pest accidently imported into the
United States via a ship in the port of Mobile, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Fire ants, like killer bees, attack in swarms. They are small,
about the size of harmless sugar ants, but they ruin crops and kill
wildlife. On humans, fire ants deliver bites that develop into
pustules and often leave scars.
</P>
<P>
   No one had figured how to stop fire ants from taking over the
South. Like killer bees, they supposedly avoid cold climates.
</P>
<P>
   I now had the solution. I was going to puree fire ants into a
million bucks.
</P>
<P>
   I put a shovel and a variety of containers in my Volkswagen bus
and headed east from my apartment in Austin until I hit the leading
edge of the fire ant invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to shovel fire ants into buckets, jars and a kitty litter
box was a lesson in humility.
</P>
<P>
   Fire ants swarmed up the shovel handle and up my legs. I jumped,
swatted, slapped, ran back to the bus and tore off in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Fire ants now have taken over most of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who wants it can have my idea. Blend up a few pounds of
fire ants and see if their juice kills other fire ants.
</P>
<P>
   If it works, you could become a millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Try it and let me know how it works. It should make another
column if nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
