<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Saturday, August 26 and Sunday, August
27, 2000 are moving today to clients of the New York Times News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ While looking through my home
files for a friend's birth date, a yellowed newspaper clipping fell
on the floor. The headline said ``Insect juice kills pests.'' The
Knight News Service article reminded me of two things: One, my
filing system sucks stump water. Two, how excited I was when I
first read this article about 25 years ago. The words in the
article written by Rich Kent caused my heart to race and a light
bulb to go on over my head. ``I'm going to be rich and famous,'' I
remember thinking. (Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ BONNEVILLE DAM, Ore. _
After 10 days on the road with the North Fayetteville Moyes in
their new land yacht, we are appoaching Portland and Delta back to
Atlanta. I'm still waiting on Alex to cook his specialty lamb
chops, the main reason I agreed to this adventure in the first
place. Unless I dozed through the film and got my facts mixed up,
Bonneville is the first super-dam Franklin Roosevelt decided to
build when he moved into the White House. The Columbia River,
bigger than the Savannah, the Chattahoochee and the Altamaha rolled
into one, has been spinning Bonneville's turbines since the middle
1930s. (Jim Minter is a former editor of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ As a reporter, it's the ones
that get away that haunt you. You don't gloat _ not for long,
anyway _ over the big interviews you bag. It's the ones that elude
you that stay with you. That's the way it is with Heater and me.
All summer long, I pursued my prey. Heater is, of course, the
Dragons' mascot, that towering green dragon whose identity has been
more closely guarded than the last Survivor. (McCarty, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CAMP _ TUXEDO, N.C. _ It's 583 miles from our house in the
Washington suburbs to the Blackfoot Lodge, the small clapboard
cabin that my son Robby and seven other boys called home for two
weeks in August. It's an even longer journey from manhood back to
boyhood. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location Atlanta, category Editorial and Op-Ed, subcategory
Columns/Commentary
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Defense Secretary William Cohen has brought a
welcome moment of sanity to a presidential campaign shouting match
about miliary spending and readiness that was threatening to get
wildly out of hand. With luck, Cohen's comments will discipline the
debate. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.)
MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Jack's in San Francisco; I'm down here, at
the appendage of the United States. We talk often, about
earthquakes and hurricanes. I always tell him that living in an
earthquake-prone area is more comfortable than being in a
hurricane-prone one because earthquakes don't visibly creep up on
you, day-by-day, mile-by-mile. With an earthquake, it's BOOM!, and
that's it (except for the aftershocks.) (Kleinberg, Cox News
Service.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ Spectrum governs the wireless world.
Come September, the feds plan to put up for bid some of the
sweetest spectrum around. Such a choice parcel of wireless real
estate is just what's needed to build out third-generation mobile
systems that enable cell phones to surf the Internet at high
speeds. But there's a hitch. In most large markets, these
wavelengths are already in use. In regulatory jargon, the FCC sale
is ``on the encumbered basis.'' (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox
News Service in the Washington bureau.) 18
</P>
<P>
   MOVED THURSDAY in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories.
</P>
