<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looks, not math, guide rocker design
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Today we'll discuss rockers for a baby crib, which
aren't a big problem, and working with oak, which can be a very big
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Williams wrote to say that ``We have an antique baby crib
from which the rockers were removed before it came to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish to build rockers for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are your thoughts on the correct size and `rocking
capability' for these rockers?''
</P>
<P>
   Williams went on to provide the dimensions of the cradle and
speculate on federal rules governing crib rockers.
</P>
<P>
   Rockers on cribs, and rocking chairs for that matter, are really
a matter of aesthetics rather than any kind of mathmetical formula.
All you really need to worry about is keeping their curve shallow
enough to promote gentle rocking.
</P>
<P>
   You don't want an older child to start rocking the baby so
enthusiastically that the crib tips over. To that end, some makers
work flats, or even recurves, into the ends of rockers to prevent
tipping.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, I recommend drawing the end profile of the crib to
scale on a piece of graph paper, and then using a compass to work
out a pleasing curve for the rockers. Generally speaking, don't run
them so long that they present a hazard to traffic in the vicinity.
</P>
<P>
   The curve can then be enlarged full-size onto wrapping paper or
something similar and used as a pattern for bandsawing the rockers,
or for making the molds if you intend to laminate them.
</P>
<P>
   And, incidentally, laws regulating things like baby crib rockers
_ if there even is such a law _ are confined to products you offer
for sale. As far as I know, our lawmakers have not gotten into the
business of regulating what we make for our own satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Shillington in Snellville, Ga., asks:
</P>
<P>
   ``Please advise (how in the world) one might drill holes and
pilot holes in 1-by-3 red oak for No. 10 wood screws. I am an
amateur woodworker at best, but am baffled as to what type of bit
to use to drill these holes. All I seem to be able to do is burn my
way through, using new bits and a 3/8-inch electric drill.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that, I have to start with a very small bit and then ream
out. I have about 60 holes to do for this project. The red oak was
probably a bad choice for an outside hanging planter of a unique
design that I saw and photographed on vacation in Alaska and want
to duplicate, but the wood is now purchased and cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I had no solution to this problem, because it is
exactly what I went through when I had a project involving screws
in white oak. I got it done, and swore I would never do it again,
an oath to which I have faithfully adhered.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
