<SLUG> BC-FBC-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASEY CASE BRINGS JUSTICE INTO QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Penn State opens its season Saturday in the Meadowlands
against Southern California, Rashard Casey will be the Nittany
Lions' starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, that would be a ``dog bites man'' bit of information.
Casey started at times last season for the Lions, is a senior, and
is the only QB with experience on the Penn State roster.
</P>
<P>
   But May 14, in his hometown of Hoboken, N.J., Casey was involved
in a fight outside a nightclub/bar. He allegedly beat up an
off-duty policeman and was charged with aggravated assault, a
felony.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State officials and coach Joe Paterno immediately began an
investigation. Their conclusion? ``We know more than you do, and it
isn't as bad as it seems.''
</P>
<P>
   Until more compelling evidence is revealed, Casey not only
remains on the Penn State roster but he will start against the
Trojans in the Kickoff Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? Nebraska coach Tom Osborne and Lawrence
Phillips? Florida State coach Bobby Bowden and Peter Warrick?
</P>
<P>
   The presumption _ as it should be _ is innocent until proven
guilty. And word from Hoboken is that the entire story has not been
revealed and the charges could be lessened to a simple misdemeanor
or dropped altogether. A grand jury has yet to rule whether it will
seek felony charges against Casey, and there is no timetable for
when it will move on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Which begs a couple of questions.
</P>
<P>
   If Casey were a third-string QB instead of the only experienced
one, would Paterno act the same way?
</P>
<P>
   He says yes.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a different standard of justice for athletes at
big-time schools?
</P>
<P>
   At Penn State, students who have been involved in fights have
been suspended for a semester.
</P>
<P>
   Paterno has his own standard of justice. Two years ago, he
suspended a linebacker for a game for using fake identification at
a local bar.
</P>
<P>
   At some schools, regulations are in place that take the decision
out of the coach's hands. Florida State, for example, had a policy
in place that forced Warrick to miss two games for his
transgression, which involved buying clothing for a fraction of its
true cost.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens with Casey, no one disputes that
something happened.
</P>
<P>
   At 73, and within seven wins of passing Alabama's Bear Bryant as
Division 1-A's winningest coach, Paterno does not have to worry
about his reputation. He is almost bulletproof.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems clear Casey needs to face some kind of consequences
for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Paterno will suspend him for a game, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   If Casey suffers no consequences, Paterno, who has spent half a
century at Penn State serving as coach and mentor to a couple of
generations of players, will have done himself and Penn State a
disservice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the hot seat
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No hotter coaching seat in college football exists today, or
most days, than the one at Notre Dame. After last year's 5-7
season, Fighting Irish coach Bob Davie knows his mission is simple:
Turn it around, and turn it around quickly. Word out of South Bend
is that a minimum record of 7-4 is required and that that might not
even be enough. Other coaches who need a quick fix are Rutgers's
Terry Shea, North Carolina's Carl Torbush, USC's Paul Hackett, and
Arizona State's Bruce Snyder . . . Games of Year, Decade, Century,
etc.: Sept. 9, Nebraska at Notre Dame _ It could be ugly, and
Nebraska has not been to South Bend since 1947; Sept. 30, Wisconsin
at Michigan _ Could be for the Big Ten title, even though it's only
September; Oct. 7, Florida State at Miami _ Just like the old days;
Nov. 18, Auburn at Alabama _ Tigers come to Tuscaloosa for first
time since 1901. Roll Tide? . . . Good surprises: Texas Christian,
Illinois, Toledo. Bad surprises: UCLA, Michigan State, Stanford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
