<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIGEAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI OR VICK? TOUGH TO PICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Butch Davis hardly entertained the
hypothetical question. At last month's Big East Media Day, the
University of Miami coach firmly refused a proposed trade of
Virginia Tech's mercurial quarterback, Michael Vick, in exchange
for the Hurricanes' veteran defense.
</P>
<P>
   Straight up. No strings attached. No players-to-be-named-later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nooo, uh-uh,'' Davis said, wasting no time in nixing the idea.
``I mean, Michael's a great player and all, but I don't think you'd
trade seven starters for one guy. Nooo, uh-uh.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because Davis knows he'll likely need his entire defense
to keep Vick in check when the Hurricanes host Virginia Tech Nov. 4
in a game that could likely determine the Big East conference
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Because it returns a solid nucleus of defensive starters,
including a veteran secondary that has been ranked among the
nation's best, Miami was picked first in the preseason media poll
to win the conference title ahead of defending champion Virginia
Tech, which must plug gaping holes on its defense and again pin all
its hopes on the talents of its Heisman Trophy-contending
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   With Miami and Virginia Tech expected to vie for the BCS and
Toyota Gator Bowl slots, Syracuse, picked to finish third, likely
will contend with Boston College, West Virginia, and Pittsburgh for
one of the three other postseason spots (the Insight.com Bowl, the
HomePoint.com Music City Bowl, and the Jeep Oahu/Aloha bowls). With
the new arrangement with the Oahu/Aloha bowls, which will pair a
Big East team against a Pac-10 opponent, the conference is
guaranteed at least four bowl spots and will get five any year
Notre Dame reaches a BCS game or does not qualify for postseason
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's flattering, but it really doesn't mean a great
deal, though,'' Davis said of his team's preseason perch atop the
conference poll. ``It's going to be where you finish at the end of
the year, which is a byproduct of how healthy you stay and how well
you play and how much progress you make.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes sustained critical losses on both sides of the
ball when starting quarterback Kenny Kelly decided to leave school
to pursue his baseball career and the NCAA ruled starting
linebacker Nate Webster ineligible for his senior year after his
dalliance with the NFL Draft.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis has more than enough talent on the shelf to replenish
his team, especially on offense, where six starters return to help
sophomore quarterback Ken Dorsey. A solid supporting cast includes
running back James Jackson and game-breaking receivers Santana Moss
and Reggie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   Vick is being counted upon to guide the Hokies back to the
Promised Land after leading his team to an 11-0 regular season and
a spot in the BCS title game opposite top-ranked Florida State,
which survived some palpitating moments to score a 46-29 victory in
the Nokia Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, he's going to keep improving,'' Virginia Tech
coach Frank Beamer said of Vick. ``He ran a faster 40 time this
year than he did last year and he's throwing the ball farther than
he did last year and as he throws more, he'll probably throw the
ball a little more accurate than he threw last year. I think where
you'll really see Michael Vick improve is in his decision making.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one area Syracuse coach Paul Pasqualoni will definitely
need improvement. He waffled last year in deciding on a starting
quarterback, going back and forth between Troy Nunes and Madei
Williams. Robin Anderson and junior college transfer Chad Elliott
will enter the mix this year to further complicate the decision for
the Orangemen, who started last season 5-1 but wound up losing four
of their last five to back into a spot in the Music City Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But if given the choice between Miami's defense and Vick, which
would Pasqualoni take? ``That's a tough question,'' he said.
``Miami's got great defensive skill and Michael Vick is probably
the best quarterback in America . . . to choose between them is
like being a little kid in the candy store, I guess. I don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the heavy losses he sustained on defense, one would expect
Boston College coach Tom O'Brien to opt for Miami's defense. But
the Eagles, picked to finish fourth, will be solid on offense, led
by senior quarterback Tim Hasselbeck.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quarterback is always a good starting point,'' O'Brien
said. ``You need somebody who can win a game for you. But those
players have to be surrounded by good players, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
