<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMNBOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S ENOUGH TO GO AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston College is typical of most major college football
programs. Its games are on five television outlets: CBS, NBC, ESPN,
Fox Sports New England, and New England Sports Network.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with generating revenue. Nor is there much
wrong with student-athletes having their schedules determined by TV
programming, especially if the school stands to make an additional
$200,000 if the game goes network instead of cable.
</P>
<P>
   BC's game against Virginia Tech Sept. 30, for instance, may air
on CBS at 3:30 p.m. or ESPN at 8 p.m. The same thing happens Nov.
25, when BC plays Miami at 3:30 p.m. on CBS or 7:30 p.m. on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the wild world of college football rights fees
has been good to television as well as the schools. Ever since a
federal court in 1984 ruled against the NCAA's control over
television deals, the rules of supply and demand have dictated the
course of some high-profile schools, such as Notre Dame, and most
conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a win-win for the most part,'' said sports business
economist David M. Carter. ``The television revenue gives leagues a
chance to make money through their own individual athletic
departments, and the cash trickles down through the conference-wide
food chain. The only problem is the bickering among schools for
their fair share.''
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the Big East, BC shares the roughly $15 million
in annual television revenues from the league's television partners
_ ESPN and CBS. In what can only be described as capitalistic
socialism, the Big East teams with the highest demand and bowl
appearances receive more, while those at the bottom receive a
minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Tom McElroy, the Big East's senior associate commissioner, would
not disclose the league's revenue-sharing plan. ``This is not the
kind of thing where it's the haves against the have-nots,'' McElroy
said. ``The have-nots get enough money, somewhere in the
seven-figure range. And the system rewards the teams that attract
the appearances.''
</P>
<P>
   McElroy said there are safeguards in the Big East's deals with
CBS and ESPN to make sure teams such as Miami and Virginia Tech are
not always shown on national television at the expense of the
league's lower teams.
</P>
<P>
   The real money is in the bowl games. Earlier this year, ABC and
the Bowl Championship Series agreed to a four-year, $400 million
contract extension. The new deal runs through the 2005 season,
which includes bowl games in January 2006. Each team playing in a
BCS game _ the Orange, Fiesta, Sugar, and Rose bowls _ receives
about $13 million, and the extension is expected to raise the
payouts to about $17 million.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said only a handful of teams make money each year and the
rich programs, such as Penn State and Florida State, get richer
because of their performance and marketability. But the vast
majority of college football programs need financial help to remain
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with most of the schools is that traditional ways
of raising money are not enough,'' Carter said. ``The teams aren't
winning, and therefore are not as attractive to watch either in
person or on television. But their fixed costs remain, and as a
result, those programs are hemorrhaging badly.''
</P>
<P>
   TV outlets are only too willing to help. ESPN aired its first
college football game in 1979, on tape. The first live telecast _
Brigham Young against Pittsburgh _ aired Sept. 1, 1984. ESPN's John
Wildhack produced that game and has since become the cable
service's senior vice president for programming. Nowadays, ESPN and
ESPN2 air 93 regular-season and bowl games. On some Saturdays,
viewers can watch five or six games, from noon to midnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of importance, college football is clearly one of our
staples,'' Wildhack said. ``It's a critical component of our
programming. And college football performs well in today's
competitive environment.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. ABC, ESPN's sister network, has 24 regular-season
games as well as nine conference championship and bowl games.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports New England will air 40 regular-season games,
including some Pacific-10 conference matchups.
</P>
<P>
   Trev Alberts, who played for the University of Nebraska in the
early 1990s and is now a college and pro football analyst for
CNN/SI, said the television money is a good thing but at some point
the athletes need to have some say over not only how the money is
spent but also how their schedules are determined. Whether the
athletes are paid is an open question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about the money,'' Alberts said. ``The athletes see
the money. They see the coaches and their salaries and endorsement
deals. At some point, they are going to want theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 1126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
