<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2002 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-TEXAS-BOS &LR;      08-25 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS IS AGAIN THINKING BIG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The words come out of Darrell Royal's mouth
without hesitation, which doesn't mean he hasn't given the subject
of University of Texas football some thought.
</P>
<P>
   Lord knows, Royal, now 76, has thought a lot about the Longhorns
the past 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   When you talk Texas football, it's impossible not to mention
Royal's name, not talk about the three national championships,
which are the main reasons the Longhorns now play in a place called
Darrell K. Royal Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Royal sees signs of life in the Texas program he hasn't seen in
20 years. He sees a spark, a pride, and yes, almost an arrogance,
and he smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the difference in Texas football from what it was?'' he
asked. ``Mack Brown. It's that simple. He knows what it's about.
And he's absolutely the best PR guy I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, at a Mexican restaurant on Sixth Street in
Austin, Brown, beginning his third year as the Longhorns' coach, is
told of Royal's assessment and he comes close to blushing, saying
how nice it was of Royal to say those things and how he just hopes
to be a part of the tradition that is now being rekindled.
</P>
<P>
   Texas. Football. No. 1. Think about that. There was a time when
you started a college football season and even if you didn't know a
thing about the Longhorns, you automatically would pencil them into
your preseason top 5, the way voters do Nebraska and Florida State
these days.
</P>
<P>
   But something happened after the Royal era, which ended _ some
say prematurely _ in 1976 when Royal took his three national
championships and 167-47-5 record to the athletic director's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Texas football started to slide. Not so much as you could see in
the early days of Fred Akers, but steadily each year until it
reached the point a few years ago when you didn't even hear the
Longhorns mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the national championship. Not even in the top 25. Not
at all.
</P>
<P>
   The facilities started to deteriorate. Texas kids who used to
put the Longhorns at the top of their wish list would look to
Oklahoma, Florida, Michigan, and, much worse, other Texas schools,
such as Texas A&AMP;M, Baylor, and Southern Methodist.
</P>
<P>
   The UT tradition was there, but it was peeling and covered with
dust.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. Texas is back. Some argue the program is still a
recruiting class or two away from being in the high-rent district
it used to occupy.
</P>
<P>
   Brown himself tries to put the brakes on the optimism that you
can find everywhere in Austin in what is still one of the best
cities in America to work and play.
</P>
<P>
   But with a schedule that does not include Big 12 heavyweights
Kansas State and Nebraska, with 18 wins in the last two seasons
(including two over the Cornhuskers), and with 18 starters
returning, the future is now for Texas, which realistically can
climb all the way to No. 1 next January in the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brown says the talk is premature. Texas No. 1? Texas in the top
10? ``We lost our last three games and we're in the top 10 in most
polls,'' said Brown. ``But that's the power and tradition of this
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Royal knows about tradition: He created most of it. In 20 years
under Royal, Texas won 11 Southwest Conference championships and
national titles in 1963, '69, and '70. When Alabama's Paul ``Bear''
Bryant wanted to jump-start the Tide by running the wishbone
offense, he called Royal, the man who invented it.
</P>
<P>
   Royal remembers when the president came by to visit. ``We always
knew when he was coming, because we could hear his helicopter,''
said Royal of Lyndon Johnson's arrivals. ``The Texas band played
`Hail to the Chief.' He loved that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown remembers the day after he took the job. They told him he
was going to be formally introduced at halftime of a Texas
basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, sitting next to George W. Bush, asked the Texas governor
for some advice. ``He told me to just say hello, but make sure that
somewhere I said, `the great state of Texas,' '' said Brown,
laughing at the memory. ``I got up and said how happy I was to be
coaching here in the great state of Texas. The crowd went nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``crowd'' is ready to go nuts. It's been too long between
coronations. The last time Texas was ranked No. 1 in any football
poll was Oct. 9, 1984.
</P>
<P>
   When John Mackovic, who was a button-down guy in a
boots-and-jeans environment, was fired after a 4-7 season in 1997,
Texas football was a footnote in its own state.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of passion, there was indifference.
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of things,'' said DeLoss Dodds, who has sat in the AD's
chair since 1981. ``We were in a world then when people played by a
different set of rules. We just weren't getting the players. And we
let our facilities slip.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodds was referring to the scandal that resulted in penalties to
Southwest Conference schools SMU, Texas Christian, and Texas A&AMP;M,
implying that Texas could not keep up with schools that cheated.
</P>
<P>
   But in its heyday, Texas didn't have to cheat. It was Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Brown came from North Carolina, where he had built the Tar Heels
into a respectable football program that could deal with every team
except Florida State in the Atlantic Coast Conference.
</P>
<P>
   But the tradition at Carolina, despite the multimillion-dollar
improvement in football facilities he oversaw in his 10-year stay
in Chapel Hill, is basketball, not football.
</P>
<P>
   At Texas, there is no question about the sport of choice. Royal
told him that from the get-go. ``The good news,'' said Royal, ``is
that a lot of people care here. The bad news is that a lot of
people care here.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown has milked it better than any dairy farmer. Walk around
the state-of-the-art football complex and you are overwhelmed by
it. From the weight room, which is better equipped than the
plushest health club, to players' lounge, which is furnished with
soft leather couches, pool tables, big-screen television sets, and
saddles, yes, saddles.
</P>
<P>
   Ride in an elevator down to the locker room that is the equal of
any NFL team and you hear the ``Eyes of Texas'' along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we do,'' said Brown, ``is geared to recruiting.''
</P>
<P>
   And Brown knows how to do it as well as anyone. Texas has 1,200
high school or prep football coaches. Brown has written or visited
all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mack embraces the tradition,'' said Royal. ``When he got
hired, he called me up and said, `Will you help me with Texas
tradition?' Right then, I knew we had something special.''
</P>
<P>
   When Texas called three years ago, Brown went to his friend,
offensive coordinator Greg Davis, and said, ``What do you think?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him it was a no-brainer,'' said Davis, who came along
and has enjoyed the ride. ``Texas is different.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown wants Texas to be better. He knows he has a team that can
win. He knows he has not one, but two quarterbacks in Chris Simms
and Major Applewhite who can help him do it.
</P>
<P>
   The talk this summer in Austin has been about the quarterbacks.
Will it be Simms, the hot-shot sophomore and son of former Giants
All-Pro Phil Simms, or Applewhite, the tough kid who set 10 school
records, including throwing for 3,357 yards and 21 TDs as a
sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite went down with a knee injury during Texas's Cotton
Bowl loss to old SWC rival Arkansas and is now fighting for the job
that many people think will go to Simms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two No. 1s,'' said Brown with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Brown says he is going to need both of them to win. He's going
to need help from fans and alumni. But he knows he can do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place,'' he said, ``is special.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Eyes of Texas''?
</P>
<P>
   Make that the ``Eyes are on Texas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
