<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PAC10-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON COACH THINKS THE SCHOOLS CAN MAKE PAC-10 BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ On a clear, sunny day _ and there are more than you
think here at this time of year _ the view seems limitless from
Husky Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   You can see Lake Washington, where many Husky fans arrive for
games by boat. You can see Mount Rainier, snow-capped and majestic.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're Washington coach Rick Neuheisel, you can see
beyond that. You can see across the country to Florida, where
Florida State is the reigning national champion.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can see the heartland of America in Lincoln, Neb., where
the Cornhuskers are the preseason pick to be No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel, in his second year as the Huskies' coach, came here
from Colorado with that vision. He came back to the Pacific-10
Conference, where he once was a UCLA quarterback and assistant
coach, to raise the bar on the level of play, not only for
Washington, but for the conference as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a passion for football here,'' he said. ``We've shown
we can be the best and we can do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel was referring to the Washington program, which climbed
to the summit in 1991 when it shared the national championship with
Miami, but he was also talking about the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10 No. 1? Surely, you jest. If there are certainties in
the ebb and flow of a college football season, it is that the
Pac-10 will not be a survivor when the cutdowns of teams are made
for the national championship in November and early December.
</P>
<P>
   You probably will be right if you say the national champion will
be a team from the Atlantic Coast Conference, such as Florida
State, or a team from the Big East, like Miami or Virginia Tech, or
a team from the Southeastern Conference, such as Florida or
Tennessee, or a team from the Big 12, like Nebraska or perhaps
resurgent Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But you almost certainly will be right if you say the national
champion will not come from the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   Not in football. If you want to talk about overall success in
athletics, then the Pac-10 becomes the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at the Sears Cup standings, which grade schools in
all sports, and you'll find a staggering six Pac-10 teams in the
top 25.
</P>
<P>
   But in football? Forget about it. A year ago only Oregon at No.
19 in the Associated Press balloting cracked the top 25. This
season the top 10 doesn't include a Pac-10 team and only Washington
at No. 13 and Southern Cal at No. 15 made the top 25.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not that there isn't or hasn't been talent. The
National Football League is loaded with former Pac-10 players,
particularly at the skilled positions. The Pac-10 had nine players
make Street &AMP; Smith's preseason All-America first and second teams.
Only the Big 12, with 12, had more.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 25 years, eight Pac-10 players have been selected
with the first pick in the NFL draft, more than any other
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the mentality seems to be that being good in football is
preferable to being great.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State coach Bruce Snyder grumbled that being good in
Olympic sports seemed more important than being good in football
and basketball to the Pac-10 powers that be.
</P>
<P>
   But it's more than that. There is a perception that Pac-10
football is softer than other conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty-boy football with a lot of passing and catching but not
much hitting,'' said Houdini Jackson, a sophomore linebacker for
the Huskies who grew up in Houston, joined the Navy, and played at
the University of Hawaii before transferring here last year.
``That's what I thought when I was in Texas. But I think this place
may be different.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   The results of last season's nonconference games don't help. The
Pac-10 was only 20-18 against nonconference competition. Its teams
were only 1-4 against opponents from the generally lightly regarded
Mountain West Conference.
</P>
<P>
   And some of the nonconference losses were so overwhelming that
no amount of spin control could help.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Arizona's 41-7 loss to Penn State in the opening game
of last season. Or Stanford, which went on to win the conference
crown, losing to Texas, 69-17; or Nebraska beating Cal, 45-0; or
Ohio State pounding UCLA, 42-20; or Arizona State losing to New
Mexico State; or Washington State losing to Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? No one is sure. Neuheisel thinks it might have
been the lack of experienced starting quarterbacks in the Pac-10
last season. Only four starters returned last season. Eight will
return this year.
</P>
<P>
   But it's more than that. It's the parity, which seems to have
engulfed the league. No one is too good or too bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We proved last year that we prognosticators don't know what
we're talking about,'' said Snyder, whose Sun Devils were picked to
win the Pac-10 two years ago and went belly-up from the start,
finishing 5-6.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the last four preseason picks as conference champion
have not even finished above .500, which is not good news for
Washington, this year's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Say this for Pac-10 teams, they don't duck many people in
nonconference scheduling. This year, UCLA will meet Alabama and
Michigan; Southern Cal will play Penn State and Notre Dame;
Washington will take on Miami and Colorado; Arizona will oppose
Ohio State; Oregon will face Big Ten champion Wisconsin; and
Stanford will play Texas and Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd all rather play someone good and beat them than someone
not so good and beat them,'' said UCLA coach Bob Toledo. ``It does
something for your program. When we beat Texas, 66-3 (in 1997), it
jump-started our program.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona coach Dick Tomey is still feeling the pain of last
year's pounding by Penn State on national television, a beating
that Pac-10 commissioner Tom Hansen correctly predicted the
conference would not recover from during that season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have a terrible feeling about a year ago,'' said Tomey.
``We contributed greatly to the image of our conference by the way
we played at Penn State.''
</P>
<P>
   The coaches hope it's cyclical.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Pac-10 was 25-12 in nonconference games. It
was an impressive 28-8 in 1997. Arizona State in 1996 and UCLA in
1998 had unbeaten seasons within their grasp, which surely would
have meant consideration for at least a share of a national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   And if you really want to break down the numbers, the Big Ten,
with only a share of a national championship since 1968, does even
worse in the debate over which is the best football conference. But
no one ever has characterized the Big Ten as ``pretty-boy
football.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington may be the Pac-10's best hope. The Huskies seem
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't seem to find the same intensity at other places (in
the conference),'' said Neuhesiel, who already has drawn the slings
and arrows of criticism from his coaching brethren. ``We have
62,000 season tickets sold here, which is twice as many as any
other school in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   In college football, battles are fought on the recruiting front
before they reach the field. It is an area Neuheisel knows well and
enjoys. But he also knows to win the ``arms race,'' as he calls it,
facilities have to be upgraded.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is in the middle of a $95 million expansion of its
athletic complex that will make it the equal of any team in the
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel said he is disturbed by what he feels is an attitude
where conference teams snipe at each other constantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can't we strive to all being good?'' he said. ``Some of
the stuff I see happening reminds me of what happened in the
Southwest Conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel's point is well taken. The Southwest self-destructed
for a variety of reasons, but a primary cause was teams turning on
each other and turning each other in in a frenzy that brought the
death penalty to one school _ Southern Methodist _ and probation to
several others.
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10 is more diligent when it comes to playing by the
rules, but the attitude seems to be one of watching what other
people are doing as much as concentrating on what you are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can all flourish,'' said Neuheisel. ``But we've got
to do it carefully. We can't take any shortcuts without some
whistles going off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
