<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2004 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-BOSCOLL-BOS &LR;      08-25 1947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSCOLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON COLLEGE'S SURPRISING 1999 RAISES EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ This is how close Boston College's football team came
last year to playing for the Big East title: Oh so very close.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. Had it not been for a pair of second-half
disappearances (a 24-24 loss to Temple Oct. 8, when the Owls scored
17 unanswered points to overcome a 14-7 halftime deficit; and a
heartbreaking 31-28 setback against Miami Oct. 23, when BC allowed
the Hurricanes to rally for 31 points in the final 17:11), BC coach
Tom O'Brien would have taken his undefeated Eagles to Blacksburg,
Va., for a huge Big East summit against undefeated and
second-ranked Virginia Tech in the regular-season finale.
</P>
<P>
   At stake: the conference title and a berth in the Bowl
Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one way of looking at it,'' said BC athletic director
Gene DeFilippo. ``But it's kind of like my golf game: I only think
of the putts I missed, but I never think about the 20-footers I did
make that I probably shouldn't have made.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Eagles left a few gimme putts on the lip, they
certainly canned their fair share of double-breaking, 20-foot
birdies from the fringe on the 18th, as Bob May did versus Tiger
Woods in the PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   There was the 20-16 triumph over Pittsburgh Oct. 16 in which BC
quarterback Tim Hasselbeck, wounded wing and all, came off the
bench when backup Brian St. Pierre got his bell rung and connected
with Dedrick Dewalt on a pair of touchdown passes, including a
winning 36-yard score with 1:48 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the Oct. 30 cliffhanger at Syracuse, where senior
linebacker Frank Chamberlin provided the gripping finish to a 24-23
victory when he stopped quarterback Madei Williams 1 yard short of
converting a critical fourth-and-13 scramble.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, there was the rousing 31-29 victory at Notre Dame
Nov. 20. After spotting the Irish a 14-0 lead in the first quarter,
the Eagles rallied behind a stellar performance by Hasselbeck to
record their eighth victory of the season and third in the their
seven meetings against Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wonderful year and Tom and his staff has done an
outstanding job with this football program,'' said DeFilippo, who
awarded O'Brien with a one-year contract extension that will take
him through the 2005 season. ``The thing that you look for, as an
athletic director, it's not always the wins and losses, but you
look at the direction of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``And by direction, I mean, how's the recruiting? Well, our
recruiting has been very, very good the last two or three years.
You look at discipline on the team and we've had very, very few
players in trouble. You look at academics, and we've had very, very
few people who've even had to use summer school to get eligible.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, you look at, does this team play hard and do they do what
they're asked to do? The answer to both those things is `Yes.' All
those ingredients, to me, make up the direction of the program and
the direction of the program is headed due north.''
</P>
<P>
   But, because of those aforementioned lapses, the Eagles instead
went to Virginia Tech for a shot at a bid to either the Gator or
Insight.com Bowl. A 38-14 loss to the Hokies sent the Eagles to
Tucson, where BC's incredible 8-3 season and first bowl appearance
in five years ended with an unsightly 62-28 loss against Colorado
in the Insight.com Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   It left many to wonder.
</P>
<P>
   What if the Eagles had showed up for the second half against
Temple? What if BC hadn't blown a 28-0 halftime lead against Miami?
What then?
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows?'' O'Brien said with a shrug. ``If you beat them,
then maybe you lose to Pittsburgh or to Syracuse. You never know.
You're going to play close games, but our previous two years here
we didn't win the close games. Last year we did. We won more than
we lost when it came down to the end of a football game, and that's
a positive and that's something we can build on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blemishes notwithstanding, last season's campaign proved to be a
breakthrough on many levels for O'Brien and his team. The Eagles
overachieved and surpassed all expectations by winning eight games,
recording a winning (4-3) conference record for the first time
under O'Brien, and finishing third in the league to earn their
first postseason berth since the 1994 Aloha Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think subsequent years will tell the tale of last year, but
I think it was important that, somewhere along the line, we had a
winning season,'' said O'Brien, who improved his BC record to 16-18
after going 4-7 in each of his first two seasons. ``I felt we were
capable of winning last year, but I never conceived that we could
win eight games, but a lot of times the kids have higher
aspirations. We stayed healthy, we caught a few breaks and we made
a few breaks of our own, and that led to a winning season. It was
very positive for the program and we have to keep it going this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Eagles will face some challenges in duplicating last
year's win total.
</P>
<P>
   While BC's strengths rest with an offense led by Hasselbeck, who
will be back at the helm as a fifth-year senior, the most glaring
deficiencies are on defense, where O'Brien must replace four
starters from last year's front seven, including Chamberlin and
All-America defensive tackle Chris Hovan, a first-round draft pick
of the Minnesota Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Hasselbeck will be surrounded by a talented backfield led by
senior running back Cedric Washington, who rushed for 1,122 yards
last year, and sophomore William Green; a veteran group of
receivers that includes Dewalt, Jamal Burke and DuJuan Daniels; and
a solid offensive line, led by senior guards Paul Zukauskas and
Paul LaQuerre. O'Brien is so impressed by his line he was prompted
to say during BC's Media Day: ``From tackle to tackle, they could
be the best we've ever had here.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Eagles will not be as experienced or as deep,
especially up front where junior tackle Antonio Garay and junior
defensive end Sean Guthrie will be expected to help plug gaping
holes left by the departure of Hovan, Adam Newman, and Mike
Willetts. Senior Ryan Burch, who was converted from fullback to
middle linebacker, will join junior Scott Bradley, who was hailed
by O'Brien as having had a strong spring, and either sophomore
Marco Williams or redshirt freshman Josh Ott to help shore up the
linebacker position.
</P>
<P>
   Senior free safety RaMon Johnson, who started at corner last
year opposite talented junior Jonathan Ordway, will be the leader
of BC's secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still not a dominant football team and have dominant
football players,'' O'Brien said. ``There's too many losses on
defense to graduation right now to project that we could win eight
or nine games again and be at that level. Who knows? I think we can
progress and get better as the year goes on, but all our experience
is on the offensive side of the football, so it's just the exact
opposite of where we were a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, with that said, I still think we can have a winning
season, and if we do that, go to a bowl game. And if we did that
I'd still think it would be a great accomplishment four years
removed from where we started.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, that's what made last year all the more amazing.
It came only three short years after O'Brien inherited from Dan
Henning a program torn asunder by a fractious gambling scandal. Who
knew it would take O'Brien just three years to clean up the mess,
restore discipline and integrity to the program, and field a team
capable of winning eight games and going to a bowl?
</P>
<P>
   But, after helping George Welsh build programs at Navy and
Virginia, O'Brien had a good handle on the situation. He knew that
the third year would be pivotal. ``When I was at Navy and when I
was at Virginia, we won the third year,'' he said. ``So I kind of
expected it, following the same kind of logic and the same kind of
path.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't quite as hard as Virginia, because we inherited some
athletes. We inherited some athletes here at BC, but there were so
many losses because of expulsions and kids out of the program
(following the gambling scandal). At Navy, we had the problem of
coming off the Vietnam War, so I mean it was still a little tough
recruiting there, as it was here.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we were still able to win seven games with Coach Welsh in
his third year there (at Navy and Virginia) and we were still able
to win here. But as I said, you want to be in a program where
freshmen play because they're good. You don't want to be forced to
play them because you have depth problems and not enough
scholarship kids or people at that position. In the next year or
two, we'll be at that level.''
</P>
<P>
   By his count, O'Brien said BC has 83 scholarship players. It is
a vast improvement from his first year when he relied on walk-ons
not only to fill out the depth chart, but in some instances, to
start games at key positions. ``We're still not at full force, but
we're much deeper than we've ever been,'' O'Brien said. ``The other
thing that is starting to manifest itself, it seems like, is the
continuity.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been some staff changes. Bill McGovern, a former
assistant at BC under Henning and most recently at Pittsburgh, was
brought back to The Heights to replace Al Golden as linebackers
coach. Former Northeastern head coach Barry Gallup is the new
director of football operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we still have had a core of four or five coaches
(including defensive coordinator Frank Spaziani, defensive line
coach Mike London, tight ends coach Don Horton, and assistant head
coach/recruiting coordinator Jerry Petercuskie) who have stayed
here along with the head coach.
</P>
<P>
   `At practices, kids understand what they're doing and where
they're going and from that standpoint we're more efficient in
practice and in everything we're doing in the program and I think
those things help to build a solid foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   BC's athletic administration has taken steps to upgrade the
football facilities, undertaking an aggressive advertising campaign
to bolster season-ticket sales by extolling ``The Speed, The Power,
The Passion'' as virtues of BC football, locking in TV appearances
for all 11 games this season, and solidifying future home dates
against marquee nonconference opponents such as Notre Dame (2001
and 2003), Stanford (2002), and Penn State (2004).
</P>
<P>
   It is all part of the grand plan to make BC's football program a
threat for the Big East title and a bowl berth on a yearly basis.
But can it really happen?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' O'Brien said. ``We can attain a conference
championship. This is not the ACC where it's Florida State and the
rest of the world. You go to the Big Ten and you could name all
four schools who have a chance to win it and everbody else is
fighting below. This conference has been won by Syracuse, it's been
won by Virginia Tech, it's been won by Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention West Virginia, whom BC will face in its opener in
Morgantown, W. Va., Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has taken a stranglehold on this thing,'' O'Brien said.
``So, if we can continue to build and to play, then we'll have as
much a chance as anybody to get to that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Just look at how close _ how very close _ the Eagles came to
doing just that a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Said DeFilippo: ``What I've done with last season is to say,
`Yeah, we may have missed some easy putts, but we sure did make a
lot of long ones, too.' So that's how I kind of look at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we were right there and that's what's exciting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
