<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-CATNAPS (Undated) _ Wake up and smell the coffee. A
Harvard School of Public Health study says nodding off for 20 to 30
minutes during the day could be bad for your health. Researchers
found that those who napped every afternoon had a
higher-than-average risk of suffering a heart attack. By RICHARD A.
MARINI.
</P>
<P>
   BIGKISS (Undated) _ If Al Gore is elected president, pundits may
be able to trace where his fortunes first turned. It started with a
kiss. On center stage at the Democratic National Convention, before
the most important speech in his political career, Gore laid a big
one on his startled wife, Tipper. In that one instant, he surprised
a nation. Political pundits, etiquette experts and regular people
have been buzzing about it ever since. By CLIFFORD PUGH.
</P>
<P>
   With: BIGKISS-FIVE and BIGKISS-FAMOUS
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-RIGHT-FIT (Undated) _ A perfect 10 might be able to get
by with a few fashion mistakes, but for a size 20, it's a different
story. Big women need to pay special attention to fit and style to
focus attention on positive features, hide trouble spots and look
their best. By ROSE MARY BUDGE.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AIR-FORCE-RECRUITING(San Antonio) _ The Air Force has gone
Hollywood in a bid to win the hearts and minds of America's young
people. Starting Friday, moviegoers will see the first Air Force
ads directed by Academy Award-winner Bob Richardson, the
photography chief of ``JFK'' and ``Wag the Dog.'' They'll also make
Air Force history by being the first to witness the debut of the
armed service's first logo, a device featuring stark diagonal bands
resembling folded wings lifted behind a star with the message, ``No
one comes close.'' By SIG CHRISTENSON.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-ASYLUM (San Francisco) _ A man who as a 14-year-old was
harassed and raped by police in Mexico because he looked and
dressed like a woman has been ruled eligible for asylum in the
United States by a federal appeals court. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-GODSARMY-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``God's Army'' is a low-cost,
appealing independent production that unapologetically targets the
nearly 5 million American members of the Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-day Saints, otherwise known as Mormons. It's also an example
of how a little creativity and sensitive writing can make a niche
movie attractive to those beyond its target audience. by RICHARD
VARA.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-BUTTERFLY (Undated) _ Such a sweet, mall film is
``Butterfly,'' such a touchingly understated portrait of a Spanish
boy's friendship with a kind old teacher, that you might not notice
the lack of an original plot. Or maybe you will notice, but you
won't care. This film captures the innocence of childhood and the
sudden betrayals that shatter it. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-CREW (Undated) _ First there was ``Space Cowboys,''
an action movie about aging astronauts returning to the final
frontier. Now comes ``The Crew,'' a winning comedy about four old
wiseguys who step out of retirement to pull one more scheme. After
endless juvenile drivel about hormones and horror and fruit pies,
perhaps Hollywood has finally noticed that a large percentage of
the population is over the age of 23. By KRIS WORRELL.
</P>
<P>
   TV-MICHAEL-RICHARDS(Undated) _ So an NBC executive type was at a
party last month in Universal City, trying to tell a critic that
the first pilot for ``The Michael Richards Show''_ the one they
didn't let us see _ wasn't all that bad, or at least as bad as we'd
all heard. William Devane just pursed his lips. ``C'mon,''said the
new cast member. ``It (stunk).'' By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RAC-TRAVERS (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ Dick Mandella has been a
thoroughbred horse trainer since 1974. In all those years he had
never entered a horse to run in the prestigious and
tradition-soaked Travers Stakes. Until Saturday when Mandella makes
his maiden Travers voyage. He won't have just any horse. He will
have the horse many think will win the 131st running of the
Midsummer Derby. By TIM WILKIN.
</P>
