<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-RIGHT-FIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MAKING FASHION FIT FOR LARGER WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROSE MARY BUDGE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A perfect 10 might be able to get by with a few fashion
mistakes, but for a size 20, it's a different story. Big women need
to pay special attention to fit and style to focus attention on
positive features, hide trouble spots and look their best.
</P>
<P>
   Her are some fashion tips for the plus-size woman:
</P>
<P>
   _ If clothes push and squeeze, don't buy them. Tight clothes
won't make you more slender _ they'll accentuate the negative.
Garments that gently caress the body rather than giving it a bear
hug are the best choice.
</P>
<P>
   While tight clothes are bad, drooping silhouettes and styles
that are obviously too large are worse. They don't mask the pounds,
they add them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Everyone knows that the black dress is a staple. But, if
you're big, don't get caught in an all-black rut thinking darker
colors will be more slenderizing.
</P>
<P>
   A bright print or a complexion-flattering pastel will add
pizzazz, not girth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big florals and animal prints look better on larger women,''
said Genie Alexander, manager of Avenue, a San Antonio plus-size
store. ``Bold prints can overwhelm someone small.''
</P>
<P>
   _ If you want to look more svelte, get rid of the dumpy flats. A
medium to high heel will look more graceful, emphasize nice legs
and instantly give a sexier look.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stretch materials will smooth out lumps and bumps and give a
smoother appearance. Because stretch materials move with the body,
they're more comfortable, too.
</P>
<P>
   _ Obvious panty lines can ruin the best-looking slacks, but
pantyhose often can solve the problem. Another hint: When selecting
undies, always go with a full-cut brief, not a bikini. Briefs with
elastic waists cover tummy bulges, while bikinis emphasize them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Push-up or underwire bras that offer firm support can
instantly improve a larger figure. A bra-fit specialist can help
you find the right size.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pantyhose with a control top can provide a firm foundation for
almost any type of apparel and are preferable to girdles and heavy
Lycra undergarments that can push flab up and out around the
midriff or under the arms.
</P>
<P>
   _ Focus attention on your face by putting a bright scarf at your
neckline or a dramatic pin on your lapel.
</P>
<P>
   _ Designers are accentuating shoulders again, and shoulder pads
can help the woman with a thick lower half to focus attention
upward, creating the illusion of smaller hips and a narrower waist.
But shoulder pads aren't for the woman with a hefty upper body.
</P>
<P>
   A longer jacket that covers the derriere is generally more
flattering to plus sizes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Small jewelry will look out of proportion on a big woman.
Large-scale pieces are best _ and don't wear too many at the same
time. Establish a focal point.
</P>
<P>
   _ Not every big woman is created equal. Study your shape and
determine if it's a triangle (narrow shoulders, wider hips), an
inverted triangle (wider shoulders, narrow hips), an oval (fuller
bustline and less-defined waist), hourglass (balanced shoulders and
hips with a well-defined waist) or a rectangle (roughly the same
width at the shoulders, waist and hips). Triangles should avoid
jackets and sweaters that stop at the largest part of the hips.
Inverted triangles should wear fuller bottoms in prints and bright
colors. Ovals should redirect the eye to the face or legs. The
hourglass figure needs to avoid tent dresses and styles without
shape. The rectangle should wear clothes that suggest a waistline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
