<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S BOOST FROM RENO IS ACTUALLY WELCOME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BILL THOMPSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore is on a roll, still bouncing from his successful
convention and still basking in the afterglow of The Kiss. The
once-boring vice president suddenly seems to be everybody's idea of
a great leader.
</P>
<P>
   Was it the scintillating speech that seemed to promise a
solution for every problem known to humankind? Or was it the
humanizing show of affection toward Mrs. Gore _ The Kiss _ that
stoked Gore's engine and revved up his sputtering campaign?
</P>
<P>
   Darned if I know.
</P>
<P>
   But I know this: Gore racked up another godsend the other day
when Attorney General Janet Reno refused to appoint a special
counsel to investigate allegations that he lied to investigators
about his 1996 fund-raising activities.
</P>
<P>
   At the risk of stating the obvious, it must be noted that an
all-out federal investigation focusing on the possibility of vice
presidential perjury might have been detrimental to Gore's crusade
to succeed Bill Clinton as president.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it's entirely possible that an investigation
wouldn't have affected him in the least. In fact, the American
people just might be so fed up with the recent trend of politics by
investigation that they'd have consoled Gore by giving him another
big jump in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   If memory serves, Clinton's job approval rating went up 10
points or so every time the special counsel's office leaked an
incriminating factoid during the Bill and Monica scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who had hoped that Gore would have to fend off a
scandal of his own from now until Election Day can salve their
disappointment by pondering the potentially disastrous effect _ for
the GOP _ of an anti-investigation backlash.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-impeachment backlash, don't forget, darn near cost
congressional Republicans their House majority two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Backlash or no backlash, I must say that I'm glad Reno decided
to let Gore off the hook. It's not necessarily that I'm 100 percent
certain that he deserves to be off the hook; it's just that I am
100 percent certain that Reno was right when she concluded that
``there is no reasonable possibility that further investigation
would produce evidence to warrant charges.''
</P>
<P>
   If Gore lied about his involvement in questionable fund raising,
rest assured that he lied in a way that would never meet the legal
test for perjury. Politicians, sad to say, are professional
prevaricators. They weigh their words carefully.
</P>
<P>
   You know how it works. It depends on what the meaning of ``is''
is.
</P>
<P>
   But never mind all that. The Clinton-Gore campaign's
fund-raising tactics have been investigated up one side and down
the other. Congressional committees, federal agents, investigative
reporters ...
</P>
<P>
   The White House coffees and telephone solicitations, the Lincoln
Bedroom sleepovers, the Buddhist temple check-passing _ it's all
been pursued, probed, plumbed and pummeled. Some of the most
ferocious Clinton-haters on the planet have tried to unearth
criminal wrongdoing by the president and/or his veep _ and all have
failed.
</P>
<P>
   So the last thing we need is another expensive, time-consuming,
populace-dividing investigation that leads to absolutely nothing
except more strife, more bitterness, more public disillusionment
with a political system that has already disillusioned far too
many.
</P>
<P>
   Reno is perhaps the most controversial, criticized and just
plain detested Clinton administration official this side of Clinton
himself, and her detractors greeted her no-special-counsel decision
with predictable scorn.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania accused Reno of
protecting Gore, saying that her refusal to authorize an
independent investigation on three different occasions was
``particularly troublesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But I'm an unabashed supporter of Gore's opponent, George
W. Bush, and I'm willing to give Reno the benefit of the doubt. I
say Reno simply did what she thought was right.
</P>
<P>
   Specter, by the way, also said that it's up to voters to make a
judgment about Gore's conduct. I will second that.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
