A2018 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-BUTTERFLY     08-25 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-BUTTERFLY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HESITANT WINGS OF A BOY ENDURE IN `BUTTERFLY' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Such a sweet, small film is ``Butterfly,'' such a touchingly
understated portrait of a Spanish boy's friendship with a kind old
teacher, that you might not notice the lack of an original plot.
</P>
<P>
   You might not notice the dog-eared edges to the tale, or the
fact that the boy-and-his-mentor motif has already been done to
death on the art-house circuit. Or maybe you will notice, but guess
what _ you won't care. Because ``Butterfly,'' for all its
derivative elements, is a film composed from perfect, tender
details, vivid snapshots that capture the innocence of childhood
and the sudden betrayals that shatter it.
</P>
<P>
   Directed and co-written by Jose Luis Cuerda, ``Butterfly'' turns
its soft focus on the boyhood travails of Moncho (Manual Lozano), a
small, quiveringly shy urchin entering his first year of school in
Republican Spain, 1931. So terrified is Moncho of his new teacher _
he's convinced the old man's a child-beater _ that he pees at the
head of class. His fears prove unfounded, however, as the gentle
Don Gregorio (Fernando Fernan Gomez) leads his charges with a light
touch and a near-holy reverence for nature. He tells them of
beetles and birds and butterflies' tongues and takes them on jaunts
through the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Into this sylvan paradise enters a few harsh political
realities, notably the tension between Republican activists who
helped depose the Spanish monarchy and disgruntled fascists loyal
to the military. Don Gregorio, an atheist with a poet's heart, is a
Republican; Moncho's father (Gonzalo M. Uriarte) is a Republican;
the wealthy businessman who tries to bribe Don Gregorio with a
couple of juicy capons is a fascist.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the political machinations are a nudge ham-handed,
the film never errs when it focuses on Moncho and the fickle shifts
of childhood. Lozano is wholly unaffected as the nervous
``sparrow,'' delivering a performance _ hardly the word _ of such
natural, pool-eyed boyness that his friendship with Gomez never
feels forced. It lacks the labored cutesiness of American buddy
flicks; the teacher never imparts his wisdom with any
condescension, and the boy, never bratty, fails to respond with
grudging admiration. He's simply a pupil with a mentor he adores
but takes for granted.
</P>
<P>
   The reflective power of ``Butterfly' (and the heartbreak of its
ending) lies in its most tranquil metaphor, that of the
spring-tongued butterfly that Don Gregorio handles so delicately in
his net. For Gregorio, who shelves anarchist-communist tracts
alongside ``Treasure Island,'' there's no difference between the
fragile liberty of life in a new republic and the translucent
beauty of an insect caught and loosed. ``Fly free,'' he says before
a crowded classroom on the day of his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez makes a wonderfully placid radical: He doesn't need to act
the firebrand, because his eyes speak volumes of suffering. As he
tells Moncho, ``an otherworldly hell doesn't exist''; the true
inferno roars around him, in the darting licks of human cruelty.
Cruelty has its day in ``Butterfly,'' but it's the hushed
resignation of Don Gregorio _ and the hesitant wings of a small boy
_ that endure.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
