<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2026 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-MICHAEL-RICHARDS-H     08-25 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MICHAEL-RICHARDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HERE'S HOPING `MICHAEL RICHARDS' GETS BETTER WITH AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An NBC executive type was at a party last month in Universal
City, trying to tell a critic that the first pilot for ``The
Michael Richards Show'' _ the one they didn't let us see _ wasn't
all that bad, or at least as bad as we'd all heard.
</P>
<P>
   William Devane just pursed his lips. ``C'mon,'' said the new
cast member. ``It (stunk).''
</P>
<P>
   You have to love this guy _ the man known to millions of
``Seinfeld'' fans simply as Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the new NBC sitcom (8 p.m. Tuesdays) is now
being billed as an ensemble show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still up for an ensemble, understanding the strengths of a
good, character-driven ensemble show,'' Richards told television
critics last month. ``I don't feel like all the pressure is on me
to drive it along.''
</P>
<P>
   He should. It's not ``The William Devane Show'' or ``Tim Meadows
Show'' or ``Vic Nardozza,'' the name of the character Richards
plays. Your name is on it, Mike.
</P>
<P>
   (A side note to Richards: Drop the artiste persona. At best, you
come off as a ponderous airhead; at worst, you seem like a guy with
funny facial ticks and an incredibly inflated sense of your
talent.)
</P>
<P>
   Nardozza is a bumbling yet effective private detective in the
tradition of Columbo and Inspector Clouseau. That has been the plan
from the start.
</P>
<P>
   How good is the new sitcom? Who knows? Devane is optimistic that
the final product will be a lot better than the first tape slapped
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were right when they said the original script stunk,
because it did stink,'' Devane said. ``It didn't work. I got four
versions of this new script _ and it's very good. I'm very happy to
be involved with these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   This year not one but four big-name stars _ Richards, Bette
Midler (``Bette,'' CBS), John Goodman (``Normal, Ohio,'' Fox) and
Geena Davis (``The Geena Davis Show,'' ABC) _ have been given their
own sitcom. Richards and Goodman are retooling their pilots; Davis'
was extremely weak at best; only Midler's is passable.
</P>
<P>
   Given the recent history of ill-defined comedic star vehicles
gone bad (the syndrome even has a name: ``Encore! Encore!'', after
Nathan Lane's 1998 disaster), Richards knows there are jaundiced
eyes looking at his project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what this show is,'' Richards said. ``There's no
trouble here. I mean, I know it seems that way because you haven't
seen a pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yeah Michael: That's the problem.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
