<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2037 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-CREW-HNS &LR;      08-25 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-CREW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     OLD MOBSTERS SCORE A HIT IN `THE CREW' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KRIS WORRELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   First there was ``Space Cowboys,'' an action movie about aging
astronauts returning to the final frontier. Now comes ``The Crew,''
a winning comedy about four old wiseguys who step out of retirement
to pull one more scheme.
</P>
<P>
   After endless juvenile drivel about hormones and horror and
fruit pies, perhaps Hollywood has finally noticed that a large
percentage of the population is over the age of 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Crew'' is an irresistible hoot of a film about four
lifelong friends who have retired from the New Jersey mob and now
live together in the Raj Mahal, a rundown retirement hotel in
Miami's South Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Once high rollers dressed in slick suits who had gobs of money
and women, they now spend their days sitting on the porch watching
the parade of bikinis go by and defending their now prime real
estate from yuppies looking for an ocean view.
</P>
<P>
   ``You said the good times were gonna last forever,'' growls Joey
``Bats'' Pistella (played to perfection by Burt Reynolds).
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we'd be dead by now,'' says Bobby Bartellemeo
(Richard Dreyfuss).
</P>
<P>
   The film's greatest strength comes from the four main
characters, and like some geriatric boy band, everybody has a role
to play.
</P>
<P>
   There's Bats, who got his nickname from his choice of weapon as
well as his crazy temper; Mike ``The Brick'' Donatelli, a sweet and
dim guy played by Dan Hedaya, who so hilariously portrayed
President Nixon in ``Dick''; Tony ``Mouth'' Donato, a quiet type
who has a way with the ladies, played by Seymour Cassel, who
co-starred with Dreyfuss in ``Tin Men''; and Dreyfuss, who plays
the sensible one.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds shines as the hot-headed Bats, a man so angry at losing
his big-shot status that he cannot maintain a job at numerous
Burger Kings because he keeps harassing the customers. (``I know
what the commercial says, lady,'' he hisses at one woman. ``But
special orders do upset us.'') Confrontational and outraged, Bats
does some of his best thinking while unconscious, a state he finds
himself in frequently.
</P>
<P>
   It's after just such a ``senior moment'' that Bats gets an idea
about how to keep management at the Raj Mahal from raising the
rents and squeezing the geezers out. It is a simple and suitably
nutty plan, and it works like a charm. The guys are renewed and
celebrate like it was old times: a new car, fancy jewelry, a
friendly hooker named Ferris (played with ample bada-bing by
Jennifer Tilly).
</P>
<P>
   All except Bobby, who knows that wiseguys always mess things up.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, life gets considerably more complicated when Mouth
suddenly becomes quite talkative with Ferris, telling her all about
their scheme. Ferris makes the geezers an offer they can't refuse:
They must whack her stepmother in exchange for her silence.
</P>
<P>
   Their hapless plan sets off a series of shenanigans that involve
a reigning drug lord, the rich widow of a deli owner and a
pyromaniacal rodent.
</P>
<P>
   Of less interest are two secondary story lines, one involving
the dysfunctional love life of detectives and ex-lovers Olivia Neal
(Carrie-Anne Moss, who starred opposite Keanu Reeves in ``The
Matrix'') and Steve Menteer (Jeremy Piven), who have been assigned
to investigate the doings at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Another unnecessary plot involves Bobby's search for his
daughter, whom he hasn't seen since she was a child. It is meant to
lend the story some moral significance but ends up just weighing
down a film that is best when taken lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Director Michael Dinner, whose film credits up until this point
include an annoyingly unfunny flick about a talking horse called
``Hot to Trot,'' does an admirable job of capturing the spirit and
speed of Miami with interesting editing (a corpse-filled drawer
closes, a file cabinet opens) and the rich golds and blues of the
beach town.
</P>
<P>
   He also gets some fine comic performances out of these veteran
actors. Dreyfuss is a steady straight man, and Hedaya is delightful
as Brick, a soft-hearted ex-mobster who still exchanges Christmas
cards with fellas from the old gang.
</P>
<P>
   While sitting in the car before one of their capers, Brick
announces, ``I gotta pee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just hold it,'' snaps Reynolds. Then, a beat later, ``Not with
your hands, you mook.''
</P>
<P>
   The script, by Barry Fanaro, who also wrote the screenplay for
the comedy ``Kingpin'' and numerous episodes of the television
series ``Golden Girls,'' is filled with such quick and comic
exchanges. And producer Barry Sonnenfeld has struck a similar tone
here as he did with the smartly funny ``Men in Black'' and ``Get
Shorty.''
</P>
<P>
   So what if there are a few too many fuhgedaboutits and other
mobster cliches? There are still so many refreshing tricks in this
old dog that it doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Kris Worrell writes for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box 15000,
Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
