<HEADER>
A2045 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     08-25 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WISDOM OF SOLOMON EXTENDS TO SEX AND MARRIAGE, TOO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JIM JONES 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sex is one of those subjects not often discussed in church. But
a Texas pastor, the Rev. Tommy Nelson, thinks that should change.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson has been talking about how to handle sex and its joys and
problems with his congregation in Denton for years. He's not
surprised by the popularity of his seminars on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an area our society is lost in space with,'' Nelson
says. ``We're not sure what marriage is or what sexuality is. Is it
something glorious or just a biological act?''
</P>
<P>
   He bases his teachings on the Song of Solomon or the Song of
Songs, one of those books of the Bible some rabbis and ministers
leave out of their sermons because of its provocative language.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with the passionate words of the bride:
</P>
<P>
   ``Let him kiss me with kisses of the mouth _ for your love is
more delightful than wine. ... Take me away with you _ let us
hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   The blushingly frank language continues with the man's
description of his alluring lover:
</P>
<P>
   ``How beautiful you are, my darling! Oh, how beautiful. Your
eyes behind your veil are doves. ... Your two breasts are like two
fawns, like twin fawns of a gazelle that browse among the lilies.
... Your lips drop sweetness as a honeycomb, my bride, milk and
honey are under your tongue.''
</P>
<P>
   The symbolic language becomes even more erotic later.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson doesn't back off from any of the passages in his treatise
on the Song of Solomon, ``The Book of Romance: What Solomon Says
About Love, Sex and Intimacy'' (Thomas Nelson, $14.99).
</P>
<P>
   It's a mystery book to many, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has the distinction of being the only book of the Bible
that seems to have been edited and censured by the church,'' he
says. ``Most people don't read it, don't understand it, and have
never heard a sermon about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, senior pastor of the 3,000-member Denton Bible Church,
says the Song of Solomon is God's guide on how to fan the fires of
sexual intimacy, resolve conflicts and fall deeper in love as the
years go by.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think God would give us dating, sex and marriage
without any guidelines?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, a former quarterback for the University of North Texas
and a graduate of Dallas Theological Seminary, says his seminars
grew out of a Bible study he taught at Prestonwood Baptist Church
in suburban Dallas. Information on his book and seminars can be
obtained by calling (877) 456-SONG or calling up his Web site,
www.thesongofsolomon.com.
</P>
<P>
   A Sept. 23 seminar at the First Baptist Church of Dallas is
touted in a news release with the heading: Pastor Tommy Nelson
Teaches Dallas Residents How to Have Great Sex.
</P>
<P>
   But his seminars are not just about the joys of sex. He has
practical tips on dating, courtship and marriage, using humor along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``So often today, girls will say about a guy, `He's a real
hunk.' The question begs to be asked, `A hunk of what?''' he
writes.
</P>
<P>
   He urges men and women to choose a partner based on character,
godliness, unselfishness, reputation and the reaction to pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Nelson conducts untraditional seminars, he is a
traditionalist on the Bible. Sex should be within the confines of
marriage, he says, and wives should submit to the decision-making
authority of their husbands. He adds, however, that husbands should
cherish and protect their wives.
</P>
<P>
   Although some people interpret the Song of Solomon as an
allegory of God's love for true believers, the most common
interpretation is that it is a collection of lyrics celebrating
human love, says the ``Oxford Commentary on the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   Did Solomon actually write those spicy love lyrics?
</P>
<P>
   Some scholars believe the verses were only attributed to Solomon
because of his reputation for wisdom. But Nelson believes Solomon
wrote the love poetry in his younger days, then wrote Proverbs and
Ecclesiastes in later years.
</P>
<P>
   How could King Solomon, who had hundreds of wives, be an
authority on sexuality and marriage?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, who should know better?'' Nelson answers. Solomon learned
about true love through experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The song that he gave us is about a holy love,'' Nelson says,
``one that is distinct and exclusive from all others.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
