<HEADER>
A2055 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-GAY-ASYLUM-HNS &LR;      08-25 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-ASYLUM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT UPHOLDS ASYLUM FOR HOMOSEXUAL TEEN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A man who as a 14-year-old was harassed and
raped by police officers in Mexico because he looked and dressed
like a woman has been ruled eligible for asylum in the United
States by a federal appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   Gay rights lawyers said Thursday's 3-0 ruling by the 9th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco was the first by any
court to recognize persecution based on sexual identity as grounds
for asylum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexual orientation and sexual identity are immutable; they are
so fundamental to one's identity that a person should not be
required to abandon them,'' Judge A. Wallace Tashima said in the
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a groundbreaking decision,'' said Shannon Minter, a
lawyer for the National Center for Lesbian Rights in San Francisco.
``It's the first time the courts have held that sexual orientation
is an immutable characteristic, and the first time they've
recognized that some gay men have innately feminine characteristics
that make them vulnerable to persecution.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Davidson, a lawyer for the Lambda Legal Defense and
Education Fund, said the case was significant for homosexuals from
other Latin American countries where, as in Mexico, gay men who
look effeminate are singled out for abuse.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, immigration judges already grant asylum
regularly to effeminate gay men from Latin America, said attorney
Sharon Dulberg, who has handled a number of such cases from Mexico,
Brazil and Venezuela. ``It's so clear that they'll be persecuted if
they return,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal immigration authorities did not dispute the idea that
homosexuals and lesbians who were persecuted in their homeland
could apply for asylum, a position accepted by the Board of
Immigration Appeals in 1990 and adopted as a binding precedent for
all immigration judges by Attorney General Janet Reno in 1994. But
in seeking to deport Geovanni Hernandez-Montiel to Mexico, the
Immigration and Naturalization Service said he was mistreated
because of the way he chose to dress and act, not because of his
sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez-Montiel, described by his lawyer as a transsexual,
said he had started dressing and acting like a woman at age 12. He
was expelled from school, thrown out of his home by his parents the
next day, and stopped, arrested and strip-searched numerous times
by the police, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 14, in November 1992, he was sexually assaulted by
police officers on at least two occasions, the court said. He also
was attacked with a knife by a group of young men.
</P>
<P>
   He fled to the United States, was arrested and deported. He
entered the United States again in October 1994, at 16, and applied
for asylum after being arrested in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   An immigration judge and the Board of Immigration Appeals said a
man who was abused because he chose to dress as a woman was not
being persecuted because of his membership in a fixed ``social
group,'' a legal category under the asylum law. The board said
Hernandez-Montiel's ``mistreatment arose from his conduct,'' a
statement condemned by the appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   Tashima said gay men with female sexual identities in Mexico
were a ``social group'' under the asylum law.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez-Montiel's lawyer, Robert Gerber, said the ruling was a
gratifying conclusion to a long legal battle. He said his client
had spent some time in a Los Angeles-area home for gay and lesbian
youth, but declined to discuss his whereabouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
