<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2059 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-DINERS-SURVIVAL-1000(     08-25 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINERS-SURVIVAL-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINERS ARE FAST DISAPPEARING, BUT THEIR SCARCITY MIGHT ENHANCE
THEIR ALLURE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A quartet of rough-hewn men, old beyond
their years, sits at the diner's horseshoe-shaped bar,
commiserating about the day's headaches and heartbreaks. All four
suck on cigarettes, almost in unison.
</P>
<P>
   Across the room, a young couple quietly lounges in a tattered
booth, picking at the scraps of breakfast left on their plates. The
woman makes idle, whispered conversation; the man listens,
acknowledging her with a nod and a soft smile.
</P>
<P>
   Behind them, three teen-agers laugh and cut up. They have school
in the morning but don't feel like going. One of them talks about
his girlfriend; another says he ``wishes'' he had girlfriend. ``No
you don't,'' the third one says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Huddled in a corner, away from the rest of the restaurant's
patrons, is a single, rotund man who does not utter a word. His
hair is cut short in boot-camp style. Slight wrinkles run down his
cheeks. He is by himself, and wants to keep it that way. ``I'd like
to be left alone,'' he says before returning to his coffee, the
only thing on the table.
</P>
<P>
   This scene, representing something that's at the same time so
American and so universal, could be from any number of movies, from
``American Graffiti'' to ``Diner'' to ``Pulp Fiction.'' But the
setting is here, on the north side of Fort Worth, at a gritty,
all-night hole-in-the-wall called Irene's Pink Poodle Coffee Shop.
</P>
<P>
   On a weekday night, in just a matter of hours, the Pink Poodle
in all its variety and diversity epitomizes the greasy beauty of
the quintessential all-night diner _ how it can offer you either an
open-armed greeting or total anonymity; a full meal or just a cup
of coffee; someone to talk to or a place to escape into your own
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   The all-night diner is an American icon, immediately
identifiable the world over from movies, plays, paintings and
novels. At one point in time, more than 6,000 independently owned
diners cut a swath through the American landscape, their flickering
signs inviting truckers, socializers, church-goers, students,
travelers, misfits _ anyone who wanted to eat or sit or chat.
</P>
<P>
   The country's race to merge this and duplicate that has wiped
out thousands of these institutions in recent years. There are only
about 2,200 today, says diner researcher Daniel Zilka, a
Providence, R.I., businessman who started a Web site,
dinermuseum.org, dedicated to preserving diners.
</P>
<P>
   The ones that remain, such as the Pink Poodle and Ol' South in
Fort Worth, the Metro in Dallas and the Iron Skillet in Arlington,
along with the Waffle Houses and Pancake Houses and
mom-and-pop-managed dives scattered throughout the country, still
honor diner traditions _ as do their patrons, even as they see
those traditions disappearing around them.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   It's 2:45 a.m. on a recent summer Saturday night, and the Metro
cafe in Dallas is jammed. Every booth is taken. Every bar stool is
occupied. Those waiting for tables do so outside, or linger near
the Metro's jukebox, occasionally slipping in quarters and tapping
their feet along to tunes.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it's easy to hear the music; the restaurant itself is
very noisy. Plates clatter. Waitresses scream orders to cooks. The
young customers are rowdy, hopping from table to table, friend to
friend, unintentionally evoking the scene from ``Swingers'' in
which Vince Vaughn drunkenly jumps on a cafe table and starts
goofing on co-star John Favreau.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette and grease smoke drift by the faces of Robert Perkins
and Clarence Gamble, two men who, huddled in a booth, are oblivious
to the roomful of action. Instead, they are focusing on finishing
off their pancakes and eggs and conversing about boxing. It's
almost a Norman Rockwell moment.
</P>
<P>
   Etched on their cheeks are the maps of their lives. Their hands
are calloused, savaged by hard times and hard labor. Lifetime
friends, they worked in steel mills most of their lives. Both wed
in their 20s, and both their wives have since passed away. Both
still wear their wedding rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't think I could take mine off, even if I wanted,'' says
Gamble, 61. ``Been on there so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Together and alone, Gamble and Perkins, 63, have been visiting
the Metro on a nearly daily basis for about 10 years. It's a place,
they say, where you can escape Texas' unmerciful heat. But it's
almost 3 in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still hot out,'' says Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   They do not consider diners a refuge, or historical monuments,
or gathering holes. They do not give a second thought to the diners
that are disappearing. For these two, the Metro is simply a place
to go and talk; it carries no special value or worth. If it closed,
Gamble says, ``we'd go somewhere else, Denny's or somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Others gathered here are far more attached to the Metro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it here,'' says Kelly Parker, a 19-year-old woman from
Dallas whose posse of friends spills over into multiple booths.
``There are so many weird people here. You never know who's gonna
walk in.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the night, the Metro hosts a cast of characters:
bikers, preppy SMU students, punk-rockers, hippies, old-timers and
young couples.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone gathered at this diner, where the red, speckled
booths are ripped and taped and the walls are made of wood
paneling, seems used to the swirling, roller-coaster chaos _ the
table of drunk cowboys and cowgirls who keep dropping utensils and
spilling glasses of water; the waitresses rushing from table to
table, delivering this, cleaning that; the cooks slinging grease;
the patrons singing along to songs on the jukebox. It is a big,
entrancing mess, a blur of every slice of America imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   You can pick out the ones who have never been here. One young,
preppy couple nervously waits for a table next to two big, burly
bikers. The couple's heads are down, their mouths shut.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanna eat and go,'' the guy says uneasily when asked
why they've come here, to this remote area near downtown Dallas and
the Deep Ellum club district, so late in the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``How 'bout we just go?'' his girlfriend says, tugging at his
arm.
</P>
<P>
   They quickly take off.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, not everyone is cut out for diners.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   According to diner historian Daniel Zilka, the first diner was
not in a stainless-steel building, but in the back of a wagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The diner was invented (in Providence, R.I.) in 1872 in a
horse-drawn lunch cart,'' he says. ``A guy by the name of Walter
Scott set up shop outside the Providence Journal newspaper, and
people would just walk up and order things.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, entrepreneur Samuel Jones took the concept a
step further, creating wagons so large, people could walk inside
and dine.
</P>
<P>
   Zilka says the diner boom exploded in the 1930s, first in the
Northeast, then across the country. Truckers and deliverymen hungry
for food and conversation populated them, and as the highways tore
through the country, diners followed.
</P>
<P>
   Writers, musicians and, eventually, Hollywood noticed and
embraced them, immortalizing the eateries in books, songs, movies
and art. Edward Hopper's 1942 painting ``Nighthawks'' is often
cited as perfectly capturing the simple, somewhat romantic pleasure
of eating at a small diner in the wee hours of the night.
</P>
<P>
   In the late '60s, folk singer Arlo Guthrie penned an 18-minute
song focusing on a diner, ``Alice's Restaurant Massacree,'' that
has since become a staple of classic-rock airwaves. Countless books
have been written about the roadside restaurant. And Hollywood has
embedded images of plates of grits and long conversations into
America's subconscious via a seemingly endless string of movies.
</P>
<P>
   There was even a sitcom based on a diner, ``Alice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're real cultural icons,'' Zilka says. ``That's why
writers and movie-makers love them, because they are a direct
reflection of society. You don't get any more `real' than a 24-hour
diner. The people who work there are real. The people who patronize
them are real. They are America.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Anita Brandon has spent a good chunk of her life working at
24-hour truck stops and diners.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hammond has spent most of his life eating at them.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon, 43, is a waitress at the Pink Poodle, where she has
worked for two years. Hammond, 67, is a regular customer there. He
visits at least once a day, sometimes twice or three times.
</P>
<P>
   For both of them, it's a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a night person,'' says Brandon, whose apron is dotted with
pins of cats. ``I can't help it. I love working nights. It's all
I've ever really done.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammond, a rancher who retired from Bell Helicopter five years
ago, says he goes to the Poodle mainly for one reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the best coffee in town,'' says Hammond, who dons a
cowboy hat and pockets a pack of cigarettes. ``Whenever I get the
notion I want coffee, I don't make it (at home). I go up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk to Hammond and Brandon awhile, though, and it becomes clear
they are drawn to the Poodle for more reasons than the night hours
and coffee. It's the social atmosphere they enjoy, the warmth and
friendliness of the patrons and workers, the unpredictable
happenings that pop up every once in a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work the bar area (of the restaurant), so I get all the
drunks that come in,'' says Brandon. ``But some of those people are
so drunk, they don't know how or care how much money they're
leaving for tips. You can make good money.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammond says that since he started going to the Poodle, more
than 25 years ago, he has seen it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes, just about everything has happened over there,'' he
says. ``Lots of characters. Some people wanna fight, some are
drunk. But they got good people working there, and they'll throw
them out.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Despite such attractions, the Poodle, like other small diners
and truck stops, is going through a tough time financially. Chain
restaurants and fast-food joints have definitely put a dent in the
popularity of diners, says Zilka.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like all owner-operated gas stations have become
convenience stores,'' he says. ``Every day, we're becoming more and
more of a homogenized society. Restaurants now are sort of like
grazing fields. Someone pours out the food and we all just eat it
up. How many people bake pies anymore? How many people make coffee
anymore?''
</P>
<P>
   As franchise-mania makes every town and city in America, and
increasingly every country, seem familiar _ and people with little
time unconsciously turn to the convenience of franchise stores and
restaurants _ the all-night diner has become an anachronism. But,
as it turns out, this pervasive corporate sameness might end up
being the savior of the diner. For as their utility as roadside
eateries and community gathering places diminishes, they remain
attractive as one of the last outposts for those seeking an escape
from cookie-cutter establishments and cookie-cutter people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those chain restaurants are the places where most people eat,
because they're fast and convenient,'' says Zilka. ``Eating in
America is almost a nuisance now. `Oh, we have to stop and get
something to eat.' Diners have the flavor of what America used to
be, but that's one reason why chain restaurants will never
completely wipe them out. They are different.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
