<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T TAKE THIS ONE PLAY AND RUN WITH IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ OK, they ran it. So now what?
</P>
<P>
   The most called-for play in the Patriots' arsenal _ backup
quarterback Michael Bishop running the option at the goal line _
finally appeared, and the result was everything talk show callers
have been saying it would be.
</P>
<P>
   It was a touchdown. It was excitement. It was fun.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a play that's going to take this team to the Super
Bowl, but who's worrying about that these days?
</P>
<P>
   The former Kansas State All-American scrambled through half the
Carolina Panthers' defense on a 1-yard scoring run in the first
quarter. The touchdown capped a 13-play, 67-yard drive that had
been engineered by Drew Bledsoe. When the ball got stuck at the
1-yard line on second down, Bishop came in and tapped Bledsoe on
the shoulder, to the delight of the fans who noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry mate, you're out,'' Bishop said.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, Bledsoe was low-fiving Bishop as he jogged off
the field. That solitary touchdown will launch a thousand calls to
sports talk hosts today, probably enough to send Verizon workers
back out on strike.
</P>
<P>
   This is what so many had envisioned for so long _ sit the
thick-legged Bledsoe down when the ball is near the goal line and
put in Bishop, who moves like a tap dancer, with rhythm and speed.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive coordinator Charlie Weis, who obviously had been
listening to talk radio when he said he was working on his game
plans, finally opted to try it, and off Bishop went into the night.
</P>
<P>
   That Bishop didn't do another thing the rest of the game will go
unnoticed by Patriot loyalists who insist his scrambling ability is
the key to the success of this team.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop didn't throw a pass Thursday night because head coach
Bill Belichick wanted to see John Friesz and Tom Brady before he
makes a final decision on who will be the third-string quarterback.
Bishop's preseason passing performance was thus left at 22 of 44 _
a 50 percent completion percentage _ with as many interceptions (2)
as touchdown passes (2). But that won't mean a thing to Bishop's
followers, who'll argue Bledsoe is all about numbers, while Bishop
is about finding ways to win.
</P>
<P>
   What also will go unnoticed is the fact that before Bledsoe took
his leave, he went 7 of 8 for 78 yards in the Patriots' 29-21
victory, pushing his summer numbers to 35 of 56, a completion rate
of 62.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   They won't even notice that while Bledsoe has been sacked only
twice this summer, the fleet-footed Bishop has been hauled down
eight times, in part because of his inexperience at solving the
riddles of NFL defenses even when they're being run by
second-stringers.
</P>
<P>
   All they will remember is Michael Bishop ran the option for a
score from the 1-yard line when he got his chance, so think of the
possibilities if he just were given the ball more often.
</P>
<P>
   A talk radio caller this week went so far as to suggest that
Pittsburgh Steelers backup quarterback Kent Graham would be better
for the Patriots' offense than Bledsoe, which made you wonder when
the people were going to come back to put the restraints on him and
take him back to his room.
</P>
<P>
   For any thinking football mind, there is no quarterback
controversy here, either in terms of who should be the starting
quarterback or who should be running the option. The answer is
Bledsoe to the first question and Bishop to the second. Each in his
own time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was great,'' Bledsoe said of Bishop's cameo
appearance. ``He puts a different kind of pressure on a defense. He
can stretch the corner. It's going to be something defenses will
have to prepare for. If it helps us win games, I'm all for it. I'll
high-five him on my way out, and he'll high-five me on my way back
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Using that goal-line option was a brilliant move by Weis and
Belichick because it showcased what Bishop might do in a game and
forces opposing defensive coordinators to work on how to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   What it also did was make clear that the play should be used
because Bishop ran it twice, first using a handoff to fullback Tony
Carter to read how the defense would play the option, then
jitterbugging through the Panthers' first defense. One thing is
clear: Bishop knows how to run the option to perfection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The corner hesitated for a minute,'' Bishop said. ``That's an
opportunity to cut it up. I think during the season it can help us
out in certain situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it can; Bishop will score on it often if given the
chance, and with touchdowns still in short supply around here, Weis
should utilize any way he can get his offense into the end zone.
Bishop is one of those ways.
</P>
<P>
   But getting Bishop in position to do what he does best is still
Drew Bledsoe's responsibility and no one else's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
