<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2073 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-MERLONI-AR     08-25 1812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-MERLONI-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 MERLONI GLAD TO BE HOME AFTER JAPANESE JOURNEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Jose Offerman drives his Rolls-Royce to the ballpark,
perhaps the gaudiest set of wheels in a Red Sox parking lot jammed
with luxury vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   When he was in Japan, Lou Merloni rode a motor scooter, a gift
from Bobby Rose, the former California Angel and his American
teammate on the Yokohama Bay Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby Rose was the MVP of the team,'' Merloni said, ``so they
gave him a Saab, which meant his scooter was available, so he gave
it to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The scooter proved handy when trying to maneuver through choking
traffic in search of a parking spot in Yokohama, the city of 3
million about 20 miles from Tokyo. ``It was crazier than having New
York City right next to LA,'' Merloni said.
</P>
<P>
   But there were times Merloni, who had never been on a scooter
before, longed for the creature comforts of home, a 15-hour plane
ride away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably one of the most humbling moments of my life,''
he said. ``When things aren't going good baseball-wise, you're not
playing, and you've got to jump on a scooter to drive home through
a crowd. A couple of times I'd get so upset, I'd be screaming
inside my helmet. I mean, here I am, I'm in Japan, I'm not playing,
I'm driving a damn scooter. It was a very humbling experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The Framingham Kid, his career with the Red Sox apparently
having come to an end despite his key role as an emergency fill-in
for Nomar Garciaparra in the Division Series against Cleveland last
October, signed a deal last November with the Bay Stars, one of six
teams in Japan's Central League. The Sox have a close working
arrangement with the Bay Stars. Before he joined the Sox, pitcher
Tomo Ohka pitched for Yokohama, though he wound up being demoted to
the Bay Stars' minor league team.
</P>
<P>
   Merloni, promised a chance to play third base every day in
Japan, signed with Yokohama last November for a base salary of
around $650,000. That was over three times more than the big-league
minimum of $200,000 he probably would have gotten from the Red Sox,
who held little promise he would be with the big-league club.
</P>
<P>
   Spring training in Japan began the first week of February,
almost three weeks before position players report to camp in the
States. From his first day, Merloni-san realized that in Japan,
they do things a little differently than the sons of Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every morning, players were required to report to the hotel
lobby to have their blood pressure checked, to make sure they were
in condition for that day's workout. Then the whole team, including
manager and coaches, would head out for a 10-minute walk to a
vacant lot, where the team did a series of stretching exercises
unknown to Yokohama's newest gaijin, the Japanese word for
foreigner or outsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of really weird movements,'' Merloni said. ``That first
week, everybody was laughing at me because I'd never done this
stuff before.''
</P>
<P>
   His second day in camp, Merloni said, players lined up on both
baselines for some soft toss, each hitter with a bucket of balls
and a teammate to toss the ball in the air to be hit. ``The buckets
were the size of water coolers, full of baseballs,'' Merloni said.
``I asked my interpreter, `How many swings, 50?' He says, `No, the
whole bucket.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `How many balls are in there?' He said, `About 250.' I
said, `You can't be serious.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, Merloni said, he would have taken no more than 20 or
30 swings in the batting cage that early in camp. It was no
different for the pitchers. One Japanese teammate, coming off elbow
surgery, wanted to test his arm. Merloni said he threw 400 pitches
during a bullpen session. Bret Saberhagen, in similar
circumstances, would have thrown about 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first at-bat in an intrasquad game, I'll never forget,'' he
said. ``The first pitch I saw was a slider. Then two curveballs, a
splitter, another slider, and I struck out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember going back to the dugout thinking, `Hey, this ain't
right. It's Feb. 6. I should be on my couch, watching TV, getting
ready for spring training in two weeks.' I saw five breaking balls
that first day, an indication of what I was going to see the rest
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the adjustment in spring training. I gave up on the
fastball. I wasn't going to see one to hit. When I did see one, it
was just to set you up, so I just washed it out of my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Merloni lived rent-free in Yokohama. It's one of the perks of
being a gaijin; he lived in a nice condo provided by the club. The
Bay Stars also furnished him with an interpreter who was always
with him, home and away, except if Merloni would step out for a
bite to eat or go to a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he said, he picked up enough language basics to
venture out on his own. There were a few English-speaking places in
town, usually full of Australians and Americans, though he gave up
on watching ESPN. ``They only showed cricket matches, soccer, and
Australian rules football,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He stayed in touch with friends back home, including
Garciaparra, through e-mail and by phone. His mom and grandmother
came for a visit; together, they toured memorials at Hiroshima and
Nagasaki commemorating the victims of the atomic bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``You walk out of there with a bad feeling in your stomach,'' he
said. ``The history, it had to be done, I guess, but it was tough
to see. You walk out of there and put yourself in their shoes. You
hear stories about people burning, and jumping into the water, but
the water was boiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have this picture of a huge rock. You're looking at it,
staring at it and thinking, `What is this?' But when you really
stare at it, you see an outline of a woman, whose shadow has been
burned in this rock. I get chills just thinking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the field, Merloni quickly learned that contrary to what he'd
been told, playing every day was out of the question. The Bay Stars
already had a native player at third base whose defense, Merloni
said, would have ranked him with the top big-league third basemen.
``I had to be perfect,'' he said. ``If I went 3 for 4 but made an
error, then I couldn't field. If I made three good plays in the
field but was 0 for 4, then I couldn't hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans, he said, were uniformly encouraging. The reporters who
covered the team, relentlessly curious.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had about five reporters with us all the time,'' he said.
``They wanted to know why I was single, they wanted to know about
my personal life, what my nickname is, my favorite American word.''
</P>
<P>
   Merloni said he never fell out of favor with the Yokohama brass,
but the manager, Hiroshi Gondo, didn't show much confidence in him.
``We'd get guys on first and third with no out and he'd hit for
me,'' said Merloni, who batted just .213, mostly as a pinch hitter.
``They'd pinch bunt for me. I'd tell them, `Hey, I was the guy who
pinch bunt for other guys in the big leagues.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Merloni came away respecting the talent of the Japanese players,
but he was continually surprised by some of the quirks: the
determination to keep the identity of the starting pitcher secret,
for example, until just before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Teams would go to great pains to hide who was going to pitch.
One opponent, he said, had its pitcher taking ground balls at short
and turning double plays in an effort to lull the opposition into
believing he wasn't pitching that day. It wasn't until lineup cards
were exchanged, Merloni said, that anyone would know who was
pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Why the secrecy? ``They told me, `If you know who's pitching,
you can go to bed and get yourself ready to face him,' '' Merloni
said.
</P>
<P>
   Merloni had dressed in the cramped clubhouses of Fenway Park,
but he never shared his locker with a tractor, as he had to do in
one Japanese ballpark. The players changed in a storage shed.
Sometimes, it was worse to be in the clubhouse, because of all the
cigarette smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy might hit a home run,'' he said, ``and they'd put five
or six cartons of cigarettes on a table and everybody would just
grab 'em and be smoking everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   And for all the controversy sparked by Carl Everett's bumping
umpire Ron Kulpa, the incident couldn't compare with the brawl
Merloni witnessed after an opposing hitter was called out on
strikes to end the game with the tying run on base.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws his helmet down and pushes the umpire, then runs
after him,'' Merloni said. ``The manager came flying out, and he
shoves the umpire to the ground. It turned into a bench-clearing
brawl between the four umpires and their team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm standing there watching, and I couldn't believe it. Guys
were swinging at the umpires, hitting them. Five guys were
suspended five games. The umpire had a broken rib and was out 2 1/2
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His playing time dwindling, Merloni was so desperate to leave
Japan he offered to give back part of his salary in order to return
to the States. Eventually, he reached a settlement, and was back by
the end of last month. Enough time, he figured, to finish the
season in the US. Even before he got back home, he was in touch
with the Red Sox, and they signed him to a minor league contract.
After playing very well in an 11-game stint at Pawtucket, the Sox
called him up at the start of their just-finished homestand,
allowing him to recoup the money he forfeited in Japan. Merloni has
played a big part in the team's resurgence, batting .366 in his
first 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   While he's glad to be back, Merloni said he gained some valuble
insight _ as well as a measure of financial security _ during his
time in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brought me a whole new level of appreciation,'' he said.
``Sometimes when you're in the big leagues, you get so caught up in
it. Every time I didn't do well last year, I was scared that I was
going to be sent down. I played scared that I would do bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, if I go 0 for 4, I don't care. Sure, I'm disappointed
that I didn't get the job done, but I'm not going to go home and
kill myself. They know that when I go out there, I'm going to give
it the best that I can.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many things in this game you can't control. If what
I do ain't good enough, so be it. I've had some great moments, a
great career. I haven't had a `career' career, but for a guy like
me, one day in the big leagues is a great career. A home run in my
first Fenway at-bat, playing in the playoffs, that's a great career
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The kind of career he can someday look back on with fondness,
when he's tooling around Framingham on his scooter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
