<HEADER>
A2075 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-SURVIVOR-BOS &LR;      08-25 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURVIVOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SURVIVOR' WINNER HONED STRATEGIES EARLY ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLETOWN, R.I. _ Richard H. Hatch Jr. was a survivor long
before he sank his toes into the sand on an uninhabited island near
Borneo, speared a stingray off the beach there in the South China
Sea, or strutted naked through the Tagi camp on his 39th birthday
to the shock and/or entertainment of one of the larger TV series
audiences in recent history.
</P>
<P>
   His history of overcoming obstacles began here in his hometown.
Despite appearances, life in this town close to the ocean and to
Newport, full of abundant hydrangea bushes and stone walls, was not
a charmed one for Hatch.
</P>
<P>
   He says he grew up in a family devoid of love. His parents
divorced after he and his three siblings were born. He dropped out
of school as a senior and battled a significant weight problem, all
while coping with the stigma of being gay in a strait-laced
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a loving home, by any stretch,'' Hatch said during
a telephone conference call Thursday. ``I don't remember being told
`I love you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But with the help of a teacher who encouraged him to join a
summer outdoor adventure program in Maine when he was 18, Hatch
began turning his life around. And eventually, he earned a diploma,
spent time in the Army and at West Point, jumped out of airplanes,
received a bachelor's degree in behavioral science, became a
corporate trainer, even adopted a troubled child of his own three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, he became the ultimate survivor, winning $1
million and a car for being the last man out on CBS's reality-TV
series ``Survivor,'' which had its final episode Wednesday night.
Although Hatch returned from Pulau Tiga in April after spending 39
days there, he had to lie to his sister and his son and keep the
results from his mother, to maintain the summer's best-kept secret.
</P>
<P>
   However, for those who know Hatch _ everyone from the contractor
working on his three-bedroom Cape-style house on a hill, to the
personal trainer at Newport Athletic Club who helped him shed 100
pounds before he started taping the program last March, to the
video production expert who filmed the audition tape that drew
CBS's attention _ he has been a man on a mission for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Smyth, his muscle-bound personal trainer, said Hatch began
devoting himself in February 1999 to a low-fat, high-protein diet
and intense workouts _ which eventually built up to four-hour
sessions after CBS chose him for ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sick and tired of being overweight,'' Smyth said.
``When I first met him, he was not anywhere near as confident as he
was on the island.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing so much weight, Smyth said, gave Hatch drive.
</P>
<P>
   But something else was driving Hatch: his newly adopted son,
Christopher, now 10. The boy began gaining weight after getting off
some medication, and Hatch did not want to see another child
ostracized for being larger than his peers. Hatch said he believed
he needed to serve as a role model, and had to drop the pounds
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Christopher would sit in the hall at the gym and read
or play Gameboy while Hatch worked out, Smyth said. But the boy
soon joined his father on 6-mile jogs at 4:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   According to police reports, Christopher wanted to quit during
one of those runs, but Hatch put him in a headlock to try to force
him to continue. The boy complained at school. And the event
erupted into a legal battle with Rhode Island child welfare
authorities, who removed the boy, and later returned him, with much
emotional damage already done, Hatch believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a firm parent,'' said Tim Downes of Downes
Construction, the company that has been slowly overhauling Hatch's
modest house since 1998. ``And the kid probably needs to be treated
that way. He's a handful.''
</P>
<P>
   Downes, whose crew was hammering decorative cedar shakes on the
house, said he knew Hatch had a good chance of winning because of
what he does for a living.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch owns Tri-Whale training, a corporate management company he
founded in Washington, D.C., and later moved to Newport. (The name
reflects his love for whales.) Growing up in Middletown, it would
be hard not to be drawn to the surrounding ocean. In fact, Hatch
began college at the Florida Institute of Technology, majoring in
marine biology.
</P>
<P>
   He then joined the Army and went to West Point, left halfway
through, moved to Manhattan, studied accounting at Baruch College
of the City University of New York, attended George Mason
University in Virginia, and finished college at National Louis's
Washington campus with a degree in applied behavioral sciences.
He's continuing his education at Providence College.
</P>
<P>
   But the jump-start on his life _ and on his survival skills _
came that summer when he was 18 and signed up for the adventure
camp Horizon Bound in the Maine woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so life-altering for me,'' Hatch said of the
now-defunct program.
</P>
<P>
   So what's he going to do with the $1 million?
</P>
<P>
   Hatch says he wants to start a camp like that of his own.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he is juggling the onslaught of potential
managers, dealmakers, and interview requests. (He had 60 broadcast
interviews to tackle just Thursday, including another stint with
David Letterman.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to figure out what the smartest way of
handling them is,'' Hatch said. ``A book is a possibility. I think
I've had an interesting life, topping that off with having been on
`Survivor.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Although he declined to discuss any endorsement deals that may
be in the works with companies such as Reebok, Hatch has already
signed on with American Program Bureau, a Newton-based firm that
sets up speaking engagements and counts Mikhail Gorbachev and
Nelson Mandela among its clients.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Walker, American Program's chairman and CEO, said Hatch
will earn more from his speeches than his ``Survivor'' prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard is very hot,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Hatch will be filling in next week on a Rhode Island
radio station's 9 a.m. hourlong broadcast. And he's not shy in
front of a microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Brown, senior production director at Perspective
Communications Group Inc., a Middletown company that videotaped
Hatch's demo tape for CBS, said he hammed it up for the camera.
</P>
<P>
   In one scene, shot in his favorite local restaurant, Hatch
jokingly asked the chef if he had anything to eat. The chef nodded
toward a piece of uncooked steak, waiting to be grilled for another
customer.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch took a huge bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of it was staged,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Once Hatch returns to Rhode Island, he says, he hopes his
lifestyle will not change, and he claims he will not flaunt his
wealth. Although he may flaunt his body. He lost another 34 pounds
on ``Survivor,'' and he underwent surgery to remove the skin around
his midsection that had been stretched beyond the point that
exercise could make it taut again.
</P>
<P>
   He is not dating anyone, but would like to.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prize,'' he said, ``may complicate that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
