<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2079 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-ART     08-25 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 WALKER FINDS IT HARD TO SETTLE IN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ This is his home. This is the place where he
will hold his free basketball camp for 100 youths this weekend.
This is where you can find him Sunday afternoons, admiring the
skills of Drew Bledsoe, but still rooting for his hometown Bears.
This is where, from October to May, you can find Antoine Walker.
</P>
<P>
   But for how long? When will the Celtics finally do what they
have been hinting at doing all summer? When will they make their
best player a full-time New England visitor?
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, you have heard a lot about the Celtics'
24-year-old captain. At times, his own employers talk about him as
if he were Sherman Klump stuffed into basketball shorts. Lost in
the commentary is this: He's smart. And when you're smart, you know
when someone is trying to get rid of you.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics are trying; Walker is resisting.
</P>
<P>
   One of Walker's friends called him earlier this week and asked
if he was keeping up with ``Survivor.'' Walker said he had never
heard of the show, even though surviving is the theme of his
Celtics summer. His bosses are apparently trying to vote him off
the team. While they make their calls, he'll be at HealthPoint
today, tomorrow, and Sunday, teaching and coaching young basketball
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't bother me in the beginning,'' Walker said of the
trade speculation, ``but there's only so much one person can take.
It's a business, so if you have a chance to improve your team with
a trade, you should do it. But after a while, after seeing your
name come up consistently in trade talks, it makes you feel
unwanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either (the Celtics) are going to make a move or they're not.
If they are, they should go ahead and do it. If they're not, let's
keep the trade talk to a minimum. It's the summer. Why is it so
hard for them to keep my name out of their mouths?''
</P>
<P>
   Walker, who dreams of making a community impact the same way Mo
Vaughn did, was asked if he wants to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``I like it here. I'd like to be a part of our
improvement. I'm tired of this team not being in the playoffs. It's
definitely not my first choice to leave. There's not a player in
the NBA who enjoys being traded. You don't want to pick up and go
play in a different city for a different coach.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to Walker, Celtics management usually behaves like
an indecisive lover. (itals)I love you. I don't love you. I hate
you. I might love you. Check with me tomorrow.(unitals) Never mind.
Before the Heat traded for Eddie Jones, Miami and the Celtics could
have completed a deal involving Walker, Jamal Mashburn, and P.J.
Brown. The Pacers were willing to trade Austin Croshere for Walker,
but Croshere rejected the deal because, while he was interested in
Boston, he wanted to play with Paul Pierce and Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Before Jerry West retired in Los Angeles, he was contemplating
another brilliant move: acquiring Walker and his salary without
giving up Kobe Bryant and Shaquille O'Neal. If that trade had gone
through, the NBA wouldn't be fair anymore. Whom could you double
team with Walker, Shaq, and Kobe all on the floor? In the land of
the Oscars, Walker would be a 21st-century Oscar Robertson,
dropping effortless triple-doubles.
</P>
<P>
   He could do the same in Boston if management brought in more
help. (itals)Starting(unitals) help. Everyone can see the Celtics
have improved their bench, even though winning teams are usually
the ones that have the luxury of going shopping for spare parts in
the summer. When a team wins 37 games, loses its most rugged
rebounder (Danny Fortson), and adds more role players to its bench,
it is destined to win 37 games again.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, you have to wonder why Rick Pitino, Chris
Wallace, Leo Papile, and company would try to trade one of the few
Celtics players who would not anchor another team's bench. Just as
puzzling was Pitino's Don't Be Like My Best Player monologue to a
group of teenage summer campers in Pittsburgh. Pitino denies making
the remarks, which were recorded by Paul Zeise, a reliable
journalist for the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Pittsburgh, Walker realized the Celtics were looking
to move him. Because Pitino is the caretaker of this organization,
it is his right to do whatever he wants in terms of personnel. But
after all of his not-so-secret attempts to trade Walker, Pitino had
better hope he is successful before training camp. You can't try to
trade a player all summer and expect him to be enthusiastic about
playing for you in the fall. Larry Brown is making the same mistake
with Allen Iverson in Philadelphia, and his actions are more
foolish than Pitino's because the 76ers are a winning team. Why not
moan about your stars' flaws in private?
</P>
<P>
   The irony, though, is that Walker's weaknesses seem to be
shrinking while the Celtics' seem to be growing. Thursday, fatigue
was draped on Walker like a designer scarf. He had taken a Los
Angeles-to-Boston red-eye so he could be here for Boston's first
'Toine's Summer Camp (he has had four in Chicago). Banners,
itineraries, and basketballs were strewn throughout his condo. You
could tell he needed sleep, but you could also tell the idea of the
camp invigorated him.
</P>
<P>
   He was too immature to be invigorated by others when he first
arrived in Boston. That is no longer the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have seen the team I had in Chicago,'' Walker said
of the camp team he coached. ``I had two little guards who were
putting crossover dribbles on everybody. And I had my brother
(12-year-old Jarvis, already 6 feet 1 inch) playing the post. Man.
We went 7-2 for the week. We lost the championship by 2 in overtime
. . .''
</P>
<P>
   Before telling the story, Walker was nearly sinking in an
armchair. Retelling it, though, gave him a temporary lift. He is
predictable in that he has soft spots for kids and sports. He loves
talking about the Red Sox (``They don't have big names, but they
know how to win''), Tiger Woods (``I never watch golf on TV, but he
made me a fan on Sunday''), and the achievements of his teammates
(``I played with Jerome (Moiso) and Paul (Pierce) at UCLA; they
both look good'').
</P>
<P>
   He's also honest. He wants to ``give back'' with his free camps,
but he also wants ``to watch the kids play ball. I like watching
young talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker was at the Capital Grille Thursday, treating his
volunteer coaches to dinner. He'll be at the Celtics practice
facility all weekend. If you care about the future of this team,
you should hope he'll be at the facility in the fall, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Michael Holley is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
holley(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
