<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2080 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     08-25 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IPO VALUE IS STILL HAZY, BUT VERIZON'S POTENTIAL IS CLEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think of it as an 800-pound gorilla with a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon Wireless Inc., with more than 25 million customers the
nation's largest mobile phone business, filed papers for an initial
public stock offering Thursday, as expected.
</P>
<P>
   The company, majority owned by the phone company Verizon
Communications, suggested in its documents that the IPO could raise
up to $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Though the figure would make the Verizon Wireless IPO the
third-largest ever, analysts and investors widely believe it to be
a low-ball estimate.
</P>
<P>
   The best guesses we heard for an eventual, real number exceed
that of the biggest ever IPO, the $10.6 billion public launch of a
``tracking'' stock for rival AT&AMP;T Wireless Group four months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The industry is moving at breakneck speed to make good on the
huge potential of wireless Internet access and the growing demand
for voice communications over the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   That takes a boatload of cash, creates unwieldy organizations
tangled by hypergrowth, and sometimes demands action before
important technical issues have been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out whether Verizon Wireless makes sense to own depends
on how the IPO values the company, impossible to tell yet without
knowing how much of the business it wants to sell to the public and
at exactly what price. We have to wait for those details.
</P>
<P>
   But valuations aside, analysts and money managers point to
Verizon Wireless as perhaps the leading competitor among a top tier
of national wireless companies, such as AT&AMP;T Wireless Group, Sprint
PCS, and Nextel Communications Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the greatest footprint in the country right now, the
highest number of customers, and a solid management team of
experienced people,'' said Mark Lowenstein, who runs wireless
research at the Yankee Group, a Boston consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The big ``footprint'' means that Verizon Wireless, based in New
Jersey, provides wireless service in 96 of the nation's 100 largest
cities. That kind of market generated sales of $13.5 billion last
year, and $7.3 billion through the first half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these guys and Sprint PCS are the two best-positioned
wireless players today,'' said John Lathrop, manager of the MFS
Global Telecommunications Fund.
</P>
<P>
   But its national market was made possible by a series of
rapid-fire mergers and combinations. Now, Verizon must figure out
how to meld four different operations into one smooth business.
</P>
<P>
   The company was created when Bell Atlantic merged its wireless
business with the Airtouch operation owned by Vodafone. When Bell
Atlantic merged with GTE Corp. (and changed its name to Verizon
Communications), it added GTE's wireless business to the pot. A
fourth business, PrimeCo, is the final piece of Verizon Wireless.
</P>
<P>
   They are all slightly different. And some, notably the old Bell
Atlantic operations, are run better than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their biggest challenge right now is pulling together all
these different carriers they've acquired,'' Lowenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of all the combinations, Vodafone owns 45 percent of
the wireless company, and Verizon Communications holds the rest of
its stock. Those percentages will decline when public shareholders
take a slice of the pie in the Verizon Wireless IPO.
</P>
<P>
   Another big challenge for all the leading wireless companies:
Are they operating on the best technology standard for the future?
There is no obvious answer.
</P>
<P>
   Europe got a big jump on America when it comes to wireless
communications because the vast majority of systems there are
operating on one technical standard. Not so in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies, such as Verizon Wireless and Sprint PCS, use a
system called CDMA. Others, principally AT&AMP;T Wireless Group, employ
another, called TDMA. The Europeans are operating on a third
standard.
</P>
<P>
   It's Beta vs. VHS, only much more complicated. And billions are
being invested in new or upgraded towers using different standards.
</P>
<P>
   Many people, like Lowenstein, believe multiple standards will
live on for years. For those who think the world will converge to
one standard _ or to several that can operate with each other
sooner rather than later _ most believe CDMA is the better option
for today.
</P>
<P>
   The Verizon Wireless IPO will be managed by Merrill Lynch and
Goldman Sachs, a rich detail that did not escape close observers.
</P>
<P>
   Just two months ago, Verizon Communications spun out an interest
of another giant operating unit, the Burlington, Mass. Internet
infrastructure company Genuity Inc., and employed Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter and Salomon Smith Barney to handle the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Genuity shares have been a flop from the start, opening weakly
and trading more than $2 below their offering price.
</P>
<P>
   But Merrill and Goldman Sachs carry some recent baggage of their
own. They managed the AT&AMP;T Wireless Group IPO in April, another
disappointment so far. Those shares finished about 16 percent below
their IPO price as of Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
