<HEADLINE>
PROMISING TRAVERS FIELD HAS FADED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Going into the Kentucky Derby, run on
the first Saturday in May, this looked like the best crop of
3-year-olds in memory. Led by Fusaichi Pegasus, touted as a
superhorse, the sophomore division was supposed to be both talented
and deep. So, what happened?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it looked like it was going to be a hell of a lot better
than it turned out to be,'' said Cot Campbell, president of Dogwood
Stable, which will run Impeachment in Saturday's $1 million Travers
at Saratoga. ``But I do think it's too early for people to make a
decision that it's a very bad group. We don't know that yet. It may
be that they do more than they've shown so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus did win the Kentucky Derby, but he was beaten
by Red Bullet, whose connections skipped the Derby, over an off
track in the Preakness. Fusaichi Pegasus then hurt a hoof in his
stall while in training for the Belmont Stakes _ from which Red
Bullet was also withheld _ and he has not run since. Following the
Belmont, Fusaichi Pegasus was syndicated to stud for $70 million,
making him almost too expensive to race, though his camp insists
he'll return in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it was discovered Wednesday that Red Bullet, who had
run a dull third in the Dwyer at Belmont July 9, will go on the
shelf until next year after X-rays revealed he had sustained a
slight fracture of the left front leg that his camp feared would
only get worse.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line is the Triple Crown, which had started out so
strongly in May, had faded completely by the Belmont in June, when
Commendable, a plodder at best, won the third leg. Of the 19 horses
who started the Derby, only three have made it to the Travers:
Impeachment, who finished third in the Derby; Curule, who was
seventh; and Commendable, who wound up 17th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand what happens with a horse who has a problem
(hello, Red Bullet), but I can't understand not running in a big
race when you've got a shot (hello, Fusaichi Pegasus),'' said
Campbell, 72, who has owned horses since 1969. ``What, $1 million
is not enough, so you're going to wait for a race worth $4 million
(the Breeders' Cup Classic in November)? The classics are our best
races, and the Travers is a classic. I'm from the school that says,
`When you're horse is doing good, run him.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, after seeing him in the Derby, that Fusaichi
Pegasus was a superhorse, but I don't think that anymore. He's in
great hands (trained by the cautious Neil Drysdale), and he has a
great pedigreee (by the late Mr. Prospector), but you couldn't call
him a superhorse now, as little as he's run.''
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment, listed at 12-1 for the Travers, is far from
special, but he does have one accomplishment. He was the only horse
to race in all three legs of the Triple Crown this year, finishing
third in the Preakness and fifth in the Belmont. A son of Deputy
Minister, Impeachment also came back in the Haskell Aug. 6,
finishing sixth, and is, by today's standards, an iron horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a rugged kind of horse,'' said Campbell. ``He likes to
mix it up. He likes to get bounced around. The more they bounce
him, the better it makes him. Twenty or 30 years ago, Impeachment's
campaign would have been considerd moderate. Now, it's a grueling
campaign. But he's never looked better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could drop him down, but he's better off running for big
money. He comes on late and gets us a piece of the purse. The
Haskell wasn't his best race, but it set him up for the Travers.''
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment may be slow, but at least he's tough. That's more
than can be said for most of his fellow sophomores, and that's why
this class is considered a disappointment.
</P>
</TEXT>
