<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 PALMER RATES WOODS GOLF'S GREATEST STAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ The great Arnold Palmer has played with and
against most of golf's legends over the years. Few players have a
greater respect for the game's tradition and history. Indeed, he's
been a major part of that tradition and history.
</P>
<P>
   But Palmer, in town for the Senior PGA FleetBoston Classic,
which kicks off Friday at Nashawtuc Country Club, says one player
may stand above the rest. He speaks, of course, of 24-year-old
Tiger Woods, who recently won his third major of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question he has surpassed everyone in his ability
to play,'' said Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem Woods is likely to face as he continues his
assault on the PGA record book is a lack of competition, Palmer
said. Woods, and the Tour, need competition to get better.
</P>
<P>
   Woods's accomplishments to date have been well documented,
particularly his record-setting performances at the Masters and the
US and British Opens. Two things left to shoot for are Byron
Nelson's mark of winning 11 consecutive tournaments in 1945, which
will be awfully tough to match given the expansion of the Tour, and
Jack Nicklaus's 18 major tournament victories. Woods is off to a
good start on that one, having won five majors, including four of
the last five.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say there's never going to be anything like this
again,'' said Palmer. ``Unless something jumps the track for Tiger
Woods, he's going to set a lot of records. He has brought a
tremendous amount of attention to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``How it is affecting him personally, and if that's going to
affect how he does in the future, I don't know. He's still only 24
years old,'' said Palmer, noting he himself didn't start on the pro
Tour until he was 25. Woods already has four years as a pro, and
millions of dollars, under his belt.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer said Woods's utter domination may not be the best thing
for the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to tune in to see what he's doing, and at
what point are they going to get bored with Tiger?'' Palmer asked.
``It's going to take a lot of enthusiasm. You're going to see how
he can keep doing this with the steam he has displayed this
summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer recalled a conversation he had with Nicklaus at the 1997
Masters, Woods's first year as a pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so in awe with his game that there's no telling how
many Masters he'll win or how many tournaments he'll win,'' Palmer
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Palmer said Woods needs someone to keep him honest, a rival.
``What an impact it would have,'' Palmer said. ``It would be
tremendous for the game of golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer thinks he has a candidate in Charles Howell, an Oklahoma
State graduate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to put pressure on him, but Charlie is only 20. He's only
slightly built, and on a slight downhill on a tee shot, he hit it
374 yards,'' Palmer said. ``That's a start. He's very good and can
play. He's confident; just how much discipline he has will tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to compare Woods with Nicklaus in his prime, Palmer said
he likes aspects of both players' games.
</P>
<P>
   He gives the driving edge to Woods. ``He's longer than Jack was,
and maybe a little straighter,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus gets the nod on iron play. ``Jack was probably as good
an iron player as I've ever seen, particularly with the long
irons,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer also praises Nicklaus's mental side. ``He's very good and
has a good mind; he thinks very positively,'' he said. ``Jack has
the ability to isolate himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Both get high marks in putting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack was a great putter in a lot of critical conditions,''
Palmer said. ``But look at how many three-putts (Woods) had in the
US Open, British, and PGA. I don't think he's had a handful,
total.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, who turns 71 next month, has played in 10 Senior events
this year and hopes to play in about 15 before the season is out.
Of course, when considering golf's all-time greats, Palmer's name
can't be discounted. He won 60 PGA events and seven majors,
including four Masters.
</P>
<P>
   There are some more figures Woods can shoot for.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
