<HEADLINE>
CURLEY LAWSUIT TESTS FINE LINE ON FREE SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH RANALLI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a legal tactic that's been used against a wide array of
controversial groups, from gun manufacturers to antiabortion
protesters and the Grand Knights of the Ku Klux Klan: File a
lawsuit seeking millions of dollars in damages in the hope that a
massive verdict will force your opponents into bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The North American Man/Boy Love Association _ a group that
advocates legalized pedophilia and, according to some opponents,
facilitates for its members sex with boys _ is the latest in a
growing number of groups that could face astronomical damage awards
that would effectively drive them out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Long seen as protected by the constitutional guarantees of free
speech and free expression, these groups are being targeted in
civil lawsuits for acts of violence committed by third parties, but
believed to have been facilitated by the groups' activities or
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, a Middlesex County jury awarded the family of Jeffrey
Curley, a murdered 10-year-old from Cambridge, Mass., $328 million
in damages from Charles Jaynes and Salvatore Sicari, the two men
convicted of his murder.
</P>
<P>
   The family's lawyer admits there is no chance of collecting from
Sicari and Jaynes, both imprisoned for life, but touts the verdict
as an important benchmark in the family's other legal battle: a
$200 million federal lawsuit against NAMBLA for allegedly inciting
the murder.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of such suits say they're a legitimate way to hold
groups morally and financially responsible for facilitating
criminal acts. But to some free-speech advocates and civil
libertarians, the suits are a disturbing end-run around the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agree, however, that the legal strategy has become a
key weapon in some of society's most controversial ideological
battles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really new tactic and an interesting one,'' Harvard Law
School professor Heather Gerken said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Curleys' attorney, Lawrence Frisoli, said the family intends
to enjoin NAMBLA ``from doing any acts in which they encourage
members to profile children, approach children, deceive parents of
children with the intent of having sex, (or offer instructions) on
how to act to impede law enforcement investigations.''
</P>
<P>
   Such activity, Frisoli said, is distinct from the group's purely
political advocacy, which essentially advocates the abolition of
laws establishing an age of consent for sexual activity. That kind
of advocacy is protected speech, Frisoli agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Gerkin said the Curley case appears to be a difficult, though
not impossible, one to win, since numerous courts have held that
there is some speech that is not protected by the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That line is often hard to draw and the courts are often
scared to draw it,'' she said. ``The hard part is proving the
causal part, that it was foreseeable that the conduct would lead to
this kind of crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Frisoli has alleged that Jaynes viewed NAMBLA's Web site just
hours before he and Sicari lured Curley into a car, and that he had
amassed a substantial collection of NAMBLA literature.
</P>
<P>
   The Curleys' federal case has drawn comparisons with a string of
cases brought against the Ku Klux Klan in recent years by the
Southern Poverty Law Center.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, for instance, the Klan in South Carolina was ordered to
pay $37.8 million for inciting the burning of a predominantly black
church.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Potok, editor of the center's Intelligence Report, said
there is a misconception that the cases against the Klan involved
only racist rhetoric. In each one, Potok said, there was a direct
connection between the people involved in the violence and the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people think they can win cases because (a group) put out
unpleasant propaganda and someone has gone on to kill someone,'' he
said. ``The reality is that there has to be more of a connection
between the speech of the group and the actions of the actor.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Curley case, he said, ``If the group is involved in
teaching ways of avoiding the law, there very well may be
liability,'' Potok said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerken also compared the Curley suit to ones filed against gun
manufacturers for selling cheap weapons, and to one of the most
controversial recent verdicts: a federal jury's award last year of
$107 million in damages against abortion opponents who listed the
names of doctors who performed abortions on mock ``Wanted'' posters
on a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Since the site contained no direct threats, some legal observers
say they believe the verdict will be overturned.
</P>
<P>
   One question that remains unclear is whether NAMBLA is as
influential as some of the other groups that have been sued for
large damage awards.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts by the Globe to contact the group have been
unsuccessful, and its Web site has been off-line for more than a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Echols, a former social worker and journalist and a
one-time undercover informant for the FBI who operates a Web site
that tracks the group, said its membership has dwindled from as
many as 1,300 in the 1980s to as few as 400 in recent years. But
NAMBLA, he said, is still helping members prey on children by
trading names of vulnerable boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an active organization hiding behind a political
movement,'' Echols said. ``Their real agenda is to facilitate their
own access to children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 1344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
