<SLUG> BC-SPEED-DATING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READY, SET, DATE: SINGLES TRY A SPEEDY RITUAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The date lasted maybe seven minutes, eight tops,
and it was as blind as they come.
</P>
<P>
   Not one of his guy friends had encouraged him to call her. None
of her gal pals had sworn he was a hottie. All they knew about each
other when they met over coffee were their first names,
conveniently emblazoned on ``Hello My Name Is'' tags stuck to their
shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm somewhere between hopeful and leery,'' Howard Shapiro, a
33-year-old immigration attorney, said before his date.
</P>
<P>
   Before hers, Vicki Karlan, a health care researcher who is also
33, said, ``I have no idea what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, no expectations _ OK, low expectations _ was part of
the appeal of the pairing, just one of the more than 250 that took
place on a recent Sunday night. Joining the couple, were 43 other
men and women also hoping to pair off, if not with the first person
they met, then with the second or third or sixth or seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The dizzying night of dating represented the latest trend on the
Jewish singles scene. Aptly named SpeedDating, the program aims to
match Jewish women with Jewish men and eliminate the awkward pauses
and unfulfilled hopes that so often accompany more traditional
first dates.
</P>
<P>
   Launched in Los Angeles a year or so ago, SpeedDating was Rabbi
Yaakov Deyo's solution to what he saw as the coldness and
coarseness of the singles scene. As educational director of Aish
HaTorah, a nonprofit Jewish resource group with branches around the
world, he saw the dating system as a hip way to hook up unmarrieds
interested in marrying Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are more than 70 ``coffees'' a month, including ones
in Kiev, London, and Melbourne for singles in four age groups: 25
to 35, 30 to 40, 35 to 45, and 45 to 60. SpeedDating sessions are
planned in Vienna, Paris, Rome and, most recently, Santiago, Chile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The L.A. dating scene is not a user friendly market, and the
coffee shops make it very painless,'' Deyo said. ``Here they're
socially comfortable. There's no pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, however, rules. SpeedDating is like musical chairs
without the music, and that requires enormous organizational skill
on Aish HaTorah's part and impressive conversational skills on the
part of the participants.
</P>
<P>
   It works like this: First names only, plus an identifying
number. Verboten topics include age, job, housing status, and
telephone numbers. The idea is to talk about something meaningful
in seven minutes. That's when a bell clangs and the men switch
tables. Then the banter starts all over again, date after date, for
seven dates, or about 90 minutes, breaks included. The cost: $15,
or about $2.14 a date, lattes and iced cafe mochas excluded.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the men fill out yellow cards, checking off the names
of the women they're interested in seeing solo. The women do
likewise. Calls go out informing them they're a match. The rest is
up to them, although another of the rules requires matched pairs to
phone each other at least once.
</P>
<P>
   At the recent gathering at Starbucks, 28 people out of 43 made
matches, or 65 percent. Deyo said the figure sometimes approaches
70 percent. So far in Los Angeles, six SpeedDating couples have
raced to the altar. The number of success stories is even higher in
New York, which has seen 15 weddings. Any day now, the first
SpeedDating baby is expected to be born.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really takes a lot of pressure off, especially for the
women,'' said Rabbi Shalom Denbo, who, as the evening's emcee
suggested, as a sample conversational topic, discussing the best
vacation ever taken and why. ``Here you don't have to ask yourself,
`Is he really trying to get to know me or is he just trying to get
me?' We're trying to show people that there's more to a date than
the superficial `how do you look.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Few at the Starbucks, in fact, dressed up for the occasion,
although that may have been as much a function of their ages _ 25
to 35 _ as their outwardly casual attitude. Before the SpeedDates
began, many of them sounded nonchalant. But more than a few,
perhaps embarrassed about the mission before them, also declined to
give their full names.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not into the whole thing,'' said one 33-year-old woman, a
three-time SpeedDater who works in computer graphics. ``I want to
expand my horizons, I guess. OK, to tell you the truth, I'm looking
for a husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Halfway through the evening, with every table filled with
couples conversing and other potential twosomes stuck leaning
against a countertop, 28-year-old Julie, a health insurance company
analyst, said she had yet not met anyone who struck her fancy. Beth
Braun, a 29-year-old psychologist, was having better luck. She
already had several yesses to mark on her card.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes a yes? A pulse,'' joked Braun, adding that a
girlfriend had signed her up and ``forced'' her to come. ``I'll
feel so rejected if no one marks me down. Thank God I have
therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike T., a 33-year-old computer consultant on his fifth round of
SpeedDating, credits several relationships of a month or more to
the program. ``To a certain degree, you are performing, because
you're being judged so fast,'' he said. ``If you're not a good
conversationalist, it's going to hurt you.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Yamorsky, 32, entered Starbucks cautiously hopeful. He
left happy, with a number of matches marked on his yellow card.
Still, he had been there before. At previous SpeedDating events, he
met other women he liked. But three proved too busy for a real
date, he said, and a fourth joined him for lunch then never
returned his calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice meeting everyone, but nothing worked out,'' said
Yamorsky, a publishing company credit manager who described his own
free time as limited.
</P>
<P>
   Like Yamorsky, many of the participants said they were not
necessarily looking for a Jewish partner, although finding one
would be nice. Instead, they said they consider SpeedDating another
avenue to meet people, get a date or two and, maybe just maybe,
spot ``the one'' in the man or woman sitting across the table.
</P>
<P>
   As Shapiro, the immigration attorney, put it, ``You can't gauge
if it's forever in a few minutes, but you can have a clue. You can
probably tell it's `no' faster than you can get a `yes.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The rabbis who run the program don't pretend that bells will
ring for everyone. All they're trying to do with SpeedDating, Deyo
said, is give people a reasonably comfortable way to consider
whether a person is worth seeing again _ and then to follow through
on their intuition.
</P>
<P>
   Devora Fond, for instance, had decided by the break that she
would see two of her speed dates again, although she said she was
not particularly attracted to either one. But as a rabbinical
student at 31, and a two-time veteran of SpeedDating, she has
discovered that potential partners often consider her too religious
or not religious enough, depending on their own practices. She has
learned to be open to any possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I thought I wouldn't like anyone,'' said Amanda
Koblin, 30, a casting director. ``I ended up liking two. I don't
know if they're love connections, but two out of six or seven ain't
bad for one night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
