<HEADLINE>
DUNST CARRIES THE SQUAD IN `BRING IT ON' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
BRING IT ON 
Directed by: Peyton Reed 
Screenplay by: Jessica Bender 
Starring: Kirsten Dunst, Eliza Dushku, Jesse Bradford, Grbrielle
Union 
Running time: 
Rated: PG-13 (sex-related material and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Bring It On'' is 90 minutes of cheerleading angst. It's a
pom-pom comedy about a pom-pom world, but Kirsten Dunst has carried
lesser entertainments than this piece of candy-colored bubble-gum
for the eyes and she makes the difference here. She's the big
reason the film rises above instantly rejectable formula to campy
pop, although, to be fair, Jessica Bendinger's screenplay
occasionally rescues itself from its own styrofoam mindlessness
with a neat tweak here and there.
</P>
<P>
   You can't be altogether down on a comedy in which the athletic
abilities of the cheerleaders tower above those of their suburban
San Diego high school football team, as they do here, or where the
cheerleaders kid their own neuroses by wondering aloud if there's
such a thing as diet Prozac. The film almost trips over a fleeting
desire to be taken seriously when it pits Dunst's mostly white
cheerleading squad against crackerjack African-American rivals, The
Clovers, from East Compton.
</P>
<P>
   Unknown to Dunst's upbeat team captain, her own squad, the
Toros, has been using routines stolen from The Clovers, so when
they compete in the national finals there's a little something
extra at stake. But before you lapse into wondering if ``Bring It
On'' is going for a Rodney King why-can't-we-all-just-get-along?
moment here, let it be made clear that it has something less than
the social relevance and intellectual density of, say, ``Coyote
Ugly.'' Most of the fun in watching ``Bring It On'' lies in
watching Dunst gidget her way through it with squeaky
irrepressibility.
</P>
<P>
   The film is easiest to take when it relaxes into its own
essential vapidity. Its romantic complications aren't exactly a
series of cliffhangers. Most of its bright lines are put into the
mouths of brother-and-sister LA refugees played by Jesse Bradford
and Eliza Dushka, the latter appealingly poised. Ian Roberts
seethes amusingly as a pill-popping, icepick-tongued Bob Fosse
clone hired to choreograph a new routine to replace the one the
cheerleaders didn't know was stolen from The Clovers. The latter
are led in winning style by Gabrielle Union. Her warmth and easy
authority convince you she could win the Olympics, much less a
cheerleading competition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
