<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV27-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAPING JOINTS WILL FIX CRACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August   27, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I plan to paint the rooms in my house, but in an addition 20
years ago, no one taped the drywall joints, so there are vertical
cracks every four feet. How can I fix them?
</P>
<P>
   SARA KILKENNY, Stow, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It seems impossible that someone would not tape joints in a
dry wall (plasterboard). It is sheer negligence.
</P>
<P>
   Several things you can try. Some are better than others.
</P>
<P>
   1. Fill the cracks with a flexible caulking, the only thing that
can be inserted in such a small crack. Press it in with your
fingers. The caulking will expand and contract with the movement of
the wall, and the patch might work for a while. Not the best fix.
</P>
<P>
   2. Paper the walls with Wall-Tex. This is a real cloth, not
paper, that will span the cracks and the cloth itself will resist
cracking. Patterns are limited with Wall-Tex, and since you want to
paint anyway, buy a plain white Wall-Tex, some with a slight pebbly
surface. You can leave it white or paint it. This will work fairly
well.
</P>
<P>
   3. The real fix: Chip out the old compound _ all of it _ over
each joint, then apply new joint compound, then apply a paper tape
and continue plastering over the tape, three thin coats. Anything
fewer than three and the joints will show.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative to the paper tape is to install self-adhesive
nylon mesh tape to the joint where you removed all old compound,
then apply the compound for a smooth finish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Half of my basement floor is dirt, and half is concrete. I'd
like to cover the dirt part with rubber roofing, to keep moisture
out as much as possible. Is that OK? Can I insulate the basement
ceiling? If so, how? Will mold grow under the rubber roofing?
</P>
<P>
   BEVERY PELLEGRINO, Mattapoisett, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. In four words: yes, yes, and probably not. Yes, you can cover
the dirt with rubber roofing, Grace's Ice &AMP; Water Shield, or
polyethylene plastic. It will help keep moisture from coming up
through the dirt. Actually, the rubber roof is overdoing it, but if
you have some with no use for it, go ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you can insulate the basement ceiling. It is a good idea
because your house loses heat through any uninsulated barrier,
including the floor over the basement. To do so, buy 6-inch
fiberglass insulation with paper backing; put the paper up,
touching the floor above, and secure the insulation with steel
hangers, pointed wires stuffed between joists every 24 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Mold might grow under the rubber roofing over the dirt floor, if
water vapor gets caught under the roofing and condenses into water.
This is less likely if you flatten and even the dirt, and put the
roofing material on in full contact with the earth. In other words,
no air pockets. This way, there will be no air space for water
vapor to enter and condense.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to prevent mold under the roofing is to ventilate
the basement, from May 1 to Oct. 31. This will also keep water
vapor from building up in the basement itself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The windows in my 30-year-old split-entry ranch are original
to the house, and are losing a lot of heat each winter. I thought
of replacements, but what kind?
</P>
<P>
   NICOLE WALDRON, York, Maine
</P>
<P>
   A. In many cases the handyman has preached against replacements
for two reasons: The high cost of new windows and the fact that old
windows can be weatherstripped with storm windows added, to achieve
the equivalent of a replacement window at a lower cost.
</P>
<P>
   But hold it, brothers and sisters. Thirty-year-old windows are
probably of pretty low quality. It's amazing how many companies
started making windows of poor quality, then went out of business.
</P>
<P>
   So, to replace your windows, replace only the movable sash, the
part that goes up and down. The frames in your house are probably
still good, certainly good enough to hold new double-glazed sash.
You can get wood sash clad on the outside with vinyl, all-wood
sash, or vinyl. I think the vinyl-clad wood is best. The
replacement sash will cost from $175 to $250 per window. And as a
bonus, you can leave your old storms on or replace them for about
$100 per window.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like to paint the mahogany boards on my deck floor. A
neighbor said you can't paint mahogany because it will peel. What
can I use?
</P>
<P>
   DENISE LEBICA, Plymouth, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Of course paint will peel from mahogany floorboards, just as
it will peel from every kind of wood floorboards. This peeling is
guaranteed on an outdoor surface.
</P>
<P>
   But there is hope: Seal the mahogany, and do it every year, with
a clear masonry or tile sealer. Or, better yet, because it will
last three to five years, coat it with one coat of a
semitransparent oil-based house stain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
