<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-JAYHAWKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JAYHAWKS LIGHTEN UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After years of trying, the Jayhawks finally scored a hit this
year with ``I'm Gonna Make You Love Me,'' a rocking,
mandolin-spiced song that singer Gary Louris originally wrote at 4
o'clock one morning about a lover who had just left him. It later
grew into ``a more universal song about perseverance,'' Louris
says, ``and about someone who is not going to take no for an
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, the song could also describe the Jayhawks, the
Minneapolis rock-and-alternative-country band that has worked hard
for respect and _ if given the right breaks _ might have achieved
stardom long ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Jayhawks have often been called ``the best band you've never
heard of.'' They have built a reputation as critics' favorites who
would land on year-end top-10 album lists, yet elicit puzzled
frowns from the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily, we still remain. And right now, we're focusing on
playing, and we're getting kind of good,'' says Louris, who has a
deadpan Woody Allen air about him. He's been trained never to get
his hopes too high, but he's not about to dismiss the attention
that has come at long last _ a full 15 years after the Jayhawks
formed.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely enough, that attention has been aided by Bob Ezrin _
better known as the producer of classic KISS albums and Pink
Floyd's ``The Wall.'' Ezrin found a way to present the Jayhawks in
a more commercial fashion on the new ``Smile'' CD without erasing
the songwriting subtleties that have been a band trademark on such
CDs as ``Hollywood Town Hall'' (1992) and ``Tomorrow the Green
Grass'' (1994).
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob wasn't familiar with the Jayhawks' history when we first
met, but he later said that we were the weirdest band he ever
worked with,'' says Louris, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   So what attracted the Jayhawks to Ezrin?
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob is a facilitator and energizer who really focused us and
encouraged experimentation and irreverence toward any particular
genre,'' says Louris. ``He gets very involved, and he really drove
certain songs to completion. If he had his way, he'd also be
writing our set lists.''
</P>
<P>
   Formerly known as a cerebral band that could rock but didn't
rock enough, the Jayhawks were determined to take a more
high-energy, rhythmic course this time _ and they knew that was one
of Ezrin's strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``As our drummer (Tim O'Reagan) said, `I'm tired of seeing
people just standing there at our shows. I want to see people
shaking their (butts) at a Jayhawks show,' '' Louris says.
</P>
<P>
   Fans should be able to do that to such new Jayhawks tunes as
``Queen of the World,'' the Beatles-sounding ``Broken Harpoon,''
and the rocking ``(In My) Wildest Dreams.'' There's even some drum
sampling included to push the rhythmic boundaries further.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll never be a drum-machine band,'' says Louris, ``but there
were some sounds that were kind of cool, so we put them in.
Basically, the rhythm section pushed for more rhythm, and they got
it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a welcome turnabout from the last Jayhawks disc, ``Sound of
Lies'' (1997), a dour record written when Louris was going through
a romantic breakup. He is now remarried and has a 1-year-old child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything would be more positive than the `Sound of Lies'
record, though I'm proud of that record,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The irrepressible mood of the new album, however, could just as
easily have been something different, says Louris, referring to how
prolific the Jayhawks were in preparing for it. ``We wrote 50 to 60
songs. We could have picked 13 other songs, and it would be a much
darker record,'' he notes. ``The mood of the record was shaped by
the choice of the songs.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the Jayhawks' mood is more upbeat these days, helped
further by the addition of new member Jen Gunderman on keyboards.
She replaced Karen Grotberg, who completed work on the new album,
then left to be with her baby daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard decision for Karen to leave, but Jen has been
great. I don't know what we'd do without her,'' says Louris.
</P>
<P>
   The Jayhawks have finally earned some breakthrough respect, yet
Louris admits he's been too busy to hear much of the Jayhawks' hit,
``I'm Gonna Make You Love Me'' (which went to No. 3 on the Triple A
charts), on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic, isn't it?'' he says. ``Because I've only heard it
on the radio once. But, hey, we hope it sounds good coming out of
those little speakers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
