<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CREW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BLAND PLOT DRAGS DOWN THIS `CREW' OF WISEGUYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE CREW 
Directed by: Michael Dinner 
Screenplay by: Barry Fanaro 
Starirng: Richard Dreyfuss, Burt Reynolds, Dan Hedaya, Seymour
Cassell, Carrie-Anne Moss, Jennifer Tilly, Lainie Kazan, Miguel
Sandoval, Jeremy Piven 
Running time: 88 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (sexual content, violence and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with the crew in ``The Crew,'' but they're
trapped on a terminally flimsy vessel. Which is another way of
saying that this comedy about geezers with guns largely wastes
Richard Dreyfuss, Burt Reynolds, Dan Hedaya, and Seymour Cassell on
a script that plays as if written on automatic pilot. As retired
mob wiseguys sedately rotting in a down-market Miami Beach hotel
until a rent increase galvanizes them into messing up on a grander
scale than anything they've tried in years, they're asked to supply
inordinate amounts of charm to a mob-cliche-ridden script that
never stays with anything long enough, amusingly enough, or deeply
enough to involve us. Space cowboys they're not.
</P>
<P>
   Their problems begin when a scheme involving an ill-chosen
corpse involves them with a druglord and some unplanned arson. Not
having the sense to lie low when they somehow emerge intact, they
ask for trouble by flaunting fancy cars, Rolexes, and young dates,
much to the consternation of Dreyfuss's ringleader. One reason he's
disinclined to join in the mindless fun is that he has a
sentimental problem. He hasn't seen his daughter for 30 years and
hopes to locate her in Miami, where he has learned she lives. What
he doesn't count on is that she'll be the investigating police
detective assigned to the case in which they become embroiled.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfuss has most of the few snappy lines. Carrie-Anne Moss
brings almost superhuman appeal to the thinly written role of his
long-estranged daughter. Jennifer Tilly enlivens matters as a
prostitute, or, as she prefers to call it, one affiliated with the
leisure profession. A newly svelte Lainie Kazan adds warmth as her
stepmother and sometime target. The old-timers do their best,
especially with their air of swagger as they enter a bingo hall, or
parody the ``GoodFellas'' walking-through-the-Copacabana-kitchen
scene during a deli's early-bird dinner special, or steal Woody
Allen's notion-idea-concept bit from ``Annie Hall.'' Well, they are
thieves, after all. Too bad they couldn't have stolen a better
script. For all its violent gestures, this one screams safety,
safety, safety, never taking anything like a real chance, never
going anywhere unruly or unpredictable in its dogged allegiance to
blandness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
