<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ARGENTINE _ MEXICO CITY - A high-profile Argentine
businessman in Mexico has confessed to police that he is the same
man who is wanted by a Spanish judge on alleged charges of murder,
torture and other crimes during Argentina's ``dirty war'' against
the left in the late 1970s, according to Mexico's Reforma
Newspaper. Although he had changed his name slightly and aged,
Ricardo Miguel Cavallo was accused by Reforma of being a former
intelligence officer back in Argentina who was identified by
victims. Cavallo is the director of a controversial privately-run
national car registry program in Mexico to prevent car thefts.
Ironically, one of the accusations against him is stealing victims'
cars. Spanish lawyers are reportedly demanding that Mexico deport
Cavallo to Spain - a move resembling the attempt to extradite
Chilean dictator Augusto Pinochet to face similar accusations by
the same Spanish judge. Cavallo was detained Thursday by Mexican
police as he was attempting to board a flight from Cancun to
Argentina, where former military officials now enjoy an amnesty
against crimes. (Ferriss, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-NAVY _ MURMANSK, Russia _ Take a look out towards cold
waves of the Barents Sea from this Arctic city, and the problems of
the Russian navy become clear. Dozens of rusting hulks of
submarines and ships sit idle, mothballed by a crippled economy
that has made them _ and the men that serve on the vessels _
increasingly difficult to keep afloat. Unlike in the United States,
where the presence of a naval base is a boon to the local economy,
Murmansk has little to boast about from the base here. The home of
the ill-fated Kursk submarine that sank to the bottom of the
Barents Sea with 118 crew members is a sad example of the problems
and concerns (both within, and without Russia) that surround
Russia's military. Developing. (Coker, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move Thurs., Aug. 24, on the NYT wire.
</P>
