<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   HOUSEWORK-MEN _ Guys, you're busted. Throughout the South,
husbands are claiming to do more housework than wives claim their
husbands are doing. Men took more credit for cooking, laundry and
housework in general than women allowed, a new AJC poll of married
adults found. In the housework category, for instance, 40 percent
of men said they either do it themselves or are an equal partner in
the housework. Meanwhile, just 23 percent of women said men do it
all or equally. Paula Jhung, author of ``How to Avoid Housework,''
isn't surprised. ``I think housework is like sex in that people lie
about it a lot,'' she says. ``Everybody claims they're doing more''
than they are. (Miller, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ Today we'll discuss rockers for a
baby crib, which aren't a big problem, and working with oak, which
can be a very big problem. Doug Williams wrote to say that ``We
have an antique baby crib from which the rockers were removed
before it came to us. ``I wish to build rockers for it. ``What are
your thoughts on the correct size and `rocking capability' for
these rockers?'' Williams went on to provide the dimensions of the
cradle and speculate on federal rules governing crib rockers.
Rockers on cribs, and rocking chairs for that matter, are really a
matter of aesthetics rather than any kind of mathematical formula.
(Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
