<HEADLINE>
CBS WINS LOOT IN `SURVIVOR' RATINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buoyed by bubbling water cooler chatter and intense media
attention, CBS's ``Survivor'' finale on Wednesday night shattered
the summer doldrums by reaching the kind of mass audience that has
nearly vanished in today's 100-channel TV universe.
</P>
<P>
   With network spokesman Chris Ender declaring Wednesday ``a
magical night at CBS,'' the final ``Survivor'' episode attracted
nearly 52 million viewers, making it the second most popular TV
broadcast of the year behind the Super Bowl. While those ratings
may not match such indelible television moments as the final MASH
show in 1983, the 1980 ``Who Shot J.R.?'' episode of Dallas or even
the Beatles original 1964 visit to ``The Ed Sullivan Show,'' they
reflect a show that tapped into the zeitgeist in way that no one
could have predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``For these days, that's awful good,'' says TV historian Alex
McNeil, of the ratings. ``It was a real phenomenon and good for the
medium of television, (which) can still galvanize and still attract
big audiences,''
</P>
<P>
   Displaying his trademark cockiness, winner Richard Hatch,
speaking to journalists Thursday, boasted that ``I did tell CBS
that I thought it was going to be their highest rated show ever.''
</P>
<P>
   As a national story, the voting on Pulau Tiga island has proved
far more riveting than the election of a new president. Wednesday's
52 million ``Survivor'' viewers dwarfed the broadcast television
audience for this summer's national conventions when Al Gore and
George Bush each attracted around 18 million viewers for their
crucial acceptance speeches.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, CNN's political debate show ``Crossfire'' examined
that very issue, exploring why, in the words of co-host Mary
Matalin, ``more people are interested in voting people off the
island than in voting for president of the United States.'' One
guest, ``Politically Correct'' executive producer Jerry Nachman
suggested that there was a better story unfolding on the island
than in the convention halls.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Survivor' was well conceived and well executed and it does
say something basic about human nature, the instinct for the self
as opposed to the instinct for the group,'' says McNeil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it captures a lot of things in the culture,'' adds
critic Steven Stark. ``In a Darwinian culture, it's a Darwinian
show.'' Comparing its basic appeal to that of ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire?'' Stark says, ``you can see ordinary people like
yourselves trying to win money.''
</P>
<P>
   Another key factor in Wednesday night's success was the airtight
silence that hid the identity of the winner in the months since the
taping ended. Despite feverish Internet rumors and one security
company's reported attempt to identify the winner through voice
analysis, Hatch's victory came as a shock to many viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really had no interest in'' divulging the outcome, Hatch
said Thursday, admitting that ``he blatantly, outright lied'' about
the results to his son and sister. CBS spokesman Ender says
contestants had to sign confidentiality agreements stipulating that
any leaking would cause them to forfeit their winnings. But he says
the secret stayed safe largely due to ``a little bit of good
planning and a little bit of luck...They (the contestants) wanted
to be part of something successful.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time, Wednesday's episode rolled around, that success had
become a media obsession. ``Survivor's'' handful of remaining
competitors graced the Aug. 28 covers of Newsweek, Us Weekly, and
People magazines. On the morning of the show, pop-culture savvy Wed
USA Today led the paper with a story teasing the finale and
featured stories about the show on the first page of three of its
section.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment Weekly produced four dummy covers with each
finalist depicted as the winner, pushed back its deadline and then
rushed its ``All Hail The Champ: The Ultra-Conniving, Buck-Naked
Corporate Trainer Richard'' version out to newsstands. Thursday
morning, the ubiquitous photo of a bug-eyed Hatch reacting to his
$1 million victory even graced the front page of The New York Times
next to the headline, ``Machievelli, on a Desert Isle, Meets TV's
Reality. Unreal.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, TV's reality also means corporate synergy and there
was plenty of ``Survivor'' success to pass around. After the
two-hour Wednesday night closing episode, CBS ``Early Morning''
host Bryant Gumbel -- whose own sagging ratings have been lifted by
the show's coattails -- hosted a ``Survivor'' reunion that
attracted almost 39 million viewers..
</P>
<P>
   At one point Gumbel asked Hatch why he seemed to be an unpopular
winner with the public. ``I think it just must be the press,'' he
replied, taking a final chomp out of the hand that turned him into
a household word.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
