<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2103 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-STEAL-BOS &LR;      08-25 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-STEAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOFFMAN'S TALE NEVER GETS OFF THE GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
STEAL THIS MOVIE! 
Directed by: Robert Greenwald 
Screenplay by: Bruce Graham (based on Abbie and Anita Hoffman's
``To America with Love: Letters from the Underground'' and Marty
Jezer's ``Abbie Hoffman: American Rebel'' 
Starring: Vincent D'Onofrio, Janeane Garofalo, Jeanne Tripplehorn,
Kevin Pollak, Donal Logue, Kevin Corrigan 
Running time: 110 minutes 
Rated: R (language, drug content and some nudity) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before there were yuppies, there were Yippies. ``Steal This
Movie!'' is an earnest but ultimately scattered effort to put
Yippie radical Abbie Hoffman's best foot posthumously forward. The
film (playing off the title of Hoffman's brassy manifesto, ``Steal
This Book!'') plunges us back into the counterculture ferment of
the late '60s and early '70s, convincing us that the government
could have taught _ and frequently did teach _ any and all would-be
revolutionaries, including Hoffman's Yippies, a thing or two about
illegal behavior. It gets off to a nice bloody tongue-in-cheek
start when Hoffman, after being beat up by two angry men in the
East Village, is told to call the cops. ``They are the cops,'' he
replies.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent D'Onofrio throws himself at the central role with his
customary dedication and gusto. Still, ``Steal This Movie!'' is
uneven, as bland and choppy as it is rambunctious, perhaps
inevitably so, given the necessarily contradictory perceptions of a
man who mocked the American flag in attacking government mockery of
the American Constitution. Hoffman was in the grand tradition of
American dissenters, opposing the Vietnam War with hormonal
exuberance, wit, and a genius for marketing. Packaging himself as
Uncle Sam on acid, he wrapped himself and his rude antics in the
Stars and Stripes and kicked street theater into a superheated
orbit.
</P>
<P>
   With Jerry Rubin, he was miles ahead of most politicians of his
time in knowing just how to plug into the electronic media. When he
accused the FBI of persecuting him, he wasn't delusional, although
his drug habit didn't help. Neither did the effects of the bipolar
disorder from which he suffered. His activism, which began with
voter registration in the South, led him to go underground, where,
after leaving his wife and child behind, he began a relationship
with a new woman and six years later under an assumed name
championed a new cause _ fighting unrestricted freighter travel on
the St. Lawrence River.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman is not an easy figure to get a handle on dramatically,
which perhaps explains why he seems to elude both the film and
D'Onofrio. The latter is as versatile an actor as America has,
immersing himself so totally in a wide variety of characters that
he never has, and never will, take on the big star persona. He's
simply too good an actor. And yet his work here seems uneasy,
making us feel for the first time that he hasn't quite nailed the
ringmaster of the circus who transformed political protest for a
few years, while struggling with his own messed-up family life and
trying to keep his idealistic impulses alive.
</P>
<P>
   The film suffers from having to crowd a lot of information into
its less than two-hour running time. Much of it unfurls in
superficial TV biopic style as a journalist in 1977 interviews
Hoffman and resorts to frequent flashbacks. These are either shrill
or prosaic. Never do they convey a sense of heat or giddiness, or
stride purposefully off in a definite direction. Better dramaturgy
than this is required to give us Hoffman's zigzag life, including
its personal dimension, as he woos and wows Janeane Garofalo with
his rock-star charisma, then plummets downhill under the twin
pressures of radical factionalism and government persecution, but
not before showering money down upon the New York Stock Exchange
and ridiculing the judge and the police at his trial for disrupting
the 1968 Democratic convention in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo's ability to project wryness and toughness indicate the
key to Emily Hoffman's survival in the face of adversity until she
died of breast cancer in 1998, nine years after Hoffman himself
died of a drug overdose. Jeanne Tripplehorn does what she can with
the limited role of Johanna Lawrenson, who sustained Hoffman during
his underground period. The film fails to address the subordinate
position of women in the radical movement, or the schisms among the
radicals. Nor does it have time to present the other radicals in
anything more than the most cursory terms. And its flatfooted
device of having a journalist interview Hoffman in 1977 to provide
a framing device for most of the historical flashbacks plays as if
it should have been buried after ``Citizen Kane.''
</P>
<P>
   The film can't even achieve much liftoff after Hoffman's
longtime lawyer, Gerry Lefcourt (one of the film's producers,
played onscreen by Kevin Pollak), uses the Freedom of Information
Act to point the journalist to the FBI files detailing the
Nixon-Hoover dirty tricks effort to discredit left-wing dissenters.
The belated bonding between Hoffman and his estranged son has a
cosmeticized feel. So does the saintly truce between the two women
in his life. It's too bad ``Steal This Movie!'' comes up so short.
We're not likely to get another telling of this story of an
important player in an important time. Shortcomings and all, it's
worth circulating, if only to inject a few images of idealistic
activism _ undeniably one of its components _ into today's
depressingly mercenary and mostly devitalized socio-political mix.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
