<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2109 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-MOLLY-BOS &LR;      08-25 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MOLLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD GOLLY, MISS MOLLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Little girls with big voices have become as common as candy in
pop music. Most of them, however, don't have a kangaroo for a
drummer. Or a pink limousine with a built-in skate ramp. Or a hit
single about wetting the bed.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Molly O!, 8-year-old international singing sensation and
star of the new Kids' WB cartoon ``Generation O!,'' which premieres
Saturday at 10:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Molly's timing is, to say the least, uncanny. One might
logically assume that the current tidal wave of young female pop
stars (Britney, Christina, Mandy, Jessica) _ or more accurately,
the massive, school-aged fan base they've created _ was inspiration
for an animated series aimed at 6-to-11-year-olds that features a
famous singer who's in third grade.
</P>
<P>
   But when children's-book author Jim Proimos, writer/director Tim
Newman (singer-songwriter Randy Newman's cousin), and writer David
Hale (who moonlights as a singer for the Blind Lemon Peel Blues
Band) dreamed up the idea several years ago, Britney wasn't even a
blip on the pop music radar. Rather, kids' music consisted of a
milquetoast folk singer, a purple dinosaur, and four fluffy Brits.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time we started talking, music for kids was Raffi or
Barney or the Spice Girls,'' says executive producer Ken Olshansky.
``There was really no smart, well-produced music that spoke to
things kids cared about. All three of the guys who came to us with
the idea have daughters, and music was central to where the show
came from.''
</P>
<P>
   Initial response to the Generation O! concept was the same
across the board: `` `If you turn this character into a boy, we can
sell it,' '' recalls co-creator David Hale, whose daughter Isabel
was the inspiration for Molly O!. ``The rule of thumb in children's
television has always been girls will watch boys, but boys won't
watch girls. We decided we wouldn't waver, though. Boys already
have that smugness, that noblesse oblige. This is a real female
empowerment thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Molly O! is about as far from Britney et al. as one
more girl with a microphone and a pop song can be. Neither blonde
bombshell nor demi-diva, Molly rocks out _ that's right, she rocks
_ in baggy shorts and T-shirts. She bums out about her bedtime and
bickers with her annoying brother. She dutifully obeys her dad, who
works in a cheese factory, and respects her unflappable mom, deputy
fire chief in imaginary suburban Appleton.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps what really sets Molly apart is the fact that unlike her
real-life contemporaries, she writes her own songs _ with a little
help from the Boston-based band Letters To Cleo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah, I'm totally in touch with my inner 8-year-old,''
says Kay Hanley of Quincy, who sings the part of Molly and co-wrote
_ with her husband, guitarist Michael Eisenstein _ the songs for
``Generation O!'' ``Not to be mushy or gooey or method-actory, but
this winter I felt like I was Molly. I just get her. When I was her
age I always wanted to be the center of attention. I was always a
spotlight hogger.''
</P>
<P>
   Songs like ``Girls Rule, Boys Drool'' and ``Damp Sheets''
contain ``some of the best lyrics I've ever written,'' says Hanley,
and she's dead serious. ``They needed to be clever and smart, but
the kind of smart thing that an 8-year-old might say.''
</P>
<P>
   To the producers' credit, they decided against casting a band
composed of session musicians and set out to find a real singer to
bring the sound of Generation O! (also the name of Molly's group)
to life in an organic, vibrant way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a really good list of young women,'' says Olshansky.
``We looked at Garrison Starr, Juliana Hatfield, Maria McKee
(formerly of the band Lone Justice). We needed someone who could
nail the emotional level of an 8-year-old, who wouldn't play by
other people's rules, who's fresh. We didn't want imitation.
Letters To Cleo took smart songwriting and applied it to kids'
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   At the suggestion of his daughter Annie _ a longtime Letters To
Cleo fan _ co-creator Proimos contacted the band during the summer
of 1998, when they happened to be in LA working on music for the
film ``Ten Things I Hate About You.'' Hanley says their interest
was piqued almost immediately. ``They didn't want it to be a
cartoony, jingle-writer version of a band. So I wrote some lyrics
for a theme song. Who knew what would come of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to the summer of 1999. Hanley was 8 1/2 months
pregnant with her daughter, Zoe (now 14 months), when she got the
call from her manager. ``I had to write, record, mix, and mail the
first song in four days. The whole thing has been very methodical,
and it's very different for us to work like that. But we busted it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the songs are true-blue pop-rock, drenched in both
youthful exuberance and rebellious bluster. In addition to the
impossibly peppy ``Generation O!'' theme, Hanley and Eisenstein
have written 13 songs that are integrated into the story line of
each of the season's episodes. (Letters to Cleo recently broke up,
but Hanley says if the show is picked up for a second season the
band will reunite for the project.) Over jangly guitars and
smashing drums in ``Strange World,'' Molly grapples with her
confusion over ``when to stand out, when to blend in'' a conundrum
that strikes to the heart of a classic, age-appropriate issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are being spoken to better now, but there's not a lot of
content in a song like ('N Sync's) `Bye Bye Bye,' '' Olshansky
points out. Adds Hanley: ``There's nothing sexualized about Molly.
It's a whole different message.'' Timely and right-minded as the
concept may be, one has to wonder if a generation that's already
been indoctrinated into the sexually charged, pristinely packaged
world of today's young pop stars will find it hard to relate to a
middle-class Midwestern girl like Molly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a bit of a concern,'' Olshansky concedes. ``Aspiration
is very important for kids. They want to be something bigger than
what they are, and the other stars are so packaged there could be a
disconnect there. But I think the combination of her being a star
and being accessible is appealing. You could aspire to be like
Molly, but you already are like Molly, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The comedy in the series comes when the worlds collide. Molly O!
may be the voice of a generation, but her mom insists on picking
her up at 10 sharp after a concert, and won't let her get her ears
pierced 'til she's older. It's juxtapositions like that, believes
Hale, that will appeal to kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing we love about Molly is that she's the biggest star
in the world, but in Appleton they think she's an odd little girl.
She's not as well-liked on the playground as she is as Wembley
Stadium or Madison Square Garden,'' Hale explains. ``Molly's
offbeat. Like other kids, she can't express it in words. But when
she sings it, everybody listens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
