<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HELEN-THOMAS (Washington) _If Vice President Al Gore and Texas
Governor George W. Bush want to grab the attention of their
audiences, they would do well to tear a page out of a new book by
Liz Carpenter titled: ``Start with A Laugh.'' Carpenter, one of
President Lyndon B. Johnson's speechwriters, offers her sure-fire
formula: ``Start with a laugh, put the meat in the middle and wave
the flag at the end.'' By HELEN THOMAS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YOUTH-VOTE (Washington) _ In a sweeping effort to energize 18-
to-21-year-old voters, national youth and civic groups are
organizing mock elections and debates moderated by young adults.
These groups are mounting a massive campaign, alarmed by a trend
that shows young people are increasingly steering clear of the
voting booth. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Much of Al Gore's strong populist
appeals to the poor and the middle class in his acceptance speech
and his orations on the campaign trail originated with Franklin
Roosevelt's New Deal and Lyndon Johnson's Great Society. By ROBERT
E. THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
