<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2128 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-MARYBAKEREDDY-EXHIBIT     08-25 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARYBAKEREDDY-EXHIBIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXHIBIT REVEALS FEMALE RELIGIOUS LEADER'S POWER IN A POWERLESS AGE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ She was a single parent and a homeless woman with
health problems.
</P>
<P>
   She was an author, a journalist, a newspaper founder, a healer
and a spiritual leader who still has followers 100 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Baker Eddy, founder of the Church of Christ, Scientist in
the late 1800s, had a life that is a lesson in overcoming hardship.
</P>
<P>
   An exhibit on her accomplishments is on display through Sept. 28
on the third floor of the J. Erik Jonsson Central Library in
Dallas. A separate exhibit on Eddy is planned for the Dallas
Women's Museum, which will open in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have many women role models that are as
multidimensional as Mary Baker Eddy,'' says Virgina Harris,
chairman of the Christian Science board, based in Boston. ``She was
able to break through the challenges and limitations placed on
women in the 19th century.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddy relied on inspiration from the Bible and on prayer to aid
in spiritual and physical healing, one of the early American
examples of the quest to connect the mind and body with the soul.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas library exhibit features newspaper clippings,
photographs, videos and audiotapes describing how Eddy founded
Christian Science, a church based on physical and spiritual healing
through prayer. Audiotapes include testimonials of people who have
turned their lives around through prayer.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit is not funded by the church. It is a project of The
Writings of Mary Baker Eddy, a nonprofit group that circulates
Eddy's works and is led by Harris, who also leads the church's
board.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exhibit is not so much about the theological side of her
life, although she is a spiritual leader,'' Harris says. ``She is
an author, a health reformer, a journalist. Her life was so
large.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddy, born in 1821, suffered as a child from what is remembered
in history as ``a spinal malady,'' which was compounded when she
injured herself in a fall when she was 45. She turned to the New
Testament of the Bible, and said she felt she learned lessons about
the healing powers of Jesus. Although she had little formal
education, she spent years working on a philosophy, which was first
published in 1875. Science and Health With Key to the Scriptures is
regarded by her followers as divinely inspired and it serves them,
along with the Bible, as a Scripture of the Christian Science
faith. She founded The Christian Science Monitor, a newspaper in
its 90th year of publishing. She died in 1910.
</P>
<P>
   Eddy accomplished all this without being able to vote, without
being able to own property and after her child was taken away from
her _ against her will _ in the years before custody laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas library, 1515 Young St. at Ervay Street, is open 1-5
p.m. Sundays,
</P>
<P>
   9 a.m.-9 p.m. Mondays-Thursdays, and 9 a.m.-5 p.m. Fridays and
Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
