<SLUG> BC-CHINA-RELIGION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN EVANGELISTS ARRESTED IN CHINA RELEASED 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beijing _ Three American evangelists who were detained in
central China on Wednesday along with a large group of Chinese
Protestants were released Friday afternoon, Chinese officials told
the U.S. Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Henan province, where the arrests were made, told a
U.S. diplomat that the three U.S. citizens had been detained for
``activities incompatible with the tourist status under which they
entered China,'' the embassy said.
</P>
<P>
   All three Americans were born in Taiwan and belong to a
California church that sends members on brief missions into China
to lend moral and financial support to the so-called house
churches. These are fervent Protestant groups that refuse to accept
the leadership of the government-sponsored church, and their
members often suffer police harassment and detention.
</P>
<P>
   The three were detained along with nearly 130 Chinese followers
of the China Fangcheng Church, a large Protestant group whose
leaders were sent to labor camps last year.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night the whereabouts of the released missionaries was
unclear, but in similar cases in the past, people declared in
violation of their visas have been required to leave the country
quickly. Chinese officials have not discussed whether any of the
detained Chinese believers would face criminal charges or
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   The three Americans belong to the Chinese Vineyard Church
Fellowship in Los Altos, Calif., and were identified by the group
as Henry Chu, 36; his wife, Sandy Lin, 28; and Patricia Lan, 25.
They had traveled to China on Aug. 13 for a two-week mission.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign missionary work is illegal in China, though informal
outside aid to churches is sometimes tolerated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
