<HEADER>
A2136 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-AIR-FORCE-RECRUITING-     08-25 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-FORCE-RECRUITING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AIR FORCE IS COMING TO A MOVIE THEATER NEAR YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The Air Force began running Hollywood-produced
advertisements at movie theaters Friday as part of its ongoing
strategy to boost recruitment.
</P>
<P>
   Moviegoers can see the first Air Force advertisements directed
by Academy Award-winner Bob Richardson, the photography chief of
``JFK'' and ``Wag the Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   The yearlong, $28.2 million ad campaign at National Cinema
Network and AMC theaters around the country is a new twist for a
service with recruiting and retention problems.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of spots that accent the Air Force's benefits, the six
new 30- to 60-second commercials, which also are to air on prime
time television starting Sept. 2, appeal to nobler qualities _
among them camaraderie, service to the nation and self-sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   One advertisement depicts an F-15 Eagle and F-16 Fighting Falcon
in a mock dogfight. Another spot shows a mother reading to her
three children, while a woman's voice in the background sings,
``Guardian angels will attend thee all through the night.'' The
camera then zooms out from a cockpit to reveal an F-117 stealth
fighter flying high in the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half a million remarkable individuals serving their country,
and they all believe they have the best job in the world,'' the Air
Force's top enlisted man, Chief Master Sergeant of the Air Force
Jim Finch, says as one spot closes. ``Join us.''
</P>
<P>
   Air Force Secretary F. Whitten Peters and Undersecretary Carol
DiBattiste said the ads are a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They appeal to patriotism, they appeal to service before self
and they appeal to people wanting to be part of a team, and the
music,'' DiBattiste said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these are thematically consistent, and they match what
our marketing research tells us we need to do to get our message
out to the American public,'' Peters said.
</P>
<P>
   If the message is new, the airing of advertising on television
is not. The Air Force spent $74 million in 1999 on its first paid
TV ad campaign and earmarked $54 million for this year.
</P>
<P>
   The switch from free public service ads that had been run in the
past to paid advertising came amid the Air Force's first recruiting
shortfall since 1979, a stunning development that prompted the
formation of new strategies to reverse the service's sagging
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has funneled its cash into TV, radio and print
advertising, billboards, a revamped Web site and a roving 18-wheel
truck with simulators dubbed the ``Air Force Experience,'' as well
as the spots running in movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   But it also expanded bonuses last year for many career fields,
with payouts ranging from $1,000 to $12,000, and added hundreds of
new recruiters.
</P>
<P>
   The armed forces are competing with a strong job market and have
resorted to advertising, bonuses and other incentive to attract
qualified young people. The services also are fighting to keep
those in the enlisted and officer ranks from leaving for
higher-paying jobs in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new advertisements also unveil the Air Force's first logo, a
device featuring stark diagonal bands resembling folded wings
lifted behind a star with the message, ``No one comes close.''
</P>
<P>
   The logo aims to raise the Air Force's profile while capturing
its colorful history and traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the service has never had a symbol as have other
services.
</P>
<P>
   Siegelgale, a New York ad firm, developed both the spots and the
logo, while Dallas-based Bozell-Kamstra bought the air time. The
work of Richardson, who won his Oscar as photography chief of the
controversial ``JFK'' and crafted the advertising spots, won
DiBattiste's approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see it, I am very proud,'' she said. ``I got the chills
when I watched every single one of those.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Sig Christenson by e-mail at sigc(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
