<SLUG> BC-RUNNING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUNNING FOR DOLLARS
</HEADLINE>
  Training goes smoothly for fund-raising runner 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   His once-sore knee nearly back to 100 percent, Valencia
marathoner- in-training Eric Heilbrun continues to rack up the
miles on the way to his goal: the Honolulu Marathon in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went 10 miles (last) Saturday,'' said Heilbrun, a sales
agent with the Southern California Automobile Club. ``Then I did a
10K on the weekend, just for the heck of it.''
</P>
<P>
   That 10K was to benefit the Exceptional Children's Foundation _
dubbed the ``Home Run'' because of its proximity to Dodger Stadium.
For his pains, Heilbrun came out with a ribbon that reads ``I
conquered Cardiac Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That second mile is all up hill,'' says Heilbrun. ``Brutal.''
</P>
<P>
   Formerly a light exerciser who used to play tennis, Heilbrun is
getting himself into shape with the Joints in Motion team of the
Southern California Arthritis Foundation. In addition to getting
into marathon running shape over five months of training, each team
member has to raise $3,100 for the foundation. The Joints in Motion
provides the professional coaching and training.
</P>
<P>
   Heilbrun recently sent out his first batch of 125 pledge request
letters. After gauging the response, he plans to send out up to 100
more. Although team members have until Nov. 15, Heilbrun plans to
have his fund-raising completed by Oct. 1 so he can concentrate on
the training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might actually start mailing to some of the businesses,
too,'' he says. ``All it takes is one guy with deep pockets to say,
`You know what? Here's $500.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not terribly concerned about making the goal yet. In
another month, if I'm not doing as well, I'll start getting
aggressive, knocking on doors and making phone calls.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he'll keep running _ 10 miles one day, six the
next, eight the week before by a man-made lake near Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm finding I'm not the fastest guy around,'' says Heilbrun.
``But even after 10 miles, I still feel fine. Before, the thought
of running 10 miles would have inspired the same fear as running a
marathon _ the thought that if I tried to run a marathon, I'd kill
myself. It's not the case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 1452EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
