<HEADER>
A2195 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-RAC-TRAVERS-HNS &LR;      08-25 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-TRAVERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ALL EYES ON DIXIE UNION AT MIDSUMMER DEBRY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TIM WILKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Dick Mandella has been a thoroughbred
horse trainer since 1974. In all those years he had never entered a
horse to run in the prestigious and tradition-soaked Travers
Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   And when Mandella makes his maiden Travers voyage Saturday, he
won't have just any horse. He will have the horse many think will
win the 131st running of the Midsummer Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Mandella's Dixie Union was installed as the 5-2 morning-line
favorite at Thursday morning's draw, which was held at the At The
Rail Pavilion in Saratoga Springs. Mandella, whose home base is in
California, has been in Saratoga with Dixie Union since the colt
won the Haskell Invitational at Monmouth Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like being the favorite,'' Mandella said after the draw. ``I
wish all the other horses weren't here. I would just as soon be
able to have him gallop around the track by himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, he won't get that wish. Eight other colts will test Dixie
Union in what many think is a wide-open race.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee Brew, who was third in the Haskell, has been made the
3-1 second choice and Unshaded, the third-place finisher in the Jim
Dandy, is third choice at 7-2. Also in the field are Curule (6-1),
Albert the Great (8-1), Postponed (8-1), Commendable (12-1),
Impeachment (12-1) and Country Coast (30-1).
</P>
<P>
   Dixie Union earned the favorite's status after the impressive
score in the Haskell. He is the only colt in the Travers field who
is coming into this race off a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Mandella had hoped Dixie Union would be a force in the Triple
Crown this past spring but a knee injury forced him to skip the
Classics. Now it appears he is attempting to make up for lost time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a small chance we could have made it to the Triple
Crown but not a good one,'' Mandella said. ``You always have to
worry when you stop on them and work on an ailment. You don't know
if they will come back the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixie Union has been first or second in all four of his starts
thisyear and one of his losses came by a neck. He has six wins in
his career; no one else in the field has more than four.
</P>
<P>
   However, no one else in the field is going to ship the Travers
Trophy to the stakes barn, where Mandella and Dixie Union have been
holed up the last few weeks. There are those in here that think
they have more than a big chance.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Nafzger, the trainer of Unshaded, is confident after seeing
his colt finish third in the Jim Dandy. Scotty Schulhofer will
saddle Postponed (fourth in the Jim Dandy). Earlier in the month,
Schulhofer had said he was not going to run in the Travers.
</P>
<P>
   However, after reassessing the Jim Dandy, he changed his mind.
It also didn't hurt that Preakness winner Red Bullet and Jim Dandy
winner Graeme Hall are going to sit this race out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came out of the Jim Dandy in good order,'' Schulhofer said.
``Some of those defections helped make our decision. I think this
is a wide-open race and I hope that he is the best horse. I think
he should run really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Zito, who trains Albert the Great, and Todd Pletcher, the
conditioner of Impeachment, make the same types of comments. The
only true outsider in the field would appear to be Country Coast,
who comes into this off a second-place finish in an allowance race.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Amoss, Country Coast's trainer, wasn't thinking Travers
Thursday morning. When the draw for the race was being held, he was
said to be fishing.
</P>
<P>
   The main speed horse in the field is Albert the Great, who had
won four straight races before falling apart and finishing last in
the Jim Dandy. He drew the nine hole and will start from the far
outside.
</P>
<P>
   That led to speculation that Zito would have to gun the colt
straight to the lead to avoid being strung out wide on the first
turn. Zito was not at the draw but said later that was not
necessarily what he is going to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to do anything,'' Zito said. ``This is America,
isn't it? This isn't a totalitarian government, is it? No, I really
don't know about the post. We'll just have to see what happens. Who
knows? It could hurt him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
