<HEADER>
A2207 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-SURVIVOR-COLUM     08-25 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-SURVIVOR-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'SURVIVOR' SATURATION HAS JUST BEGUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Thursday, Aug. 24, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Watching these 16 idiots whittle themselves down to one
tiki-torch-bearing winner is going to be great lazy-mind summer
entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   _ My take on ``Survivor'' after the first episode aired.
</P>
<P>
   Memo to my fellow ``Survivor'' viewers: Our addiction to the
best game show since ``Beat the Clock'' does not end with Richard's
surprise triumph.
</P>
<P>
   I know we have the ``Survivor'' book, the ``Survivor'' board
game, the four finalists doing a ``Got Milk?'' ad campaign, all the
contestants doing a special ``Top 10'' list for Letterman, Sean's
acting career, Richard's radio gig, the second season and maybe
Jenna posing for Playboy to look forward to, but that's not enough,
is it?
</P>
<P>
   So here's what CBS should do. Load all 16 ``Survivor'' stalwarts
onto a bus, take 'em to the ``Big Brother'' house, kick out those
boring losers and lock in Rudy, Richard, Susan, Kelly and Co. for
the next 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   To further spice it up, let Jordan the stripper from ``Big
Brother'' come back to the compound and do that trampoline routine
we were promised but never got to see.
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine the possible dramas that could unfold if the
``Survivor'' gang took over that house?
</P>
<P>
   Crusty old Rudy would finally snap at Machiavellian Richard and
would enlist Susan to help him re-enact a scene out of ``A Few Good
Men'' _ a code red-type of hazing ritual on a nude-and-sleeping
Rich as the night vision cameras rolled.
</P>
<P>
   Colleen and Greg would be like Sandy and Danny in ``Grease,''
reunited after a near-romance bloomed at the beach. (``He got
friendly, holding my hand'' _ ``Well she got friendly down in the
sand!'')
</P>
<P>
   Sonja could torture everyone with a nightly ukulele jam session.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Stacey Stillman, last seen snarling at Susan, ``You
switched your vote!'' as her torch was being extinguished, could
settle the score with her double-crossing former pal.
</P>
<P>
   They've got a pool, so the curiously incompetent YMCA coach
Gervase could learn to swim.
</P>
<P>
   It would be magic, my friends. Start that e-mail campaign to CBS
president Les Moonves immediately.
</P>
<P>
   I'll not apologize for buying into the ``Survivor'' hype. What,
we should yearn for the golden days of summer TV when reruns, bad
variety shows and moldy pilot episodes ruled the airwaves?
</P>
<P>
   Of course ``Survivor'' is an exploitative exercise in national
voyeurism _ but it's also a brilliantly conceived, flawlessly
executed petri dish, a masterpiece of casting and editing that
reveals much about who we are and how we live at the outset of the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
   The petty bickering, the manipulative machinations, the
flirtations, the tears, the bitching about who's carrying the
workload, the high-fiving moments of triumph, the silly fits of
laughter _ all these vignettes are reminiscent of what takes place
in any work environment, or among any extended group of friends.
</P>
<P>
   Or within any family, come to think of it.
</P>
<P>
   I think most of us figured ``Survivor'' would be a blend of
``The Real World'' and one of those extreme sports shows. We'd see
impressive physical specimens climbing trees and hunting wild boar
and swimming with sharks as they competed with one another but also
worked together to make it through another challenging day on the
island.
</P>
<P>
   Well. There was a little bit of that, but we also had fat naked
guy Rich and vomiting layabout Ramona and shaved-chest Sean and
lazy-ass Gervase and trash-talking Susan and Bible-thumping Dirk
and cute little Colleen and crabby old Rudy, who's just this side
of John Rocker with some of his cracks. (In the latest Newsweek,
which has the four finalists on the cover instead of the Democratic
National Convention or the Russian submarine, Rudy says,
``Personally, I don't hang around lesbians, queers, hippies,
doctors and lawyers ...'')
</P>
<P>
   These people aren't triathletes, they're the descendants of the
castaways on ``Gilligan's Island'' crossed with the cast of ``Days
of Our Lives.''
</P>
<P>
   In less than three months, consider the catch phrases and quotes
from ``Survivor'' that have wormed their way into the national
lexicon.
</P>
<P>
   Immunity challenge. ``I liked him before I knew he was a
queer.'' Tribal council. ``Women are the stupidest thing on the
planet next to cows.'' The alliance. ``On the island, fire is a
sign of life.'' Pagong and Tagi. ``The tribe has spoken.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if you hated the show or never tuned in, you cannot deny
its impact on the popular culture. Some day, all the retrospectives
and books chronicling the '00s will include ``Survivor'' as one of
the first major pop events of the decade. God knows where we go
from here.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the co-host of ``Ebert &AMP; Roeper &AMP; the
Movies.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
