<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2218 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-NAVY-$ADV26-1s     08-25 1536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-NAVY-$ADV26-1stLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUB TRAGEDY SYMBOLIZES RUSSIA'S RUSTING NAVY
 &HT;    Eds: Deletes 8th graf which began ``All these scenarios. . .''
 &HT;    Note: Graphic material is at the bottom of this story
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, August 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MURMANSK, Russia _ As visitors navigate the waterway snaking out
of Murmansk harbor, past rusted hulls of fishing vessels and cargo
ships filled with nuclear waste, the sinking of the Russian
submarine Kursk appears less a tragic accident than a disaster
waiting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   As the sound heads north along the Kola Inlet, toward the
Severomorsk headquarters for the Russian navy's Northern Fleet,
15-foot concrete walls topped with barbed wire rise ominously along
the waterway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rusted military ships are behind those walls. They think we
don't know about them but we all do,'' said Nikolai Semenov, a
sailor who moonlights as a fisherman so he can feed his wife and
three children.
</P>
<P>
   The corroding carcasses of a once-proud fleet are an apt
metaphor for Russia's navy, which now can barely feed or pay its
sailors. Patrols have been cut by 70 percent and the post-Soviet
economic collapse has forced the top brass to mothball
three-fourths of the submarine fleet in this Arctic port, where
nearly all of its 400,000 people rely on the military for their
livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin finally acknowledged the desperate state of the navy
and other branches of the armed forces _ though not in time for the
Kursk's 118 crew members who perished. On Aug. 11, one day before
the disaster, President Vladimir Putin told a Russian Security
Council meeting it was time to reform a military in which ''pilots
don't fly and sailors barely go to sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Failure to quickly reform poses not only a danger for Russians,
as the Kursk disaster shows, but to the United States and other
NATO countries as well. Leaking reactors on scrapped ships and
submarines imperil the world's most heavily fished sea. Poorly
trained and equipped Russian crews increase the possibility of more
disasters at sea, maybe next time involving U.S. servicemen.
Experts say there are risks of poorly-supervised or
badly-maintained Russian subs causing a collision with a U.S.
vessel in heavily-trafficked submarine channels. Likely to foot the
bill for such a catastrophe would be the U.S. taxpayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of the navy poses a threat, not only to Russians but
(other) countries,'' said Pavel Flegenhauer, an independent
military analyst based in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Soviet leaders viewed the remote, icy Barents Sea as a strategic
lake to base enough nuclear submarines to threaten Canada and the
United States with fiery destruction from the top of the globe. The
Arctic submarine force was Moscow's insurance in case its other
nuclear forces were knocked out in the early stages of missile
exchange with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   This strategy has survived the collapse of the Soviet Union, but
the funds to sustain the strategy have not. Russia's defense budget
plummeted in the mid-1990s, with the navy receiving only a fraction
of overall military spending, according to Dmitry Litovkin, a
retired navy captain.
</P>
<P>
   Litovkin, a former submariner, said the Northern Fleet's subs
did not receive maintenance in 1999, as admirals diverted most of
their budget to a new nuclear-powered battleship, Peter the Great.
</P>
<P>
   Although the causes of the Kursk's sinking are not known,
neglect may end up topping the list. Several reports have claimed
that the submarine left port without vital batteries to power
backup air-purifying and light systems in an emergency. Russian
newspapers, citing anonymous military sources, said emergency exits
and safety equipment aboard the vessel were substandard when they
were installed in 1994, a compromise hushed up at that time with
bribes.
</P>
<P>
   After the Kursk plunged 354 feet to the bottom of the Barents
Sea, the navy had no team to save the crew or retrieve the ship.
Russia's deep-sea diving unit mainly exists on paper _ all training
had stopped and its divers had left for better-paying jobs,
Litovkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Another cause of the disaster could be equipment failure.
Regular poaching of metals and other valuable items from naval
vessels has been a chronic problem. Sailors have stolen everything
from air conditioners to silver and titanium casings to supplement
their salaries. A mid-level naval officer receives only $100 per
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when everyone wanted to join the service
because of the prestige. The navy also promised a free home for
your family. Instead, we waited years for our apartment and months
for our salaries. We stripped metal off ships to resell it,'' said
Alexei Bergnikov, a thick-set 36-year-old father of one and
resident of Murmansk. He left the navy in search of better pay
after serving five years in the Northern Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the military, work is hard to come by in Murmansk, a
windswept city where the sun shines just four months a year. Grim,
hand-to-mouth living here makes safety concerns secondary,
compounding the possibility of environmental catastrophe to an area
extending far beyond Russia's borders, ecologists say.
</P>
<P>
   The Kola Peninsula has 270 military and civilian nuclear
reactors on its soil, the largest concentration in the world,
according to the Norwegian environmental group Bellona. The thin
strip of land, 1,000 miles north of Moscow and only 50 miles from
Norway, borders the Barents Sea, the world's most heavily fished
sea.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety of the 140 Russian submarines based on the peninsula have
been decommissioned but not scrapped safely, according to Alexei
Yablokov, former President Boris Yeltsin's environmental adviser.
Thirty-five of the subs still contain nuclear reactors or fuel, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has neither the money nor facilities to transfer and
store the radioactive fuel. The result is a growing stockpile of
poorly stored nuclear waste, much of it heaped in docked submarines
or boats that require constant maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   ''These vessels are a catastrophe waiting to happen. They are
floating Chernobyls,'' Yablokov said. ''They require constant
cooling or else there is the possibility of an explosion.''
</P>
<P>
   Those at greatest risk are in Murmansk. The town, built at the
end of World War I, has experienced its share of close calls in
recent years: In May 1998, radio stations warned people to take
iodine tablets after a fire on a nuclear-armed submarine set off
fears of nuclear fallout.
</P>
<P>
   Those who try to raise the nuclear waste problem publicly risk
persecution. Alexander Nikitin, a former Navy captain turned
environmentalist, has spent two years in prison and five years in
court after publishing a report detailing nuclear dumping by the
Northern Fleet. After winning acquittal on charges of treason
earlier this year, the Federal Security Service, the successor
agency to the KGB, has appealed to the Supreme Court to overturn
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the financial constraints and environmental dangers, the
question of abolishing the navy does not figure in the Kremlin's
calculations for military reform. In fact, Putin himself views the
navy as a vehicle to reclaim Russia's superpower status.
</P>
<P>
   According to Russia's new defense strategy published this
spring, Putin wants to reduce Russia's land-based nuclear forces in
favor of the underfunded conventional forces. To keep up a
semblance of nuclear parity with the United States, Russia would
rely heavily on its submarine-based nuclear missiles, with the
Northern Fleet. This would be a continuation of the same Soviet
policy of an Arctic-focused deterrent.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, Russia does not have the funds to adequately carry
out these reforms. Moreover, the strategy itself is anachronistic,
says retired U.S. Navy Rear Admiral James Carroll, vice president
of the Center for Defense Information based in Washington. He
believes that both Russia and the United States are pursuing
outdated military strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should quit trying to play the Cold War and preparing for
World War III,'' he said. ``They should be talking about
cooperation'' on environmental and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information: http://www.janes.com/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.government.gov.ru/english/
</P>
<P>
   Graphics/Fact Box:
</P>
<P>
   Since World War II, the Russians have lost 8 submarines.
</P>
<P>
   September 1957 _ the M-256 submarine of the Baltic fleet; 42
crewmembers died.
</P>
<P>
   January 1961 - the S-80 submarine of the Northern fleet; 68
crewmembers died
</P>
<P>
   March 1968 - the K-129 submarine of the Pacific fleet; 98
crewmembers died
</P>
<P>
   April 1970 - the K-8 nuclear submarine of the Northern fleet; 52
crewmembers died.
</P>
<P>
   October 1981 - the A-178 submarine of the Pacific fleet; 31
crewmembers died.
</P>
<P>
   October 1986 - the K-219 nuclear submarine of the Northern
fleet; four crewmembers died.
</P>
<P>
   April 1989 - the Komsomolets nuclear submarine of the Northern
Fleet; 42 crewmembers died.
</P>
<P>
   August 2000 - the Kursk of the Northern Fleet; 118 crewmembers
died.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
