<SLUG> BC-TAILHOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAILHOOK CONVENTION AGAIN MARRED BY MISCONDUCT ACCUSATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This story will be updated as necessary.) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Navy is facing a new accusation of misconduct
at the annual convention of the Tailhook Association, officials
said Friday. The accusation comes nine years after drunken
debauchery and sexual assaults at a Tailhook convention roiled the
service, leading to resignations, fines and changes in the
military's treatment of women.
</P>
<P>
   A man and a woman staying at a hotel in Sparks, Nev., where the
association held its convention last weekend, reported being
verbally and physically assaulted in a hallway by a group of men
attending the convention, according to Navy officials.
</P>
<P>
   The couple, whom the Navy did not identify, reported the
allegation to Navy officials on Tuesday, two days after the
convention ended. The Navy's inspector general and its criminal
investigation division have begun an investigation into the
accusations, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Navy official said it was not yet clear how many men
were reported to be involved, though it appeared at least some of
them were active duty officers.
</P>
<P>
   The accusation could prove particularly embarrassing for the
Navy since it restored its official recognition of the association
only eight months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The association, named for the steel hooks on jets that enable
them to land on aircraft carriers, is a private group based in San
Diego that acts as a sort of booster club for naval aviation and
has long been associated with the Navy and its officers corps.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy withdrew its recognition of the association following
the public furor over the group's 35th annual convention in 1991,
where 83 women, some of them in the Navy, reported being assaulted
or harassed in a Las Vegas hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The misconduct reported last week did not appear to be as
serious or widespread at that; a senior navy official said the men
in the hallway were accused of ``inappropriate physical contact''
with the woman.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the allegation could once again force the Navy to
reconsider its relationship with the association.
</P>
<P>
   When the Navy restored its recognition last January, the
secretary of the Navy, Richard Danzig, said that the association
had given its assurances that there would be no repeat of the kinds
of incidents that made Tailhook synonymous with the mistreatment of
women in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman said Friday that Danzig would not comment on the
incident until the investigation was completed.
</P>
<P>
   Tailhook's president, Lonny K. McClung, a retired Navy captain
and pilot, expressed concern about the accusations, but said he
knew little about what was alleged to have happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you it was a very successful convention,'' he said
in an interview. ``There were only two noise complaints from the
hotel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
