<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-LATAM (Miami) _ In a major address on Latin American
relations, Texas Gov. George W. Bush takes a hard line on Cuba's
communist regime while praising modernization in Mexico and
Colombia. Speaking in Miami before a private meeting in Dallas with
Mexican President-elect Vicente Fox, Bush said ``our future cannot
be separated from the future of Latin American,'' but he said the
region ``often remains an afterthought of American foreign
policy.'' By JOHN W. GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TAILHOOK-ENCORE (Washington) _ Navy personnel attending last
week's Tailhook Association conference are being accused of
inappropriate contact with a female civilian, a disclosure that
harkens back to what many in the service call ``the dark days'' of
1991. It was then in the Las Vegas Hilton hotel that a group of
drunken Navy aviators groped several female officers in after-hours
parties. The incident eventually cost senior Navy officials their
jobs, sparked numerous investigations and set off a flurry of
soul-searching about whether the Navy ever could welcome women into
its ranks as equals. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-ECONOMY (Abuja, Nigeria) _ Nigeria's economy will be a
key topic on President Clinton's agenda for his weekend visit.
Several American oil executives say that the business climate in
the African nation, after years of problems, is promising. By
MICHAEL HEDGES.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-PIPELINE (Austin, Texas) _ Texas Land Commissioner David
Dewhurst, who toured the site of a New Mexico pipeline explosion,
says he is concerned about an old Texas pipeline that make be put
back into service to transport gasoline from Houston to El Paso.
Both pipelines are 50 years old and both went through areas of high
salinity, a cause of corrosion. Corrosion is considered the most
likely cause of the New Mexico blast, which killed 11 people. By
CLAY ROBINSON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HELEN-THOMAS (Washington) _ If Vice President Al Gore and Texas
Gov. George W. Bush want to grab the attention of their audiences,
they would do well to tear a page out of a new book by Liz
Carpenter titled: ``Start with A Laugh.'' Carpenter, one of
President Lyndon B. Johnson's speechwriters, offers her sure-fire
formula: ``Start with a laugh, put the meat in the middle and wave
the flag at the end.'' By HELEN THOMAS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YOUTH-VOTE (Washington) _ In a sweeping effort to energize 18-
to-21-year-old voters, national youth and civic groups are
organizing mock elections and debates moderated by young adults.
These groups are mounting a massive campaign, alarmed by a trend
that shows young people are increasingly steering clear of the
voting booth. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HINES-COLUMN (Santa Fe, N.M.) _ As the primeval drama of Richard
Strauss' ``Elektra'' flooded from the stage and orchestra pit at
the glorious high-desert opera here last week, a basic truth of the
current presidential campaign came to mind again: revenge. George
W. Bush has repeatedly denied that settling old scores is a motive
force in his race against Al Gore, but almost no one believes him.
Bush is, simply, too ornery a son to sell that line. By CRAGG
HINES.
</P>
<P>
   ELY-COLUMN (Undated) _ In years past, it has seemed especially
silly to contend that Labor Day marked the proverbial kick-off day
for presidential campaigns. But there is a palpable yearning in the
ranks of the press _ and the political junkies _ that the 2000
presidential campaign will get well organized and under way a week
from Monday, which is only 64 days out from Election Day, Nov. 7.
By JANE ELY.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN _ (Austin, Texas) _ Politicians, especially when
they are in the middle of election campaigns, don't like to answer
hypothetical questions. Just for fun, though, here is a different
type of hypothetical question, one that George W. Bush certainly
doesn't want to answer: What if Bush loses his presidential race
and is still governor of Texas during next year's legislative
session? By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Much of Al Gore's strong populist
appeals to the poor and the middle class in his acceptance speech
and his orations on the campaign trail originated with Franklin
Roosevelt's New Deal and Lyndon Johnson's Great Society. By ROBERT
E. THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
