<SLUG> BC-ARETSKY-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UP FROM THE ASHES OF A CUBAN CIGAR CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two years ago, on a sultry August morning, Ken
Aretsky was playing golf in Southampton, N.Y., and riding high
indeed. That regrettable public unpleasantness at the ``21'' Club
was long behind him (more about that later). He was loving his life
as the doting father of two small children (more about that later,
too). And he was basking in critical accolades for having created
two successful new Manhattan restaurants, Patroon and Butterfield
81 (much, much more about that later, as well).
</P>
<P>
   That's when the phone call came: The U.S. government was
charging him with violating the Trading With the Enemy Act. Such a
transgression can be a felony punishable by 10 years in prison and
a fine of $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents armed with search warrants had seized dozens of
boxes of cigars from the upstairs cigar bar of Patroon, Aretsky's
three-star restaurant at 160 E. 46th St. The next day Aretsky and
his cigar bar manager stood in federal court, accused of buying and
selling cigars made in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   In a stogie-crazed city afire with aficionados overwhelmed by an
abundance of bootleg Cuban Cohibas and Montecristos, cigar
worshipers bristled at the news.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, cigarophiles loudly contended that the arrest was a
publicity stunt. For though the United States had imposed a trade
embargo on Cuba in the early 1960s, for decades American cigar
smokers had hidden Cuban stogies in their luggage and had had
cigars mailed to them from London tobacconists.
</P>
<P>
   But officials said they were following up on a violation of
federal law. Customs agents had tracked a large illegal shipment of
Cuban cigars to a house in Connecticut. A raid there had revealed a
list of clients that included Aretsky, his manager and five others,
who were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was devastating,'' said Aretsky, now 59, in his first
interview since that time. ``I was shocked. I suppose some people
think that notoriety is cool, but I didn't, and neither did my
family. It was rough for them. I worried about the future of my
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Aretsky had never had a brush with the law before. He grew up at
504 Grand St. on the Lower East Side, took over his father's
seltzer-gas supply business, sold it, then made a 1972 success of
his first restaurant, Truman's, in Roslyn, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   After a stint in Manhattan as a stockbroker (one co-worker was
the future domestic diva Martha Stewart) he opened the thriving
Upper East Side saloon, Oren &AMP; Aretsky. He followed that with
Arcadia at 21 E. 62nd St., which flourished until the lease ran out
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Aretsky was asked to turn around that power-lunch
dinosaur, the ``21'' Club. He amended the food and attracted a
devoted, less geriatric following. His genial presence was marked
by his signature wardrobe, for which the word ``dapper'' is hardly
dapper enough.
</P>
<P>
   But after eight years at the helm, ``I still had no equity
position in the restaurant,'' he said, adding that he was fired in
1995 after a dispute with the owners. He sued for breach of
contract, but says the case is in limbo because the company that
hired him filed for bankruptcy last year.
</P>
<P>
   Aretsky jumped back on the horse immediately by opening an
American bistro, Butterfield 81, then opened his competitor to
``21,'' Patroon, which won three stars from The New York Times in
1996 and again in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   By then Aretsky was enjoying mature fatherhood. He and his third
wife, Diana Lyne, a former Tiffany &AMP; Co. senior vice president who
is a consultant there, had two children, Grace and Eugene, now 7
and 6. (He has two grown children from his first marriage.)
</P>
<P>
   And then federal agents came through the door. Aretsky
acknowledged that ``Cubans were sold here with my knowledge,'' he
said on a recent afternoon in the former cigar bar, now a banquet
space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly we did something wrong and were punished
accordingly,'' Aretsky said. The U.S. attorney's office in
Manhattan says he ultimately pleaded guilty to two misdemeanors and
paid a $5,000 fine. He was sentenced to serve 200 hours of
community service.
</P>
<P>
   What Aretsky never anticipated was that he would become so
passionate about his court obligation, as he journeyed to the
city's inner-city high schools, mentoring students and working with
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   He is doing so through the auspices of a 10-year-old nonprofit
group called C-Cap, which promotes restaurant careers among
inner-city students. ``I'm trying to get these kids interested in
working as line cooks and pastry chefs and managers,'' Aretsky
said. ``There aren't enough bodies to fill all these jobs, and
restaurants need these kids' tremendous energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Aretsky's supervisor, Richard Grausman, founder and president of
C-Cap, said, ``Ken has put his whole heart into this,'' referring
to the group that reaches out to 2,200 students a year. ``Ken has
been wonderful with the kids and the teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, this August, Aretsky is about to embark on a new
multimillion-dollar restaurant venture on the Upper East Side.
``It'll be a fabulous neighborhood American brasserie,'' he said,
name and location to be revealed ``imminently.''
</P>
<P>
   What of his missionary work with students? ``It's a new world to
me, something I knew nothing about,'' he said. ``I hope to keep
involved with these kids for the rest of my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
