<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-CASINOS-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD TIMES ROLL ALONG AT HOTELS AND CASINOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 27) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The great advantage of a hotel,'' George Bernard Shaw once
observed, ``is that it's a refuge from home life.''
</P>
<P>
   With the economy booming, hoteliers are entertaining lots of
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has noticed. For the first seven months of the year,
an index of 20 hotel operators compiled by Salomon Smith Barney was
up 18.5 percent, drubbing the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, which was down
2.6 percent in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   And it looks as if the good times will keep rolling, because
business travel picks up in early fall.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Rietbrock, head of lodging and gaming research at
Salomon Smith Barney, took time last week to discussed the
conditions in his segment of the travel industry. Following are
excerpts from the conversation:
</P>
<P>
   Q. Retailing stocks have been weak recently, largely on fears
that the economy will slow. Do you see any signs of a slowdown
coming to gambling and lodging stocks?
</P>
<P>
   A. The stocks have been strong performers this year, but off of
very depressed levels. Most of these stocks, for example, are well
below their 1999 highs.
</P>
<P>
   And the outlook remains extremely strong. The fundamentals are
better than they were last year, and earnings are 25 percent
higher, on average.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How does assessing the lodging industry compare with
forecasting the overall economy?
</P>
<P>
   A. This is the easiest business in the world to look at.
</P>
<P>
   Supply of new hotels grows with new construction, and new
construction, which has been high for three years, is showing signs
of slowing down. But it is still pretty high.
</P>
<P>
   And demand for hotel room space is very highly correlated with
growth in the gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   Q. This is very much a ``people'' business. How is this
labor-intensive industry adapting to the Internet age?
</P>
<P>
   A. The hotel industry is way behind other travel industries,
most notably the airlines, in cutting travel agency fees.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody is working hard to develop online booking services,
and in most cases, right now online bookings are less than 2
percent of total bookings. Within five years, we could see that
percentage rise to 10 percent to 15 percent. That will save the
hotel companies a lot of money, and put a lot of pressure on travel
agent fees.
</P>
<P>
   But I don't think it will go much further than that, because the
inherent problem with direct booking is that when most people
travel they want to book their airline, rental car and hotel
together.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there is a lot of talk about a joint booking portal for the
hotel industry, but so far the coordination hasn't been there. The
big hotel companies, the Marriotts of the world, don't have a lot
of incentive to give smaller brands equal shelf space.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is the strong economy helping gambling companies, too?
</P>
<P>
   A. Business is healthy coast to coast, and that is a function of
the economy's strength.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Las Vegas has surprised everyone. A lot of new casinos
were built out there last year, and all that construction has not
only been absorbed, but the companies continue to grow their
earnings against tough year-over-year comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   The thing that has been great is Las Vegas' ability to transform
itself. It used to be all about gambling. But now it is gambling,
entertainment, shopping, great restaurants, golf. It is more like
Orlando. That, in turn, has made it a much more acceptable place to
hold large conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Atlantic City continues to grow moderately but
steadily, and the riverboat casinos are doing great, mainly because
several of those markets have liberalized their boarding policies.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Which gambling stocks do you like?
</P>
<P>
   A. We are recommending Park Place Entertainment, which is the
old Hilton gaming business. In the last year they bought Caesar's
from Starwood and have dominant positions in Las Vegas and Atlantic
City.
</P>
<P>
   We also like Harrah's Entertainment. They have a lot of big
properties and have developed the first frequent-gambler card,
which tracks gambling patterns and gives management a much better
understanding of what gamblers like and don't like.
</P>
<P>
   And MGM Grand is a neat company, although we recently downgraded
it because the stock has gone up a lot. The management team is very
shareholder-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Any picks among hotel operators?
</P>
<P>
   A. Our key recommendations are Starwood, Four Seasons and
Marriott International.
</P>
<P>
   Starwood has a lot of exposure to the big urban markets in the
United States and has become a pretty successful turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   We like Four Seasons because of the strength of the upscale
market in big cities, and because of its growth internationally.
</P>
<P>
   The key to Marriott is the brand: It is something like
McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 1629EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
