<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2237 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV     08-25 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE IPO LULL MAY BE OVER, BUT NASDAQ IS STILL STUCK IN SIDEWAYS
MODE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, August 27) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The law of supply and demand is a powerful thing. And right now
that power may be why the Nasdaq Composite seems stuck in a
maddening sideways groove.
</P>
<P>
   From June 1 to mid-July, Nasdaq ran up 26 percent, teasing
investors back into technology stocks that had gotten hammered just
weeks earlier. Then, to the disappointment of investors, the stocks
lost steam. In addition, while other broad indexes have recently
seen an improvement in breadth _ increasing numbers of stocks that
are rising _ the Nasdaq has not.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Hickey, editor of ``The High-Tech Strategist,'' an
investment newsletter in Nashua, N.H., is surprised by none of
this. The action in Nasdaq this summer is inextricably linked to
changes in the supply of and the demand for its companies' stocks,
he believes. As supply dwindled, stocks rallied. When supply rose,
stocks stalled.
</P>
<P>
   There are several sources of Nasdaq supply, of course, the
biggest being the issuance of new shares by fledgling companies.
The number and size of initial public offerings waiting in the
wings has ballooned since the spring as the market has proven
unwilling to absorb the supply. According to First Call/Securities
Data Corp., some 280 companies are currently awaiting their debuts.
These companies, mostly technology concerns, hope to raise around
$36 billion from investors by the end of the year. That is about
the same amount raised in initial public offerings in all of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Hickey senses that issuers and bankers are increasingly antsy
about getting these deals done. ``With the Nasdaq as weak as it has
been this year and all the stories of internet bankruptcies, there
is a tremendous urgency to go public,'' Hickey said. ``Wall Street
is going to feed as much as they can and more to the market here.''
</P>
<P>
   Another considerable source of supply comes from stocks that
recently went public whose insiders are allowed to sell their
shares. Under the terms of so-called IPO lockup restrictions,
insiders cannot sell their shares until about six months after a
public offering; at that time, millions of shares of stock can be
sold.
</P>
<P>
   Hickey believes that when huge numbers of lockups expire, Nasdaq
struggles. In May, according to IPOlockup.com., insiders at 63
companies were free to sell 2.7 billion shares. Nasdaq fell 12
percent during the month. In June, the shares available for sale
dwindled to 1.3 billion shares and Nasdaq rose 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, the lull is over. By the end of August, some 1.7
billion shares issued by 53 companies will have been unlocked. And
in September 1.8 billion shares in 45 companies will be free to
trade for the first time. Happily, the shares available for sale
drop to about half that level in October.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the insiders whose shares are unlocked may not want
to sell their holdings. But since so many of these stocks are
trading well off their highs, insiders may want to get out while
the getting's good.
</P>
<P>
   There are other sources of supply that may put pressure on
Nasdaq in coming weeks. Hickey pointed out that there will be
enormous stock and bond offerings by European telecommunications
companies looking for funds to pay for spectrum technology licenses
they are buying in government auctions. The Netherlands, Britain,
Germany, France and Belgium are all auctioning Internet spectrum to
companies that will have to issue securities to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Will demand for these shares and bonds be sufficient to soak up
the supply? Perhaps. But Hickey noted that early fall is a season
that is not known for strong mutual fund or stock market inflows.
</P>
<P>
   This fall could be different, of course. But swallowing $36
billion of new equity issuance will be a lot for even this bull
market to stomach without a hint of indigestion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
