<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2238 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-SCHOOL-NETSUBSIDY-NNS     08-25 1522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-NETSUBSIDY-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE SCHOOLS GETTING MILLIONS FROM FEDS FOR INTERNET SERVICES 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
FRIDAY, Aug. 25, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.) 
 By BILL CAHIR  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Gore had to devote part of his
acceptance speech last week to rejecting a position taken by his
running mate, saying he would not approve any voucher plan that
would ``drain taxpayer money away from our public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic politicians perform obeisance for the nation's
teacher unions by opposing public funding for school choice
programs, but skip one detail. Private schools already participate
in federal K-12 programs. In addition, through a relatively new
Internet subsidy that Gore supports, private and religious schools
receive funding directly from a nonprofit agency set up by the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Religious and other private schools get e-rate money from the
Washington-based Universal Service Administrative Company.
Established by the Federal Communications Commission, USAC
distributes e-rate funds to schools and libraries that apply for
it. The money pays for Internet wiring and deep discounts in online
services. Breaks range from 20 percent to 90 percent, depending on
the level of poverty in the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Private schools are eligible,'' said USAC spokesman Melvin
Blackwell. ``They apply in the same fashion as everybody else. They
do it directly. There's no middleman in this process.''
</P>
<P>
   For each of the first two years, private schools collected about
$34 million of the available e-rate funding. The program doled out
$1.6 billion in its first year and $1.9 billion in its second.
</P>
<P>
   About 80,000 private schools' classrooms, including 45,000
classrooms in Catholic schools, have been wired to the Internet
through e-rate money, according to FCC Chairman William Kennard.
More than 1 million classrooms, predominantly in public schools,
have been wired to the Internet through the program since its
inception in January 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters do not consider the e-rate a public subsidy for
private schools. The USAC, they say, is running a private trust.
The USAC receives payments from phone companies, and distributes
the money to schools and libraries. The companies recover their
costs by charging consumers about 25 cents to 35 cents each month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not public money, per se,'' said Jeff Burnett, a lobbyist
for the National Association of Independent Schools. ``You and I
are paying for this on our phone bills. As the lawyers would say,
it's a fee, not a tax.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 Telecommunications Act deregulated the telephone and
cable industries, cutting fees that long distance companies had
paid for access to local phone lines by $2.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the package, lawmakers compelled phone carriers to
offer Internet discounts to schools and libraries. The FCC launched
the e-rate in January 1998. The companies' decision to pass the
cost along to consumers came as a surprise to the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, we had no idea you were going to pick up the tab on
your telephone bill,'' said U.S. Rep. Bill Goodling, R-Pa.,
chairman of the House Education and the Workforce Committee. ``It
was never discussed.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is technically true the e-rate doesn't offer public
money to private schools, it does afford religious and other
private institutions an equal opportunity to benefit from a public
program. Private and religious schools are eligible if their
endowments do not exceed $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Clinton administration said they wanted to help all
schools get online, they made it very clear they meant `all
schools,''' said Patrick Canan, a Washington-based education policy
analyst for the U.S. Catholic Conference. ``I didn't see it as a
big inconsistency, and I don't think they did, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception, the e-rate has overturned ordinary
politics.
</P>
<P>
   A champion of the Internet subsidy, Gore supports the e-rate
while denouncing any notion of funding private school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who claim the government should fund private school
choice initiatives attack the e-rate as an improper tax on phone
bills.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   A new poll suggests that killing the e-rate could be politically
risky.
</P>
<P>
   Phi Delta Kappa on Aug. 22 released its annual survey of adult
attitudes about public education. It found that 69 percent of 1,093
people ``believe that the use of computer technology has improved
the quality of instruction in the local schools, and 82 percent
believe the schools should invest more in this area.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   There has been no end of GOP attempts to snuff out the e-rate.
</P>
<P>
   A House bill sponsored by U.S. Rep. Sam Johnson, R-Texas, states
in a toothless resolution that ``the e-rate discount program for
schools and libraries should be terminated.''
</P>
<P>
   The Top Ten Terrible Tax Act, introduced by U.S. Rep. Tom
Tancredo, R-Colo., would repeal the monthly phone fee and a
collection of other levies.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., chairman of the House
Telecommunications, Trade and Consumer Protection Subcommittee,
last year introduced a bill to scrap the e-rate and start a more
modest, $500 million grants-to-states program in its place.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a supporter of private school
voucher initiatives, is proposing to nix the e-rate. The Republican
presidential nominee would lump it into one $3 billion pot of money
to be administered by the U.S. Education Department. He would
combine the e-rate with $750 million in existing technology
programs, such as a $75 million initiative for training teachers to
work with computers.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Lisaius, spokesman for the Bush campaign, criticized the
e-rate application process as too much of a headache for schools.
Bush's plan, he said, would offer schools ``unprecedented
flexibility in using federal education technology funds.'' It would
fund the purchase of computer hardware, not just wiring and
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats claim the Bush approach would not work. The Education
Department, they say, lacks the legal power to collect fees from
telephone companies and, as a fallback, would not be able to obtain
the needed money from Congress. Inevitably, Bush's plan would
result in a cut in funding, they predict.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is simply a wrongheaded proposal,'' said Linda Roberts,
director of the U.S. Education Department's technology office.
``The e-rate funding comes out of telecommunications law, not
education law. ... We have no jurisdiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Private schools, meanwhile, have come to regard the e-rate as a
godsend. It promotes their ability to purchase online services and
to wire their schools for new computers. And it provides seed money
they use as leverage with their alumni and other donors.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Sister Dale McDonald, an education policy expert at the National
Catholic Education Association, estimates that 3,400 out of 8,000
Catholic schools have received e-rate money.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we speak to people who have received the funds, they are
extremely enthusiastic,'' McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   One Catholic school, Aquinas High School in the Bronx, N.Y., has
received $506,000 in e-rate funding over three years. Every
classroom in the building is now linked to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly was a dream that wouldn't have been accomplished
without the e-rate opportunity,'' said Sister Margaret Ryan,
president of the school. ``It's a very exciting time here. We've
trained all of our teachers to integrate technology into their
lessons on a daily basis.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court in May declined to hear a case about the
e-rate financing system, leaving the FCC's approach intact.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, public and private schools and libraries are doing
everything in their power to obtain e-rate money. They have
requested $4.72 billion, more than twice what the FCC can provide.
</P>
<P>
   As the rush for e-rate cash continues, it remains up to the
presidential candidates, and voters, whether the government should
scrap the e-rate program. It is the clearest example of a
government initiative treating religious schools, secular private
schools and public schools as equals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore wants to continue to use the e-rate to provide
low-cost Internet access to schools that serve our nation's most
disadvantaged students,'' said Dan Pfeiffer, a spokesman for the
Gore campaign. ``Bush's proposal threatens the e-rate program by
removing it from its funding source.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisaius denied any risk of lost funding, claiming Bush would
work with Congress to get the $3 billion or more. ``It's a question
of leadership,'' he said. ``Leaders set goals and work with others
to accomplish them.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information, see www.sl.universalservice.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 1632EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
