<SLUG> BC-GREIG-FILES0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sense of sight
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Microscopes and telescopes. Bifocals and
binoculars. Sunglasses and magnifying glasses. Opera glasses and
lorgnettes. Humans will do anything to improve eyesight. Why?
Vision is a major player in the sensory game. When eyes are not an
open window to the soul, they are picking up light and color, depth
and distance. Sending these pictures as electrical impulses to the
brain, the eyes feed the mind with images to be processed. The most
sophisticated cameras have failed to duplicate the process.
</P>
<P>
   Take the prominent physical position of the eyes. Think cavemen
ever noticed that as predators their eyes were in the front of
their heads? Convenient. All the easier to track and slay that
woolly-mammoth dinner. Prey, on the other hand, have eyes on the
sides of their heads. Side or peripheral vision comes in mighty
handy when being stalked. Just ask Wile E. Coyote.
</P>
<P>
   But what do you know about the sense of sight? Ever wonder which
substance in the iris determines eye color? What exactly 20/20
means? Or how often the average grown man cries? Have any idea what
colorblindness is? How many times a day you blink?
</P>
<P>
   This edition of the Greig Files is the third installment in a
series on the senses. So grab those drugstore reading glasses and
settle in. You are about to find out why seeing is believing.
</P>
<P>
   DID THE ANCIENTS SPORT RAY-BANS?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. Emperor Nero watched the gladiators cavort though
green-tinted stones. To improve his vision, to deflect the sun or
to be stylin'? No one knows for sure.
</P>
<P>
   The first assistive devices for the eyes were crude glass or
water globes through which objects or letters were magnified. By
A.D. 1000, a reading stone (polished magnifying glass) was commonly
held in front of the eye rather than on an object or paper. Glasses
developed by the Chinese were believed to protect the eyes from
evil forces.
</P>
<P>
   Generally those in the who-invented-it biz give eyeglasses an
Italian birth sometime in the 13th century. When Gutenberg's
printing press made books available to the hoi polloi, eyeglasses
were no longer a symbol of wealth. Credit the English with creating
the familiar earpiece-anchoring eyeglasses, and credit
Philadelphia's own Ben Franklin with bifocals.
</P>
<P>
   And contact lenses? Proposed by several folks _ da Vinci to
Descartes _ but the first glass lenses worn on the eyeball by a
human were made by Adolf Fick in 1887. Modern plastic lenses are
the refinement of Kevin Tuohy in the 1940s.WHAT DOES 20/20 MEAN?
</P>
<P>
   Merely a measure of distance vision _ shorthand devised in the
days of the paper eye chart. What a person sees at 20 feet is what
should be seen at 20 feet. Someone with 20/40 vision must be as
close as 20 feet to see what a person with normal vision can see at
40 feet, explains Dr. Jim McNabb.
</P>
<P>
   OH, SAY CAN YOU SEE?
</P>
<P>
   Just how is this miracle of sight achieved?
</P>
<P>
   The eye picks up light reflected by an object (e.g. a teddy
bear) through the pupil. The iris, a muscle, changes the size of
the pupil to control the amount of light. It also gives eyes their
color. The lens focuses on an object (thinning if the object is
distant, thickening if it is near). On the rear wall of the eye is
a thin layer called the retina. The retina contains two types of
visual cells _ rods and cones.
</P>
<P>
   Rods (about 125 million thin straight ones per eye) read shapes
in low light and report objects in black and white. Cones (7
million fat ones) identify color and take in the brightness. Cones
specialize in one of three colors _ red, green or blue. Rods see no
color, so humans cannot see color at night.
</P>
<P>
   The eyeball is protected by the cornea, a translucent tissue. A
clear gel provides steady pressure below the cornea to sustain the
eye's shape.
</P>
<P>
   Neurons pass the collected information along to the brain in
electrical impulses. The message is received by the visual cortex.
The visual cortex turns the message right side up and voila _ the
teddy bear!
</P>
<P>
   WHO IS VISUALLY IMPAIRED?
</P>
<P>
   Although more than 1 million Americans are legally blind, nearly
100 million are visually impaired without corrective lenses. The
leading causes of blindness in the United States are conditions
such as macular degeneration, glaucoma and cataracts.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmingly, the trudge of the baby boomers to senior status
means those 40 and older affected by vision problems will double in
the next 30 years, according to Prevent Blindness America.
</P>
<P>
   What's an aging boomer to do? Schedule regular comprehensive eye
examinations.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT MAKES THOSE EYES CRYING IN THE RAIN BLUE?
</P>
<P>
   A small amount of melanin, which is the only pigment in the eye.
The more melanin, the darker the eyes. In the absence of melanin,
the eyes are pink, as in albinos.
</P>
<P>
   WHO NEEDS A SWEAT BAND?
</P>
<P>
   When you have eyebrows, that is their function _ to protect the
eyes from dripping brow sweat. Lashes guard against small particles
and dust in the air that can get in the eye and cause problems.
Lashes also deflect glare from the sun's harsh light and are a
handy place to slather mascara.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT HAS A MAXIMUM OF SIX DOTS?
</P>
<P>
   The Braille rectangle. Invented by Frenchman Louis Braille in
1829, Braille uses one to six dots in various combinations (63 in
all) to allow the visually impaired to feel words. Braille
characters are embossed, and reading is accomplished by fingers
feeling across the page. There are individual Braille codes for
disciplines such as mathematics and science.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about Braille, contact the International
Braille Research Center at www.braille.org or (410) 659-9323.
</P>
<P>
   CAN YOU TRUST WHAT YOU SEE?
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   Fall leaves change color _ or do they? (Yes, readers, in some
parts of the world leaves alter colors as the weather cools.)
</P>
<P>
   The steady replacement of chlorophyll (the source of the green
in green leaves) ceases in cool weather. The absence of chlorophyll
allows the other colors that were always in the leaf to be seen.
Want to know more about vision and color? Consult Diane Ackerman's
``A Natural History of the Senses.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT IS A DISADVANTAGE OF THE Y CHROMOSOME?
</P>
<P>
   The increased incidence of colorblindness. Approximately 8
percent of men vs. less than 1 percent of women are born with a
color vision defect.
</P>
<P>
   Remember those cones in the eye's retina? If the cones do not
properly develop, then perception of red, blue or green is
adversely affected.
</P>
<P>
   Very few people see no color at all, a condition called
monochromasy, in which there are no cone cells. More common is
dichromasy, in which one cone does not have correct pigment and
usually a person sees blues and yellows but has difficulty with
reds and greens.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, aging causes lenses to darken, making it difficult
to distinguish dark colors from one another.
</P>
<P>
   SO WHAT MAKES THAT TEAR CASCADE DOWN AN OTHERWISE STALWART
CHEEK?
</P>
<P>
   Some tears lubricate the eye, removing harmful substances. Some
assuage emotion, and others are shed in response to pain. Their
main purpose is to lubricate the eye and make those protective lids
move.
</P>
<P>
   Tears contain water, salt, protein, a few lipids, fats and some
sugars. Although rabbits, dogs and rats have tear ducts, only
humans cry for stress-related reasons. William Frey, author of
``Crying: The Mystery of Tears,'' reports emotional tears contain
more protein than tears shed over slicing an onion, but that is
about as exact as the chemistry gets.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the content of tears, a good cry lessens stress.
Is stress relief important? Of course. Stress causes or, at the
very least, is a contributing factor to physical illness. Frey
notes the chances of having a heart attack are 14 times higher in
the 24 hours after the death of a loved one or close friend. Tears
in the grieving process help reduce that stress.
</P>
<P>
   ARE TEARS REALLY TABOO-HOO HOO?
</P>
<P>
   In certain quarters, yes.
</P>
<P>
   Some literature suggests crying is a social signal motivating
sympathy and demonstrating trust.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to cry in front of the boss, but few can get
through a film like ``Brian's Song'' or ``Steel Magnolias'' without
a tear. Odysseus was a big weeper, and a few high-profile macho
types _ Bill Clinton to Mickey Mantle _ have cried publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Before the age of 12 or 13, the frequency of crying is about the
same for boys and girls. During the teen-age years, differences
emerge that are driven by hormones such as prolactin and
testosterone, notes Frey. On average, women cry five times a month;
men, 1.4. For women, that means tears spilling over cheekbones; for
men, merely brimming eyes.
</P>
<P>
   A tendency to cry is not related to genetics (at least parents
get a hall pass on this trait) or personality.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT DO MICHELLE PFEIFFER, BRAD PITT AND GLENN CLOSE HAVE IN
COMMON?
</P>
<P>
   They have all been fitted with special-effect contacts by Custom
Color Contacts, the company that turns baby blues into wolf eyes,
permanently dilated pupils or mirrored eyes. These hand-painted
laminated lenses run $1,250 a pair. Remember, Tom Hanks' milky
white eyes in ``Philadelphia''? Yikes!
</P>
<P>
   In addition to special effects, these lenses are purchased by
those with disfiguring eye injuries and are even used as a
cosmetic. (Should Paul Newman ever want to shed his baby blues for
hazel.)
</P>
<P>
   WHICH INNER CIRCLE IS BIGGER?
</P>
<P>
   Gotcha. They are both the same size. Optical illusions amuse and
confuse. The eye sends information to the brain for interpretation.
The brain estimates the size of the inner circles by automatic
comparison with the surrounding outer circles. It is no wonder
eyewitness testimony is frequently called into question.
</P>
<P>
   For more fun optical illusions, including one featuring Bill
Clinton and Al Gore, visit www.eyeillusions.com or
www.keystoneblind.org/illusion.htm for a few difficult ones.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT THE HECK IS BLEPHAROPLASTY?
</P>
<P>
   Eyelid surgery, which is the second most popular cosmetic
surgery procedure for men (after rhinoplasty) and the third for
women (after liposuction and breast augmentation), according to the
American Society of Plastic Surgeons. Eyelid surgery is
increasingly popular (more than 142,000 were performed in 1999).
This procedure removes excess fat, skin and muscle from around the
eyes. A possible side effect? Temporary inability to completely
close the eyes. Egads!
</P>
<P>
   What does an eye lift cost these days? Uppers, $1,775; lowers,
$1,894; combined, $3,030. Fees exclude operating room, anesthesia
or related expenses (e.g. _ recuperative spa time).
</P>
<P>
   EYE YI YI YI YI YI !!!
</P>
<P>
   The word pupil has its roots in the Latin pulpilla, a little
doll. Romans saw doll-size reflections of themselves in the eyes of
others.
</P>
<P>
   Caucasian eyes appear blue at birth and after death, greenish
brown.
</P>
<P>
   The patterns of colors and spots on the iris are as individual
as fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   The human eye weight is about 7 grams.
</P>
<P>
   On average a person blinks every two to 10 seconds for .03
seconds per blink. That is 30 minutes a day of total blink time
with closed eyes.
</P>
<P>
   A newborn baby sees the world upside down until the brain learns
to turn the picture around.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: ``A Natural History of the Senses,'' by Diane Ackerman;
University
</P>
<P>
   of Washington; http://tqjunior.thinkquest.org
</P>
<P>
   HOW ANIMALS SEE THE WORLD
</P>
<P>
   Worker honeybees have 5,500 lenses in each eye.
</P>
<P>
   Buzzards can see rodents from a height of 15,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Because a chameleon's eyes move independently, it can see in two
different directions at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Each fly eye has 10,000 lenses.
</P>
<P>
   The pupil of the octopus eye is rectangular.
</P>
<P>
   A penguin's eye has a flat cornea to allow for clear vision
underwater.
</P>
<P>
   A scallop has 100 eyes around the edge of its shell to detect
predators.
</P>
<P>
   Scorpions may have as many as 12 eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Pigeons have eyes mounted laterally on their head and can view
340 degrees _ everywhere except the back of their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Snakes have no moveable eyelids but a clear scalelike membrane
covering the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Eric Chandler, Neuroscience for Kids,
http://faculty.washington.edu/(tilde)chudler/amaze.html
</P>
<P>
   WOULD YOU LIKE A HANKIE WITH THAT POPCORN?
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say the slam-dunk tear producer for men and women is
the 1957 flick ``All Mine to Give'' starring Glynis Johns and
Cameron Mitchell. This heart-wrenching angst fest is the story of
an 1850 immigrant family in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Need a good cry? Try one of these movies:
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian's Song''
</P>
<P>
   ``An Affair to Remember''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Champ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Way We Were''
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan''
</P>
<P>
   ``Terms of Endearment''
</P>
<P>
   ``Old Yeller''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Wonderful Life''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bambi''
</P>
<P>
   SIGNS OF POSSIBLE EYE TROUBLE IN CHILDREN
</P>
<P>
   A professional eye examination for a child is recommended
shortly after birth, at 6 months, age 3 or 4 and periodically
throughout the school years. Consult an eye doctor if any of the
following signs appear:
</P>
<P>
   Crossed or misaligned eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Presence of white pupil in color photo.
</P>
<P>
   Recurring infections on eyelids.
</P>
<P>
   Covering or shutting one eye.
</P>
<P>
   Irritability doing close work.
</P>
<P>
   Squinting eyelids together. Unusual amount of blinking.
</P>
<P>
   Holding objects close to eyes. Complaints of nausea, headaches
or dizziness after close work. Reports of eyes feeling itchy or
burning.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Prevent Blindness America
</P>
<P>
   EYE SPY: DEFINITIONS
</P>
<P>
   _ Aqueous humor: Clear, watery fluid found in the anterior
chamber. _ Cornea: The transparent tissue covering the front of the
eye. Does not have any blood vessels; does have nerves. _ Iris:
Circular band of muscles that controls the size of the pupil. The
pigmentation of the iris gives color to the eye. Blue eyes have the
least pigment; brown eyes have the most. _ Lens: The transparent
tissue that bends light passing through the eye. To focus light,
the lens can change shape by bending. _ Pupil: Hole in the center
of the eye where light passes through. _ Retina: Layer of tissue on
the back portion of the eye that contains cells responsive to light
(photoreceptors). _ Rods: Photoreceptors responsive in low-light
conditions. _ Cones: Photoreceptors responsive to color and in
bright conditions. _ Vitreous humor: Clear, jellylike fluid found
in the back portion of the eye. Maintains shape of the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Source: University of Washington
</P>
<P>
   THE EYES HAVE IT _ COMMON MALADIES
</P>
<P>
   Astigmatism: A condition that occurs when the cornea is slightly
irregular in shape, preventing light from focusing properly on the
retina. Vision may be blurred at all distances.
</P>
<P>
   _ Amblyopia: Lazy eye is the loss or lack of development of
central vision in one eye and is not correctable with lenses. It
usually develops before age 6, and it does not affect side vision.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cataract: A clouding of the lens. Surgical removal usually
improves vision. _ Glaucoma: A disease destroying the optic nerve
and eventually causing vision loss. _ Myopia: Nearsightedness is a
condition in which near objects are seen clearly, but distant
objects do not come into proper focus. Nearsightedness occurs if
the eyeball is too long or the cornea has too much curvature. _
Hyperopia: Farsightedness is a condition in which distant objects
are usually seen clearly, but close ones do not come into proper
focus. Farsightedness occurs if the eyeball is too short or the
cornea has too little curvature. _ Presbyopia: A condition in which
the crystalline lens of the eye loses its flexibility, which makes
it difficult to focus on close objects. (Happy 40th birthday!) _
Spots (floaters): Small, semitransparent or cloudy specks or
particles within the clear, jellylike fluid that fills the inside
of the eyes. Since they are within the eyes, these particles move
as the eyes move, darting away when you try to look at them
directly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Strabismus: Crossed eyes occurs when one or both eyes turn in,
out, up or down. Poor eye muscle control usually causes crossed
eyes. This misalignment often first appears before a child is 21
months old but may develop as late as age 6. _ Age-related macular
degeneration: A disease affecting the central area at the back of
the eye, the macula, impairing the ability to see fine details.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
