<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV27-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSIDER THE SOURCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 27, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Agreement is hard to come by in the fledgling science of
economics. The effect of a particular tax cut, or price increase, a
model change, depends on the behavior of millions of persons. They
having a way of trying to outguess not only the decision makers,
but one another as well.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the outcome is ``anybody's guess,'' but rather
that the range of possible outcomes usually is pretty broad. No
wonder that those projected federal surpluses, whose magnitude
depends on the behavior of any number of politicians over many
years, bear watching.
</P>
<P>
   Such verities as exist in science, therefore, are to be highly
prized. Perhaps the most universal of all this is the limit on the
speed of light. Ever since Albert Einstein in 1905 derived the
special theory of relativity and expressed the relationship between
mass and energy (E (equals) mc2), it has been universally agreed by
physicists that nothing in nature could exceed the speed of light
in a vacuum. That speed had been measured by A. A. Michaelson and
E. W. Morley in 1887 and was found to be the same in all directions
_ that being part of the mystery that Einstein explained.
</P>
<P>
   So it was with some chagrin that I _ and perhaps you _ picked up
the paper a few weeks ago and learned that the cosmic speed limit
had been broken.
</P>
<P>
   There was the news on page one of The New York Times, the
Washington Post, The Boston Globe, and the Los Angeles Times. ``The
Speed of Light is Exceeded in a Lab; Scientists Accelerate a Pulse
of Light,'' headlined the Post.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the NEC Research Institute in Princeton, N.J.,
looking for ways to speed up electrical circuits, had pumped two
laser pulses into a glass chamber filled with a vapor of cesium
atoms and created a laser that shot light out of the cell 300 times
faster than the statutory 186,000 miles per second. Their results
were reported in a July issue of the journal Nature; a fuller
account was pending peer review.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting to reporters on the experiment, Aephriam Steinberg of
the University of Toronto said, ``The broadest message is never
trust your textbook.'' What wonders might be next? A new Einstein?
Interstellar travel? Time travel?
</P>
<P>
   Thus it was with greater-than-usual relief that I hit the ``read
mail'' button on my computer the next Friday afternoon. And read
``What's New,'' a weekly column for the American Physical Society
by Robert L. Park. ``Opinions are the author's and not necessarily
shared by the APS,'' reads the disclaimer, ``but they should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Groan! ``The real news in physics (last week) was that the Tau
neutrino, the last of the fermions predicted by the Standard Model,
had been the discovered at Fermilab,'' the e-mail read.
</P>
<P>
   ``But front-page headlines across the country were proclaiming
`The Speed of Light Has Been Broken'. It's now going to be
impossible to characterize any claim as physically impossible
without people scoffing, `That's what they said about the speed of
light.' '' Already his newsletter was receiving a triumphant series
of letters and calls from Einstein-deniers, the PhD physicist
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he continued, the news stories and the Nature paper on
which they are based, probably involve an old and well-understood
sleight of hand. Already Charles Bennett had called from IBM's
Watson's Laboratories to assert that the news was ``little more
than a confused rehash of an old story where the peak of a wave
packet leaving the `superliminal' medium is causally related to
just the leading edge of the wave packet entering the medium.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, a few days later, Tom Seigfried of the Dallas
Morning News weighed in with a careful story debunking the claim
that the ``cosmic speed limit'' had been broken. Scientists had
been producing such effects for years. The experiment was a cartoon
special effect; the trick had to do with the excited atoms
interacting in such a way as to rearrange a new peak in the packet
of light, forward of the original peak.
</P>
<P>
   The authors themselves acknowledged that special relativity was
intact. The result was ``a direct consequence of classical
interference of different frequency components of an anomalous
dispersion region.''
</P>
<P>
   Park and the newspaper reporters who follow him have been doing
this for years: Assaying often ludicrous claims of those who
announce some kind of astonishing discovery whose mechanism has
been overlooked for years by a complacent scientific establishment.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that this sometimes doesn't happen. Indeed, there's
probably no more familiar story in science than the breakthrough
reportedly rejected by the referees who ``know'' that its results
cannot be so.
</P>
<P>
   But not every rejected paper is a breakthrough, and the more
comprehensive the claim to subvert the accepted wisdom of the
scientific community, the more intense the scrutiny to which the
assertion be subjected before it is reported out as fact.
</P>
<P>
   Park, a professor of physics and former chairman of the
department at the University of Maryland, pursues his
reconnaissance through a weekly electronic column (available at
www.aps.org). Director of the Washington office of the American
Physical Society since 1982, he keeps up a witty and well-informed
commentary on science, budget matters, security issues, and the
latest in pseudo-scientific fads _ everything from creationism in
Kansas to Florsheim's ``Magneforce'' shoes.
</P>
<P>
   In general he has stayed away from ``supply-side economics.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Park published ``Voodoo Science: The Road
from Foolishness to Fraud'' (Oxford University Press). It's an
especially entertaining history of various scientific controversies
that have hit the front pages since Park took up his cudgel _ cold
fusion, homeopathic medicine, the supposed ill effects on health of
electromagnetic fields, the strategic Defense Initiative and its
mythical X-ray laser, the ``Roswell Incident'' and the UFO craze,
and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Park concludes, ``Voodoo science is a sort of background noise,
annoying but rarely rising to a level that seriously interferes
with genuine scientific discourse. Cold fusion might interrupt the
flow of science for a few months, but those who make extraordinary
claims must eventually produce the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The more serious threat, he says, is to the public, which has
less basis for judging competing claims when direct appeals to a
lay audience are made. Scientists may have an obligation to step
in.
</P>
<P>
   Hence Park's reflections on the story of how the cosmic speed
limit was broken _ or not. The scientists themselves may have been
relatively circumspect in reporting their results themselves, but
the press release from computer giant NEC adopted a rather
different tone. ``One can only speculate on (its) objectiveness,''
he wrote. ``But it's the first time I've ever seen a press release
on basic research that had the company's Nasdaq trading symbol in
the first line.'' He's right, of course. Textbooks are not always
the last word, but the broadest message of the story of the cosmic
speed limit is: Consider the source.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
