<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEEP BLUE: THE CYPERSPACE CELEBRITY
 &HT;    300&AMP;add. Moving in the (l) lifestyle and (f) financial
categories for release Monday, Aug. 28.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When an advertiser needs a high-powered sports
figure for a product endorsement, booking agents check out the
Q-rating. Think Tiger Woods, Michael Jordan, Deep Blue.
</P>
<P>
   Deep Blue?
</P>
<P>
   Talk about high-powered. The IBM product has become the first
computer to attain celebrity status.
</P>
<P>
   According to Steven Levitt, president of Marketing Evaluations,
the research company that has tracked Q-ratings of celebrities for
the past 36 years, Deep Blue ranks on a par with some real people
like Donald Trump and LL Cool J, and some fictional characters like
Austin Powers and Count Chocula.
</P>
<P>
   Q-ratings are calculated by combining popularity, rated on a
scale of 1 to 5, with familiarity. About one out of two people, the
survey shows, is familiar with Deep Blue.
</P>
<P>
   Deep Blue's Q-rating of 9 was derived from a recent survey of
1,200 Americans. By comparison, Albert Einstein rates as a 56,
Mickey Mouse 44, Elvis 33 and NBC's Tom Brokaw 28. New York Yankees
owner George Steinbrenner will finish the season as a 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more people can relate to somebody as a favorite, the more
they're likely to watch the television show in which these people
appear, the more likely they are to be persuaded by that person in
advertising,'' Levitt told National Public Radio this month.
</P>
<P>
   Deep Blue earns its keep as a top-of-the-line RS/6000 SP
supercomputer, plugging away at complex projects in an IBM Research
lab in Yorktown, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   It first won fame by playing Garry Kasparov, the reigning world
chess champion, in 1996. Deep Blue lost that time, but when an
improved model defeated Kasparov in a 1997 rematch, the computer
ended up on the cover of Newsweek.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   IBM let all comers watch the chess matches in real time on the
Internet, which was still in its embryonic phase. That decision, in
turn, helped bolster the early popularity of the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after those games, Deep Blue has displayed its
staying power as a pop icon. Or, as an IBM spokesman put it: ``The
man vs. machine issues that drove initial interest are fading as a
technology-friendly Internet culture has fun with Deep Blue the
'personality.'
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, Deep Blue has emerged as a celebrity character
in Internet comic strips, in political satire, in late-night talk
show humor and in a tech-savvy TV animated show, Fox's
``Futurama.''
</P>
<P>
   In July, an episode of ``Futurama'' featured Deep Blue as an
intern as a ``Vice Presidential Action Ranger'' for Democratic
White House hopeful Al Gore. The computer was charged with the task
of protecting the Earth's time-space continuum.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
