 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Saturday, Aug. 26. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ASSESS (Jerusalem) _ A News Analysis on Prime Minister
Ehud Barak and recent political developments in Israel. By John F.
Burns.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-EXTREMISTS (Berlin) _ Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer
is pessimistic about the eradication of rightist extremism in the
east of Germany, saying in an interview that it will take a
``generation and a half'' to overcome the wounds of an area that
reminds him of his youth ``in the twilight zone'' between democracy
and authoritarian tradition. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-OPPENHEIMER (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ In this
society riven by race, the color line has long been crossed by only
the most determined of souls. So when the late Harry F. Oppenheimer
was remembered on Friday, here in the small Anglican church where
he worshiped for decades, no one had to ask why so many people from
such different walks of life had come to pay tribute to a titan of
business and industry. By Henri E. Cauvin.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TAILHOOK (Washington) _ The Navy is facing a new accusation of
misconduct at the annual convention of the Tailhook Association,
officials said Friday, nine years after drunken debauchery and
sexual assaults roiled the service, leading to resignations, fines
and changes in the military's treatment of women. A man and a woman
staying at a hotel in Sparks, Nev., where the association held its
convention last weekend, reported being verbally and physically
assaulted in a hallway by a group of men attending the convention,
according to Navy officials. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-LATIN-AMERICA (Dallas) _ Gov. George W. Bush, in Miami
Friday morning, charged on Friday that the Clinton administration
had neglected Latin American relations and ``squandered''
opportunities to expand trade in the region, and he pledged to put
countries in Central and South America at the top of his foreign
policy priorities. Later in the day, Bush traveled to Dallas for a
private meeting with Vincente Fox, the president-elect of Mexico.
By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EMULEX-PLUNGE (New York) _ At 10:13 a.m. Friday, investors in
Emulex, a California company that makes fiber-optic communications
equipment, got some terrible news. Bloomberg News, a leading
financial news service, was reporting that Emulex had announced its
chief executive had resigned and the company planned to restate its
earnings for the last two years. Details would follow _ at 5:00
p.m., after stock markets had closed for the weekend. Investors
rushed to shed their shares, and Emulex stock promptly went into
freefall, plunging from 103 to 45 in 15 minutes. The drop stripped
more than $2 billion in Emulex's market valuation before the Nasdaq
stock market halted trading in Emulex stock. There was only one
problem with the story. It was not true. It was the latest _ and
most devastating _ in a lengthening string of fake press releases
and other hoaxes that are increasingly roiling the financial
markets. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-HISTORY-PLURALISM (Undated) _ The writing of American
history underwent a significant change in the 1960s and '70s _ one
that remains in place today _ when younger historians shifted their
emphasis from the public life of the nation to the private lives of
its citizens. But critics of the new history have worried about the
fragmentation of the past, with each group telling its own story.
And even advocates have wondered about the place of so many
categories in the larger scheme of things. By David Oshinsky.
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-AUTHORS (New York) _ With more Americans than ever in
prison, an exhibition in New York is offering a survey of American
convicts' writings. For almost as long as there have been prisons,
prisoners have turned into authors for diversion, creative
expression, solace, penance, vindication, vengeance and release
(physically and metaphysically). By Ralph Blumenthal.
</P>
