<HEADER>
A2245 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV27-     08-25 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIT PLAYERS NO MORE: CORAL BELLS WITH FLASH 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 27) 
 By CASS PETERSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many a gardener grows coral bells, but only a few for the sake
of their flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Not that coral bells don't have lovely flowers. They do. They
send up spikes covered with small bell-shaped blossoms in colors
from pure white to purple-scarlet. The flowers, bobbing atop stems
so slender they are almost invisible, look as if they are floating
above the plant, not tethered to it at all.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, coral bells have an extraordinarily long season of
bloom for perennials. In my Pennsylvania garden, plants in full sun
bloomed from April through June and, if the faded blooms were cut
back, again in September. The ones that got only half-day sun often
started in May and bloomed into August.
</P>
<P>
   But coral bells, botanical name Heuchera (pronounced
HEW-ker-ah), are usually valued most for their foliage. The leaves
are round or heart-shaped and sprout from a central crown, giving
the plant an attractive mounded form. Many perennials look a bit
tattered after they're done blooming, but coral bells look fresh
all season long. They even stay green in winter in most climates.
</P>
<P>
   Coral bells are sun lovers, especially in the North, and they do
best in soil that is moist but well drained. Sandy soil is fine,
clay is not. But while they flourish in a sunny spot with rich
soil, they'll also survive and look decent in fairly dry soil in a
partly shady spot. They'll even grow under a black walnut tree,
where few plants care to be.
</P>
<P>
   A plant that will grow where many plants will not can expect to
be planted there. I've seen many a garden with a collection of
undernourished coral bells hugging a western wall or grubbing for
moisture under the Rose of Sharon bushes.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their subdued good looks and tidy growing habits
(they tend to stay where they're planted, rather than invade the
rest of the garden), coral bells often also see duty as foils for
more flamboyant plants _ as a ground cover in the rose garden, in
drifts between silvery-leaved artemisias or as an edging plant.
</P>
<P>
   But coral bells have recently been liberated from the backstage
and supporting roles in the garden. Plant breeders are turning out
some cultivars that deserve star billing. They're so flashy they
may need some background plants of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Among the earliest of the new breed of coral bells was a
cultivar called Palace Purple, which had large bronzy-red and
purple leaves and white flowers on 18-inch stems. It was unusual,
looked great and was easy to grow _ prize-winning characteristics
that won it the Perennial Plant Association's designation of
Perennial Plant of the Year in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful as it is, I still use Palace Purple mostly in the
background or foreground to highlight more brightly colored flowers
and plants. It is spectacular growing behind flowering
forget-me-nots or soapwort, where it continues to look good after
those spring bloomers stop flowering. It is lovely growing in front
of Russian sage, woolly betony or any of the blue- or silver-leaved
ornamental grasses. I like it in drifts with day lilies, too.
</P>
<P>
   Palace Purple is a hybrid of Heuchera micrantha. Most of the
standard red-flowered cultivars are selections from the species H.
sanguinea. But there are around 50 other species of Heuchera, and
the breeders have used several of them to create stunning new
cultivars. There are cultivars with leaves up to 10 inches across.
Foliage colors range from metallic silver to chocolate brown and
olive green, some with ruffled or deeply cut foliage.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the newer cultivars are hybrids of several Heuchera
species, often including H. americana. This native species is even
more shade- and drought-tolerant than most Heucheras, and it is
resistant to the mildew that plagues coral bells in humid climates.
The result is a plant that is not only showier than standard coral
bells, but also more rugged in the garden.
</P>
<P>
   To be honest, some of the newly introduced coral bells are a
mite overdone for my taste. I like the one called Plum Pudding,
which is richer in color than Palace Purple, and Regal Robe, which
has dark green leaves with a silvery overlay and black veins.
Pewter Veil is an interesting silvery olive color with reddish
edges to the leaves.
</P>
<P>
   But the coffee- and chocolate-colored cultivars don't appeal to
me much, and the intensely silver cultivars, like Mint Julep and
Mint Frost, look more like caladiums than coral bells. These might
eventually grow on me; I wasn't keen on the white-leaved Lamiums
when I first saw them, either. But they can easily be overdone, and
one of the beauties of the old-fashioned coral bells is that it is
almost impossible to have too many.
</P>
<P>
   That won't be an immediate problem with the new cultivars, which
tend to be pricey _ up to twice the price of a more familiar
variety like Firefly or White Cloud. But like all coral bells, they
can and should be divided every few years.
</P>
<P>
   The flashy new coral bells are gradually making their way into
garden centers, or can be ordered by mail. Two sources are The
Primrose Path, 921 Scottdale-Dawson Road, Scottdale, Pa. 15683,
(724) 887-6756, www.theprimrosepath.com and Roslyn Nursery, 211
Burrs Lane, Dix Hills, N.Y. 11746, (631) 643-9347,
www.roslynnursery.com.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes. The breeders also are working on cultivars of coral
bells that have extra-tall, extra-prolific stems of extra-large
flowers. The idea is to make the plant more useful for cut flower
production. I, for one, would happily grow them for the sake of my
garden.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
