<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2247 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-OLYMPICS0826-COX     08-25 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Politics vs. sports: Olympics wins audience favor
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For about two weeks during the heart of the
presidential campaign the political gymnastics may have to yield to
the real gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
   The heavyweights of the White House race are trying to figure
out how to compete for attention with the little girls on the
uneven parallel bars and whatever other drama develops down under
during the Sept. 15-Oct. 1 games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The Summer Olympics and presidential elections always happen in
the same year. But this year's games are unusually late. The
campaigns are trying to figure out what it will mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' said Karl Rove, top strategist for GOP nominee
George W. Bush. ``I think there is, at the least, going to be
competition on the evening news. And it's clearly going to be that
people's attention is going to be elsewhere. How much elsewhere we
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   In Nashville, Jano Cabrera, spokesman for Democratic
presidential nominee Al Gore, is sure about one thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be watching,'' he said of the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   And, history and NBC tell us, so will millions of other voters.
Linda Fowler, director of Dartmouth College's Rockefeller Center,
has a pretty good idea of what happens when politics goes
head-to-head with sports.
</P>
<P>
   Sports wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like stopping the campaign for two weeks,'' said Fowler.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Hall Jamieson, Dean of the University of Pennsylvania's
Annenberg School for Communication, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The polls will essentially freeze during the Olympics,'' she
said. ``If you are ahead in the polls you hope (the Olympics) are a
big success and you lock your lead in and people start paying
attention again at the first debate,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The debate schedule has not been set, though it seems likely
none will occur before October.
</P>
<P>
   Dartmouth's Fowler believes Gore caught a huge break when his
post-convention bounce gave him a slight lead in most major polls
after trailing for months. Running second heading into the Olympics
would have been a problem for Gore, according to Fowler.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I realized how late the Olympics are going to be, I
thought, `Oh my gosh, this is terrible for Al Gore because he was
the one down in the polls,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jamieson and Fowler believe the Olympic effect is being seen in
the candidates' current schedules. Bush and Gore _ perhaps
anticipating the Olympic lull _ have been campaigning full-time for
months. It's a schedule that has rendered Labor Day _ the
traditional start of the fall campaigns _ as an artificial milepost
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are charging ahead,'' Cabrera said of Gore's Olympic
strategy. ``Our stance has been that the American people will be
able to distinguish between entertainment and the serious issues
they need to focus on in the election.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign is operating under the theory that it is
always competing for attention. If it's not the Olympics, it's
something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a regular basis, the American people go to the movies,
watch sports and attend their kids' plays, but that doesn't change
the fact that when it comes to the issues, especially when it comes
to electing a president, they understand how significant a decision
this is,'' Cabrera said. ``Obviously, there will be some folks who
do nothing but watch the Olympics. But there are also some folks
who do nothing but watch the Weather Channel.''
</P>
<P>
   At Bush's Austin headquarters, campaign officials are trying to
figure out how to make the most effective use of the time during
the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it even more important where he is during that period
of time because when he goes into a market during that period of
time he is going to be able to have an impact. But will he have
less of a national impact? I think so, but there is no way to
know,'' said Rove.
</P>
<P>
   Jamieson said there is no doubt the impact will be reduced.
Given an option to yak about anything other than politics, many
Americans will, she noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It dampens talk about politics,'' she said about the big draw
of the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   But a savvy campaign _ and Jamieson believes both are _ can take
advantage of the lure of the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Olympics build viewership for TV it could increase the
audience for advertising, particularly if the ads are uplifting and
patriotic and visionary,'' said Jamieson.
</P>
<P>
   Neither camp will talk about its ad strategy. Bush has the
advantage of some experience with what happens when a late-breaking
Olympics intersects with a presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The 1988 games in Seoul _ which came during the George
Bush-Michael Dukakis presidential race _ also were held during the
final two weeks of September. The elder Bush said this week that he
did not recall whether the games had a major impact on the race.
</P>
<P>
   Jamieson said it's hard to place much value on anything from the
1988 race because it was ``such a bizarre election year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dukakis campaign was in total disarray and the Bush
campaign was using ads very effectively. The Olympics were not a
distraction from the Bush campaign in 1988 because the Bush
campaign was so effective at getting its message out and Dukakis
was so inept,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, as evidenced by the bounce each candidate got
from his convention, both campaigns have been effective in pitching
their messages and moving poll numbers. The next major opportunity
for that kind of effort will come during the debates.
</P>
<P>
   But those events also could face a peculiar threat from sports.
First pitch in baseball's World Series is scheduled for Oct. 21.
</P>
<P>
   The nightmare scenario for the candidates is that the Yankees'
pitching holds up, the Mets finally figure out how to beat the
Atlanta Braves and the nation is treated to (suffers through?) the
wretched media excess that would be heaped upon the first-ever
Yankee-Met fall classic in the nation's media hub.
</P>
<P>
   Game 7, if necessary, is Oct. 28, 10 days before Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
