<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2251 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-JOURNALISM-CHIC-ART-$     08-25 1476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNALISM-CHIC-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READY FOR A NATTY NEWSHOUND? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., restaurant name, spelled 'ino, is CQ) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, August 27) 
 By RICK MARIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Journalism is no glamour biz. Bad hours, peanut pay.
Unflattering lighting. Or so the inmates complain. As for the style
sense, the women are more presentable. The men make casual Friday
look like the Oscars. Dockers and Rockport are their Gucci and
Prada.
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, the September issue of W magazine's 16-page men's
fashion spread is somewhat jarring. There's Joel Stein, Time's
nerdy humor boy, in a black corduroy Tommy Hilfiger suit, and Kurt
Andersen, the unironed magazine veteran and co-founder of
Inside.com, in Armani, among other working journalists. The
headline? ``Medium Cool.''
</P>
<P>
   A few gallons of Wite-Out are being applied to the old
ink-stained-wretch cliche. NBC has a new fall series called
``Deadline,'' about a dapper columnist who solves crimes in his
spare time. Cameron Crowe, in his movie ``Almost Famous,'' opening
Sept. 15, recounts his days as a 15-year-old Rolling Stone writer
during an era when rock journalists could still pretend to be
almost as cool as their subjects. And in the pipeline, there's
``Serendipity,'' which began filming in New York last week, and may
be the first movie in which the dramatis personae include an
obituary writer for The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Redford and Hoffman played a better-looking Woodward
and Bernstein has the profession been made to look so cool. This
development raises important questions like these:
</P>
<P>
   _Is the Fourth Estate experiencing a rehabilitation?
</P>
<P>
   _What are the three other estates, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   But those are matters to be debated in The Columbia Journalism
Review. The issue raised by the W spread and this wave of movies
and television shows is that dressing up the image of journalists
requires careful thought about what they're going to be dressed up
in. As Marcus Teo, the men's fashion editor at W, explained:
``These are behind-the-scenes people not known for having much of a
clue about style or fashion. We wanted to turn the rumpled into the
fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   Fabulous isn't quite the word for Oliver Platt, the Falstaffian
character actor who plays Wallace Benton, the crusading hero of
``Deadline.'' But he certainly looks distinguished in bow tie,
double-breasted blazer and flamboyantly draped scarf. Dick Wolf,
the show's creator and one of its executive producers, places
Benton ``in the tradition of Jimmy Breslin and Mike McAlary.''
Except neither Breslin nor the late McAlary were bow tie types.
</P>
<P>
   Benton's wardrobe is more ``Paper Chase'' than ``Lou Grant,''
maybe to remind viewers of his professorial duties, teaching
journalism to a class of eager cub reporters. The crime-solving
part of the show is done with the aid of his students in their
joint quest for ``nothing but the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Platt's brother, Adam Platt, is a journalist (a
restaurant critic for New York magazine). To get into character,
the actor brother spent time researching the writer brother's
milieu. He visited a newsroom, lunched with reporters at the Four
Seasons and _ more in keeping with the stereotype _ sought out free
booze at open-bar parties.
</P>
<P>
   Crowe's movie has even more personal significance: It's
autobiography. Before he wrote movies, Crowe wrote magazine
articles. At the prodigious age of 15, he was assigned a story by
an editor at Rolling Stone who had no idea that the kid on the
other end of the phone actually was a kid. The movie is loosely
based on the callow Crowe's experiences following bands around and
writing about them, even though he wasn't much older than their
youngest fans. The boy wonder sees it all: Drugs, sex, stupid
arguments between the guitarist and the lead singer.
</P>
<P>
   And check out the crazy threads! William, the Crowe character,
dresses pretty much like 15-year-olds dressed in 1973. Sneakers,
T-shirt, ungainly satchel. But when he calls Rolling Stone's
offices, there's a glimpse of his grown-up counterparts: Editors in
Op Art polyester shirts and tinted glasses, brandishing cigarette
holders. Even the magazine's founder, Jann Wenner _ well, a young
actor playing him _ is there, looking in his pinstriped shirt and
hip-huggers like something out of a Tommy Hilfiger campaign. When
this movie comes out, the magazine may be deluged with internship
applications.
</P>
<P>
   William's idol and role model is Lester Bangs, the late rock
critic and gonzo editor of Creem magazine. ``Be truthful and
unmerciful,'' Bangs counsels his would-be protege. And a total
slob, he might have added. The Bangs look, and worldview, were pure
antichic: Droopy jeans, Guess Who T-shirt and a beat-up motorcycle
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made that T-shirt,'' said Betsy Heimann, the film's costume
designer. ``That's the only way I could be true to the
silhouette.'' The silhouette of the '70s being form-fitting _ no
matter how fit the form. (And Bangs, played by Philip Seymour
Hoffman, was not buff.) For the others, Heimann worked from
photographs of the staff in the Rolling Stone archive. The
fictional band in the movie represents the post-hippie, pre-glam
country rock interregnum of the Eagles, the Allman Brothers, Lynyrd
Skynyrd. ``The American rock star as cowboy outlaw,'' as Heimann
encapsulated it.
</P>
<P>
   It was a look many rock critics kept alive well past its, and
their, prime. As Robert Palmer once wrote in The New York Times,
you could always tell the rock critic in a punk or new wave club
because he was the only one with long hair. For years, Dan
Aquilante's column in The New York Post had the quintessential rock
critic photo byline: A tiny head encased in the world's largest set
of headphones.
</P>
<P>
   Rock critics may have been ripe for some image rehab, but if
ever there was an unlikely beat to be hipified it is that of the
obituary writer. Jeremy Piven, 35, plays the obit writer and best
friend in ``Serendipity,'' a romantic comedy with John Cusack and
Kate Beckinsale due to open early next year. The film's original
(since departed) costume person presented Piven with a get-up that
he felt was a little on the cliched side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to have patches on my elbows, you know?'' he
said, looking around L'Uomo, a men's clothing store on Bleecker
Street last week. Asked to pick out a few items a typical obituary
writer would wear, he rejected most of the stuff as too expensive.
He said he imagined his character as an aspiring novelist
(accurate) who worshiped Hemingway (accurate) and therefore might
wear a guayabera shirt because Hem would have worn one in Cuba
``with a light spring jacket over it'' (iffy).
</P>
<P>
   At 'ino, a tiny restaurant across Bedford Street from the
apartment where he was staying, he reflected on his own brushes
with journalism. Piven has been in 35 movies, most recently ``The
Crew'' (which opened Friday) and has done his share of television
work (``The Larry Sanders Show,'' ``Ellen''). But his name is known
only to a small cult of fans. This he blames in part on the press
and his own disinclination to seek it out, as well as a former
publicist who advised him to wear berets on talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Hollywood, they know the press is bought and paid for, but
they still believe the hype,'' he said. As for entertainment
reporters, ``they'll take a quote and twist it up, so they can put
it out there and sell papers.'' But that's just his opinion. For a
guy like his character in the movie ``who went to Brown and
worshiped Hemingway, he would be more romantic about it,'' Piven
said. The Cusack character's best friend, he added, would not be
``a sellout punk.''
</P>
<P>
   The fashion-forward W magazine shoot notwithstanding, what this
crop of fictional journalists have in common is nostalgia.
``Deadline'' romaticizes a mostly bygone era when columnists were
feisty characters with personalities as big as their circulation.
Described in NBC's promotional tape as ``a new breed of
journalist,'' Wallace Benton seems more like the last of a dying
one. ``Almost Famous'' wistfully recreates the bygone era of
unlimited access to the bands and stars of the day. Now, rock
reporters prescreened by publicists feel lucky to score an hour in
a hotel room with their subjects. And ``Serendipity''? We'll see
when it comes out, but at least we know the Piven obit writer gets
to pal around with John Cusack.
</P>
<P>
   The danger, of course, is that actual journalists might start
believing their press. That they might actually start wearing
fur-collared coats. They would do well to keep in mind Lester
Bangs' words of wisdom to his naive acolyte. ``You are not cool,''
he tells him.
</P>
<P>
   Not even medium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 1654EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WEST-FIREFIGHTERS-NYT     08-25 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-FIREFIGHTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FIREFIGHTERS, IT'S BEGINNING TO FEEL LIKE WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHALLIS, Idaho _ They head out before dawn and trudge home after
dark, weary and covered in soot, still clutching the shovels and
axes that are their weapons. They sleep as many as 21 to a tent, in
makeshift camps pitched beneath smoky, lung-choking skies.
</P>
<P>
   That is how thousands of firefighters across the West have spent
summer 2000, a season so devastating that commanders say they
cannot help but view it as a war.
</P>
<P>
   Others are beginning to view it that way, too. In fact, the
United Service Organization, best known for organizing shows to
entertain U.S. troops overseas, has now come to this remote corner
of Idaho. With three former beauty queens dressed in red, white and
blue micro-mini-dresses cooing and flirting from a flatbed truck in
a roadside meadow, the scene along the Salmon River on Thursday was
perhaps only the most surreal in a summer in which fire has drawn
people from around the country to the most isolated of places.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely something new,'' said Sgt. Craig Smith, 29,
of Birmingham, Ala., a Marine whose unit was dispatched to eastern
Idaho on Aug. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is among some 1,700 men and a handful of women in eastern
Idaho battling the largest of dozens of major fires burning across
the western United States. His coworkers include paramedics from
Tennessee, high-school dropouts from California, and federal
land-managers from all over the United States.
</P>
<P>
   After working 16-hour days on end, this group found itself
gawking on Wednesday and Thursday nights at the performers from the
USO, an organization whose past tours have almost always been
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our missions are primarily to remote and isolated places, and
there aren't too many places in the United States that qualify,''
said James Pearcy, the USO's director of entertainment. ``But I
guess sleeping on the ground for 30 days in a fire zone in the
middle of nowhere would have to count.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by Victoria Reed, a former Miss Maine, the New York-based
troupe performed a medley of staples that included everything from
``America the Beautiful'' to ``All My Lovin','' while planting as
many lipstick-red kisses as possible among a whooping audience that
found it hard to believe what had come to the camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a year!'' John Wallace, 23, a contract worker from Tule
Lake, Calif., said in disbelief, commenting not only on the
performance but also on the record paychecks that have resulted
from the record fire damage. ``I'm planning on living through the
winter off it.''
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, well over 25,000 men and women are involved in the
firefighting, including what will soon number more than 4,000
military personnel from the Army, Marines and the National Guard,
in an operation whose cost is estimated at $15 million a day. But
with 1.4 million acres still burning in the West, the current force
is not nearly sufficient, federal officials say, and a shortage of
trained supervisors means that it cannot prudently be reinforced.
</P>
<P>
   So federal officials have said there is little they can do to
fight many of the blazes. From fire camps like this one, the main
effort has been focused far from the flames, in efforts to
safeguard houses from danger and to make sure that the danger has
passed in areas where fires have already burned through.
</P>
<P>
   ``The resources have just run dry all over the country, and so
we've had to back off to wider lines,'' said Bill Cyr, 48, an
engineer with the Los Angeles Country Fire Department who since
Aug. 5 has bunked down under a yellow-tarp every night with a
20-man Marine unit, for which he is serving as a temporary adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Across the United States, nearly 6 million acres of land have
now burned this year, and with hot, dry weather conditions in the
West showing no sign of abating, the devastation is likely to
become the worst in at least half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the worst fires are in western Montana's Bitterroot
Valley, where a wind-driven flare-up in the last two days has added
to a blanket of smoke so thick that on Thursday midday felt like
deepest dusk. But the Clear Creek fire, burning northwest of here
in the Salmon-Challis National Forest, remains the largest single
blaze in the country, spanning some 165,000 acres, with only about
one-third contained.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 1,755 people, 16 helicopters, 66 fire engines
and 14 bulldozers have been assigned to fight the fire. But the
area is so vast and so isolated that commanders say that much of
their time and energy is devoted to logistics.
</P>
<P>
   The nearest substantial airport, in Idaho Falls, is three hours
away from this camp, which is set on a highway so that it can be
resupplied. Reaching the fire lines takes the crews an hour each
way by bus, traveling on narrow Forest Service roads.
</P>
<P>
   And though the food served at the camp is far better than
standard military fare, it does not come cheap, said Dale B.
Thompson, a Park Service ranger based in Arizona who is managing
the food operation here. A Thursday dinner that included halibut
and au gratin potatoes dished up by the Big Sky Catering Co. of
Missoula, Mont., which specializes in providing for fire crews,
cost taxpayers $16 a meal, for a total tab of $12,000, Thompson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The USO troupe flew in and out of Boise, Idaho, seven hours
away, and was returning to New York for regular weekend
performances on the USS Intrepid, the warship-turned-museum now
docked in New York. The Marines, who arrived here Aug. 5, have had
only one day off since, and receive no extra pay for their fire
service, said Lt. Alison Ake, a spokeswoman. The unit is scheduled
to return to California on Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   By law, the civilian firefighters contracted by the Forest
Service and other federal agencies receive more generous treatment.
</P>
<P>
   They are required to take one day off for every 14 days of work,
or two days every 21, and most of them get time-and-a-half for
overtime, which adds up quickly over the long days. Wallace, the
23-year-old Californian, figures he will earn $3,000 a month this
summer as a member of what is known as a Type II, or second-tier,
fire crew. That is more than triple his regular wintertime wage.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks in the smoke, firefighters say, simple pleasures
feel like enormous rewards. Brian Crawley, a 33-year-old paramedic
from southeast Tennessee, was looking forward to a brief respite
from what would be two back-to-back 21-day fire tours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm headed to the big metropolis of Challis,'' Crawley said,
``for two things I can't get here: a bed and a bath.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 1659EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
