<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2256 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MASE-GOD26-COX     08-25 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASE-GOD26-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   From hip-hop to God
</P>
<P>
   By Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mase was the kind of rapper who talked about flashy
things like a Mercedes, was rich enough to own one and could crowd
his female admirers into a fleet of them and still have an
overflow.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's a preacher, his focus has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Outwardly, Minister Mason Betha still looks like Mase as he
walks into Atlanta's Gladys Knight's Chicken &AMP; Waffles. In a blue
Fred Taylor football jersey, black jean shorts and scuff-free white
Nikes, the 23-year-old appears very much the young man who made his
way into the hip-hop world alongside Sean ``Puffy'' Combs. His is
not the look of a person leading a Christian crusade in Atlanta,
his adopted hometown.
</P>
<P>
   When he finally settles into a booth along the wall you notice:
The platinum, diamond-encrusted Rolex he used to wear has been
replaced by a tasteful silver watch. On his right wrist, where a
similarly diamond-laden bracelet used to be, are two simple strips
of cotton: One is rainbow-striped with the letters W.W.J. D. (What
Would Jesus Do?); the other is green and says ``Yes I Believe.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear him tell it, though, giving up the showy jewelry and
fame _ and the kind of women that come with them _ was easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only gave back the devil the stuff I got serving him,'' the
Jacksonville native says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I was corrupting young people's minds to get that
money,'' he adds. ``I was telling guys things like, `If you don't
have sex with at least five women a day, you're nobody.' Leading
millions of people astray. Imagine how much more I can have doing
the right thing, and serving God?''
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the old life behind
</P>
<P>
   Betha left the world of hip-hop stardom last summer _ just as he
was at the peak of his success. He was known for a trademark
languid monotone that somehow came across as hip.
</P>
<P>
   And it had only taken him three years to have a No. 1 hit with
``Puffy'' Combs (the 1997 single ``Can't Nobody Hold Me Down''), a
3 million-selling solo debut album (1998's ``Harlem World'') and
such mainstream appeal that the chubby-cheeked rapper was asked to
do the theme song for a Nickelodeon movie (``Take Me There'' for
1999's ``The Rugrats'').
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I just woke up and I just knew everything I was
supposed to be doing,'' he says in his first interview in Atlanta.
``And it wasn't nothing that I was doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all made sense,'' he continues. ``You grow up with 11
friends and you're the only one still alive. Why? I was sleeping
with five women a day _ and (I) don't have no babies, don't have no
AIDS, no herpes, no nothing. It's nothing but God. I've been places
where people have been like this close'' _ his hand sweeps across
the width of the small table, then he pretends it's a gun ``and
shot. And I just started running and said, `How did that not hit
me?' It all just made sense.''
</P>
<P>
   But leaving his old life behind wasn't without its own
challenges. First he had to tell Combs _ the president of Bad Boy
Records , that he wanted to leave. Combs had just lost his best
friend and biggest star, Christopher ``Notorious B.I.G.'' Wallace,
in a drive-by shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to hear it for real,'' Betha says.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, when he told Combs ``it was God telling me to
do this,'' Combs released him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not crazy!'' Combs says of the conversation. ``How could I
tell that man, `No you can't do what God told you to do?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the folks in Betha's life weren't as easily
convinced. ``Friends, family _ everybody besides Puff _ didn't get
behind me,'' Betha says without a hint of hurt. But his eyes lower.
``I look at it like this,'' he adds, ``that's the position God
wanted me to be in to be a better man.''
</P>
<P>
   With nothing to really keep him in New York City, where he'd
lived since he was 5, he moved to Atlanta last year. It wasn't
unfamiliar territory. In fact, it was at Club 112 in Buckhead that
he first met Combs in 1996. In 1998, Betha formed his All Out
record label with producer Jermaine Dupri's Atlanta-based So So Def
Records. ``Atlanta has always been my favorite place to go, even
when I was `in the world,' '' he says. ``When I came down here,
people used to show me a lot of love.''
</P>
<P>
   Betha won't say where he lives in Atlanta _ merely ``Fulton
County'' and ``past Chastain Park.'' Or whether he lives with his
mother or five brothers and sisters. (Mason Betha Sr. left the
family months after he was born).
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain though: He hasn't been backpedaling into
Atlanta's nightly music scene. ``You would never know he lived here
if you looked for him at a party,'' Dupri said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at church or shopping,'' in Phipps Plaza or Lenox Square,
Betha insists. ``That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. Last fall you could find him on the Clark Atlanta
University campus, where he pursued a math degree for a year.
That's where Betha met and befriended Detroit native Jasper
Littlejohn. ``We've developed like a big brother/little brother
kind of relationship,'' he says. ``He's someone I respect because
he's totally against compromising. That's the reason he didn't go
into gospel rap _ because, he's like, `you can't mix Jesus with
anything.' The people I tried to be around before, who said they
were about God, were compromising, saying crazy things like `You
can still drink as long as you don't get drunk.' ''
</P>
<P>
   What makes Betha so convincing, says Littlejohn, is that he is
more like a peer than a parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to be disrespectful to anybody, but when a 50-year-old
pastor tells me `Don't have sex with someone,' it's hard for me to
hear that because he has a wife and kids. When Mase says it, you
know he's going through that same struggle with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Littlejohn has joined Betha's non-denominational S.A.N.E.
(Saving A Nation Endangered) Ministries, which he hopes to will
make appearances in every state over the next two years. Betha
won't say how the crusade is financed, but it has hit five cities
in the past three months, New Orleans, Dallas, Detroit, Memphis and
Miami. At each stop, it has generated enough offerings to pay for
the previous one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had about 2,000 people show up for each one,'' says Tina
Ellis, Betha's assistant. ``And at least 250 people in each city
get saved.''
</P>
<P>
   Betha's pastor at East Point's 1,500-member Siloam Baptist
Church, Jonathon Carter, witnessed his work in Dallas. And wasn't
surprised. After his 1999 move to Atlanta, Betha went to Carter's
small, red brick church at the recommendation of a Jacksonville
pastor. And he was ``terribly confused'' Carter said. ``But I still
knew that he had a call on his life the day he came... God's going
to do great things through him.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Betha has introduced his S.A.N.E. Ministries across the
country, he hopes to lead them to a church he thinks he'll start in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Why there?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because that's where the entertainers go for vacation,'' he
says. ``And I wouldn't be a man of God if I came from a world and
didn't go back to help that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   But both Betha and Carter see the rapper called to lead a youth
ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of them,'' Carter explains, ``and God is using this
young man they know from music to speak to them in a different
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, yes.
</P>
<P>
   But determinedly, and in that same languid montone that made him
a star.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 1701EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2257 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-RELIGION-MUSIC0826-CO     08-25 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-MUSIC0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    4Him gives Christian hymnal standards modern treatment
 &HT;    By James Lloyd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ At a time when the hymn book, choir and organ are
becoming endangered species in many churches in favor of the
ubiquitous praise band and modern worship choruses flashed on a big
screen, the contemporary Christian group 4 Him has released a
collection of traditional songs called ``Hymns: A Place of
Worship.''
</P>
<P>
   If any group could pull off giving the pop treatment to such
songs as ``It Is Well, Savior Like a Shepherd'' and ``Great Is Thy
Faithfulness,'' it would be 4 Him, which will perform tonight at a
free concert at Island MetroPark. After all, this quartet recorded
some of the '90s' most significant lyrics, often written by member
Mark Harris. Such songs as ``The Basics of Life,'' ``The Message''
and ``Great Awakening'' encourage uncompromising faith that is
reflected in action that influences culture. They may be anthems
future generations look to for inspiration, just as the songs on
``Hymns'' have influenced so many others.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Chrisman of 4 Him agrees that the ``big'' songs are the
ones that seem to resonate with listeners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have learned our lessons over the years . . . that
we can try and hip ourselves up and . . . chase after the newest
sound, but really it all comes back to the big song, the big
ballad,'' he said recently from his home in Daphne, Ala., near
Mobile.
</P>
<P>
   Success can breed pressure to repeat, however, and Chrisman
admits Harris has felt it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially after Mark wrote ``The Basics of Life,'' I think
that ever since then, he's felt a lot of pressure on different
levels . . . to deliver that song again on every record,'' Chrisman
said. ``My opinion is, you just let it come. Whatever songs God's
given us, we go with, and one of those songs always pops up.''
</P>
<P>
   Peer recognition has come with the hit songs. Since 4 Him went
solo in 1990 after working for three years with the group Truth, it
has been named group of the year three times by the Gospel Music
Association, as well as being its Dove Award-winning new artist in
1991. 4 Him also was nominated for a Best Pop/Contemporary Gospel
Grammy in 1997 for ``The Message.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, 4 Him is pondering the future. With a contract with
Benson expiring soon and with most members being husbands and dads
_ Chrisman, 34, has been married for 10 years to his wife,
Jacqueline, and has a son, Lucas, 7, and a daughter, Kayleigh, 4 _
they frequently discuss how much longer they should keep recording
and touring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting to that point . . . of saying, `Let's do this as
long as God is calling us and blessing us.' . . . And we're gonna
continue until he says stop,'' Chrisman said. ``But we feel like
there is a lot of life in 4 Him. We feel like we have a lot of
creative energy left to give it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chrisman drew inspiration during the ``Hymns''project as group
members immersed themselves in the stories behind the songs. The
song ``Be Thou My Vision'' was particularly meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not somebody, whoever wrote this, who was sitting
around banging his brain on a piano going, `I've got to get this
lyric finished. I've got to get this lyric finished. I'm on a
deadline for our record.' This was a guy who was moved by the
presence of the Lord in his life, and these lyrics just poured out
of him,'' Chrisman said. ``It's just the most honest heart cry for
a relationship with God that I've ever heard. . . . When I read
this lyric and began to sing it and internalize it, it moved me
like nothing else ever has.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Chrisman has no problem with the modern worship
movement _ in fact, he can see 4 Him moving more into ``making
music that causes people to stand up and worship'' _ he believes
the old hymns have their place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the Old Testament teaches us (that) God told the
Israelites so many times, `If you want to have the faith to know
that I'm going to get you out of this little bit of trouble that
you're in, I want you to look back and see what I've done for you
in the past.' And that's gonna give you the faith to say, `If God
didn't abandon us then, he won't abandon us now,' '' Chrisman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think that's what the hymns do. I think we can look back
at those hymns and go, you know these are the songs that our
fathers worshiped to and our grandfathers worshiped to. Why do we
feel like we've got to throw them out just because we're the next
generation?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 1701EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
