<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ARGENTINE-0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICAN NEWSPAPER SAYS ARGENTINE HERE COULD BE WANTED TORTURER
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 2000 News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A high-profile Argentine businessman accused of
being a wanted torturer during Argentina's dictatorship is in
custody here, pending possible attempts to extradite him to Spain
to face charges of terrorism, torture and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of an explosive newspaper report here, Mexican
police detained Argentine Ricardo Miguel Cavallo in Cancun, Mexico,
as he was boarding a Thursday afternoon flight bound for Buenos
Aires, Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican police stopped Cavallo _ who has offered conflicting
information about his past _ on suspicions he may have falsified
his identity. The bespectacled businessman has been working here on
a legal work visa, directing Mexico's privately-run National
Registry of Motor Vehicles, a program started to help control
Mexico's problem with car theft.
</P>
<P>
   The registry has been in the news lately because of complaints
that it is redundant and costly. A lengthy investigative report
published Thursday by Mexico's Reforma Newspaper on Cavallo's
alleged sordid past has added to a sense of scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Based on testimony by five torture victims, Spanish court
documents and comparative photographs, Reforma's investigation
suggests that Cavallo, 48, is actually Miguel Angel Cavallo, a Navy
captain accused of atrocities committed against political prisoners
held during Argentina's 1976-1983 dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Among other ex-military officials from Argentina, Spanish Judge
Baltasar Garzon has accused Miguel Angel Cavallo of committing
atrocities at Argentina's infamous Naval Mechanical School, a
well-known place of torture during the regime.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish judge has implicated Cavallo in the murder of at
least two people, the disappearance of another and the torture of
others, according to Reforma. The judge also, ironically, accuses
Cavallo by of stealing the cars of victims and falsifying
documents.
</P>
<P>
   After being shown photographs, five former political prisoners
in Argentina told Reforma they believed Cavallo had tortured them
and others.
</P>
<P>
   They said he was known by various nicknames, including
``Serpico.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's him. I'd stake my life on it,'' a former prisoner named
Mario Villani was quoted in Reforma as saying. ``I can forget a lot
of things, but never the faces of those I met while in captivity.''
</P>
<P>
   Garzon is the same Spanish judge who tried to have Great Britain
extradite former Chilean dictator Augusto Pinochet to Spain on
similar charges.
</P>
<P>
   Angered at the failure to bring abusers to justice in Chile and
other Latin American dictatorships, activists have hailed
international attempts to extradite figures like Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy this month a former military officer was detained on a
request by French officials who want to question him about the
disappearance of a French woman in Argentina during the
dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   An amnesty law in Argentina has absolved military officials from
prosecution for atrocities, although some have been implicated
recently in the theft and illegal adoption of babies born to
prisoners who were killed in captivity after giving birth.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina recognizes that at least 9,000 people vanished and
were presumed killed during the military government, which went on
a witch hunt against anyone it deemed ``subversive.''
</P>
<P>
   If Cavallo is positively identified, the Spanish government
would have to officially request his extradition, said Mexican
legal expert Ignacio Burgoa.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish officials are reportedly reviewing the case now.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Mexico extradited a suspected Basque terrorist to
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday there were conflicting reports in Mexican and
Argentine news organizations on whether Cavallo had confirmed to
police that he was Miguel Angel Cavallo.
</P>
<P>
   The office of Mexico's Attorney General declined to confirm or
deny any of the
</P>
<P>
   reports.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Ferriss can be e-mailed at: susanf(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
