<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2263 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS &LR;      08-25 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE AND BUSH: START WITH A LAUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HELEN THOMAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Humor goes a long way in politics. If Vice
President Al Gore and Texas Governor George W. Bush want to grab
the attention of their audiences, they would do well to tear a page
out of new book by Liz Carpenter titled: ``Start with a laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter, a former Texas newspaperwoman who was Lady Bird
Johnson's press secretary and a speechwriter for President Lyndon
B. Johnson, has a sure-fire formula for speechwriting: ``Start with
a laugh, put the meat in the middle and wave the flag at the end.''
Renowned for her warmth and wit, she always leaves them laughing.
</P>
<P>
   As the politicians drone on during the campaign, it is amazing
how little humor they manage to muster. Of course, there are still
some southern-style, suspender-snapping old-time politicians around
_ but not many.
</P>
<P>
   Some past occupants in the White House had a sense of humor and,
as Carpenter points out, it served them well at times.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kennedy was noted for his quick wit and one-liners.
Johnson was a good storyteller and a great mimic, especially when
mocking his political enemies.
</P>
<P>
   In her book, Carpenter recalls some humorous presidential
anecdotes from the past.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that when Will Rogers called on an anxious President
Warren Harding during the Teapot Dome scandal, he told Harding:
``I'd like to tell you some of my latest jokes, Mr. President.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, you won't have to do that, Will,'' said Harding. ``I
appointed them.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rogers visited the White House in the FDR era, he asked
first lady Eleanor Roosevelt where the president was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever you hear laughter,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter also recalled a Kennedy speech to the White House
Correspondents Association. The president, who had been accused of
nepotism when he appointed his brother Bobby as the attorney
general, told the gathering that ``Bobby wants to practice law and
I thought he ought to get a little experience.''
</P>
<P>
   She also tells how Kennedy was able to disarm critics who
claimed that he was using his father's riches to buy the primary
election in West Virginia in 1960. Hubert Humphrey, Kennedy's chief
rival in that contest, thought so too. Nor were the rumors
dispelled after Kennedy won big. He managed to clear the air,
however, when he appeared at a Gridiron Dinner, pulled a piece of
paper from his pocket and said he wanted to read a telegram from
his father which said: ``Dear Jack, don't go after Alaska and
Hawaii. You don't need them and I can't afford them.''
</P>
<P>
   Since LBJ was her boss, Carpenter was able to recount Johnson's
humor best of all.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was a well-known telephone addict. He once called Ohio
Congressman Wayne Hayes at 1 a.m. and said: ``Did I wake you,
Wayne?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, Mr. President,'' Hayes replied. ``I was just lying here
waiting for your call.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter said Johnson was always determined to have his words
understood by the man on the street.
</P>
<P>
   When he read a draft of a speech quoting Aristotle, the Greek
philosopher, he turned to the startled speechwriter and said:
``Aristotle! These folks don't know who Aristotle is.'' Then he
picked up a pen, scratched out the reference to Aristotle and
scribbled in: ``As my dear old daddy used to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter recounts President Ronald Reagan's one-liners when he
was shot in an assassination attempt in 1981. ``Honey, I forgot to
duck,'' Reagan told his wife Nancy.
</P>
<P>
   As he was about to go into surgery at George Washington
hospital, Reagan looked up at the surgeons and expressed the hope
that they were all Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Self-deprecating humor by presidents goes over big with
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   When the Whitewater investigation first surfaced, President
Clinton attended a White House Correspondents Association dinner
and said: ``I'm happy to be here. I am really delighted to be here.
If you believe that I've really got some land in northwest Arkansas
I'd like to show you.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton then recalled that the press dinners began in 1944 when
President Roosevelt delivered his fireside chats over radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not much different today except that you insist that the
president sit directly on the logs.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter says psychologists confirm the bonding influence of
humor. The presidential candidates would do well to heed Mark
Twain's observation:``Against the onslaught of humor, nothing
stands.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remember that old adage that starts ``With friends like that''
</P>
<P>
   Can Vice President Al Gore be his own man only when President
Clinton is not around? Apparently so. In the manner of the
``Survivor'' television series, the president has been kicked off
the island and told to get lost so that he doesn't detract from
Gore's election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is now telling reporters that he is willing to do
whatever is asked of him but he also says ``the most important
thing is for the candidates to carry the message to the people and
I think they are doing a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Helen Thomas can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address helent (at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
