<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2266 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-LOBBY-AROMATHERAPY-AR     08-25 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOBBY-AROMATHERAPY-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING THE SWEET SMELL OF SUCCESS TO A NEW LEVEL OF LITERALNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sunday, August 27) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What does the lobby of your building smell like?
Disinfectant? Wet dog? If you're one of the 13 purchasers of
multimillion-dollar apartments in the Loft SoHo building opening at
30 Crosby Street in the fall, expect ylang-ylang and rose oil.
</P>
<P>
   The developers of the luxury property had already planned
mind-boggling amenities _ a wine cellar and wine-tasting room,
leather walls, personal garbage systems, which automatically sort
the recycling _ when they decided that what they really needed was
a custom lobby scent. No other building in New York has one.
Nothing as bourgeois as, say, fig. And nothing as overt as the
stuff sprayed with stealth force by women in black overcoats on the
first floor of Bloomingdale's.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was subtly to affect the mood of Lenny Kravitz, Liv
Tyler and the other well-heeled residents, who will soon be closing
on apartments where aromatherapy hits them when they walk through
the door. The scents will change with the time of day and the
season. ``We decided that in the morning, there should be something
invigorating,'' said Edward Baquero, a managing partner of Landmark
Development, the building's developer. ``A sort of
great-day-seize-the-moment kind of scent. And when they come home,
it should be more a feeling of serenity. A sense of calmness.''
</P>
<P>
   The developer turned to Aveda, the aromatherapy behemoth, to
design the scents, which will circulate through the lobby via the
building's duct system, using a technology from England that pumps
the essential oils into the air. ``It won't be a blast,'' said
Daria Myers, the senior vice president for global marketing at
Aveda. ``It is very subtle. Very ambient. And you will feel that
change in moods as you walk through the lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers said that while the Japanese sometimes waft aromas through
the air of office buildings or hospitals, the idea has not taken
hold in this country. Consultants from Japan and England weighed
in, and an herbalist was brought in on the project, as Myers said,
``to determine the organic certification and the functionality'' of
each essential oil. (This is the company, after all, that
trademarked the name Pure-fumes to describe its organic essential
oils.)
</P>
<P>
   Aveda executives did not want to reveal their special
concoctions for The Loft. In fact, the scents are still being
finalized. (Each component, Myers said, must undergo ``mood
mapping,'' which tests their psychological effects.)
</P>
<P>
   But the scent meant to do all the top-of-the-morning work is
likely to include a grapefruit note, which is known to be
refreshing, as well as essences of peppermint, orange and cinnamon,
which offer a similar boost. In the evening, residents will be
soothed by lavender, which is said to relax, and ylang-ylang and
rose oil. There might be some lemon in there, which is deodorizing.
</P>
<P>
   In cold weather, warming scents will be added; in the summer,
cooler notes. The building's interior designer, Benjamin
Noriega-Ortiz, will sign off on each.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really go over the top,'' Baquero said. In a building where
apartments sell for $2.5 million to $7.5 million, does this seem in
any way surprising?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
