<HEADLINE>
FROM THE DEPTHS, RETAIL STOCKS LOOK FOR AIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 27) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What with a climb in interest rates, poor weather and a hangover
from Year 2000 computer problems, retailers' stocks have been about
as popular as last year's fashions. The question is whether they
are distressed merchandise or a legitimate bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Since mid-April, the Standard &AMP; Poor's retail stores composite
index has tumbled 20 percent _ a decline that analysts attribute
mainly to market recognition that, sooner or later, the Federal
Reserve always gets its way. And the Fed's chairman, Alan
Greenspan, wants consumers to stop spending so much, lest inflation
heats up.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have six rate hikes without people feeling nervous''
about a diminished impetus to shop, said Carole Cranmer, a retail
analyst at Josephthal &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts are divided. Some say retail stocks have probably
hit bottom, while others, like Ursula Moran of Sanford Bernstein,
advise patience, predicting that prices will be marked down still
further.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Fed wins, it means that spending decelerates,'' Moran
said. ``But history suggests we're not out of the woods yet.'' She
noted that it took about a year for retail stock prices to turn
higher after the Fed ended its last round of rate increases in
1995. And while the Fed passed up a chance to raise rates last
week, it is not yet certain that it is through for this round.
</P>
<P>
   Still, income and job growth are stronger than they were in
1995, and store executives have quickly learned to harness
technology to prevent too much inventory buildup, long a major
vulnerability of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There still appears to be the ability to spend,'' said Susan
M. Sterne, proprietor of Economic Analysis Associates, which
studies consumer behavior. ``I think people are too negative on the
stocks; they're running away from them too fast.''
</P>
<P>
   With some notable exceptions, the stock prices show the damage:
Wal-Mart, the world's biggest retailer, is 27 percent below its New
Year's Eve high of $70.25. Among others, Federated Department
Stores is down 45 percent this year, Gap 42 percent, Circuit City
40 percent, Saks 31 percent, Home Depot 26 percent and Lands' End
24 percent. And Gottschalks, a West Coast chain, trades at just six
times earnings, in contrast to an industry average of 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very weak spring season'' for merchants, Sterne said.
The expected business surge from Y2K has not occurred this year,
she noted, although it helped produce a fabulous final 1999
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies missed their profit and revenue targets in the
second quarter, and others, including Wal-Mart and Target, warned
of shortfalls in the current one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are starting to see the deceleration'' in spending that
Greenspan has been trying to engineer, said George Strachan, senior
retail analyst at Goldman Sachs, citing a small decline in
comparable-store sales in July, the first monthly contraction since
November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Strachan has removed several of the stocks from his
recommended list. And he assigns only a market weighting for the
discounters, which generally cope best when business slackens,
gaining market share at department stores' expense.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeffrey Feiner, retail analyst at Lehman Brothers, is
upbeat. ``You typically buy the retail stocks when the news gets
most negative,'' because they tend to lead the business cycle,
Feiner said. ``Most of the downside is already fully priced into
the stocks.'' He predicted a rebound in the first half of next
year, perhaps earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Although some carriage-trade stores like Tiffany have thrived
during the economic boom, their stocks have not kept pace. For
bargain hunters, however, analysts favor companies like the rapidly
expanding Target _ formerly Dayton Hudson _ with a mostly
value-conscious core of customers.
</P>
<P>
   Another common recommendation is Wal-Mart. Although it has
withdrawn its ``always the lowest price'' pledge, it is still
oriented toward value. ``If consumers really cut back on spending,
many will be looking for bargains,'' Feiner said, and Wal-Mart can
use its muscle to beat the prices of the competition. Despite the
company's profit caution, Feiner reiterated his ``buy''
recommendation this month, as did Credit Suisse First Boston
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, however, downgraded the stock,
which carried a price-to-earnings multiple of 40 this summer, to
``market perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Venator, the former Woolworth's, has gained 111 percent this
year, and six Wall Street analysts forecast further gains, rating
it a buy or strong buy.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies that Wall Street likes are Talbots, a retailer
of classic women's apparel that is one of Merrill Lynch's favorite
stocks in any group, and Kohl's, a Wisconsin-based chain that sells
what Moran of Bernstein called a ``carefully edited'' selection of
brand-name household goods at highly competitive prices.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have spectacularly bucked the downward trend, and
the price of Kohl's stock is 58.5 times what the company is
expected to earn per share this year. But it could still be a
bargain, said Strachan of Goldman Sachs. With much of the country
yet to glimpse its first Kohl's, he called the company ``one of the
few blue-sky opportunities left in broad-line retailing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
