<HEADLINE>
BC-GARDENCOLUMN &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    TIPS HELP LAWNS SURVIVE THE HEAT
 &HT;    BY KATHY HUBER
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gardeners continue to write and call with lawn questions. The
following advice was gathered from turf pros, and in large part
from the specialists at Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   Proper mowing and watering will help pull St. Augustine lawns
through the extreme hot, dry conditions.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage a healthy St. Augustine turf, mow at the proper
height _ 2 1/2 to 3 inches. Mow hybrid Bermuda grass at 1/2 inch to
1 1/2 inches. Mow frequently, removing no more than a third of the
blade height. Frequent mowing encourages thicker turf, which in
turn lowers evaporative water loss. Leave the clippings on the lawn
to break down and replenish nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid excessive thatch, the nondecomposed organic matter between
the soil surface and the base of the blades. Heavy thatch _ caused
by overfertilization, overwatering and improper mowing _ slows
water intake and can become a home for pests.
</P>
<P>
   Aerate. Not enough can be said about this simple practice that
improves air and water movement in the soil.
</P>
<P>
   Water properly to promote good lawn health and to conserve
water. Do not apply water faster than the soil can absorb it. Water
early in the day, when the sun is less intense, temperatures are
lower and, in most cases, there's no wind. These conditions
decrease evaporation.
</P>
<P>
   Water deeply and slowly. If you sprinkle water lightly, you'll
only encourage the roots to rise to the moisture, where they will
be subject to higher temperatures and will dry quickly. Encourage
roots to grow downward by applying enough water to wet the soil 6
inches down. This, in turn, will better arm the turf against
drought stress.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M turfgrass extension specialist Gene R. Taylor II says
1/2 inch of water (irrigation or rainfall) every four to five days
should provide adequate moisture for the average Houston lawn. A
half-inch of water, he says, will wet a clay soil down to the
desired 6-inch depth, assuming the lawn has received irrigation or
rain in the past week or so.
</P>
<P>
   If a clay soil is completely dry, however, it will take a little
more than 1 inch of water to wet to a depth of 6 inches. Since
water infiltrates a clay soil at a rate of less than 1/4 inch per
hour, it's best to run sprinklers long enough to apply 1/4 inch,
turn them off and allow the water to soak in. This minimizes
surface runoff. Then turn the sprinklers on again to complete
irrigation.
</P>
<P>
   According to A&AMP;M studies, it takes about 3/4 inch of water to
wet a dry loam 6 inches down, and 1/2 inch to travel 6 inches down
in a sandy soil.
</P>
<P>
   To measure how much your sprinkler waters in a set amount of
time, the A&AMP;M experts suggest placing three to five short-sided,
open-top cans in a line that starts near the sprinkler and
continues to the edge of the sprinkler's coverage. Let the
sprinkler run for 30 minutes, then measure and average the amount
in the cans. Determine the depth of wet soil. If there's 1/2 inch
in the cans and the soil is wet 6 inches down, irrigation is
complete. If the average amount is 1/2 inch of water and the
moisture depth is 3 inches, turn the sprinkler on for another
half-hour to wet soil to the desired 6-inch depth.
</P>
<P>
   Then, if hot, dry conditions persist, apply another 1/2 inch of
water in four to five days.
</P>
<P>
   Visit the Texas Nursery &AMP; Landscape Association's Web site at
www.txnla.org for more consumer drought information. Also useful is
www.waterwisetexas.org.
</P>
<P>
   It's best to keep nitrogen levels low during drought conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Apply a high-potassium fertilizer in the fall to encourage good
root development over the winter months.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; Could you please tell me where to get skyflower vine? &QL; 
_ L.M., Houston, Texas &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Local nurseries carry this vine on occasion. I would just
ask when it will be available. Skyflower (Thunbergia grandiflora):
A deciduous perennial vine, skyflower produces orchidlike
lavender-blue blooms late summer to frost or well into spring after
a mild winter. Plant this rapid grower in sun or filtered sun in a
soil rich in organic matter. It will freeze to the ground during a
cold winter, so mulch to protect roots. It should return from the
roots in spring.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Huber is the Houston Chronicle's garden editor.
</P>
<P>
