<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: For free trade, but not Castro
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush pledged today to breathe new life into stalled
free-trade negotiations with Latin America if elected president,
and to retain all current sanctions on Fidel Castro's Cuba. ``My
word to you, Mr. Castro: Let your people live in freedom,'' Bush
said in a Miami speech outlining his foreign policy goals for the
Western Hemisphere. That statement prompted a standing ovation from
the Cuban-Americans in the audience. In advance of a meeting in
Dallas with Mexico's President-elect Vicente Fox, Bush also
reiterated an intention to hire more border enforcement officers.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN GOES IT ALONE
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lieberman made his first solo outing as a vice presidential
nominee today, blasting the Republican tax cut plan and saying he
wants to help families ``win the competition'' against violence in
popular culture. In Claymont, Del., a suburb of Wilmington,
Lieberman promoted Al Gore's plan for targeted tax cuts for
middle-income families. He disputed George W. Bush's argument that
the Democratic plan would bypass many needy families. ``We believe
in using our prosperity to target tax cuts to the working class
families who need it most,'' he told a crowd of about 300
Democratic activists.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY: WORTH HIS PENSION
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney vehemently defended his work in the oil services
business, bristling at any suggestion that he was less than
successful as the CEO of Halliburton. And he insisted once more
that as vice president he would take steps to ensure that his
multimillion-dollar retirement package from Halliburton Co. did not
pose a conflict of interest. ``We went from being a second-tier,
second-rank energy services company to being the biggest in the
world,'' he said in Central Point, Ore. Cheney complained that the
New York Times report characterizing his record at Halliburton as
mixed was ``a distortion,'' ``bad journalism'' and ``seriously
flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN UNDER THE KNIFE AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan is recovering at Washington Hospital Center after
undergoing a second round of surgery to treat gall bladder disease.
The Reform Party presidential candidate was suffering from what his
campaign called ``severe abdominal pain.'' ABC News reported that
doctors determined the pain resulted from a gallstone that wasn't
removed when his gall bladder was taken out in a previous surgery
last week. Buchanan is expected to be released later today or
Saturday morning. He is not expected to return to the campaign
trail until after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   YOU'VE GOT TO HAVE HEART
</P>
<P>
   Ever since his campaign began, George W. Bush has tried to shuck
one central notion: that he doesn't have the brains for the job.
But campaign officials recently have worked to head off a second
``Wizard of Oz''-style problem: that he doesn't have the heart for
a tough campaign. This campaign will be won on issues and ideas,
they say. The issue of drive bubbled up again last week as Bush,
after the Democratic convention, cut short a single stop in Memphis
to return to Texas to jog at a favorite athletic club. And Bush's
tentative schedule leading up to Labor Day also indicates that
he'll be on the campaign trail four days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-SEMITIC GRAFFITI
</P>
<P>
   Someone scrawled an anti-Semitic message in the local
Gore-Lieberman campaign headquarters in Chico, Calif., a Democratic
Party activist says. Bob Ray said he arrived at the office and
found ``No Jew in the White House'' written in ink in big letters
across two large erasable boards and a planning calendar. Police
Lt. Mike Simpson said investigators were told a campaign worker
left the office unlocked Wednesday night, and there were no
suspects. Ray said he plans to keep the message up to remind them
of the importance of the election. Chico is 100 miles north of
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   NEW ADS AIMED AT SENIORS
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's campaign introduced a new TV spot today about
Social Security, Medicare and prescription drugs into 21 states
they had already targeted as the campaign ad war heats up. In
addition, the Republican Party is set to start next week with an ad
buy worth millions of dollars in just nine states. Says Bush in the
ad: ``We will make prescription drugs available and affordable for
every senior who needs them. . . . President George W. Bush will
keep the promise of Social Security. No changes. No reductions. No
way.'' The ad is a blend of Bush's comments with scenes of older
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   BUSHES HIGH ON FLORIDA CHANCES
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush rounded up $1.5 million for Florida's Republican
Party at a closed-door reception in a private Coral Gables, Fla.,
enclave. ``I intend to contest this state,'' Bush said as he
arrived at Miami International Airport. ``We have a good chance of
winning.'' Looking around and not seeing his brother, Gov. Jeb
Bush, the candidate joked, ``I'm a little disappointed the chairman
of my campaign is late.'' The Bushes are confident that they can
carry Florida, where Democratic presidential candidates have
prevailed only three times in 50 years. But the Democrats are
making a full-court press for the state.
</P>
<P>
   KOSHER MEAL AT FUND-RAISER
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore pulled in more than $1.25 million at a pair of
fund-raising dinners in Washington for the Democratic Party. The
first dinner drew 30 people, most of them Indian-Americans. The
second dinner drew about 60 people, most of them friends of Joe
Lieberman, who also attended. Both dinners were served at the
Mayflower Hotel, but the second was a Glatt Kosher meal, the pure
form of Kosher food, blessed by a rabbi and provided by a
restaurant, Dahan of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   DEBATE, OR THEY MIGHT SUE
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has accepted a debate invitation from Judicial Watch, a
conservative group that is one of the Clinton administration's
harshest critics. The proposed Oct. 20 debate would be on how a new
president can ``return ethics to our government.'' George W. Bush
has yet to accept any debate proposals for the fall. The two
campaigns have squabbled in recent days over the timing and number
of debates between their presidential candidates and between their
running mates. Judicial Watch has filed a series of lawsuits
against the Clinton administration on issues ranging from access to
FBI files to missing White House e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   LIKE HEMLINES AND THE STOCK MARKET
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader shrugged off a poll that showed him mired in the
single-digits in California. ``They go up and down,'' said Nader,
who is on the biggest fund-raising swing of his campaign. ``Look at
Gore and Bush's numbers in the last few weeks: They go up and
down.'' Nader was in Sacramento, winding up a five-day trip to the
nation's most populous state, a favorite destination of politicians
hunting for campaign cash. The Field Poll showed Nader supported by
4 percent of likely California voters, statistically unchanged from
the 7 percent he drew in a June survey.
</P>
<P>
   SOFT MONEY FLOWS LIKE OIL
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee collected almost $800,000 in
unregulated ``soft money'' donations from energy companies after
George W. Bush tapped Halliburton CEO Dick Cheney as his running
mate. The $791,100 in energy contributions during the last week of
July were part of the $25.2 million in soft money that the RNC took
in last month. Some energy companies had not given any soft money
this year until Cheney joined the ticket. Cheney headed the oil
services company for five years after serving in Congress and as
secretary of defense; Bush also is an ex-oil executive.
</P>
<P>
   IT PAYS TO SAVE
</P>
<P>
   The head of the House Republicans' fund-raising arm is urging
GOP lawmakers to save their campaign treasuries for the fall, not
drain them to respond to Democratic ads now on the air. ``The most
important thing right now is for you to be frugal with your
campaign resources, resources that you will need to control
October,'' Rep. Tom Davis of Virginia, head of the National
Republican Congressional Committee, wrote House Republicans this
week. Though it leads in fund-raising, the GOP committee has put
less money in the bank than its Democratic counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   MONUMENTS MADE TO TOPPLE?
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney raised the possibility that some of the new national
monuments created by President Clinton could be reviewed and
possibly rescinded if he and George W. Bush are elected in
November. ``Of course it's not my decision to make. It's the
president-elect who has to make the decision,'' Cheney said. He
said Clinton has used his executive authority ``willy-nilly all
over the West'' to create national monuments covering nearly 4
million acres without considering the desires of the people
affected. Many fear it could harm the Western economy by removing
land from uses like grazing, logging and mining.
</P>
<P>
   CUTTING AWAY ON TAX CUTS
</P>
<P>
   Rick Lazio, Hillary Clinton's Senate opponent in New York, moved
to distance himself from George W. Bush's tax cut plan by offering
a package that is nearly 40 percent smaller than Bush's. Lazio's
proposal includes a call to allow taxpayers to deduct Social
Security payments from their federal income taxes. Lazio said his
total proposal would save the average New York family about $3,000
a year. This week, Bush has found himself defending the fiscal
prudence of his $1.3 trillion, 10-year tax cut, in the face of
attacks by Democrats and polling data suggesting that the idea has
not stirred much voter interest.
</P>
<P>
   MORE TEXAS INMATES GETTING OUT
</P>
<P>
   The July parole rate in Texas reached its highest point in any
month since George W. Bush became governor in 1994, but the parole
board head, Gerald Garrett, says politics played no role. Nearly 29
percent of eligible convicts were approved for parole in July,
statistics show. A year ago, the figure was 18 percent. The Texas
Department of Criminal Justice said July's parole rate was the
highest for any month since July 1994, when the board approved 31.8
percent of cases considered. Top lawmakers and state officials have
said Texas's $610 million budget overruns are in part to blame on a
higher prison population in county jails because of tougher parole
rules.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
