<HEADER>
A2280 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-FITCAMP1STTAKE     08-25 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FITCAMP1STTAKE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The skinny on a central tennessee fitness spa where sweat-soaked
guests lose for less
 &HT;    Eds:Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 27.
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAYNE COUNTY, Tenn. _ The hills are alive with the sound of
groaning.
</P>
<P>
   Yet no matter how much we wail, grunt and pant, the rolling
countryside around the Tennessee Fitness Spa remains serene. It is
another hot, still morning in a week of such mornings, which means
we're on another March of Pain. Grudgingly we trudge toward
Heartbreak Hill, one of several aptly named rises along our walking
course.
</P>
<P>
   Gnats buzz about our ears and eyes, oblivious to our frantic
shooing. Turtles poke their heads out of a trailside pond. Tadpoles
dart to and fro in puddles along the rutted path.
</P>
<P>
   In the spa's emu paddock, a gaggle of pop-eyed ostrich wannabes
look on curiously as we file by, cursing the merciless late summer
sun. Their quizzical stares seem to say, ``Who are these mad
creatures, with their sweaty pelts and pinched faces?''
</P>
<P>
   We are a diverse group _ in age, class and temperament _ who
have come to this 100-acre retreat in Nowheresville, Tenn., 173
miles west of Chattanooga, for reasons various. We are a single
mother from Sandy Springs, Ga., taking a break from the rigors of
raising two kids under 7. We are a professor from Nashville fed up
with being stressed out and grouchy.
</P>
<P>
   We are an Indiana flight attendant looking for a vacation that
doesn't involve getting on a plane _ again! We are a travel writer
for a newspaper that covers Dixie like the dew, on an assignment
that has turned quite personal after a disastrous trip to the
scales.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us are fairly fit, some fairly not. Our generational
touchstones range from the World War II to Watergate to Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   Different people, united in soreness.
</P>
<P>
   And in purpose. For we don't consider this punishment, but a
means to a reward. Together, we walk for miles and miles along
forested trails and country roads, only to return to the spa
facilities and immediately begin lifting, lunging and stepping.
</P>
<P>
   We subsist on small meals _ scraps, really, compared with our
usual biggie-size rations. Evenings, we collapse exhausted into our
beds at an early hour, so we can get up and do it all again
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Because we all have one goal: to leave a part of ourselves
behind in this bucolic refuge.
</P>
<P>
   A big, jiggly part.
</P>
<P>
   Camp Value
</P>
<P>
   The place is misnamed. That soft, feminine three-letter word _
spa_ just doesn't fit. Suggesting pampering and luxury, it probably
accounts for the dearth of Y chromosomes here on any given day. The
spa averages 30 guests a week, and the ratio of female-to-male
guests is usually around 10 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   But there's nothing soft about the intense, exhilarating workout
one experiences under the guidance of the gung-ho staff. If you
feel ``pampered'' after one of drill sergeant, excuse me, fitness
director Pam Hampton's aerobics classes, then you've probably come
straight from a Louisiana chain gang.
</P>
<P>
   The backwoods setting doesn't scream ``spa'' either. The
compound is nestled next to a sorghum-slow creek in a thicket of
oak, poplar and sweetgum trees. It sits in front of Natural Bridge,
an awesome double-span rock formation that juts over a natural
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like camp,'' notes Jeanne Fuchs, 50, an elementary school
teacher from Gainesville, Fla. ``I'm an outdoor type of person, so
this appeals to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Accommodations are clean but spartan _ no TV in most rooms, and
if you want a phone, you have to rent one. The athletic facilities,
including a junior Olympic-size pool, a racquetball court and a gym
for aerobics and weight training are adequate but would never be
mistaken for a Bally's or Australian Body Works. Meals are served
in a quaint, countrified dining hall.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are the requisite facial-manicure-massage services
(which cost extra), but they take a back seat to the central
concept: no-nonsense fitness and nutrition instruction at an
affordable price. One of the cheapest of its kind in the country,
the spa attracts visitors who can't afford to put a foot in
California's Golden Door and other high-end retreats, which can
charge upwards of $5,000 a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there are rich people who wouldn't want to come here
_ they would want to go hang out with other rich people,'' says
Sandy Seidel, from Potomac, Md. (There are quite a few teachers
here this week. Could educators be more open to improving
themselves than other professions? Discuss.)
</P>
<P>
   Seidel, 54, isn't drawn to the deluxe lodgings and gourmet fare
offered at the posh spas. ``I don't need fancy,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   To save money, she caught a Greyhound to Nashville and met the
spa's shuttle there. She booked a bed in one of the four-person
``quads,'' which she shared with two strangers. Meals are included
in the price, so she didn't have to spend big bucks eating out.
``With transportation and everything, it cost me $800 for the
week,'' she says proudly.
</P>
<P>
   Even affluent guests appreciate the cut-rate cost. Quoth Ainslie
Todd, aka Mrs. T. Hardy Todd III, a member in good standing of the
Memphis Garden Club: ``All women love a bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   An inexpensive alternative to glitzy health retreats was what
owners Joe and Nancy Shaw were counting on when they opened the spa
in 1991. ``I wanted to do something for middle America,'' says Joe
Shaw, who admits that he also wanted to keep the risk low for his
first spa venture.
</P>
<P>
   Born in nearby Lawrenceburg, Shaw, 66, struck it rich as a gold
miner and real estate investor in Alaska before retiring to Florida
in 1980. Remembering Natural Bridge from family trips, he returned
to the once-popular tourist attraction in 1990 and found it ``a
shambles. The weeds were head-high, and all the buildings were
falling in.''
</P>
<P>
   By coincidence, a real estate agent was also visiting the
property that day and told Shaw it was for sale. He snapped it up
and began designing a spa based on others he had visited, including
the National Institute of Fitness (now called Red Mountain) in
Ivins, Utah. He spread the word through ads in fitness magazines
and regional newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We struggled for the first few years,'' Shaw recalls, but says
the business is now profitable. He believes the spa has succeeded
because of its we're-all-in-this-together atmosphere. ``It's very
egalitarian here. Once you get your sweats on, it doesn't matter if
you're worth $5 million or $5,000.''
</P>
<P>
   And all the Coca-Cola stock in the world won't help you when you
face ... the weigh-in.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
