<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2281 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-FITCAMP2NDTAKE     08-25 1845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FITCAMP2NDTAKE27-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   WAYNE COUNTY, Tenn.: you face ... the weigh-in.
</P>
<P>
   A plus-size surprise
</P>
<P>
   This can't be right. Surely the scales must be broken. 185
pounds? But I weighed 155 just recently. OK, 12 years ago, but
still ...
</P>
<P>
   Here it is, the ugly truth: All guests face the dreaded
``fitness assessment'' the day they arrive. The staff weighs you
and takes measurements of your chest, stomach, arms, hips and
thighs, then factors the figures to determine your body fat
percentage. For me, that result is bad enough _ I carry 30 percent
body fat, several notches over the norm. But it's the weight figure
that really smarts.
</P>
<P>
   If there were a window in the weighing room, I could have
watched my reporter's objectivity fly out of it. Suddenly, I'm in
this to lose _ and lose big _ just like my spa-mates.
</P>
<P>
   As I talk with them I begin to hear myself in their confessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like to eat carbs and salt,'' admits Molly Wender,
the Sandy Springs single mom. (Don't we all, Molly.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the type of person who is good for three months, then bad
for three months,'' says Patye White, the Indiana flight attendant.
(Been there, sister.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here to get away from the refrigerator,'' Walt Inge, a
free-lance medical writer from northeast Atlanta, confides. ``I
work at home, so I'm about five steps away from a big block of
cheddar cheese.'' (Mmmm, cheese.)
</P>
<P>
   Wender, 38, echoes the feelings of anticipation and apprehension
most of us have the first day. ``I'd love to lose weight, but I
don't want to set myself up for disappointment,'' says the pretty,
soft-spoken jewelry designer, who sells her sterling and pearl
pieces at the Dogwood Festival and Dakota J's in Altanta, among
other outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Wender's sons, Max, 6, and Sam, 3, are visiting Dad for the
week, giving Mom a rare break to concentrate on herself. ``This is
like a dream,'' she says of her first spa visit. ``I can't believe
I'm really doing this.'' An athletic youngster _ she swam
competitively in high school _ Wender has found that there is
little room for exercise in a mother's hectic schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be very careful with my time,'' she says. ``I've
tried to schedule an hour a day for me.'' She hopes the spa stay
will be the beginning of a more consistent fitness regimen.
</P>
<P>
   Most guests, in fact, say they came for a ``jump-start.'' If
that's so, the fitness staff here is more than ready to boost us
into action.
</P>
<P>
   Will work out for food
</P>
<P>
   ``This ain't no powderpuff stroll'' reads the caption on one of
the spa's T-shirts. Believe it.
</P>
<P>
   The six-day workout program, Monday to Saturday, begins at 8
each morning with the walk. Guests select one of three groups.
``C'' group starts out walking two miles on Monday and works up to
five on Saturday. ``B'' group goes from three to eight miles, and
the superhumans in ``A'' group go from five to 10. Those who find
trekking too strenuous can take water walking classes in the pool.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Carolyn Everston started when she first came here
three years ago. ``I was too out of shape to do the walk,'' she
remembers. A research methodology professor at Peabody College in
Nashville, Everston, 65, says she first sought out the spa because
``I was in a high stress job, I had put on weight, and I was always
in a bad mood.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen visits later (``I come here whenever it gets to be too
much''), she's happier, slimmer, and charging ahead with the ``A''
group.
</P>
<P>
   Torn between macho pride and a fear of overexertion, I choose
``B.'' My main walking buddies for the week are Sharon Ponte, of
Vandalia, Ohio, and Michele Taylor, of Nashville, a mother and
daughter who came here for a little one-on-one time.
</P>
<P>
   We are constantly dropping our birdies.
</P>
<P>
   That is, the loose upraised fists walk director Jeff Holt
informs us we should stride with as if we were cradling baby chicks
_ instead of dangling hands. This promotes upper body toning and
prevents swelling in the fingertips, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have your birdies?'' Holt crows when he sees our hands
go slack. We are also supposed to clutch imaginary quarters between
our ... well, let's just says it's an exercise to tone the gluteal
muscles.
</P>
<P>
   After the walk, we head straight for stretch class, a soothing
half-hour of yoga-style flexing. Then it's back to the grind in a
daunting succession of workouts, including aerobic boxing,
abdominal toning, weight training, indoor volleyball (called
Wallyball), step aerobics and aquacise.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance is optional for each _ the staff urges us not to
overdo it, but does suggest we stick to a daily program of two
aerobics classes, a weight-training class and a stretch class,
along with four abs classes during the week. After dinner, there
are more activities, from spirited games of water volleyball to an
aggression-relieving self-defense demonstration by a local police
officer.
</P>
<P>
   For the first few days, many of us try to do everything. By
Wednesday, we've learned to take a few much-needed breaks during
the day. ``That's the way it always happens,'' Hampton says. ``By
Thursday afternoon, the gym looks like a ghost town.''
</P>
<P>
   The fitness regimen is only half of the equation. We're also on
a strict nutrition plan: 1,000 to 1,200 calories per day, not
counting trips to the all-veggie salad bar (no bacon bits here).
</P>
<P>
   That sounds like a starvation diet, but kitchen magicians Angela
Creecy and Belinda Jones make a little go a long way. The simple,
satisfying fare includes omelets and bagels for breakfast, grilled
chicken and taco salads for lunch, spaghetti, lasagna and sauteed
trout for dinner. All meat dishes are made with turkey; vegans can
order one of several tasty tofu entrees. For between-meal snacks,
there are seasoned baked potato wedges and apples.
</P>
<P>
   Though Creecy and Jones serve up a few clunkers _ not even
Emeril could conjure edible French Toast out of low-fat wheat bread
and Egg Beaters _ most meals are downright delicious.
</P>
<P>
   And filling. There are few complaints of hunger, and most of
those potato wedges remain in the mini-fridge. As Inge puts it
midweek, ``I thought I'd being gnawing on the doorknob by now, but
I'm fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Bringing it all back home
</P>
<P>
   Saturday is Judgment Day. After our final walk, we are reweighed
and remeasured to see how many pounds and inches we've shed. Like
the initial assessment, this one is private, but that doesn't stop
everybody from gathering in the rec room to compare stats.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did you do?'' we all ask excitedly, and cheer each other's
losses. Most of us have dropped between 2 and 6 pounds; Seidel took
off 5, Wender, 4. Taylor is celebrating even before she receives
her final body fat count. ``I've lost 5 1/2 pounds, the rest is
gravy,'' she declares, chuckling at the reference to forbidden
food.
</P>
<P>
   I am also 5 1/2 pounds lighter, perhaps a little more after I
burn a bunch of calories doing a happy-dance around the scales. And
my body fat has plummeted. OK, it's down 2 percent, but still, I
feel like Kate Moss.
</P>
<P>
   Even the people who didn't lose very much seem to think it's all
been worth it. White, who arrived in good shape, parted with only
three-quarters of a pound. Nevertheless, she says, ``This is the
best vacation I've had in my life. I love the way my days were
filled, I love the way my mind was healed, and I love the
camaraderie.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, fast friendships have bloomed all over the place. Like
kids at camp, we've forged attachments that look to last. At the
final lunch on Saturday, we're already reminiscing about our time
together.
</P>
<P>
   Who could forget Mary Ellen Borgelt, of Austin, Texas, crooning
loudly along to ``Breaking Up Is Hard to Do'' in aquacise class? Or
Flower Fajardo, of Tampa, razzing Holt during a particularly fierce
game of Wallyball (``Your team should be called the cow pies!'').
Or Todd sneaking into the kitchen to nab a pan of low-fat cookies
to munch on while we watched ``Sleepy Hollow'' in the TV room, only
to sputter in disgust when I took them back. (``You'll thank me at
your final assessment!'' I responded, taking a stab at being the
voice of reason while wilting under her hot scowl.)
</P>
<P>
   Back home in Sandy Springs a few days later, Wender is suffering
from spa withdrawal. ``I miss it,'' she confesses, talking on the
phone as she prepares lunch for Max and Sam.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the trip, she had steeled herself against
disappointment, but now says, ``I'm only disappointed that I had to
leave. I just loved exercising and being out in the country. It
helped me get my head in the right place to achieve my goals.''
</P>
<P>
   We both admit we'd like to lose a couple to 20 pounds more, and
discuss our efforts to continue the program. I've been walking four
miles in the morning, Wender's been alternating walks with
abdominal workouts. Our eating habits are also getting an overhaul:
Wender has motored to Harry's Farmer's Market in Alpharetta to
stock up on tofu and soy, while I came straight home and threw out
the full-fat mayonnaise. Bonding over shared objectives, we make
plans to go on occasional walks together.
</P>
<P>
   If you see us out around Stone Mountain or Piedmont Park, stop
and say hi. You'll recognize us by the determined look on our
faces.
</P>
<P>
   And our newly baggy workout clothes.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: The Tennessee Fitness Spa is near Waynesboro,
Tenn., about 290 miles from Atlanta. Take I-75 to Chattanooga, go
west on I-24. At the Monteagle/Sewanee exit, go west on U.S. 64 to
Waynesboro. In Waynesboro, take County Road 99 north to spa, about
10 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines offers Internet users discounts to Nashville
for $59 each way with a seven-day advance (Saturday night stay
required). Go to www.nwa.com, click on ``View All Promotions,''
click on Atlanta offers. The spa provides a shuttle service from
Nashville Airport, departing at 1 p.m. Sunday. There is a $50
pick-up fee.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  How much: Weekly rates for the discount periods now-Sept. 10,
Oct. 29-Dec. 3 and Feb. 20-March 12 are as follows: quad (women
only) _ $550; double _ $625-$700; private _ $925-$1,015; penthouse
(including 1 queen-size bed, two twin beds, kitchen, TV, VCR and
washer/dryer) _ $700-$1,215, based on single, double or triple
occupancy. All other times, add $45 for quad, $70-$75 for double,
$100-$110 for private, $70-$135 for penthouse. There are two
motorhome hook-ups; weekly rate for RVs is $385, plus a $50
one-time hook-up fee. Daily rates available with a two-night
minimum. Add 8.75 percent tax. Meals and classes are included.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What to bring: Reading materials, radio and/or Walkman, alarm
clock, sunhat and sunglasses, many changes of socks, at least two
pairs of walking and aerobic shoes, athletic wear, rain gear, swim
suit and water shoes (if desired), flashlight, water bottle and
fanny pack.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information and reservations: 1-800-235-8365; www.TFSpa.com.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Altanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
