<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2284 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-BOOKMAN-EDITORIAL0827     08-25 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKMAN-EDITORIAL0827-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Medical use of human embryos makes for challenging debate
 &HT;    By Jay Bookman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It seems, on its face, a step too far down a dangerous
road. The idea of destroying living human embryos so we can extract
cells to be used for medical research and treatment ... we can't go
there, no matter what benefits it might bring.
</P>
<P>
   Except...
</P>
<P>
   Except that the human embryos in question already exist and are
already being destroyed, even in the absence of stem-cell research.
As part of the process of in vitro fertilization, the increasingly
popular technique that allows infertile couples to have children,
more embryos are created than can be implanted. At the moment,
those surplus embryos are simply being destroyed and thrown away.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, embryonic stem cells might help the crippled to
walk again. They might restore minds lost to the ravages of
diseases such as Alzheimer's or Parkinson's, or to strokes. They
might also offer a cure to diseases such as juvenile diabetes and
some forms of cancer. In time, they may even be able to restore the
functions of almost any failing organ in the human body. Stem cells
have the potential capacity to perform all those healing miracles
because they can divide and create almost any kind of cell present
in the human body.
</P>
<P>
   For a lot of people, none of those ``excepts'' matters much. I
can understand their feeling. But for others _ me included _ they
do make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Unless we are willing to ban in vitro fertilization _ and nobody
in power is talking seriously about such a step _ human embryos
will continue to be created and discarded on a regular basis. Those
embryos are not being created for the purpose of being destroyed or
exploited; they are being created in honest hope of helping a
loving family bring a child into the world.
</P>
<P>
   Once those embryo have been created for a good purpose, and once
it has been determined that their purpose has been served and they
are destined to be destroyed, the moral landscape changes. We then
face a choice of simply discarding the embryos, or using them as
sources for cells that can be used to save human lives.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institutes of Health _ after a year-long process of
consultation with scientists, ethicists, religious and political
leaders and the general public _ has issued guidelines that dictate
how federally funded stem-cell research will be conducted. The
rules reflect a sober appreciation of the moral dangers and
potential benefits involved in the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Under the NIH funding guidelines, it would be illegal to create
embryos for the purpose of conducting stem-cell research or for
treatment. Only embryos that are created for the purposes of in
vitro fertilization, frozen for storage and then destined for
destruction could be diverted to such research. And to avoid the
commercialization of potential human life, embryos cannot be bought
or sold for purposes of research; they can only be donated.
</P>
<P>
   The NIH process _ and the dignity with which it was conducted _
can serve as an important model as we confront similarly complex
questions already on the horizon. The unraveling of the human
genetic code, for example, is certain to raise issues that our
existing moral guidelines do not address. Like stem-cell research,
genetic engineering spotlights the chasm that sometimes exists
between what we can do, and what we ought to do.
</P>
<P>
   Resolving such issues cannot be left to scientists alone; they
can and must play a role, but they are not equipped to make that
kind of decision for the rest of us, and it would be unfair to dump
that burden on them.
</P>
<P>
   And clearly, politicians can't handle the task either, at least
not without some help. Although in many cases the ultimate decision
will lay in the hands of elected leaders, they will need the
technical guidance of scientists and the moral direction of
religious leaders and ethicists. They'll also have to do some
searching of their own souls to guard against exploiting such
serious issues for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Jay Dickey (R-Ark.), for example, opposes use of
embryonic stem cells for either research or medical treatment.
That's a responsible, understandable position, founded in his
belief that human life begins at conception, even when that
conception occurs in a test tube. Unfortunately, however, Dickey is
unwilling to credit those who disagree with any similar degree of
thoughtfulness on the matter. In fact, after the NIH guidelines
were announced, Dickey dismissed them as a political ploy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration didn't have to bring this up right in the
middle of the election,'' he complained. ``Their concern is not so
much with science as it is with promoting the Clinton-Gore
pro-abortion agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion that political gain might be wrung from such an issue
is of course nonsense. But Dickey's accusation does illustrate the
danger inherent in debating such complex, heated issues in a
political context. A little mutual respect for the opinions of
others might go a long way as we wrestle with the challenges coming
our way.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
