<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2285 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-SUNBEAM-$ADV27-NY     08-25 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-SUNBEAM-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRINGING NEW ORDER TO SUNBEAM'S CHAOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 27) 
 By JANE TANNER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ In the last two and a half years, Jerry Levin
has managed to bring some order to the chaos that once prevailed at
the Sunbeam Corp., the household appliance maker that installed him
as chief executive after the notorious ouster of Albert Dunlap in
1998. But it has not been easy.
</P>
<P>
   He inherited a company that, after Dunlap's abrupt
reorganization, had factories that were in disarray, employees who
were demoralized and retailers who were infuriated.
</P>
<P>
   A former chief executive of both Revlon Inc. and the Coleman
Co., Levin, 56, was sent in by Ronald Perelman, the billionaire
financier who owns 34.5 percent of Sunbeam. Among Levin's burdens:
interest costs on $1.6 billion in long-term debt and $800 million
in zero-coupon bonds due in 2018 but redeemable in three years,
losses of $1.2 billion over the past two years and a continuing
Securities and Exchange Commission investigation into accusations
of accounting fraud that date from 1998. Dunlap has not gone away,
either. He contends that the company owes him $5 million in back
salary.
</P>
<P>
   Also clouding the picture is a consolidated shareholder lawsuit
that was filed after Sunbeam's stock fell 50 percent in one month
in early 1998. On Aug. 17 of this year, the stock hit a new low,
$1.75, and it closed at $2.06 on Friday. The suit contends, among
other things, that the company misrepresented the health of the
operations and future prospects to inflate the price of the stock.
A trial is set for next June.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the turmoil, analysts and shareholders give Levin credit
for improving operations. William Steele, an analyst at Banc of
America Securities, pointed to a number of signs of health,
including increased cash generated from sales _ $28 million, up
from $20 million last quarter _ and increased manufacturing
efficiency, demonstrated by Levin's ability to keep the gross
margin flat despite a 3 percent decline in revenue last quarter.
``My belief is that they are working their way up,'' Steele said.
</P>
<P>
   Recounting his early days at Sunbeam, Levin said that on his
second day, he started calling the chief executives of major
discount retailers, like Wal-Mart Stores and Kmart, to begin
repairing fractured relationships. ``Once they finished venting, it
was my turn to beg,'' Levin said last week in an interview at
Sunbeam's headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
   Levin's most immediate challenge is the debt. The company's fate
is precarious until it can be lowered.
</P>
<P>
   He has held lenders at bay _ Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, First
Union National Bank and Bank of America have a $1.7 billion IOU due
in 2005 and 2006 _ and installed executives to rev up the product
segments. He is creating joint licensing agreements. And he
recently sold Eastpak, the backpack maker, for $89.9 million to the
VF Corp. Earlier this month, Levin also put up for sale a unit that
makes electric clippers and other products for barbers and animal
groomers.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more: He tossed out product lines like a water
purifier that had been heralded as a $100 million revenue generator
but whose sales proved to be disappointing. And he pumped more than
$60 million into research and development that now is putting new
products on the shelves. Those include fuel-cell-powered generators
that are scheduled to go on sale next year, as well as linked,
high-technology household products like an alarm clock that
automatically starts a coffee maker. The company also introduced a
new line of Coleman outdoor grills and updated versions of pressure
washers for contractors and homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   It may all be meaningless, however, if Levin cannot reduce the
debt. In the first half of this year, with interest expenses of
$109 million, the company lost $139.6 million on sales of $1.15
billion. This summer, Sunbeam had cash and cash equivalents of
$25.9 million versus total debt of $2.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   If he cannot, well-known brands like Coffee, Coleman and Oster
may end up on the auction block. If Levin succeeds, however, his
long-term plan for recovery has a chance. ``Jerry's plan is well
thought out _ getting it executed is another thing,'' Steele said.
</P>
<P>
   The first challenge is to restructure the bonds that the company
sold in March 1998 to provide cash to buy Coleman, the camping
outfitter. ``Now that we feel the businesses are fixed and doing
well, this is No. 1 on our list,'' Levin said.
</P>
<P>
   It has to be. If Sunbeam cannot swap the notes for bonds with
different terms, bondholders could take control of the company.
Under current provisions, bondholders could start calling in their
chips in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam cannot pay cash because covenants with lenders forbid
it; the company has to offer stock. But if Sunbeam were to satisfy
the redemptions, bondholders could end up holding 61 percent of the
stock. The biggest loser would be Perelman, who owns 37 million
shares and has long looked to Levin as a strategist and turnaround
executive.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Sunbeam made an initial offer to bondholders that could
have called in $500 million in debt, but when the offer expired on
Aug. 7, there were few takers. Sunbeam has extended the offer to
Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   But even Levin does not expect bondholders to accept the offer.
He has been flying around the country, meeting with them one on one
to negotiate a deal. The rub for bondholders is that the offer on
the table gives them only a 23 percent interest in the company, or
34.2 million shares. ``Sunbeam didn't offer them enough of the
company,'' said Shawn Foley, a bond analyst at Merrill Lynch Global
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Sunbeam was offering the same terms for all the
bondholders. Those who bought in initially at $37.42 on $100 do not
want to swap out on the same terms as speculators who more recently
paid just $5 to $10, said Jonathan S. Mack, a lawyer in Minneapolis
for four firms that got into the original bond offer and who filed
a lawsuit contending fraud similar to that claimed in the
stockholders' lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Many shareholders besides Perelman are unhappy about inevitable
further stock dilution in any deal with bondholders. ``You know it
needs to be done, but you hate to get more diluted,'' says Douglas
Herold, a securities analyst at Invista Capital Management, a
subsidiary of the Principal Financial Group. Invista is the
third-largest shareholder, with six million shares, though it sold
about one million during the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the bonds, there are tens of millions of stock
options floating around; many are exercisable at $7 a share.
MacAndrews &AMP; Forbes, Perelman's company, has warrants to buy 23
million shares of common stock at $7 a share, part of a settlement
it made with Sunbeam after the stock price plummeted after the
purchase of Coleman. Lawsuits by other shareholders are challenging
that settlement. Other Coleman shareholders received warrants to
buy 4.98 million shares and lawyers in the case received 498,000
for fees and expenses.
</P>
<P>
   When Levin and other top executives joined Sunbeam in the summer
of 1998, they received 2.8 million options exercisable at $7. Most
are Levin's. In the three-year contract that Levin signed in
January, he received options to buy three million shares at $4.125
each.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty about dilution has kept Sunbeam's stock in the
subbasement. ``It's difficult for Wall Street to come in and make
this investment,'' Levin conceded. ``They don't know how many
shares are going to be outstanding. It's hard to calculate. They
can take it right down to earnings, but can't take it down to
earnings per share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we give Wall Street some guidance about what we've done
to our capital structure,'' Levin added, ``it's a gamble, it's a
bet, it's a risk.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
