<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2301 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-GARCIA-COLUMN0827-COX     08-25 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN0827-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    A face behind the statistics
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ They called themselves the Knights of the Round
Table, my dad and his poker-playing cronies. Every Wednesday night,
after the Lions Club meeting, the round poker table would be
liberated from its hiding place, and the knights would joust.
</P>
<P>
   They played some crazy games with names like Dr Pepper (10s, 2s,
and 4s wild); something called 7-Up (never did understand that one)
and Baseball (3s and 9s wild, and if you draw a four, you get
another card).
</P>
<P>
   Like sharks, the knights were fascinating to watch, but you
didn't want to get in among them.
</P>
<P>
   It was such a tight-knit group that they mostly took turns
winning. Like Blanche DuBois, the knights lived off the kindness of
strangers. ``There was this guy from San Antonio who got in our
game once. Said he was going to teach us how to play poker. And we
let him,'' Dad recounted on more than one occasion. ``All it cost
him to teach us was about $400.''
</P>
<P>
   Those games required card sense, knowledge of the other players
and nerve.
</P>
<P>
   Dad never had much money. He certainly didn't have a lot of
education. But in his heyday, he had nerve.
</P>
<P>
   In spades.
</P>
<P>
   He was born Dec. 14, 1919, in San Angelo to Crecencio and
Concepcion Garcia, the oldest boy in a family of eight children
(one of whom died in childhood). Growing up Latino in the Texas of
that era was a daily and daunting challenge. His father pulled him
out of school in the sixth grade and put him to work to help
support that big family.
</P>
<P>
   That background, combined with service in World War II and an
insatiable reading appetite, taught him lessons about life and
living you can't buy at the Harvard Business School. He worked for
more than 30 years as a salesman for an office supply and printing
outfit.
</P>
<P>
   Dad's wry West Texas wit made him a storyteller of the first
rank. He always had an ice-breaking quip, joke or observation to
charm his customers, friends and acquaintances. He used words the
way an artist uses a paintbrush. Dad described the drubbing handed
one of his candidates this way: ``That fella plowed up a snake.''
</P>
<P>
   He worked on a lot of local campaigns, worked the Viva Kennedy
and Viva Johnson efforts in the 1960s. He was on the first Office
of Economic Opportunity board in Tom Green County. He served
frequently on grand juries and was tapped often for civic boards
and commissions. He was an officer in the American GI Forum and
president of his Lions Club. He is a good father to my sisters
Cynthia and Rebecca. He is a wise and loyal friend and one of my
best teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, a group of the town's power brokers urged
him to run for the City Council. They told him he wouldn't have to
worry about money or opposition, he recounted. All he had to do was
say ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   With all those assurances, I asked then, why did he refuse them?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I told them that I don't have much education and I
didn't want to embarrass them or me. But, son, talk is cheap. They
can't control everybody and they can't really guarantee that the
money will be there. And if I run and lose, they won't need me
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   He looked at me and winked: ``Better kingmaker than king.''
</P>
<P>
   I've got a million funny Dad stories, but I want to share these
few with you because there was another story about him in the
newspaper last week.
</P>
<P>
   It was the report on the rise of diabetes in the United States.
Almost 16 million Americans have diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Dad is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Complications from the diabetes, which has been his unwanted
companion for the past 30 years, dealt this knight a mighty blow
last year. So debilitated is he by the disease that he lost
mobility as well as his ability to communicate coherently. The man
who loved to tell stories can't tell us where he hurts. My mother
and his wife of 53 years was forced to make the heart-breaking
decision of putting him in a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   So, as he begins this new stage of his life, I thought I would
introduce him to you. To politicians and researchers, he's just
another health statistic.
</P>
<P>
   But he's my dad.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 1801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
