 &HT;    CoxNet Cox News Service budget
 &HT;    FOR SATURDAY, Aug. 26, 2000
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For questions, please call 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ARGENTINE _ MEXICO CITY - A high-profile Argentine
businessman in Mexico has confessed to police that he is the same
man who is wanted by a Spanish judge on alleged charges of murder,
torture and other crimes during Argentina's ``dirty war'' against
the left in the late 1970s, according to Mexico's Reforma
Newspaper. Although he had changed his name slightly and aged,
Ricardo Miguel Cavallo was accused by Reforma of being a former
intelligence officer back in Argentina who was identified by
victims. Cavallo is the director of a controversial privately-run
national car registry program in Mexico to prevent car thefts.
Ironically, one of the accusations against him is stealing victims'
cars. Spanish lawyers are reportedly demanding that Mexico deport
Cavallo to Spain - a move resembling the attempt to extradite
Chilean dictator Augusto Pinochet to face similar accusations by
the same Spanish judge. Cavallo was detained Thursday by Mexican
police as he was attempting to board a flight from Cancun to
Argentina, where former military officials now enjoy an amnesty
against crimes. (Ferriss, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-NAVY _ MURMANSK, Russia _ Take a look out towards cold
waves of the Barents Sea from this Arctic city, and the problems of
the Russian navy become clear. Dozens of rusting hulks of
submarines and ships sit idle, mothballed by a crippled economy
that has made them _ and the men that serve on the vessels _
increasingly difficult to keep afloat. Unlike in the United States,
where the presence of a naval base is a boon to the local economy,
Murmansk has little to boast about from the base here. The home of
the ill-fated Kursk submarine that sank to the bottom of the
Barents Sea with 118 crew members is a sad example of the problems
and concerns (both within, and without Russia) that surround
Russia's military. Developing. (Coker, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move Thurs., Aug. 24, on the NYT wire.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-FLA _ George W. Bush campaigns at Florida International
University in Miami on a second day of a trip to the Sunshine
State. (Crowley, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ Live coverage of meeting between Vicente Fox and George
W. Bush in Dallas. (Susswein, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   JONBENET _ ATLANTA _ The giant spotlight that follows the
JonBenet Ramsey case will shift to Atlanta Monday, as the slain
girl's parents speak once again with investigators who've probed
the case for over three years. The prospect of Ramseys walking out
of the interviews in handcuffs, or of the police clearing the
couple of suspicion, remain doubtful, according to both sides. But
Boulder, Colo., Police Chief Mark Beckner insists that new
questions _ not new evidence _ have arisen. (Schneider, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ While looking through my home
files for a friend's birth date, a yellowed newspaper clipping fell
on the floor. The headline said ``Insect juice kills pests.'' The
Knight News Service article reminded me of two things: One, my
filing system sucks stump water. Two, how excited I was when I
first read this article about 25 years ago. The words in the
article written by Rich Kent caused my heart to race and a light
bulb to go on over my head. ``I'm going to be rich and famous,'' I
remember thinking. (Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ BONNEVILLE DAM, Ore. _
After 10 days on the road with the North Fayetteville Moyes in
their new land yacht, we are approaching Portland and Delta back to
Atlanta. I'm still waiting on Alex to cook his specialty lamb
chops, the main reason I agreed to this adventure in the first
place. Unless I dozed through the film and got my facts mixed up,
Bonneville is the first super-dam Franklin Roosevelt decided to
build when he moved into the White House. The Columbia River,
bigger than the Savannah, the Chattahoochee and the Altamaha rolled
into one, has been spinning Bonneville's turbines since the middle
1930s. (Jim Minter is a former editor of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ As a reporter, it's the ones
that get away that haunt you. You don't gloat _ not for long,
anyway _ over the big interviews you bag. It's the ones that elude
you that stay with you. That's the way it is with Heater and me.
All summer long, I pursued my prey. Heater is, of course, the
Dragons' mascot, that towering green dragon whose identity has been
more closely guarded than the last Survivor. (McCarty, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   COKE-DUNN _ ATLANTA _ Jeffrey Dunn, who last month was elevated
as Coca-Cola's No. 2 executive in North America, has been named
president of the operation. (Seward, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-PEON _ Roberto Peon, the point man for BellSouth's
spectacular success in Brazil, is getting a promotion. The news
comes a week after BellSouth's big-ticket gamble in Europe; more on
BellSouth's strategy. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TRILOGY _ Ford announces a new Internet initative for dealers
and Trilogy will provide the software. Further example of auto
industry's embrace of the Internet. (Mahoney, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVOR-CORPTRAINERS _ Thanks a lot Richard. You've just given
corporate trainers a black eye and your million-dollar
Machiavellian manipulation didn't help their image or cause either.
Can a corporate trainer's Survivor-scheming ways really work in the
real world? Is Mach-The-Knife really the corporate trainer of the
future? No way, says one local corporate training guru. ``Companies
want you to figure out how to make the organization work better.
Because that's what's going to pay off in the bottom line. You
wouldn't want an organization where there's one survivor and
everybody else has left.'' (Joyner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
15.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERNCO _ ATLANTA _ Just one week after winning a takeover
battle for a Welsh utility, Southern Co. is in the thick of another
contest to increase its stake in the utility that serves Berlin and
take over the power company serving eastern Germany.
</P>
<P>
   (Quinn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-MANSIONS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The market for mansions may be
softening, real estate agents say. In June, 15 existing homes sold
for more than $1 million, up from 10 in June of last year,
according to the latest numbers from the Austin Board of Realtors
and the Texas Real Estate Center at Texas A&AMP;M University. But in
July, only seven sold.
</P>
<P>
   And there were more of them on the market than ever. In June of
1999 there were only 74 active listings of $1 million or more. That
number more than doubled this year _ there were 156 active listings
in July. (Poe, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
