<SLUG> BC-DARIA-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARIA NEVER SLIPS IN `FALL'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. `Tonight' refers to Sun., Aug. 27.) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Daria Morgendorffer may be the only teen-ager who has no use for
summer vacation, but she makes a compelling case for her viewpoint
in the MTV movie ``Daria: Is It Fall Yet?'' Daria, who has had her
own MTV series for three years after escaping from ``Beavis and
Butt-Head,`` extends her trademark deadpan sardonicism to feature
length and proves, as did her former acquaintances with ``B&AMP;B Do
America,'' that a one-note shtick can play that long if handled
delicately and smartly.
</P>
<P>
   As the film opens, Daria is overjoyed at the prospect of three
solid months of slacking and moping. Her parents, on the other
hand, have other ideas, signing her up to be a counselor at an
irksomely precious, insanely politically correct children's camp,
the OK-to-Cry-Corral. Her buddy Jane, who's still miffed at her for
stealing her boyfriend Tom _ Daria with a boyfriend? Who'd have
guessed she'd ever do anything so proactive? _ heads to a
pretentious art camp, where she's propositioned by a bisexual.
</P>
<P>
   Daria's airhead sister Quinn is subjected to a tutor's
attentions, but much to her mystification, finds she enjoys
intelligence, if it's also cute. And Kevin and Brittany, the class
airheads (and most popular kids), endanger lives as pool
lifeguards.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, Daria experiences much angst _ over her
boyfriend, who comes from an overprivileged, overmoneyed family,
and over a distraught, disaffected young boy she counsels at camp,
a younger version of her who hasn't yet learned to greet life with
a stiff smile and a caustic rejoinder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is It Fall Yet?'' is, like Daria, smart and low-key and
fatalistic in a bizarrely life-affirming way. The virtually
clip-art nature of the stylized graphics and minimal animation suit
the satiric tone of the show, and this film, perfectly. Like
``Beavis'' before her, ``Daria'' tells her youthful MTV audience
that most teens are essentially idiots, but from her point of view,
the smart kids get the last laugh. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``Daria: Is It Fall Yet?'' &QL; 
What: Animated feature starring the sardonic refugee from ``Beavis
and Butt-Head.'' &QL; 
Where: MTV. &QL; 
When: 7 tonight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
