<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Saturday, Aug. 26 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-LATIN-AMERICA (Dallas) _ Gov. George W. Bush, in Miami on
Friday morning, charged that the Clinton administration had
neglected Latin American relations and ``squandered'' opportunities
to expand trade in the region, and he pledged to put countries in
Central and South America at the top of his foreign policy
priorities. Later in the day, Bush traveled to Dallas for a private
meeting with Vincente Fox, the president-elect of Mexico. By Frank
Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-TAX (Washington) _ In the shorthand of presidential
politics, Gov. George W. Bush's big tax cut proposal is either an
overdue effort to return to taxpayers what is rightfully theirs,
or, as Vice President Al Gore would put it, a risky scheme to
reward the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   EMULEX-PLUNGE (New York) _ At 10:13 a.m. Friday, investors in
Emulex, a California company that makes fiber-optic communications
equipment, got some terrible news. Bloomberg News, a leading
financial news service, was reporting that Emulex had announced its
chief executive had resigned and the company planned to restate its
earnings for the last two years. Details would follow _ at 5:00
p.m., after stock markets had closed for the weekend. Investors
rushed to shed their shares, and Emulex stock promptly went into
freefall, plunging from 103 to 45 in 15 minutes. The drop stripped
more than $2 billion in Emulex's market valuation before the Nasdaq
stock market halted trading in Emulex stock. There was only one
problem with the story. It was not true. It was the latest _ and
most devastating _ in a lengthening string of fake press releases
and other hoaxes that are increasingly roiling the financial
markets. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   BURUNDI-CLINTON (Nairobi, Kenya) _ In December, Nelson Mandela
took on one of Africa's most frightening problems: the tiny and
beautiful country of Burundi, where Hutu and Tutsi have taken turns
massacring each other in the thousands for the last 40 years. Rumor
was that he accepted the task reluctantly, but he has worked hard
and pushed enemies near to a settlement. They are not there yet,
and that will present a dilemma when President Clinton arrives in
Tanzania on Monday to meet with Mandela and Burundi's leaders. By
Mandela's rigid timetable, the Burundians were to seal their
intention to end seven years of civil war in an accord signed in
front of Clinton and several dozen other heads of state. By Ian
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   WEST-FIREFIGHTERS (Challis, Idaho) _ They head out before dawn
and trudge home after dark, weary and covered in soot, still
clutching the shovels and axes that are their weapons. For
thousands of firefighters across the West, these will be their
memories of summer 2000, a season so devastating that commanders
say they cannot help but see it as a war. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
