<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2315 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-NITEOUT-JOAN-JETT-ART     08-25 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-JOAN-JETT-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODY WHO? JOAN JETT GETS RAUCOUS AT WNBA COURTSIDE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT12 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 27) 
By DOUGLAS CENTURY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joan Jett stood outside the 31st Street VIP entrance
to Madison Square Garden at 7 p.m. on Thursday, looking fierce and
impatient. ``Let's go!'' she said, clapping, glancing at her
longtime manager and musical collaborator, Kenny Laguna. ``The
girls are already warming up!''
</P>
<P>
   Jett, the goddess of tight-leathered '80s rock, is such a
devoted fan of the WNBA's New York Liberty, that it pains her to
miss even a second of the team's preliminary shoot-around. What
Jack Nicholson is to the Los Angeles Lakers, Jett is to the
Liberty, a superfan and courtside fixture whose spirited cheering
seems to bring the home team luck. Jett's seat in the Garden for
every Liberty game is the same one occupied by Woody Allen at
Knicks games. While Allen always seems to be skulking moodily
beneath a floppy fishing cap, Jett is as loud and demonstrative as
she is on stage at one of her rock shows.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's Game 1 was crucial in the best-of-three playoff
against the Liberty's nemesis, the Houston Comets, the reigning
WNBA champs. And if the streets of Manhattan lacked the general
frenzy of a springtime Knicks playoff run, you wouldn't know it
once you stepped inside the Garden. These hoops stars may wear
ponytails with color-coordinated scrunchies, but for celebrities
like Jett, the Liberty has become the hottest sports ticket in
town. The talk show host Rosie O'Donnell, the actress Rosie Perez
and the rapper Queen Latifah are devotees of Liberty home games.
Men turn out, too: actors like Gregory Hines, Michael Imperioli and
the Baldwin brothers are frequently spotted in courtside seats.
Still, no one has come to embody the bulldog devotion to the
Liberty like Jett, rock's proto-riot grrrl.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she arrived, as Spike Lee often does at Knicks games,
decked out in every piece of officially sanctioned team regalia.
Jett looked very East Village, all tattoos and silver tribal
jewelry. She wore tight black leather jeans, of course, and a tank
top that said Dare Devil Tattoos. And though it was a steamy August
evening, the lithe, petite former brunette (her head has been
shaved for several months) sported a tiny black wool hat that was
somewhere between a longshoreman's cap and a yeshiva boy's
skullcap. Upon entering the Garden lobby, she was greeted by a
chorus of school girls shouting ``Hey, Joan!'' and ``We love your
new song!''
</P>
<P>
   On the escalator, Jett turned back to the crowd and offered a
word of advice: ``Be loud tonight! Everybody, be loud!'' Then she
and Laguna took their courtside seats, immediately behind the
official scorekeeper and announcer, and Jett began to shout
encouragement to Liberty players as they ran onto the Garden floor.
``We got the home court advantage, guys, don't forget it!'' she
said. Just before the opening, ``Unfinished Business,'' the Liberty
fight song Jett wrote in the vein of her ``I Love Rock and Roll,''
began blaring.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Lobo, a Liberty star who is missing the playoffs because
of an injury, came by in her cornrows and a smart brown pantsuit _
``Your song's fantastic,'' she said, touching Jett lightly on the
hip.
</P>
<P>
   The game did not begin auspiciously for the hometown heroes.
Houston opened up an early lead, while the Liberty kept missing
easy chances. Jett led a raucous chant of ``L-I-B-E-R-T-Y!'' Then
she turned to berate her companion. ``You should have your butt up
yelling,'' she told Laguna, who with his graying blond hair and
glasses, black T-shirt and chunky gold chain, looked like a cross
between an aging 60s rocker and an extra on ``The Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would but I don't know how to spell,'' Laguna said,
shrugging. As the Liberty sank further behind in the score, Jett
began a ferocious shout of ``Dee-fence!'' trying to psyche out the
Houston ballhandlers.
</P>
<P>
   Laguna explained, ``She totally believes her chants affect the
opposition _ like a hex.''
</P>
<P>
   Halftime brought no beer break for Jett. A WNBA official slipped
her a computer printout of the first-half statistics, which she
studied intently. Then she scanned the Garden, which was packed
with 19,500 fans, spotting many NBA stars: Stephon Marbury of the
Nets and Marcus Camby, the Knicks forward, cradling a baby boy
sucking a pacifier.
</P>
<P>
   For the Liberty, the second half began just as bleakly as the
first. But Jett kept trying to find something to root for. When a
third foul was announced on Houston's Tiffani Johnson, Jett jumped
up and screamed at the official: ``That's her fourth! That's her
fourth!''
</P>
<P>
   The scorekeeper realized his error; and the announcer, turning
to smile at Jett, acknowledged: ``Tiffani Johnson _ that's her
fourth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They get it wrong sometimes,'' Jett said, proudly.
</P>
<P>
   On cue, Jett's ``Unfinished Business'' fired up again, the video
projected overhead. Suddenly, the Liberty had new momentum; players
began making steals and converting layups; they closed to within
two points. Jett's fists clenched as she bounded up and down.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the end, the Houston squad proved too disciplined, and
Cynthia Cooper, the Comets standout guard, drove a dagger through
the Liberty's heart with a final basket and free throw. The buzzer
sounded. Houston, 59; New York, 52.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough, but not impossible,'' Jett said,
contemplating the odds of the New York team winning two consecutive
games on the road. She and Laguna were leaving the next morning for
Houston, and Jett said she would be just as vocal, on the Comets'
home court. ``I'm gonna be just like this, except it's in
Houston,'' she said. ``Let's see if those Texas fans don't try to
kill me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 1814EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
