<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2316 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FED-GREENSPAN-BOS &LR;      08-25 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-GREENSPAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED CHIEF SEEN LEANING TOWARD `NEW ECONOMY' THEORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Has Alan Greenspan become a ``new economy'' convert?
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve chairman seemed to move deep into that camp
in a speech Friday to an influential group of US economists who
met, as they do each August, in scenic Jackson Hole, Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's comments held significance for monetary policy, Fed
watchers said, because they indicated his strengthening conviction
that a stunning surge in the productivity of US workers will
persist as a powerful check on inflation, ensuring that the
longest-running expansion in US history has no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   The swing in the chairman's views made some economists nervous
that the Fed may even become too accommodating if his concerns
about inflation lessen.
</P>
<P>
   In simple terms, new economy advocates argue that the US economy
has undergone fundamental change in recent years, due to
unprecedented investments by corporate America in desktop
computers, servers, and assembly-line technology. Technology has
made US office and factory workers more productive, which, in turn,
has kept down companies' costs _ and inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan agreed with that view, saying that technology
investment has ``stepped up the pace of capital deepening and
increased productivity growth.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to say that it would be ``difficult to find credible
evidence in the United States that the rate of structural
productivity growth has stopped increasing.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's brief remarks about productivity, embedded in a
speech about capitalism's global reach, elaborated on reasons
hinted at this week, after Fed board members voted against an
increase in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting on Tuesday was the second in which members did not
act, halting a year-long campaign to cool an overheated economy.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Yardeni, chief economist for Deutsche Bank Securities in
New York, said Fed inaction Tuesday and on June 28 may indicate
Greenspan has prevailed over the more hawkish board members. Fed
governor Laurence Meyer, for one, has argued for aggressive an
interest-rate policy to preempt inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Yardeni, a leading proponent of new economy ideas, said
Greenspan, in Friday's speech and in his July congressional
testimony, ``seems to be more and more convinced that the rebound
in productivity growth is sustainable, that's it's not just a
temporary, cyclical phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's main point was about the world economy and the
profound impact of technology and globalization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the meaningfully different views initially held of the
way the world does _ and should _ work, powerful global competitive
forces appear for now to be driving the economic and legal
paradigms of many nations into closer alignment around a more
competitive market capitalism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it was his views on productivity that analysts said differed
sharply from a year ago. In July 1999, in testimony to Congress,
Greenspan said that ``history counsels us to be quite modest about
our ability to project the future path and pace of technology and
its implications for productivity and economic growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The new economy theory has gained credence in recent months as
productivity continues to rise. But it is still controversial among
academic and Wall Street economists, making Greenspan's remarks
Friday all the more surprising, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greenspan keeps getting increasingly in awe of these new
economy factors,'' said Nicholas Perna, an economic consultant in
Ridgefield, Conn. But Perna said the country has not yet seen the
full effects on inflation of rising wages, due to a tight labor
market, or of the recent run-up in oil prices. ``This doesn't
happen instantaneously,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, as always, hedged his views, saying productivity
would eventually crest and fade, as it has in the past. But, he
added, at present ``such a shortfall is not anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the US Department of Labor reported this month that
American workers' productivity increased at a blockbuster 5.3
percent annual rate during the second quarter, April through June.
</P>
<P>
   That was an acceleration from already-high rates, boosting the
one-year productivity gain to 5.1 percent, its highest since 1983,
when the current golden era of economic growth first got under way.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, yearly productivity gains were about 1.5 percent
during the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Fed said that it would leave the federal funds
interest rate, an overnight rate, unchanged at 6.5 percent. To
explain the vote, the Fed cited productivity for boosting the
nation's ``potential growth rate'' and ``containing costs and
holding down underlying price pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists said such strong gains in productivity are unusual,
if not unprecedented. Productivity typically picks up speed in the
early years of an expansion. This time, it has persisted _ and even
gained strength _ as the expansion has matured.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan noted that the advent of the railroads and the laying
of tracks from East to West in the 19th century ``helped elevate
economic growhth for a considerable period fo time. But the pace of
growth eventually slowed when full or near-full exploitation of the
newer techologies was achieved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 1817EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
