<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2321 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GAP-NEWLOOK-ART-$ADV2     08-25 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAP-NEWLOOK-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT COLORS BLOOMING IN THE DUST OF KHAKIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 27)  
 By RUTH LA FERLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As a fashion model, Anna Karlstrom has seen her share
of the good, the bad and the unwearable. So when a garment rates a
second look from her, it means something. Slipping on an
orchid-colored leather jeans jacket the other day, her eyes grew
wide. ``This,'' she murmured, ``is cool, for the Gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Karlstrom, 19, who was modeling Gap clothes, didn't find the
pieces assembled for the camera cutting edge exactly. But they
were, in her view, a hip and wildly colorful departure from the
standard issue crew neck T's and khaki trousers that have long been
the retailer's mainstay.
</P>
<P>
   Filtering into Gap stores since mid-July, when the chain sold
off the last of its summer cargo shorts, are lace-bordered tank
tops, filmy skirts and leathers in hothouse hues of carmine, pink
and mauve.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly these trend-driven looks were intended by the retailer
to shake up shoppers lulled into a torpor by last year's surfeit of
khakis, cargo pants and polo shirts. ``We are showing more
fashion,'' acknowledged Kenneth S. Pilot, the president of the Gap
brand. ``And we're providing it for a broader audience.''
</P>
<P>
   The change hasn't come a moment too soon. In the past year the
company has seen its profits slide as consumers defected to
competitors like American Eagle and Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, which
served up Gap-style classics with a brash urban twist. To make
matters worse, Old Navy, the Gap's sister chain, has been stealing
customers from Gap stores, with lower prices for nearly identical
merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Also contributing to the slowdown at the Gap is a perception by
consumers that the store is clotted with casual looks at a time
when fashion has moved in a dressier, racier direction.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's declining confidence in the chain's ability to
please shoppers has been reflected in its stock price, which has
plunged from a February high of 53.75 to around 28.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, there have been signs that the retailer is
beginning to climb out of its trough by veering from its
all-khaki-all-the-time formula, and courting current fashion.
``They missed the trends in the first half of the year,'' said Rick
L. Snyder, a retail stock analyst at Morgan Keegan &AMP; Co. in
Memphis, Tenn. ``But they got back on track for the second half
with fashion-driven merchandise.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Jaffe, an analyst with Paine Webber, added, ``Clearly
the Gap has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   By focusing on leather, a hit for the chain last fall, and
swinging away from the baggy, androgynous style to a trimmer,
snappier silhouette, the store is attempting to ingratiate itself
with a fashion-minded, slightly older and more sophisticated
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a very strong improvement in performance since
the Gap sold off its cargo pocket shorts in mid-July,'' Jaffe said.
``Consumers saw fresh product and spent.''
</P>
<P>
   The company says shoppers are plucking up crocheted halter tops,
swingy leather skirts and shapely jackets, lace bordered tank tops
in sherbet colors _ an array of items that might, in short, have
been snatched off the racks at Express, Wet Seal or H &AMP; M, some of
the Gap's newer competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gap looks cooler, and that's by design,'' said Lisa
Schultz, the retailer's executive vice president for product
development and design. Recently, Schultz, who oversees a
100-member design team, detected a sea change in fashion. The Gap,
which looks for direction to MTV, vintage stores and fashion
runways, sent small design teams to such fashion destinations as
Ibiza, Spain, and South Miami Beach, Fla. ``Even in these casual
places, we noticed that fashion had gotten dressier,'' Schultz
said. The Gap responded with coral-tinted crocheted halters and
wispy skirts in scarf-patterned silks and other overtly girlish
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz added that the chain's recent tendency to push fashion's
envelope is partly a measure of the design department's increasing
clout within the company. ``As in any company, I sometimes have to
push for new ideas that might make the merchants here
uncomfortable,'' she said. But lately, the corporate side has
proved more open-minded. ``These days there's a lot of respect for
the design office,'' Schultz said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been cautious, however, about how and where to
expand the boundaries of hip. The Gap courts notoriously fickle
teen-agers, but also older consumers looking for stylish clothes to
wear to work, not just on weekends. ``Until now,'' joked Pilot,
``you couldn't leave home after Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   The shift has been noticeable in the men's collection, enlivened
and dressed up with stretch button-down shirts and twill trousers,
and a vivid infusion of color in everything from Oxford shirts to
leather jackets, offered for fall, in a surprising olive green.
</P>
<P>
   But changes have been most eye-catching in the women's
collection. ``For us the style is more about evolution than
revolution,'' Pilot said. But a look at the collection would seem
to indicate otherwise. Among the Gap's decidedly un-Gaplike fall
looks: hobo bags in fringed leather or suede, snug-fitting
color-blocked sweaters and claret-colored swingy leather skirts _
the kind of things that blew out of H &AMP; M's Fifth Avenue flagship
last spring. Large Gap stores in major markets are also stocking
``1969,'' a collection of vintage-style denims bordered in stripes,
and tie-dyed designs, the last group inspired by Tokyo street
fashions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our idea,'' Schultz said, ``is to offer items that you can mix
with basic looks found elsewhere in the store, and by that strategy
keep customers in the store who might have ventured elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   After Labor Day, the new merchandise mix will be reflected in
the retailer's windows and outdoor advertising. ``It has to,
because I can't look at khaki one more day,'' Pilot said,
chuckling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
