<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Aug. 26, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Abnormal heat will persist from the southern Plains to the
interior Gulf Coast states as sinking air currents continue to
suppress clouds and rainfall. A few isolated afternoon
thunderstorms will form near the Texas and Louisiana coasts.
Farther north, at the edge of the hot, sultry air mass, clusters of
thundershowers will form from northern Kansas to the western Ohio
River Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast and Middle Atlantic states will be warm, with
ample sunshine. Isolated afternoon thunderstorms may form near the
Appalachians in Virginia and North Carolina. Meanwhile, a broken
band of thunderstorms will precede a cold front from Ontario to the
central Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, numerous afternoon thunderstorms will form from the
southern Sierra to the northern Rockies. Cooler air will spread
across the Northwest in the wake of a front.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: HISTORIC HEAT
</P>
<P>
   At Wichita, Kan., the mercury has reached or exceeded 100
degrees on 16 days this August. The record for 100 degree days in
August at Wichita was set in 1936, when 22 days were recorded. But
this month's heat in the southern Plains pales in comparison to a
summerlong heat wave of 64 years ago. In Kansas City, readings
exceeded 100 degrees on 53 days in 1936. That summer, in the midst
of the Dust Bowl years, set records for absolute maximum statewide
temperatures that still stand in 15 states from the Plains to the
Middle Atlantic region. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
