<SLUG> BC-STRETCH-FABRICS-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYCRA'S NEW REACH: ET TU, J. CREW? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday,Aug. 27)  
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've been dressing myself for 45 years now, and there have been
few surprises. But I got one last month. I bought my first piece of
tailored stretch clothing: a poplin dress shirt, in a cotton Lycra
blend, from Banana Republic.
</P>
<P>
   It was blue. It was bouncy. On that Monday morning, I put it on.
I pulled it down by the shirttails to tuck it into my trousers. It
snapped back up. I looked over my shoulder in a panic and moved
away from the window. I pulled it down again, slowly, and we hung
there together in a kind of aerobic boing. It was clothing with a
vote _ my dictatorial sartorial days were over.
</P>
<P>
   I got to work, but my shirt and I were now in this together. I
moved, it moved _ my elastic shadow. I felt like a piece of
animation or a special effect. My shirt took a few flexes on its
own, with me inside. By noon, it had plans for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   If the men's wear industry is to be believed, stretch _ once
confined in my mind to prom limos and the truth _ is here to stay
in tailored clothing, thanks to the general blur between business
wear and casual and an awakening on the part of men that fashion
can help them, too, feel sexual. The springy synthetic stretch in
bicycle shorts is invading the upper body, in shirts and sweaters.
The industry is also able to achieve synthetic-free stretch by
compressing the weave of natural fabrics like wool. This
``mechanical stretch'' is no longer the exclusive, big-deal domain
of expensive suiting by Jil Sander or Calvin Klein.
</P>
<P>
   Textiles with a technological edge, like the nylon shine that is
now popular on denim jeans, fade in and out as fads. But stretch as
a trend might be here to stay, remaking the traditional men's
closet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put it in everything we can,'' said Michael Smaldone, vice
president of men's design at Banana Republic, which had sales of
close to $2 billion last year. ``They're our best-selling items.''
Smaldone estimated that 50 percent of the men's collection in the
fall would be pieces with a stretch component, 40 percent involving
Lycra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who isn't doing it?'' said Stan Gellers, senior editor for
tailored clothing at DNR, a men's wear trade publication. ``Name
the line _ Nautica, DKNY, Slates, Kenneth Cole, Calvin Klein _
everybody has stretch. It was a gimmick; now it's a given _ from a
young, cutting-edge customer to the mainstream in two years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Van Heusen is doing it for Regis,'' Gellers added, speaking of
the nation's No. 1 dress shirt manufacturer, Phillips-Van Heusen,
and its signature collection with Regis Philbin, the host of the
nation's number No. 2 television show, ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Banana Republic is widely credited with publicly bending the
mental barrier on stretch with an aggressive advertising campaign
last fall that featured business-suited models in yoga positions,
firing rubber bands and taking active strides in slim trousers that
would have split the difference on conventional pants.
</P>
<P>
   My poplin shirt, the model by which the company gauges continued
interest in stretch items, was introduced in 1997. ``It was very
quiet,'' Smaldone recalled. ``Like, `We'd better hold hands and put
it in the line and pray it goes.''' When it outsold every item in
the men's collection that month, which it continues to do three
years later, ``we made noise about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A staple of women's clothing, stretch didn't get the warmest
welcome from traditional men's wear retailers. ``It had a rough
time getting into the classic men's stuff,'' said Gray Maycumber,
senior editor for textiles and fabrics at DNR. ``Retailers thought
it cheapened the clothing.'' Brooks Brothers, for 182 years a gold
standard in conservative men's clothing, initially resisted the
innovation, said Jarlath Mellett, the design director _ but
eventually gave in. Stretch arrived without fanfare in 1996. Now,
two large fall dress shirt collections, including Brooks Brothers'
new color introductions, will be stretch fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing several new stretch items in its Fall Preview 2000
catalog, I called J. Crew, whose rollneck, chino-happy look I
equate with natural fibers, especially cotton. Lycra blends at J.
Crew _ that's like Quaker adding plastic packing peanuts to its
oatmeal.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Formby, executive vice president of design at J. Crew,
choked back a surprised laugh when I called him. Yes, there was
``high-level discussion'' at the company over stretch, he said _
``a brawl,'' in fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scared a lot of people,'' he added. ``A lot of people
equated stretch with synthetic.'' They got over it. J. Crew
introduced a Lycra-blend suit in 1995; Formby estimated that 15
percent of the men's collection this fall will involve stretch.
</P>
<P>
   What he said next snapped me back to reality. The stretch
customer is different, he explained _ ``a little faster, a little
younger.''
</P>
<P>
   Younger than I am, that is. My age exceeded my jacket size in
1992. My stretch shirt was moving with the times, but was I?
</P>
<P>
   Gellers at DNR agreed with Formby that stretch's best buyers are
younger. ``Polyester double knits gave stretch the black eye in the
1970s,'' he said. ``But you're dealing with a customer in their 30s
who never knew polyester stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Banana Republic describes that customer as being the company's
demographic ``sweet spot,'' a spokesman said. At 48, I am six
months away from the end of their plank, which is 49.
</P>
<P>
   Lycra is six years younger than I am. Invented by Dupont in 1958
as a replacement for rubber, the elastane yarn trademarked as Lycra
has 600 percent more memory for shape than rubber does, which is
why even 4 percent in cotton fiber can turn a shirttail into a
slingshot.
</P>
<P>
   This year, with growing sales and acceptance, Dupont introduced
a $40 million global advertising campaign for Lycra, created by
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi in New York and Geneva, which includes magazines,
television, movie theaters and billboards. The television spots,
directed by Jeff Kennedy, a music video veteran who has worked with
Lauryn Hill, went on the air in July. They star Brian Delmonico, a
National Collegiate Athletic Association champion gymnast, the
first official ``face'' _ and body _ of the product since its
invention.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Delmonico is a man is not accidental. An in-house
Dupont magazine reported that by directing their sights at men, the
company was ``increasing the target by 250 percent.'' Print ads for
Lycra are scheduled for GQ, Esquire, Details and Men's Health.
</P>
<P>
   Delmonico was dubbed ``Lycra Man'' in Teen magazine's July
issue. In a survey conducted in 20 countries this year, Dupont
discovered that men's primary ``emotional image'' of Lycra was
``modern.'' Fashionable and sensual were up there, too.
</P>
<P>
   This information produced a long look in the mirror last week,
shirt-tailed and pantless.
</P>
<P>
   ``What men now face is the problem women used to face,'' John
Gagnon, an emeritus professor of sociology at the State University
at Stony Brook, said when I called later that day. Gagnon studies
sexuality. ``Men are more comfortable with displaying themselves,''
he explained. ``But as men move out from behind the suit, into
sexual clothing, it means that their sexuality is on the line.
There's greater display, but there's a greater potential for
failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Would I pick myself up? My stretch shirt, with a squeeze of the
arm and a suave synthetic come-on, was ready to make the move. Wait
until it finds out what I'm really like.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
