<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECOMMERCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE EMBRACE E-COMMERCE, BUT CONVENIENTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHARON MOSHAVI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Slow to embrace e-commerce and online shopping, Japan is
finally embarking on its own Internet revolution. But it is doing
so in a very Japanese way: at the 7-Eleven.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the 7-Eleven, as well as other convenience stores.
</P>
<P>
   The stores, known here as ``conbini,'' have achieved a
remarkable commercial and cultural dominance they hope will give
them an edge in Japan's nascent e-commerce business.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, America has convenience stores, too. In fact, the
concept was born in the United States in the 1920s. Japan imported
the idea and opened its first one in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   But something happened on the trip over. The in-and-out,
beer-and-burrito concept disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the shell stayed American, the inside became pure
Japanese,'' says Mark Schilling, a pop culture writer and longtime
resident of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Conbini are more than just stores. They have become centers of
community life, functioning as town halls, culture clubs, and
venues for romance. And they are everywhere. Their bright shiny
signs, with names like FamilyMart and Just Spot and yes, 7-Eleven,
beckon you at nearly every street corner, in every city or town in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``A convenience store is like air for people. Without it, you
wouldn't know what to do,'' said Yuji Fukuda, an analyst who
follows retail trends for Tokyo's Dentsu Institute for Human
Studies.
</P>
<P>
   People go to the conbini to pick up a ramen soup, a rice ball
wrapped in seaweed, or maybe an octopus snack. They'll pay a phone
bill or send a fax. They'll hang out with friends, spend hours
reading magazines, or check out the latest fashion in nail
stickers.
</P>
<P>
   The conbini have become such an indispensable part of life that
rental ads promote an apartment's proximity to a convenience store.
Now, as the conbini start Web sites and turn their shops into hubs
for e-commerce, ``It could be a very powerful phenomenon,
especially among young people,'' Fukuda said.
</P>
<P>
   People in their teens and 20s have led the way in turning the
conbini into a retail force. In response to their whims and fads,
convenience stores turn over their inventories with remarkable
speed, creating and catering to the latest fads in soda or make-up,
or this summer's hot fashion accessory, paper leis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even a pencil cannot be old-looking. It has to be cool and
new,'' said Hidetoshi Akiyama, a 7-Eleven Japan official.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's convenience magic,'' said Junko Hasegawa, a 22-year-old
college student who likes to troll the aisles with her friends to
find the latest vitamin supplements or candy. ``There's always
something new, and it's impossible to leave without buying
something.''
</P>
<P>
   With about 35,000 convenience stores in densely populated Japan,
half of all customers live or work within five minutes of one.
That's a testament to the stores' popularity, but it's also forcing
conbini to scramble for new ways to attract customers. That's where
the Internet comes in.
</P>
<P>
   7-Eleven, Japan's largest convenience-store operator (which got
so big and rich it took over the American chain in 1991) is leading
the pack. On July 1, it launched an online virtual mall that sells
everything from CDs to flowers to tour packages. The purchase is
then delivered to the nearest 7-Eleven, where the customer picks it
up and pays for it.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in October, the company will place Internet terminals
in many of its stores. The idea is to market the Web site, whetting
people's appetite for computers and the Internet. The number of
homes with personal computers in Japan is still a fraction of what
it is in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce has been slow to take off in Japan because of the
smaller number of PCs, and because the Japanese have never really
taken to credit cards. Most merchants don't accept them because
card companies charge exorbitant fees, and the debt-averse Japanese
prefer cash.
</P>
<P>
   Buying an item online, and later walking five minutes to a
convenience store to pay for it and pick it up, seems like it might
appeal to many Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Japanese are used to conbinis as more than just
places to shop. They have been paying their utility bills at
convenience stores since the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   7-Eleven is targeting online sales of $1.8 billion by the year
2002. It's also trying a few other Internet tactics, such as
getting the elderly online with a computer-based meals-on-wheels
service. The company has taken a stake in Sony's Playstation.com,
which means that customers can pick up their Playstation systems
and games at 7-Elevens.
</P>
<P>
   Others are following similar paths. Chains like FamilyMart and
Lawsons will soon install computer terminals, and through tie-ins
with companies like the computer giant NEC and Toyota Motor, plan
to sell all kinds of goods online.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a number of analysts here are skeptical about whether
consumers really want to buy goods like books or watches from
convenience stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers decide they want to use stores for certain purposes.
For example, food retailers have never been able to sell clothing
to anybody,'' said Mike Allen, a retail analyst in Tokyo with ING
Baring Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Allen doesn't think the convenience stores can go online quite
as easily as they think. ``They can't really start up a brand new
business without starting a brand new infrastructure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But 7-Eleven, for one, thinks it can be done, and without
bleeding red ink. Company officials point out that since they are
dealing with wholesalers, they won't have to hold inventory the way
the online giant Amazon.com must. And thanks to 8,200 or so
7-Eleven stores, the company already has a delivery system in
place.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also trying to adapt itself to Japan's favorite
way to log on: the cellular phone. Like many companies, 7-Eleven
has created a Web site designed for the tiny screen of a mobile
phone.
</P>
<P>
   Convenience stores are betting they can once again change the
face of Japanese retailing. Over the last three decades, the
country's local neighborhood shopping streets have changed
dramatically. Dingy but friendly corner shops have been replaced by
the convenience stores' bright, impersonal aisles.
</P>
<P>
   Some complain of the loss of culture and community. But by and
large, Japanese don't seem too upset. No one gripes about the
``convenience store on every corner,'' the way some Americans
complain about the ubiquitous Starbucks and Baby Gaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few complain about the conbini's cheapish culture, but most
people don't say that,'' said Fukuda. ``At least not yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
