<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG ROSTER TROUBLING FOR PATRIOTS COACH BELICHICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Cutting a roster to 53 players is always a
troubling time for a coach. Well, it's that time for Bill
Belichick, who finished 3-2 in his first exhibition season as coach
of the Patriots after an impressive and innovative 29-21 win over
the Carolina Panthers Thursday at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick said Friday he has one major concern, the ``overall
depth'' of the team.
</P>
<P>
   What Belichick faces is having to rely on younger players at the
end of the roster at virtually every position. The cuts won't be
tough, it's what you're left with that is the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick said he will likely make the cuts Sunday, just before
the 4 p.m. deadline. His coaches and players will take Saturday
off, after coaches spent most of the day evaluating players.
Belichick will also have to get a few players through waivers so he
can put together a five-man practice squad, and he may cut beyond
53 so he can leave himself some room in case he covets a player cut
by another team.
</P>
<P>
   One decision was made, as Belichick placed guard Todd Rucci, who
is still recuperating from knee surgery, on the non-football injury
list since the injury did not occur on the football field. Where
did it take place, you ask? No answer was forthcoming. The
designation gives the Patriots a six-week window to figure out what
role they foresee for Rucci _ either on the active roster or on
injured reserve for the season. The Patriots will be on the hook
for his $2.05 million cap number, but don't have to count him on
the roster for the first six weeks of the season. Look for rookie
Adrian Klemm (knee) to join Rucci on that list, but middle
linebacker Ted Johnson (hamstring) and defensive tackle Henry
Thomas (knee) are likely to make the roster since they're close to
being ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what the roster may look like and the decisions that face
Belichick:
</P>
<P>
   QUARTERBACKS (4): Drew Bledsoe, Michael Bishop, John Friesz, and
Tom Brady. The Patriots could take their chances and send Brady
through waivers and, if he clears, place him on the practice squad.
But the Jets used four quarterbacks last season, so it's a viable
option.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING BACKS (3): Raymont Harris, Kevin Faulk, and J.R.
Redmond. The team has invested a lot of time in all three and all
should stick. Faulk may be the starter, but Harris will get playing
time while Redmond is brought along slowly and used on special
teams. This is an area Belichick is eager to upgrade. Washington
has made Skip Hicks available for a third-round pick or better.
Will the Patriots bite?
</P>
<P>
   FULLBACKS (3): Tony Carter, Chris Floyd, and Harold Shaw. The
one player they may not be able to live without is Shaw, a valuable
special-teamer. Can Shaw do the same things as Carter? Floyd is a
pure fullback with toughness and blocking ability, but could he be
expendable. The Patriots could keep all three or there might be a
salary-cap casualty.
</P>
<P>
   WIDE RECEIVERS (6): Terry Glenn, Troy Brown, Tony Simmons, Chris
Calloway, Sean Morey, and Shockmain Davis. Here's the rub: While
it's great that Davis and Dane Looker have looked good late in
games, teams use their top four receivers. The other guys are used
on special teams and are around in case of an emergency, so who's
the best and most-experienced special teams player? Morey. Davis
and Looker could make it or one could wind on the practice squad.
If Looker doesn't make the roster, the Patriots don't have to give
the Rams a sixth-round pick next season.
</P>
<P>
   TIGHT ENDS (2): Rod Rutledge and Eric Bjornson. One blocks, the
other catches. You could go with three and include Harvard's Chris
Eitzmann, but he looks more like a developmental player and belongs
on the practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   OFFENSIVE LINEMEN (9): Bruce Armstrong, Max Lane, Derrick
Fletcher, Damien Woody, Jason Andersen, Greg Robinson-Randall,
Lance Scott, Grant Williams, and Adam Davis. With Rucci and Klemm
out, this is what you're left with.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSIVE LINEMEN (9): Willie McGinest, Brandon Mitchell, Chad
Eaton, Bobby Hamilton, Greg Spires, Thomas, Jeff Marriott, Garrett
Johnson, and Reggie Grimes. Did Spires beat out Grimes Thursday
night? Whither sixth-round pick Dave Nugent? Grimes and Nugent look
like guys who need to develop, especially if Thomas is kept.
</P>
<P>
   LINEBACKERS (7): Tedy Bruschi, Johnson, Andy Katzenmoyer, Rob
Holmberg, Chris Slade, Marc Megna, and Maggy Tuitele. Tuitele and
Megna may still be bubble guys, but Megna is a maniac on special
teams and Tuitele has done a nice job in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSIVE BACKS (8): Ty Law, Antonio Langham, Kato Serwanga,
Otis Smith, Lawyer Milloy, Tebucky Jones, Larry Whigham, and Tony
George. It looks like Chris Carter and Antwan Harris are the odd
men out. Belichick played Jones virtually the entire game Thursday
at free safety to see whether he could handle it. He seemed to pass
the test.
</P>
<P>
   KICKERS (2): Lee Johnson and Adam Vinatieri. They win by
default.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE BUBBLE: Chris Carter, Antwan Harris, CB Kelly Malveaux,
RB Patrick Pass, Nugent, Eitzmann, Grimes, Looker, DT Maurice
Anderson, G Josh Rawlings, LB Orlick Johnson, G Rob Gatrell, and LS
Lonnie Paxton.
</P>
<P>
   You can see why Belichick is concerned about depth. The
decisions at the end of the roster come down to rookie free agents.
Some will excel and others will fall by the wayside. Coaches have
reason to worry that when injuries claim their starters, then there
goes the season because inexperienced players have to take their
place.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Smith signing was key. It may cost Antwan Harris
his job, but the Patriots know if Law or Langham go down, they have
an experienced player in the wings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
