u a BC-CARS-TECH-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      08-25 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-TECH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 A NO-PRESSURE ARENA FOR TESTING ALL MAKES OF CARS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ Nick Bobotis came to see the Lexus IS 300, but
while he was at it, he took a test drive in the Acura 3.2TL and the
Infiniti I30, something he could never do at a single dealership;
nearby, keys in the ignition, sat an Audi A4, a BMW 320i, a
Chrysler 300M and a Lincoln LS _ names that constitute much of the
roll call of midsize, upscale sedans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no pressure, and you can compare side by side,'' said
Bobotis, of Alexandria, Va., marveling at this new way to shop for
cars as he completed a turn around a half-mile test track, which
included a straightaway with a digital timer, a slalom and a
simulation of broken pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, in a tent big enough for a three-ring circus, in a
different section of this unusual auto marketing effort, another
shopper, Mustafa Ozdemir, watched, fascinated, as a woman he might
have mistaken for a salesperson demonstrated the three-way seat in
the rear of a new minivan. The seat could be positioned for
third-row passengers, or folded flat into a footwell, or flipped
over so that it faced the rear, providing a comfortable seating
area for a tailgate party if you didn't mind your feet hanging out
of the back of the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one is the Honda, but the Mazda has it, too,'' said the
woman, demonstrating that unlike most sales personnel, she had no
desire to push one model over the other. ``And the 2001 Pontiac
will have it,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Bobotis and Ozdemir were among 2,000 licensed drivers who
shopped in the first weekend of August at an event so different
that it doesn't have a generic name yet. What it was, was a
multibrand car show and test-driving venue. And it was sponsored by
a company that does not sell cars.
</P>
<P>
   The event was the second of six being put on around the nation
by Edmunds, a publisher of automotive books that has mostly
transformed itself into an Internet company, Edmunds.com. The
Edmunds Web site provides comparative information on a variety of
cars. The company said the event here, which it called EdmundsLive,
was a real-world version of the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   But under the tent there was also a circle of 24 computers, with
Edmunds.com as the home page, that visitors could use to look up
information on cars. Among the information on the Web site _ and
posted near the cars in the tent _ was what Edmunds calls true
market value, which is the company's estimate, based on
mathematical models and current supply and demand, of what a
consumer could reasonably expect to pay for any model of car. It
also lists the manufacturers' suggested retail price as well as the
invoice, which is the basis for what dealers pay for the cars on
their lots.
</P>
<P>
   Edmunds says the site _ like the tour events _ lets customers go
to a dealer with choices already narrowed down, possibly to a
single vehicle, and with a price in mind that will reduce haggling
and the feeling that one may have made a bad deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to the consumer who they want to go to to buy, if they
go at all,'' said Jeremy P. Anwyl, the chief operating officer.
Most people would end up going to a traditional dealership, company
officials said, but Anwyl said they would ``leave here more
convinced they're going to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   General Motors dealers in California have sometimes held similar
events on their own, featuring the company's cars. And GM did
something similar two years ago, in the same parking lot here,
outside the stadium where the Redskins play football. That show
covered a wider band of the market, with cars, pickups and sport
utilities, and likewise had no pressure to buy immediately, but its
object was to sell GM models.
</P>
<P>
   The Edmunds event, part of a six-city tour that began in Atlanta
and will be repeated at Raceway Park in Englishtown, N.J., Thursday
through Sunday, Sept. 3, includes 132 total cars representing more
than 50 models.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $15 for each adult 18 and over, a price that does
not come close to covering costs, company officials say. Whatever
profit Edmunds makes comes from the commissions it is paid by four
sponsors with booths in the tent: CarsDirect.com, which lets
consumers order cars over the Internet; eCoverage, which sells
insurance online; PeopleFirst.com, an online lender; and
1SourceAutoWarranty.com, which sells extended warranties on the
Web. But Edmunds has no financial interest in the preferences of
shoppers, said Avi Steinlauf, the marketing director. ``We're not
in anybody's pocket,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   That was clear in the minivan area, where a shopper climbed into
a Ford Windstar. ``It's a little noisier than the others,'' said
Bob Featherly, who was escorting shoppers to cars and answering
questions. ``But it's got very nice doors,'' he said, pushing a
button that activated one of the motorized sliding doors.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic scene was at the sport utility vehicle test
track. Several truckloads of dirt had been brought in to create the
illusion of an off-road track, including ``blue sky hill,'' a mound
so steep that nothing except the sky was visible through the
windshield of a Ford Expedition as it was driven over the obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   Jeannine Fallon, an Edmunds spokeswoman, said surveys collected
from visitors as they left the Atlanta stop indicated that
two-thirds planned to buy a car in the near future. The others, she
said, ``saw it as some sort of amusement park, and they were happy
to pay the 15 bucks.'' Steinlauf, the marketing director, said
people were spending four to five hours at the event, even coming
back for a second day; Edmunds had expected shoppers to stay an
average of 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, all the visitors to the show here seemed to like the
idea of a no-pressure arena for comparison shopping. ``You can
really look at the cars, without somebody in the background eyeing
you as if you're their next commission,'' said Judy Fiery, who came
with her husband, Sam, from Hagerstown, Md., about an hour and a
half by car, to spend a day of their vacation at the show.
</P>
<P>
   The Fierys' daughter had just graduated from Frostburg State
University, near Hagerstown, and their graduation gift was going to
be a down payment on a Jetta; meanwhile, Fiery was looking over
what might replace their 1989 Mercury Sable, with 115,000 miles, in
a year or two. Now that their daughter had graduated _ and ``the
Bank of Mom and Dad is finally closed,'' as Fiery put it _he had
his eye on the LS or the 300M. But Fiery, who works in a Mack Truck
engine assembly plant, was also just enjoying the show.
</P>
<P>
   Bobotis, the shopper who had come to see the Lexus, was, too.
``What I can't stand at an auto show is that you can't even adjust
the seat and see if you can get comfortable, because the electrical
system has been turned off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Bobotis, who drives a 1993 Mustang that ``has another year
in it, maybe,'' also liked the side-by-side comparison. In 1987, he
said, he had worked for six months as a salesman in a Ford
dealership in Waldorf, Md., and one day a customer whom he was
accompanying on a test drive pulled into the lot of a Volkswagen
dealer, to try out a competitor's model. ``I'm thinking, `The nerve
of this guy,''' said Bobotis. ``But he was pretty smart.''
</P>
<P>
   The ride-and-drives here were not perfect; some shoppers
complained that on the courses, which were up to five-eighths of a
mile long, they could not test the vehicles at highway speed. On
the other hand, few dealers would park a test-drive model at the
head of an obstacle course of traffic cones and invite the shopper
to make the tires squeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
