<HEADLINE>
HIGHER INTEREST RATES EXPECTED IN EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRED ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Europe is hardly in the midst of a major
economic boom, but the European Central Bank is increasingly likely
to hit the brakes as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of hawkish warnings, the central bankers have made
it clear that they are alarmed about inflation and the doggedly
depressed value of the euro compared with the U.S. dollar. Most
analysts predict that the central bank's board of governors will
increase interest rates when they meet next Thursday, but many
worry that the move could stunt growth without shoring up the euro.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a self-produced problem,'' said Hans Meltzer, an
economist at Deutsche Bank Research. ``If the ECB were as generous
about inflation as Greenspan and the Federal Reserve, it wouldn't
have a problem.'' When the euro was introduced at the start of
1999, the European Central Bank announced that its goal was to keep
inflation below 2 percent a year, a goal that is considerably
tougher than that of the U.S. Federal Reserve Board.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst Welteke, president of the Bundesbank, Germany's central
bank, and a governor at the European Central Bank, drove home the
nature of European worries in a toughly worded speech Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ECB cannot be satisfied with the developments of the
external value of the euro,'' Welteke said. Noting that the weak
euro has led to sharply higher import prices, Welteke said the
risks of inflation had increased measurably. ``The longer external
price pressures persist, the higher are upward risks to price
stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Since its introduction, the euro has lost over 20 percent of its
value against the dollar. At its current value of about 91 cents,
it remains near its all-time low of nearly 88 cents, and many
currency analysts have abandoned any hope that it will climb back
to parity with the dollar in the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   The euro's weakness stems primarily from the drawing power of
the U.S. economy, which continues to attract huge amounts of
foreign investment and thereby generate heavy demand for dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The weak euro has aggravated inflationary dangers because it has
pushed up the cost of imports, most particularly of oil. With
prices still near their highest levels in years for oil, which is
bought exclusively in dollars, European fuel bills have delivered a
double blow and pushed up the prices of other products.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Europe's annualized rate of inflation is now about
2.4 percent, well above the central bank's target, and the trend is
still upward. On Thursday the German government reported that
prices in German factories shot up in July at the fastest rate in
nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   But many economists argue that the inflation threat has been
overstated. Meltzer of Deutsche Bank noted that most of the recent
surge in prices stems from soaring oil prices rather than from more
structural causes like rising wages. Stripped of oil and other
volatile items, the core inflation rate is 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts are betting that central bankers will raise their
baseline interest rates next week by one-half of a percentage
point, from 4.25 percent to 4.75. That is still substantially lower
than the U.S. federal funds rate of 6.50, but it poses several
risks.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious risk is that it will stop Europe's current
economic upswing, just as unemployment in Germany and France is
beginning to sink below 10 percent for the first time in many
years. If economic growth does slow, the decline could drive the
value of the euro down. Though currencies normally rise when
interest rates are increased, the euro's biggest source of weakness
is Europe's slower economic growth compared with that of the United
States.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The currency risk was put into focus this week, when a closely
watched survey of German business sentiment showed an unexpected
and sharp drop in confidence. The news quickly prompted some
forecasters to conclude that German growth had peaked, and
investors reacted by selling euros and briefly pushing their value
below 89 cents.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, many analysts said they believed that the drop in
confidence was misleading and that the German economy, Europe's
biggest, still had room to grow. The German central bank has
predicted that growth will approach 3 percent next year, and the
Deutsche Bank predicts that it will go slightly higher.
</P>
<P>
   But the fragility is clear. Recent data on Europe's trade
balance showed that the weak euro continued to bolster exports by
making them cheaper in world markets. But the data also showed that
European imports were increasing. While part of that reflects the
effect of exchange rates, Tony Norfield of ABN Amro theorized that
it might also indicate a preference of Europeans for buying
imported goods.
</P>
<P>
   Whether European growth is stalled by tougher monetary policy,
analysts at Dresdner Kleinwort Benson predict that the euro will
remain beleaguered and unloved for some time. Even assuming that
European rates are increased in the next few weeks, Dresdner warned
this week that another record low ``appears within reach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
