<HEADER>
A2350 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-PLANE-SAFETY-LEF     08-25 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-PLANE-SAFETY-LEFKOWITZ-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO WORDS CAPTURE THE FEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Saturday, Aug. 26, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By MARY R. LEFKOWITZ    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY, Mass. _ A few months ago I was on a plane that almost
crashed. For the first three hours it was a routine flight from
Boston to Denver, crowded, with sporadic food and beverage service.
</P>
<P>
   Then, an hour before our scheduled landing, the pilot announced
that one set of the plane's landing wheels would not descend. But,
he assured us, he could land the plane safely on two wheels.
Although fire trucks would meet us on the ground, he said, there
was no need to be concerned. They were simply being cautious. They
liked to use occasions like this for practice. Was there really
nothing to worry about? I wondered. None of the other passengers
seemed particularly concerned.
</P>
<P>
   But about half an hour later the mood in the cabin changed when
the pilot made a second announcement: The situation was
deteriorating badly. None of the landing wheels could descend. We
would need to fly around in circles at a low altitude, the pilot
explained, to burn up most of the fuel so that the plane would not
catch fire when we landed on its metal belly. The crew pointed out
the exits and explained how we should brace ourselves for landing.
They spoke reassuringly but looked tense and worried. They told us
to strap ourselves in tightly and stow our carry-on baggage. The
cabin lights were extinguished. No one said a word. I looked at my
husband; we were both speechless.
</P>
<P>
   As we flew around in silence, I tried to imagine, as calmly as I
could, what would happen. I knew that no one walks away from a
plane crash. Even if our plane did not explode when it hit the
ground, chances were it would be engulfed in flames soon after. The
seats my husband and I sat in were equidistant from two exits but
close to neither. The chances of our escaping were almost nil.
There was nothing, absolutely nothing, I could do. And so we all
sat there in the eerie silence.
</P>
<P>
   Then suddenly, just as we were scheduled to land, the pilot
announced that the landing gear had descended. We would have an
ordinary landing after all. The passengers applauded and began
talking excitedly. The pilot landed the plane expertly and switched
off the engines. I saw that we had come in at a remote part of the
vast Denver airport, surrounded by fire engines and men in
heat-reflecting fire suits. We were towed to the gate and greeted
by television crews. They asked earnestly: What did it feel like?
What did you think about? I told them what happened, but not how I
felt. At the time, I couldn't put it into words.
</P>
<P>
   Why was I so inarticulate? As a professor, I have spent most of
my life explaining all sorts of complicated things to other people.
But facing imminent death turned out different from what I had
thought it would be. I would not have imagined that I could be so
calm and deliberate, that I would not spend what I supposed were my
last few minutes of life thinking about something other than myself
and what I was losing.
</P>
<P>
   My life did not pass before my eyes. Instead, I thought of the
people on airplanes that had crashed. The ``black boxes,'' when
recovered, can reveal what a flight's crew was saying. But there is
no way to know what was going through the passengers' minds when
they realized that their plane was about to fall from the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Are the passengers on the planes that actually crash as
uncannily calm as we all were _ silent, unlamenting, bracing
ourselves in the dark cabin? Do they, before the last moments,
experience, as we did, a terror so anesthetizing that it could pass
for courage?
</P>
<P>
   (Mary R. Lefkowitz, a professor of classical studies at
Wellesley College, is the author of ``Not Out of Africa.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
