<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2356 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-EATONVANCE-$AD     08-25 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-EATONVANCE-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH: DUNCAN W. RICHARDSON AND JACOB REES-MOGG
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 27) 
By JOANNE LEGOMSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To Duncan W. Richardson and Jacob Rees-Mogg, co-managers of the
$322 million Eaton Vance Information Age fund, risk is clearly not
a measure of financial virility. Investing in the technology, media
and telecommunications sector ``does not have to be an extreme
sport,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, avoiding unnecessary risk is the pair's guiding
principle. When buying and selling stocks in this fast-paced,
highly volatile sector, the managers adhere to a philosophy of
growth at a reasonable price.
</P>
<P>
   One result of the approach is that both Richardson, who oversees
the fund's assets in the United States, the majority of the
portfolio, and Rees-Mogg, who is based in London and selects the
non-American holdings, have largely sidestepped pure Internet plays
like e-tailers or content-oriented Web sites &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Rees-Mogg is openly leery of many of the measures &UR; _ &LR;  like
price-to-sales ratios &UR; _ &LR;  that analysts and investors use to value
fledgling technology, media and telecommunications companies that
have yet to earn money. He relies on more traditional yardsticks.
One is the peg ratio, which compares the price-to-earnings multiple
to the long-term earnings growth rate of a company; another is the
ratio of enterprise value (the market value of a company's debt and
equity, less cash) to cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   He concedes, however, that this approach can mean lost
opportunities. Two years ago, he said, he passed on a chance to buy
shares in an Australian Internet game maker, Uproar.com, at the
initial public offering &UR; .  &LR; ``The stock did phenomenally well for a
while,'' he said, but added, ``We are comfortable making that kind
of mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The tempered approach to growth investing has not compromised
returns. For the three years ended Aug. 22, the fund returned 29.16
percent, annualized, compared with 14.73 percent for all world
stock funds tracked by Morningstar Inc. and 19.12 percent for the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton Vance Information Age was created in 1995 to capture what
both managers viewed as powerful long-term opportunities resulting
from rapid technological change and industry deregulation in
markets outside the United States. ``We view the three sectors as
an interlocking trinity,'' Rees-Mogg explained, meaning that growth
in one industry necessitates growth in the others.
</P>
<P>
   Both Richardson, 42, and Rees-Mogg, 31, have media-flavored
family backgrounds. Richardson's father worked in advertising and
public relations for Burson Marsteller, now part of Young &AMP;
Rubicam, the big advertising and public relations company that is
to be acquired by WPP. Rees-Mogg's father, Lord Rees-Mogg, was vice
chairman of the Board of Governors of the British Broadcasting Co.
from 1981 to 1986 and was editor of The Times of London from 1967
to 1981; he is still a columnist for the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The fund now contains 108 stocks, with the American and foreign
weightings generally conforming to those of the Morgan Stanley
Capital International index; the managers, however, have
considerable latitude to adjust the percentages. Typically, about
60 percent of the fund is invested in American stocks; but at the
end of July, the figure was almost 70 percent, with an additional
14.6 percent in Japan and 15.8 percent in Europe. Eighty-eight
percent of the assets were in stocks, with the balance in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The global fallout from the recent gyrations in the Nasdaq
market has reinforced the managers' aversion to risk. ``This is no
time to be complacent,'' Richardson said. ``Valuation risk is very
high in this market.''
</P>
<P>
   The Azlan Group of Britain has been one of the fund's successful
smaller holdings. The company, with $653.8 million in revenue last
year, makes computer systems and peripherals and provides related
training. Rees-Mogg said the company was well positioned to take
advantage of the growth in the network communications sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its partnerships with some of the leading technology companies
should permit the company to grow organically and through
acquisitions'' that create added value for shareholders, he said.
The share price has more than doubled, to 183.5 pence, or $1.25,
since he bought the shares two years ago at an average price of 67
pence.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson is bullish on McGraw-Hill, the publisher that also
owns the S&AMP;P index franchise and debt rating agency. Although the
company has reported double-digit earnings increases for several
years, the stock has not received much attention on Wall Street, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is becoming more of a global operator,''
succeeding in adapting its basic businesses worldwide, he said. He
expects the share price to be driven by strong results in textbook
publishing and financial services _ especially the bond rating
business. Most states are running budget surpluses and making
education a top priority _ trends that should accelerate the drive
to upgrade school textbooks, he added. He said that the company
could beat the Wall Street earnings forecast of $2.35 a share for
this year and that its earnings growth percentage could be in the
mid-teens for the next few years. At $59.94, the stock sells at
25.11 times earnings, versus a P/E of 29.95 for the S&AMP;P 500.
Richardson first bought shares in 1997 at an average price of
$53.14.
</P>
<P>
   Rees-Mogg likes the Nippon Broadcasting System, a radio
broadcasting group and publisher of audiovisual materials; the
company went public in Japan in 1996. In part, the investment,
started in March 1999 was a play on strength in advertising
revenues. He bought the shares at the equivalent of $30.85; they
closed Friday in Tokyo at 6,500 yen, or $60.72.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
