<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-KIARIO0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2001 Kia Rio delivers true value
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Although not as intriguing as a visit to the Brazilian
city with which it shares its name, the 2001 Rio from Kia does have
some attention-worthy features. They include:
</P>
<P>
   A base price of $8,668.
</P>
<P>
   Adequate room for four adults.
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures of 25 mpg regular unleaded in the city and 31 on the
highway.
</P>
<P>
   Those pluses may not send the Korean manufacturer's sedan to the
top of the best-selling cars list, but it's difficult to imagine
that it won't find buyers in a U.S. market where the average
new-car transaction is more than $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Rio, to be sure, is not a large car, and it can be daunting
to mix it up with trucks, SUVs and full-size cars on crowded
expressways while driving one. But it's refreshing to find a car at
this price that seems well-made and built of decent materials.
</P>
<P>
   The test Rio, which totaled $11,432 after adding options that
included a four-speed automatic transmission, air conditioning and
stereo, performed as might be expected of a 3,000-pound car with a
108-horsepower engine.
</P>
<P>
   Sluggish at start-up, the Rio seemed to gravitate toward the
right-side lanes on expressways and cruised comfortably as long as
it wasn't asked to join the flock in abusing the speed limit or to
make frequent speed changes of any significance. Pass with
prudence, in other words.
</P>
<P>
   The ride was expectedly noisy with the 1.5-liter four-cylinder
engine hammering away, but the steering was respectably tight, the
brakes had a solid feel and visibility was good.
</P>
<P>
   Controls were well-placed, and the optional tilt steering wheel,
part of a $300 package, seemed a necessity because of the lack of
space. What might surprise some is the fit-and-finish, which
generally appeared precise, and the tasteful quality of the mildly
patterned upholstery, which was also used on the door panels.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking luxury-level quality here _ just no-nonsense
materials that contributed to the sense that whoever designed and
built the Rio wanted to give buyers true value for their money.
</P>
<P>
   What flash the Rio had came from its paint, a ``sunburst gold''
guaranteed to add to the car's visibility quotient in traffic or
parking lots. But the fact it has four doors and a four-figure base
price is what begs to be noticed about the Rio, which should prove
a welcome newcomer to a virtually ignored segment of the automotive
market.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
