A2359 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-TAILHOOK-ENCORE-HNS &LR;      08-25 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAILHOOK-ENCORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW TAILHOOK PROBE RECALLS 1991 SCANDAL THAT SHOOK THE NAVY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The disclosure Friday that Navy personnel at last
week's Tailhook Association conference stand accused of
``inappropriate conduct'' toward a civilian woman triggered
immediate comparisons with the notorious 1991 Tailhook convention
that shook the Navy to its roots.
</P>
<P>
   The annual convention of Navy and Marine Corps aviators in
September of that year led to charges that 140 drunken servicemen
allegedly groped 83 females, many of them military officers, in
after-hours parties at the meeting in the Las Vegas Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy said Friday it is investigating a complaint by a
civilian couple that at least one service member staying at a
Sparks, Nev., hotel ``inappropriately'' touched the wife as she was
making her way though a hallway and that several servicemen made
``inappropriate comments,'' according to Lt. Com. Cate Mueller, a
Navy spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents are alleged to have taken place during the Aug.
17-20 Tailhook convention at the Sparks hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The Tailhook Association is a private organization that
represents Navy and Marine Corps aviators. The Navy suspended its
relationship with the group following the 1991 episode and restored
a connection this year for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The 1991 incident led to the resignation of Navy Secretary H.
Lawrence Garrett and Adm. Frank Kelso, the chief of naval
operations, and an end to numerous careers of lower level officers
present at the parties. It sparked several investigations,
congressional outrage and set off a flurry of soul-searching about
whether the Navy ever could welcome women as equals.
</P>
<P>
   The shadow of Tailhook also loomed over the 1996 suicide of
Kelso's successor, Adm. Jeremy Boorda. Boorda shot himself through
the heart after learning that Newsweek was preparing an article
questioning whether he was allowed to wear combat medals from tours
in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy investigation of Boorda's death, the Washingtonian
magazine said Tailhook factored into the suicide. There was a
drumbeat of hostility toward Boorda from members of the Navy's
``old guard,'' the magazine said, who considered Boorda a
``political admiral'' who had appeased politicians in his handling
of the scandal. The criticism weighed heavily on Boorda, according
to the magazine.In the wake of Tailhook, the Senate Armed Services
Committee required that every candidate for promotion in the Navy
have his or her record scoured for attendance at the 1991 Tailhook
event. More than 90 promotions at one point were held up by the
committee and many officers left the Navy because of the delay in
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   The 1991 scandal also generated questions about the Navy's
ability to investigate itself. The service was criticized for
belatedly beginning an investigation into charges of sexual
harassment and abuse made by several female Navy personnel. The
Navy's probe found little or no culpability.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the Pentagon's Inspector General investigated the Navy
probe and found many ``deficiencies'' in the Navy's internal
inquiry. The Pentagon IG concluded that Navy officials simply were
attempting ``to limit the exposure of the Navy and senior Navy
officials to criticism regarding Tailhook '91.''
</P>
<P>
   For some monitors of women in the military, the Tailhook episode
showed that women, even those in the officer ranks, were treated as
second class citizens.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Quarterly Report on Women and the Military, a
private journal devoted to women in the armed forces, Tailhook
``heightened social awareness of the disparity between the equality
of opportunity to choose occupation in the civilian sector and the
formal limitations on the roles of women in the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Retired Army Gen. Colin Powell, chairman of the joint chiefs at
the time, said Tailhook forced the military to treat female
servicemembers as equals.
</P>
<P>
   By 1993, Powell had confidently declared that the armed forces
had learned their lesson from Tailhook ``with respect to
relationships between men and women and what is acceptable behavior
and what is not . We are going through the last few chapters of the
Tailhook story, and then I think we'll be on our way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
