<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2360 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHENEY-HALLIBURTON-2T     08-25 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-HALLIBURTON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: FEW OPTIONS ON CHENEY OPTION PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can Dick Cheney find a way to have his money and still avoid a
possible conflict of interest resulting from his options to buy
stock in Halliburton Co., which he headed until the Republican
Party chose him as its candidate for vice president?
</P>
<P>
   The answer appears to be not with any certainty. Wall Street has
a lot of products that use complicated derivative securities, and a
cadre of people who design new ones, but tax experts say that none
of them solve the problem of getting Cheney out of having an
economic interest in Halliburton _ at least not when taxes are
considered. Perversely, the available strategies would leave him in
a position to profit most if Halliburton's stock collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears to me that the only sure ways out would be for
Halliburton's board to change the rules or for Congress to change
the tax law,'' said David M. Schizer, an associate professor at
Columbia Law School who specializes in tax law.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion of a tax law change may not be completely
frivolous. A highly technical change that would solve Cheney's
problem has been proposed by the Clinton administration, Schizer
said, but Congress has shown no interest in passing it.
</P>
<P>
   Though this problem affects only Cheney, it may in the future
affect many other executives who leave companies for public
service. Stock options have become common, and rules that delay
exercising them are in place at virtually all the companies that
issue them. Successful corporate executives are likely to have a
significant part of their wealth tied up in options that cannot be
immediately exercised unless their companies waive rules that apply
to other employees with options.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's problem stems from the fact that the Halliburton board,
in allowing him to take early retirement to join the Republican
ticket, did not change when he could exercise the options. As a
result, he must either forfeit them _ thus giving up millions in
potential benefits _ or hold onto them until long after a new
administration takes office.
</P>
<P>
   If he simply held them, every action by a Bush-Cheney
administration would be scrutinized for whether it was helping
Halliburton's stock price. That would be sensitive for any major
company that has government contracts, but it would be particularly
touchy for Halliburton, since the company is in the oil services
industry and its stock price is heavily influenced by the price of
oil, which could be affected by U.S. energy policy.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has said that if elected, he will sell his stock in
Halliburton before he takes office, but he has not said what he
will do with the options other than assert that he will avoid a
conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has 400,000 stock options, of which 166,667 can be
exercised this December, after the election but before the next
administration takes office. He can exercise 133,333 options in
December 2001 and 100,000 in December 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of options means that their value can soar or fall
far faster than the price of the underlying stock. For example, at
$53 a share, near Halliburton's recent stock price, the options
expiring in 2001 and 2002 would be worth $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   But if the price rose by $10 a share, a change of about 19
percent, the value of the options would leap 73 percent, to $6.1
million. If the price fell by $10, to $43, the value of the options
would fall 66 percent, to $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   If one ignores tax considerations, there are several ways Cheney
could lock in the current price, minus some transaction costs. He
could, for example, do a ``forward sale'' of Halliburton stock,
delivering it only after the options could be exercised.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, noted Robert Willens, a tax expert with Lehman
Brothers, the tax treatment would vary drastically depending on the
market price when the option was exercised.
</P>
<P>
   If the stock rose a lot by the time he exercised the option, the
result would be a lot of ordinary income, because profits from
exercising employee stock options are based on the market price
when the option is exercised. There would be a corresponding
capital loss on the forward sale. But capital losses cannot be
deducted from ordinary income above a $3,000 annual limit. If he
did not have sufficient capital gains to offset those losses, he
would face a large tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   How big could that be? Suppose Halliburton stock price is $50
when he does a forward sale and it rises to $80 by the time he
exercises the 100,000 options that mature in 2002. Not counting
taxes, he would take in $11.50 a share _ the difference between the
$50 price he is getting and the $39.50 a share that he must pay
Halliburton for the stock. His profit, pretax, would be $1.15
million.
</P>
<P>
   But the tax would be based on the difference between what he
paid _ $39.50 _ and the $80 market value. So at the top federal
rate of 39.6 percent, he would owe $1.16 million in taxes, $450,000
more than his actual profit.
</P>
<P>
   Partly offsetting that would be a large capital loss on the
sale, of $30 a share, or $3 million. But if he had no capital gains
from other investments, he could deduct only $3,000 of that from
his income.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if Halliburton's stock fell, he would have
less ordinary income and a capital gain on the forward sale. That
would leave him in a far better tax position than if the stock went
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony is that the derivatives position that leaves him
with a neutral position pretax leaves him with an economic
after-tax interest in the stock going down,'' said Schizer, whose
article on issues regarding executive compensation, ``Executives
and Hedging: The Fragile Legal Foundation of Executive
Compensation,'' appeared in the March issue of the Columbia Law
Review.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Cheney could use other strategies, but each has its own tax
consequences. Some would risk involving the ``constructive sale''
rules and force him to pay immediate taxes even before he realized
any profits. And when the money came in after the options were
exercised, the tax treatment would again vary markedly depending on
whether the stock had risen or fallen in the interim.
</P>
<P>
   Tax experts differ on whether the constructive sales rules would
apply in this case. But since there appear to be no precedents, it
would be risky for Cheney to assume they did not.
</P>
<P>
   An executive unconcerned about appearances and merely looking to
lock in some profit from his options would avoid those rules by
leaving himself with some exposure to the stock, for example
protecting him from losses if the shares fell below $50 and
relinquishing gains if they rose above $60. But if Cheney followed
that course, he would still have a stake in Halliburton _ the very
appearance of a conflict of interest that the tactics are intended
to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney might also borrow money under a contract that required
him to repay the loan with the stock he would get when he exercised
the options. But that could leave him with a large expense _ deemed
interest expense under the tax law _ that might not be deductible
unless he had a lot of other investment income. In that case, he
would suffer at tax time if the stock had risen sharply.
</P>
<P>
   All this could be avoided if Halliburton would let Cheney
exercise the options before he took office. But that might anger
other employees with options who did not have that right.
</P>
<P>
   Halliburton conceivably could amend its plan to let Cheney sell
his options to someone else, or to allow him to enter into
contracts that would let him deliver the options, rather than the
shares, when they can be exercised. Then the tax laws would be
simpler and the tax effect much more predictable, Schizer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has proposed a highly technical
change in tax laws dealing with straddles, another strategy that
Cheney might use. The proposal is aimed at what the administration
considers a possible abuse of tax law now being used to shelter
some income in transactions unrelated to Cheney's situation, and
Congress has shown little interest in the measure.
</P>
<P>
   But Schizer said the proposed change would effectively allow
Cheney to offset his losses and gains from one strategy, no matter
how large they were, and thus lock in his profits now, both before
and after taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another possible course that Cheney could take would be to
agree to donate the net profits to a charity after he was able to
exercise the options. But there is a tax trap even in that
strategy: The tax law limits the amount of charitable deductions to
half of a person's income. Cheney might find that he had to pay
taxes on some of the profits even after he had given them away. In
that case, he could take deductions in future years but would have
an immediate cash-flow problem.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians often complain that the tax laws are too
complicated. Cheney, in trying to decide what to do about his
options, appears to be learning how accurate that complaint is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
