<HEADER>
A2363 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-WITNESS0826-COX     08-25 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WITNESS0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Absence shows faith on Sabbath
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Absence can be a better witness to God than
in-your-face-evangelism.
</P>
<P>
   But it tends to be Jews who use absence to proclaim their faith.
Most Christians don't bother.
</P>
<P>
   Many Jewish merchants at trade shows leave their stalls barren
on the Sabbath. They sacrifice a day's sales to be obedient to the
law of their God.
</P>
<P>
   Trade shows, where retail merchants buy goods for resale,
generally take place for three or four days over a long weekend.
The markets are in New York and more than a dozen other major
cities.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, one of the major days of any show, many booths
owned by Orthodox Jews are empty of merchandise and salesmen. At
times, a modest poster stands on their empty showcase that reads:
</P>
<P>
   ``Our exhibit is closed today so that we may observe Sabbath. We
look forward to seeing you tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The gesture has to be expensive. They make no sales. They can do
no work in obedience to their understanding of God. But they make a
solid witness to their faith.
</P>
<P>
   I have attended many such shows and have yet to see a sign on
Sunday declaring that a stall owned by Christians is closed in
honor of the Resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Sunday is not the Sabbath and Christians are under
no obligations to refrain from work. But many Christians insist
that Sunday is their Sabbath and want an indifferent world to honor
it. Few do themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Christians are often driven by the evangelical imperative to
proclaim the Gospel to all people. But few bear witness to their
faith with the same powerful effect that a closed booth at market
does for Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   Some do. Years ago, I knew a fine tennis player in the small
Connecticut town where we lived. Fritz was a loyal churchman, but
he never wore his faith on his sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   One summer, he entered a town-wide tennis tournament and, over
several weeks, overwhelmed everyone he played. He was scheduled to
play for the championship at 10 a.m. on a Sunday morning in late
August amid great crowds at the town park.
</P>
<P>
   He told the officials that he would not be on the courts. He was
due in church at that time to help administer Holy Communion.
Someone else could do that, he admitted, but that was where he
belonged. He would forfeit the game.
</P>
<P>
   Tournament officials _ and townspeople _ were astounded,
bewildered and then impressed. The match was changed to Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Fritz won easily. More importantly, he was obedient to his faith
and willing to pay the modest price of being Christian at that
time.
</P>
<P>
   Like Jews who abandon their booths on Sabbath, he made a
statement about his values and his faith that no evangelical talk
about Jesus could match.
</P>
<P>
   Absence _ or simply the threat of it _ can be a powerful
witness.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
