<HEADLINE>
LAST MEAL FOR TEXAS' CONDEMNED NOT EXACTLY HAUTE CUISINE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
 By JOHN MORITZ 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ Say this about Texas prison inmates: They
ain't eating high off the hog.
</P>
<P>
   The state's 112-unit system raises cattle, pigs, chickens and
vegetable for consumption by its 150,000 inmates, but the prisoners
don't get the prime cuts, by any means.
</P>
<P>
   Even Fort Worth's Richard Wayne Jones' request for two BLTs as
part of his final meal this week was rejected because inmates are
not served bacon.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the high cholesterol that worries prison officials.
It's the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials decided it was cheaper and easier to grind up
most parts of the slaughtered hogs into sausage. And that's what
the inmates who ask for bacon get _ last meal or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the amount of people we have to feed and the amount of
pork we process, if we were to take the time to (prepare) bacon, it
works out to be about one slice per inmate per month,'' explained
Glen Castlebury, a spokesman for the Texas Department of Criminal
Justice. ``It's just not worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, executed Tuesday for killing 27-year-old Tammy Livingston
of suburban Fort Worth in 1986, was not alone in his desire to
depart this world with the taste of bacon on his lips.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, 10 of the last 50 inmates to die by injection in
Huntsville had asked for some variety of the sizzling strips.
</P>
<P>
   One, John Albert Burks of Waco, requested a full pound of bacon
before his execution on June 14.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, bacon is not the only popular item condemned
prisoners ask for _ and don't get _ as their last meal. Of the 230
inmates to die since Texas reinstituted capital punishment 18 years
ago, 21 requested T-bone steak.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they got a plate of Salisbury steak, which is grilled
ground beef that resembles hamburger, smothered in gravy.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, prison cooks prepare the Salisbury in the shape of
a T-bone.
</P>
<P>
   Other requests must conform to the prison's basic menu, which
includes such fare as fajitas, fried chicken, scrambled eggs and
cheeseburgers or hamburgers with a side of fries.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
