<HEADER>
A2368 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-25 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ADVANCE FOR SUNDAY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    HYPOTHETICAL LOOK BEYOND NOVEMBER
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CLAY ROBISON
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Politicians, especially when they are in the middle of
election campaigns, don't like to answer hypothetical questions.
</P>
<P>
   A question such as, ``How would you cut taxes if the Legislature
faces a budgetary shortfall next year?'' Or, ``What programs would
you cut first if you don't want to raise taxes to meet a revenue
gap?''
</P>
<P>
   Politicians don't like to answer those questions because doing
so would force them to be more specific than they usually want to
be. They could even find themselves taking an unpopular stand on
something. Horror of horrors!
</P>
<P>
   Just for fun, though, here is a different type of hypothetical
question, one that George W. Bush certainly doesn't want to answer:
</P>
<P>
   What if Bush loses his presidential race and is still governor
of Texas during next year's legislative session?
</P>
<P>
   I am not predicting a Bush loss, but at the risk of offending
the governor's legions of supporters, it COULD happen.
</P>
<P>
   If so, the legislative session that convenes in January could
end up being five tumultuous months in Austin. The session
certainly would be very partisan, perhaps the most partisan that
Texas &QL; 
legislative watchers have ever witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven forbid that it would approach the absurdity of the
partisanship that has plagued Washington in recent years, but it
could quickly make everyone forget the bipartisanship that
prevailed during Bush's first three legislative sessions.
</P>
<P>
   That bipartisanship was what enabled Bush to meet most of his
legislative goals _ and brag throughout the country about his
leadership abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also is touting the Texas Legislature's bipartisan
tradition as an example of how he, as president, would work to
improve government in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Bush is promoted to the White House, next year's
legislative session will have a mean partisan streak anyway because
it will be a redistricting session.
</P>
<P>
   Redrawing congressional and legislative district boundaries
after each federal census is, quite naturally, the most partisan of
legislative activities. The partisanship will be even more intense
next year because of the near-parity between Democrats and
Republicans in the Legislature _ and the Texas Democratic Party's
struggle to stay afloat in a flood of recent Republican gains.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that mix a lame-duck governor who would rather be
president and a lieutenant governor who would rather be governor _
remember, Lt. Gov. Rick Perry also has a lot at stake in the
presidential race _ and you may have a powder keg looking for a
match.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush worked well with most Democrats during previous
legislative sessions and a few Democratic lawmakers are openly
backing him for president, a number of Democrats have been blasting
his record as governor and campaigning for Democratic nominee Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush claims leadership on education, children's health
care and other important issues, his Democratic critics would have
the country believe that Bush couldn't find his own office in the
state Capitol without their guidance.
</P>
<P>
   The truth, as usual, is somewhere in the middle, but hard
feelings could linger if the debate were to help derail Bush's
presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Bush were able to forgive and forget, the stage,
nevertheless, would be set for some even deeper partisan divisions
over, say, hate crimes, the most partisan and most emotionally
divisive issue to confront the governor and legislators in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats will try to pass a hate-crimes bill again next
year, and if Bush is still governor he will likely continue to
oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   There also may be more fights over the size of the new
children's health insurance program, education reforms or civil
justice changes, and differences may be sharpened not only by
redistricting but also by memories from the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   One Bush admirer and longtime legislative observer said one of
the biggest changes that Bush may notice, if he is still governor
next year, is a change in Democratic legislators who have quietly
supported most of his programs over the years.
</P>
<P>
   With their own party's future at stake, he said, they may decide
that it's time to become more partisan.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, another legislative session with Bush in the
governor's office may not be very productive. It could be
entertaining, though.
</P>
<P>
   Robison is chief of the Chronicle's Austin Bureau.
(clay.robisonchron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
