<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2371 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ELY-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-25 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ADVANCE FOR SUNDAY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    HOPING POLITICAL WISH-LIST COMES TRUE LABOR DAY
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JANE ELY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   In years past, it has seemed silly to contend Labor Day marked
the proverbial kick-off day for presidential campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Recent tradition has had the Democratic and Republican
candidates engaged in structured and calculated campaigning so hard
for so long that Labor Day was, at most, a blip in the chronicling
of that year's presidential wars.
</P>
<P>
   But, when you read stories in the next week about Labor Day
being the true beginning of it all this year, you may be assured
there's a fair amount of hope in the hearts of all political
writers that, for once, those stories are correct.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there's a palpable yearning in the ranks of the press _
and the political junkies _ that the 2000 presidential campaigns
will get well organized and under way a week from Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, Democrat Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush have
been trudging around out there for political eons _ in fact,
literally years.
</P>
<P>
   And _ except for that long time there when Gore's political
flavor of the month(s) was to be harsh and negative _ they've
really been quite subdued, rarely even openly and truthfully
conflicting on issues on which, without question, they are
diametrically opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Don't misunderstand. This is not a call for full-scale negative
campaigning or even an occasional super attack that slings real
old-time political mud.
</P>
<P>
   It's a plea for campaigns that contrast, for campaigns that tell
the voters what each candidate wants government to do _ or not do _
on all the many levels of government and society.
</P>
<P>
   And, it's a plea for campaigns that tell how each candidate
proposes to effect his plan without ignoring _ no matter how much
he might wish _ the Congress of the United States and its vital
role in passing programs.
</P>
<P>
   As an aside of sorts, let's also consider this an urgent plea
for the attention of the electorate _ and, not incidentally, all
those constantly griping yahoos who like to justify their not
voting because, oooooh, they claim to be put off by any genuine
laying out of political differences, which they contend amounts to
mudslinging.
</P>
<P>
   Bosh and nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   It is not mudslinging to disagree with a political opponent. In
fact, we all should hope and pray for candidates who can _ and will
openly _ disagree on issues.
</P>
<P>
   Along these lines, the press, of course, must do its part. For
the easiest and most obvious example of all: If Gore stays
absolutely enamored of his people-vs.-the-powerful line, someone,
by golly, is going to have to investigate and demonstrate how his
opponent really is as stupid as Gore portrays him. Or, how stupid
Gore must think the electorate is.
</P>
<P>
   For example, were Bush really interested only in helping the
rich and powerful, as Gore contends, Bush most certainly is stupid.
</P>
<P>
   But, Bush is not stupid. Neither is Gore. And, Gore, especially
right now, must recognize the electorate's not stupid either.
</P>
<P>
   The Dem vice president and the GOP governor of Texas differ on a
huge number and variety of issues. The majority of the issues are
obvious _ even if the candidates' presentations of their views on
them vs. their opponents' are obfuscated, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   At the risk of being painfully realistic, there's yet another
point that should be added to the wish-list for Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we all should hope the campaigns will get under way in
great earnestness by then. And, yes, we should hope we are offered,
and we appreciate and understand, a great deal of substance in this
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But we also need to acknowledge that, while Gore was right when
he maintained ``the presidency is more than a popularity contest,''
an election is a whole lot about personality and popularity. And it
should be.
</P>
<P>
   Americans need to like their president. The president should be
popular. Bush has been considered likable, personable and popular
for a long political time now.
</P>
<P>
   The night Gore accepted the Democratic presidential nomination,
he became likable for a lot more Americans. He also started
climbing up in the polls that night. You think he still wants the
presidency decided exclusively on substance?
</P>
<P>
   The real question is, of course, can we expect any true
substance _ not just promises and vague beliefs _ from either of
them along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever they're going to do and however they're going to do it,
it sure would be nice if these two guys get really going on it by
Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's a cliche all America oughta like. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ely is a Houston Chronicle columnist. (jane.elychron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
