<SLUG> BC-R-WEST-FIREFIGHTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FIREFIGHTERS, IT'S BEGINNING TO FEEL LIKE WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating)   By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHALLIS, Idaho _ They head out before dawn and trudge home after
dark, weary and covered in soot, still clutching the shovels and
axes that are their weapons. They sleep as many as 21 to a tent, in
makeshift camps pitched beneath smoky, lung-choking skies.
</P>
<P>
   That is how thousands of firefighters across the West have spent
summer 2000, a season so devastating that commanders say they
cannot help but view it as a war.
</P>
<P>
   Others are beginning to view it that way, too. In fact, the
United Service Organization, best known for organizing shows to
entertain U.S. troops overseas, has now come to this remote corner
of Idaho. With three former beauty queens dressed in red, white and
blue micro-mini-dresses cooing and flirting from a flatbed truck in
a roadside meadow, the scene along the Salmon River on Thursday was
perhaps only the most surreal in a summer in which fire has drawn
people from around the country to the most isolated of places.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely something new,'' said Sgt. Craig Smith, 29,
of Birmingham, Ala., a Marine whose unit was dispatched to eastern
Idaho on Aug. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is among some 1,700 men and a handful of women in eastern
Idaho battling the largest of dozens of major fires burning across
the western United States. His coworkers include paramedics from
Tennessee, high-school dropouts from California, and federal
land-managers from all over the United States.
</P>
<P>
   After working 16-hour days on end, this group found itself
gawking on Wednesday and Thursday nights at the performers from the
USO, an organization whose past tours have almost always been
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our missions are primarily to remote and isolated places, and
there aren't too many places in the United States that qualify,''
said James Pearcy, the USO's director of entertainment. ``But I
guess sleeping on the ground for 30 days in a fire zone in the
middle of nowhere would have to count.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by Victoria Reed, a former Miss Maine, the New York-based
troupe performed a medley of staples that included everything from
``America the Beautiful'' to ``All My Lovin','' while planting as
many lipstick-red kisses as possible among a whooping audience that
found it hard to believe what had come to the camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a year!'' John Wallace, 23, a contract worker from Tule
Lake, Calif., said in disbelief, commenting not only on the
performance but also on the record paychecks that have resulted
from the record fire damage. ``I'm planning on living through the
winter off it.''
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, well over 25,000 men and women are involved in the
firefighting, including what will soon number more than 4,000
military personnel from the Army, Marines and the National Guard,
in an operation whose cost is estimated at $15 million a day. But
with 1.4 million acres still burning in the West, the current force
is not nearly sufficient, federal officials say, and a shortage of
trained supervisors means that it cannot prudently be reinforced.
</P>
<P>
   So federal officials have said there is little they can do to
fight many of the blazes. From fire camps like this one, the main
effort has been focused far from the flames, in efforts to
safeguard houses from danger and to make sure that the danger has
passed in areas where fires have already burned through.
</P>
<P>
   ``The resources have just run dry all over the country, and so
we've had to back off to wider lines,'' said Bill Cyr, 48, an
engineer with the Los Angeles Country Fire Department who since
Aug. 5 has bunked down under a yellow-tarp every night with a
20-man Marine unit, for which he is serving as a temporary adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Across the United States, nearly 6 million acres of land have
now burned this year, and with hot, dry weather conditions in the
West showing no sign of abating, the devastation is likely to
become the worst in at least half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the worst fires are in western Montana's Bitterroot
Valley, where a wind-driven flare-up in the last two days has added
to a blanket of smoke so thick that on Thursday midday felt like
deepest dusk. But the Clear Creek fire, burning northwest of here
in the Salmon-Challis National Forest, remains the largest single
blaze in the country, spanning some 165,000 acres, with only about
one-third contained.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 1,755 people, 16 helicopters, 66 fire engines
and 14 bulldozers have been assigned to fight the fire. But the
area is so vast and so isolated that commanders say that much of
their time and energy is devoted to logistics.
</P>
<P>
   The nearest substantial airport, in Idaho Falls, is three hours
away from this camp, which is set on a highway so that it can be
resupplied. Reaching the fire lines takes the crews an hour each
way by bus, traveling on narrow Forest Service roads.
</P>
<P>
   And though the food served at the camp is far better than
standard military fare, it does not come cheap, said Dale B.
Thompson, a Park Service ranger based in Arizona who is managing
the food operation here. A Thursday dinner that included halibut
and au gratin potatoes dished up by the Big Sky Catering Co. of
Missoula, Mont., which specializes in providing for fire crews,
cost taxpayers $16 a meal, for a total tab of $12,000, Thompson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The USO troupe flew in and out of Boise, Idaho, seven hours
away, and was returning to New York for regular weekend
performances on the USS Intrepid, the warship-turned-museum now
docked in New York. The Marines, who arrived here Aug. 5, have had
only one day off since, and receive no extra pay for their fire
service, said Lt. Alison Ake, a spokeswoman. The unit is scheduled
to return to California on Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   By law, the civilian firefighters contracted by the Forest
Service and other federal agencies receive more generous treatment.
</P>
<P>
   They are required to take one day off for every 14 days of work,
or two days every 21, and most of them get time-and-a-half for
overtime, which adds up quickly over the long days. Wallace, the
23-year-old Californian, figures he will earn $3,000 a month this
summer as a member of what is known as a Type II, or second-tier,
fire crew. That is more than triple his regular wintertime wage.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks in the smoke, firefighters say, simple pleasures
feel like enormous rewards. Brian Crawley, a 33-year-old paramedic
from southeast Tennessee, was looking forward to a brief respite
from what would be two back-to-back 21-day fire tours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm headed to the big metropolis of Challis,'' Crawley said,
``for two things I can't get here: a bed and a bath.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
