<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2373 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-25 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ADVANCE FOR SUNDAY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    OPERATIC TOUCH FOR THE PRESIDENTIAL RACE
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CRAGG HINES
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. _ As the primeval drama of Richard Strauss'
Elektra flooded from the stage and orchestra pit at the glorious
high-desert opera here last week, a basic truth of the current
presidential campaign came to mind again: revenge.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has repeatedly denied that settling old scores is
a motive force in his race against Al Gore, but almost no one
believes him. Bush is, simply, too ornery a son to sell that line.
</P>
<P>
   More specifically, Bush was far too involved in his father's
humiliating 1992 banishment from the presidency by the Clinton-Gore
ticket _ and witness to the ex-president's slow recovery of his
genial equilibrium _ for us to accept that getting even is not at
least a subtext for the younger Bush.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as last month, the Texas governor told London's
Daily Telegraph: ``You can't win if your reason for running is
revenge. Revenge is such a negative.'' Left unsaid, however, was
the fact that revenge is also a bright-burning fuel. And in the
same set of remarks, Bush conceded: ``I'm a loyalist. I'm a warrior
for George Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for many of the GOP candidate's fellow
Republicans. There's good reason that Newsweek's cover of Bush and
his vice-presidential contender, Dick Cheney, who was the elder
Bush's defense secretary, bore a simple caption: ``The Avengers.''
</P>
<P>
   Revenge is certainly not the Bush campaign's be-all and end-all.
There is an increasingly distinct set of distinguishing issues for
the electorate to base its votes on. But revenge is enough of a
palpable factor that Bush and his campaign _ and his family and its
friends _ must work to keep their exacting memories and injured
feelings in check.
</P>
<P>
   As the post-convention polls and Bush's less-than-steady
campaigning of late show, there's no room in the race for
peevishness.
</P>
<P>
   As warm as the public remembering of President Bush may have
become, we are too egalitarian a nation to put much faith in
political royal houses. Kennedy kin may flourish as vote-getters in
warmly Democratic constituencies, but for all the People magazine
cover-power of the clan, only one has made it to the White House
(so far).
</P>
<P>
   The operatic themes of vendetta and dynasty are more often than
not a passing point of interest in the campaign, an excuse for an
arresting phrase (``restoration convention'' in Britain's Guardian,
``redemption convention'' to USA Today) or, ahem, a column.
</P>
<P>
   The themes of revenge and lineage are not even unknown to Gore.
His political career in Tennessee was in many ways a bid to redeem
his father's defeat in 1970, after a long run as a Southern
populist in the House and Senate, by a rich conservative
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   That was 30 years ago, and the Bush wounds are far fresher, with
President Clinton vividly still on the scene and anxious to parlay
his legacy with the election of Gore. It may not be easy for the
Bushes to resist rising to what looks like it will be plentiful
baiting by Clinton-Gore.
</P>
<P>
   As shrewd a politician as Clinton didn't just happen to observe
in the days immediately before the Republican convention that a
basic rationale of the current Bush campaign was that ``my daddy
was president.'' Former President Bush snapped, threatening to tell
what he really thinks of Clinton ``as a human being.'' Is there
really any doubt what that view is? And would it advantage his
candidate-son if the former president let loose? The answer was so
clearly no that the elder Bush waved from the VIP section in
Philadelphia and quickly returned to an extended vacation in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   A close reading of Gore's performance last week in and around
the Veterans of Foreign War convention in Milwaukee pointed to more
bearding. In an interview with Cox newspapers after his speech,
Gore gave a left-handed defense of the elder Bush's endgame in the
Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always defended former President Bush's decision to
pull back when he had the knife at Saddam's throat,'' Gore said,
quickly adding: ``I think it was a mistake'' but ``an
understandable mistake. ... I think we ought to cut him some slack
on it.''
</P>
<P>
   That will have the Bushes, father and son, doing a slow burn.
But a quiet one, if they know what's politically smart.
</P>
<P>
   It's not Elektra, but it's not bad political theater.
</P>
<P>
   Hines is a Houston Chronicle columnist based in Washington, D.C.
(cragg.hineschron.com)
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
