<HEADLINE>
DISSIDENT POET FREED BY CHINESE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After an international protest from prominent
writers, Chinese authorities Friday freed a Boston-based poet and
editor from detention and were set Saturday to put him on a San
Francisco-bound airplane.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official confirmed the release of Bei Ling,
who was jailed Aug. 11 for distributing copies of Tendency
Quarterly, a journal edited in Cambridge, Mass. that regularly
includes articles and essays extolling the virtue of freedom of
expression.
</P>
<P>
   While the official had no information on Bei Ling's brother,
Huang Feng, who was also being held, a Boston associate of Bei Ling
said the two brothers were let go together.
</P>
<P>
   It happened after the US government asked for the release of the
brothers and after several well-known writers protested the
detention. Among those speaking out for Bei Ling and his brother
were Arthur Miller and Susan Sontag as well as Irish Poet Laureate
Seamus Heaney and Mexican poet Homero Aridjis. Sontag wrote an
op-ed piece in The New York Times, calling on the US government to
protest forcefully.
</P>
<P>
   As external pressures grow for more openness in China, the
country's Communist Party leadership has stepped up a crackdown on
dissent over the last year, banning the Falun Gong spiritual
movement, detaining human rights workers and handing down harsh
prison sentences to democratic activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We raised the case of Bei Ling through diplomatic channels
with the Chinese in Washington and Beijing, noting that we were
unaware of any criminal wrongdoing on the part of Bei Ling or his
brother and urging their immediate release,'' said the State
Department official, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``We
welcome their decision'' to release the brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese scholars believe that the rush of publicity about Bei
Ling's detention, coming less than two weeks before top Chinese
leaders attend the United Nations Millennium Summit in New York,
helped win his release.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response from the outside world was very strong,'' said
Merle Goldman, a professor of Chinese history at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   Even more importantly, she said, was that Chinese leaders wanted
to avoid ``any large-scale protests when they come to New York.
There will still be protests but nothing like there would have
been. It does show they care about their image in the outside
world. They don't want to be classified as a renegate nation,
grouped with nations like Iraq and Iran.''
</P>
<P>
   Meng Lang, an associate of Bei Ling, said Friday in Boston that
Bei Ling's brother told him over the telephone that the brothers
were fined the equivalent of $22,000 and remain under probation for
the next year. Bei Ling, he said, was to remain under police
supervision until he left the country, allowed only to talk with
his family. Meng Lang said that under pressure from authorities,
Bei Ling paid $2,200 of the fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am glad that the Chinese government released Bei Ling and
his brother, but they are released only under (probation) and
what's more, they were fined,'' Meng Lang said Friday through a
translator. ``The fine was for the supposed illegal publication of
Tendency, but Tendency is registered in Cambridge, Massachusetts,
and it should be protected by American government.''
</P>
<P>
   Bei Ling _ who was born Huang Beiling, but began using the name
Bei Ling 12 years ago after arriving in the United States _ founded
the journal in 1993 with several other Chinese exile writers.
</P>
<P>
   They have produced 13 copies, printing between 2,000 and 3,000
editions each time, sending them out by subscription to Sinologists
and Chinese writers as well as taking up to 1,000 copies to China
and giving them away.
</P>
<P>
   For the last several years, the journal was tolerated by
authorities. It published interviews with Heaney, Sontag, Nadine
Gordimer, Czeslaw Milosz and Octavio Paz; ran essays about religion
and Chinese poetry; and generally advocated freedom of expression.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, two uniformed officers and one plainclothes
officer seized several hundred copies of the journal from a bar
near Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
   While Bei Ling should arrive in San Francisco this weekend and
later travel to Boston, Meng Lang said that Bei Ling's brother, a
Chinese citizen, will remain in China. ``But he has expressed his
concern over the phone that he is not having full freedoms yet,''
Meng Lang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
