<P>
   AMWEST (Phoenix) - The FAA ordered America West on Friday to
prove within a week that it has competed with required maintenance
directives on a quarter of its aircraft fleet. The airline safety
regulatory agency also has given the Tempe-based carrier 30 days to
prepare an action plan for improving its maintenance practices,
oversight and record-keeping. America West would have to ground the
planes if it doesn't satisfy FAA regulators. The action comes as
the result of safety audits the FAA is conducting of all major
carriers in the wake of the Alaska Airlines crash. The action
against America West is the first taken by the FAA relating to
those audits.
</P>
<P>
   The problems the FAA has turned up are similar to concerns the
agency had in July 1998 when it fined the company $2.5 million. By
PETER CORBETT. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
