<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2378 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-COMMANDER-BOS &LR;      08-25 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-COMMANDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-SUB COMMANDER SAYS NEW TORPEDO MAY HAVE SUNK KURSK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Alexander Nikitin, a former Russian submarine
captain who has been jailed for exposing the dangers of radiation
leaks from that nation's aging fleet, said Friday he believes the
Kursk was sunk by explosions of a new type of torpedo the submarine
was testing.
</P>
<P>
   Nikitin, who was cleared earlier this year by the Russian
supreme court of espionage charges in connection with his
revelations of potential radiation dangers, dismissed other
theories about the cause of the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   As far as suggestions by Russian military leaders that the Kursk
had collided with another submarine or ship, he said in a talk at
Harvard University, ``I think that's just ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said some radiation can be expected to begin leaking
from the wreck of the Kursk within a few months, but that is not
the biggest radiation danger in the region; other Russian
submarines, mothballed but still loaded with nuclear fuel, are
sitting at docks and poorly maintained, and they could begin
leaking radiactivity at any time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking through an interpreter, he said of the Kursk that, ``I
know that kind of submarine really well, I've been on them many
times. Such submarines don't just go down all of a sudden. Some
serious event took place.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling it ``my personal version'' of what must have happened,
he said, ``I'm almost positive that two torpedos exploded in the
forward section.'' He added that he was ``pretty sure'' of this
because he had seen information to that effect on the Web site of a
Russian military newspaper, Krasnaia Zvezda (Red Star), but the
information was removed an hour later.
</P>
<P>
   ``The information concerned possible testing of two new torpedos
on the submarine at that time,'' Nikitin said.
</P>
<P>
   Others have suggested the exploding torpedo theory. Earlier this
week, a report in the newspaper Izvestia said, ``The typical
training torpedo does not contain explosive materials. But an
experimental torpedo containing a liquid-fuel rocket could have
exploded.''
</P>
<P>
   Nikitin, who has been working for more than five years to draw
attention to the problems of the ailing Russian nuclear program and
its potential for environmental devastation, was trained as a
nuclear engineer before becoming a submarine captain. He has
undergone 12 trials and spent more than 10 months in jail so far,
and faces another attempt by prosecutors to revive the case against
him this fall. He is being supported by the human rights
organization Amnesty International, which sees him as a classic
case of an environmental whistleblower facing harsh government
reprisals for his revelations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is heroic,'' said Marshall Goldman, associate
director of Harvard's Davis Center for Russian Studies, who invited
Nikitin to talk there Friday. ``How many of us are willing to go to
jail for our principles?''
</P>
<P>
   Nikitin said the new torpedos are being developed as a
cost-cutting measure. Conventional solid-fueled torpedos use silver
in critical components, but the liquid-fueled versions do not.
</P>
<P>
   ``These new torpedos probably exploded, and the first section''
_ the forward part of the sub where the torpedo tubes are located _
``was severely damaged. They didn't have time to blow their tanks
in order to surface. The bulkheads between sections one, two, and
three were probably destroyed as well, which affected the hermetic
seal of the entire submarine.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained that even if the first section of the submarine and
its ballast tanks were completely flooded, the sub would still have
been able to surface. Only if two or more sections and their tanks
were flooded would it be unable to do so.
</P>
<P>
   He said specialists had reported that the sub first sank to
about 200 feet, then to 330 feet. At 360 feet, he said _ about the
depth where the sub ended up _ the water pressure would have been
sufficient to destroy any remaining bulkheads.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, he said, there was nothing that any survivors on
board could possibly have done to surface. There were probably one
or more air pockets within the sub, he said, and ``as the time went
on, the air pocket probably migrated from one section to another''
as the sub settled, and ``the crew probably migrated with it. But
eventually, the ship was completely flooded and the crew
perished.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the idea, still being pushed by Russian authorities, that
there had been a collision, Nikitin said the Kursk has a
displacement of 23,000 tons _ an exceptionally large submarine.
``If a collision had occurred, it would have required a submarine
of similar size'' to cause the Kursk serious damage, he said.
``There was nothing like this around.''
</P>
<P>
   Nikitin said that leakage of some radioactive cooling water from
the Kursk's two nuclear reactors could begin within a few months.
But, he added, this is not the greatest radiation danger in the
region, just the tip of a much larger iceberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kursk added to the existing situation, but there is a more
dangerous situation'' already in the area, Nikitin said in an
earlier interview. ``There are more than 110 submarines that are
laid up but not disposed of'' at docks around the Murmansk region.
These subs, many of which contain more than one nuclear reactor,
add up to a total of about 250 reactors in the area.
</P>
<P>
   That makes it, Nikitin said, ``the largest concentration of such
reactors in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Of these submarines, he said, ``some have been laid up for ten
to fifteen years and still have their reactors on board. It's a
very serious situation, they could sink at any time. The longer
they are docked, the harder it will be to dispose of the nuclear
reactors later on.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation, he said, is ``very dangerous not only for the
environment, but for the people who work there.'' And, he said,
``the Russian government doesn't have the means to solve these
problems at the moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
