<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FLA0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush appeals to Latinos and the elderly in Florida campaign
stomp
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Appealing to Hispanic voters in Florida and other key
states with large Latino populations, Texas Gov. George W. Bush
promised Friday to expand free-trade with Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching for another targeted audience, Bush also released a new
campaign ad Thursday vowing that there will be ``no changes, no
reductions,'' in Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who arrived in Florida Thursday night to attend a private
event raising more than $1.5 million for GOP campaigns, spoke to a
mostly Hispanic audience at Florida International University Friday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   During his speech, Bush pledged to work toward giving Mexico the
same partner status that Canada and Great Britain share with the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should I become president, I will look South, not as an
afterthought, but as a fundamental commitment of my presidency,''
Bush said of Latin America. ``Just as we ended the great divide
between East and West, so today we can overcome the North-South
divide.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush made his remarks just hours before flying to Texas for a
meeting with Mexico's President-elect Vicente Fox. Bush said that
if he is elected president, he will ask Fox to meet with him before
the inauguration, ``to keep Mexican-American relations moving
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox and Bush already have one disagreement. Fox wants an
increase in open borders so that Mexican workers can come into the
United States more easily. Bush and the Clinton administration have
expressed reservations about Fox's proposal. Bush said he wants to
hire more border patrol officers so that, ``we can make our borders
more than just lines on a map.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also promised to work closely with Colombia and other
countries in their ``battle against Narco-terrorists.'' Bush said
the United States should increase efforts to help countries replace
drug crops with other legitimate income producing crops.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush wants to open free-trade with most of Latin America
he said he is not prepared to do the same thing with Cuba saying
President Fidel Castro, ``has not even begun the journey,'' toward
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I challenge the Castro regime to surprise the world and
adopt the ways of democracy. Until it frees political prisoners,
and holds free elections and allows free speech, I will keep the
sanctions in place,'' said Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential nominee said Congress should give
the president ``fast track'' authority allowing the president to
negotiate trade agreements without fear of Congress attempting to
amend the agreement. Congress would only be able to accept or
reject the entire agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Because the president does not have fast-track authority,
``other nations are unwilling to negotiate with us seriously,''
Bush said. President Clinton asked for fast-track authority but the
Republican-controlled Congress refused to give it to him.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign also unveiled a new advertisement Friday that is
being shown in key battleground states, including Florida. Aimed at
seniors, the 30 second commercial promises ``no changes, no
reductions'' in Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   In the ad Bush also promises to, ``make prescription drugs
available and affordable for every senior who needs them.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad concludes with these lines: ``you earned your benefits.
You made your plans. And President George W. Bush will keep the
promise of Social Security. No changes. No reductions. No way.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris LeHane, campaign spokesman for Vice President Al Gore, the
Democratic nominee, called Bush's prescription ad claim ``100
percent false.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They only way Bush could accomplish that goal would be by
voting for Al Gore. Bush literally spends more money on his
misleading ad then he does on his prescription drug plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore will be campaigning in Tallahassee on Monday with his wife,
Tipper. Bush's running mate, Dick Cheney, is expected to be in
Florida on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
