<HEADER>
A2384 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-WORCESTER-FIRE-BOS &LR;      08-25 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORCESTER-FIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME SEE PAIR IN FATAL WAREHOUSE FIRE AS SCAPEGOATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nov. 28, 1942. Fire breaks out in Boston's Cocoanut Grove
nightclub, flames creeping along the fabric-covered walls, then
racing across the dance floor. Patrons and employees try to escape,
but owner Barnett Welansky has barricaded most of the exit doors. A
revolving door, one of the few routes out, quickly gets jammed; 492
people perish inside. Welansky is convicted of involuntary
manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 3, 1999. Fire breaks out in the Worcester Cold Storage and
Warehouse Co. building, when two homeless people, squatting inside,
knock over a candle during an argument. They leave the building
without telling anyone. Hours later, six Worcestver, Mass.
firefighters die in the blaze. The homeless pair, Julie Barnes and
Thomas Levesque, are charged with involuntary manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The two tragedies, separated by more than 50 years, are
connected by the threads of Massachusetts' legal system: the
prosecution's case against Barnes and Levesque rests largely on
precedents set in the case of the Cocoanut Grove. Upholding
Welansky's conviction in 1944, the Supreme Judicial Court
established the definition of involuntary manslaughter _ ``an
unlawful homicide unintentionally caused by wanton or reckless
conduct'' _ that state courts are bound by today.
</P>
<P>
   It will be up to Superior Court Judge Timothy Hillman, and
possibly a jury, to determine if Barnes's and Levesque's conduct
rose to the standard of ``wanton and reckless.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Hillman considers a motion to dismiss the case, it will
also be in his power to determine whether Barnes and Levesque
should have been charged with manslaughter at all. And if the
Cocoanut Grove case sets the standard, some criminal defense
attorneys say, the Worcester case doesn't come close.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only in the most extraordinary kinds of cases that these
kinds of charges are brought,'' Boston defense attorney Jamie
Sultan said. The Cocoanut Grove case, he said, involved ``much more
than ordinary negligence. Certainly, not reporting a fire _ I can't
think of any circumstance where that would be deemed a criminal
act.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some criminal defense lawyers say the magnitude of the
Worcester tragedy, and the community's outpouring of grief and
anger, has led to an overzealous prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horrific situations sometimes lead publicly elected officials,
such as a district attorney, to act when he normally would have
handled the situation differently,'' said J. W. Carney Jr., a
criminal defense attorney and former prosecutor. ``There was such
an outpouring of sorrow and outrage in Worcester that it's easy to
find a scapegoat. Sometimes, tragedies just happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But Worcester prosecutors say Barnes and Levesque could have
prevented the tragedy, had they behaved differently. At a hearing
earlier this month, assistant District Attorney Larry Murphy told
Hillman that the pair were behaving recklessly before the fire
spread: They were trespassing in a building and scuffling on a bed,
and they failed to notice the flames right away.
</P>
<P>
   The blaze would not have been as massive, or the results as
tragic, if Barnes and Levesque had reported it right away, Murphy
said. They clearly knew the fire was dangerous, he said, because
they left the building without gathering their belongings. But
because they didn't call the fire department, he said, the fire
gathered strength for at least an hour before it was detected.
</P>
<P>
   The pair had ``absolutely no concern for the other man,'' he
said. ``Absolutely no concern for the firemen. We say that's
reckless.''
</P>
<P>
   But Levesque's attorney, Ed Ryan, told the court there was a
clear difference between the Welansky case and the Worcester fire.
Welansky's decision to barricade nightclub doors was ``intentional,
affirmative conduct,'' Ryan said. Barnes and Levesque made an error
of omission _ failing to report the fire. And while that might
constitute negligence, Ryan said, it shouldn't be a crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could leave this building today and see some poor soul under
attack in the street,'' Ryan said. ``If I turn around and go the
other way, having had the opportunity and the knowledge to look the
other way . . . can I be charged with involuntary manslaughter if
that person dies?''
</P>
<P>
   That argument is a foundation of the criminal justice system,
defense lawyers say. Neglecting a duty to the community might be a
moral failure, they say, but it's rarely prosecuted as a criminal
act.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not required, upon pain of criminal penalties, to
be responsible citizens,'' Sultan said. ``People are free to be
responsible . . . or irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Worcester case isn't quite so clear-cut, Boston defense
attorney Harvey Silverglate says, because Barnes and Levesque
didn't just see the fire _ they caused it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a fire that you started, do you have an obligation
to report it, since a fire is an inherently dangerous thing?'' he
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Hillman acknowledged the complexities of the case during the
hearing earlier this month. He asked prosecutors whether ``we are
about to set a standard'' by trying Barnes and Levesque. And he
asked defense attorneys whether, in some cases, there is a legal
obligation to report a fire: ``If a candle were tipped over in a
multifamily dwelling . . . would there be a duty to the other
tenants?''
</P>
<P>
   Common sense dictates that there would, Ryan replied. ``If you
have an inhabited building and you know it and you start a fire,
you can't walk away from it,'' he said. ``That doesn't amount to a
recognition that not calling someone would result in the deaths of
six firefighters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 1933EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2387 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FIRES-OVERVIEW0827-CO     08-25 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRES-OVERVIEW0827-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Tales from the front lines
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If any places were ripe for fires of epic proportions
this summer, they were the vast forests, brushlands and grasslands
of the American West.
</P>
<P>
   For years, massive amounts of combustible dead limbs, toppled
trees and logging debris _ what foresters call fuel _ had been
accumulating on the forest floors and had reached dangerous levels
in huge stretches of woodlands. In many forests, the deadwood stood
higher than six feet, a sure sign of unhealthy woods, forestry
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the fuel-choked forests was that until the 1970s,
the U.S. Forest Service's policy was to extinguish all fires. A
public education campaign featuring Smokey the Bear in a park
ranger hat drummed into Americans a revulsion to wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   But scientists later realized that fire actually is a friend of
the forest. Occasional low-intensity fires that sweep through
woodlands remove deadwood and underbrush and return vital nutrients
to the soil without harming mature trees and other vegetation and
wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   When fires are suppressed and deadwood builds up to massive
levels, forest fires can become towering infernos, able to leap
from tree crown to tree crown with explosive speed, turning huge
swaths of forests into charcoal and threatening houses and entire
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1970s, Forest Service scientists and other land
management agencies have tried to offset the deadly buildup of dead
trees and brush with deliberate ``prescribed'' burnings. They also
have altered their once strict fire-suppression policies to let
fires burn themselves out in wilderness areas if human habitation
is not threatened.
</P>
<P>
   But forestry experts say the effort has been too little and too
late. Just this month, critics were laying part of the blame for
the western fires on the Clinton Administration, saying the White
House had not acted quickly enough after being warned over the
years that there was a small window of opportunity _ perhaps a
decade _ before the forests became so inundated with fuel that
every fire could have catastrophic consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 40 million to 60 million acres of federal forest _ nearly
all of it in the West _ are in dire need of thinning, forestry
officials say. And the drought is complicating matters.
</P>
<P>
   Three good years of rainfall that spurred the growth of plants
were followed by a searing drought. This year's dry spring was
lethal. It dried out vegetation more quickly than usual, extending
the growing season, and also melted snow more rapidly, so that more
water than usual ran away in streams instead of soaking gradually
into the ground to keep vegetation green longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fuel here has only about 4 to 7 percent moisture; that's
about as dry as lumber dried in a kiln,'' said Keith Wooster, a
biologist with the Chattahoochee National Forest in Georgia who was
dispatched to the Ryan Gulch area 30 miles east of Missoula, Mont.,
to fight a major wildfire.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on a smoky ridge overlooking a steep slope where the
Ryan Gulch fire roared nearby, Wooster pointed to a layer of dead
limbs, each about the diameter of a baseball bat. ``They are so dry
you could light them with a match,'' he said _ and then he had to
walk briskly to get away from the intense smoke and heat welling up
from the wildfire.
</P>
<P>
   A few hundred feet away, his colleague, George Custer, a fire
protection expert with the Ocala National Forest in Florida, used a
drip torch to set a ``backfire.'' It would remove fuel from the
advancing wildfire; with nothing to burn, the wildfire would go
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least that's what we hope,'' Custer said. ``We're literally
fighting fire with fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the big wildfires were sparked by dry thunderstorms that
have produced much lightning and little rain. A few wild blazes
have been human-caused. No matter what triggers them, when the
cataclysmic fires get going, their ashes can be borne aloft and set
new fires as far as a half mile away.
</P>
<P>
   What complicates the firefighters' jobs is that the West is
adding population rapidly, creating what's called an
``urban/wildfire interface'' of houses, farms and ranchettes tucked
high among the trees. In such a setting, the highest priority for
firefighters is to protect the homes and other structures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going into situations that, absent homes and property,
we wouldn't be putting firefighters into,'' said Steve Frye,
incident commander for the firefighting efforts in Montana's
Bitterroot Valley. He called the intense fires raging in the valley
``unprecedented,'' with veteran firefighters saying they have never
witnessed such ferocious fires, with flames shooting up 150 feet
high.
</P>
<P>
   Given the flames' unpredictability, protecting people and their
homes and barns and other structures may, even under good
conditions, require high-risk tactics. Critics say that if people
insist on living at the very edge of forests or in the woods
themselves, then they should not expect firefighters to endanger
themselves to protect dwellings so vulnerable to wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   One of the critics is Forest Hayes, the mayor of Darby and a
retired Forest Service district ranger. The Bitterroot Valley, he
says, has become a focal point in the national firefight because of
the sheer number of homes pressed up inside remote canyons and
under the canopy of the lodgepole pine forests that throughout
history have been the scene of dramatic forest fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fire trucks have a hard time getting up to those houses,'' he
said as he stood in a park in Darby last week, updating residents
on the fires and offering words of comfort and advice to frightened
homeowners. ``And when they build, they leave debris and brush
right up to the very edge of their homes; that's inviting the fire
to come get you.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 285,000 acres have burned in the Bitterroot area
alone.
</P>
<P>
   In all, more than 1.5 million acres in 11 western states have
succumbed to wildfire so far this summer, the most destruction from
wildfires in at least 50 years. Before the flames are finally
snuffed out, they will be the worst in more than a century, veteran
firefighters say.
</P>
<P>
   At least 30,000 firefighters are battling the blazes across the
region, with reinforcements from Canada, Australia and New Zealand,
as well as from the Army and Marines, who together have dispatched
three battalions. The government is spending at least $15 million a
day to stop the fires. Southwestern Montana is ground zero.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
