<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-UNION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3,000 RAYTHEON WORKERS SET TO STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly 3,000 Raytheon Co. manufacturing workers in Massachusetts
may strike this weekend in a contract dispute that has exacerbated
frayed relations between the defense firm and much of its work
force.
</P>
<P>
   Talks were still under way Friday night at between Raytheon and
the union that represents its local blue-collar employees.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are ``seriously divided'' on issues such as health
and pension benefits, union leaders said earlier this week.
``Things aren't going well,'' said a person familiar with the talks
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The union's contract expires at midnight Saturday; a meeting is
scheduled Sunday morning at which members will vote to strike or to
continue to negotiate with the Lexington, Mass. defense company.
</P>
<P>
   Union negotiators also want job-security guarantees following
thousands of layoffs by Raytheon in recent years. The company has
shifted missile programs to plants in Arizona, where it pays
workers less; the Pentagon says the transfers have saved Raytheon
as much as 35 percent on some programs.
</P>
<P>
   Saving cash is a priority for Raytheon, whose stock trades at
around a third of the high it reached last year because of earnings
disappointments. It expects to have some leverage over the union,
which after layoffs represents just a fraction of the Raytheon's
14,000 Bay State employees.
</P>
<P>
   But the union, Local 1505 of the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers, is also digging in.
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders feel betrayed for helping the company win a
controversial state tax break in 1995 on the understanding the deal
would preserve jobs. And even though the US Labor Department has
sued to require a new election of Local 1505's top officers, the
union member whose complaints led to the suit said he supports the
current leaders in their negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they recommend a strike, I'll be the first one out on the
picket line,'' said the dissident, George Noel, a circuit-card test
operator and an unsuccessful candidate to become the union's
business manager last year. As described to him by other union
members, Noel said, the company's recent offers have been
``atrocious.''
</P>
<P>
   The union's current contract was ratified two years ago and
provided wage increases of 5 percent in its first year and 4
percent in its second year. Now union negotiators seem to be
seeking increases of at least 5 percent a year to keep pace with
rising cost of living in the Northeast. But one example for
Raytheon is an agreement it struck last fall with workers at its
Arizona missile plants, who received a four-year contract providing
annual raises of 3 percent to 4 percent each year.
</P>
<P>
   Another stumbling block is paid time off. Protected from layoffs
by their seniority, most of Local 1505's workers are 40 and older,
and receive five weeks of vacation a year, plus nine sick days.
Raytheon is seeking to give each employee 25 days off a year,
effectively eliminating the sick leave many enjoy, according to
sources on both sides of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon spokesman David Polk declined to specify the company's
exact positions, but said ``we have hope that we can reach a
successful agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Polk said negotiators are seeking a contract ``that is fair and
equitable to our employees and that still enables the company to
compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Local 1505's president, Stanley Lichwala, nor its
business manager, Michael Zagami, returned phone calls. Lichwala
has hinted of a pending strike in the past and, in an interview two
weeks ago, said that ``the union is united to fight the company to
get a fair contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Local 1505 filed its answer to the Labor
Department's lawsuit in US District Court in Boston this week,
denying the government's contention that its election last year
violated federal election rules.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the government's charges are based on complaints by
Noel. He alleged ballots weren't counted secretly in last year's
election because the polling-booth partitions were too low, and
that fliers supporting Zagami's candidacy were mailed at union
expense. The government says the union agreed in March to re-run
the election, but then reversed itself.
</P>
<P>
   In an Aug. 23 response Local 1505 called the Labor Department
``incapable'' of supervising a new election. When government
officials tried to do so, according to the filing, they ``directed
and/or permitted Raytheon Company to interfere with, restrain,
and/or coerce employees and/or union representatives.''
</P>
<P>
   A Labor Department spokesman declined to comment. Said
Raytheon's Polk, ``Raytheon maintained complete neutrality
throughout'' the election process.
</P>
</TEXT>
