<SLUG> BC-KENYA-PRIEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN CATHOLIC PRIEST IN KENYA FOUND SHOT TO DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ An American priest who made many enemies among
the powerful and corrupt in Kenya was found shot to death Thursday
on a rural roadside a few yards from his pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   The Roman Catholic priest, the Rev. John Anthony Kaiser, 67, a
native of Minnesota who had lived in Kenya for most of the last 36
years, died from a shotgun blast to his head. Near his body was a
shotgun and in his shirt pocket a live round of its ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators said they suspect it was murder, not suicide,
and the American ambassador here has urged the Kenyan police to
accept help from the FBI in the investigation. No spent shell was
found on the scene. A local reporter who saw the body said Kaiser
was shot from the back with such force that he was nearly
decapitated.
</P>
<P>
   In a country with periodic _ and unsolved _ politically
motivated murders, human rights groups were quick to suspect
someone in government whom Kaiser had angered with his frequent,
and public, denunciations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who in Kenya is desperate to kill Father Kaiser and why now?''
asked Willy Mutunga, head of the Kenya Human Rights Commission, at
a news conference of human rights groups, lawyers and women's
groups Friday in downtown Nairobi. ``They could only be powerful
people who saw him as a moral thorn in their evil flesh.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser most recently ran afoul of a Kenyan minister of state,
Julius Ole Sunkuli, over allegations that the official had sexually
violated a minor.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the girl reportedly sought counsel from Kaiser, who
advised her to speak to lawyers who later pursued a case against
Sunkuli. The minister was charged with statutory rape in June and
is expected to appear in court again later this month. He has
denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   After the allegations became public, Kaiser, a member of the
Society of St. Joseph, was refused renewal of his work permit. The
permit was granted late last year only after strong protest from
the American Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser's difficulties with government officials stretch back at
least to the mid-1980s, when he became active defending victims of
land disputes. He also spoke out against politically motivated
tribal clashes in the early 1990s, and criticizing two top Kenyan
government ministers for involvement in the eviction of farmers
from their land in the Rift Valley. He was held under house arrest
briefly in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   An official close to the investigation of Kaiser's death said,
however, that the evidence did not immediately point to any
particular suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police have pronounced it a murder and we assume that is
the case,'' said an official, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity. ``Beyond that _ and beyond the general fact that he had
a number of enemies _ there is no specific theory about who did
this or why they did it. It could be anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   After Kaiser's body was found _ near the town of Naivasha, about
50 miles northwest of Nairobi _ some of Kaiser's friends have told
reporters that he seemed unusually agitated in the past several
days. In recent weeks he reportedly told several people he feared
for his life.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, Kaiser reportedly had dinner with the bishop
of Ngong, about 25 miles west of Nairobi, and left about 7 p.m. to
drive to his parish, about 150 miles west.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser's body was found by a passing motorist about 6 a.m.
Thursday near his Toyota truck at the roadside, said police
investigator Mary Ruara. She said the scene had been arranged to
suggest a suicide, with sheets and blankets laid out near the
pickup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 1942EDT &QL; 
