<HEADER>
A2397 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-TEXAS-PIPELINE-HNS &LR;      08-25 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-PIPELINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MEXICO BLAST CAUSES CONCERN ABOUT TEXAS PIPELINE 
 
  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Land Commissioner David Dewhurst said
Friday that he was ``scared'' by similarities between a natural gas
pipeline that exploded in New Mexico last weekend and an old
pipeline that may be reopened to transport gasoline from Houston to
El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   ``Similarities between the ... pipeline that blew out ... and
the Longhorn pipeline, quite frankly, scare me,'' Dewhurst said,
even though the two pipelines are designed for different
commodities.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Dewhurst visited the site near Carlsbad, N.M.,
where 11 people were killed and another person critically injured
Aug. 19 when the pipeline operated by El Paso Natural Gas Co.
exploded near their campsite.
</P>
<P>
   Both pipelines, he said, are about 50 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the pipeline business, that's not a good thing,'' he added.
``There have been six major pipeline blowouts (in the United
States) since 1985. Like Longhorn, all six of these blowouts have
involved pipelines that were installed in the 1950s and the 1960s _
old pipes.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Texas pipeline, owned by Dallas-based Longhorn
Partners Pipeline, was built in 1950 to carry crude oil from West
Texas to refineries in Baytown near Houston. It has been inactive
since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Dewhurst also said that both the El Paso pipeline that blew up
and the Longhorn pipeline run through areas of high salinity, which
contributes to corrosion, the second leading cause of pipeline
explosions.
</P>
<P>
   He said that a draft environmental assessment of the Longhorn
pipeline found that the pipeline's corrosion-control practices were
``questionable.''
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary investigation found corrosion in one section of
the blown-out pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   Dewhurst toured the site of the New Mexico blast with National
Transportation Safety Board Chairman Jim Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a pretty scene,'' Dewhurst said. ``Apparently the
fireball was 1,200 degrees. It reached 350 feet in height. Sand
turned to glass. Concrete turned to powder. ... It's a scene I'll
never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   On its 700-mile proposed route across Texas, the Longhorn
pipeline would pass through or near residential neighborhoods in
Houston, Austin and several other communities and would cross the
environmentally sensitive Edwards Aquifer, from which drinking
water is drawn, in Central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Dewhurst said that 42,000 people in the Houston area's Harris
County alone live within 1,250 feet _ less than one-quarter of a
mile _ from the Longhorn route. Two elementary schools in Harris
County, he said, are located within 200 feet of the line.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorn proposal has drawn heavy opposition from
landowners, environmentalists and public agencies. Dewhurst said he
will continue to work to block the Texas pipeline until he is
convinced it can be operated safely.
</P>
<P>
   Longhorn said in a written statement that a federal regulatory
review of its pipeline proposal, which is now under way, will
produce ``one of the most extraordinarily safe and environmentally
sensitive pipelines in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the second time that the land commissioner had publicly
raised questions about the Longhorn pipeline. In March, he
announced that he would not sign easement documents necessary for
the pipeline to operate across six Texas rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Dewhurst said Friday that he hoped the Longhorn pipeline could
eventually be put into operation, and he said he was willing to
work with the company to make sure all his concerns about safety
were adequately addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, the pipeline should and can be safe,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dewhurst said he will discuss with federal officials how much of
the Longhorn pipeline should be replaced and whether part of the
line should be rerouted to bypass heavily populated and
environmentally sensitive areas.
</P>
<P>
   Among other points that still had to be worked out, he said,
were assurances that pipe bends, which are often difficult to
inspect, had been adequately inspected for corrosion.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement, Longhorn said that it was confident a safety
and environmental study now being conducted by the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency and the U.S. Department of
Transportation's Office of Pipeline Safety ``will incorporate the
newest and most stringent standards for pipeline.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he (Dewhurst) is going to be greatly relieved when the
final (federal) approval with its mitigations (improvements) is
issued because just about every concern he's expressed will be
addressed in that document,'' added Longhorn spokesman Al Erwin.
</P>
<P>
   Erwin also said that part of the pipeline may be replaced, but
he didn't know how much.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the Longhorn pipeline would eventually compete with
entrenched West Texas gasoline suppliers, including New
Mexico-based Navajo Refining Co. Navajo is fighting the project and
has helped to fund some of the citizen opposition to the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   The New Mexico explosion and the Longhorn controversy come at a
time when federal regulators have been slapping pipeline operators
with fewer fines.
</P>
<P>
   A General Accounting Office report issued in May raised
questions about decisions by the Office of Pipeline Safety to
reduce the use of fines against operators and lessen its dependence
on state inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Dewhurst said the federal agency employs only 55 inspectors to
cover 2 million miles of pipeline in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1989 and 1998, 226 people were killed and another 1,030
were injured in accidents along the nation's natural gas and
liquids pipelines, according to a GAO analysis of the Office of
Pipeline Safety's data.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
