<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2401 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-TEXAS-SAFETIES082     08-25 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-SAFETIES0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ready to knock the stuffing out of you
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Safeties typically are a motley bunch. They have
to be fast enough to run with the wide receivers, cocky enough to
intimidate those same wideouts, hit hard enough to knock a running
back out of his shoes and salty enough to change defensive calls
just by reading the quarterback's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   These same safeties _ free and strong _ usually walk with a
swagger and chatter to anyone who'll listen.
</P>
<P>
   They have a roguish attitude, a devious glint in their eyes, a
devil-may-care approach to the game and life.
</P>
<P>
   Then you have the University of Texas' starting safeties _
senior Greg Brown and junior Lee Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Both are self-confessed mama's boys with hearts as soft and
mushy as a too-ripe banana.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson got so homesick two years ago that he boxed all his
stuffed animals and called his mother to pick him up and take him
back to Longview. These days, his teammates call him ``Tigger''
because his dorm room is decorated in the overwhelming orange and
black motif of that famous cartoon character from ``Winnie the
Pooh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a big kid,'' said Ahmad Brooks, Jackson's suite
mate, rolling his eyes as he described his buddy's dorm room.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the team's fashion plate, found himself spending his
monthly meal money check and maxing out two credit cards to buy
designer duds when he got to Texas in 1997. He's since curbed his
spending and switched preferences from cotton knit to silk. His
mall time now is spent in the classroom, and with his B average in
pharmacy, he has the best chance of any UT defensive player to be
named academic All-American.
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, these guys are anything but the stereotypical
safety. But they leave those soft hearts on the sideline, with
their on-field play indicating they might be the best safety combo
in the Big 12 Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good tandem because physically, they're so much
alike,'' said UT defensive coordinator Carl Reese. ``They both have
a lot of tools, and they both bring a lot to the table
physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Added secondary coach Everett Withers: ``Safeties come in all
shapes and sizes . . . I've never been associated with safeties
with this size and athleticism. But that's the trend these days to
find those big rangy guys who can run.
</P>
<P>
   It took several strokes of fate to even have them playing beside
each other. Jackson battled an intense case of homesickness before
earning a starting job as a sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got here, I didn't want to be here,'' Jackson
said of his first semester at UT in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, only injuries forced the coaches to take a long look
at Brown. He was third string last season in the opener against
North Carolina State. By the fourth quarter against the Wolfpack,
after season-ending injuries to Quentin Jammer and Chris Butcher,
Brown was the starter by default.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew in my heart I was a pretty good player,'' said
Brown, a teammate of quarterback Major Applewhite at Catholic High
School in Baton Rouge, La.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I needed a little boost. God gave me the chance. He was on
time, although I had always wanted the playing time a little
sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 6 feet 3 inches and 210 pounds, is blessed with an NFL
physique. He has grown two inches and gained 20 pounds since his
senior season at Longview High when he was one of the most coveted
defensive back prospects in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Longhorns voted Jammer, the safety-turned
cornerback, as the team's hardest hitter, Jackson was named on
several ballots.
</P>
<P>
   He notched 86 tackles last season, second best on the team to
the 101 by defensive tackle Casey Hampton. In only the first week
of preseason drills, Jackson already has stuck a teammate so hard
that he almost gave himself a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a freak accident,'' Jackson said earlier this week, a
day after he suffered pain and nausea from his big hit. ``I'm not
going to hold back. I'm still going to go out there and hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Brown: ``Yeah, Lee's stacked. He looks like an NFL
safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown is only a shade smaller at 6-2, 210. And he, too, can
deliver a blow. He started the final 13 games of 1999 and by
season's end was an honorable-mention pick on the coaches'
all-conference team. His 82 tackles were third best on the team
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his high grades and excellent leadership ability, he
also was named UT's representative to the NCAA Foundation
Leadership Conference last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Brown plans on becoming a pharmacist after football, but he
would like to give the NFL a chance next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I have a real good shot of getting drafted in one
of the late rounds if I can drop my 40 time a tenth or two,'' Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But first, I want to win me a national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
