<SLUG> BC-NY-KRAMDEN-STATUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV ICON IN BRONZE TO LOOM LARGE AT PORT AUTHORITY 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT17 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEAN E. MURPHY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The management of the Port Authority Bus Terminal
near Times Square believes a half-ton statue of the actor Jackie
Gleason will make commuting more enjoyable for the 185,000
passengers who catch a bus there daily. And the promoters of the
cable television channel TV Land, which has relaunched the 1950s
series ``The Honeymooners,'' couldn't agree more.
</P>
<P>
   Commuters can draw their own conclusions on Monday morning, when
an eight-foot bronze statue of Gleason as Ralph Kramden _ the
Brooklyn bus driver he portrayed in ``The Honeymooners'' _ will be
mounted outside the Eighth Avenue entrance to the world's busiest
bus terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry if the sidewalk gets a bit squeezed with the
bigger-than-life Gleason, the management says. ``The congestion
that you envision happens during the rush periods,'' said Cedrick
T. Fulton, general manager of the bus terminal. ``The majority of
the hours of the day, that situation doesn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulton sees the statue as part of the terminal's effort to make
the commuting experience a memorable one and envisions passengers
stopping to have their pictures taken with the statue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am trying to delight my customers, to tell the world this is
a great place,'' he said. ``There is nothing to worry about, come
and visit sometime.''
</P>
<P>
   TV Land, which has paid for the statue, says it is ``honoring a
public icon.'' The channel is not being charged a promotional or
advertising fee by the Port Authority. Rob Pellizzi, vice president
for marketing, says the statue belongs to a publicity campaign that
``has been concentrated on the biggest bang.'' Pellizzi said the
channel was thinking of promoting its other shows with ``similar
partnerships'' across the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
