<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2412 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-BAYLOR-QB0826-COX     08-25 2138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAYLOR-QB0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Huddle up: Big 12, name your starters
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Greg Cicero's tunnel vision isn't so extreme
that he fails to notice what's going on beyond the Waco city
limits.
</P>
<P>
   The onetime Texas Longhorn is focused on establishing himself as
the starting quarterback at Baylor this fall as the Bears try to
begin the uphill climb from a 1-10 pratfall in Kevin Steele's
head-coaching debut. Cicero readily acknowledges he occupies an
unsettled position for Baylor but is quick to note that that hardly
makes him unique this year in the Big 12 Conference, especially
among the Lone Star State branch of the family.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look around.
</P>
<P>
   At Texas, the Longhorns are encouraged by Major Applewhite's
rehabilitation from knee surgery and are wondering about the
ramifications of a subsequent battle with Chris Simms for the
starting spot.
</P>
<P>
   At Texas A&AMP;M, Coach R.C. Slocum has picked Mark Farris over
Vance Smith and redshirt freshman Colby Freeman. Farris will get
his first career start in the opener at Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Tech fans fervently hope that sophomore Kliff Kingsbury
lives up to the tantalizing promise shown in his limited
appearances last season as he directs first-year coach Mike Leach's
air-it-out offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fun part of this season will be that in addition to it
being my starting time, it'll be theirs, too,'' Cicero said of the
other mostly unproven quarterbacks. ``When we play each other,
it'll be mano-a-mano: me against them to draw some comparisons, and
that's the way it should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be fun. You should want to do your best against the
best, and there are a lot of good quarterbacks in this league even
though most of them are pretty inexperienced.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the respective fates of the Big 12's Texas contingent _
and to a lesser extent some of their brethren to the north as well
_ rest in large part this season on their ability to stabilize
potentially ticklish quarterbacking situations. That's nothing new,
of course, for the most important position on the field, but it's
more pronounced this year because of the rash of quarterback
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think there are (QB) issues all across the country,
not just here, because it's such a critical position,'' Texas Coach
Mack Brown said. ``It's obviously the most difficult position to
play on the team, and if you don't have one, you get beat. Period.
It's that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   The ramifications could be especially significant at Texas and
A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   If the Longhorns are to justify TV analyst Beano Cook's
prediction that they'll be in the Orange Bowl's national
championship game, then Brown must resolve the Applewhite/Simms
situation as delicately as possible to avoid distractions and
possible divisiveness. At A&AMP;M, coming off an 8-4 season in which
the Aggies were shut out twice and lost three games by a 112-6
margin, Slocum knows he needs Farris, or someone, to step up in
order to avoid another disappointing season that would make his hot
seat even hotter.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes aren't as high at Tech and Baylor. The Raiders are in
their first year in Leach's system, which produced Tim Couch at
Kentucky and record-setting passing numbers last season at
Oklahoma. The Bears hope Cicero's headiness and accuracy can help
them begin the climb back to respectability after last-place
divisional finishes in each of the Big 12's first four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback questions aren't limited to the Texas schools.
Oklahoma State hopes Tony Lindsay, out most of last season with a
knee injury, regains the form that made him the Big 12 freshman of
the year in 1997. National championship hopeful Nebraska arguably
has the league's best in Eric Crouch, but a redshirt freshman,
Jammal Lord, backs him up.
</P>
<P>
   The other top teams in the North _ Kansas State and Colorado _
also have their questions. K-State returns starter Jonathan Beasley
and experienced backup Jeremy Milne. But redshirt freshman Ell
Roberson III, a highly touted runner and thrower from Baytown Lee,
is expected to have a major impact _ if the hand injury he had in
two-a-day workouts isn't serious. Roberson has been compared to a
young Michael Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our philosophy is that you go into the spring the way you
finish the fall,'' Snyder said recently. ``Jonathan came out of
(last) fall as our No. 1. The situation was competitive in the
spring, and I will say the gap was closed, but Jonathan remained
the No. 1 quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado lost starter Mike Moschetti and backup Adam Bledsoe. So
the job will be in the hands of sophomore Zac Colvin or
junior-college transfer Bobby Pesavento, and only Colvin has
started a Division I-A game (one, at that).
</P>
<P>
   But that is there and this is here. Closer to home (south of the
Red River, in other words), this is how the quarterback pictures at
the four Texas schools are coming into focus.
</P>
<P>
   BAYLOR
</P>
<P>
   After last season, when the Bears ranked last in the Big 12 in
passing, total offense and scoring offense, Steele's immediate
recruiting priority was a junior-college quarterback who could step
in immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We targeted six guys,'' Steele said. ``And we felt Greg was
the best.''
</P>
<P>
   It was more than the 2,800 yards and 33 touchdowns Cicero threw
for last season in leading Palomar College of San Marcos, Calif.,
to an 8-3 mark. It was also for the two years he spent at Texas,
even though he never got on the field in a real game.
</P>
<P>
   Cicero redshirted as a freshman in 1997. In August before the
1998 season, a severe knee injury sidelined him for the year.
Believing he was losing a numbers game with Applewhite's emergence,
he decided to transfer to a junior college.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't your traditional transfer,'' Steele said. ``He'd
spent two years in the Big 12 and had been exposed to big-time
football. He had an understanding of what this is about. He doesn't
ask, `What do I do?' He asks, `Why do we do this, and what do we do
if they do that?' ''
</P>
<P>
   With good size (6 feet 4 inches, 210 pounds), exceptional
intelligence and a good arm, Cicero quickly asserted himself with
the Bears. Steele has been reluctant to formally name him as the
starter, preferring to encourage competition with junior Mike Odum
and redshirt freshman Guy Tomcheck. But it's all but a done deal.
</P>
<P>
   Cicero picked Baylor over Hawaii, San Diego State, New Mexico
State and Temple (Temple? ``They throw the heck out of the ball,''
he explained).
</P>
<P>
   The idea of returning to Central Texas, where he said he left on
good terms with the Longhorns, enticed the native of Anaheim,
Calif., although Cicero admits he never expected to return to the
state after he left _ ``Maybe to change planes on a flight or
something,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty funny how it's worked out,'' he added. ``But I was
used to the weather, the people, the league. It felt right.''
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   The expected spring duel between Applewhite and Simms didn't
happen because Applewhite was recuperating from surgery after
tearing the anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee in the
Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of the 1999 Big 12 Conference co-offensive player of
the year (Applewhite shared it with Crouch) hasn't lessened the
intrigue and speculation about what Brown will decide this fall.
The coach is low-keying it, and earlier this week was exceedingly
annoyed with a local TV station that posted a who-should-start poll
on its Web page. He has not missed any opportunity to encourage
fans and media to appreciate having two top quarterbacks instead of
obsessing over who will start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to evaluate because it's all about the getting the
ball in the end zone, and those intangibles are sometimes hard to
measure,'' Brown said. ``And the other thing is it's the most
widely discussed topic by the media and the fans because everyone
certainly has an opinion about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Letting Applewhite and Simms duke it out isn't exactly the worst
problem Brown could have. Applewhite embodies those intangibles.
Simms is the bigger, stronger athlete who demonstrated poise and
savvy in the appearances he did make last season, particularly his
surprising start at A&AMP;M when Applewhite was ill.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he isn't concerned about hurt feelings when he names
a starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``At any position, if two guys think they should start, the one
who doesn't will get his feelings hurt,'' he said. ``I'll have 115
mamas mad at me in the starting game because they think their son
should be starting, and we only start 11. It's been that way for 17
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the 1-2 spots work themselves out, Brown is more
concerned with who will be No. 3. The only other scholarship
quarterback is freshman Chance Mock, who has said he wants to
redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said possibilities include sophomore strong safety Beau
Trahan and freshman Tony Jeffery. Both played quarterback in high
school. Jeffery has said he wants to play wide receiver. Trahan
appears to be the emergency choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to find a third guy who could take some snaps,'' Brown
said. ``If it got to a point where we needed Chance (in order) to
win this year, we'd play him because the team takes precedent over
the individual.''
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS A&AMP;M
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies have built their football reputation not on
quarterbacks but the defensive players who harass them. Witness the
fact that their last all-conference QB was Bucky Richardson in
1991. But this year it was even more unsettled than usual.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a question of quantity. But quality? Even with the
announcement that Farris will start, that's still to be determined
since only he and Smith have any college experience, limited though
it is.
</P>
<P>
   In five mop-up appearances last year, Farris completed six of 16
passes for 53 yards. The husky Smith (6-4, 226) also appeared in
five games, completing five of 14 passes for 86 yards, including a
TD and interception.
</P>
<P>
   Many perceive Farris to be the safe choice because the
25-year-old has unusual maturity after spending five years playing
minor-league baseball. But Slocum, for understandable reasons,
won't endorse that theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We picked Mark because of overall performance in the spring
and summer,'' Slocum said Monday when announcing his decision.
``With all the things we like to do with our offense, he gives us
the best chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum emphasized that the race was ``very close, very close.''
He added that Smith and Freeman will compete for the No. 2 spot and
that both will get their chances to play.
</P>
<P>
   Farris said his outlook and approach haven't changed since
Monday's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't let it change me, and I don't think it changes the way
Vance and Colby look at things, either,'' he said. ``I think they
understand. I would. Someone has to go out on the field first and
it just happens to be me.''
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS TECH
</P>
<P>
   It's unrealistic to expect Kingsbury to consistently duplicate
the same kind of numbers he posted in Texas Tech's spring game.
After all, 24 of 26 for 321 yards and three touchdowns, multiplied
by 12, is slightly mind-boggling.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Leach isn't expecting it. But the Raiders' first-year coach
does believe the raw-boned sophomore is the prototypical
quarterback for his pass-happy offense, which did wonders for Tim
Crouch at Kentucky and, last year, Josh Heupel at Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want a tall guy who's mobile, and Kliff is,'' Leach said.
``Arm strength is the least important issue, but he's certainly got
that. What you really need to make this offense work is accuracy
and the ability to make good decisions, and he's got those things,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   So Kingsbury is Tech's man, period, although Leach proclaims
faith in redshirt freshman backup B.J. Symons. The Raiders expect
excellent results from Kingsbury despite limited experience _ six
appearances last year, including a start in the season finale
against Oklahoma when Rob Peters was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   In that game, Kingsbury completed nine of 17 passes for 259
yards and three TDs as the Raiders said farewell to Spike Dykes
with a 38-28 victory.
</P>
<P>
   His collegiate stats aren't huge _ 25 of 57 for 492 yards and
four TDs _ but Kingsbury believes his playing time last year,
albeit limited, has dramatic carryover advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably wouldn't be where I am now if I hadn't played some
already,'' he said. ``Being in the heat of the battle is a big part
of it, because a little experience goes a long way. The game's
slowed down a lot. With every repetition, it slows down a little
bit more.''
</P>
<P>
   Kingsbury is experienced throwing the ball. At New Braunfels
High School, where his father Tim is head coach, he threw for 3,009
yards (216 of 341) and 34 TDs as a senior for a 13-2 Class 5A state
semifinalist team.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
