<HEADER>
A2413 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-RAC-TRAVERS-HISTORY-1     08-25 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-TRAVERS-HISTORY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PAST RACES OFFER SUBTLE INSIGHTS INTO SATURDAY'S DERBY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Subs headline)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATT GRAVES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ If you're a history buff, the Travers
has some interesting nuances to consider.
</P>
<P>
   An important factor to include when drawing up your Travers
ticket is that since 1986, a horse who raced in the Haskell has
come from New Jersey to win the Midsummer Derby six times. That's
nearly 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And while many trainers believe a race over the Saratoga Race
Course track is a major plus entering the 1 1/4-mile Travers, the
fact is that only six Jim Dandy participants have won it since
1970.
</P>
<P>
   We don't have the Jim Dandy winner (Graeme Hall) in this field,
but there are four Dandy also-rans in this field of nine _ Albert
the Great, Unshaded, Postponed and Curule. Does that mean you can
throw out all of them? No, but keep it in mind.
</P>
<P>
   We have four horses coming from the Haskell _ Dixie Union,
Commendable, Impeachment and Milwaukee Brew. Only two of them ran
very well, winner Dixie Union and Milwaukee Brew, who finished
third.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Mandella never has run a horse in the Travers, but he's
certainly won plenty of other big races, most of them on the left
coast. So you have to take notice that he's trying Dixie Union in
the 131st running of the Midsummer Derby. I know I am.
</P>
<P>
   In Dixie Union, Mandella has a 3-year-old that is fulfilling the
promise he showed before a knee chip sidelined him after last
year's Breeders' Cup Juvenile, where he was one of the favorites at
4-1.
</P>
<P>
   His win in the Haskell on Aug. 6 over the likes of Captain
Steve, Milwaukee Brew and More Than Ready signals he's good enough
to beat this suspect Travers field, which was weakened by the
defections of Red Bullet and Graeme Hall.
</P>
<P>
   And Mandella said something this week that made me believe he
thinks he has the best horse in the field. Mandella said he
probably would have sent Dixie Union against older horses in this
weekend's Pacific Classic at Del Mar if he hadn't already been in
the East. Taking on General Challenge and River Keen is certainly a
stiffer task than this.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd have run him in the Swaps Stakes, I sure would have
thought about it,'' Mandella said. He'd have thought about it, but
would he have done it?
</P>
<P>
   This Travers field lacks real star quality, with Commendable
being the only Triple Crown race winner in it. No Fusaichi Pegasus,
no Red Bullet.
</P>
<P>
   Dixie Union beat Milwaukee Brew and Impeachment in the Haskell.
Albert the Great would need a major recovery from his seventh-place
performance _ dead last _ in the Jim Dandy to win the Travers.
</P>
<P>
   Curule is a possible threat, as are Unshaded and Postponed, but
none of them has ever won a Grade I stake. Country Coast ran third
in the Illinois Derby against a weak field. Why is he here?
</P>
<P>
   The big question mark about Dixie Union is whether he can get 1
1/4 miles. But considering that his sire is Dixieland Band and his
dam is by Capote, it appears that 10 furlongs may be a bit beyond
his scope. Dixieland Band has sired more sprinters than routers.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee Brew may sound like the name of a horse who should be
running at Finger Lakes, but I liked the way this son of Breeders'
Cup Classic winner Wild Again closed against the grain of
notoriously speed-favoring Monmouth Park.
</P>
<P>
   Dixie Union also closed well, but his normal style is to be on
or near the lead.
</P>
<P>
   He was taken back because of early traffic problems in the
Haskell, but likely will be up near the pack in the Travers.
Milwaukee Brew lost by only a length under jockey Mike McCarthy. In
the Travers, he gets Jerry Bailey. Enough said.
</P>
<P>
   This is a horse owned by Frank Stronach (who also owns Red
Bullet) and trained by Tino Attard, a Malta immigrant who was one
of 26 children. What a millennium Travers story this would be.
</P>
<P>
   The picks: Milwaukee Brew, Unshaded, Dixie Union, Albert the
Great.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Matt Graves writes for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box 15000,
Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
