<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2414 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     08-25 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FROM DETROIT, DECISIVENESS AND PATIENCE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La.)  By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  When Joe Dumars III was 15, his father of the same name sat him
down one night inside the little brick house on Martin Luther King
Street in Natchitoches, La., and said, ``I'm going to bring you out
and let you see what the real world is like.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was family tradition, a rite of passing, father and son
heading out at dawn in the 18-wheeler, making the cross-country run
from one Kroger supermarket to another.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're 15, you want to impress your father with how
strong you are,'' Dumars once said. ``I'm grabbing the bags, just
slinging them the first two, three stops. He never said a word.
Just looked at me and smiled.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard work with a hearty attitude would become the trademark of
the teen-ager's 14-year pro basketball career. When late-night
celebrity was suddenly as available to the All-Star-caliber player
as 100 cable channels, Dumars would click right past Arsenio and
rest on Charlie Rose. He and his backcourt opposite, Isiah Thomas,
were the pillars of two championship seasons in Detroit, but
Dumars, the quiet and dignified star for whom they have named the
league's sportsmanship trophy, has fittingly remained at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, the first place the Pistons will go now is
into free fall, after Grant Hill packed his coatless bag for Doc
Rivers' magic kingdom in Orlando, just as Dumars took front-office
control. In an era of the one-size-fits-all superstar contract,
when the highest bid has been displaced by the most verdant view of
the 18th green, Dumars can only offer a Palace in a parking lot, a
half-hour from chilly, gritty Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   This is what the real sports world is like and, upon reflection,
the trade that would have sent Patrick Ewing to Seattle earlier
this week represented much of what ails it. David Falk and company
pulled off a deal that had an odious and collusive quality, until
one blue-collar Joe responded to a fan outcry and wisely pulled the
plug.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other three teams in that deal were making out pretty
good,'' Dumars said.
</P>
<P>
   The needy SuperSonics would have received the gimpy but still
capable Ewing, along with a token of the agent Falk's appreciation
in the person of the free agent Maurice Taylor. For sending another
Falk client, Glen Rice, to New York with a hefty new contract he
would not get elsewhere, the Lakers would have landed the Pistons'
power forward Christian Laettner, as well as the backup center
Chris Dudley, to mimic Shaq in the middle and on the free-throw
line. The Knicks would have reeled in Rice and the enigmatic Vin
Baker, providing depth to facilitate a trade for another big man,
perhaps the Falk client Dikembe Mutombo.
</P>
<P>
   From both coasts, from the entertainment centers and ranking
television markets, this made perfect sense. It sounded right.
Except Dumars was about to receive an assembly line of bricklayers
and bunglers, and he realized he couldn't sell future cap room to
restless patrons. When he reportedly asked the Knicks to send him
even one useful player, Marcus Camby, the deal was suddenly off,
Ewing didn't have a way out, Rice didn't have a deal and Falk, for
once, didn't have his way.
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner and baseball's other heavy wallets never
worry about such elaborate schemes. With no salary cap, they just
sign away the game's financial stability and competitive balance.
The result is that even a team such as Arizona, boasting a fairly
crowded new ballpark and a division title after two major league
seasons, has to borrow money to keep competitive pace.
</P>
<P>
   Their annual playoff runs say the Knicks did not hang on to
Ewing too long, but they took on a paralyzing debt in the quest to
salvage one title with him. And just as they realized they had lost
ground again in the Eastern Conference, here came Falk to bail them
out of a bind, in the process of securing Ewing's next financial
score. Then Dumars ruined everything.
</P>
<P>
   Falk, of course, would never think of threatening a general
manager who won't play ball with a future ban on his client.
Attracting star free agents, even a homegrown one such as Chris
Webber, will nonetheless be a trickier task for Dumars than
slinging a produce bag.
</P>
<P>
   With patience, with the right trade and draft moves, he could
yet succeed in remaking the Pistons, the way Donnie Walsh has done
it in Indiana, the way Don Nelson is doing it in Dallas. The system
rewards patience and prudence. It'll be hard work, a long haul. Joe
Dumars did not have to prove he was the right man for the job this
week, but he did, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Last thought on the trade: Good for him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
