<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Saturday, Aug. 26. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-LATIN-AMERICA (Dallas) _ Gov. George W. Bush charges that
the Clinton administration has neglected Latin America, pledges to
put those countries at the center of his foreign policy priorities
and outlines a way of thinking about the region that places it on a
par with American interests in Europe and Asia. By Frank Bruni. (We
plan to move the story by 8:45 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.) 1,500
words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1.
</P>
<P>
   Top center: 3-column New York tourists photo.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   EMULEX-PLUNGE (New York) _ At 10:13 a.m. Friday, investors in
Emulex, a company that makes fiber-optic communications equipment,
got some terrible news. Bloomberg News reported that Emulex planned
to restate its earnings for the last two years. Emulex investors
rushed to shed their shares, and the company's stock went into
freefall, plunging from $103 to $45 in 15 minutes. The drop
stripped more than $2 billion from the company's market valuation
before the Nasdaq stock market halted trading at 10:33. Other
financial news outlets soon joined Bloomberg in reporting Emulex's
woes. There was only one problem with the story. It was not true,
the latest in a lengthening string of fake press releases and other
hoaxes that are increasingly roiling the financial markets. By Alex
Berenson. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-TAX (Washington) _ In the shorthand of presidential
politics, Gov. George W. Bush's tax-cut proposal is either an
overdue effort to return to citizens what is rightfully theirs, or
as Vice President Al Gore puts it, a risky scheme to reward the
wealthy. By Richard W. Stevenson. (The story has moved in ``p''
news file.) 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to BUSH-TAX-EXPERTS, inside.
</P>
<P>
   BURUNDI-CLINTON (Nairobi, Kenya) _ In December, Nelson Mandela
took on one of Africa's most frightening problems: the tiny and
beautiful country of Burundi, where Hutu and Tutsi have taken turns
massacring each other by the thousands for the last 40 years. Rumor
was that he accepted the task reluctantly, but he has worked hard
and pushed enemies near to a settlement. They are not there yet,
and that will present a dilemma when President Clinton arrives in
Tanzania on Monday to meet with Mandela and Burundi's leaders. By
Ian Fisher. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   WEST-FIREFIGHTERS (Challis, Idaho) _ They head out before dawn
and trudge home after dark, weary and covered in soot, still
clutching the shovels and axes that are their weapons out on the
battle lines. For thousands of firefighters across the West, these
will be the memories of summer 2000, a season so devastating that
commanders say they cannot help but see it as a war. And now even
the United Services Organization, best known for taking Bob Hope to
the troops overseas, has come to this remote corner of Idaho to pay
a variety-show tribute. By Douglas Jehl. (The story has moved in
``a'' news file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
