<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-bash-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOCKHART UNABASHED ON SHOWTIME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. `Tonight' refers to Mon., Aug. 28) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boy, oh, boy, did Neil LaBute not take the correct messages from
his religious training. LaBute, the screenwriter-director of the
misanthropic romps ``In the Company of Men'' and ``Your Friends and
Neighbors'' _ his next, ``Nurse Betty,'' is lighter, but then, it'd
just about have to be _ revels in exploring the psyches of
characters damaged beyond common sense, reason and decency; people
for whom traditional morality simply is not an option.
</P>
<P>
   We watch, fascinated or repelled, unable to turn away from these
characters, maybe because we fear they'll plunge a knife into our
backs if we do. And in ``bash: latter day plays,'' LaBute gives us
a trio of Mormons who are unable to escape neither the yoke of
their religious upbringings nor their own darker impulses _ with
the implication that one fuels the other.
</P>
<P>
   In this triptych of monologues _ shot last December at Beverly
Hills' Canon Theatre _ LaBute essentially tells us the same story
three times: An insipid character blathers on randomly at first
before getting to the point, and the point is a ghastly act.
</P>
<P>
   In the first, Paul Rudd and Calista Flockhart play a happily
lobotomized couple relating to offstage friends their own takes on
the same incident, a lavish party they attended in New York. Rudd's
character wanders from the event to commit a spontaneous, vile act
of homophobia, while Flockhart's character chatters away, oblivious
to her boyfriend's hate crime; yet, it's suggested, is mildly
complicit.
</P>
<P>
   Flockhart takes center stage in the second piece, about a young
single mother molested by a teacher and her startling revenge. Ron
Eldard portrays a pathetic, glad-handing traveling businessman in
the third monologue, relating to a captive, unseen audience _ she's
a drunk and he's buying the drinks _ the extents he has gone to to
hold down his job.
</P>
<P>
   Performances are highly stylized, which take a couple of minutes
to adjust to, but they're uniformly nervy and intense. Rudd
expertly turns his vaguely likable yokel into a demon on a dime,
while Flockhart transcends her Ally McBeal persona to maintain a
level of impassioned scatteredness throughout her tragic piece.
Eldard's bravura work in the final tableau masks the more cliched
aspects of his character, emerging as something more real and
scary.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, ``bash'' could use some tonal variation
beyond the savage desperation exuded by each character. It's grim
and often compelling stuff, but it seems to be chasing its own
tail. There's no larger point beyond ``people are evil,'' and you
don't need a highfalutin' play to tell you that _ heck,
``Survivor'' did that without nearly as much pretention. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
The show: ``bash: latter day plays.'' &QL; 
What: Trilogy of monologues. &QL; 
The stars: Calista Flockhart, Ron Eldard, Paul Rudd. &QL; 
Where: Showtime. &QL; 
When: 8 tonight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
