<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2426 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-GLOBALSTAR-ART-$ADV27     08-25 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBALSTAR-ART-$ADV27-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE GLOBALSTAR'S DEBT HISTORY, FOUNDER REMAINS OPTIMISTIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT17 was sent on 8-24 to NYT photo clients.
Graphic was sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 By THERESA FOLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bernard Schwartz has spent much of his life as one of
the nation's most revered chief executives. He devoted year after
consistent year to delivering record returns while building the
Loral Corp. into a top military contractor.
</P>
<P>
   At 74, Schwartz could well afford to bask in retirement.
Instead, he has taken on one of the biggest gambles of his career,
starting Globalstar, an international wireless telephone service
that is covering the globe with 48 satellites.
</P>
<P>
   That gamble, shadowed by the failure last year of the Iridium
satellite telephone system, now looks like another long shot: Wall
Street is up in arms, a bank loan is in default and his junk bonds
recently traded at less than 30 cents on the dollar. His woes are,
in turn, casting doubt on the prospects for Teledesic, the
satellite telecommunications venture backed by Craig McCaw, the
cellular telephone entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the capital markets have been burned, you are really
up against a wall of skepticism,'' said Les Levi, an analyst at
Chase Securities. ``This is a pretty nasty sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz, however, says he is close to success and far from
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Satellite communications,'' he said, ``is one of the growth
industries that not only will show huge business success but be
part of the forces shaping the way humans beings live in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Globalstar went into service in March.
Loral, having sold off its military businesses and renamed itself
Loral Space and Communications, owns 42 percent of it. Schwartz
remains chairman of both companies.
</P>
<P>
   Globalstar, based in San Jose, Calif., is much like Iridium,
Motorola's global satellite telephone system that filed for Chapter
11 bankruptcy protection last August. Globalstar, with simpler
technology and more durable satellites, is less expensive to users,
although far more expensive than standard cellular service.
</P>
<P>
   But things have not gone as planned. Customers, put off by
handsets costing $700 to $1,200 and charges of $1 to $1.70 a minute
_ often more abroad _ are staying away. The service is also just
becoming available in countries like Russia and China.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Schwartz told financial analysts that Globalstar
would have 500,000 subscribers and $500 million in revenue this
year. So far, though, it has 13,000 subscribers and, for the first
half of the year, only $2 million in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   What went wrong?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not much,'' Schwartz said in an interview from his office in
Manhattan. It is just that his plan is taking longer to execute, he
said. ``The biggest impact was the Iridium bankruptcy, which put
off the buying public and gave us the need to overcome the Iridium
syndrome,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Press reports predicting Globalstar's bankruptcy have also hurt,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz said he momentarily considered bankruptcy, but only
because an executive has to look at all options.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the numbers he gave out? He said they were not
meant as projections and, besides, Globalstar's sales will reach an
annual rate of $400 million to $500 million by the end of next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say, therefore, that we may be a year out of
position against that original business model,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz, however, confirmed that without additional financing
or a sudden jump in sales, Globalstar will run out of cash in
March. Its condition would be worse but for a strategic move that
Schwartz made in late June. He drew a $250 million line of credit,
then defaulted, relying on a legal agreement that forced the
investors who had guaranteed the loan to repay it. Some of the
largest ones, like Lockheed Martin, Qualcomm and Loral, have done
so, but not happily.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin, which is negotiating with Loral for repayment,
refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Globalstar has already given Lockheed generous compensation, in
rights to buy stock, for the loan guarantee, Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why, to be candid with you, it's newsworthy that
Lockheed Martin is upset,'' he said. ``The people in hell want ice
water. It's not something people take notice of.''
</P>
<P>
   Many shareholders have suffered as well. In late January,
Globalstar, which was already publicly traded, sold an additional
$268 million in stock at $35 a share. On Feb. 23, Schwartz told
analysts and investors that handset deliveries were running late,
and on May 8, the company disclosed that sales were well behind
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Globalstar shares closed Friday at $10.50, up $1.38 on news of
expanded coverage in Latin America. Schwartz said that when the
offering was made, he had no idea that sales were slow.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Globalstar has gone based on Schwartz's reputation,
the measures he has taken to keep it solvent could hurt his ability
to raise more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time you burn someone, it makes it that much harder the
next time,'' said Armand Musey, an analyst at Banc of America
Securities, referring to the loan default. ``It was not illegal,
but was an act of desperation, and is viewed as somewhat of a dirty
trick.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz started building his new empire in about 1990, when
Loral bought the satellite manufacturing operations of Ford
Aerospace. Loral and several partners formed Globalstar in 1991 and
sold its stock to the public in 1995. With the Cold War over,
Schwartz sold off Loral's military businesses to Lockheed Martin
the next year. In 1997, Loral added a fleet of telecommunications
satellites from AT&AMP;T. While Globalstar operates the mobile
telephone service, Loral makes several types of satellites and
operates those handling telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz dismissed worries that Globalstar will run out of cash,
saying that he can go back to his partners for more capital next
year, if necessary. ``We believe Globalstar is in a very
attractive, viable market, in which we have the only solution,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But a major partner, Qualcomm, which also supplies equipment,
has had to pay $22 million of the bank loan and is owed a total of
about $608 million. Qualcomm is making no promises about putting up
more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we will be approached,'' said Julie Cunningham,
Qualcomm's senior vice president for investor relations. ``We would
need to look at the specific business plan and see what other
partners are putting in.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Investors are watching to see how Schwartz handles Globalstar's
next challenge, in the form of a $500 million loan from Banc of
America. The bank can demand immediate repayment and assume
ownership of two satellites if Globalstar does not have $100
million in revenue for the year ending March 31, a goal that
Schwartz says is unlikely to be met.
</P>
<P>
   Bond holders, meanwhile, owed $1.4 billion, anticipate losing
much of their money, said Levi, the Chase Securities analyst.
Judging from Globalstar's outlook, he said, ``It is very likely
they will default on their public high-yield notes.''
</P>
<P>
   The bonds have been trading at 25 cents to 29 cents on the
dollar. Schwartz said the bond payments would be met, and the bank
loan dealt with before it comes due.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Schwartz is optimistic that once Globalstar attracts more
customers during the next six months, financial support for
satellite telephone service will flourish.
</P>
<P>
   But investors might have a longer memory than he supposes, said
Roger Rusch, who heads TelAstra, a consulting firm in Palos Verdes,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``The satellite industry has gotten a black eye,'' Rusch said.
``People are going to be reluctant to get involved in these things,
because they think they've been led down a path where success is
implied and not delivered.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2428 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-BURUNDI-CLINTON-ART-(     08-25 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURUNDI-CLINTON-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH MANDELA AND CLINTON AS MIDWIVES, A DELICATE PEACE MAY BE BORN
TO BURUNDI 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ In December, Nelson Mandela took on one of
Africa's most frightening problems: the tiny and beautiful country
of Burundi, where Hutu and Tutsi have taken turns massacring each
other by the thousands for the last 40 years. Rumor was that he
accepted the task reluctantly, but he has worked hard and pushed
enemies near to a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   They are not there yet, and that will present a dilemma when
President Clinton arrives in Tanzania on Monday to meet with
Mandela and Burundi's leaders. By Mandela's rigid timetable, the
Burundians were to seal their intention to end seven years of civil
war in an accord signed there, in front of Clinton and several
dozen other heads of state.
</P>
<P>
   Thus Clinton, eager for some success in Africa, could have stood
as midwife of sorts over the birth of one small bit of hope in the
ceaseless turmoil of central Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But a consensus is growing that it would be unwise _ even
dangerous _ to push Burundi too far before the meeting. The fear is
that an incomplete document, signed in a hurry to please important
foreign guests, could push Tutsi hard-liners opposed to the accord
into more violence. The threat of further killing in Burundi is all
too real.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want all those heads of state to be aware that they are
going to be manipulated if they think they are going to assist in a
peace accord that all parties agree with,'' said Louis-Marie
Nindorera, of the Burundian human rights group Iteka. ``They have
to know that most of the people who are there are still deeply
divided.''
</P>
<P>
   A historical precedent haunts the proceedings in the resort town
of Arusha, in Tanzania. It was there in August 1993 that the
warring parties in Rwanda _ Burundi's northern neighbor _ also
signed a peace deal. It was not accepted by many of the Hutu
majority in Rwanda. The authority of the Hutu president, Juvenal
Habyarimana, dwindled; Hutu militias formed. By April 1994, a
genocide against the Tutsi minority exploded, killing in the end at
least 500,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The situation in Burundi is not directly parallel: It is Tutsi
who rule there, in a precarious position because they represent
only about 15 percent of the population. But there are
similarities. As the signing has grown near, violence has flared.
Hutu rebels fighting the Tutsi-controlled government launched
several attacks on the capital, Bujumbura, in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, hard-line Tutsi groups _ reluctant to give up
their long-held power over the majority Hutu _ have been protesting
the peace accord on the streets of Bujumbura. Several experts say
they are also forming armed militias, with no clear accountability.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The tension is so high that Pierre Buyoya, the nation's
president and a Tutsi, felt he had to warn Tutsi hard-liners
against staging a coup this weekend when he goes to Tanzania to
meet Mandela and Clinton. It was an unusual admission of his
vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who want to overthrow the government so that the
president will not be there to sign the peace agreement should know
that their actions will come to no good,'' Buyoya told civil
servants and government administrators on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Shoring up his position at home, Buyoya canceled a trip this
week to South Africa to meet with Mandela for final talks before
the planned signing.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It is not impossible that most of the 19 Burundian
representatives at the negotiating table will end up signing a
complete peace accord on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Given the fears of violence _ and the differences that remain
over the accord itself _ it is also possible that nothing will be
signed. But officials say that what is most likely is that some of
the delegates will sign off only on the points of agreement. They
would also, officials say, affirm their commitment to continue
talking.
</P>
<P>
   That would fall short of Mandela's expectations, and may in fact
try his reportedly waning patience. Clinton would also be forced to
preside over a ceremony with less certain importance than he might
prefer. But U.S. officials say they are aware of the risks of
pushing too hard and are not eager _ with few recent
accomplishments toward making peace in Africa _ to stoke the coals
of ethnic hatred.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will travel to Tanzania, at a minimum, to put his stamp
of approval on the progress Mandela has made thus far, the
officials say. ``There is no desire to force anybody into
anything,'' said one administration official, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity. ``It is our great desire to consolidate the
progress that has been made so far and continue to do what we can
do to support Mandela's efforts to narrow the differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Many experts say Clinton's blessing of a realistic document
could be useful in the next phase of talks, though many officials
fear a loss of momentum after Clinton leaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that there is such an international interest and
support for Mandela's efforts and the efforts of Burundians makes
people feel they should behave responsibly,'' said Jan van Eck, a
facilitator with the Center for Conflict Resolution in South
Africa, who has worked with Burundi's factions since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   There have been outbreaks of ethnic violence since Burundi, like
Rwanda, gained its independence from Belgium in 1962, particularly
against the Hutu in 1965 and 1972. The Tutsi have dominated
politics, the army and business. This most recent civil war broke
out in 1993, when power shifted for a brief time to the Hutu
majority. In July 1993, the first Hutu president, Melchior Ndadaye,
took office. But three months later, Tutsi paratroopers
assassinated him, setting off widespread killings of Tutsi.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, 200,000 Burundians are estimated to have died.
</P>
<P>
   The peace accord that Mandela has been shaping essentially
envisions an eventual return of power to the Hutu majority _ who
make up nearly 85 percent of the population _ but with rights and
protections for the Tutsi.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, the accord calls for a second legislative body,
a senate, with broad veto powers that would be split evenly by
ethnicity. The army would also be divided evenly for at least 10
years, despite the Tutsi's far fewer numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But many Tutsi say these measures do not give them enough of a
say or protection. Moreover, the Hutu and Tutsi disagree over the
terms for a tribunal on genocide and a peace and reconciliation
commission. This has caused particular tension among the Tutsi, who
want the killings in 1993 recognized as genocide.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The accord envisions a three-year transitional government before
general elections, but the sides cannot agree on a leader. They
also disagree on whether a cease-fire should be signed before or
after the signing of the accord.
</P>
<P>
   What complicates the issue further is that the two main Hutu
rebel groups actually engaged in fighting are not involved directly
in the peace talks. So even if a fairly complete document is signed
on Monday, it will be, as Mandela has frequently pointed out, only
the beginning of the push toward a final peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
