<HEADLINE>
CONGO PRESIDENT KEEPS PEACEKEEPERS GUESSING 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A week of conflicting signals from President
Laurent Kabila of Congo has left the Security Council no closer to
knowing when, if ever, a peacekeeping mission can be sent to the
country. The council this week decided that U.N. officials who have
been in Congo preparing for the peacekeepers could stay until Oct.
15, giving Secretary General Kofi Annan and the council time to
reconsider the operation.
</P>
<P>
   After announcing on Thursday that the peacekeepers and support
forces, totaling about 5,500 people under current plans, could have
free access in Congo, Kabila's government appeared Friday to be
backtracking, officials said here.
</P>
<P>
   In nearly a year of trying to prepare for a peacekeeping
operation in a country with inadequate roads, electrical supplies
or other basic services in many areas, the U.N. advance team has
met repeated obstacles. Because Congo officials always try to
control flights and other activities, the Security Council has
demanded freedom of movement without the need for permits or
advance notice as the United Nations establishes centers of
operation.
</P>
<P>
   In Congo, U.N. officials have faced not only operational hurdles
but also orchestrated hostility against international workers,
including attacks on U.N. offices in Kinshasa, the capital.
Officials said they feared more violence if the government did not
stop encouraging or condoning the anti-U.N. feelings.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Annan sent a Nigerian general and former military
ruler, Abdulsalami Abubakar, to Congo to tell Kabila that he had to
cooperate with the United Nations if the peacekeeping mission was
to go ahead. Abubakar will report to Annan next week.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the picture for a peacekeeping mission, Kabila said
this week that he was freezing a peace accord signed last year in
Lusaka, Zambia. That agreement set up a series of steps toward
reconciliation in Congo, which has been caught in a prolonged war
of shifting alliances for more than five years. The war has
unsettled much of south-central Africa, diplomats from the region
say.
</P>
<P>
   An African diplomat said this week that some regional leaders
had concluded that if Kabila could not defeat several rebel groups
operating in the country, most of them with outside support, he
would retreat to his home territory around Lumbambashi and leave
the rest of Congo to the competing groups.
</P>
<P>
   In one positive move, Kabila, who refuses to meet with political
opponents, has established a human rights panel in Congo and
allowed a U.N. monitor to visit the country in recent weeks. The
monitor, Roberto Garreton, a human rights lawyer from Chile, had
been barred from Congo for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Although Garreton's final report has not been published, he said
this week when he left Congo that there was little good news in
either government-controlled or rebel-controlled areas or in border
regions where Rwanda and Uganda still had troops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
