<HEADLINE>
`THE LAST OF THE BLOND BOMBSHELLS': NAME THAT TUNE, THEN BELT IT
OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Broadcast notes appear at end of review. Time, channel are for New
York area. Check local listings.) 
(EDS: spelling Su, in production notes, is cq) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A woman is having lunch with her grown children at an outdoor
cafe when she is transfixed by the familiar tune a street-corner
guitarist is playing. The children, who are pretty sure that Mom's
going dotty, can't understand why she's suddenly enraptured.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your pulse doesn't quicken when you hear Hoagy Carmichael's
`Star Dust,' then I've failed as a mother,'' the woman says with
ironclad certainty.
</P>
<P>
   So where do you stand on the ``Star Dust'' question? Does the
melody haunt your reverie? Would you like to hear it, and a pride
of other pop standards, played in bracing swing-band arrangements?
Do you have a tolerance, even a secret fondness, for nostalgic,
life-affirming movies that bypass the head and go straight to the
heart? If so, be sure to catch ``The Last of the Blond Bombshells''
Saturday night on HBO. Your pulse will not only quicken, it'll do
the jitterbug.
</P>
<P>
   The woman whose children don't get it is Elizabeth, played with
infectious relish by Dame Judi Dench. When first encountered, she
is at a memorial service for her husband. At the sound of one of
the dear departed's favorite musical selections, Gilbert and
Sullivan's ``Pirate King,'' Elizabeth's mind supplies another song,
``(I'll Be Glad When You're Dead) You Rascal You,'' performed by a
World War II vintage all-girl band, the Blond Bombshells.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager, Elizabeth was the band's tenor saxophonist, the
prettiest and most talented of the young women who nightly donned
platinum wigs to become the Blond Bombshells at a London ballroom.
Well, almost all were young women. The drummer was a young man
named Patrick who preferred drag to draft, hiding from military
service in wig and gown and enjoying the embrace of all his band
mates but Elizabeth.
</P>
<P>
   Now the new widow worries her embarrassed children by embracing
life, hauling out her sax to join that outdoor guitarist for
regular jam sessions. Who should happen by and catch a performance
but Patrick (Ian Holm)? The young rake is now a bit bent and faded,
but Holm makes sure that he still has the glint in his eye and the
spring, however rusty, in his step.
</P>
<P>
   The two gray Bombshells hit upon a plan to try to find other
surviving band members to play a reunion gig. Elizabeth's wide-eyed
granddaughter Joanna (Millie Findlay) offers them a job at her
school dance.
</P>
<P>
   This warm bath of a film, directed by Gillies MacKinnon from a
script by Alan Plater, glides gracefully in and out of flashbacks
in which the band performs tunes like ``Opus One'' and ``A
Nightingale Sang in Berkeley Square.'' (The sight of young Patrick
in his dress will kindle a momentary memory of ``Some Like It
Hot,'' but this movie dances on different turf.)
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth and Patrick warm to their task and each other, finding
the band's singer, Gwen (Cleo Laine), performing with a jazz combo.
(Laine's rendition of ``Taking a Chance on Love'' is just one of
the film's musical rewards.)
</P>
<P>
   They find Dinah, the trumpet player (Olympia Dukakis, spewing
vaudeville Brooklynese that seems to come not only from another
continent but also from another movie) living in a Scottish castle
with dogs named Patty, Laverne and Maxene. They find the
Bombshells' leader, Betty (Joan Sims), playing piano at a seaside
dive; Annie, the trombonist (June Whitfield), in a Salvation Army
band; Evelyn, the alto sax player (Billie Whitelaw), in jail. They
lure Madeleine, the bass player (Leslie Caron, who still has Gigi's
sparkle), from her native France. Each of these performers makes
maturity look like great fun.
</P>
<P>
   The reconstituted band sounds ragged at first. But there's
really no suspense about whether the Bombshells will find their
chops and show the young listeners a trick or two. This is a fable,
after all, and if the soundtrack makes the little geriatric
ensemble sound better, and bigger, than the Basie band in its
prime, so what?
</P>
<P>
   When Laine belts out ``It Don't Mean a Thing if It Ain't Got
That Swing,'' there's no doubt that she has got that swing. So does
this film. And that's the name of that tune. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE LAST OF THE BLOND BOMBSHELLS'
</P>
<P>
   At 9 p.m. ET Saturday on HBO
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Gillies MacKinnon. Written by Alan Plater. Su
Armstrong, producer; Analisa Barreto, co-producer; Richard
Great-rex, director of photography. Music by John Keane. Produced
by HBO Films in association with the BBC and Universal Television.
Simon Wright, executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   With: Judi Dench (Elizabeth), Ian Holm (Patrick), Leslie Caron
(Madeleine), Olympia Dukakis (Dinah), Cleo Laine (Gwen), Joan Sims
(Betty), Billie Whitelaw (Evelyn), June Whitfield (Annie) and
Millie Findlay (Joanna). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
