<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: TRANQUILIZER REPORTS DENOUNCED
</P>
<P>
   The mother of a sailor who died on the submarine Kursk angrily
denied that officials had tranquilized her to halt her denunciation
of a Kremlin official at a stormy meeting on the disaster.
Videotape showed that Nadya Tylik collapsed in mid-tirade after
being injected during a confrontation with Deputy Prime Minister
Ilya Klebanov. But Tylik said her husband had asked a doctor for
the injection because he feared the confrontation would worsen a
heart ailment. Contrary suggestions in the Western press, she said,
were ``lots of lies.''
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: SEVEN ACCUSED IN BOMBING PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Seven suspected members of a guerrilla group were arrested and
accused of planning a bomb attack on the Incirlik airbase in
southern Turkey from which American and British military planes
carry out patrols over the no-flight zones in Iraq. No details of
the plot or the arrests were announced. The police also said a
member of the group, the Revolutionary Peoples' Liberation
Army-Front, was arrested in Istanbul in possession of explosives,
hand grenades and a gun. &QR;
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: JOINING INTERNATIONAL COURT
</P>
<P>
   The government said it would publish legislation enabling
Britain to join an international criminal court that would try
suspects on charges of war crimes, genocide and crimes against
humanity. So far 15 countries have passed such laws; 60 must do so
before the court can come into existence. The United States opposes
the court, saying it would make American soldiers vulnerable to
politically motivated prosecutions abroad. &QR;
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: PREMIER DERIDES POLLS
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Jean Chretien, in power since 1993, has dismissed
polling trends that show his Liberal Party slumping and the
opposition Canadian Alliance rising. ``We will win the next
election because we have a huge majority over everybody else,'' he
said. Chretien, who has vowed to seek a third term in elections
that are to be held by next June, told reporters he was not
bothered by an Angus Reid poll that showed Liberal support falling
to 43 percent of respondents and Alliance support rising to 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   PERU, JORDAN: ARMS RUNNING DENIED
</P>
<P>
   Jordan angrily denied accusations by President Alberto Fujimori
of Peru that top Jordan commanders were involved in the trafficking
of thousands of Russian assault rifles through Peru to Colombian
guerrillas. Foreign Minister Abdelelah Al Jatib said Jordan and
Peru were involved in legal arms sales, and that corrupt Peruvian
officials ``are not capable of controlling the activities of
traffickers in their own country.''
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: GERMANS TELL OF MISSILE FACTORY
</P>
<P>
   Germany's intelligence agency says it has detected a factory 25
miles southwest of Baghdad where Iraq is making missiles able to
carry conventional, chemical or biological weapons. ``There is a
real danger that sooner or later Germany will be within the range
of these weapons,'' the agency was quoted as saying in the daily
Bild. The report follows an American report last month that Iraq
had restarted its missile program.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS
</P>
<P>
   LETTER TO GADHAFI RELEASED
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan, intending to squash reports that
there had been a secret deal with Libya to limit the scope of the
trial of two Libyans accused in the Lockerbie airliner bombing,
took the unusual step of releasing a letter he wrote to Moammar
Gadhafi of Libya last year. The letter and an annex assured Colonel
Gadhafi that the trial would not be used to undermine his regime,
but it made clear that Scottish prosecutors at a special court in
the Netherlands would be following normal prosecutorial procedures.
</P>
<P>
   FINN RULES HIMSELF OUT
</P>
<P>
   Finland's ex-president, Maarti Ahtisaari, said he was definitely
ruling himself out as a candidate for United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees. A successor to Sadako Ogata of Japan,
who has held the job for nearly a decade, is expected to be named
by early October. Ahtisaari, now one of an international panel of
arms inspectors for Northern Ireland, was considered a strong
European candidate for the job.
</P>
</TEXT>
