<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2437 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-DUNN-COX     08-25 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-DUNN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke names exec to head North America unit
 &HT;    By Christopher Seward
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jeffrey Dunn, who last month was elevated to
Coca-Cola's No. 2 executive in North America, has been named
president of the operation.
</P>
<P>
   In October, he takes over as head of the beverage company's
largest business group, replacing President Ralph Cooper, who
retires at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The North America group has the highest per-capita consumption
of Coke products but in recent years has seen sluggish sales
growth, with case volume increasing just 1 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock took a hit Friday after analyst Jennifer
Solomon of Salomon Smith Barney said slow growth will continue in
North America because of pricing pressures. She also suggested that
more competition in Japan, where Coke derives 20 percent of its
revenues, may hurt business there.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, Coke's stock traded as low as $55 before closing
at $56, down $1.94.
</P>
<P>
   ING Barings analyst Manny Goldman said the selection of Dunn to
head the North America unit, which includes the United States and
Canada, is a smart move because of his extensive background in the
company's U.S. fountain business.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, 44, first joined the fountain business in 1985 and over
the years held several key posts, including vice president of
marketing and eventually general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said Dunn's challenge will be to expand the company's
carbonated soft drink business, which includes Coca-Cola Classic
and Diet Coke, and take advantage of consumers' growing appetite
for waters, teas and other noncarbonated products. He expects the
North America business to experience a turnaround in earnest next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Stahl, who headed the North America group before being
named president and chief operating officer of Coca-Cola Co.
earlier this year, said Dunn's ``strategic approach to business,
consumer marketing skills and leadership acumen'' made him suited
for the new post. Before being named deputy group president in
July, Dunn oversaw marketing for the operation. The University of
Georgia graduate joined Coke in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, who had been head of North America for only a few months
after Stahl was elevated, has been with the company for 35 years.
He was head of Minute Maid, another Coke business, and held several
other senior posts in Europe and North America.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman credited Cooper for putting Minute Maid on solid
footing. ``He came in and got the sales going, and this is against
Tropicana,'' he said. ``Cooper did a fine job.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
