<P>
   &UR; MONEY AND BUSINESS (Will move in `f' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CATERPILLAR-VIETNAM (Vung Tau, Vietnam) _ As U.S. companies look
for business in Vietnam, Caterpillar leads the way. By Wayne
Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic)
</P>
<P>
   GLOBALSTAR (Undated) _ Bernard Schwartz, the chairman of
satellite companies Loral Space and Communications and Globalstar,
is a revered figure on Wall St. At the age of 73, he has spent much
of his life delivering consistent, record-setting profits to
shareholders of his now-defunct defense company Loral. Now he is
fighting to save his last big business gamble _ the Globalstar
mobile telephone satellite system _ from collapse. By Theresa
Foley.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo and graphic)
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-BOOKS (Undated) _ Gary Hamel is a sophisticated business
thinker, the co-author of one of the finest business books ever
written. His new book, ``Leading the Revolution'' (Harvard Business
School Press, $29.95), is a handbook on how mavericks can originate
novel ideas and actually maneuver employers into entering new and
profitable businesses. By Fred Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   With:
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-BOOKS-HAMEL (Undated) _ Creative ideas for new businesses
should emerge from every level of a company, says Gary Hamel,
author of ``Leading the Revolution.'' Hamel works with companies on
instilling a capacity for what he calls ``radical innovation.'' He
is also the co-author, with C.K. Prahalad, of a business classic,
``Competing for the Future.'' By Fred Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEK IN REVIEW (Will move in `a' or `i' categories, as noted) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-AFRICA-REVIEW (Undated) _ This weekend, on a return
engagement in Africa, President Clinton is singing the praises of
President Olusegan Obasanjo of Nigeria. The Clinton administration
has seized on Obasanjo, whose victory last year ended years of
military dictatorship, as an anchor of democratic stability in
restive West Africa. But there are risks. Obasanjo presides over a
country that is fractured by Islamic extremism. Nigeria is the
second-most corrupt nation on earth, according to Transparency
International, a nonprofit group based in Germany. And Obasanjo's
record on human rights has already been stained, and his top aides
have been selling their influence. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category.)
</P>
<P>
   VOTER-TURNOUT-REVIEW (Undated) _ What if they gave an election
and everyone came? Turnout in the last three U.S. presidential
elections has hovered at around half of the nation's voting-age
population, which has prompted a good deal of national
hand-wringing. If everyone eligible voted this November, the number
of ballots cast would roughly double. But would all those millions
of additional votes change the outcome for the main contenders? By
Michael R. Kagay.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category.)
</P>
<P>
   ESTROGEN-HEART-REVIEW (Undated) _ It seemed so clear a decade
ago: Of course hormone replacement therapy would protect women's
hearts after menopause. After all, women's heart disease risk
starts to rise in middle age, around the time that their ovaries
stop making estrogen. But now, new data are turning the estrogen
hypothesis on its head and showing that even the best-intentioned
analysis can go astray if it relies on indirect evidence. By Gina
Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category.)
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-MEXICO-REVIEW (Mexico City) _ As Vicente Fox paid his first
visit to Washington as Mexico's president-elect and informally
presented his ideas for a more liberal northward flow of Mexican
workers, his proposals stirred a flurry of mixed emotions at home.
Among the poor, Fox's proposals have sparked hopes that they might
soon be able to cross the border with more protections and dignity.
For Mexico's middle classes, an opening of the border seems more a
necessary evil. To them, the border is the epicenter of Mexico's
ambiguous, love-hate relationship with the United States. Because
it is a gateway to the most powerful country in the world, the
border is a kind of mythical place, but also a place where Mexico's
disadvantages are magnified. By Ginger Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category.)
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-IDENTITY-REVIEW (Berlin) _ As the 10th anniversary of
German unification approaches on Oct. 3, it seems clear that the
conjunction of recovered German nationhood with a diminished
nation-state has had some disturbing effects. The giant of Europe
is edging toward its anniversary in a mood of some agitation,
wondering aloud what to do about rightist extremism, pondering
where the roots of xenophobia lie, lamenting the misunderstanding
between Wessis and Ossis (Westerners and Easterners), and groping
for a shared sense of German identity that is nonthreatening. By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' category.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Will move in `e' category or as noted) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RAUSCHENBERG-ART (Captiva, Fla.) _ For his high school
graduation present, Robert Rauschenberg wanted a ready-made shirt,
his first. A decade or so later he made history with assemblages of
junk; sculptures and music boxes made of packing crates, rocks and
rope, and red paintings like ``Yoicks'' sewn from fabric strips.
Art sometimes has its roots in odd places. At 74, he is an American
institution, the paradoxical fact of an anti-orthodox career. By
Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-TELENOVELLAS (Rio de Janeiro, Brazil) _ When a television
serial about an 18th-century courtesan went off the air here two
years ago, few at the struggling network that had produced the
drama, called ``Xica da Silva,'' expected it to have much of an
afterlife. But then 150 episodes were dubbed into Spanish and sold
to a dozen other countries in Latin America, where the series
quickly went on to become a ratings phenomenon. Now the United
States, or at least the growing portion of it that watches
Spanish-language television, has succumbed to the same spell. By
Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   NIJINSKY-DANCE (Undated) _ Just over 50 years after his death in
London on April 8, 1950, events on three continents reaffirm the
apparently boundless fascination with the legendary Polish-Russian
dancer-choreographer Vaslav Nijinsky, whose brief career
(1907-1917) ended at 29 with mental illness that gripped him the
rest of his 61 years. The most comprehensive Nijinsky exhibition
ever assembled began touring European museums in March;
Nijinsky-themed stage plays ran this year in Tokyo, London and
Scottsdale, Ariz.; and in May, for the first time, the Royal Ballet
performed ``L'Apres-Midi d'un Faune,'' his 1912 debut work, and a
controversial re-creation of his 1913 ``Jeux.'' The never-ending
Nijinsky season continued on July 2 when the Hamburg Ballet gave
the premiere of John Neumeier's homage, ``Nijinsky.'' By Daniel
Gesmer.
</P>
<P>
   BALLET-DANCE (Undated) _ Today's ballet world has two poles, and
both are in danger of freezing over. Plotless, or abstract, ballets
are at one pole; narrative ballets are at the other. By Jack
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   TAVERNIER-FILM (Paris) _ Bertrand Tavernier's latest film did
not begin with the ``big idea'' of denouncing poverty and
unemployment hidden behind France's stolidly bourgeois facade.
Rather, its genesis was an anecdote heard one evening over dinner
with his 33-year-old daughter, Tiffany, and her husband, a poet who
had taught in public schools in run-down communities. From that
conversation was born ``Ca Commence Aujourd'hui,'' or ``It All
Starts Today,'' Tavernier's 19th feature film. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   BOULEZ-SALZBURG-MUSIC (Salzburg, Austria) _ Pierre Boulez's
``Structures,'' Book 2, for two pianos is music of uncompromising
complexity. At the time of its premiere, in 1961, the work
galvanized composers in the avant-garde and in academic circles. No
one, including Boulez, could have thought it would reach outside to
mainstream audiences. So it must have been deeply satisfying for
Boulez when, at the conclusion of the third of four recent concerts
at the Salzburg Festival in honor of his 75th birthday, an audience
that nearly filled the 1,500-seat Felsenreitschule burst into
cheers after hearing a brilliant performance of ``Structures.'' By
Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   BAYREUTH-MUSIC (Bayreuth, Germany) _ Founded 124 years ago by
Richard Wagner, the Bayreuth Festival is under siege from several
directions. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   WEBERN-MUSIC (Undated) _ The complete recording of Anton
Webern's output just released by Deutsche Grammophon does much more
than refute old and sterile arguments against serialism. But that
it does, and overwhelmingly. By Paul Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   ACCIDENTAL-ART (New York) _ When Jackson Pollock first lifted
his brush from the canvas and allowed paint to drip in tangled
skeins across the surface, or Jean Arp and Marcel Duchamp began to
experiment with chance procedures, they sought in the accidental
and unpredictable the means to shatter the stale conventions of art
making. What these artists _ all currently featured at the Museum
of Modern Art as part of the show ``Making Choices'' _ hoped to
attain was freedom from the past and from academic formulas, and
the random act was their declaration of independence. By Miles
Unger.
</P>
<P>
   SWEDISH-HOUSES-ARCHITECTURE (Stockholm, Sweden) _ Some people
collect Hula Hoops, cookie jars, Japanese screens or racing cars;
Lars Sjoberg collects houses. What began as a childhood fancy
became a reality when he needed places to live and evolved into a
compulsion when he saw old houses about to be torn down. By Rita
Reif.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (Will move in `t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-VIETNAM (Hanoi) _ Twenty-five years after the end of the
Vietnam War and a month after the United States completed a
historic trade agreement with its former enemy, tour organizers in
both countries hope that U.S. travelers will finally start to make
their way to Vietnam in large numbers. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Questions and answers about prehistoric
caves in France; finding accommodations in Scottish castles; tours
of Belize and Guatemala. By Suzanne MacNeille.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Lead item: The opening of the American
Discovery Trail, the first coast-to-coast, nonmotorized trail, will
be celebrated next month in San Francisco. The 6,356-mile trail
runs from Cape Henlopen State Park in Delaware to Limantour Beach
in Point Reyes National Seashore, about 45 miles north of San
Francisco. All told, it traverses 15 states and the District of
Columbia, and it leads to 14 national parks, 16 national forests
and 10,000 sites of historic, cultural or natural significance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STYLES (Will move in `l' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GAP-NEWLOOK (Undated) _ Filtering into Gap stores since
mid-July, when the chain sold off the last of its summer cargo
shorts, are lace-bordered tank tops, filmy skirts and leathers in
hothouse hues of carmine, pink and mauve. Clearly these
trend-driven looks were intended by the retailer to shake up
shoppers lulled into a torpor by last year's surfeit of khakis,
cargo pants and polo shirts. By Ruth La Ferla.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-JOAN-JETT (New York) _ Nite out with Joan Jett, the
goddess of tight-leathered '80s rock. By Douglas Century.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo)
</P>
