<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2441 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-TAILHOOK-1STLD-WRITET     08-25 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAILHOOK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAILHOOK CONVENTION AGAIN MARRED BY MISCONDUCT ACCUSATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite with new reporting. Expands by 600 words.)  
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Navy is facing a new accusation of misconduct
at the annual convention of the Tailhook Association, officials
said Friday, nine years after drunken debauchery and sexual
assaults at another convention led to resignations, fines and
changes in the military's treatment of women.
</P>
<P>
   A man and a woman staying at a hotel in Sparks, Nev., where the
association held its convention last weekend, reported being
verbally and physically assaulted in a hallway on Aug. 19 by a
group of men attending the convention, Navy officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy did not identify the couple, but said the man reported
the accusation to Navy officials on Tuesday, two days after the
convention ended, using a telephone hot line set up to handle
sexual harassment complaints after the association's raucous
convention in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The misconduct reported did not appear to be of the same
magnitude as the events in 1991, when 83 women, some in the Navy,
reported being assaulted or harassed in a hotel in Las Vegas.
Nonetheless, the accusations included disturbing echoes of the
previous scandal, which roiled the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that as few as 10 and as many as several dozen
Navy and Marine aviators may have been in the hallway of the Nugget
Hotel at the time the man and woman say they were assaulted.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy's inspector general and its criminal service have begun
an investigation into the accusation, and investigators have
already conducted interviews with some of those involved, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The case could prove particularly embarrassing for the Navy
because it only restored its official recognition of the
association eight months ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the secretary of the Navy, Richard Danzig, said
that the association had given its assurances that there would be
no repeat of the kinds of incidents that made Tailhook synonymous
with the mistreatment of women in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Friday that Danzig would not comment on the
incident until the investigation was completed. They said it was
premature to say whether the association could once again lose its
official status with the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   The latest accusation of misconduct was swiftly denounced on
Capitol Hill. Rep. Carolyn B. Maloney, D-N.Y., said it was a
disappointment that the convention had produced new allegations
only months after the Navy reinstated its official ties to
Tailhook.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another sad day for women in the military,'' she said in
a statement. ``When a woman can't walk through a hallway without
being groped, there is a serious problem.''
</P>
<P>
   A statement released by the Pentagon said the man and woman, who
are married, were staying at the hotel, but not as part of the
convention. As they returned to their room, they tried to pass
through what the man described as a crowded hallway, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The man reported that the crowd in the hallway, all or most of
them men, made abusive comments when he asked them to make room for
them to pass.
</P>
<P>
   As the couple fought their way through, at least one man in the
hallway made ``inappropriate physical contact'' with the woman, a
senior Navy officer said, declining to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The Tailhook Association, named for the steel hooks on jets that
enable them to land on aircraft carriers, is a private group based
in San Diego that acts as a sort of booster club for naval aviation
and has long been associated with the Navy and the Marine Corps.
</P>
<P>
   Although the lack of official recognition never prohibited
officers from attending, last weekend's convention was the first
since the Navy restored its ties. Attendance swelled to 2,000, with
1,200 to 1,300 active-duty officers in attendance, the
association's president said.
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials said that several Navy admirals and Marine
generals attended the convention, but they declined to identify
them, and it was not clear whether any were aware of the events in
the Nugget's hallway.
</P>
<P>
   One official said that a senior Navy officer contacted the man
afterwards and apologized, indicating he was at least aware of what
happened.
</P>
<P>
   The official said it was not clear whether the officer had
reported any misconduct to his superiors, as required by Navy
policy. The senior officer's role during or after the event will
also be a subject of the investigation, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A Navy spokesman, Cmdr. Gregory J. Smith, declined to discuss
the senior officer's conduct, citing the investigation, but said
that the man indicated in his report that he was not satisfied with
the apology offered.
</P>
<P>
   Tailhook's president, Lonny K. McClung, a retired Navy captain
and pilot, expressed concern about the accusations, but said he
knew little about what was alleged to have happened.
</P>
<P>
   The convention, which began on Aug. 17 and lasted until last
Sunday, included a series of cocktail parties, dinners, seminars
focused on the future of naval aviation and even a fly-over of
naval jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you it was a very successful convention,'' McClung
said in a telephone interview. ``There were only two noise
complaints from the hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We left feeling pretty good about the convention,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Ken Lightfoot, a detective with the police department in
Sparks, a suburb of Reno, said that the police had not received any
criminal complaints related to the Tailhook convention, though
police did respond to two medical emergencies at the hotel,
including a man with a head injury at 3 a.m. last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Tailhook scandal in 1991 had a profound impact on the Navy
and the Marine Corps. More than 100 officers were eventually
implicated in the assaults or other riotous behavior at the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   The worst of the assaults came when a group of drunken pilots
formed a gauntlet in a hotel corridor and molested women as they
passed.
</P>
<P>
   The uproar over the assaults led to the resignation of the
secretary of the Navy, Lawrence H. Garrett III, and the early
retirement of the chief of naval operations, Adm. Frank B. Kelso
II, both of whom attended the convention, though they denied
witnessing the worst of the behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Friday that neither Danzig nor the current chief
of naval operations, Adm. Vern Clark, attended this year's
convention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
