<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2443 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-SURVIVOR-CORPTRAINERS     08-25 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURVIVOR-CORPTRAINERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Survivor' voted out by corporate trainers
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks a lot, Richard.
</P>
<P>
   You've just given corporate trainers a bad name. You spent your
summer scheming on a sun-soaked island, but now it's back to the
real world. It's lucky you won that million, because finding
another job as a corporate trainer could be hard.
</P>
<P>
   Face it, Richard, you're not a team player.
</P>
<P>
   While you were methodically voting others off ``Survivor''
island, you may have done yourself and fellow corporate trainers a
disservice. Your Mack-the-Knife tendencies haven't done much to
advance the trainer credo of togetherness, teamwork and tolerance.
In fact many of your corporate training peers are wondering: With
corporate trainers like you, who needs enemies?
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was on that show he was really working for himself,''
said Pat Galagan, a spokeswoman for the American Society for
Training &AMP; Development in Alexandria, Va., the country's largest
training organization. ``A corporate trainer is always working for
some kind of client either inside the company or outside and a
really good trainer can help a group of people work together to
achieve a specific goal and that's not at all what was happening on
`Survivor.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of nonethical Machiavellian behavior isn't the sum
total of corporate training,'' said Alan Axelrod, an Atlantan who
has written books about the leadership styles of Gen. George Patton
and Elizabeth I.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Patton would have drummed a guy like Richard Hatch out
of the Army, Axelrod said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hurt the image of corporate trainers who are there to
support people and build their skills,'' agreed John Challenger, a
Chicago area outplacement specialist who has done some corporate
counseling and training.
</P>
<P>
   OK, Richard, so you don't score many points with your peers, but
a few of them think you might do well in your recently announced
new venture as an overseer of a boot camp for troubled teens.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't work out and a book or movie deal doesn't come
through, you might try your hand at whipping mercenaries into shape
or working as a corporate efficiency expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see this fellow's experiences as being valuable for
training hard-nosed negotiators,'' Axelrod said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, being a game-playing snake may get you $1
million or the corner office, but every corporate crocodile
eventually gets his comeuppance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the real world ...there's a kind of corporate karma that is
at work and a real feeling that what goes around, comes around,''
said Axelrod. ``The trouble with being a Machiavellian is if you
don't attain the top position, sooner or later somebody else will
take you out. It works well when the rules are clearly defined the
way they were on the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ruthlessness may work in a game that lasts 39 days. It's
usually not going to be the basis of a lifetime career.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep it up, Richard, and you may find yourself back on the
island. This time it could be permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a company would want to pay you if you simply
were trying to help the individual reach his own goal. Companies
want you to figure out how to make the organization work better,
because that's what's going to pay off on the bottom line,'' said
Carolyn Turknett, executive vice president of Turknett Leadership
Group in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't want an organization where there's one survivor
and everybody else has left.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
