   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Many a gardener grows coral bells, but
only a few do for the sake of their flowers. Not that coral bells
don't have lovely flowers. They do. They send up spikes covered
with small bell-shaped blossoms in colors from pure white to
purple-scarlet. The flowers, bobbing atop stems so slender they are
almost invisible, look as if they are floating above the plant, not
tethered to it at all. What's more, coral bells have an
extraordinarily long season of bloom for perennials. By Cass
Peterson.
</P>
