   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-AFRICA-REVIEW (Undated) _ This weekend, on a return
engagement in Africa, President Clinton is singing the praises of
President Olusegan Obasanjo of Nigeria, a former general who was
elected last year in Africa's most populous country. The Clinton
administration has seized on Obasanjo, whose victory ended years of
military dictatorship, as an anchor of democratic stability in
restive West Africa. But there are risks. By Blaine Harden. (Will
move in ``i'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   VOTER-TURNOUT-REVIEW (Undated) _ What if they gave an election
and everyone came? Turnout in the last three American presidential
elections has hovered at around half of the nation's voting-age
population, which has prompted a good deal of national
hand-wringing. It's obvious that if everyone eligible voted this
November, the number of ballots cast would roughly double. But
would all those millions of additional votes change the outcome for
the main contenders, George W. Bush and Al Gore? By Michael R.
Kagay. (Will move in ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-DISPOSAL-REVIEW (Detroit) _ The deaths and injuries
attributed to failed Firestone tires are horrific, but recalling
6.5 million tires poses another problem: What to do with them once
they are taken off Ford Explorer sport utility vehicles and other
light trucks? If someone figured out a way to stack the tires in a
column at a landfill, they would form a pile 949 miles high. By
Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   REALITY-TV-REVIEW (Undated) _ Long before anyone ever heard of
reality television, or its most recent efflorescence, ``Survivor,''
a group of scientists began putting ordinary people into unusual
situations and observing how they behaved. In perhaps the most
famous experiment, Dr. Stanley Milgram's study of obedience to
authority, the subjects meekly delivered what they believed were
potentially fatal electric shocks to another person when ordered to
do so by an experimenter in a white coat. Such research stimulated
heated ethical debate. Now, in a twist that oddly merges the
science of the past and the entertainment of the present, a
production company is planning to re-enact the Milgram study and
other social-psychology classics. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   ESTROGEN-HEART-REVIEW (Undated) _ It seemed so clear a decade
ago: Of course hormone replacement therapy would protect women's
hearts after menopause. After all, women's heart disease risk
starts to rise in middle age, around the time that their ovaries
stop making estrogen. And there was indirect evidence that the drug
was working. But now, new data are turning the estrogen hypothesis
on its head and showing that even the best-intentioned analysis can
go astray if it relies on indirect evidence. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   CANDIDATES-SURVIVOR-REVIEW (Undated) _ The two candidates
surveyed their voters and saw a group evenly divided _ loyal
stalwarts on each side, swing voters in the middle. Pundits and
fans who had followed the race closely had no idea who would win.
The venue was the nerve-racking finale of the CBS hit show
``Survivor.'' Richard, who won, excelled at defining his candidacy.
This year's presidential candidates tried to make similarly
effective speeches at their televised conventions. Comparisons
between the candidates and the survivors proved irresistible. By
Jenny Lyn Bader.
</P>
<P>
   SINGLE-VOTERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Last week, riding a wave of
strong polls following his family-focused speech at the Democratic
National Convention, Al Gore reiterated his intention to make
families, particularly ``working families,'' the focus of his
campaign. Gore took great pains to project an image of himself as a
devoted husband and father who understands that all families want
the same opportunities for their children. But where does his
parent-focused campaign leave unmarried voters, a group that has
supported the Democratic party by a strong majority in recent
years? By K.A. Dilday.
</P>
<P>
   DEBATES-REVIEW (Washington) _ Given that both sides are bracing
for a down-to-the-wire presidential race, the nationally televised
debates between Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore
could be especially crucial this year. The common wisdom is that
Gore _ the oratorical slayer of Ross Perot, Jack Kemp and Bill
Bradley _ is such a vaunted debater, and Bush such a novice, that
it would be like watching a karaoke competition between Barbra
Streisand and Britney Spears. The truth is that Gore and Bush are
more evenly matched than people think. Bush, in fact, could even
come out ahead. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-MEXICO-REVIEW (Mexico City) _ As Vicente Fox paid his first
visit to Washington as Mexico's president-elect and informally
presented his ideas for a more liberal northward flow of Mexican
workers, his proposals stirred a flurry of mixed emotions at home.
Among the poor, Fox's proposals have sparked hopes that they might
soon be able to cross the border with more protections and dignity.
For Mexico's middle classes, an opening of the border seems more a
necessary evil. To them, the border is the epicenter of Mexico's
ambiguous, love-hate relationship with the United States. Because
it is a gateway to the most powerful country in the world, the
border is at once a kind of mythical place, but also a place where
Mexico's disadvantages are magnified. By Ginger Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-IDENTITY-REVIEW (Berlin) _ As the 10th anniversary of
German unification approaches on Oct. 3, it seems clear that the
conjunction of recovered German nationhood with a diminished nation
state has had some disturbing effects. The giant of Europe is
edging toward its anniversary in a mood of some agitation,
wondering aloud what to do about rightist extremism, pondering
where the roots of xenophobia lie, lamenting the misunderstanding
between Wessis and Ossis (Westerners and Easterners), and groping
for a shared sense of German identity that is nonthreatening. By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
