<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-OPPENHEIMER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA'S OPPENHEIMER REMEMBERED AS A MAN WHO TOUCHED MANY
LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ In this society riven by race, the
color line has long been crossed only by the most determined of
souls.
</P>
<P>
   So when Harry F. Oppenheimer was remembered Friday, here in the
small Anglican church where he worshiped for decades, no one had to
ask why so many people from such different walks of life had come
to pay tribute to a titan of business and industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Oppenheimers earned much of their fortune in gold, diamonds,
minerals and other holdings during the country's darkest days. But
more than many of his fellow magnates, Oppenheimer, who died last
Aug. 19 at age 91, was a champion of change. The longtime chairman
of the world's biggest mining companies, Anglo American and De
Beers, and one of the world's richest men, Oppenheimer opposed
apartheid and pushed for an end to the oppression of blacks.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday morning, cabinet ministers and corporate chiefs, black
and white, made their way to St. George's Church in the city's
Parktown neighborhood, filing in alongside ordinary employees and
parishioners who also felt themselves touched at one time or
another by the man affectionately known as Harry O.
</P>
<P>
   Oppenheimer was far from a revolutionary, and he often found
himself at odds with those who were _ namely, the outlawed African
National Congress. But in the end many in the country, including
leaders of the liberation struggle, judged him to have been a
friend of their fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played an important role, from a different type of
trench,'' said Cyril Ramaphosa, who was secretary-general of the
African National Congress during the early 1990s. ``His trench was
not the struggle, the armed struggle. It was in the boardroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramaphosa said that the business success that Oppenheimer
achieved should not discount the enormous contribution he made to
the country's evolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will always be questions of whether, in the process of
making his money, whether it was advanced through the help of
apartheid,'' Ramaphosa said. ``My answer to that is he operated in
the time and he did well in advancing the causes of many people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Godsell, one of the Anglo American Corp.'s top executives,
said the collective complexion of the people who had shown up
signified the place Oppenheimer held in South African life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says a lot about him and it says a lot about where the
society we live in has come from,'' Godsell said.
</P>
<P>
   Oppenheimer championed the creation of black trade unions and
was influential in ending an employment system that set aside
certain jobs for whites only. He also developed programs to bring
blacks into positions of responsibility in his companies.
</P>
<P>
   One person who came to know Oppenheimer's good works was Isabel
Louw, a 60-year-old black woman who was a parishioner at St.
George's in the 1960s and 1970s. She was one of those people who
benefited from his generosity and so she, too, came Friday to pay
her respects.
</P>
<P>
   Oppenheimer, she recalled, had helped her son with a scholarship
to college in Cape Town, and later the Oppenheimer family helped
him obtain a job at the company in spite of his student activism,
which made him a target of state security agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very nice and he always was helping,'' she said. ``He
was rich man, but he wasn't a boaster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
