<HEADER>
A2460 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BELLSOUTH-PEON     08-25 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-PEON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth promotion signals Latin America strategy
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The point man for BellSouth's spectacular success in
Brazil has been given a high-profile promotion.
</P>
<P>
   While Roberto Peon remains president of company operations in
that country, a job he has held since 1997, he will also head
BellSouth's Internet and publishing efforts throughout Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   Charles C. Miller III, president of BellSouth International,
said Peon will be responsible for wireless Internet service as well
as the electronic Yellow Pages. ``These are two of our biggest
opportunities in the region, and that is exactly where we need
Roberto the most.''
</P>
<P>
   The promotion is a reward for Peon, but it also validates the
past decade's decisions while signaling future company direction.
</P>
<P>
   Peon led the campaign to take advantage of the fastest-growing
telecommunications service in the largest market in Latin America,
one of the world's most promising regions.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Mexico, Peon is fluent in English and Spanish, as
well as Portuguese _ the language of Brazil. He led the team that
studied the market for a decade and then bid more than $3 billion
for two wireless licenses in Brazil, a price thought exorbitant by
some analysts. Additionally, BellSouth and its Brazilian partners
spent roughly $900 million to build wireless networks. In May,
BellSouth paid $240 million for a minority stake in a third
wireless company.
</P>
<P>
   But Brazil's hunger for wireless has proved fierce. BellSouth
launched wireless service in Sao Paulo and the northeast of the
country in May and June 1998. By year's end, the two units had more
than 1 million customers. BellSouth now has more than 3 million
customers among the three wireless units.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Latin America remains a largely untapped telecom market
and BellSouth _ along with Telefonica of Spain _ ranks as a leading
investor.
</P>
<P>
   For the first quarter of this year, BellSouth revenues for the
region were $695 million, according to documents filed by the
company with federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Telefonica, BellSouth has specialized in wireless
communications and has more than 8 million wireless customers in 10
countries. BellSouth has just begun offering Internet access via
phone lines in five markets where, thus far, it has only 169,000
customers. The company has also started offering wireless Internet
access in Argentina, Chile and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes for the region are high enough that BellSouth is planning
to issue a ``tracking'' stock for its Latin American unit later
this year. Like other trackers, the Latin American offering will
not give shareholders ownership. However, it is meant to give
investors a way to profit from the growth in the region and to
``unlock'' some of the value that is not otherwise reflected in
BellSouth stock.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, BellSouth continues to invest in Europe as well. Last
week, the company and its partners bid $7.6 billion in an auction
for German wireless licenses, Europe's largest and most lucrative
telecommunications market. BellSouth's portion of the bid was about
$880 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
