A2461 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-SOUTHERNCO-COX     08-25 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERNCO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern Co. unit fights for control of German firms
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fresh from victory in a takeover battle for a Welsh utility,
Southern Co. is embroiled in a high-profile struggle over control
of two German power companies.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Energy Inc., Southern's international subsidiary, wants
to expand its holdings in Berlin's electric utility, which serves
metropolitan Berlin, and then acquire the company that generates
electricity for almost all of the former East Germany.
</P>
<P>
   SEI was surprised two weeks ago when E.ON, a conglomerate that
is Germany's largest energy company, decided instead to sell its 49
percent stake in Berliner Kraft und Licht, the Berlin utility known
as Bewag, to Hamburgische Electricitaets-Werke, the utility known
as HEW that serves Hamburg. HEW is majority-owned by Sweden's
state-owned utility.
</P>
<P>
   SEI prevailed this week in the German courts by winning an
injunction blocking the sale until 2017 on grounds that it has veto
power over any such transaction. SEI purchased 26 percent of Bewag
in 1997 for $830 million, the largest U.S. investment to date in
continental Europe's rapidly consolidating utility industry.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Harland, SEI's director for German operations, said Friday
that the fight is shaping up as a major test of U.S. investment in
Europe's energy sector and whether ``it's possible (for a U.S.
company) to take a meaningful role in the European club.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Amsterdam, Netherlands, Harland
noted that E.ON has investments in the U.S. chemical sector and
that it would not be in its interest to act in a ``capricious
manner'' in this case.
</P>
<P>
   SEI wants use an expanded investment in Bewag as a springboard
to acquire Vereinigte Energiewerke, the eastern Germany power
generator known as VEAG, and integrate the two companies.
</P>
<P>
   The two investments would amount to ``hundreds of millions of
dollars'' and give SEI a major foothold for further expansion in
Europe's utility sector, Harland said.
</P>
<P>
   HEW is also bidding for VEAG. German Economics Minister Werner
Mueller, who is viewed as antagonistic to SEI, declared this week
that HEW offers ``the clearer solution'' for the east German
company. It was only last week that a joint venture of SEI and
Pennsylvania-based PP&AMP;L was declared the winner over Japan's Nomura
Securities in a takeover fight for Welsh utility Hyder PLC. The
partnership will pay $3.7 billion in cash and assumed debt.
</P>
<P>
   SEI is due next year to be spun off by the parent Southern Co.
into a separate publicly traded company to handle riskier U.S. and
international investments.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, E.ON is being forced by European antitrust
regulators to divest its holdings in both Bewag and VEAG as a
condition for a $14 billion merger earlier this year that created
the company from two German energy concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Harland said SEI wants to sit down with all the parties and
negotiate a settlement, and could envision shared ownership of the
East German utility. But SEI will insist on maintaining its stake
in Bewag, which includes effective management control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll fight the battle and win in court, but that wouldn't be
a win for anyone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
