<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2470 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FIRES-OVERVIEW0827-1S     08-25 2424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRES-OVERVIEW0827-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: 1STLEDE long version.
 &HT;    EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY.
 &HT;    Montana on fire
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MISSOULA, Mont. _ In rolling valleys surrounded by raw, angular
mountains, the last hay bales of summer are being hauled to barns.
Cornfields are ready for harvesting. Pine siskins and goldfinches
feast on ripened sunflowers. Sumacs are taking on the reds and
yellows of autumn.
</P>
<P>
   It is picturesque, a tourist's delight _ if you can see it.
</P>
<P>
   In almost any direction from Missoula in western Montana, grand
vistas of peaceful valleys and rugged mountains are dimmed, as they
have been for most of August, by thick, acrid smoke billowing from
more than 25 major wildfires. In their wake, the blazes have left
widespread forest destruction and human misery.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the relentless flames have charred nearly 650,000 acres
of Montana's forests and grasslands and destroyed more than 250
homes and barns. With the massive fires continuing to rage, state
and federal authorities in Montana have declared 19.6 million acres
_ an area roughly the size of Maine _ off limits for recreation.
</P>
<P>
   The end is not in sight, and that has dashed the once rosy
outlooks of entire communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This town depends on tourists stopping here, but with so many
areas shut down to recreation, businesses here may not survive,''
said Forest Hayes, the mayor of Darby (pop. 940), 60 miles south of
Missoula. ``It's going to take a long time for this place to return
to normal; you get the feeling that the worst is yet to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Darby is connected to several other small rural communities in
the scenic Bitterroot Valley by U.S. 93 out of Missoula. Along the
way _ in restaurants, stores, churches and, of course, along the
front lines _ folks talk of little else but fire.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this is war.
</P>
<P>
   FIRE IS A FRIEND
</P>
<P>
   If any places were ripe for fires of epic proportions this
summer, they were the vast forests, brushlands and grasslands of
the American West.
</P>
<P>
   For years, massive amounts of combustible dead limbs, toppled
trees and logging debris _ what foresters call fuel _ had been
accumulating on the forest floors and had reached dangerous levels
in huge stretches of woodlands. In many forests, the deadwood stood
higher than six feet, a sure sign of unhealthy woods, forestry
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the fuel-choked forests was that until the 1970s,
the U.S. Forest Service's policy was to extinguish all fires. A
public education campaign featuring Smokey the Bear in a park
ranger hat drummed into Americans a revulsion to wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   But scientists later realized that fire actually is a friend of
the forest. Occasional low-intensity fires that sweep through
woodlands remove deadwood and underbrush and return vital nutrients
to the soil without harming mature trees and other vegetation and
wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   When fires are suppressed and deadwood builds up to massive
levels, forest fires can become towering infernos, able to leap
from tree crown to tree crown with explosive speed, turning huge
swaths of forests into charcoal and threatening houses and entire
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1970s, Forest Service scientists and other land
management agencies have tried to offset the deadly buildup of dead
trees and brush with deliberate ``prescribed'' burnings. They also
have altered their once strict fire-suppression policies to let
fires burn themselves out in wilderness areas if human habitation
is not threatened.
</P>
<P>
   But forestry experts say the effort has been too little and too
late. Just this month, critics were laying part of the blame for
the western fires on the Clinton Administration, saying the White
House had not acted quickly enough after being warned over the
years that there was a small window of opportunity _ perhaps a
decade _ before the forests became so inundated with fuel that
every fire could have catastrophic consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 40 million to 60 million acres of federal forest _ nearly
all of it in the West _ are in dire need of thinning, forestry
officials say. And the drought has made the dead wood as dry and
dangerous as an open matchbook.
</P>
<P>
   Three good years of rainfall that spurred the growth of plants
were followed by a searing drought. This year's dry spring was
lethal. It dried out vegetation more quickly than usual, extending
the growing season, and also melted snow more rapidly, so that more
water than usual ran away in streams instead of soaking gradually
into the ground to keep vegetation green longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fuel here has only about 4 to 7 percent moisture; that's
about as dry as lumber dried in a kiln,'' said Keith Wooster, a
biologist with the Chattahoochee National Forest in Georgia who was
dispatched to the Ryan Gulch area 30 miles east of Missoula, Mont.,
to fight a major wildfire.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on a smoky ridge overlooking a steep slope where the
Ryan Gulch fire roared nearby, Wooster pointed to a layer of dead
limbs, each about the diameter of a baseball bat. ``They are so dry
you could light them with a match,'' he said _ and then he had to
walk briskly to get away from the intense smoke and heat welling up
from the wildfire.
</P>
<P>
   A few hundred feet away, his colleague, George Custer, a fire
protection expert with the Ocala National Forest in Florida, used a
drip torch to set a ``backfire.'' It would remove fuel from the
advancing wildfire; with nothing to burn, the wildfire would go
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least that's what we hope,'' Custer said. ``We're literally
fighting fire with fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the big wildfires were sparked by dry thunderstorms that
have produced much lightning and little rain. A few wild blazes
have been human-caused. No matter what triggers them, when the
cataclysmic fires get going, their ashes can be borne aloft and set
new fires as far as a half mile away.
</P>
<P>
   What complicates the firefighters' jobs is that the West is
adding population rapidly, creating what's called an
``urban/wildfire interface'' of houses, farms and ranchettes tucked
high among the trees. In such a setting, the highest priority for
firefighters is to protect the homes and other structures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going into situations that, absent homes and property,
we wouldn't be putting firefigters into,'' said Steve Frye,
incident commander for the firefighting efforts in Montana's
Bitterroot Valley. He called the intense fires raging in the valley
``unprecedented,'' with veteran firefighters saying they have never
witnessed such ferocious fires, with flames shooting up 150 feet
high.
</P>
<P>
   Given the flames' unpredictability, protecting people and their
homes and barns and other structures may, even under good
conditions, require high-risk tactics. Critics say that if people
insist on living at the very edge of forests or in the woods
themselves, then they should not expect firefighters to endanger
themselves to protect dwellings so vulnerable to wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   One of the critics is Forest Hayes, the mayor of Darby and a
retired Forest Service district ranger. The Bitterroot Valley, he
says, has become a focal point in the national firefight because of
the sheer number of homes pressed up inside remote canyons and
under the canopy of the lodgepole pine forests that throughout
history have been the scene of dramatic forest fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fire trucks have a hard time getting up to those houses,'' he
said as he stood in a park in Darby last week, updating residents
on the fires and offering words of comfort and advice to frightened
homeowners. ``And when they build, they leave debris and brush
right up to the very edge of their homes; that's inviting the fire
to come get you.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 285,000 acres have burned in the Bitterroot area
alone.
</P>
<P>
   In all, more than 1.5 million acres in 11 western states have
succumbed to wildfire so far this summer, the most destruction from
wildfires in at least 50 years. Before the flames are finally
snuffed out, they will be the worst in more than a century, veteran
firefighers say.
</P>
<P>
   At least 30,000 firefighters are battling the blazes across the
region, with reinforcements from Canada, Australia and New Zealand,
as well as from the Army and Marines, who together have dispatched
three battalions. The government is spending at least $15 million a
day to stop the fires. Southwestern Montana is ground zero.
</P>
<P>
   SMOKED OUT OF HOMES
</P>
<P>
   ``Look into my eyes,'' Sally Johnson said as she pointed to her
reddened orbs this past week. ``They look as if I've been carousing
all night, but it's from all the smoke. Everyone around here has
bloodshot eyes, and we're also told that breathing the smoke is
equivalent to smoking 10 packs of cigarettes a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a retiree, lives with her daughter on about 20 acres
near Hamilton, 48 miles south of Missoula. The wildfires that are
ravaging western Montana forced them to evacuate their home this
month, but the Ravalli County Sherriff's Department allowed them to
return after they signed a liability waiver stating name, age and
next of kin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fires are getting near again, and we may have to leave
once more,'' said Johnson, who had stopped at a U.S. Forest Service
information booth along Highway 93 to check on the status of the
blazes. ``It's tough staying in the house anyway; it's full of
smoke and ash from the fires, and you can't air it out because the
smoke never goes away.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter and Joan Giles, who own a small ranch near Hamilton, no
longer have a home. ``But I still have her,'' Carter Giles said as
he waved his arm towards Joan. ``That's what matters most.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing they saved after a wildfire destroyed their
home, barn, fences and outbuildings was a prized bull, a cow, a
calf and a few other animals.
</P>
<P>
   The animals are being housed in an emergency shelter at the
Ravalli County Fairgrounds in Hamilton. The Giles' temporary home
is a camper at the Anglers Roost RV Park on the Bitterroot River.
The park's owners, Ron and Joan Englund, are letting the Gileses
and others who have been burned out of their homes stay for free
the first week. The second week, the guests have to pay only for
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I once thought a lot of people around here were cheap; they
never wanted to spend a dime,'' said Gary Wiley, manager of the
fairgrounds. ``But after seeing so many of them helping out their
neighbors, I now regard them as frugal, not cheap. They are
generous when it counts.''
</P>
<P>
   MANAGEMENT TEAMS TO THE RESCUE
</P>
<P>
   When major fires, floods, hurricanes or other disasters occur,
the federal government sends in ``incident management teams'' to
protect people and property. Although the teams are composed of
civilian workers, they are organized along military lines, with a
commander and various officers under him in charge of logistics,
information, supplies, field work and other support.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 such teams are battling the Montana fires. Each
team has its own base camp _ ``tent cities'' of hundreds of workers
that spring up overnight, complete with sleeping areas, latrines,
shower facilities, kitchens, mess halls, weather stations, supply
depots, information centers and other facilities to support
firefighter crews trying to contain towering flames on the front
line.
</P>
<P>
   The team commander requests the number of crews needed to fight
the fires. The leader also can request helicopters to dump water on
the flames, bulldozers to cut fire lines and other equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, you don't always get what you need,'' said Mike
Melton of Jackson, Miss., the Ryan Gulch team commander.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt gave firefighters a
blank check to draw on the national treasury for supplies, the
vastness of the fires has stretched available manpower and
firefighting equipment very thin across the West. ``Money can't buy
any more experienced fire crew bosses,'' said Melton, who at one
point was in charge of about 625 people battling the Ryan Gulch
blaze.
</P>
<P>
   By late Friday, however, that fire was more than 90 percent
contained, and Melton was releasing several crews to fight other
raging fires in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   ``We leave here having done a job everyone can be proud of,''
Melton told his team members. ``Don't give up this thing. There's a
lot of work to do cleaning the land.''
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL EVENT BECOMES SOCIAL SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   In Hamilton in the Bitterroot Valley, the Renalli County Fair,
which is the main social event of the year, has been cancelled.
``The fair is supposed to be a time to celebrate, but right now a
lot of folks around here can't celebrate,'' said fairgrounds
manager Gary Wiley.
</P>
<P>
   The fairgrounds have been turned into a shelter for animals
belonging to residents who had to evacuate or lost their homes.
Last week, volunteers, including Boy Scouts, Girl Scouts and 4-H
members, were caring for more than 600 horses, cows, llamas, sheep,
goats, chickens, dogs and cats.
</P>
<P>
   When Wiley sent out a request for food for the animals, people
responded in droves. Now the barns and storerooms at the
fairgrounds are groaning with animal feed. ``One rancher brought in
a bale of hay, all he had left,'' Wiley said. ``He said his cattle
had gotten badly burned from the fires, and he had to shoot every
one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiley said there will be some kind of celebration later on,
``when we are finally through this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, though, people are struggling to get through. Air
levels in the usually clear Bitterroot Valley have reached
hazardous levels, prompting health officials to urge county school
leaders to consider school closings if polluted air persists.
American Red Cross nurses also are urging residents to wear face
masks to prevent breathing in the smoke.
</P>
<P>
   But one small group was celebrating last week. Three regulars at
the Rocky Knob Lodge and Bar on U.S. 93 near Conner said their
homes were among eight on nearby Laird Creek Road that escaped the
fire. ``A helicopter with a big bucket hanging from it came and
dumped water on my house just when the fire was starting to get to
it,'' said Al Colyer, nursing a Budweiser at the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Along the road, crude, homemade signs thank firefighers for
saving their homes.
</P>
<P>
   But seven other houses along the road were destroyed. ``This
place here was at first reported as burned down,'' said Becky
Burkett, Rocky Knob's bartender. ``But here we are, wide open for
business and taking care of everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
