<HEADLINE>
BOSTON COLLEGE BOOT CAMP BENEFITS ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's regularly described as academic boot camp _ boot camp with
a heart, boot camp leavened with tough love.
</P>
<P>
   It's boot camp for minority students, members of the incoming
Boston College Class of '04.
</P>
<P>
   The 47 ambitious, enthusiastic students who make up this group
are the latest incarnation of a program that has literally
transformed The Heights. In the 21 years since the inception of the
Options Through Education program, BC has gone from a virtually
lily-white university with a minority population of less than 1
percent to a vibrantly diverse institution that's 24 percent
students of color.
</P>
<P>
   Under the free OTE summer program, students with strong grades
but subpar standardized test scores spend six weeks on campus in an
intensive academic program to prepare them for the rigors of
freshman year.
</P>
<P>
   If summer school evokes images of sleeping late and sitting
through a couple of notably undemanding classes, think again. This
was 7 in the morning until 11 at night, intense coursework with
study halls and field trips. Bed check was at 2 a.m., and many
students studied right up to that moment. This was not for the
faint of heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are typically kids with good grades and tough test
scores,'' said BC spokesman Jack Dunn. ``Some are kids who went to
schools that were not the best inner-city schools. But people saw
something in them.''
</P>
<P>
   The program costs the school $2.7 million a year, which Dunn
describes as ``the best investment we've made.''
</P>
<P>
   A typical day began with two hours of English, followed by an
hour of math, followed by more English, followed by contemporary
social issues. Mandatory study hall began at 6:30. Free time
finally began at 9:30 p.m. Most nights that meant they were free to
keep studying.
</P>
<P>
   For Drudys Nicolas, a Boston Latin graduate, and Juan De Jesus,
entering BC from Boston College High School, the program, which
concluded two weeks ago, furnished a perfect introduction to campus
life _ and they are products of good schools.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the academic discipline, OTE gives its participants a
ready-made peer group when classes start later this month, a
valuable aid in the transition to college.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a challenge academically, but you know the
friendships you make during those six weeks are going to be
lifelong friendships,'' Nicolas said.
</P>
<P>
   Summer school called for group projects that demanded working
together and tested the limits of their new friendships. Under the
watchful eye of program coordinator Joanna Maynard _ ``our mom for
six weeks,'' as Nicolas put it _ no one dropped out, no one failed,
and the group emerged ready to start college.
</P>
<P>
   OTE's success comes at a time of considerable anxiety about
minority enrollment. While rollbacks of affirmative-action programs
have had little demonstrable effect on enrollment, keeping minority
students in school remains a challenge for colleges across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   At Boston College, OTE is prelude to a four-year program for
Asian, African-American, and Latino students intended to assist
them throughout their college careers. It has paid off with a
graduation rate of over 90 percent in the past eight years, nearly
double the national average of 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The program includes a house on campus where students can get
tutorial and other assistance, and a network of graduates who keep
tabs on how minority students are faring at BC. This fall, for the
first time, both the president and vice president of the student
body are African-American, which may say something about the
program's success in helping worthy students thrive on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are students who didn't meet the requirements on
paper,'' says Sheilah Shaw Horton, a BC administrator. ``If you
examine a transcript and look beyond what's on paper, and if you
give them the proper support they need _ support they didn't know
existed, because it didn't exist at their high schools _ you can
see them through to graduation.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicolas is planning to study nursing, while De Jesus has his eye
on management school. Both believe this summer has laid the
foundation to go on, and to prove test scores are no measure of
being ready to succeed, or to lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We formed a bond academically,'' De Jesus said. ``We feel like
we're ready to take on any challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Adrian Walker's e-mail address is walker(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
