<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BIZ-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD BUSINESS NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG GREW 10.8 PERCENT IN QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong has extended its recovery, reporting that its economic
output grew 10.8 percent in the second quarter. The increase is
smaller than the 14.3 percent recorded in the first quarter, but
the government raised its forecast for full-year growth to 8.5
percent, from 6 percent. Some economists worry that Hong Kong
continues to be dogged by price deflation. And while the
territory's exports surged 17.7 percent _ fueled by the strong U.S.
economy _ domestic consumer spending rose by 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   NEW BIDDER FOR RIO ALGOM
</P>
<P>
   The British mining company Billiton PLC has agreed to buy Rio
Algom Ltd. of Canada for $1.16 billion in cash, topping a hostile
$1.02 billion offer from a Canadian rival, Noranda Inc. Mainly a
producer of aluminum, coal and zinc, Billiton said Rio Algom would
give it ``a significant entry point into the global copper
business.'' Billiton is offering 1.7 billion Canadian dollars, or
27 Canadian dollars for each Rio Algom share, 2.50 Canadian dollars
more than Noranda's offer.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   SWISSCOM PLANS TO REORGANIZE
</P>
<P>
   The leading Swiss phone company, Swisscom AG, said it would
reorganize its business around operational units to focus more on
mobile communications and less on fixed-line operations. Its mobile
operations will be folded into a separate company, Mobile Com AG,
which it plans eventually to spin off to the public. Meanwhile,
Swisscom plans to sell its 50 percent stake in Tesion, a fixed-line
operator, to its partner, Energie Baden-Wuerttemberg AG.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE FAVORABLE FOR BP AMOCO
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders of the Russian oil company Sidanko approved a plan
that would return the assets of an oil-producing subsidiary to BP
Amoco, Russia's biggest foreign investor. Shareholders voted to
increase Sidanko's share capital by 37.7 percent, which will give a
rival oil company, Tyumen Oil, a stake in Sidanko and will allow BP
Amoco to retain its 10 percent stake. Last year, Tyumen pushed
Sidanko's subsidiary into bankruptcy and bought it at a bargain
price over BP Amoco's objections. Under the new agreement, Tyumen
will return the assets to Sidanko in exchange for a stake of 25
percent plus one share.
</P>
<P>
   EU APPROVES AD AGENCY DEAL
</P>
<P>
   The European Union Commission cleared the purchase by the
British advertising company WPP Group of a United States rival,
Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc., for $4.7 billion. The deal is expected to
close in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
