<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAUMA-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY SITTER SUES DOCTOR ACCUSED IN WIFE'S MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH RANALLI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Saying she suffers from nightmares, the baby sitter who
was just a foot away from Dr. Richard Sharpe's estranged wife when
he allegedly gunned her down last month has filed a $5 million
lawsuit against the wealthy dermatologist.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit describes how the terrified 19-year-old herded
Sharpe's two young children into a bathroom after the shooting and
placed them in the bathtub as she frantically dialed 911. While she
waited for police, she huddled by the bathroom door, listening for
Sharpe's footsteps, expecting she would be next.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Dormitzer's attorney, John J. Weltman of Boston, said
she has been ``a mess'' since the night of July 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has devastated her,'' he said. ``She's been really just
totally unable to function. She can't sleep, she can't work, she
can't even drive. Her mother has to take her everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe's civil attorney, Julianne Balliro, did not return a call
Friday seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   In one of her nightmares, Dormitzer says she's following Sharpe
as he stalks a woman, powerless to help. In another, she's the
woman being hunted, desperately trying to put distance between
herself and Sharpe, a terrifying echo of the night Karen Sharpe was
killed.
</P>
<P>
   Dormitzer, a college freshman from Newton, was so traumatized by
the shooting that she was taken by ambulance to a nearby hospital
to be treated for shock, her lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawsuit is the second one filed against Sharpe in connection
with his wife's death. Two days after the shooting, attorney Jacob
M. Atwood filed a $100 million wrongful death suit on behalf of the
couple's children.
</P>
<P>
   According to prosecutors, police, and court records, Dormitzer
was baby sitting for the couple's son, Michael, 7, and daughter,
Alex, 5, on the night of July 14 when Karen Sharpe arrived home
just before midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Her estranged husband, who had allegedly abused her in the past,
then suddenly appeared at the door of the house in Gloucester, in
violation of a restraining order.
</P>
<P>
   She only had time to ask, ``What are you doing here? I think you
should leave,'' before Sharpe allegedly leveled a high-powered
rifle at her chest and fired.
</P>
<P>
   After the shooting, Dormitzer reacted as ``every parent's dream
baby sitter,'' said Weltman.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing Sharpe would shoot her next because she witnessed the
crime, Dormitzer ran into an adjoining room, but not before
grabbing Michael and pulling him behind a couch to hide, according
to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point, Michael jumped up and she grabbed him and pulled
him down,'' Weltman said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, while dialing 911 on her cellular phone, Dormitzer took
the boy and his sister into a bathroom. She locked the door, put
the children in the bathtub, where they would be safer from flying
bullets, and then crawled over next to the door to listen in case
Sharpe was approaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``(She) remained there in fear for her life and the lives of the
children until the police arrived,'' the lawsuit states.
</P>
<P>
   Since the shooting, Dormitzer has suffered from nightmares,
headaches, stomach pain, and nausea, and is receiving both
psychiatric counseling and medication to help her deal with the
trauma, the lawsuit states.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is little doubt that this heinous crime was a
significantly traumatic incident for Kristen Dormitzer that will
haunt her for the rest of her life,'' said one motion filed with
the suit. ``Ms. Dormitzer was close enough to this event that she
at times still smells the gun powder and burning flesh from the
high-powered round tearing through Karen Sharpe's body. Kristen
Dormitzer lived a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Middlesex Superior Court Judge Raymond J.
Brassard approved Dormitzer's bid to attach $850,000 worth of
Richard Sharpe's real estate and other assets.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe ran a lucrative plastic surgery practice and holds
medical patents that may be valuable, according to sources close to
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Both Dormitzer's suit and the earlier one filed on behalf of
Sharpe's children seek to attach his personal assets, two houses, a
Merrill Lynch investment account that reportedly contains more than
$1 million, and his stock in two companies, Clickmed Corp., an
Internet medical business, and LaseHair Inc., a cosmetic surgery
company.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe, 45, fled briefly to New Hampshire after the shooting but
was arrested the next day. He is being held without bail on
first-degree murder charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
