<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-MANSIONS0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mansion buying spree loses some momentum
 &HT;    By Sheryll Poe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The market for mansions may be softening, real
estate agents say.
</P>
<P>
   In June, 15 existing homes sold for more than $1 million, up
from 10 in June of last year, according to the latest numbers from
the Austin Board of Realtors and the Real Estate Center at Texas
A&AMP;M University. But in July, only seven sold.
</P>
<P>
   And there were more of them on the market than ever. In July
1999, there were 72 active listings of $1 million or more. That
number more than doubled this year to 156.
</P>
<P>
   But the trend _ if it is one _ is very recent. Through July, the
total of number of $1 million-plus properties sold was 73. For the
first six months of 1999, 23 mansions were sold.
</P>
<P>
   The recent fluctuations in the stock market and layoffs in tech
companies have contributed to the slide. According to local
economist and principal of Angelou Economic Advisors Inc., Angelos
Angelou, the growth of the dot com companies and the venture
capital that funded them have fueled the real estate market,
particularly in the million and above range. ``The recent problems
in the dot com world are going to inevitably cause a slowdown of
homes in those price ranges,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, sellers anxious to cash in on the real estate
euphoria have simply priced themselves out of the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are putting million-dollar homes on the market
just based on hearing that people can get whatever they ask for,''
said real estate agen-- Bill Stanberry of Stanberry and Associates.
</P>
<P>
   There were 144 homes going for more than $1 million in June, up
from 74 last June. It takes more than a year to sell most of these
homes, which account for less than 1 percent of the local market.
</P>
<P>
   The softening is far from a slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got a little enamored by that frenzy, especially in
that high-end market,'' said Kathleen Bucher, an agent with Re/Max
Heart of Texas Realtors. ``I don't think prices are reducing; it's
just affecting the multiple offers on million-dollar houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Bucher has five luxury homes on the market, including two
lake-front properties and a ranch in Giddings. The ranch, which is
50 miles east of Austin, includes an air strip, stables and 600
acres. It went on the market for $2.5 million more than six months
ago and is now offered at $1.75 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have sold 10 times over if it wasn't in Giddings,''
Bucher said. ``Most people don't need an air strip and 600 acres.''
</P>
<P>
   And with so many properties topping $1 million, buyers are
becoming more discriminating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buyers are questioning the value, whether it even is a real
value,'' Stanberry said. ``They're just not willing to write a
check for whatever it takes. They want to make sure it's worth what
they're paying for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
