<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ASSESS-2TAKES(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: BARAK WARNS OF `TRAGEDY' IF PEACE PACT NOT REACHED
</HEADLINE>
 By   JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak has warned of ``a
tragedy'' ahead for Israel and the Palestinians if they fail to
reach a peace agreement, and has hinted that he fears a return to
the Islamic terrorist attacks that killed scores of Israelis in the
mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview published in Friday's editions of Yediot
Ahronot, Israel's most widely circulated newspaper, Barak said he
could not predict whether a peace pact could be reached with Yasser
Arafat, the Palestinian leader. But he said whatever chance there
was of an agreement on Jerusalem and other contentious issues was
now up to Arafat showing ``flexibility and openness,'' which was
not forthcoming at the Camp David talks that foundered last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there will be an agreement, but I am sure
there should be one,'' Barak said. ``I am sure the alternative is
tragedy. It would not be appropriate to go into detail as to what
could happen later on.'' At another point, he noted that within the
past 18 months _ roughly the period since he campaigned for and won
Israel's May 1999 election on a pledge to push assertively for
peace with the Palestinians _ there had been no major terrorist
attacks on Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to mounting pressure from opposition parties for a new
election later this year or early next year, Barak said that, if
forced to go to the polls again, he would campaign on the peace
offer he made to Arafat at Camp David. That offer included
concessions on Jerusalem and other issues. A new opinion poll
published on Friday in Yediot Ahronot showed a continuing erosion
of public confidence in Barak, with only 33 percent rating his
performance as prime minister as ``good'' and 64 percent as ``not
good.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barak predicted he would win an election, because most
Israelis know the potential consequences of abandoning the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   If the Israeli Parliament calls for new elections, as many
politicians expect, when it returns from its summer recess on Oct.
29, Barak said: ``I will go to the people to ask their trust in
continuing to steer the helm of the peace process, and I tell you
that this trust will be given, because we are now faced with
dramatic decisions. With a year and a half having passed without a
terror attack, whoever closes the road to an accord is taking a
heavy responsibility on themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   After Barak returned empty-handed from Camp David on July 25,
his government was in serious disarray. His ruling coalition had
already lost its parliamentary majority before he left for
Washington when two ultra-Orthodox parties quit the government in
disagreement over the peace process. His political position was
further weakened after his return, when Parliament rejected the
government's candidate for the Israeli presidency, the former prime
minister Shimon Peres, in favor of a little-known candidate, Moshe
Katsav, of the main opposition Likud Party.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, in the past week, Barak has gone on the political
offensive. First, he stunned his own Labor Party by announcing that
he planned a ``secular revolution'' that would strip the Jewish
religious establishment of legal powers and privileges accumulated
over Israel's 52-year history. On Wednesday, he challenged Likud to
join the ``march'' to a more secular state by forming a new
Labor-Likud government of national unity, similar to one that ruled
in the 1980s. He suggested that such a government could be formed
within ``a few weeks'' if the peace process, vigorously opposed by
Likud, falters.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Barak appears to have found renewed confidence in his peace
proposals, even as the impasse with the Palestinians shows no sign
of easing. When he landed back in Tel Aviv from Camp David, he
described the concessions he had tentatively accepted in
Washington, including a limited Palestinian foothold in East
Jerusalem, as ``null and void'' because Arafat had rejected them
and demanded full Palestinian sovereignty over all of East
Jerusalem. But if this suggested that Barak was preparing to draw
back from the Camp David proposals, the interview with Yediot
Ahronot on Friday suggested the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Shlomo Ben-Ami, the acting foreign minister, who was a key aide
to Barak at Camp David, told reporters on Friday in Jerusalem that
far from rejecting the proposals put forward by President Clinton
at Camp David, and tentatively accepted by Barak, Israel now wanted
the proposals codified in a ``collective paper.'' Such a document
would have to be agreed on by Israel and the Palestinians and set
out exactly what was proposed and what was rejected at Camp David.
``We must work on the basis of what was created at Camp David, and
not return to square one,'' Ben-Ami said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The change did not appear to reflect any new confidence by Barak
that Arafat will accept the Camp David proposals, or any
modification that might be acceptable to Barak. After Camp David,
Arafat used a 20-nation tour of Europe, the Middle East and Asia to
round up support in the Arab and Muslim worlds for his refusal to
accept anything less than the return of all of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Although he failed to get backing for his plan to make a
unilateral declaration of a Palestinian state on Sept. 13 _ even
from the Palestinians' closest allies like Egypt and Russia _
Arafat lined up fairly solid support for his position on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports in the Palestinian press, Arafat, in his
diplomatic encounters since Camp David, has used strong invective
against the Israelis, and Barak in particular, accusing them of
``lies'' in depicting Arafat as the spoiler at Camp David _ a view
seemingly shared by Clinton, who said at the time that he had found
Barak more ``creative'' in seeking solutions. In the interview on
Friday, Barak hit back, saying that there was ``a great deal of
misunderstanding and lack of knowledge'' among Arabs, and in
particular Palestinians, over the most sensitive of all issues in
the conflicting claims for East Jerusalem _ Haram al Sharif, called
the Temple Mount by Jews.
</P>
<P>
   For Jews, the Temple Mount is the most sacred of all places, the
site, according to Jewish beliefs, of the first and second temples
destroyed by the Babylonians and Romans. Among Muslims, the site,
and its two Muslim shrines, the Dome of the Rock and Al Aksa
Mosque, are among the holiest of all Islamic sites. At Camp David,
Barak tentatively agreed to proposals that would have granted
religious sovereignty over the Mount to the Palestinians, but
retained Israeli political sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Barak complained that Arafat was distorting the issue
by suggesting that the Israeli position masked a desire to dig up
the foundations of the old temples, and to use the findings as a
grounds for usurping the Muslim claim. ``Arafat has created the
impression in the Arab world as if we were demanding sovereignty
over the Temple Mount in order to dig up the temple,'' Barak said.
``But we know the reverse: Our faith prevents us from digging
there. We want to ensure an arrangement where no one digs for the
temple, not even the Muslims.''
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
