<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MUBARAK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO VISIT MUBARAK IN EGYPT 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   White House officials said Friday that President Clinton would
add a brief stop in Cairo, Egypt, to his Africa trip to discuss the
Middle East peace talks with President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders will discuss the latest developments and ways to
encourage the negotiations, said the White House spokesman, Jake
Siewert.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrives in Abuja, Nigeria, on Saturday for a two-day
visit aimed at buttressing the country's fragile democracy. On
Monday, he flies to Tanzania to meet participants in the Burundi
peace negotiations being held in Arusha.
</P>
<P>
   The president had been scheduled to return briefly to Abuja on
Tuesday to refuel his plane, but officials on Friday added Cairo to
his itinerary because Mubarak will not be attending a meeting of
world leaders early next month at the United Nations in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will use the U.N. session to meet with both Prime
Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian
leader.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said Clinton was eager to meet with Mubarak as
well to help jump-start the peace talks. The president spoke with
both Mubarak and Barak early Friday to discuss the Cairo meeting,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly juggling a variety of foreign policy challenges, Clinton
will travel to Colombia on Wednesday on a one-day trip to lend
support to the counternarcotics campaign started by President
Andres Pastrana.
</P>
</TEXT>
