u p BC-FLA-CAMPAIGN-NYT &LR;      08-25 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BUSH, IN FLORIDA, FOCUS ON FRIENDLY CROWDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related story, BUSH-LATIN-AMERICA) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It seemed a long way to travel to preach to the choir.
Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush both courted Florida
voters this week, but spoke mostly to the already converted.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made his party's usual pilgrimage to the retirement
condominiums of Broward County north of Miami, a loyal Democratic
base, where he spoke about protecting Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got goose bumps,'' said Renee Kugler, 66, of Tamarac, at
Gore's talk on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Texas governor campaigning in the state where his
brother Jeb Bush is in his first term as governor, met Friday with
a largely Cuban-American audience in Miami, a long-devoted
Republican constituency. He challenged Fidel Castro to embrace
democracy and got a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may have been five minutes during the Democratic
National Convention when I stopped to think about how well things
are going,'' said Heidi Marcelo, a 20-year-old Cuban-American, at
Bush's talk Friday morning at Florida International University.
``Now I've gone right back to Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   As campaign stops go, for both men, it was the equivalent of an
overstuffed armchair, soft, familiar and comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   But far back in the audience at Bush's speech, Jorge Herrera
wondered why a candidate would court votes he already has instead
of trying to change other voters' minds.
</P>
<P>
   Herrera, who is in a minority among Cuban-Americans, plans to
vote for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore needs to come here,'' said Herrera, 19, who studies
political science at Florida International.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from a middle class family, and Gore seems to suit my
needs more,'' he said. Other young Cuban-Americans might side with
him if they saw Gore in person, Herrera said.
</P>
<P>
   He came to hear Bush with an open mind, willing to be swayed,
said Herrera, who lives in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``all Bush talked about today were the things that
people here wanted to hear,'' such as continued sanctions against
Cuba, and expanded trade elsewhere in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Gore did not seek votes in Little Havana. Bush did not court the
condo vote.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not reach out to black Miamians, almost a forgotten
constituency in Miami. But then, neither did Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Gore is already pretty solid with the black community down
here,'' said Garth Reeves, publisher emeritus of The Miami Times, a
newspaper devoted to black readers. ``We're a little afraid of
Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters in the middle said they heard or saw little to sway them
in the newspapers or on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore doesn't talk about anything interesting,'' said Fred
Truby, a 37-year-old fund-raiser for nonprofit organizations. ``Who
is he? He's a Southern boy, but he's a senator's son. He went to
Vietnam for the war, but he didn't fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really upset about Bush,'' said Truby, who lives in South
Miami. ``While his dad was president, he was just a party boy.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, neither candidate seemed to care about that sliver of
undecided voters.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, where a large part of the population was Republican to
begin with and incensed by the Clinton administration's handling of
the Elian Gonzalez custody battle, Bush was welcomed as a hero.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not mention Elian Gonzalez; he did not have to. Many
players in the saga _ including Ramon Saul Sanchez, who organized
street protests _ were in the audience and are already in his camp.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's much-talked-about break from Clinton on the Elian
Gonzalez case _ saying that he thought a family court should decide
the matter _ has been largely dismissed and even ridiculed here as
a political gesture.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of dwelling on that issue, Bush tersely denounced
Castro and promised to resurrect free-trade negotiations with Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should have been more verbal about the situation in Cuba,''
said Alex Acosta, 18, who studies international relations at
Florida International. But he considers himself a strong Bush
supporter.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican rallies at Florida International have, like the
Democratic rallies at the condos, become a political tradition.
Bush's father and brother kicked off their Florida campaigns here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a supporter of his father and his brother, and he will
have my vote as well,'' said Scherry Jenkins, a member of the
Republican Women's Club of Coconut Grove.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Gore and his running mate, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, had that same warm reception, if not more so, in what
people refer to here as the condo canyons.
</P>
<P>
   Kugler said she was willing to consider Bush, but she quickly
dismissed him after seeing recent news coverage of him. He just
seemed fake, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't like Bush,'' said Kugler, who moved to South
Florida 28 years ago. ``He has this look on his face, this smirk.
He just doesn't cut it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, by contrast, ``oozes with compassion,'' Kugler said.
And Gore is tightly bound to them by his political promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prescription drugs are a big burden for us,'' Kugler said of
the older residents of the condos. ``He's trying to make it
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Lil Kaufman, who lives in the Kings Point condo in Tamarac, said
there were some ``undecideds'' among the older residents going into
Gore's visit, but ``I think they're decided now.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not that Gore pulled huge numbers to him on this trip,
but cemented the cracks in his support, older residents here said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida is a tough one for Gore,'' said J.P. Monroe, a
political science professor at the University of Miami. ``This
state is leaning Bush.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
