<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, AUG. 26 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-MEXICO-U.S.-FOX-NYT (moved Wednesday, August 23)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, August
23 about proposals by Mexico's president-elect, Vicente Fox
Quesada, to allow more Mexicans to work legally in the United
States misstated the month he was elected. It was July, not June.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-NYT (moved Thursday, August 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, August
24 about a coalition proposal by Prime Minister Ehud Barak of
Israel referred incorrectly to the history of direct elections for
his office. The 1996 election, won by Benjamin Netanyahu, was the
first in which Israelis voted directly for prime minister. The
election won by Barak last year was the second.
</P>
<P>
   BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT (moved Saturday, August 19)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, August
19 about the front-runners for most valuable player in baseball
referred incorrectly in some editions to the two most recent
players from New York teams to have won the award in the same year.
They were Don Newcombe and Mickey Mantle, in 1956 _ not Sandy
Koufax and Elston Howard, in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-CIR-P-BRAIN-NYT (moved Wednesday, August 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, August
16 about bicycle computers referred incorrectly to their means of
measuring pedal rhythm, or cadence. Only rotations of the crank are
tracked, by sensors; gear sizes do not have to be entered into the
computer.
</P>
</TEXT>
