<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-WAR0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Art of War' makes casualty out of Snipes
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - ``The Art of War `` takes its lofty title from an
ancient handbook of military strategy by Asian general Sun Tsu, who
believed that wars can be won without ever having to actually
fight.
</P>
<P>
   Wesley Snipes, in contrast, prefers a more hands-on approach.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran action star ably demonstrates his martial arts and
weapons skills in the mundane thriller from Canadian director
Christian Duguay. The film features a handful of bracing chase
scenes and fight sequences, but they fail to prop up an
insubstantial plot.
</P>
<P>
   Snipes carries the big-budget B-movie with sheer charisma, but
he deserves better material.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Art of War,'' which was not screened for critics, casts
Snipes as Neil Shaw, a deeply classified government agent. In the
dated prologue, set in Hong Kong on the eve of the new millennium,
Shaw performs a high-tech theft of Chinese military secrets and
battles an army of thugs before parachuting off a skyscraper under
heavy machine-gun fire.
</P>
<P>
   The murky, convoluted story involves an impending Chinese trade
agreement with the United Nations. Before the treaty can be signed,
the Chinese ambassador is murdered at a U.N. banquet in New York.
Shaw, who officially doesn't exist, is framed as the assassin.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw goes underground to clear his name. In keeping with genre
conventions, he enlists the aid of a beautiful U.N. translator,
Julia (Marie Matiko), who believes his innocence, and plays
cat-and-mouse with wily FBI agent Cappella (Maury Chaykin).
</P>
<P>
   His apparent foe is Asian business mogul David Chan
(Cary-Hiroyuki Tagawa), described as the Donald Trump of Hong Kong,
who has ties to the Chinese mob.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomatic intrigue runs much deeper, but most folks will
probably have it figured out well before the end of the first act.
</P>
<P>
   Other players include U.N. Secretary General Douglas Thomas
(Donald Sutherland), U.N. chief of security Eleanor Hooks (Anne
Archer) and Shaw's partner, Bly (Michael Biehn).
</P>
<P>
   The wobbly plotting merely marks time between action sequences.
The screenplay by Wayne Beach, who also wrote the similarly styled
Snipes vehicle, ``Murder at 1600,'' and newcomer Simon Davis Barry
is riddled with preposterous twists and coincidences.
</P>
<P>
   Former cinematographer Duguay, who previously directed
``Screamers'' and ``The Assignment,'' devotes his interest to the
violent set pieces, leaving the rest of the film to languish. His
pacing is erratic and the editing is choppy.
</P>
<P>
   Chaykin (''Entrapment'') provides what little humor the movie
can muster.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's escape from an FBI van is lifted nearly wholesale from
``The Fugitive.'' The derivative finale features a John Woo-style
two-gun standoff and ``Matrix''-like bullet trails.
</P>
<P>
   Snipes, who served as executive producer, sprints gun-in-hand
through overly familiar territory. He's battled political
corruption in ``Murder at 1600,'' played an innocent man on the run
in U.S. Marshals and been immersed in international intrigue in
``Rising Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also done much more involving and challenging work. ``The
Art of War'' is a rote, sloppy thriller that goes by the musty old
book.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
