<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2519 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CATERPILLER-VIETNAM-A     08-25 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATERPILLER-VIETNAM-ART-$ADV27-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. FIRMS NEGOTIATING FOOTHOLD IN VIETNAM'S UNCERTAIN EMERGING
MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 27)  
 By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VUNG TAU, Vietnam _ To explain why he is so excited about the
new trade agreement with the United States, Pham Van Tuat clambered
aboard the Xin Thu, his new 89-foot wooden fishing trawler, and
gestured into its spacious holds: Lower American tariffs for
Vietnamese seafood products in the United States, he explained,
will mean more demand for tuna and squid.
</P>
<P>
   And that is where this $125,000 trawler comes in.
</P>
<P>
   The Xin Thu, the largest of his nine boats, can travel 400 miles
out to sea and bring back 200 tons of fish, Tuat said. To
demonstrate how, he bundled his visitors down into the engine room.
There, still bearing its maker's signature yellow paint, was
something that makes many American executives here as excited as
Tuat: a brand-new, $32,000, 480-horsepower Caterpillar engine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be exporting to America soon,'' Tuat said triumphantly,
hurrying his guests onto a skiff to beat the ebb tide back to
shore. ``I'm planning to build another boat like this one. But even
bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   To a large extent, Tuat's plans are the fruits of seven years of
toil by Anthony Salzman, an entrepreneur from New York. Salzman
came to Hanoi from Japan in 1993, hoping to capitalize on that
country's swelling investment in Vietnam. He wound up opening a
dealership for Caterpillar, which was among the most vocal
companies in urging the Clinton administration to lift the U.S.
embargo that blocked trade for 19 years.
</P>
<P>
   Salzman, 49, is now one of Vietnam's most prominent American
residents, well known for his outspoken, unrelenting style. And he
is just one of many American executives here who say a trade pact
will unleash a tide of exports _ and lift his fortunes with it.
After five years of talks, the United States and Vietnam signed the
agreement July 13, and it is expected to be ratified by Congress,
though probably not this year.
</P>
<P>
   Since President Clinton ended the embargo in 1994, the American
commercial venture in Vietnam has resembled its earlier military
one, with optimism quickly bogged down in a quagmire of red tape,
corruption and Communist recalcitrance. To skeptics, the new
agreement is yet another capitulation: tariffs on Vietnamese goods
would drop immediately, while Vietnamese tariffs and quotas on
American products would fall only gradually, in some cases enduring
as long as seven years.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters here say the agreement represents a new,
irrevocable commitment by Vietnam to open the country to global
markets and to play by internationally accepted trade rules.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, as Vietnamese exports rise and foreign investment
returns, executives like Salzman say, demand will also rise for
American products, whether toothpaste or trucks and bulldozers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impact is indirect,'' Salzman said.
</P>
<P>
   With rising export revenue, he predicted, ``my electric business
is going to grow, my marine-engine business is going to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And as everything else grows,'' he added, ``the infrastructure
business should grow, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Salzman said he foresees $1 billion in sales for his venture,
V-Trac _ for Vietnam Tractor _ during the next 10 years if Vietnam
carries through on its commitments. But he and other veterans of
business here warn that change should not be expected overnight.
With or without the trade accord, Vietnam is still a poor,
Communist country, with an absence of legal, social and physical
infrastructure that sent foreign investment inflows plummeting to
about $1.5 billion a year in 1999 from roughly $3.3 billion in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Vietnam is no longer a hostile, war-ravaged
country. More than half the population is too young to have ever
seen an American GI. And Vietnam's other former adversaries,
meanwhile, have moved back in. France was the top investor in the
country last year, and Japan the top trading partner. The United
States is still only Vietnam's seventh-largest foreign investor and
trading partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be a challenging market, but I think the potential is
definitely here,'' said Michael Frisby, counselor for commercial
affairs at the American Embassy in Hanoi and a Vietnam war veteran.
``Companies should come and investigate this market, because with
ratification of the treaty the potential in Vietnam will increase
exponentially.''
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam is already rich in resources. It is the largest producer
of black pepper and robusta coffee, which is used for instant
blends. And it is the second-largest exporter of rice, after
Thailand, and a key source of seafood, cashews and bauxite. Its
workers earn high marks from foreign employers _ and not just for
the low pay.
</P>
<P>
   The country also has much potential as a consumer market. More
than one-third of its 78 million people live in poverty, but some
of its roughly 18 million urbanites are sitting on what bankers and
economists estimate are billions of dollars in gold and other
hidden savings, with perhaps $1 billion to $2 billion more coming
in from relatives overseas every year. Many Vietnamese hoard their
money to avoid income taxes, and because they do not trust banks.
</P>
<P>
   Although American companies lack much market share here, their
brands are easily recognized. When Coca-Cola returned in 1994, it
found people still familiar with its logo. Offices in Vietnam at
that time were still using old IBM computers and keeping cool with
rusting Carrier air conditioners, all left behind when the United
States pulled out nearly 20 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The first Caterpillar equipment arrived here before World War
II, when Vietnam was still a French colony. More Cats, of course,
came during the American military involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Old Caterpillar tractors and bulldozers were still rumbling
across the landscape in 1990, when Bruce St. John, then
Caterpillar's representative in Bangkok, traveled to Vietnam to
assess the prospects.
</P>
<P>
   He learned that Vietnamese mechanics still knew how to service
Caterpillar equipment. Given Vietnam's infrastructure needs, St.
John, who served in the Army in Vietnam in 1970 and 1971, predicted
a lucrative market for Caterpillar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like a very attractive opportunity,'' said St. John,
who now works at the same factory, in Mossville, Ill., where Tuat's
engine was built.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, St. John testified before Congress about the embargo.
Caterpillar's stance set off protests from groups that had been
urging the United States to pressure Hanoi to find American
soldiers missing in action.
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar executives argued that Vietnamese markets were
falling to Japanese and European competitors and that more
influence on the MIA issue could be gained by trading with Vietnam.
In 1993, Caterpillar opened its office in Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   Salzman took an unlikely road to Vietnam _ and to bulldozers.
His father, Herbert, secured the family fortune in 1967 when he
sold the company his own father founded, Standard Bag, to Boise
Cascade. Herbert Salzman went on to serve four presidents in
various positions at the State Department and started the agency
that would become the Overseas Private Investment Corp., which
guarantees American investments in third-world countries.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Salzman studied at Yale University and Duke
University law school. After working at American Express and Lehman
Brothers, he chose to explore his entrepreneurial roots, a decision
that took him to Portugal and Spain. Then he tried Asia, starting
in 1992 with Japan, where his wife was born.
</P>
<P>
   When his effort to crack Japan's closed markets did not succeed,
Salzman and his wife moved to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yen were pouring in,'' he recalled. ``It meant that Vietnam
was going to be an important Asian economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanoi was a long way from the Salzmans' apartment on Fifth
Avenue in Manhattan. When he and his wife called an exterminator to
rid their new home of rats, Salzman said, a man showed up with a
snake in a bag.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts by the Communist government to keep tabs on the new
capitalist arrivals were equally rustic. Salzman said he learned
that his phones were tapped when he heard officials breathing over
the line. Fax machines were illegal _ they were too hard to
decipher.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Salzman said he never felt any animosity as a citizen of
Vietnam's former enemy. He set up the first American Chamber of
Commerce in Hanoi and began prospecting for business ideas that
would capitalize on Vietnam's obvious need for new infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Salzman had just abandoned hopes of investing in a cellular
telephone operator when he met Caterpillar's Hanoi representative,
James Ferrara. Caterpillar was already fielding offers from its big
distributors in Hong Kong, Indonesia, France and Canada to expand
to Vietnam, Salzman said.
</P>
<P>
   Salzman prevailed over the other bidders, he said, by appealing
to the company's traditional preference for family-owned
dealerships. In mid-1994, he set up V-Trac. A Caterpillar
spokesman, Jeffrey Hawkinson, said Ferrara was not available to
confirm Salzman's account.
</P>
<P>
   While many Vietnamese knew Caterpillar's name, Salzman needed to
spread the word that Cat was back. In 1995, he advertised a contest
offering a $1,000 prize for the oldest working Caterpillar
equipment in the country. The winning entry was a 1939 generator
serving on a tugboat. The overwhelmed winner carried off his prize
in two shopping bags filled with Vietnamese currency.
</P>
<P>
   Selling new equipment, however, was still difficult. The same
year, V-Trac lost a $7 million contract to supply bulldozers and
other heavy equipment to one of Vietnam's cement companies. Salzman
blamed the Jackson-Vanik law, a Cold War statute aimed at Communist
countries not allowing free emigration. The law prohibited trade
financing to such countries by the Export-Import Bank or by OPIC,
the agency started by Salzman's father. The Vietnamese cement
contract went instead to Komatsu of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, President Clinton waived the Jackson-Vanik restrictions
against Vietnam, and last year V-Trac won $2.3 million in financing
from OPIC, the first deal the agency had made in Vietnam since the
war. V-Trac now employs 140 people in seven offices around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   But financing is still difficult to obtain from risk-averse U.S.
government agencies, Salzman said. The Ex-Im Bank, for one, started
operations in Vietnam in December, but has yet to finance a deal.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the trade accord may be a bigger boon to companies from
other countries as they invest in Vietnam. Textile companies from
Taiwan, for example, poured millions of dollars into Vietnam on the
prospect of exporting to the United States with reduced tariffs.
Now, a Taiwan trade official said, they are counting the minutes
until the agreement is ratified by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But what is good for Taiwan textile companies in Vietnam may
also be good for Caterpillar. Just north of Vung Tau, the Hualon
Corp. of Taiwan has a factory that makes cloth and polyester yarn.
When the plant opened in 1997, there was no electricity, so Hualon
paid $15 million for three Caterpillar generators. Now it is
planning to build a second plant next door, more than doubling its
power needs.
</P>
<P>
   Power is now available from the local utility, but Hualon's
generators remain cheaper _ and more reliable. Back in Vung Tau at
the Technical Raw Material Trading &AMP; Supplying Co., Phan Doan Hung
showed off a new, $400 million shoe factory left dormant for a day
by a power failure; its 2,200 employees had to stay at home.
</P>
<P>
   Hung and the companies in Europe, Korea and Taiwan that buy his
shoes said the trade agreement would mean more business for his
factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to export our product directly to America,'' he
added. ``That way we can earn a bigger profit.''
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that he has the power he needs to meet his contract
deadlines, Hung is buying a $61,000 Caterpillar generator. ``Please
come soon,'' he said to a visiting V-Trac executive. ``You see what
it's like today. I worry, worry, worry.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Ford Vietnam, a joint venture between Ford Motor and a
Vietnamese partner, also uses Caterpillar generators to power its
$102 million factory near Hanoi. Business is slow: Ford makes only
100 of the 14,000 cars that the factory could produce each month.
Company executives are optimistic that the trade agreement will
change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agreement makes me feel even more confident because of the
way it makes other businesses grow,'' said Deborah Aronson, general
director of Ford Vietnam. ``There's a significant retail population
that is looking to demonstrate its success.''
</P>
<P>
   Chronic power failures, however, underscore Vietnam's
limitations as a market and investment. Though the economy is
regaining speed, unprofitable state-owned businesses drain
government coffers, while banks, like so many countries in Asia,
are paralyzed by bad loans. Income tax rates are so high that it is
sometimes cheaper for foreign companies to hire expatriates than to
pay Vietnamese a competitive after-tax wage.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-Vietnam trade agreement also leaves unresolved a litany
of structural problems, executives say. Vietnam is only beginning
to experiment with capital markets; it recently opened a stock
market, but regulations still hobble businesses' ability to raise
money. Vietnam is trying to overhaul these rules, but its
bureaucracy is still Byzantine, its licensing rules unclear, and
its foreclosure and bankruptcy laws inadequate. Courts are not
independent; they answer to the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   And some executives here do not share Salzman's faith that the
trade pact will permeate the economy. Ronald Kiel, 3M's managing
director in Vietnam, agrees that the accord is essential for
Vietnam's future but says the country's goods are too poor and its
infrastructure too decrepit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you're going to see an explosion of industrial
output because the country isn't geared up for it,'' Kiel said.
</P>
<P>
   Others have more faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Vietnam does have the potential for explosive
economic growth, more so than most countries in Asia,'' said Wesley
Grove, the chief representative of Chase Manhattan Bank in Ho Chi
Minh City.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard Letellier is another believer. Letellier is chief
executive of Morning Star Cement, a $400 million joint venture of
the Swiss cement giant Holderbank Financiere Glarus and Vietnam
National Cement.
</P>
<P>
   Booming demand for cement to build homes has sent Morning Star's
production soaring from 400,000 tons in 1998 to 1 million tons last
year. The trade agreement, Letellier predicted, ``will open the
Vietnamese market to U.S. investors, and this means new
infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And this is good,'' he added, ``for the cement business.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no need to guess whose equipment Morning Star uses to
excavate the limestone to make that cement.
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar's dividend doesn't end at the quarry. Increased
shipping traffic is also helping the Bien Dong Shipyard south of Ho
Chi Minh City. Bien Dong's workers are putting finishing touches on
a new $70,000 ferry; inside it is a $30,000 Caterpillar engine.
``After this one's done, we're building another for the same
purpose but with a 400-horsepower Caterpillar engine,'' said Phan
Ngoc Chuc, Bien Dong's director.
</P>
<P>
   Chuc is investing $200,000 and hiring 20 new workers to double
the shipyard's production and to take advantage of what he thinks
will be a boom in demand for another kind of vessel. Dwindling
catches and environmental concerns have prompted Vietnam to push
its fishing fleet farther out to sea, requiring larger, more
powerful boats. Such big boats are more economical when they remain
at sea, so Chuc foresees building other boats to transport their
catch to shore.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Vung Tau, Tuat remembers that when he was a boy in the
1950s, he had to go only about a mile out to catch all the fish he
needed. Bigger boats won't be enough to compete in the American
market now, he realizes. He and other fishermen will need to
improve the quality of their product, he says, investing in more
ice and freezers that will burn more fuel.
</P>
<P>
   That may help Caterpillar sell bigger engines in Vietnam. But it
could help Tuat, too. One of his sons, it so happens, sells ice.
The other sells fuel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
