<HEADLINE>
VARGAS CHANNELS RAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ To watch Fernando Vargas fight is to think he's
engaged in a sort of chess match, his skills against his opponent's
with little if any emotion in the equation.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the rage that burns inside him, the rage that has
caused him difficulties outside the ring, is also present inside of
it.
</P>
<P>
   To the dismay of his opponents, he simply has a knack for
channeling it in a cooly destructive manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely want to make my opponent pay,'' said Vargas, not
necessarily implying that his opponent had done anything wrong.
``It makes it sweet. I want him to pay. I think about all the bad
things that have happened in my life as if he did them to me. It
helps me get angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him to pay for what he's said and done. It's like, `Did
you like that (punch)? How about that one?' It's like killing him
slowly, torturing him, and I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   LATEST ADDITION: Where does Vargas' anger come from?
</P>
<P>
   His father abandoned the family when Vargas was a child, which
left him with a crushing feeling of being unloved.
</P>
<P>
   And, as if that weren't enough, he'd always blamed himself. He
felt as if he had done something to drive his father away. The pain
has left him bitter to this day.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's also made him perhaps the most devoted father in
the world. He talks animatedly about his two boys every chance he
gets.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was Fernando Jr., 3. And now there's one-month-old
Amado.
</P>
<P>
   The meaning of Amado? Loved.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the name and he always will be,'' said Vargas, a
resident of Oxnard.
</P>
<P>
   STAR POWER: Vargas is becoming accustomed to an increasing
amount of attention and believes he deserves recognition.
</P>
<P>
   However, he's still amazed when fans fawn over him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the Quartey fight, I had to run from a bunch of people
to get into the limo. I thought, `What is this? A Michael Jackson
appearance?''' he said laughing. ``It was funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``... I do appreciate it, though. At the Julio Cesar Chavez
fight (against Kostya Tszyu a few weeks ago), I got an ovation that
I think was second only to Chavez. It gave me goose bumps. Me and a
friend looked at each other and said, `Can you believe that?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm living a dream I don't want to wake up from. It's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   FULL-TIME JOB: Vargas said that if he beats Thompson and signs
to fight Trinidad on Dec. 2, he will take only two weeks off before
resuming training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna go to Mexico and then come right back. That's it,''
he said. ``It'll be an easy camp because I won't have a chance to
get heavy. I guess I inherited a fat gene because I do get fat.''
</P>
<P>
   Could that mean (ital)big(endital) trouble after he retires?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be big and fat and just play with my grandchildren,'' he
said laughing.
</P>
<P>
   WEIGHT MATTERS: The fighters weighed in separately on Friday
after their scuffle at a news conference on Thursday that left
Vargas with a bloody lip.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas weighed 153 pounds. Thompson came in two pounds over the
154-pound limit at the official weigh-in, but came back later at
153{. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
