<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2524 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-R-DUTCH-U.S.-FINANCE-     08-25 1893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-DUTCH-U.S.-FINANCE-ART-1155(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUTCH FINANCIAL GIANT PLANS TO EXPAND TO U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Del., Iowa)   (Repeating to add graphic note)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nearly a year after Congress cleared the way for
insurance companies to own banks and vice versa, most U.S. banks
and insurers are still on the sidelines, unable, analysts say, to
see how to turn the new opportunity into profit.
</P>
<P>
   But early in September, a big Dutch company that pioneered
banking and insurance combinations in Europe, ING Group, is
planning to break into the American field with a stripped-down,
virtual bank that will eventually sell insurance. It hopes to
become a model for getting the most out of both businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The bank is part of a larger plan by ING, a financial services
giant with operations in more than 60 countries, to build a
brand-name empire in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The company, whose U.S. headquarters is in Atlanta, has already
amassed a stable of about a dozen insurance companies, including
two big recent additions bought for nearly $14 billion. It says it
plans to spend roughly $80 million _ a huge amount in the insurance
world _ to unite everything under one umbrella and establish its
name across North America.
</P>
<P>
   Before Congress scrapped the Depression-era Glass-Steagall Act
and other laws that had kept insurance companies and banks
separate, two U.S. giants, Travelers Group and Citicorp, joined
together as Citigroup in the kind of merger that financial services
executives had long argued would better serve customers and add to
their fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   But since the bill became law last November, bankers and
insurers have been waiting for signs that customers would rush to
do their banking and buy insurance with the same company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Citigroup has had some success,'' said Tom Brown, chief
executive of Second Curve Capital, a financial services fund, ``but
the jury is still out.''
</P>
<P>
   For European companies, however, the verdict is in. Banking and
insurance combinations have been operating in Europe for more than
a decade, some with considerable success. Whether ING can make it
work here is far from certain, but it will not be for lack of
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the U.S. financial services will eventually
consolidate down to maybe 10 major entities,'' said Colin Devine,
an insurance analyst at Salomon Smith Barney.``ING is obviously
serving notice that it intends to be one of the 10.''
</P>
<P>
   ING's newest addition, an online bank, will feature a savings
account paying 6.5 percent interest _ triple the rate at most
established banks, but about on par with Internet banks that
require minimum deposits of $1,000 or so to open an account.
</P>
<P>
   ING Direct will have no minimums, no limits on withdrawals and
no fees. The bank also plans to offer consumer loans, mortgages and
certificates of deposit. Term life insurance and mutual funds,
which ING now sells through its insurance outlets, will later be
added to the bank roster.
</P>
<P>
   To keep costs down, the bank will be run out of a renovated
six-story warehouse in Wilmington, Del., where real estate and
labor are relatively cheap.
</P>
<P>
   The bank will not offer checking accounts, which often are money
losers. But it will electronically link checking accounts that
customers have at other banks to their accounts at ING Direct,
allowing them to transfer money in and out, much as banks now let
customers electronically shift funds to and from brokerage houses.
As in many banks, deposits in ING Direct will be federally insured
up to $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of branches, the bank will have a scattering of
cybercafes where people can drop in to buy pastry and coffee, surf
the Web and perhaps check on their digital accounts. Ewald Kist,
the chief executive of ING, said ING came up with the idea of the
cafes, which it has used with its online banks in Canada,
Australia, Spain and France, because ``people like to feel
something, see something real.'' The first ING Direct Cafe in the
United States is set to open in early October in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have bought a bricks-and-mortar bank, but that would
be nothing new for the U.S. market,'' Kist said. ``We're not in
competition with hundreds of thousands of banks. We're doing a new
trick.''
</P>
<P>
   And somewhat like beaters in a grouse hunt, ING will have 10,500
financial planners with insurance and brokerage licenses around the
United States, the largest force of its kind in the country, to
point out the virtues of the new bank to their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Wicker, a banking analyst at Meta Group, a technology
research firm in Stamford, Conn., said he thought the bank would
``definitely make a dent in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   But other experts are skeptical. James McCormick, president of
First Manhattan Consulting Group, which specializes in financial
services and telecommunications, said he sees the bank as a niche
player rather than as a challenger to big banks like Wells Fargo
and Bank One.
</P>
<P>
   Customers concerned primarily about high returns from a bank
``are not loyal,'' McCormick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And while this segment is not small,'' he added, ``not
everybody goes with a bank on that basis. So you have limited
growth potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, ING's effort stands out as a bold attempt to capitalize
on a new opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Since the company's formation through the merger of a bank and
an insurer in the Netherlands in 1991, ING has been quietly selling
insurance in the United States through regional companies like Life
of Georgia. ING's insurance predecessor, Nationale-Nederlanden, had
owned U.S. insurance companies since the late 1970s. But you had to
read the fine print to know that the companies were related or
Dutch-owned.
</P>
<P>
   ING's latest acquisitions, ReliaStar Financial Services, a deal
announced in May, and the nonhealth insurance units of Aetna
Financial Services, announced in July, will make ING one of the
United States' biggest insurers. Now it is planning to shed its
cloak of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is going to be a lot of noise about ING in the U.S.,''
Kist said. ``We are a strong company, a world player, and we want
to capitalize on that strong name.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new strategy, all of ING's U.S. possessions _
including its New York investment banks, ING Barings and Furman
Selz _ are being tied together with the parent's name and its
orange lion logo. For example, Equitable of Iowa, which the Dutch
company bought in 1997, has become ING Equitable Life.
</P>
<P>
   ING's expansion is the latest foray by European companies into
the world's biggest market for financial services. Companies like
Aegon (also based in the Netherlands), the Dutch-Belgian Fortis,
AXA of France and Allianz of Germany have been attracted to the
United States by favorable economics and regulatory policies.
</P>
<P>
   And they are becoming substantial players. Early last year, for
example, Aegon bought Transamerica Corp., a big U.S. life insurance
company. And in June, a unit of AXA, which already was a leader
here, bought Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co., the New York
money-management and institutional research firm.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &UR; BC-DUTCH-U.S.-FINANCE-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ATLANTA: research firm. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though proposed foreign acquisitions in some U.S. industries,
notably telecommunications, have stirred nationalistic concerns,
there have been no such reverberations yet in the fragmented
financial services business.
</P>
<P>
   To European buyers, U.S. insurance companies, which generally
trade at lower price-to-earnings ratios than their European
counterparts, seem like bargains.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, even with state-by-state regulation of insurance as
well as some aspects of banking in the United States, and even with
the European Union smoothing out the regulatory differences among
its 15 member nations, the Europeans say that doing business in the
United States is easier and less costly than it is in the patchwork
of countries and languages that make up Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, companies that want to be truly global feel
they must have a significant presence in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Another lure is that with more and more Americans responsible
for managing their own retirement with 401(k) plans and the like
rather than traditional pensions, the personal investment business
is booming here far more than it is in Europe, where pensions are
still primarily a governmental obligation.
</P>
<P>
   And like their U.S. counterparts, ING and the other European
insurers doing business in the United States are focusing more on
investing these days than on insurance.
</P>
<P>
   So the Europeans have been steadily picking off U.S. companies.
And many are still on the hunt. But ING, Kist said, is finished
``with our shopping list for now.''
</P>
<P>
   The job at hand, he said, is to fit the pieces of the company's
empire together to maximize economies of scale and to centralize
different lines of business in headquarters around the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The old marble and glass Georgia Life building, for example, set
on the edge of Atlanta deep in a hardwood forest, has been
designated ING's command post not only for the U.S. operations but
for those of Canada and Latin America as well. Des Moines, Iowa, is
to become the center for fixed annuities.
</P>
<P>
   The whole idea of expanding ING's U.S. operations, Kist said,
was so that it would be able to become a low-cost provider. ``You
need to be well priced and you need to have a presence in all the
states,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ING's U.S. competitors have also been consolidating, but so far
banks and insurance have largely remained separate. Banks have been
reluctant to buy insurance companies, experts say, because they
would have to tie up a lot of capital for generally sluggish
returns.
</P>
<P>
   Most insurers cannot afford a bank big enough to give them a
national network of outlets for insurance, and even some that could
pony up the money say they regard banking profits as less
predictable than those from insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The industries, however, have been converging to some extent.
Many banks have contracted with insurers to sell policies through
their branches for a fee. And a handful of insurers have begun
experimenting with banking, mostly aimed at their insurance
customers.
</P>
<P>
   State Farm Mutual Automobile Insurance Co., the biggest U.S.
insurer of cars and homes, has started offering a range of
financial services online and through its agents. But unlike ING,
State Farm is completely new to banking and it concedes that it is
just getting its feet wet.
</P>
<P>
   So is MetLife, one of the biggest life insurers. On Aug. 16
MetLife said that it was buying a small New Jersey bank, Grand
Bank, and that it hoped to start up early next year _ perhaps,
analysts say, with an online operation.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, ING is the company to watch. Brown, the financial
consultant and fund manager, said he expected that many competing
bank executives would open accounts at ING Direct to ``see how it's
going and to be a fast follower if it succeeds.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is among those who see long odds. ``In our experience,''
he said, ``pioneers usually end up with arrows in their back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
