<HEADER>
A2529 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-RELIGION-2NDLD-     08-25 0304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-RELIGION-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN EVANGELISTS ARRESTED IN CHINA RELEASED 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS lede to update with Saturday events and information from
pastor; deletes `nearly 130' from 4th graf, as info now appears in
last graf; deletes last three grafs of original text and subs with
new graf of info. from pastor in Calif.) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Three American evangelists who were detained in
central China on Wednesday along with a large group of Chinese
Christians were released on Friday, their pastor in California
said, and on Saturday they were flying to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Henan province, where the arrests were made, told a
U.S. diplomat that the three U.S. citizens had been detained for
``activities incompatible with the tourist status under which they
entered China,'' the embassy said.
</P>
<P>
   All three Americans were born in Taiwan and belong to a
Protestant church in California that sends members on brief
missions into China to lend moral and financial support to the
so-called house churches. These are fervent Christian groups that
refuse to accept the leadership of the government-sponsored church,
and their members often suffer police harassment and detention.
</P>
<P>
   The three were detained along with Chinese followers of the
China Fangcheng Church, a large Protestant group whose leaders were
sent to labor camps last year.
</P>
<P>
   The pastor in California, who spoke by telephone to his Chinese
colleagues, said about 100 of the detained Chinese were still being
held at a police station or local prison. He did not know if any
would face criminal charges. One Chinese woman was beaten by
police, the pastor said, while another, who was pregnant, was
freed. Several of the other worshipers from the original group of
130 managed to escape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
