<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-FROSH0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech's freshmen should see action
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coach George O'Leary has 10 freshmen on the Georgia
Tech depth chart. The designation allows them to travel with the
varsity and gives them a chance to play during their first year.
</P>
<P>
   This year's freshmen might be the best the Jackets have had. And
there is a good chance that all 10 will see action Sunday at
Virginia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   A look at the young players:
</P>
<P>
   Nate Curry, receiver, Miami. Curry is the second-fastest player
on the team, behind junior flanker Kelly Campbell. Curry has shown
he can catch in practice. He also could see duty on kickoff returns
or punt returns.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Smith, receiver, Clinch County. The Tech coaching staff
thinks it got a steal in Smith. The 5-foot-10, 175-pounder is
athletic and could run a reverse or even throw a pass. Smith also
could help on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul Foschi, tight end, Old Brookville, N.Y. O'Leary always
liked Foschi as a player. At 6-4, 268, Foschi is tough, can block
and catch and is relatively fast. Leon Robinson, offensive guard,
Garden City. Robinson has a broken right hand. The 6-4, 290-pounder
has been a solid performer from the start. ``He's kind of a raw
talent, but he's a fluid kid,'' offensive-line coach Mac McWhorter
said. ``He's as athletic as any I've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnathon Jackson, fullback, Jacksonville. Jackson could play
sooner than expected. Sophomore backup fullback Gary Johnson was
moved to the defensive line, and linebacker Ross Mitchell was moved
to fullback. Jackson has taken the majority of snaps this fall,
with Tech resting Ed Wilder as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Cox, cornerback, Chicago. Cox backs up Jamara Clark and
has perhaps the best chance of seeing action Sunday. Cox is quick,
recovers well and plays the pass and the run.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Green, strong safety, Hyattsville, Md. Green, 6-2, 195,
is playing behind Chris Young but could be used in several roles as
a defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   Hobie Holiday, linebacker, Houston County. The 6-3, 248-pound
linebacker might not wind up as a linebacker. Tech already uses him
in the defensive line in certain situations. Holiday will play
behind Matt Miller, but definitely will play.
</P>
<P>
   Daryl Smith, linebacker, Albany. Smith is the real catch of the
recruiting class. He is playing behind Ather Brown but could be a
starter soon. Smith can play inside and outside and at 6-2, 227, is
the closest thing the Jackets have to a prototypical linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Keyaron Fox, linebacker, Westlake High. Fox is a true outside
linebacker. He has exceptional speed and plays behind Recardo
Wimbush. At 6-2, 210, Fox is quick and agile and will see action
Sunday to try to help contain Virginia Tech quarterback Michael
Vick.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
