<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- JAIN-RELIGION -- Bawa Jain,
a veteran of interfaith activities is the general secretary of the
Millennium World Peace Summit of Religious and Spiritual Leaders
due to begin meeting at the U.N. on Monday. Jain, 44, a native of
India and citizen of the U.S., has traveled widely, asking
prominent people in the worlds of Buddhism, Christianity, Hinduism,
Islam, Judaism and other faiths to attend the summit at which 2,000
people from 90 nations and a wide spectrum of faiths are to begin
spending four days on issues related to peace. (Vincent Laforet/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) SRINAGAR, Kashmir-- Aug. 25, 2000 -- KASHMIR-FEMINIST --
Asiyah Andrabi, conservative Muslim and radical feminist, believes
that women should be heard and not seen, so she makes her demands
for equal rights from behind the black cloth curtain of an
all-enveloping burqa. Andrabi with her eight-month-old son, Ahmad.
(Barry Bearak/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) DALLAS -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- BUSH-3 -- Republican
presidential candidate George W. Bush boards his campaign plane
enroute to Dallas from Miami, Friday. Bush was heading to a meeting
with Mexican President-elect Vicente Fox at the University of Texas
at Dallas. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) DALLAS -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- BUSH-2 -- Republican
presidential candidate George W. Bush, right, meets with Mexican
President-elect Vicente Fox at the University of Texas at Dallas,
Friday. Fox met on Thursday at the White House separately with
President Clinton and with Vice President Al Gore. (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- NY-KRAMDEN-STATUE -- The
Frank Sinatra statue may have caused an uproar, but there's another
one about to be installed in the Times Square area virtually
unnoticed: an eight-foot-tall statue of Jackie Gleason as Ralph
Kramden, in front of the Port Authority Bus Terminal. The cast of
'The Honeymooners' in a 1955 photo from left: Jackie Gleason,
Audrey Meadows, Art Carney and Joyce Randolph - appear in character
as, respectively, Ralph and Alice Kramden and Ed and Trixie Norton,
as shown in this 1955 file photo. (The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- EMBARGOED FOR USE AFTER
SUN., AUG. 27 -- AFRICA-PHOTO-EXHIBIT -- Clinton's brief passage to
Africa this weekend will provide a thousand pictures. Few, perhaps,
will convey the depths of vibrant cultures that have survived war,
disease, the slave trade and the political boundaries and border
disputes that are sometimes the cause of longstanding, often
intractable conflict. Many of these rituals, some performed rarely,
others dying out, have been photographed by Carol Beckwith and
Angela Fisher, who have traveled to the continent separately and
together for 30 years. The photographs are on exhibit at the
Brooklyn Museum of Art through Sept. 17. Visitors to the exhibit
earlier this week. (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) CONCORD, Mass. -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- GLF-PALMER-WOODS-BOS
-- Arnold Palmer, taking part in the PGA FleetBoston Classic which
starts Friday, shows his new driver to Dana Quigley earlier this
week. Palmer has been keeping an eye on Tiger Woods and his
mounting accomplishments on the PGA Tour. ``There's no question he
has surpassed everyone in his ability to play,'' Palmer said about
Woods. (Frank O'Brien/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WALTHAM, Mass. -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS --
In the last few years, you have heard a lot about Antoine Walker,
the Celtics' 24-year-old captain. At times, his own employers talk
about him as if he were Sherman Klump stuffed into basketball
shorts. Lost in the commentary is this: He's smart. And when you're
smart, you know when someone is trying to get rid of you. Walker at
home during a recent interview. (Frank O'Brien/The Boston Globe)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BOSTON -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- BBA-REDSOX-MERLONI-BOS -- For
Lou Merloni, Boston is a long way from Japan. ``I remember going
back to the dugout thinking, 'Hey, this ain't right. It's Feb. 6. I
should be on my couch, watching TV, getting ready from spring
training in two weeks.''' Merloni at Fenway park last Wednesday.
(Jim Davis/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. AUG. 27 --
NITEOUT-JOAN-JETT -- Joan Jett, the goddess of tight-leathered 80's
rock, a devoted fan of the WNBA's New York Liberty. Jett is the
female equivalent to the Liberty of what Jack Nicholson is to the
Los Angeles Lakers, a superfan and courtside fixture whose spirited
cheering seems to bring the home team luck. Jett, courtside during
Game 1 of the WNBA Finals, Thursday at Madison Square Garden.
(Michelle V. Agins/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. AUG. 27 --
SUB-JOURNALISM-CHIC -- Not since Redford and Hoffman played a
better-looking Woodward and Bernstein has the journalism profession
been made to look so cool. As W would have it: Joel Stein of Time,
left, in Hilfiger, Versace and cashmere; Emil Wilbekin of Vibe, in
camel and fur by Lang. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
Retransmitting for photo number
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. AUG. 27 --
GAP-NEWLOOK-2 -- The Gap is hoping to bring back defectors with a
fashion-conscious line of girlish, body-hugging clothes, including
deeply colored leathers. By focusing on leather, a hit for the
chain last fall, and swinging away from the baggy, androgynous
style to a trimmer, snappier silhouette, the store is attempting to
ingratiate itself with a fashion-minded, slightly older and more
sophisticated audience. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. AUG. 27 --
GAP-NEWLOOK-1 -- The Gap is hoping to bring back defectors witha
fashion-conscious line of girlish, body-hugging clothes. The
company has been cautious, however, about how and where to expand
the boundaries of hip. The Gap courts notoriously fickle
teen-agers, but also older consumers looking for stylish clothes to
wear to work, not just on weekends. (Tony Cenicola/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. AUG. 27 --
LOBBY-AROMATHERAPY -- The developers of the The Loft SoHo, Edward
Baquero, left, and Stephen Touhey at the soon to be aromatherapy
enhanced property in Manhattan's SoHo district. In order to subtly
effect the moods of Lenny Kravitz and the East Side socialites who
will be closing on their apartments this fall, the developers
turned to Aveda, the aromatherapy behemoth, to design scents which
will circulate through the lobby through the building's duct
system. (David Corio/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- ARETSKY-PROFILE -- After he
was sentenced two years ago to 200 hours of community service for
selling Cuban cigars in one of his restaurants, a violation of the
U.S. trade embargo against Cuba, Ken Aretsky never anticipated that
he would become so passionate about his court obligation. Aretsky,
standing outside Patroon, one of his restaurants, has continued to
work with high school students in training them for careers in the
restaurant business. (Librado Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- SLUG -- A tourist takes in
the sites of Manhattan from the top deck of a double-decker tour
bus on Times Square, Friday. (Librado Romero/The New York Times)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PALMYRA, Syria -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- SYRIA-PALMYRA-2-COX --
It's more than 1,700 years past its prime. But Palmyra was once the
bustling home to 350,000 people. The figures in swirls are
depictions of veiled women on a relief statue at the Temple of Bel
in Palmyra. (Larry Kaplow/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) DAMASCUS, Syria -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- SYRIA-TRAVEL-2-COX --
As Syria slowly opens to the west, a small but growing number of
Americans are getting to know the exotic city of about 3 million
people. Ornate mosaics adorn the treasury, where money and
valuables used to be stored in the courtyard of the Omayyad Mosque
in Damascus. (Larry Kaplow/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) DAMASCUS, Syria -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- SYRIA-TRAVEL-1-COX --
As Syria slowly opens to the west, a small but growing number of
Americans are getting to know the exotic city of about 3 million
people. The medicinal herb stalls in Damascus' Old City offer
newts, dried plants and a number of parts of assorted animals.
(Larry Kaplow/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PALMYRA, Syria -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- SYRIA-PALMYRA-COX --
It's more than 1,700 years past its prime. But Palmyra was once the
bustling home to 350,000 people. The 12th Century Muslim castle of
Qala'at Ibn Ma'an looks down on the ancient city of Palmyra. (Larry
Kaplow/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) MIAMI -- Aug. 25, 2000 -- BUSH -- George W. Bush, the
Republican presidential candidate, pledged Friday to take a hard
line against Cuban leader Fidel Castro if elected president, and to
breathe new life into U.S.-Latin America trade relations. Bush
listens to an ovation following his introduction at Florida
International University, Friday. (Stephen Crowley/The New York
Times)
</P>
