<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE MINDS; A POSTCONVENTION HIGH; WISHFUL IN WISCONSIN 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  LIKE MINDS
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has found a soul mate, at least in his
views of how government should work. He is Vicente Fox, the
president-elect of Mexico, who is so simpatico with Gore that he
ordered a Spanish translation of a Gore report on reinventing
government. Gore wrote the 150-page report, titled ``From Red Tape
to Results,'' in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, Fox made it required reading for his staff. The
gist of it is that government should be run more like a business,
with attention to customer service and performance agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a former Coca-Cola executive, distilled the report's
message on his business cards. They read, in Spanish, ``To create a
good government that is competitive, transparent, honest,
participatory and proactive, one that works better, costs less and
benefits society.''
</P>
<P>
   A POSTCONVENTION HIGH
</P>
<P>
   For all the soporific effect that this year's party conventions
had on some viewers, it seems they left good feelings in many an
American heart. A poll by the Joan Shorenstein Center on the Press,
Politics and Public Policy at Harvard University found that
opinions of the presidential campaign became much more positive
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Of about 1,000 adults surveyed after the conventions, 50 percent
said they were encouraged by recent campaign events, while only 25
percent said they were discouraged. And 61 percent said they
thought the campaign's tone had recently been positive, while only
17 percent said it had been negative.
</P>
<P>
   All good news for Shorenstein researchers, whose concern about
political apathy and alienation led them to call themselves the
Vanishing Voter Project.
</P>
<P>
   WISHFUL IN WISCONSIN
</P>
<P>
   The leading Republican candidate for the U.S. Senate in
Wisconsin, John Gillespie, has challenged his opponent, Sen. Herb
Kohl, to a campaign spending cap of $4 million, or about $1 per
voter.
</P>
<P>
   Gillespie, a political novice, wants to ``get a handle on
outrageous campaign spending,'' said his campaign manager, Bruce
Pfaff.
</P>
<P>
   Gillespie has two challengers in the Republican primary on Sept.
12, but he is considered the likely nominee. Kohl, the
multimillionaire philanthropist, is unlikely to agree to the cap,
said Joanne Anton, his campaign manager. She said that Kohl, who is
seeking his third term, will spend less than the $6.8 million he
spent in 1994 and will spend the least amount possible to run an
effective campaign.
</P>
<P>
   TODAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   No public appearances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
