<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-GOLDEN-LEAGUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON RETURNS AND WINS TUNEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Some of the world's finest athletes,
including a healthier and humbler Michael Johnson, may have been
running and leaping here Friday night, but in this particular year,
the only city that really matters in track and field is Sydney,
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a summer of dress rehearsals in Europe, the
continent that writes most of the checks and generates most of the
consistent interest in the signature sport of the Olympics, and
this Golden League meet did a better job than most of whetting the
appetite for the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the U.S. Olympic trials in Sacramento,
Calif., Maurice Greene, Michael Johnson and Marion Jones competed
in the same place. The difference this time was that all three
emerged uninjured, if not unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   Greene won the men's 100 meters in 9.88 seconds, which would
have been the fastest legal time this year if not for the fact that
the following wind was a tenth of a meter per second over the
allowable limit. Johnson won the men's 400 in 44.07 seconds in his
first race since he and Greene pulled up with injuries on July 23
and failed to finish the highly anticipated and hotly debated
200-meter final in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   As for Jones, she won the women's 100 in 10.83 seconds, the
second-fastest time this season; it was five-hundredths of a second
slower than her 10.78 in London this month.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones did not fare nearly so well in the long jump, her
second event of the evening, finishing fifth after fouling on four
of her six attempts and jumping no better than 21 feet 7{ inches on
her two fair efforts. Both were well short of the 22-10 effort of
the winner, Tatiana Kotova, a Russian who won the first three
Golden League meets this season before missing the last two because
of minor injuries from an auto accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like I can't get two events in one meet right,'' said
Jones, who will try to get five events right in Sydney, where she
hopes to win gold medals in all of them.
</P>
<P>
   In her last outing, on Aug. 11, Jones won the long jump in
Zurich, Switzerland, after struggling in the 100, getting off to a
rotten start and chasing down Inger Miller to win by a hundredth of
a second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight was just the opposite,'' Jones said, sounding fresh
and eager after nearly two weeks at home in Raleigh, N.C., with her
husband, C.J. Hunter, and her coach, Trevor Graham. ``Here I
thought my 100 was very good, and I jumped so-so. But I'm very
pleased with my start in the 100. That's what I was concerned about
and what we corrected when I went home. That was not Marion in
Zurich. For the past three years, I'm a master of my technique, and
to run a race like that, I don't know what came over me. But Trevor
definitely drilled me when we got home.''
</P>
<P>
   The more daunting task is drilling Jones effectively in the long
jump. Though she has not lost a 100 since 1997, Friday night's loss
was her fourth in the long jump this season, and she is not
scheduled to jump again in competition until the Olympics begin
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Devers has been much more consistent in the 100-meter
hurdles and Friday night she all but clinched a share of the Golden
League jackpot (50 kilograms of gold) by winning in 12.53 seconds.
To earn a share, athletes must win their event in five of the seven
Golden League meets and then compete in the Grand Prix final in
Qatar after the Olympics. Devers, undefeated in the hurdles this
season, has already won five Golden League races; the last is next
week in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Greene also has a chance to win the jackpot. Since returning to
competition in Zurich after his hamstring injury, he has reasserted
himself as the Olympic favorite in the 100.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really putting a lot of pressure on myself to come out
there and run fast,'' Greene said. ``The wind was too much, but who
cares?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
