<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-LIBERTY-COMETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIAR SCENE FOR COMETS, AND HISTORY IS ON THEIR SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  By   LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The scene has shifted back to the familiar stage, with the
principal stars ready again from last year, the year before and the
year before that.
</P>
<P>
   This summer theater brings the promise of suspense, but always,
it seems, leads to an inevitable outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Comets brushed by the Liberty in Game 1 of the WNBA
championship, 59-52, on Thursday night in Madison Square Garden
thanks to their superstars whose timely shots seemed to find the
basket by muscle memory, and whose defense befuddled the home team
all night.
</P>
<P>
   Because the WNBA championship is a best-of-three series, the
Comets can win their fourth consecutive league title on Saturday in
Houston, at the Compaq Center. The Liberty needs to win twice in a
place where the Comets have lost only one playoff game in four
years.
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in those four years, New York arrives in
Houston as the undaunted obstacle. ``We're not going down there to
lose, I can tell you that,'' Liberty guard Becky Hammon said after
Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been the Comets' ever since we opened up in 1997,''
Comets coach Van Chancellor said. ``We are back to Houston. But
just because we go to Houston doesn't mean we win.''
</P>
<P>
   The odds say otherwise. In 1997, New York went to Houston for
the one-game championship with the confidence of having won three
regular-season games against Houston, then promptly lost, 65-51. In
1998, Phoenix was Houston's victim. Last year, the Liberty pushed
the Comets to the limit, Teresa Weatherspoon's improbable halfcourt
shot forcing Game 3, before bowing out again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to believe in the impossible, when no one else
does,'' Weatherspoon said. ``Sure, we're somewhat frustrated
because we didn't get this one at home and didn't play a tremendous
basketball game, didn't put the ball in the basket. But those
things happen and you have to come in and correct it.''
</P>
<P>
   New York needs to correct its shooting first. The Liberty, which
never led in Game 1, lost because it shot 32.1 percent and only
center Tari Phillips scored in double figures. She had the best
individual effort of anyone, including Houston's Cynthia Cooper,
who hit the winning shot. Phillips had a game-high 24 points,
shooting 10 for 19, and pulled down a game-high 15 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   No one else on the Liberty made more than two field goals, going
0 for 8 from 3-point range, struggling to get free off screens.
Tamika Whitmore missed 10 shots from short range.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give them credit for their defense because they are very
athletic and they can challenge shots,'' Liberty coach Richie
Adubato said, ``and we give up four, five inches to each person in
our guard and small forward situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammon hit just one outside shot all night, guarded by Cooper,
who is five inches taller.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty hopes to build on the bright spots in the loss. The
Comets outrebounded the Liberty by only 35-34, while the Liberty
held Houston to 35.5 percent shooting. For the final motivation,
the Liberty can draw upon Weatherspoon's epic shot in last year's
Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets, meanwhile, are fueled by the thought that they can
become the first professional sports team since the NHL's Islanders
(1980-83) to win four straight titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to go out and play for 40 minutes and not make it come
down to a halfcourt shot,'' Swoopes said. ``If we go out and take
care of business in the first half and in the second half, then we
should walk away champions.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
