<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2545 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-SEMINOLES-WEINKE-     08-25 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEMINOLES-WEINKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEMINOLES QUARTERBACK IS EVEN OLDER, BUT BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Shortly after Florida State's football
players assembled to begin their quest for a second straight
unbeaten season, the team doctor was giving his annual speech about
the various viruses that could strike them.
</P>
<P>
   He showed a slide of a player who had lost much of his hair.
Suddenly, many of the players in the room began pointing at Chris
Weinke and chanting, ``Chris! Chris! Chris!''
</P>
<P>
   It was their playful way of having a few laughs at the expense
of Weinke, their 28-year-old quarterback, who has a prominent bald
spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not holding his age well,'' tight end Ryan Sprague said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that word is out that Weinke's high school class in St. Paul
had its 10-year reunion this year, Weinke, Florida State's senior
leader, may face a new wave of jokes about his age. He has been
called Methuselah and Rip Van Weinke by his teammates, but not
often in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've laid down the law,'' said Weinke, who will be back at
quarterback Saturday night when Florida State, ranked No. 2 in the
Associated Press poll of reporters, opens its season at home
against Brigham Young, which was 8-4 last season. ``I don't want to
date myself. For the most part, I don't feel out of place at all.''
</P>
<P>
   He fits most on the football field, where he is a dream come
true for Coach Bobby Bowden, who is 70. Weinke is the first
three-year starter at quarterback in a quarter-century at FSU. With
Weinke surrounded by talented blockers and receivers and
experienced running backs, Bowden says he has a pat hand on
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Weinke comes into this season with a 21-1 record as a starter,
including 20 victories in a row. He holds school records for the
number of 200-yard games passing (20) and yards per completion
(14.8) and is in position to break many of the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's better today than he was last year,'' Bowden said. ``He's
sharper and more accurate with his passes, and there's less
hesitation on where he's going with the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Weinke decided in January that he would return for his
senior season rather than opt for the National Football League
draft, he decided to improve his physical condition dramatically.
Never mind that teammates say he is a millionaire already, mostly
from real estate investments with the money he received from six
seasons as an infielder in the Toronto Blue Jays organization. He
dropped nearly 20 pounds, to 229.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do whatever I could do to be the best that I could
be,'' he said. ``My main focus was getting quicker.'' He will still
be a drop-back passer, mindful of the career-threatening neck
injury he suffered two seasons ago, but he says he will not be an
easy target anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to see me running around,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His offensive line, acutely aware that Weinke's health may well
make a difference in whether the Seminoles repeat as national
champions, has sworn to keep the opposition off of him. Of course,
it helps that Tarlos Thomas, a senior, and Brett Williams, a
sophomore, are pro-caliber tackles and that the senior guards
Justin Amman and Jerry Carmichael have extensive starting
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal this year is not to give up any sacks,'' Thomas said.
``I mean we don't want his jersey dirty, unless we're patting him
on the back after a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinke was never close to leaving FSU for the NFL, he says now.
For one thing, some pro scouts projected him as a third-round pick,
at best. For another, he knew the Seminoles were loaded for another
title run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could sit on the bench and make the minimum of whatever
they're paying up there,'' he said, ``and I'd be watching Florida
State on TV every Saturday, knowing I could be a part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5-inch Weinke shrugs off talk about his Heisman
Trophy candidacy, which figures to blossom if FSU picks up where it
left off last season, when it capped a 12-0 season with a 46-29
victory over Virginia Tech in the Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not here to win any awards,'' he said. ``I'm not here to
do anything but win a national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the next breath, some ego does surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to realize that I came back for a reason: to
be the most dominating quarterback who has ever played here,'' he
said. ``I think I can do that, because I know what it takes to get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, Weinke will not have his favorite receiver, Peter
Warrick, who has gone to the pros. While Bowden says that because
of Warrick's distinctive explosive moves, the next version of him
``is probably down in elementary school somewhere; about every 10
years you see one like him,'' Weinke believes the Seminoles are
loaded with talented receivers.
</P>
<P>
   He points out that in the two games Warrick missed last season,
against Miami and Wake Forest, he completed passes to 11 and 10
receivers, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one big reason I came back,'' he said. ``I know what
kind of ability these guys have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
