<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CLASSIC-PREVIEW0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    QBs can expect quick hooks
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kentucky coach Hal Mumme calls himself a
``one-quarterback coach.'' For that reason, the SEC's top passer
from a year ago is playing at a Division II school this season.
</P>
<P>
   For several Southeastern Conference teams, however, two
quarterbacks won't be a crowd in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama, the defending SEC champion, will start quarterback
Andrew Zow in Saturday's opener at UCLA. However, Crimson Tide
coach Mike DuBose said sophomore Tyler Watts also will play a
couple of series against the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   At Florida, Steve Spurrier is expected to start senior Jesse
Palmer, but the Gators coach won't have much patience if the
Canadian struggles. Redshirt freshman Rex Grossman and freshman
Brock Berlin, who enrolled in Florida during the spring, had
contended for the job until Palmer pulled away in preseason camp.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback battles in Tuscaloosa and Gainesville could help
decide the SEC. If the Crimson Tide and Gators get consistent play
under center and avoid quarterback controversies, the teams should
be near the top of their divisions.
</P>
<P>
   LSU still hasn't settled on a starter, and South Carolina's
competition isn't over, either.
</P>
<P>
   A closer look:
</P>
<P>
   Alabama: DuBose finally named Zow the starter last week. Zow, a
junior from Lake Butler, Fla., was clearly the better quarterback
in camp, but DuBose faced tremendous pressure to start Watts, who
was a star at Pelham (Ala.) High School.
</P>
<P>
   DuBose said Watts would get at least one series in each half
against UCLA. Zow has a stronger arm than Watts. Watts is more
mobile and is an accurate passer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Zow) is having an off day, I will go to the second
quarterback,'' DuBose said. ``But that's not a demotion. That's
simply trying to help the football team and would not be indicative
of who would be the starter the following week.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida: Palmer, who completed only 46 percent of his passes
last season with five interceptions and two touchdowns, is the
favorite to replace Doug Johnson, who graduated.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer won the job in camp, but Spurrier is worried about his
ability to play well in games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't just go all out and say he's our guy because his
history is he doesn't have a track record,'' Spurrier said. ``I
wish he had a track record of going the distance about five weeks
in a row. Now don't get me wrong, I think he's very capable. I
think he can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Palmer does the job, then the Gators might redshirt Berlin,
USA Today's Louisiana player of the year last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
