</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRILOGY0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ford, Trilogy to put dealers online
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Austin's Trilogy Software Corp. and Ford Motor
Co. will expand their efforts to make Ford a leader in Internet
auto sales with an online program that allows consumers to select,
price and order a car directly from dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   FordDirect.com, a new business formed by more than 4,000 Ford
dealers and the No. 2 U.S. automaker, will launch next month in
California, the company and dealers announced Friday. It is a
linchpin of Ford's long-term strategy to get most of its revenue
from the Internet while capitalizing on the efficiencies of online
sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big endorsement for e-commerce,'' said Joe Liemandt,
Trilogy's Chief Executive Officer.
</P>
<P>
   FordDirect.com, which will be owned and operated primarily by
the dealers, could swiftly become one of the largest online
startups, based on Ford's revenue of $162 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is not expected to affect Texas dealers any time
soon because of uncertainty over state restrictions on Internet
sales of new cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is way down on the list, because they (Ford's dealers)
feel it's going to be much more difficult to comply fully with what
the state asks us to,'' said Chris Porch, chief executive of Ford
Trilogy Joint Venture.
</P>
<P>
   That business, which employs about 150 people in Austin, was
launched earlier this year to strengthen Ford.com and enable Ford
dealerships to do business on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   FordDirect.com takes that further.
</P>
<P>
   The site will provide about five dealers in the ZIP code of the
car buyer and provide maps and the distance to each.
</P>
<P>
   Each dealer's entire inventory will be available for browsing,
and prices, which dealer sites don't offer now, will be available,
Ford officials said. In addition, the database will include
vehicles en route from the factories, Porch said.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers will be able to configure the options they want and
will see the closest matches to their choice. They'll also be able
to put a down payment on their credit card and arrange financing
from Ford Credit Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The changing times call for a change in procedures,'' said
Jerry Reynolds, chairman of the dealer group that approached Ford
about the venture months ago to give consumers ``the convenience,
trust and value they are looking for in online transactions.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim O'Connor, president of the Ford division of Ford Motor Co.,
called the venture ``nothing other than a true breakthrough'' in
giving consumers online ``confidence and peace of mind, knowing
that the entire experience is backed by Ford and our dealer
partners.''
</P>
<P>
   Dealers will pay $25 for every referral they get from
FordDirect.com, and $200 for what Chris Markey, Internet director
of Covert Ford, called ``shrink-wrap deals.''
</P>
<P>
   In those cases, customers will have chosen a car from the
dealer's lot, put a down payment on a credit card and financed the
purchase through Ford Credit. All the dealer has to do is get the
purchase agreements signed and deliver the car.
</P>
<P>
   Markey said Covert sells about 120 cars a month, 12 percent to
15 percent of its volume, over the Internet now. Covert is among
the top 15 Ford dealerships in the country, Markey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting 1,200 requests (for information) a month. We're
hoping FordDirect will add 100 to 200 a month.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement gives Trilogy a respite from recent
disappointments in several of the online businesses it has launched
in recent years, including carOrder.com. One of many online car
brokers, carOrder.com laid off 100 employees last week, admitting
it couldn't make money brokering autos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look for the demise of these lead-providing services in the
next five years, because customers are going to be bypassing them
and going directly to the dealers,'' Markey predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Trilogy's Porch said lessons learned at carOrder.com will
help it build the FordDirect.com sites for dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
