<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2548 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-NEBRASKA0826-COX     08-25 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NEBRASKA0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cornhuskers are ready to roll
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. _ In January, Eric Crouch kept squirming in his
seat while watching the Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was painful. Very painful,'' the Nebraska quarterback said.
``I just kept thinking, 'Man, that could be us.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was undefeated Florida State and Virginia Tech
playing in New Orleans for the national championship. The
Cornhuskers finished 12-1 and ranked No. 3 last season because of a
24-20 upset loss to Texas on Oct. 23. Nebraska later avenged that
loss by beating the Longhorns 22-6 in the Big 12 championship game,
but it wasn't enough to get the Cornhuskers into the Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the year, a lot of people thought we were the
best team in the country,'' wingback Bobby Newcombe said. ``I
didn't argue with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of Nebraska's strong finish, which included a 31-21 win
over Tennessee in the Fiesta Bowl in a game that wasn't that close,
the Cornhuskers are a consensus No. 1 in the major preseason polls.
They are a strong favorite to be playing for this season's national
title on Jan. 3 in the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   If such high expectations are a burden, Nebraska is bearing it
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team did finish strongly and there is a possibility that
this could be a great football team,'' said third-year coach Frank
Solich, now solidly entrenched after taking over for Tom Osborne in
1998. ``There's a lot of football to be played, but if we reach our
potential, I'm excited about where that might lead us.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska is a logical pick because of the way the team evolved
since early in the 1999 season. The offense could not hold on to
the ball. By the third game, Solich replaced Newcombe at
quarterback with Crouch and the offense started to settle down.
Nebraska still fumbled too many times _ 49 in all, with 25 lost _
but rolled over opponents like the Cornhuskers of old.
</P>
<P>
   Crouch, who has added 10 pounds of muscle and will play at 205,
ran for 889 yards and became the first quarterback since 1955 to
lead Nebraska in rushing. Fully recovered from offseason shoulder
surgery, Crouch should be even better in 2000. He will direct an
offense that returns 10 starters and led the Big 12 in rushing with
265.9 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this offense has a chance to be really good,'' said
Crouch, who was the Big 12 co-offensive player of the year with
Texas quarterback Major Applewhite. ``We're so much more
comfortable with one another than we were at this time a year
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing missing from the Nebraska offense is a big-time
I-back, which has always been a staple of Cornhusker football. A
year ago Solich kicked his best I-back off the team, the
disgruntled DeAngelo Evans. Talent returns in Dan Alexander (865
yards) and Correll Buckhalter (662), and junior-college transfer
Thunder Collins ran for 1,548 yards and 23 touchdowns two years ago
at East Los Angeles Junior College.
</P>
<P>
   But the defense is not as set, which is why the Cornhuskers are
not a cinch to make it to Miami. They will miss the Browns, Mike
and Ralph, who gave Nebraska one of the most talented secondaries
in the country. New players also will fill four of the seven
positions up front.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska also has to replace Charlie McBride, its longtime
defensive coordinator. Craig Bohl, the former linebackers coach,
has the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't be Charlie McBride, but I can continue to implement
his philosophy,'' said Bohl, who played for Nebraska 1977-79. ``At
Nebraska, when one guy leaves somebody is supposed to be ready to
step up to the plate. That goes for players and coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At Nebraska, the defense should never be the weakness of the
team,'' said linebacker Carlos Polk.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska should be 9-0 when it goes to No. 9 Kansas State on
Nov. 11. On Sept. 9, the Cornhuskers go to Notre Dame, which could
be very embarrassing for the Irish. Nebraska goes to Oklahoma on
Oct. 28, but the improving Sooners still aren't ready for that kind
of challenge.
</P>
<P>
   If Nebraska wins in Manhattan, Kan., where it lost two years
ago, it should finish 11-0 and meet Texas again for the Big 12
title. And if the Cornhuskers win all of their games, they won't be
on the outside looking in at the national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``How good can this team be?'' Newcombe asked. ``As good as it
wants to be. If we're willing to work for it, the sky's the limit.
I really believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   NEBRASKA
</P>
<P>
   Location: Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment: 25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Frank Solich, 21-5 in three years at Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium: Memorial (74,031).
</P>
<P>
   All-time record: 743-297-40.
</P>
<P>
   Big 12 championships: Two _ 1997, 1999); Big Eight championships
_ 20.
</P>
<P>
   1999 record: 12-1, 7-1 Big 12 North (1st); beat Texas 22-6 in
Big 12 Championship game; beat Tennessee 31-21 in Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule: Sept. 2 vs. San Jose State; Sept. 9 at Notre Dame;
Sept. 23 vs. Iowa; Sept. 30 vs. Missouri; Oct. 7 at Iowa State;
Oct. 14 at Texas Tech; Oct. 21 vs. Baylor; Oct. 28 at Oklahoma;
Nov. 4 vs. Kansas; Nov. 11 at Kansas State; Nov. 24 vs. Colorado.
</P>
