<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MAYOR-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI MAY FILE SUIT AGAINST ANIMAL GROUP OVER ADS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Wis., Pa., Va.)   By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Angry over the use of his face on billboard
advertising as far away as Oshkosh, Wis., Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
repeated a threat to file suit against an animal rights group that
is trying to publicize a possible link between milk consumption and
various illnesses, including prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ad is tasteless,'' Giuliani said at a news conference on
Friday, adding that he would decide over the weekend whether to sue
the group, People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, which is
based in Norfolk, Va. ``My illness is a very public matter, which I
am fine with, but I don't like people exploiting it, either.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's threat of legal action, which he made initially in
comments to reporters on Thursday night, did not appear to have
deterred the animal rights group, which said it would put up more
of the billboards.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute centers on ads that the group, known as PETA, has
posted this week in three cities in milk-producing areas _
Lancaster, Pa., and Oshkosh and Appleton in central Wisconsin. The
ads parody the ubiquitous ``Got Milk?'' campaign sponsored by the
dairy industry, and are dominated by what appears to be an oversize
mug shot of Giuliani with a band of white _ intended to look like
milk _ above his upper lip.
</P>
<P>
   A brief text reads ``Got prostate cancer?'' Below that phrase,
it asserts, ``Drinking milk contributes to prostate cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   PETA, known for its strident tactics in promoting animal rights,
said the ad was intended to protest the dairy industry, not
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Friedrich, the group's vegetarian-campaign coordinator,
said on Friday that PETA hoped the ad would draw attention to
studies that have raised the possibility of a link between dairy
consumption and several types of serious illnesses, and to what he
called the hypocrisy of the dairy industry in promoting the health
benefits of milk.
</P>
<P>
   Although scientists are uncertain about the exact cause of
prostate cancer, according to the American Cancer Society, there is
an increased risk of the disease associated with eating animal fat,
red meats and dairy products.
</P>
<P>
   Friedrich would not say how many more billboards would be
erected, or where. But it seemed unlikely that the ads would find
their way to New York City, since PETA said it had already been
rejected by several companies that post ads on billboards, in
subways and on taxis in the city.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the advertising agency in Wisconsin that put up the
two billboards there said they would be taken down. Wisconsin farm
leaders attacked the ads as misleading and insensitive.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who has declined to specify which treatment he is
undergoing for his prostate cancer, has reacted to the ads by
keeping a glass of milk at his side in public appearances and by
making repeated references to drinking milk. At a town hall meeting
at the Norman Thomas High School on East 33rd Street in Manhattan,
he turned from the podium several times to drink a glass of milk
and to refill it from a half-gallon carton. And on his weekly radio
call-in show, he broke away for a commercial by telling the
program's listeners he would ``take a short glass of milk and come
back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
