<SLUG> BC-CAR-BRISTOL-PROFILE0826-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small track, big thrills
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - The largest crowd to assemble for a sports event this
weekend will be at Bristol Motor Speedway for tonight's
Goracing.com 500.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150,000 are expected to gather around the half-mile
oval track to see one of the most exciting Winston Cup races of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Season-ticket holders from 50 states and seven countries make
the annual pilgrimage to the foothills of the Appalachian Mountains
each August. Rusty Wallace, who has won nine times at Bristol, said
it is easy to understand the popularity of the legendary night
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most exciting race out there,'' said Wallace,
tonight's pole sitter. ``Since it's the most exciting, everybody
wants to go to it. The track is small, compact and full of drama.
There are a lot of exciting places around (NASCAR), but nothing
like this place.''
</P>
<P>
   But the track, now owned by Speedway Motorsports Inc., was not
always Winston Cup's hot spot.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Clark, the president and general manager of Atlanta Motor
Speedway, worked in public relations at Bristol from 1977-82. He
said a big turnaround in the track's history was when lights were
installed during his first year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
