<SLUG> BC-TEN-OPEN-QUALIFY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAUFFMANN MOVES CLOSER TO MAIN DRAW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ky . , Ind.)  By RON DICKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cedric Kauffmann was a long shot to compete in this
week's U.S. Open qualifying. Now he is on the verge of making the
main draw. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kauffmann, who is from a suburb of Paris, is No. 312 in the ATP
rankings. With little chance of playing at all, he flew to New York
as the second alternate for the qualifying rounds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the first alternate, Karsten Braasch, reported 15 minutes
late to Monday's sign-in, so Kauffmann replaced him. On Tuesday,
Gregory Carraz pulled out of the competition with an injury,
allowing Kauffmann into the bracket. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old Kauffmann has pounced on the opportunity. In the
first round he defeated Marcos Ondruska, once ranked 26th, in
straight sets. Friday he beat another tour veteran, Marc-Kevin
Goellner, 7-6 (4), 7-5. To get into the main draw, which begins
Monday, Kauffmann must defeat the journeyman Mark Knowles on
Saturday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably be nervous in the warm-up, but after that I'll
be fine,'' said Kauffmann, a baseline specialist with quick feet.
``I have nothing to lose. I got very, very lucky. This is a chance
of a lifetime.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kauffmann has made $7,500 for reaching the final qualifying
round, nearly twice as much as his prize money total for the year.
He plays mostly in entry-level professional tournaments called
Futures. In his last Futures event, he earned $117 for losing in
the first round. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staying at a friend's apartment in Brooklyn, Kauffmann takes the
subway to the National Tennis Center in Flushing Meadows-Corona
Park, in Queens. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kauffmann, who earned a finance degree at the University of
Kentucky, is not banking on an athletic career. Every day he stops
at a Kinko's near Grand Central Terminal to check his stocks on the
Internet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll make more money in finance than I ever will in tennis,''
he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vinck Qualifies  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Christian Vinck of Germany is the only player to beat Andre
Agassi in Agassi's hometown of Las Vegas. Vinck, who accomplished
that feat at a minor tournament in 1997, updated his resume Friday
by qualifying for the Open with a 6-1, 6-2 third-round victory over
James Sekulov.
</P>
<P>
   Olympians Fare Well  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Olympians in the Sydney Games had a good day Friday. Sebastien
Lareau of Canada earned a spot in the Open's main draw by defeating
Hugo Armando, 6-4, 6-3. Alex O'Brien, a doubles specialist, is a
victory away from qualifying for singles after he beat Michael
Kohlmann, 7-6, 6-3. Other second-round winners in the men's bracket
were Wayne Black of Zimbabwe and Barry Cowan of Britain. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the women's side, Petra Mandula will have a chance at the
main draw before she represents Hungary in the Games. Mandula
defeated Anca Barna of Germany, 2-6, 7-5, 6-0. Janet Lee, who was
born in Lafayette, Ind., but will represent Taiwan in the Olympics,
needed three sets to beat Anna Zarska of Poland, 6-0, 3-6, 6-0. Lee
must win her match on Saturday to make the Open. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lucic Coming Back  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mirjana Lucic took another step toward rebuilding her career by
winning her third straight match to qualify for the main draw.
Lucic, whose WTA ranking has plummeted 202nd from 32nd, dropped the
first set to Sandra Nacuk and was down 2-0 in the second before
rebounding for a 4-6, 6-3, 6-3 victory. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Motivated to Win  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Declaring that he would rather qualify as a winner than a lucky
loser, Israel's Harel Levy trounced Rodolphe Cadart, 6-1, 6-0. As
the top-ranked qualifier, Levy was already assured of a spot in the
main draw. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
