<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURFING- </SLUG>
  
SURFING THE NET:  TECH-WARY BOARD RIDERS FIND THE WEB ISN'T ALL WET &HT;      By GREG AMBROSE
 &HT;    c.2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Dr. Mark Renneker is no technophobe. He's just
angry that technology has sullied the purity of the sport he loves:
surfing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate how surfers are allowing themselves to be enslaved by
being spoon fed by the Internet services,'' Renneker said.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, when a record heat wave one week made conditions
hellish for the staff and patients at San Francisco General
Hospital, Renneker planned a last-minute surf getaway by
downloading a weather map packed with arcane meteorological icons
and lines.
</P>
<P>
   After expertly analyzing the data, Renneker then jumped on a
flight to Alaska, where he and a friend surfed fun waves under the
midnight sun. He made it back to the hospital before his next
shift.
</P>
<P>
   In an irony not lost on many surfers, people who disdain the
metaphor ``surfing the Net'' as demeaning to their sport are
increasingly turning to the Web to help them find waves.
</P>
<P>
   This shifting tide has online surf sites ramping up staffs and
utilizing the latest in technology _ from Webcams to satellite
imagery to real-time ocean buoy wave reports _ in the hopes of
pocketing a piece of the $2 billion surfing industry.
</P>
<P>
   The two most advanced surf sites, San Francisco startups
Swell.com and Hardcloud.com, are battling for the attention of
reluctant Net &LR;   &LR; surfers like Renneker, who are juggling the demands
of career and family as they continue to pursue their passion for
wave riding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our philosophy is, where people spend their time is where they
will spend their money,'' says Hardcloud.com Editor Jim Kempton,
who found the perfect lure to steer traffic to Hardcloud by
purchasing Surfcheck, an Internet surf-forecasting site.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kempton, Hardcloud.com, with an office in San
Francisco's Mission District, wants to provide a global village
that quickly and easily connects the scattered surfing tribes with
information about other surfers, events and surf destinations
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Launched in February with $6.5 million in venture capital,
Hardcloud's editorial staff is paying itself miserly wages by
dot-com standards. But the online surf magazine is nurturing its
cash until the real moneymaker begins to pay off: the Internet surf
shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sustainability is the big mantra in the editorial offices
here,'' said Kempton, who is counting on sponsorships with the
print media and other companies as well as e-commerce to eventually
pay the bills and turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that if we capture the volume of the 10 best shops,
we're going to make it,'' says Kempton, whose company scored a coup
in a musical alliance with MP3.com. ``We'll be bigger than most of
the shops in the industry and able to market to thousands of people
who aren't able to get to a surf shop now.''
</P>
<P>
   Swell.com, located in San Francisco's Richmond District, is also
working toward becoming a one-stop shop to fill surfers' needs for
information, entertainment, surf clothing and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   AN EYE ON THE COMPETITION
</P>
<P>
   In fact, both sites are closely matching each other's moves.
</P>
<P>
   Both startups have been cruising the virtual waters like
ravenous great white sharks, devouring smaller surf Web sites and
print media surfing editors and writers in an effort to become the
apex predator in the online ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Swell.com is spending its $15 million in venture capital raiding
the offices of print media surf magazines in the Media Valley of
San Clemente (Orange County), heart of the surf industry and where
both startups have offices. Hardcloud's Kempton, a former editor of
Surfer magazine, also has recruited photographers, editors and
writers, leaving the print surf media scrambling for replacements
in a field where experienced workers are scarce.
</P>
<P>
   Both startups are also keeping a wary eye on extreme-sports
sites Bluetorch and EXPN, which focus on streaming videos of
surfing competition and travel adventures.
</P>
<P>
   Hardcloud got its rival's attention by acquiring Surfcheck,
which uses 100 spotters around the world to report on surf
conditions at top beaches, augmented by 125 strategically placed
cameras that let surfers view real-time waves from California to
South Africa and prime surf spots in between. Additionally, trained
meteorologists' long-range forecasts of significant swells help
fuel surfers' exotic travel dreams and provide practical local
information.
</P>
<P>
   Swell immediately bested Hardcloud by acquiring Surfline, the
father of all surf-forecasting sites.
</P>
<P>
   Surfline provides computer programs and data that allow people
to do their own forecasts, but not everyone is willing to invest
the necessary time. ``Most people just want us to tell them what
the waves are going to be like, and we do that for them,'' said
Sean Collins, Surfline's founder, who took surf forecasting out of
the dark ages by adapting government meteorological data and
tailoring it toward surfers' needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every surfer is a surf forecaster, always looking at wind,
tides, swell, doing the calculations in their head,'' Collins
added. ``We're just carrying it a little bit further for them.''
</P>
<P>
   With Surfline's subscription fax system, which contains detailed
reports and toll-call services that provide the same daily reports
and long-term forecasts, surfers are able to keep working until
they see a swell predicted a week in advance, take some vacation
time and head to Mexico or Costa Rica for the swell's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring Surfline had an immediate benefit for Swell. Many of
the 5 million people who access Surfline's faxes and who make 1
million toll calls yearly now swarm to Swell.com for free online
reports and forecasts. Additionally, Surfline now offers Surf
Alert, which e-mails surfers when a good swell is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR'S DUTY
</P>
<P>
   In Half Moon Bay, it is crucial that Jeff Clark has the
most-precise weather information available each winter when he runs
the Men Who Ride Mountains surfing contest at Mavericks, the
treacherous surf spot off Pillar Point.
</P>
<P>
   As the contest director, it is his job to alert a special group
of surfers from Australia, Hawaii and throughout California to grab
a plane for the day that the waves will be epic for the surf
contest. Clark relies on his own years of experience interpreting
conditions that he can see in the ocean near his home, as well as
storms thousands of miles away visible on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Clark also seeks input from Mark Sponsler of StormSurf, whose
incredibly detailed and sophisticated reports Clark shares with
other surfers on his Web site, www.maverickssurf.com.
</P>
<P>
   With such expertise for the surfing masses to tap into,
forewarned surfers swarm the coast well before most swells actually
arrive.
</P>
<P>
   While appreciating Sponsler's input and accurate forecasts,
Clark is pleased that many smaller swells slip under StormSurf's
radar screen. ``I'm a firm believer that the guy who gets up early
and checks out the ocean deserves to be the only guy out,'' Clark
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, what the satellites say and what I see hitting the
shore are different. Nothing beats experience, and knowing what you
are looking at,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   SHOCK OF THE NEW
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult task for the surf Web sites is convincing the
purists to embrace the new technology.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Bay Area wave riders, former Surfer magazine editor
Matt Warshaw is tormented by his relationship with the Internet.
Warshaw likes to keep his search for surf low-tech as an antidote
to the high-tech nature of just about everything in the Bay Area,
but his link to Swell complicates his quest for simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   Warshaw, the author of the surfing world's first encyclopedia,
is the online librarian for Swell, letting its writers use his
extensive computerized database of surfing literature that reaches
back to the early 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   With great difficulty, Warshaw has refrained from using Swell's
online surf-forecast services, preferring to find waves through
traditional methods. ``I made sure I live near the beach with a
good view of the surf, and look at it in the morning and plan my
day,'' said the Sunset District resident.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then, I'm still single and can afford to live where I
want. If I suddenly had a family and lived 20 miles inland, I'd
probably log on to the beach cameras.''
</P>
<P>
   FEWER PHONE CALLS
</P>
<P>
   For years, Warshaw has been deluged by calls from friends asking
about the surf conditions. But these days, the calls come less
often as more of his friends surf the Internet to find out about
the waves. Technology also has intruded on his quietly satisfying
morning surf-check ritual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't feel good to stand on the bluff at Taraval Street
with two surf cameras aimed at you,'' Warshaw said. ``It feels like
you're at the 7-Eleven, or in a prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Renneker, the San Francisco physician, has spent years teaching
himself the intricacies of surf forecasting, learning to decipher
isobars, barometric pressure, wind gradients, fetch and other
elements essential for understanding how waves are created. He
makes deft use of modern technology in his search for waves, and
yet he is no friend of the technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find the increased access to information about weather and
swell forecasting to really run against the grain of the nature of
surfing,'' Renneker said. ``By that I mean the surprise, the
wonderment of getting out and finding the surf yourself, the
adventure and thrill of discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   EMPIRICAL KNOWLEDGE
</P>
<P>
   Renneker points out that before technology allowed surfers to
peer into the heart of storms to determine when and where the
wind-born waves would arrive, surfers roamed the coast by car,
searching for surf. And along the way they gained knowledge of how
the swells, winds and tides interact differently at each surf spot
to produce good waves.
</P>
<P>
   ``That knowledge is being lost among surfers,'' Renneker said.
``The new technology also creates disappointment more often than
happiness. If a swell is forecast and you have a picture of it in
your mind, if it isn't what you expect, then you have scorn for
what you find.''
</P>
<P>
   SurfFax creator Steve Decile is amused by his longtime
collaborator's disdain for high tech. ``Doc pooh-poohs the
technology, but I send him eight pages a day of material I get off
the Internet and he uses it for his own surf forecasts.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Decile, he still finds wonderment in his relationship
with the ocean, even though technology has stripped away much of
the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Driving down the street, I'll see a swell and say to my wife,
`Look at that, that is from a storm 11 days ago off New Zealand and
I predicted the waves.' I still can't get over that after all these
years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
