<SLUG> BC-SURFSIDE-SURFSIDE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
AVAILABILITY OF METEOROLOGICAL DATA ONLINE CAN BE A DOUBLE-EDGED
SWORD &HT;    By GREG AMBROSE
 &HT;    c.2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Rapid advances in technology can create growth
opportunities for some surf-forecasting companies while leaving
others high and dry.
</P>
<P>
   The availability of meteorological data online has been a
blessing and a curse to SurfFax founder Steve Decile, who has
attracted enough paid subscribers to turn his hobby into a
full-time job.
</P>
<P>
   Faxing was high tech nearly a decade ago, when the Santa Barbara
surfer decided that surf reports delivered over the telephone were
too difficult to remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought you could give more information on paper and save
the paper and use it as a journal,'' Decile said. ``It makes an
excellent reference library.''
</P>
<P>
   So Decile became a student of meteorology with an emphasis on
surf forecasting, and working out of his home by computer he
created SurfFax. He shared each of his hard-learned meteorological
lessons with his subscribers, using humor and insight to teach them
how to become their own surf forecasters.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of subscribers across the Pacific have come to rely on
the detailed SurfFax reports and weather charts that forecast
swells and describe wave conditions. One of the customers he is
most proud of is the Army Corps of Engineers, which uses his faxes
to help with its coastal projects.
</P>
<P>
   But high technology is constantly being surpassed by higher
technology, and the same online data that have made Decile's
forecasting work easier have resulted in companies like
Hardcloud.com and Swell.com being able to lure his customers away
for a free ride on their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mark Sponsler wouldn't mind growing rich through his
devotion to high technology, but the creator of StormSurf is too
busy enjoying the ride. Advertising barely pays to keep his site
operating, which is OK with Sponsler, who enjoys comparing ideas
and knowledge with others who share his passion for surf
forecasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to make a living off of it,'' he says. ``We
could dummy it down a lot and widen our audience, but our focus is
for expert-level surfers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sponsler sees broadband Internet access as the wave of surfing's
forecasting future, with cable modems and DSL enabling people to
make full use of the incredible amount of weather data available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without that, you're back in the Stone Age,'' says Sponsler.
His observations show that people are hitting his site during
working hours Monday through Friday, which tells him they are at
work using machines with high-speed Net connections. That allows
them to easily access graphics from the government-sponsored
QuikSat satellite program that displays wind speed and wind
direction across 95 percent of the ocean's surface every day, a
technology only recently made available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look right into storms as they are forming, see how
big the fetch (the distance that the wind blows across the ocean,
which creates waves) is and confirm what wave models suspect is
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   StormSurf.com is a serious site geared toward experienced
surfers with a desire to learn more about meteorology. The free
site examines significant storms in the Pacific and forecasts the
surf they will generate. The site also provides an in-depth series
of links and tools to allow surfers to expand their knowledge and
even take information from the center of storm, plug it into a
Java-based program and see exactly when the swell will arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, we used to waste a lot of time driving around
looking for waves. Now you can have it all scoped out before you
leave home,'' Sponsler says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd that surfs Mavericks (in Half Moon Bay) are ocean
engineers, lawyers, doctors, environmental scientists, very
successful in their professions. Forecasting helps people narrow
that target to make maximum use of the precious surf time they
have, and then spend more time doing meaningful things with other
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
