<SLUG> BC-ORACLE-ORACLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
ORACLE TO OFFER FREE SALES SOFTWARE &HT;    By KELLY ZITO
 &HT;    c.2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a direct swipe at market leader Siebel
Systems, Oracle Corp. next week will begin giving away software
over the Internet that is designed to manage sales data.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the world's No. 2 software company will officially
launch OracleSalesOnline.com. Instead of installing software from
CDs, salespeople will be able to manage contact information,
scheduling and sales forecasts through the site using a Web
browser. The software, called ``sales-force automation,'' resides
on Oracle servers.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time the Redwood Shores company is making its
software available online for free, according to Lisa Arthur,
Oracle's vice president of e-business marketing. The company
specializes in developing software that stores and manages vast
amounts of corporate data.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a watershed event in sales-force automation,'' Arthur
said. ``It gives people a way to get into e-business quickly at no
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the company is up-front about the money-making strategy
behind the tactic _ Oracle hopes to sell additional sales and
marketing software as well as consulting services to the users of
OracleSalesOnline _ it doesn't mention the venture's other goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fully featured product directly aimed at Siebel, the
company which clearly leads the market,'' wrote Lehman Bros.
analyst Neil Herman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oracle is giving away the first dose for free and then
charging once you're addicted to the results,'' Herman wrote.
</P>
<P>
   One competitor said such a ``Trojan Horse'' strategy will likely
alienate potential Oracle customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to make money by selling add-ons and services,''
said Keith Raffel, founder of Mountain View's UpShot.com, which
offers sales-automation software for $55 per month per user. ``With
us, it's what you see is what you get. We don't have hidden
charges.''
</P>
<P>
   San Mateo's Siebel Systems, the No. 1 maker of so-called
customer-relationship management software, also took the
announcement in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been working on this for five years and they have less
than 1 percent market share,'' Siebel chief executive Tom Siebel
told Bloomberg News this week. ``So the fact that they have another
product that they're shipping for free is no news.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Oracle has ``little presence'' in the sales-force
automation market, Herman wrote. And free software may do little to
change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, there is some risk in this strategy, as sophisticated
buyers typically associate free software with lower quality or lack
of depth and breadth of functionality,'' Herman wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle said the software code is exactly the same as the one a
customer would receive on a traditional CD.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Oracle said 300 companies are using OracleSalesOnline,
including NetLedger, a San Mateo online accounting firm, Enterprise
Rental Car and GE Medical Systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 2239EDT &QL; 
