<HEADLINE>
VENUS WILLIAMS AND SELES SET FOR NEW HAVEN SHOWDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ Monica Seles, still trying to regain the form
that made her one of the dominant women's players in the early
1990s, and Venus Williams, the reigning Wimbledon champion, won
Friday to set up a showdown between the top two seeded players in
Saturday's final of the Pilot Pen tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The second-seeded Seles, the winner of nine Grand Slam titles
but none since 1996, recovered to beat the veteran Nathalie
Tauziat, 2-6, 6-2, 6-1, Friday afternoon at the Connecticut Tennis
Center. On Friday night, the top-seeded Williams, who has won her
last three tournaments and 18 matches in a row, defeated Amanda
Coetzer, the fifth-seeded player, 6-3, 6-4, in the second
semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has beaten the 26-year-old Seles in all three of their
previous meetings, including a final two weeks ago in San Diego,
when Williams was extended to three sets before defeating Seles,
6-0, 6-7 (3), 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 feet 2 inches and 120 pounds, the 28-year-old Coetzer gave
away 11 inches and 40 pounds to Williams. And where Williams is a
power hitter, Coetzer is a counterpuncher whose only chance Friday
night, she conceded before the match, was to induce errors. She did
that, since Williams committed 26 unforced errors. But Williams
compensated for those errors with 26 winners, two aces and about a
dozen service winners.
</P>
<P>
   Coetzer took a 3-2 lead in the first set on a service break in
the fifth game. But she could never break Williams' serve again and
was broken three times under Williams' withering ground-stroke
assault.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old Tauziat had never won a set from Seles in nine
previous meetings on clay, grass, hard courts and indoor carpet.
But she took advantage of a slow start by Seles and won the opening
set by breaking Seles' serve in the first and third games while
saving break points in the second and fourth games. Seles, who got
in only 48 percent of her first serves in the
one-hour-and-22-minute match, committed 15 unforced errors in the
first set.
</P>
<P>
   But Seles, who has won three tournaments this year and is ranked
sixth in the world, got stronger and steadier as the match
progressed while Tauziat gradually faltered.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
