<SLUG> BC-TEN-HAMLET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENGVIST ON A ROLL AT THE RIGHT TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Thomas Engvist of Sweden, it could be coming together at the
right time. Engvist, who took the title in Cincinnati earlier this
month and then reached the quarterfinals in Indianapolis, defeated
Fabrice Santoro in straight sets Friday in Commack, N.Y. The
victory propelled him into the Hamlet Cup semifinals and signaled
his readiness for next week's U.S. Open. ``Everyone has different
ways of preparing for the big ones,'' said Engvist, who is seeded
seventh for the Open. ``For myself, I like to play a lot of
matches. When I do that, I play better. I'm confident, I'm winning
matches ... this has been the best I've been preparing ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Serving 11 aces and refusing to be goaded by Santoro's
frustrating array of drop shots, slices and dinks, Engvist rallied
from 0-4 in the first set to post a 7-6 (4), 6-4 victory. Saturday,
Enqvist will face the winner of the match between Michael Chang and
Arnaud Clement of France.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one on the tour plays like Fabrice,'' said the third-seeded
Engvist. ``I thought it was a really good match.''
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's other semifinal, top-seeded Magnus Norman, the Swede
who is the defending champion, will play 11th-seeded Richard
Krajicek of the Netherlands. Krajicek was waved into the semifinals
on a walkover when Carlos Moya withdrew Friday morning with an
injury to his right big toe.
</P>
<P>
   Moya, who defeated Jan-Michael Gambill 3-6, 7-6 (2), 7-6 (5),
apparently injured his toe during the match, which began Thursday
evening but lasted past midnight. His status for the U.S. Open is
uncertain, although he insisted he would play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not even thinking about not playing,'' Moya said. ``I am
hoping to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
