<HEADER>
A2567 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      08-25 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROMISES OF CUTBACKS FALL SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although Democrats and Republicans pretend to represent distinct
choices in governance, there's one area where you can't tell fish
from fowl.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the Contract with America and the GOP's triumphant
battle for Capitol Hill supremacy? Remember the pledges to downsize
government?
</P>
<P>
   Well, after all was said and done, the revolutionary Republicans
proved no less enthusiastic about big government than the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   How do we know this? Stephen Moore, the Cato Institute's
director of fiscal policy studies, and fiscal policy analyst
Stephen Slivinski recently completed a study titled ``Return of the
Living Dead: Federal Programs That Survived the Republican
Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   What's most impressive about their revelations is how the
GOP-controlled Congress not only failed to shrink the leviathan,
but also how it gave many programs in question more money than even
the Clinton administration had sought.
</P>
<P>
   Total nondefense spending will expand by 11 percent in real
inflation-adjusted terms from 1999-2001. Overall expenditures for
95 of the largest ``living dead'' programs have risen 13 percent
since Republicans took over Congress in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``A major reason for all the new spending,'' Moore and Slivinski
say, ``is the inability or unwillingness of Republicans to
eliminate virtually any government program.'' Thus, they say, there
seems to be a consensus in Washington that ``the era of big
government is here to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the truly great ironies is that some surviving programs
weren't just GOP ``Contract'' targets, but also had been singled
out for elimination as far back as '92 by California Democrat Leon
Panetta when he was House Budget Committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   After an impressive beginning following the 1994 election that
gave congressional control to Republicans, the GOP apparently lost
its nerve. Nearly 200 programs were axed from 1995-97 and domestic
discretionary spending declined slightly in real terms. Since the
first year of the Republican revolution, though, ``the trend has
clearly been toward more expansive budgets each year.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most interesting failure of the GOP will involved
the Commerce, Education and Energy departments, which the
revolutionaries had vowed to dismantle. Not only have they
survived, but two of the three Cabinet agencies enjoy significantly
larger budgets now than they did five years ago. The GOP, in fact,
has spent more on the Education Department than the White House
proposed two of the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   This is a development largely overlooked by fiscal mavens,
probably because the emergence of a putative budget surplus has
made the quest to rein in federal spending a matter of less
urgency.
</P>
<P>
   The surplus, however, is a chimera mostly created by surpluses
from excess Social Security revenues and taxes dedicated to
specific spending activities but not appropriated for the intended
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   There may indeed by good reasons to choose sides this election
year based on the parties' respective differences. As it happens,
though, spending proclivities isn't one of those differences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
