<SLUG> BC-GLF-NEC-WOODS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS BREAKING RECORDS, NOT WINNING HABIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AKRON, Ohio _ Tiger Woods has developed two habits he does not
want to break: winning golf tournaments and setting records.
</P>
<P>
   During Friday's second round of the NEC Invitational, Woods
added another spectacular day to his spectacular summer. He flirted
with shooting a 59. He tied the Firestone Country Club course
record, shooting a 9-under-par 61. And by building a seven-stroke
lead, he threatened to turn another tournament into a rout.
</P>
<P>
   Showing no ill effects from last weekend's emotional victory at
the PGA Championship, Woods was 15-under, seven strokes ahead of
Phil Mickelson and eight strokes ahead of Justin Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   It has become obvious that Woods does not believe in letdowns.
Instead, he never lets up. His score of 125 set a PGA Tour record
for 36 holes, breaking the old mark of 126 set by six other
players. Woods also tied the course record of 61 set by Jose Maria
Olazabal in 1990, and it was Woods' 29th consecutive round of
shooting even par or better, another tour record. Both Mark O'Meara
(1993) and Craig Stadler (1997) have shot 28 consecutive rounds of
even par or better, but since 1980, when the tour began keeping
that statistic, nobody had shot 29 consecutive rounds without
shooting over par.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, that is, until Friday. From the first few holes, it was
obvious Woods was on top of his game, which meant he would finish
on top of the leader board. The big question was: How low would he
go? Through his first seven holes, Woods was five under par for the
day, and some people in his gallery began screaming, ``Fifty-nine,
fifty-nine.'' Only three players in tour history have shot 59 in
competition _ Al Geiberger, Chip Beck and David Duval. Woods didn't
get the 59. But that didn't spoil his day.
</P>
<P>
   How does it feel to be in the kind of zone Woods is in?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have an idea of where you want to put the golf ball, and
you're able to do it,'' said Woods, who put himself in excellent
position to win this World Golf Championships event for the second
consecutive year. ``The game looks easier when you do that.''
</P>
<P>
   It looked easier than easy for Woods. It looked almost
effortless, an awesome display of power, control and putting. On
the par-5, 625-yard No. 16, one of the most famous holes in golf,
Woods became only the fourth player to send a ball flying over the
green in two shots, joining Arnold Palmer, Raymond Floyd and John
Daly.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting a 356-yard drive, Woods cooked a 2-iron shot that
landed 6 feet past the pin and rolled into the back rough. The
crowd went wild. Woods almost made eagle when he barely missed his
chip shot from 20 feet, but he converted the next putt for birdie
while giving another example of how his game differs from everyone
else's.
</P>
<P>
   Woods also birdied the par-4 No. 17 to reach nine under par,
meaning he needed an eagle at the par-4 No. 18 to make 59. After
hitting his tee shot at No. 18 into the right rough, Woods hit his
approach shot over the green, chipped to 8 feet, then made the putt
for par to shoot 61.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps two missed putts cost Woods a chance at 59 _ a 15-foot
birdie putt at No. 13 that stopped just short of the hole, and a
4-foot putt that Woods missed at No. 14 that led to his only bogey
of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Woods said he never seriously considered shooting 59. His main
goal was to increase the one-shot lead he started the day with.
From that perspective, the day was a huge success.
</P>
<P>
   The competition, meanwhile, had to feel somewhat helpless. The
majors are over, Woods has won seven times this year, and this
37-player event is an excellent chance for a huge payday, with a $5
million purse and $1 million going to the winner.
</P>
<P>
   But in Woods' case, the rich may get even richer. How was
Mickelson supposed to feel? He shot his second consecutive 66, he
started the day with a birdie and an eagle, yet Mickelson lost
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taking a lot more under par to win tournaments now,''
said Mickelson, who will be paired with Woods in Saturday's final
group.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Woods was paired with Jim Furyk, who shot a 69, but
who could not keep up.
</P>
<P>
   On No. 11, Furyk hit a great approach shot within 4 feet of the
pin. But Woods outdid him, hitting a wedge shot from 80 yards that
landed inside of Furyk's ball, 3 feet from the cup.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of day. And Woods still had the weekend to try
and outdo himself
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Tiger ever enters a tournament that he doesn't
think he can win,'' said Fluff Cowan, who caddies for Furyk and who
used to caddie for Woods. ``Nearly flawless golf. That's how I'd
describe what I saw today.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
