<HEADLINE>
KANSAS MAN SET FOR SENTENCING ON SEX OFFENSES HANGS SELF IN JAIL
CELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY RIZZO  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A man facing almost 30 years in prison for
sexual encounters with young girls used a bed sheet to hang himself
early Friday in his Johnson County, Kan., jail cell, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   Andre M. Nammour, who was scheduled to be sentenced next week in
Johnson County District Court, had been in the jail in Olathe since
Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   A deputy making a bed check discovered the 35-year-old Fairway
resident about 12:10 a.m. Friday, according to Sheriff's Department
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Paramedics were called, but efforts to revive Nammour were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   The individual-inmate cells in the facility that opened in 1988
were designed to prevent such incidents, but authorities said that
Nammour had been able to attach the sheet to an air vent. Although
the county recently opened a new jail, many prisoners still are at
the old jail, including maximum-security inmates such as murder
suspect John Edward Robinson Sr.
</P>
<P>
   A deputy had checked on Nammour less than 30 minutes before his
body was found, and authorities were attempting to pin down exactly
how long it had been. Cell checks routinely are made every 15 to 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Although they did not term it a suicide note, officials also
said they had recovered a letter addressed to one of Nammour's
relatives in which he described his state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   A news release from Nammour's attorney, Patrick W. Peters, said
Nammour had previously told police and jail officials that he had
felt like killing himself.
</P>
<P>
   He was not on suicide watch at the time of his death, jail
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   He had been put on suicide watch earlier, but jail psychiatric
personnel had subsequently approved his removal from that status.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre felt very bad about the pain he had caused to others,''
Peters said in his news release. ``He pled guilty so that the three
girls would not have to come to court.''
</P>
<P>
   Nammour pleaded guilty in July to charges of rape, aggravated
criminal sodomy and two counts of indecent liberties with a child.
The charges involved 13- and 15-year-old sisters and another girl
who was 11 at the time videotapes were made.
</P>
<P>
   Police had recovered videotapes of Nammour having sex with the
girls, according to prosecutors and police. Detectives with the
Sheriff's Department estimated that they recovered about 1,000
hours of video footage involving six girls.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys were to recommend a 29-year prison term at his
sentencing, scheduled for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The last jail suicide in Johnson County was in March 1995, when
a Fairway man jailed on arson charges used a cord from a laundry
bag to hang himself.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at that time said it was the first suicide at the jail
since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1996, a convicted sex offender who was going to be
sentenced to prison shot himself to death in a Johnson County
Courthouse rest room.
</P>
<P>
   The man, who was free on bond before his sentencing, smuggled a
.357-caliber handgun into the courthouse. Metal detectors have
since been posted at courthouse entrances.
</P>
<P>
   Peters said members of Nammour's family were traveling to the
Kansas City area Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Nammour was an emigre from Lebanon who had come to the United
States in 1988 after fighting for a pro-Israeli and American
militia, according to Peters.
</P>
<P>
   He had worked in the United States as a computer technician.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
