<SLUG> BC-RAC-PACIFIC-CLASSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIMMING IS A SECRET NO MORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL MAR, Calif. _ Jockey Garrett Gomez was leaning against a
wall at trainer Bobby Frankel's barn one morning this week,
speaking of the splendors of the colt named Skimming, when Frankel
walked out of his office and joined the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't brag on this horse too much,'' Frankel admonished
half-seriously. ``I like to sneak in the back door. Like North
Carolina State when they won the NCAA.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankel's allusion to a 1983 basketball tournament is a bit out
of date _ but then, so is his wish to keep Skimming a secret going
into the $1 million Pacific Classic today at Del Mar racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   If Skimming's potential ever was a secret, it was given away
when the 4-year-old son of Nureyev and Skimble won the San Diego
Handicap earlier this month by eight dominant lengths over Prime
Timber. That gate-to-wire victory made Skimming the ``now'' horse
and the obvious choice for bettors hoping to beat Pacific Classic
favorite and defending champion General Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   All Frankel, a Hall of Famer and a four-time Pacific
Classic-winning trainer, has to do is maintain Skimming's recent
form, and the horse's front-running speed should be too much for
his six opponents in the 1-mile signature race of the Del Mar
summer.
</P>
<P>
   That's easier said than done, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``That race (the San Diego) might have been too good,'' Frankel
said, worrying that Skimming might have run the race of his life
three weeks too soon. ``The edge I've got going in this race is
that I don't think anybody can run with him early. The negative is
that I'm picking up weight.''
</P>
<P>
   Skimming will carry 124 pounds, like all of the older horses in
the Pacific Classic, while 3-year-old Tiznow will get in with 117.
Skimming's burden is 12 more than he had in the 11/16-mile San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Another obstacle: He hasn't run in a Grade I stakes before, and
hasn't won a race as long as 1{ miles.
</P>
<P>
   And another: He no longer has the element of surprise. The other
riders know they can't let Skimming get away with an easy lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Frankel believes any horse who tries to stay with Skimming
in the opening furlongs will be committing ``suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankel also trains one of the other potential early-speed
horses in the Pacific Classic. That's the 4-year-old gelding
Euchre, winner of the Bel Air Handicap at Hollywood Park last time
out. Skimming is owned by Juddmonte Farms, Euchre by Frank
Stronach.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Frankel instructs Euchre jockey David Flores to lay off
the pace, an early challenge to Skimming could come from Tiznow or
Forty One Carats _ or from nobody. Tiznow will race without
blinkers this time, indicating trainer Jay Robbins wants him to lag
early and wait for the front-runners to tire.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he (Skimming) runs like he did last time, you know he'll be
in front turning for home,'' said Frankel, whose Missionary Ridge
(1992) and Bertrando (1993) scored the only gate-to-wire victories
in the Pacific Classic's nine runnings.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel thinks Skimming ran so brilliantly in his prep _ going
three-quarters of a mile in 1:09 3/5 finishing in 1:41 _ because he
took to the Del Mar surface particularly well. It was the colt's
first race at Del Mar, and it marked his third victory in five
starts since coming to the United States from England, where the
rules prohibited treating his pulmonary bleeding problem with
lasix.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't one of the stronger Pacific Classic fields. Early
Pioneer, the longshot Hollywood Gold Cup winner, is out with a
minor injury. A Skimming victory might be the most exciting
possible result.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez, who picked up the mount because Alex Solis was out of
town on the day of the San Diego, thinks Skimming shows the
qualities of a star.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good horse has got to be able to make (multiple) moves
throughout a race, and he can do it,'' Gomez said. ``If they're
going slow, he can be on the lead, and if they're going fast, he
can sit second or third.''
</P>
<P>
   Skimming showed he isn't a one-dimensional front-runner when he
rallied from a close fourth to win his U.S. debut under Solis.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez, 32, a fringe top-10 jockey at Del Mar, was the regular
rider for the popular Budroyale, and guided Concern to victory in
the 1994 Arkansas Derby. Asked this week to name the best horse he
has been on, Gomez thought for a few seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be ... this horse right here,'' Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Frankel asked Gomez not to give away the secret.
</P>
<P>
   Too late. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 2246EDT &QL; 
