TROJANS TAB McCULLOUGH AS STARTING RUNNING BACK 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ After being coy about who will start at
tailback all training camp, the USC coaching staff has decided that
sophomore Sultan McCullough will make his first career start for
the Trojans against Penn State on Sunday in the Kickoff Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sultan will get the start,'' running backs coach Kennedy Pola
said. ``We're gonna mix it up, but Sultan will play in our regular
package and Malaefou (MacKenzie) will play in our three (wide
receiver) package. But we'll change it to keep things
off-balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Tailback was the last position on the depth chart that had not
been officially decided. McCullough and MacKenzie are both expected
to play significant amounts of the game, and senior Petros
Papadakis will play in short-yardage situations.
</P>
<P>
   BETTER WEATHER: The Trojans were thrilled with the weather in
the New York-New Jersey area Friday. There was little humidity and
it was cooler than in 1996, when the Trojans also played Penn
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last time, I remember it was so hot, I didn't even want to go
inside the Statue of Liberty,'' defensive tackle Ennis Davis said.
``This is much better. I keep praying the weather doesn't change.
But we're prepared for the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   WHERE'S CASEY? Penn State quarterback Rashard Casey was
conspicuous by his absence from Friday's media day. The Nittany
Lions brought several players, but not Casey, who is accused of
felony aggravated assault against an off-duty police officer and
has been a huge source of controversy for head coach Joe Paterno
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he needs this. I don't need this,'' Paterno
said. ``You guys wouldn't let him talk about football.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Casey, Paterno had a surprising response about how
the incident affected his quarterback and the Nittany Lions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might turn out to be a blessing,'' Paterno said. ``He's
really asserted more leadership and the kids have rallied around
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Paterno said he told Casey, a native of nearby Hoboken, N.J.,
not to ``let anyone take away from a trip that should be about
going home to have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the assault incident, Paterno said he has still not
discussed it with Casey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine at what point it might be (a distraction),''
Paterno said.
</P>
<P>
   SEA SICK: USC wide receiver Marcell Allmond experienced some
problems during the team's cruise of New York Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sick. I don't like that,'' Allmond said. ``My stomach is
still turning but I'll get through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Allmond, who will start Sunday, should get plenty of
opportunities if the Nittany Lions decide to double-cover wide
receiver Kareem Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping it will be a little bit of a breakout for me,''
Allmond said.
</P>
<P>
   NOT-SO-CLASSIC MEMORY: Paterno claims he doesn't remember that
Curtis Enis gained a Kickoff Classic-record 241 yards against USC
in 1996. But Hackett, who was coaching with the Kansas City Chiefs
at the time, said he knew all about the performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The alumni have continued to remind me about Curtis Enis and
the outcome of that game,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   BOUNCING BACK: Hackett was pleased with USC's energy during a
90-minute practice held at the New York Giants' indoor facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the long plane ride and being stagnant, we needed to
break a sweat,'' Hackett said. ``It was good. I feel we're getting
our energy back.''
</P>
<P>
   SURPRISE VISITOR: New York Giants head coach Jim Fassel, who
played at USC in 1969, stopped by Friday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a USC guy, and he's been a rival,'' Hackett said. ``He
coached at Stanford when I was at USC (as an assistant) and we've
known each other in the NFL. He's also a Manhattan Beach guy.''
</P>
<P>
   BACKUP QUARTERBACK: Former Westlake (Calif.) High quarterback
Zac Wasserman is battling another freshman, Sean Schellenger, for
the No.3 position on the Nittany Lions' depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a fine prospect,'' Paterno said. ``But it's hard to get
the freshmen enough work. But one of them might be a backup, so
we've got to get them ready.''
</P>
<P>
   CONFERENCE HONOR: Hackett said he is aware that the sagging
reputation of the Pacific-10 Conference will be at stake again in
this national matchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fact that all the other coaches in this league
said, `Hackett, it's up to you.' That was an indication,'' he said.
``Our feeling is that this is a new year and the Pac-10 will stand
on its own.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
