<HEADLINE>
LAZIO DEFENDS TAX-CUT PLAN AS TOOL TO SPREAD PROSPERITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A day after he unveiled his tax cuts proposal,
Rep. Rick Lazio Friday fended off skepticism from Democrats and
sought to defend his plan as a way to continue to spread
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, the Republican nominee, visited a thriving business in
nearby Malta and then came here to discuss his tax plan in
interviews with five television stations. Aides to Hillary Rodham
Clinton, his Democratic opponent for the U.S. Senate, have called
it a ``reckless'' venture that would squander the surplus and
stifle the economic boom. Clinton's campaign office said Lazio's
plan would produce $1.24 trillion in cuts, rather than the $776
billion Lazio cited.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio fired back, saying: ``This is a campaign that is based now
entirely on fear-mongering, on negative attacks, on ripping our
state apart. I can't imagine that Mrs. Clinton is proud of the kind
of campaign that she's waging right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's tax cut plan _ a compilation of ideas he has talked
about on the stump as well as those advocated by other Republicans
_ includes as its centerpiece a proposal to allow people to deduct
from their federal income taxes the payroll tax that finances
Social Security. He also called for reducing the capital gains tax
to 15 percent from 20 percent and eliminating the inheritance tax
and the so-called marriage tax, among other taxes. He suggested
that federal surpluses of $4.4 trillion projected over the next 10
years would offset any loss of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, in five satellite interviews with stations in
Buffalo, Binghamton, Syracuse, Rochester and Westchester County _
all markets in a region that both camps consider a key battleground
for votes _ Lazio sought to drive home his points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The estimates we have are based on nonpartisan sources,''
Lazio told viewers in Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reduction in the capital gains is important to stimulate
business to continue to invest in themselves'' was a message for
Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a responsible tax plan that will help incentivize
economic development,'' he said to Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of the day, Clinton, for one, remained
unconvinced. Her proposals would trim taxes by $496 billion over 10
years and include a cut in, rather than elimination of, the
marriage penalty and inheritance tax. She has said that the surplus
should be used first to pay down the national debt and then to
shore up Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary has presented New Yorkers a plan to provide targeted
tax cuts and preserve Medicare and Social Security,'' said Cathie
Levine, a spokeswoman for Clinton. ``Rick Lazio's reckless $1.2
trillion tax cut would explode the deficit and drive interest rates
sky-high.''
</P>
<P>
   Her comment was in a statement that included a 2,243-word
compilation of what the Clinton campaign said was Lazio's history
of negative campaigning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
