<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS TAKE THEIR CUTS AND HAND JOHNSON ANOTHER BEATING
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On April 15, 1989, a wild 25-year-old left-hander
started for Montreal against Pittsburgh and could not get out of
the second inning. None of the five outs he recorded were
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, three teams and 352 games later, that pitcher
faced a Mets lineup that included no position players who were
active then. And for the first time since then, Randy Johnson, the
second most prolific left-handed strikeout pitcher in baseball
history and the best pitcher in the National League, failed to fan
a batter.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets own Johnson. There is no mistaking that now, not after
they clobbered him and the Arizona Diamondbacks, 13-3, at Shea
Stadium in a victory that increased the Mets' lead in the National
League wild-card race to 5 1/2 games over Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Since the opening game of the division series last October,
Johnson has faced the Mets four times. The Mets have won each game,
and in those games Johnson is 0-3 with a 7.29 earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the major league strikeout leader this year, has 2,971
career strikeouts, second only to the Hall of Famer Steve Carlton
among left-handers. Despite his struggles against the Mets, he had
always shown hints of his dominance. In 182/3 innings over three
games, Johnson had struck out 29 Mets.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday night he fanned no one and could get only seven outs.
The Mets collected six hits and six runs in two and a third innings
off Johnson, who walked two, made one error and watched as a Gold
Glove-winning teammate made another.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was not throwing as hard as usual _ his fastest pitch
was 94 mph _ and he gave up several hits off his slider. But more
than anything else, the Mets seemed to be afflicting his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Zeile, who had no hits and five strikeouts in 10 career
at-bats against Johnson, knocked a slider up the middle for a
leadoff single in the second. Johnson was unnerved, and Benny
Agbayani walked on four pitches to bring up Jay Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Damian Miller, Johnson's personal catcher, who did not start
when the Mets knocked out Johnson in the fourth inning at Arizona
three weeks ago, set up inside on Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said this week he needed to establish his inside
fastball to beat the Mets, and he tried to do it here. But the
pitch missed badly, and Payton drove the outside fastball to right
field.
</P>
<P>
   His single scored Zeile and sent Agbayani to third. Mike Bordick
chopped a ball to third, where Matt Williams, a three-time Gold
Glove winner, bobbled it on the transfer from his glove to his
hand. As his throw arrived home, Agbayani slid around Miller to
give the Mets a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The next two batters bunted: Rick Reed to get Payton to third,
and Joe McEwing to bring Payton home. McEwing, the reserve who is
Johnson's celebrated nemesis, got a slider and bunted it hard
toward first base. The Diamondbacks did not expect that, and first
baseman Greg Colbrunn could only step on first as Payton scampered
home with the Mets' third run.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the error and the bunt, Johnson was having no luck.
But he made his own bad luck in the third. Edgardo Alfonzo,
starting for the first time since Monday after missing time with a
stiff neck, lined a slider to left to lead off the inning, bringing
up Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza chopped a ball in front of the plate, and Johnson caught
it on one hop. He wheeled to second to start a double play, but
fired low, under the glove of Tony Womack at second. Johnson threw
his head back in disgust as Alfonzo went to third, and Zeile drove
Alfonzo in when he singled on a fastball above the belt.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Johnson walked Agbayani on four pitches. Again, Payton
followed with a drive to right with runners on.
</P>
<P>
   But this hit, off a 90 mph fastball, was harder and farther than
the right fielder Danny Bautista thought. Bautista came in on it,
then had to hustle back, taking an awkward angle. He stuck up his
glove, but the ball carried over it and rolled to the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Two runs scored to put the Mets ahead, 6-0. Agbayani was thrown
out at home, but the 38,237 fans at Shea Stadium did not care. They
were having too much fun roaring at Johnson as he marched slowly to
the dugout, lifted in the third inning, his shortest start in more
than four years.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks got to within three runs in the sixth inning
when Steve Finley homered off Reed, who went seven innings and
improved to 8-4. But in the bottom of the sixth, after a
bases-loaded walk, Agbayani whacked a bases-clearing double that
put the Mets ahead, 10-3.
</P>
<P>
   A rout was on, the victory was secured, and the improbable feat
of beating Johnson had become routine for the Mets. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
