<SLUG> BC-GOP-GORE-AD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP AD AIMS TO DIFFUSE GORE'S BOOST FROM PRESCRIPTION ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark. Del. La., Mich., Mo., Ohio, Pa., Wash., Wis.)  By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two days after canceling one advertisement that
attacked Vice President Al Gore on his trustworthiness, the
Republicans Friday released another that criticizes Gore's plan for
providing a prescription drug benefit for older Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee is spending $7 million to
broadcast the 30-second advertisement in nine states beginning
Monday. The sum is a huge one this early, and it underscores how
urgently the Republicans believe they need to counter Gore's surge
in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the party prepares to run the commercial, the campaign
of Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican nominee, is distancing
itself from it by paying for its own commercials on the same
subject, but without the comparison to Gore's plan or the
suggestion that Gore's plan is bad for older Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP commercial says in part: ``And Al Gore? Gore opposed
bipartisan reform. He's pushing a big-government plan that lets
Washington bureaucrats interfere with what your doctors prescribe.
The Gore Prescription Plan: Bureaucrats decide. The Bush
Prescription Plan: Seniors choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, a spokesman for Gore, said that the commercial was
misleading because Bush had not offered a specific prescription
drug plan: ``Zip, zero, nada, nothing,'' Lehane said, adding that
the commercial seemed to be a defensive move.
</P>
<P>
   Republican strategists acknowledged that Gore had gained ground
with his constant discussion of prescription drugs, and said that
the party hoped at least to neutralize his success on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we neutralize it, we can go back to our issues of
character, integrity and leadership,'' one strategist said.
</P>
<P>
   There seemed little concern among Republican officials that the
party would be branded as the first to go negative in what has
rapidly become the opening round of the fall campaign, even though
the traditional Labor Day opening is more than a week away. Their
real concern is that Gore has successfully moved _ ``pivoted'' one
said _ into the fall campaign by discussing an issue voters care
about.
</P>
<P>
   And with that pivot, Gore, after months of stasis, began setting
the campaign agenda at a time when the Bush campaign has appeared
off-course. Republicans, along with everyone else, have been
watching Gore's favorable ratings rise in polls.
</P>
<P>
   Bush on Wednesday canceled a commercial that had been sent out
to 350 television stations. It used excerpts from an interview with
Gore from six years ago in which Gore said that President Clinton
had never lied.
</P>
<P>
   The ambivalence over that commercial reflected a debate within
Republican circles on how negative Bush should go against Gore, and
how soon. The emergence of the GOP's commercial Friday effectively
answers that question, for now. The party and the campaign both
wanted to erode Gore's success; putting the advertisement in the
mouth of an anonymous narrator in a commercial paid for by the
party allows Bush to claim the high road, but still get a message
across.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial features a moment in which Bush says: ``Every
senior will have access to prescription drug benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the issues on which he has had an advantage
over us,'' said one Republican strategist referring to Gore. ``If
we don't have an adequate response, then people will care about an
issue that he has an advantage on. This is a recognition that Gore
has gotten people talking about this issue, and it ranks in the
double-digits with people, so yes, it's a concern.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercial is intended for undecided voters. It is to run in
Arkansas, Delaware, Louisiana, Michigan, Missouri, Ohio,
Pennsylvania, Washington and Wisconsin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
