<SLUG> BC-NY-HARASS-CHICKEN-NYT </SLUG>
 
TWO WHO CLUCKED FOR REVENGE ARE ARRESTED FOR HARASSMENT c.2000 N.Y.
Times News Service   Two former employees of a mortgage brokerage
firm near Albany became so annoyed when a New York City woman
pulled out of a deal, the police said, that they harassed her for
months by calling on the phone and clucking like a chickens.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two men, Scott Chittenden, 28, of Cohoes, N.Y., and Victor
Guilianelle, 32, of Ballston Lake, N.Y., were arrested on Thursday
and charged with aggravated harassment, the Cohoes Police
Department said. Both are free on bail pending a court appearance
next week. If convicted, each faces up to a year in prison.
</P>
<P>
   To protect her privacy, the police withheld the name of the
woman, who is a secretary at the State Labor Department in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to clucking over the phone, the police said, the two
men also clipped Perdue chicken advertisements from newspapers and
mailed them to their victim, and Chittenden once called her,
pretending to be Regis Philbin and inviting her to be a contestant
on ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought it was really funny,'' said Detective Lt. Tom
Ross, of the Cohoes department. ``And once they saw her reaction,
they got caught up in it. They got hooked.''
</P>
<P>
   The two made 30 to 40 calls over three or four months, Ross
said, after the woman reneged on a home mortgage deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, she got a better rate,'' he said. ``I think we've all
been hit up with telemarketers. Usually, they're just rude. These
guys took it to another level.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman received some of the calls at her office, a
spokeswoman there said. Distraught, she informed her boss, who
asked investigators for the Labor Department's inspector general to
trace her calls. That led to Chittenden's home and the office of
Tri-City Funding in Clifton Park, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man works at Tri-City any longer, according to Joseph
Zappone, a lawyer representing the company. He would not say
whether their departures were tied to the charges, but said that
Tri-City officials had no knowledge of any harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not our business practice to use aggressive business
tactics in any way, shape or form,'' Zappone said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 2321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
