<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-LA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. UNFAIR TO WOMEN WORKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAM PARK 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles women don't get a fair return on what
they invest in the fabric of the city, according to recent
testimony before a City Council committee.
</P>
<P>
   Despite efforts to promote gender equity, from government
contracts to the city's flourishing adult entertainment industry,
women often are discriminated against and underrewarded, and
sometimes abused, speakers said.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Wu, president of the Los Angeles City Commission on the
Status of Women, said the commission and the City Council intend to
explore ways to address women's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 360,000 women-owned businesses in Los
Angeles County, and research indicates that by 2005, fully half of
area businesses will be owned by women.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles adheres to a federal goal of awarding a minimum of 4
percent of city contracts to women-owned businesses. In 1999, $1.1
billion in contracts were awarded, and $55.2million, or 4.6 percent
went to women.
</P>
<P>
   Women and minorities are better represented in some fields than
in others and, in some kinds of contract awards, women and
minorities get 40 percent to 50 percent of the work, Diane Castano
Sallee, director of the Los Angeles Minority Business Opportunity
Committee, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Because Los Angeles County is one of the most diverse in the
nation and has perhaps the largest pool of women and minorities to
draw from, it could lead the way in awarding contracts to those
groups. The key is communicating opportunities to the businesses
that are seeking work, and the city is building on several programs
to do that, Sallee said.
</P>
<P>
   Gender pay equity, enforcement of sexual harassment and job
discrimination laws, and -- especially for poorer women -- better
transportation and affordable, available child care are always near
the top of the list.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers noted many of the discrepancies:
</P>
<P>
   --Female nurses average 15 percent less pay than male nurses.
</P>
<P>
   --The man who seats you in a restaurant is called a maitre d'. A
woman who seats you is called a hostess and is paid significantly
less.
</P>
<P>
   --Women are seamstresses. Men are tailors and generally earn
more.
</P>
<P>
   L.A.'s entertainment industry has a notorious record, speakers
said.
</P>
<P>
   The adult entertainment industry is an $8 billion to $12 billion
business -- largely based in Los Angeles County. More than 1,000
people perform sex acts for money each month, and they are
sometimes forbidden to use condoms to protect themselves. They have
no health benefits and are subject to abuse by those who make money
off them, a former sex worker told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   The mainstream movie industry has its own gender issues. Screen
Actors Guild statistics show there are twice as many roles for men
as for women, and men work twice as many days on average. Women
over 40 get only 24 percent of women's roles available.
</P>
<P>
   Men over 40 get 36 percent of men's roles.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the solutions proposed to the city Friday included
access to 24-hour affordable child care, better transportation,
tuition reimbursement for city employees and educating women about
finance options.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
