<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAIN-RELIGION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 WORLD RELIGIOUS LEADERS TO HOLD MEETING ON PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Changes ``occupied'' to ``once occupied'' in 5th-last
graf.)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT21 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine a meeting that puts Israel's chief rabbi, an emissary of
Iran's top ayatollah, the head of the World Council of Churches and
a granddaughter of Mahatma Gandhi together in the same room. An
unexpected grouping, to be sure. But it would have only a few of
the spiritual figures due to begin meeting at the United Nations on
Monday, when 2,000 people from 90 nations and a wide spectrum of
faiths are to begin spending four days on issues related to peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a unique opportunity for religious leaders to have an
impact on the political process,'' said Bawa Jain, a veteran of
interfaith activities who is general secretary of the event, the
Millennium World Peace Summit of Religious and Spiritual Leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Jain, 44, a native of India and citizen of the United States who
lives in New Jersey, has traveled widely, asking prominent people
in the worlds of Buddhism, Christianity, Hinduism, Islam, Judaism
and other faiths to attend.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, backed by a large advisory board filled with
religious figures, scholars and diplomats, has been organized in
cooperation with the office of the U.N. secretary-general. But it
is not an official U.N. event, and its financing has come largely
from foundations.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of its breadth, the event is not unique. At meetings in
South Africa last year and in Chicago in 1993, the Parliament of
the World's Religions drew wide interfaith participation.
</P>
<P>
   But it may be, as Jain said, the biggest in terms of the high
level of leadership involved. Among its goals is the creation of an
advisory council of religious leaders to work with the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   What seems to have helped in attracting participants are the
event's location, at the United Nations; its timing, in the year
2000; and its focus on peace. Five hundred delegates are coming,
many with associates as well.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the religious figures mentioned above _ Rabbi
Meir Lau, from Israel; Ayatollah Abdollah Vaeze Javadi, from Iran;
the Rev. Konrad Raiser of the World Council of Churches; and Ela
Gandhi _ those attending are to include Cardinal Francis Arinze, a
Vatican official representing Pope John Paul II; Kuni Kuniaki, high
priest of Shintoism's Grand Shrine at Ise, Japan; and Bishop Vashti
McKenzie, first female bishop in the African Methodist Episcopal
Church.
</P>
<P>
   (One major figure not attending is the Dalai Lama, spiritual
leader of Tibet, whose presence at the United Nations was blocked
by objections from China, casting a shadow over the proceedings.)
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jain belongs to the Jain faith (it is not at all unusual, he
said, for believers to carry its name as their own). It originated
in India and espouses ahimsa, or nonviolence toward all living
creatures.
</P>
<P>
   He is vice president of the Interfaith Center in New York, an
organization headed by the Rev. James Parks Morton, retired dean of
the Cathedral of St. John the Divine.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Morton spoke of Sushil Kumar, Jain's spiritual
mentor, who was long active in promoting dialogue among religious
groups. ``All of the big, international interfaith conferences I
attended, he was there,'' Morton said.
</P>
<P>
   Jain said Kumar had a religious vision at age 7, was ordained a
Jain monk at 15, and was deeply affected by the violence between
Hindus and Muslims that marred the independence of India and
Pakistan half a century ago. Kumar, he said, pursued interfaith
activities as a way of improving relations between adherents of
different religions.
</P>
<P>
   Kumar came to the United States in 1975 and, six years later,
found a site for the area's first Jain temple, on property once
occupied by a Jewish summer camp in Blairstown, N.J. Jain, then
running a construction company in India, supplied craftsmen for the
project. Before Kumar died in 1994, he asked Jain to take a lead in
interfaith efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Jain said the process culminating in the event next week had
originated in a conversation between Ted Turner and U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan. Turner suggested that religious
leaders ought to come together to promote world peace, Jain said.
</P>
<P>
   Jain said a U.N. official had asked him to get involved, after
which he sought assistance from David Finn, founder and chairman of
Ruder-Finn, a public relations company in New York. Finn's daughter
Dena Merriam, a Ruder-Finn partner and vice chairman who works with
religious and cultural organizations, joined in, lining up
foundation support.
</P>
<P>
   The event's advisory board has more than 40 people, including
the Roman Catholic theologian Hans Kueng. Its chairman is Maurice
Strong, an adviser to Annan who organized the Earth Summit in
Brazil in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Jain said he found inspiration for the event in the memory of
Kumar. ``It's his blessing,'' Jain said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
