<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
 
IS McCULLOUGH NEW KING OF TAILBACK U? 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ Maybe if you were raised to believe you were
some kind of royalty, you too would be prone to fits of outrageous
self-confidence. As Sultan McCullough was, and is.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with the name. It's Muslim and it's pronounced
(ital)SOOL-tawn(endital). The USC tailback was named by his late
father, whose own given name was Bruce, later changed to Shaheed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up, I didn't know what my name meant. I asked my
mom,'' the now-20-year-old McCullough said the other day as he
lugged his helmet and pads to the locker room following a Trojans
practice session in Irvine. ``She told me it meant `king.' I
thought I was kind of special. I thought I couldn't die. I thought
I couldn't endure pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I got beat up a few times, and I found out that wasn't
true.''
</P>
<P>
   A buoyant confidence could not be pounded out of him, though.
</P>
<P>
   McCullough charges into his second collegiate season, beginning
with Sunday's Kickoff Classic game against Penn State at Giants
Stadium in New Jersey. He is more than comfortable with the notion
he will be the key to the USC ground game and the USC ground game
will be pivotal in the team's success or failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be the next star, the next running back, the next
go-to guy,'' said McCullough, who idolizes Marcus Allen.
</P>
<P>
   He described a USC offense with three kings: ``Carson Palmer in
the passing, Kareem (Kelly) in the receiving, and Sultan in the
rushing.''
</P>
<P>
   Trojans-watchers share two-thirds of McCullough's confidence in
that area. Palmer, the strapping quarterback returning from injury,
is the team's star and leader. He's a given. Kelly, the
sprinter/wide receiver, was the 1999 Pacific-10 Conference Freshman
of the Year. He's a given.
</P>
<P>
   McCullough comes off a redshirt freshman season in which he
gained 413 yards and scored, ahem, one touchdown as Chad Morton's
backup. He has something to prove.
</P>
<P>
   The question has always been whether McCullough can translate
his sensational speed into tough yards between the tackles. He was
the 1999 Pac-10 100-meters champion and is advertised as the
fastest USC football player ever. But the upright running style he
uses on the track is entirely different from the
low-center-of-gravity approach he needs on the field.
</P>
<P>
   As if to demonstrate how much he has learned in this regard,
McCullough put his pads and helmet down on the grass and dropped
into what looked like a boxer's crouch. Then he slapped his thighs,
hips and shoulders rapidly. Tacklers ricocheting off. No pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a football player now,'' USC head coach Paul Hackett
said. ``He has decided this business of being a track guy isn't
founded.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett calls McCullough's acquired skill ``in-line running,''
referring to a back's ability to pick for yards at the crowded line
of scrimmage. The coach got a glimpse of it when McCullough rushed
for 154 yards and two touchdowns on 21 carries in the Trojans'
second and final preseason scrimmage last week at Orange Coast
College.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see him bounce off tacklers and get underneath guys,
you say, `Ahhhh!''' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   McCullough's confidence has been tested, to be sure. A prep
All-American at Muir High in Pasadena, Calif., he enjoyed the
atmosphere in which a player dealt directly with his head coach.
Expecting to find a sympathetic ear in the same office in college,
he instead found a thicket of assistant coaches and counselors.
</P>
<P>
   He felt isolated and felt worse during his redshirt season in
1998. McCullough watched the road games on television and sulked.
He started 1999 as USC's fifth running back and couldn't be
disappointed to wind up as the team's second-leading rusher behind
Morton's 1,141.
</P>
<P>
   Now Morton has moved on to the New Orleans Saints. USC's depth
chart lists a three-headed replacement _ McCullough, junior power
runner Malaefou MacKenzie and senior short-yardage man Petros
Papadakis. On paper, Tailback U has become Tailbacks U. But it
seemed to be McCullough's position to lose, a notion proven true
when he was named the starter on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he crashes into a Penn State defense that hasn't allowed
a 100-yard game to any running back in 15 games but has nine new
starters. A strong opener for McCullough will signal good things
ahead for the Trojans. They might think of themselves as a passing
team these days. But it's no coincidence that USC's decade-long
absence from the season-ending top 10 coincides with their slide
below the 2,000-yard mark in annual team rushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my first game as a starter, and I want to see what I can
do against the best,'' McCullough said. ``If I do my job this week,
all the questions will be answered. Am I tough? Can I run in the
middle?''
</P>
<P>
   He thinks he is, and he thinks he can. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kevin Modesti's column appears in the Daily News three days a week.
He can be reached at (818) 713-3616. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 2327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
