u a BC-HERALD-SQUARE-TRAFFIC     08-25 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERALD-SQUARE-TRAFFIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING SOME OF THE CHAOS OUT OF HERALD SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
  By JAYSON BLAIR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Perhaps no intersection in the city is as chaotic as
Herald Square, where the traffic of 34th Street, Broadway and
Avenue of the Americas intersects with tens of thousands of
shoppers, tourists and Midtown workers in a compressed patch of
streets that defy the rules of sound urban planning.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to restore some order to the area, the city's
Department of Transportation has embarked on the final stage of a
reconfiguration that would eliminate a lane of traffic on Broadway,
reverse the flow of cars on 33rd Street, and create pedestrian
plazas below 34th Street.
</P>
<P>
   The changes seek to make things easier for the roughly 20,000
people who travel through the area during a typical peak hour,
competing with thousands of vehicles moving through Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike similarly congested Times Square, the Herald Square area
and its traffic patterns are particularly problematic, with
southbound Broadway running into the northbound Avenue of the
Americas.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the traffic changes, the plan adds more
pedestrian islands for those who want to walk through the
intersection. The plan was designed by Transportation Department
engineers who had been monitoring the area for about three years.
Herald Square is either home to or near several subway lines, a
PATH train station, an entrance to Pennsylvania Station and several
department stores, including Macy's.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department and the 34th Street Partnership,
the local Business Improvement District, finished placing barriers
on Broadway and Avenue of the Americas between 34th and 33rd
Streets and in certain lanes yesterday. City officials said they
had also installed video cameras throughout the area to monitor the
flow of traffic, and they will review the tapes each month to judge
the impact of the changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our No. 1 priority is safety,'' said Joseph G. Albano, the
Manhattan borough commissioner for the transportation department.
``We are concerned with it, but we are also looking for a way to
balance the needs of both the vehicular and pedestrian traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   According to 1997 state transportation data, 315 people were
treated at hospitals for injuries in accidents around Herald
Square. The intersection of West 34th Street, Broadway and the
Avenue of the Americas ranked as the third most dangerous in
Manhattan and seventh most dangerous in New York City, officials
said. From 1994 through 1997, 25 people were killed in crashes in
Herald Square, according to Transportation Alternatives, a local
advocacy group that promotes travel without cars.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Pisark, the vice president for retail services at the 34th
Street Partnership, said: ``This experiment really favors
pedestrians'' and ``seems to work. Buses were getting through,
people were making it through.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes will be made permanent if city engineers determine
that the current experiment has been a success, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   And there were signs that it just might work. Pisark said he saw
something unusual yesterday: an ambulance swiftly made its way
south on Broadway through Herald Square in rush-hour traffic. ``My
hat's off to the Department of Transportation,'' he said. ``That's
quite a feat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
