<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUNNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE HOPES TO AVOID FLAGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JILL PAINTER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's not just lip service.
</P>
<P>
   Cal State Northridge football coach Jeff Kearin wants his
football team to cut down on penalties. And he's taking steps to
make sure the Matadors aren't the most penalized team in the Big
Sky Conference again.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin brought in several Big Sky officials, as well as local
officials from other conferences, for both Wednesday's practice
scrimmage and today's 10:45 a.m. PDT scrimmage at North Campus
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no questioning that it's part of discipline,'' Kearin
said. ``We play kind of an aggressive defense. We lead the
conference in defensive holding, for example. They were legitimate
calls. I can't say they're not if they called them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competitive penalties _ the holding, clipping, illegal
procedure _ I don't mind. You mind, but you can handle those. It's
the ones like the late hits and personal fouls that you worry
about. We need to play the game between the whistles and the
lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, CSUN had 121 penalties for 1,095 yards _ about 150
yards more than Northern Arizona, the second most-penalized team.
CSUN, which averaged 98.3 penalty yards per game, had more than
double the penalty yards as Montana _ the least-penalized team in
the Big Sky.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors had 15 penalties last season in a 34-21 loss to
Portland State _ a game they had to win to stay in the hunt for a
playoff berth. Even Kearin was flagged twice last year. He's vowed
that won't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN will see if it's made any strides when it opens the season
a week from today against Air Force in Colorado Springs. That
should be a tough assignment _ Air Force is expecting a sellout for
Parents Weekend at Falcon Stadium (capacity 52,480).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why coach Kearin is getting all these refs in
practice,'' fullback Crayton Milton said. ``It's just like
practicing for a game. The refs tell you what you should and
shouldn't do. We're on the road to getting better at that.''
</P>
<P>
   BRADY'S STATUS: Quarterback Marcus Brady's right throwing arm is
fine, according to Kearin. Brady sat out most throwing drills
Thursday because of a twinge and soreness in his arm, but he
competed in drills again Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good not using him,'' Kearin said. ``He needed a rest
and the other guys needed the repetition.''
</P>
<P>
   INJURY REPORT: Milton has a sore neck and probably won't play
today. ... Offensive linemen Johnny Acosta (back) and Mike Allen
(ankle) didn't practice Friday. ... Keith Kincaid returned to
practice after nursing an ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   LIGHT SCRIMMAGE: Today's scrimmage won't include tackles to the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take it easy,'' Kearin said. ``We're beat up and we're
sore. It's typical training camp stuff but I don't want to get
anybody hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   A barbecue will follow at 12:30 p.m. PDT.
</P>
<P>
   HICKS TO SUIT UP: Running back Matt Hicks is expected to
participate in his first practice with the Matadors on Monday.
Hicks _ who transferred from Air Force _ was admitted to CSUN on
Friday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
