<SLUG> BC-NY-TEENS-DROWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE RECOVER BODIES OF BROOKLYN TEEN-AGERS DROWNED IN THE HUDSON
RIVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: No byline) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The bodies of two emotionally disturbed teen-agers
from Brooklyn who disappeared after jumping into the Hudson River
on Tuesday have been found, and the group home supervisor who took
them to the river's edge has resigned, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of the boys, Arimendis Lajara, 15, and Cedric
Florence, 17, were found 12 hours apart not far from where they
disappeared at the confluence of the Hudson and Croton Rivers in
Croton-on-Hudson, N.Y. They were identified by family members, said
the Westchester County medical examiner, Millard Hyland.
</P>
<P>
   Cedric's body was found about 8 p.m. Thursday about 70 yards
west of Tellers Point, the southern-most point of Croton Point
Park. He died of asphyxia by drowning, Hyland said.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy is scheduled Saturday for the second boy, whose body
was pulled from the water at 9:50 a.m. Friday about half a mile
away.
</P>
<P>
   The boys, who lived in a group home on the grounds of the
Brooklyn Children's Psychiatric Center, had been on a camping trip.
They were hiking with four other boys and a supervisor, Lenox
Gabriel, down a steep path to the water's edge when three of the
boys jumped, fully clothed, into the water. Gabriel jumped in to
try to save them; one boy managed to swim to shore, but the others
disappeared in a treacherous spot where the rivers converge and
crosscurrents can swiftly overwhelm swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel, 47, who had to be pulled from the water himself, was
hospitalized. He has since resigned as community residence manager
of the group home.
</P>
<P>
   The police said Gabriel had told them that he never intended to
take the boys swimming; he and other counselors on the trip had
been warned against going in the water.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel could not be reached Friday for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal and departmental investigations by the Westchester
County police and the Office of Mental Health are continuing.
</P>
<P>
   An intensive search for the boys that involved several agencies,
including the U.S. Coast Guard, shifted from a rescue effort to a
recovery mission Thursday, when, after 48 hours of searching,
officials began to lose hope of finding the boys alive.
</P>
<P>
   The recovery of their bodies, however grim, was a source of
relief for the boys' families, who said it brought an end to the
uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   A recreational boater spotted Arimendis' body floating in the
water Friday, in an area where swimming is prohibited, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The other boy's body was recovered by a member of the Coast
Guard Auxiliary who had been alerted by a water scooter rider.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 2330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
