<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ROSTER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS COACH SAYS HE WILL FIT SYSTEM TO PLAYERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Mercifully, the Cowboys' 0-5 preseason has come
to a close. Evaluations are in, auditions are a wrap and final cuts
are being withheld upon notification of next-of-kin.
</P>
<P>
   NFL teams have until 3 p.m. CDT tomorrow to be down to 53
players.
</P>
<P>
   But the wheels already are turning for Dave Campo and his 19-man
coaching staff. They were at Valley Ranch yesterday, trying to find
the best personnel to be fitted with the right schemes.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, they were trying to come up with the best team they
could buy for $62.172 million, the NFL's salary-cap limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to bring the scheme to the players,'' Campo said
yesterday. ``The mistake that you make is when you say, `This is my
scheme, and you're going to do it.' We've never done that here, not
defensively ... and we won't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will tailor something to get the best out of whichever 11
guys that we have lined up.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo's biggest concern going into the Sept. 3 season opener
against the Philadelphia Eagles is a ``young secondary,'' even
though three of the Cowboys' four starters _ Darren Woodson, George
Teague and Ryan McNeil _ each have eight or more seasons of NFL
experience.
</P>
<P>
   But] rookie Kareem Larrimore from West Texas A&AMP;M is being
counted on _ as a matter of attrition _ to start at left cornerback
eight days from now at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In the Cowboys' 24-17 preseason loss to the St. Louis Rams on
Thursday night, ``Kareem played better than you might think,''
Campo said. But the fourth-round draft pick has had first-half
lapses in each of his three preseason starts in place of Kevin
Smith, now on the reserve/retired list.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four cornerbacks who started for the Cowboys last season
_ Deion Sanders, Kevin Mathis, Smith and Charlie Williams _ only
Williams is still with the team. And he's recovering from a
summerlong staph infection caused by off-season knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   To hide Larrimore _ or help him, depending on your point of view
_ the Cowboys have several options:
</P>
<P>
   Play two-deep zone, with safety help provided to Larrimore on
most pass plays.
</P>
<P>
   Disguise coverages to muddy the reads between quarterback and
receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Run stunts/games up front, then bring pressure with a linebacker
or a defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make it to where it's not a `coverage situation'
every time \Rfor Larrimore\S ... where the quarterback doesn't have
a lot of time to throw,'' Campo said. ``But I really believe that
our front four is going to come on and rush the passer this year.''
</P>
<P>
   It rarely showed this preseason. The Cowboys played nine
quarters without registering a sack until middle linebacker Dat
Nguyen broke through Thursday night to tackle Trent Green for a
10-yard loss on the Rams' opening drive.
</P>
<P>
   That was the lone sack of the game for either team. The Cowboys
finished the preseason with eight sacks and an average of barely
one quarterback pressure per quarter in five games.
</P>
<P>
   Unfazed by the numbers, Campo instead finds solace in defensive
end Greg Ellis' return for the season opener after breaking his leg
in two places Dec. 12. And Ebenezer Ekuban re-emerged at left
defensive end against the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ekuban looked like he did at the end of last season,'' Campo
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Larrimore watch continues, with much faith, hope and
scheming to help him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to understand that \RLarrimore\S is a
rookie who is seeing a lot of situations out there for the first
time,'' Campo said. ``If he's the guy \Rto start\S, which looks
like he will be, we'll take steps to make sure the scheme comes to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Briefly Wide receiver Chris Brazzell's hamstring
injury suffered against the Rams was not serious. He is listed as
day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Troy Hambrick, an all-special teams contributor,
suffered a high-ankle bruise while lead-blocking on Joey Galloway's
punt return. Free-agent rookie Hambrick also is listed as
day-to-day. Said Dave Campo: ``It took four different guys ... to
do what he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo called this preseason ``very, very successful ... probably
the best we've had in years'' in spite of the Cowboys' 0-5 record.
Campo's logic: Minimal injuries going into the season. Tight end
David LaFleur (groin) played against St. Louis, while running back
Emmitt Smith (calf), wide receiver Jason Tucker (groin) and
fullback Robert Thomas (knee) are all expected to resume practice
today after missing the Rams game.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coaches were in the dark for about an hour at Valley
Ranch yesterday. A power outage delayed review of the game tape. It
also knocked out computers and e-mail at one of the NFL's busiest
times of the year. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 2342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
