<DOCNO> NYT20000825.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2719 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-FINANCE-LAZIO-NYT &LR;      08-25 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FINANCE-LAZIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI FUND-RAISER MOVES TO ASSIST LAZIO 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The chief fund-raiser for Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
aborted campaign for U.S. Senate is moving to set up an independent
committee to tap money from Giuliani's national network of
contributors and finance television advertisements on behalf of
Rep. Rick Lazio's campaign for the Senate, political leaders have
said.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican said it was ``90 percent certain'' that the
fund-raiser, Bruce Teitelbaum, would go ahead with creating the
committee. Although some details of its structure were still being
worked out, the committee would be set up independently of Lazio,
and would be exempt from most restrictions on campaign
contributions, one official said.
</P>
<P>
   As contemplated, the independent committee would provide prove a
much-needed assist for Lazio, the Suffolk County Republican who
entered the race only three months ago to replace Giuliani, who is
undergoing treatment for prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has been under pressure to raise money fast in order to
catch up with his opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic candidate for Senate has collected $18.6 million,
compared with the $8.5 million accumulated by Lazio, who has said
he needs at least $15 million to be competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Teitelbaum is reported to have said he thought he could raise
several million dollars from the network of Giuliani's supporters,
or, perhaps more accurately, opponents of Clinton. The money would
probably go to finance television advertisements and other
activities, like a get-out-the-vote drive, one official said.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there are some risks here for Lazio. He has
repeatedly criticized Clinton for what he has described as campaign
finance abuses, in particular, her use of committees that collect
largely unregulated soft money.
</P>
<P>
   With much fanfare, he signed a ``New York Freedom From Soft
Money Pact,'' while Clinton was collecting such contributions in
California. And he has also campaigned with Sen. John McCain, who
has led the effort in Washington to eliminate soft money and who is
expected to make a television advertisement on Lazio's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Teitelbaum helped Giuliani raise $23 million before he quit the
race, an amount that stunned Clinton and her supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Teitelbaum declined to comment this week. Lazio's campaign
manager, Bill Dal Col, did not return several calls seeking comment
on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money is largely unregulated contributions raised by
political party committees and outside groups. By law, it is not
supposed to be used to directly promote a candidacy, but the
parties have found ways to work around that. Contributions to the
official campaign committees, like those set up for Lazio and
Clinton, are limited to $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign says she has two soft-money accounts set up
with outside committees. Lazio has none, his aides said. One
official familiar with the negotiations to set up the new committee
said that in order to avoid such criticism the committee would be
an independent entity that would raise and spend money on its own _
and, at least officially, without Lazio's knowledge, to make
certain that the committee does not run afoul of election laws.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Lazio acknowledged this week that they were aware of
what Teitelbaum, and a small group of other Lazio supporters, were
trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   The effort by Teitelbaum is notable for political, as well as
financial, reasons. Until now, Giuliani has seemed to offer what
many Republicans have viewed as perfunctory support for Lazio,
although he did urge his donors to turn over contributions to the
congressman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
