A2722 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLYMPICS-WRESTLERS-NY     08-25 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-WRESTLERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRESTLERS' DISPUTE MIRED IN COURTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Sydney Olympics begin in three weeks, but the roster of the
U.S. Greco-Roman wrestling team remains in a legal chokehold.
</P>
<P>
   A match between Matt Lindland and Keith Sieracki took only
minutes at the Olympic trials in June, but two months later, the
outcome remains locked in a judicial tug of war between federal
arbitrators and federal judges. Sports law experts say the ultimate
referee could be the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Sieracki, an Army sergeant, defeated Lindland, a four-time
national champion in the 167{-pound category, by a score of 2-1 in
their deciding bout at the Olympic trials. Lindland filed an
immediate protest, saying he had been tripped in violation of
Greco-Roman rules, which prohibit the use of the legs to conduct a
maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. wrestling federation, the sport's national governing
body, rejected the protest, and the case became as entangled as the
two wrestlers on the mat.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Olympic athletes have the right to seek binding federal
arbitration to resolve disputes, according to the federal Olympic
and Amateur Sports Act. All sports federations under the Olympic
umbrella also agree to be bound by rulings of the American
Arbitration Association, and the U.S. Olympic Committee has
Olympians sign a code of conduct form saying they will submit to
arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the whole resolution process has been thrown on its ear,''
said Jeff Benz, a lawyer who represented the cyclist Christine
Witty in another arbitration case. ``We're back to having courts
resolve sports disputes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindland first filed for arbitration, and an arbitrator ordered
a rematch, which Lindland won, 8-0. Saying he thought the rematch
was merely practice, Sieracki then filed his own arbitration case,
saying the first arbitration decision should be invalidated because
he had never been invited to the proceeding to defend himself.
Thursday, an arbitrator ruled in Sieracki's favor, and it appeared
he would be heading to the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   But Lindland took his case to the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Chicago, which ruled later on Thursday that the original
arbitration should be enforced and that USA Wrestling should submit
Lindland's name to the USOC for participation in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The committee now finds itself with a difficult decision. Both
Sieracki and Lindland have won arbitration rulings. The committee
is not bound by the 7th Circuit ruling, although Judge Frank
Easterbrook wrote in his decision, ``We trust the USOC will act
responsibly once it receives USA Wrestling's nomination of
Lindland.''
</P>
<P>
   Easterbrook suggested that both wrestlers might have to be named
to the Olympic team. International Olympic rules would not allow
for that without a waiver from wrestling's world governing body.
Short of that, the USOC will have to choose either Sieracki or
Lindland or let the case play itself out in the courts, legal
experts said. Mike Moran, a spokesman for the committee, said
yesterday that it would study the matter over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The case has pointed out the weakness in the USOCs arbitration
process. Ed Williams, a New York lawyer who helped write the
athletes' rights section of the Olympic and Amateur Sports Right
Act, said it might be necessary to amend the act to make sure that
all parties were brought together at one arbitration hearing so
that conflicting arbitration rulings did not occur.
</P>
<P>
   He also said it might be necessary to state in writing that
``field of play'' decisions made by referees or umpires are off
limits to arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly this decision by the first arbitrator may cause other
athletes to consider whether they want to arbitrate field-of-play
decisions,'' Williams said, which could lead to a chaotic situation
in which baseball players take umpires' calls to arbitration and
figure skaters challenge judges' subjective rulings. ``It has been
generally understood that decisions by referees or umpires are not
subject to arbitration, but we haven't written it down in the
rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sieracki is exploring his legal options, said his
lawyer, Lt. Col. Dan Shaver. One is to seek to have the arbitration
ruling in his favor validated by a federal appeals court, just as
Lindland did. That would leave conflicting decisions, which may
require the Supreme Court to adjudicate, sports law experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides my divorce, it's the most frustrating thing I've ever
been through, and my divorce was pretty frustrating,'' Sieracki
told The Associated Press. He added: ``I've always felt you were
supposed to leave it all on the mat, not in the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindland called the conflicting legal rulings ``insanity'' but
told reporters he felt he felt compelled to appeal what he thought
was a ridiculous outcome at the Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you know you're right, it's hard to say, `Whatever,' and
walk away,'' Lindland said. ``My nature is not to quit.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
