<SLUG> BC-LOBSTER-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PESTICIDE MAKERS ARE SUED OVER LOBSTER DEATHS IN 1999 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Conn., Ill.)   By ALAN FEUER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 1,100 lobstermen from New York and Connecticut filed a
federal lawsuit on Friday charging that pesticides sprayed last
year to kill mosquitoes carrying the West Nile virus had devastated
the lobster population in Long Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in Central Islip,
N.Y., seeks at least $125 million from five pesticide
manufacturers. They are accused of disregarding the likelihood that
their products would seep into coastal waters and kill marine life.
While the suit acknowledges that New York  &UR; s &LR; tate, Connecticut, New
York City and Suffolk County used the pesticides to fight the
spread of West Nile, it does not accuse any public officials of
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit says lobstermen have witnessed a ``dramatic and
severe'' decrease in the number of lobsters in Long Island Sound.
This decrease, the suit maintains, began immediately after heavy
rains washed the pesticides into the sound.
</P>
<P>
   Laura McGowan, a spokeswoman for Clarke Mosquito Control
Products Inc. of Roselle, Ill., one of the defendants, said she had
not seen the lawsuit and could not comment on it. Representatives
of the other pesticide manufacturers named in the suit could not be
reached for comment. They are Cheminova Inc. of Wayne, N.J.; its
parent, Cheminova Agro of Denmark; Agrevo Environmental Health,
which has headquarters in Frankfurt; and Zoecon Corp. of
Schaumburg, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Gladstone N. Jones, the lead lawyer for the lobstermen, said the
spraying of pesticides had wiped out about 90 percent of last
year's full-grown lobster population. Jones also said the
pesticides had killed many young and larval lobsters, meaning that
the lobster harvest in the sound could be damaged for 5 to 10 more
years.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the lobstermen had chosen to sue the pesticide
manufacturers because they were in the best position to warn
government officials of the product dangers. ``They had the
information in their control that in all likelihood, this fishery
would be wiped out,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also pointed out that like insects, lobsters are
arthropods and are particularly susceptible to pesticides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
