<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BOYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L. BRYCE BOYER, 84, PSYCHOANALYST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Utah)   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. L. Bryce Boyer, a psychoanalyst who advanced the concept of
countertransference in doctor-patient communication, died on Aug. 9
in Walnut Creek, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Boyer, whose practice was in Berkeley, Calif., was 84.
</P>
<P>
   Transference, in psychotherapy, is the unconscious tendency of
patients to transfer to analysts feelings and attitudes associated
with significant influences in the patients' early lives. The
feelings, affectionate or hostile, may relate to a parent, for
instance.
</P>
<P>
   In countertransference, the analysts may experience emotional
reactions reflecting their own inner conflicts and needs.
</P>
<P>
   In classical psychoanalysis, countertransference was regarded as
an obstacle to treatment. But Boyer argued that analysts' feelings
could be important tools in understanding patients and helping the
analysis to progress. It was not a popular view, and many
mainstream analysts shunned Boyer and his approach.
</P>
<P>
   Boyer also believed that psychoanalysis should be more than a
treatment for the neuroses of the ``worried well,'' as he put it.
Instead he championed it as a treatment for people with serious
psychological disturbances like psychosis, severe borderline
pathology, psychosomatic illness or addiction.
</P>
<P>
   He lectured throughout the Americas and Europe and published
numerous books and articles. His ideas found a more favorable
reception abroad, he thought, particularly in South America.
</P>
<P>
   His most important papers were collected in ``The Regressed
Patient'' (1983) and ``Countertransference and Regression'' (1998).
Each remains in print.
</P>
<P>
   Boyer was the founder of Boyer House in San Rafael, Calif., a
residential psychoanalytic treatment center operated by a nonprofit
foundation. He trained the staff and provided the guidance for the
treatment of clients, who live in households of three to five
people in central Marin County.
</P>
<P>
   Bryce Boyer was born in Vernal, Utah, and received his medical
degree at Stanford University in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 60 years, Dr. Ruth McDonald Boyer,
an anthropologist and historian of folk art; two sons, Nehemiah and
Dewey; nine grandchildren; and six great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Boyer shared a keen interest in his wife's professional work.
They traveled together and occasionally joined forces writing and
editing.
</P>
<P>
   They studied indigenous cultures and the effect of outside
forces on them, and developed a lasting relationship with the
Mescalero Apaches, who adopted Boyer, an avid student of folklore
traditions, as a shaman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 2349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
