<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELLECK-LAUSD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAUSD COVETS SELLECK PROPERTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOMINIC BERBEO  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Actor Tom Selleck's brother is facing off against
the Los Angeles Unified School District in a jobs vs. schools
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Developer Daniel F. Selleck wants to build a $20 million
commercial complex in Van Nuys, a suburb of Los Angeles in the San
Fernando Valley. But the planned facility -- which would employ
2,000 people -- is being challenged by LAUSD officials who want the
property for a much-needed high school.
</P>
<P>
   Selleck told a city Planning Commission hearing officer that he
bought the old Carnation Ice Cream plant at 8015 Van Nuys Blvd. in
May 1999 and was moving forward with development plans when the
district contacted him two weeks ago about using it for a high
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just putting the final touches on this major
project,'' Selleck said after the meeting. ``Waiting until the last
minute isn't a wise way to do business.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Selleck Development Group is willing to negotiate
with the district -- but only if the school board sticks to a tight
``good faith'' time schedule without dragging the deal on for
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is money, and we can't sit around waiting forever for
them to make a decision,'' Selleck said.
</P>
<P>
   School officials asked the commission to delay granting Selleck
a permit to develop the property so they could decide whether they
want it for a high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a crisis stage here, and schools must be a
priority,'' said school board member Julie Korenstein.
</P>
<P>
   The district plans to open 18 new schools in the Valley within
the next seven years and broke ground in Van Nuys this week on the
Valley's first new elementary school in 29 years.
</P>
<P>
   Korenstein said the Northeast Valley is one of the areas hardest
hit by the county's school crisis, with more than 12,000 students
attending three of the area's high schools: James Monroe High, Van
Nuys High and Francis Polytechnic High. In the next six years, she
said, the number will grow by at least 6,500.
</P>
<P>
   Selleck said he plans to begin construction in October on a
project that includes manufacturing, retail space, a warehouse and
a fast-food restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Korenstein said the district has been considering the site for
the last two years and approved an initial feasibility study in
November -- showing the school would cost from $83 million to $92
million to build -- but has not yet made a purchase offer to
Selleck. She could not say why the district had waited until this
month to contact Selleck.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a prime spot, and the bottom line is, if it comes down
to taking the land by eminent domain we might have to consider
that, but we're more than willing to negotiate,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Richard Alarcon, D-Van Nuys, invoked the Belmont
Learning Center and Ambassador Hotel scandals in arguing for a
quick decision on the use of the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Belmont was half built before explosive and toxic gas problems
that had been largely ignored forced the district to abandon the
$170 million project. LAUSD also has been locked in a 10-year war
over seizing the Ambassador Hotel property by eminent domain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand the need for schools, but we don't want to see
another long, drawn-out debacle like the Ambassador Hotel or
Belmont,'' Alarcon said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair to the developer, who has shown they can build
good projects that create quality jobs like they did at the former
(General Motors) plant site.''
</P>
<P>
   Angelo Bellomo, the district's top environmental safety officer,
said a new environmental review system would help speed along the
process, and a full report from the state Department of Toxic
Substances Control is due in the next few months on whether any
environmental safety mitigation measures are needed at the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The horror stories of the Ambassador Hotel are over,'' Bellomo
said. ``We've already developed a work plan for this site, and
we're prepared to move quickly as far as the environmental issues
are concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the site was particularly attractive because it does not
appear to be heavily polluted.
</P>
<P>
   The zoning hearing was headed by Robert Duenas, a city planner,
who extended the public input period until Sept. 4. The full
Planning Commission is set to make a final decision on Selleck's
application for a zoning variance Sept. 28.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
