u k BC-EDIT-TWA-CRASH-NYT &LR;      08-25 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TWA-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A SEARCHING LOOK AT FLIGHT 800 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, Aug. 26:
</P>
<P>
   As flying becomes safer, crashes become harder to explain. That
has been the paradox hovering over the investigation of the TWA
Flight 800 disaster. In the immediate aftermath of the crash, which
killed all 230 people on board, there were theories that the plane
had been brought down by terrorists or an errant missile.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after one of the most painstaking investigations in the
history of aviation, the National Transportation Safety Board has
ruled out those possibilities. Instead, the board determined that a
``fuel/air explosion inside the center wing tank'' was the probable
cause of the Boeing 747's breaking up in midair off Long Island,
N.Y., 12 minutes into its flight from Kennedy Airport to Paris on
July 17, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   What is not known for certain is what ignited the explosion,
though a short circuit in electrical wiring is strongly suspected.
</P>
<P>
   The only wiring inside fuel tanks consists of low-voltage wires
for fuel gauges. A short circuit there is deemed unlikely. But
inspectors believe that a short circuit in wiring outside the tank
may have led to a surge of current in the wiring inside, providing
the spark. In the absence of certainty, the Federal Aviation
Administration has drafted three dozen airworthiness directives on
fuel tank safety that seek to address each possible ignition and
explosion source.
</P>
<P>
   One approach is to make a jet's fuel tanks less flammable. The
fuel in an aircraft's center wing tank is flammable roughly a third
of the time, when the combination of air, fuel vapors and
temperature is just so.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA says that ``nitrogen inerting'' technology has been
rapidly developed as a result of the crash. This technology should
soon enable airlines to replace the air in gas tanks with inert gas
before takeoff, significantly reducing the amount of time the
center wing tank's fuel is flammable. The other approach is to
eliminate possible sparks. Here the FAA has focused on worn wiring.
</P>
<P>
   TWA Flight 800 will also be remembered for its impact on the way
victims' families are treated in the aftermath of an air crash.
Reacting to the families' plight, Congress passed legislation
requiring that airlines act more efficiently and more humanely in
providing them assistance and information. But the most fitting way
for government and industry to honor the dead is through steps
designed to prevent a similar disaster in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-25-00 2356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
