u k BC-EDIT-TEACHERS-NYT &LR;      08-25 0355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TEACHERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FINDING QUALIFIED TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
 -NYT   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, Aug. 26:
</P>
<P>
   New York state's education commissioner, Richard Mills, and New
York City's schools chancellor, Harold Levy, have reached a
compromise on a lawsuit by the state aimed at barring the city from
placing uncertified teachers in low-performing schools as of next
month. The accord gives the city breathing room but requires it to
reach full compliance by 2001. This will not be easy, given a
nationwide teacher shortage that could stagger schools statewide
unless Gov. George Pataki and the Legislature develop a strategy to
produce and recruit high-quality teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Mills brought the lawsuit to enforce a new state regulation
requiring the city to hire only certified teachers in
low-performing schools beginning this fall. The compromise allows
the city to delay its compliance in high-shortage fields like math
and science, in recognition that filling these positions will be
difficult. But the same regulation that resulted in this suit will
soon require that every newly hired teacher in the state be
certified. This will be problematic. There is a national bidding
war for teacher talent, and about half the state's teacher corps
could actually retire over the next decade. For starters, New York
needs to pass a law allowing seasoned teachers who have reached age
55 to pay their pensions into an annuity and continue teaching
without an earnings limitation.
</P>
<P>
   The state Legislature has begun to focus on the problem but has
fallen short of the inventiveness that is on display in
Massachusetts, California, New Jersey and North Carolina. In the
1990s, Gov. James B. Hunt led North Carolina to greater gains on
national reading tests than in any other state. North Carolina
raised statewide teacher salaries, supplied novice teachers with
paid mentors as well as other supports, and gives financial rewards
for teachers who achieve national certification. Albany will need
to devise similar measures to get New York through its teacher
shortage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
