<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-25 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2744 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-REAL-CONFESSIONS     08-25 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-REAL-CONFESSIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REAL CONFESSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Aug. 26: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Court TV, which has distinguished itself with live coverage of
court proceedings, will offer a new and bizarre program this fall.
``Confessions,'' the new entry, will be a 30-minute show, with each
episode presenting three videotaped police confessions of people
who have committed murders, rapes and other violent crimes.
Broadcasting the tapes is legal because they are part of the public
record in cases where the suspects were convicted or were found not
guilty by reason of insanity.
</P>
<P>
   Court TV executives say ``Confessions'' fits in perfectly with
their network's mission of exposing the inner workings of the
criminal justice system. But culling out the grisliest snippets of
selected criminal confessions is little more than a rank appeal to
prurience and the thrill of violence, motivated by the network's
desire for an audience-grabbing hit.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could be cheaper to produce than simply replaying grainy
videotapes made by police and prosecutors. Each confession will be
edited down to 10 minutes or less. There will be no host or
narration, no explanation of the cases, how the suspects were found
or how long the interrogation process actually took, because that
would detract from the show's ``watchability,'' explains one Court
TV executive.
</P>
<P>
   Since a confession tape is ``just a guy talking,'' says the
executive, it may not hold viewers without some added visual
texture. So the show's creators will put in split-screen
re-enactments of the crime scene and other atmospheric images,
alongside the criminal confessor.
</P>
<P>
   Since its beginning, Court TV has given viewers solid programs
focusing on many aspects of criminal justice. The role confessions
play is a worthy subject. But a few minutes of isolated tape cannot
provide meaningful insight into criminality or even into the minds
of these particular offenders. Worse, the utter lack of context can
actually misinform viewers about how interrogations work.
</P>
<P>
   Court TV made its mark with gavel-to-gavel coverage of trials
that showed the entire courtroom process. The network has the legal
right to show the confession tapes. But it is regrettable that it
is willing to sabotage its reputation for serious legal journalism
with a lurid show where tales of murder are offered as a night's
entertainment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
